<SLUG> BC-MEDIABYTES-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 MYPRIMETIME.COM SEES ITSELF AS BOOMER HUB  &HT;     By DAN FOST 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Do Baby Boomers want their very own home on the Internet?
<P>
   A new San Francisco startup thinks they do _ and is launching a
Web site, www.myprimetime.com, to provide it.
</P>
<P>
   The site is founded by three former journalists from CNNfn, with
$4.25 million in backing from Hummer Winblad, one of the more
prestigious venture capital firms.
</P>
<P>
   MyPrimeTime offers regularly updated sections on jobs,
investing, health and leisure _ topics for which scores of Web
sites already exist. But MyPrimeTime says it brings value by
putting all the topics on one site and by making them relevant for
people between the ages of 35 and 53.
</P>
<P>
   Baby Boomers _ that vast demographic bulge of 81 million people
born after World War II, from 1946 to 1964 _ are not a monolithic
group. Most of them don't even think of themselves as Baby Boomers,
but identify themselves in other ways.
</P>
<P>
   That presents a challenge to the MyPrimeTime entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
   ``For any kind of community play to work, it's essential that
there's something special that holds the community together,'' said
Andrea Williams, director of equity research at E-Offering in San
Francisco. ``I'm not sure what it would be for Baby Boomers that
they couldn't find at Yahoo or any of the other portals.''
</P>
<P>
   For Boomers of a certain age, another San Francisco company,
ThirdAge Media, offers a specially tailored Web site. Although the
MyPrimeTime folks say ThirdAge is for older folks, ThirdAge founder
and Chairwoman Mary Furlong said, ``We service people 45 and
older.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though Furlong declined to take on MyPrimeTime directly,
it's clear that the ThirdAge site could present MyPrimeTime's most
formidable obstacle. Furlong was reached in New York, where she was
just taping a segment for CBS's ``The Early Show.'' That's the same
CBS that in June plunked down $54 million for roughly one-third of
ThirdAge Media, joining other big backers like Softbank and Si
Newhouse's Advance Publications.
</P>
<P>
   Furlong, an industry veteran who founded SeniorNet, notes her
site's nearly three-year head start and 700,000 registered
community members, and she touts that Time tabbed her as one of the
50 most important people shaping cyberspace today.
</P>
<P>
   Still, MyPrimeTime execs say they're on a fast ramp, and it
looks like it's true. In rehabbed brick-and-glass offices tucked
behind the old U.S. Mint, the company this week announced a
partnership with Fidelity, in which the mutual fund giant will
sponsor its personal finance section.
</P>
<P>
   Those sorts of partnerships, as well as advertising and
unspecified future e-commerce deals, will form the backbone of
MyPrimeTime's planned revenue stream.
</P>
<P>
   It's all thanks to the fundamental premise that Baby Boomers are
the biggest, wealthiest generation in U.S. history and therefore
are worth targeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never before were able to micro-target an audience as
large as the Boomers,'' said Craig Forman, co-founder and CEO of
MyPrimeTime. ``It's only in this medium that you could tackle the
aggregation of 81 million people because we tackle it person, by
person, by person.''
</P>
<P>
   The three founders are 38, 40 and 44 years old. ``We look at our
lives as a mirror of the site,'' said Helen Whalen, another
co-founder and the company president.
</P>
<P>
   Note that neither site wants to offend its readers by implying
that they're old, so instead, they refer to them as ``Third Agers''
or people hitting ``my prime time.'' Boomers, as MyPrimeTime's
Whalen said, like to think of themselves as 10 years younger than
they really are.
</P>
<P>
   E-FORTUNE: Here comes Fortune magazine, launching a tech
supplement that it plans to call eCompany Unlimited. Never mind
that there's already a real company called eCompany. (That firm
owns www.ecompany.com. Typing www.ecompanymagazine.com or, worse,
www.pathfinder.com/ecompany takes you to the site of the new
Fortune offering.)
</P>
<P>
   The magazine will be based in the San Francisco Bay Area,
debuting next May with a starting circulation of 200,000. Former
Fortune and Time writer Ned Desmond, 41, will head it.
</P>
<P>
   I found what's motivating the folks at Fortune's parent, Time
Inc., in my mailbox this month: a 424-page issue of Fast Company, a
356-page Wired, a 314-page Red Herring and a 338-page Business 2.0.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe I'll hit a Boomer Web site for health information _ these
magazines are giving me a hernia.
</P>
<P>
   GIMME AN E: ECompany Unlimited comes as folks start to complain
about words starting with ``e,'' such as eBay, E-Trade, eToys,
E-Loan, E-Stamp. Just this week, I was pitched by companies calling
themselves eAlity and eDedication. Egads!
</P>
<P>
   One firm, Persistence Software of San Mateo, wants to e-liminate
all the e-idolatry. For its campaign, titled, ``E-Nough,''
Persistence created the Society for the Preservation of the Other
25 Letters of the Alphabet, and it is compiling a list of flagrant
e-violations at its Web site, www.persistence.com/enough.
</P>
<P>
   SKY'S THE LIMIT: The Industry Standard's weekly San Francisco
rooftop gatherings have proven so popular, the magazine has had to
make the event invitation-only.
</P>
<P>
   When he founded the Standard last year, John Battelle also
launched a new tradition in the San Francisco Internet community by
inviting people to the roof of the offices at Pacific and Battery
streets.
</P>
<P>
   But with lines snaking around the block and crowds squeezed onto
the aerie, the party was becoming more of a burden than a blast.
Now the magazine will pick its guest list the democratic way: with
technology.
</P>
<P>
   The list of invitees will be sorted by computer. ``We have a
pretty deep database of information on these people,'' said Stacey
Foreman, the Standard's chief of staff. Some of the invites are
selected randomly, and some are picked based on how often the
person attends, or whether they fit the goals of the event's
sponsor _ usually an advertiser who picks up the tab for the
evening's food and drinks.
</P>
<P>
   Still, things can get tight. More than 3,000 people are
registered; 400 to 600 actually get invited; and the rooftop only
holds 75 people at a time.
</P>
<P>
   If you get the weekly e-mail touting that evening's party,
you're in. If not, wait til next week, and check your in-box.
</P>
<P>
   FRAGRANCE-FREE: Wired magazine is known for some breathtakingrk, but the latest cover can leave you gasping. To tout a
story about technology that enables people to send smells over the
Internet, the magazine slapped a scratch-n-sniff sticker on a
cartoon by Ren and Stimpy's creator John Kricfalusi, showing a slob
plucking hairs from his armpit, a cat vomiting, and other people
doing things so disgusting as to prohibit their mention here. (And
we're not bashful, so you know it's gross.)
</P>
<P>
   At least the scratch-n-sniff doesn't try to realistically match
the cover. While some smell of lily, mine smells sweetly of banana.
</P>
<P>
   As one colleague said: This magazine is owned by the same folks
who publish the New Yorker?
</P>
<P>
   Media Bytes appears every Thursday in The Chronicle. Send buzz,
dirt, tips and comments to fostd &LR; sfgate.com, call (415) 777-6004 or
fax (415) 543-2482.
</P>
</TEXT>
