<HEADLINE>
`FALSTAFF': NO ENHANCEMENT NEEDED
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review.) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT-16 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By ANTHONY TOMMASINI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   NEW YORK _ There were two stories
to report from the New York City Opera on Tuesday night. The first
is the marvelous new production of Verdi's ``Falstaff,'' directed
with vitality and imagination by Leon Major and offering a
performance by remarkable young American baritone Mark Delavan that
should finally prod the Metropolitan Opera to sign him for
something soon. The Met can boast few better Verdi baritones on its
roster this season.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The other story concerns the continuing controversy about the
New York State Theater's new sound enhancement system. Those who
object seem to be a small minority. But that minority is getting
agitated, if some shouted comments from one listener during a set
change are representative of more widespread displeasure.
</P>
<P>
   First to the good news. This joint production was formerly
presented at the Glimmerglass Opera in Cooperstown, N.Y., in the
summer of 1998. John Conklin's attractive sets are mostly simple,
movable panels that suggest the interiors of Tudor homes and ale
houses. Conklin's costumes, however, are in period, and the mixture
of somewhat abstract sets and historically appropriate costumes
works beautifully.
</P>
<P>
   Major has sometimes been criticized for overdoing the comic
antics in his opera stagings, but here his work is just right. He
has coaxed droll, nuanced and funny performances from his cast.
</P>
<P>
   As the merry wives of Windsor plot a joke against Falstaff for
his amorous self-delusions while they chat around Alice Ford's
dining room table, Alice's daughter, Nannetta, slumps in a chair in
a corner glumly eating grapes because her father is trying to force
her to marry the pompous Dr. Caius. The pratfalls and double takes
of the cast have been carefully choreographed by Major, but they
are wonderfully sensitive to the antics in the music and are
rendered with utter naturalness.
</P>
<P>
   The title role is often undertaken by baritones in the later
stages of their careers. It was bracing to hear the music sung by a
fresh, strong voice. Sir John is old and fat, but he is not a
buffoon. He is proud of his enormous potbelly, to him a symbol of
grandeur and virility. Delavan played Falstaff as self-absorbed, a
sucker for flattery and light on his feet despite his paunch: a
Tudor aristocrat version of Ralph Kramden. Only after he has been
humiliated by Alice and her co-conspirators and tossed into the
Thames in a basket of dirty laundry does he sit alone outside the
inn, sipping a glass of warmed wine, and brood about his life, his
growing weight, his graying hair. Delavan made it a poignant
moment.
</P>
<P>
   His singing was crisp, supple and impressive. His voice is
enormous. No one had any trouble hearing him at the State Theater
before it was sound-enhanced. On this night his voice seemed almost
to overwhelm the system. His fortissimos positively shook the
place, leading that unhappy patron in an upper balcony to shout:
``Turn off the mikes, turn off the mikes! Let's have some real
sound up here.''
</P>
<P>
   The sweet-voiced soprano Amy Burton as Alice Ford, the fine
mezzo-soprano Leah Creek as Meg Page and mezzo-soprano Marion
Pratnicki in a winning company debut as Dame Quickly were the merry
wives.
</P>
<P>
   Soprano Sari Gruber was a delightful Nannetta, although some of
her floated soft high notes had a tremulous quality. She and the
ardent lyric tenor Gordon Gietz as her beloved Fenton made an
endearing couple. The baritone Stephen Powell brought his sturdy
voice to the role of the wealthy, patriarchal Ford.
</P>
<P>
   George Manahan conducted a lithe performance of this miraculous
score. But like that complainer from the balcony, I would have
preferred to hear it without the electronic assist.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `FALSTAFF'
</P>
<P>
   Opera in three acts by Giuseppe Verdi. Libretto by Arrigo Boito,
after Shakespeare's ``Merry Wives of Windsor'' and ``King Henry
IV''; conductor, George Manahan; director, Leon Major; sets and
costumes by John Conklin; lighting by Pat Collins. At the New York
City Opera. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With: Amy Burton (Alice Ford), Sari Gruber (Nannetta), Marion
Pratnicki (Dame Quickly), Leah Creek (Meg Page), Mark Delavan (Sir
John Falstaff), Gordon Gietz (Fenton), Stephen Powell ( Ford), John
Lankston (Dr. Caius), Joel Sorensen (Bardolfo) and George Cordes
(Pistola).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
