<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROCKETS REFUELING FOR ANOTHER TITLE RUN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ With so many new players, the Houston Rockets should
have issued nametags when training camp opened this month.
</P>
<P>
   Gone from last year's team are Scottie Pippen, Antoine Carr,
Othella Harrington, Michael Dickerson, Brent Price, Rodrick Rhodes,
Sam Mack and Anthony Miller. They have been replaced by rookie
Steve Francis, Shandon Anderson, Kelvin Cato, Carlos Rogers, Tony
Massenburg, Walt Williams, Don MacLean and Thomas Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   Why such a drastic transformation in one off-season? Rockets
coach Rudy Tomjanovich took a long look at his team and realized
changes had to be made.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets will still pass the ball inside to their double
low-post tandem of Hakeem Olajuwon and Charles Barkley, ]two
36-year old future Hall of Famers in the twilight of their careers.
However, Tomjanovich wanted to tweak his offense, and plans to use
the young legs and high energy of Francis, Anderson, Rogers, Cato
and Williams to move up and down the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have great players in `Dream' (Olajuwon) and Charles, and
they're at the end of their era,'' Tomjanovich said. ``But the
league has turned into an athletic, long league with guys like
(Kevin) Garnett and (Tim) Duncan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always talked about how we needed to get some athletic,
long guys that can run and have the long reaches. And in Cato and
Carlos Rogers, we feel we have those kind of guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Francis, who refused to report to the Vancouver Grizzlies after
they drafted him, was subsequently traded to the Rockets. The No. 2
overall pick in the NBA Draft is not yet as graceful of a point
guard as Stephon Marbury and Allen Iverson, but the signs so far
are promising.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every game to me is a learning experience, so I'm learning
every game,'' Francis said. ``There's a lot of things that I have
to work on to get myself better to get ready for the regular
season.''
</P>
<P>
   Tomjanovich said Francis, who was a natural shootingguard in
college, is destined for stardom.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just feel blessed that we had an opportunity to acquire
Steve,'' he said. ``He's a truly talented player, and a lot of
people thought he'd wind up as the number one pick in the draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a lot to learn, like any rookie coming in. But he
seems to have a knack for getting points on the board, and he
really hasn't even gotten untrack yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Tomjanovich is happy that the Rockets are solid enough to
attract a quality player like Francis, and an equally quality
player like Anderson, who was one of the top free agents this
summer. Anderson spurned a five-year, $24.5 million offer to return
to the Utah Jazz, and instead signed a two-year, $4.2 million offer
with the Rockets.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson's slashing, attacking-the-basket style should benefit
from NBA rules passed during the off-season. He said he decided not
to return to the Jazz for a number of reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a better fit for me here, not just basketball-wise, but I
think socially,'' said Anderson, who is single. ``I just get a
better feel here.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, Cato and Rogers came from Portland as part of the
Pippen trade. Cato, selected by the Mavericks with the 15th pick of
the 1997 draft and traded to Portland, is feeling at home with the
Rockets.
</P>
<P>
   ``They brought enough of my Portland teammates to make this look
almost like our old team,'' Cato said. ``I know we've got a lot of
talent, but talent can only go so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we look good on paper. But we're still learning
right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Still learning the playbook, and each other's names. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
