<SLUG> BC-CAR-STURBIN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOODYEAR'S EXIT SOUNDS LIKE SORRY EXCUSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   First it was Formula One. Then it was the Indy Racing League and
Championship Auto Racing Teams.
</P>
<P>
   Next thing you know, Goodyear will be pulling out of the baby
carriage tire market, or signing an exclusive contract to supply
recaps for Yugos.
</P>
<P>
   OK, those are exaggerations. But no matter how many times
Goodyear executive Stu Grant referred to the prohibitive research
and development costs associated with the IRL-CART split the other
day, Goodyear's decision to no longer supply tires to domestic
Indy-car teams looks like a sorry case of turning tail in the heat
of competition.
</P>
<P>
   Bad show. Bad press. And hardly the image we have come to
associate with the company that boldly has billed itself ``No. 1''
on the sidewalls of its Eagle racing radials.
</P>
<P>
   Goodyear's exit will leave Firestone as sole supplier to IRL and
CART teams beginning in 2000, room-servicing the Nashville-based
manufacturer a monopoly Goodyear once enjoyed for 20 years. Since
returning to Indy-car racing in 1995, Firestone Firehawk-shod cars
have won 59 of 71 CART races and four consecutive PPG Cup
championships. Included is the driver's title to be decided between
Dario Franchitti and Juan Montoya in the season-ending Marlboro 500
at the California Speedway on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Firestone-equipped CART drivers have won 18 of 19 events this
season, and led 2,419 of 2,519 laps (96 percent).
</P>
<P>
   Only five of the 27 cars entered in CART's season-ender will be
on Goodyears and victories by the most notable of those drivers _
Al Unser Jr. and Gil de Ferran _ would have to be classified as
remote.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1998, Firestone has won 36 times in 37 CART races.
</P>
<P>
   Bad show. Bad press. So, time for a little CART damage control.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the playing field in the IRL has been more level.
Both tire-makers have won 17 races and two Indianapolis 500s since
Tony George launched the IRL in 1996. Texan Greg Ray scored a
series-leading three victories and wrapped up the 1999 driver's
championship in a Firestone-equipped Dallara in the season-ender at
Texas Motor Speedway on Oct. 17.
</P>
<P>
   TMS, in particular, has proven to be a bane to Goodyear-equipped
IRL teams. Recall that the September 1998 race on the 1.5-mile,
high-banked trioval was marred by tires that shredded at speed on a
hot, fall Sunday afternoon in Fort Worth. Goodyear engineers
promised a better, safer tire for the June 1999 night IRL race,
which actually was run in the heat of twilight. And while Scott
Goodyear won that event on Goodyears, several of the manufacturer's
top teams were hampered by blistered tires less than 25 laps into
the race.
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Brack, who won the 1998 Pep Boys IRL championship and the
1999 Indy 500 on Goodyears supplied by team owner/Goodyear loyalist
A.J. Foyt, was among the drivers who tested at TMS a month before
the season-ending Mall.com 500. In what amounts to a dose of
gallows humor, Brack summed up the manufacturer's progress:
``September last year, the tires blew up on us, and now they're
only blistered. So, they're going in the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Bad show. Bad press. When George announced in late September
that the IRL would go it alone for perhaps as long as four years,
he presented Goodyear with a convenient way out.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Grant said the level of research and development
required to become even more competitive was not worth the price of
operating separate engineering programs for CART's varied circuits
and the all-oval IRL.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's financial from the standpoint of value for the dollar
invested,'' said Grant, Goodyear's general manager for global race
tires. ``That's the way we are looking at our racing operation,
whether it'd be CART or IRL or Formula One. It's not sheer number
of dollars. It becomes return on investment.''
</P>
<P>
   Grant said that Goodyear allocated additional resources to its
faltering CART programs when it pulled out of Formula One after the
1998 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had an excellent road-racing tire in F1 in 1998, and we
needed improvement on road-course and street circuits in the CART
series after 1997 and 1998,'' Grant said. ``We took that technology
developed in F1 and put those people onto that project and they did
a darn fine job in improving our CART (results) on road-courses and
street circuits.''
</P>
<P>
   Translation: Bad show. Bad press. De Ferran scored Goodyear's
only CART victory so far this season on the permanent road-course
at Portland (Ore.) International Raceway in June.
Firestone-equipped drivers won the 10 other CART races contested on
either road-courses or temporary street circuits in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Goodyear is free to concentrate more of its R&AMP;D resources on
NASCAR's wildly popular Winston Cup, Busch Grand National and
Craftsman Truck series. Goodyear, incidentally, enjoys an
exclusivity contract in those series through 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad about that tidy monopoly. Because it might have been the
perfect time for Hoosier Tire to reenter the heat of competition,
and try to determine who's really No. 1 where the rubber meets the
road in NASCAR, too.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCHITTI, MONTOYA SET FOR RUN AT CART CROWN
</P>
<P>
   The third-closest points race in CART's 21-year history will be
decided between Dario Franchitti and Juan Montoya at the California
Speedway on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the outcome, the friendly rivals have booked a
post-race party for Fontana, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``We agreed some time ago that win or lose, we are going to have
a small party after the race,'' said Franchitti, a Scotsman who has
built a nine-point lead (209-200) after 19 events.
</P>
<P>
   ``A little party, by the way,'' said Montoya, the Colombian who
will have to overcome two decades of history if he plans to add the
championship to his already stellar rookie season. Montoya will
start the Marlboro 500 knowing that the points lead never has
changed hands at the season-ending race in the 20 previous years of
Championship Auto Racing Teams competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would love to see myself winning the championship,'' said
Montoya, driver of the No. 4 Target Honda/Reynard owned by Chip
Ganassi. ``But if it doesn't happen, everything has a reason. You
know?''
</P>
<P>
   Montoya has been sensational as the replacement for two-time
CART FedEx Series champion Alex Zanardi. Montoya has established
CART rookie records for victories (7) and laps-led (929) and has
tied the rookie mark for pole positions (7). If he can outscore
Franchitti after 250 laps around the 2-mile California Speedway,
Montoya will join Nigel Mansell (1993) as the only rookies to have
won the PPG Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's surprising having won seven races and everything we've
done and we haven't won the championship,'' said Montoya, whose
crashes in consecutive street races in downtown Houston and Surfers
Paradise in Australia gave Franchitti the championship lead. ``I
think we gave away points to Dario, too many points to Dario, too
easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we'll see what happens. I'm just going to try to take it
as cool as I can.''
</P>
<P>
   Franchitti remained in contention on the strength of three
victories, including the most recent round in Australia, and a
series-high 11 podium finishes. Franchitti, who finished third in
last year's championship, can clinch by finishing as low as third.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, my position is slightly different from Juan's in
the fact that I don't need to go out and win the race,'' said
Franchitti, driver of the No. 27 Kool Honda/Reynard owned by Barry
Green. ``I just sort of need to be within a place or two, I guess.
But I would like to get out there and try to win this thing. So I'm
going to be out there pushing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The No. 1 priority is the championship, but you just gotta go
and treat ever race the same as we have for the whole year.''
</P>
<P>
   This is, however, only the second 500-mile race on CART's
schedule. Tony Kanaan won the U.S. 500 at the Michigan Speedway in
July, in what amounted to an afternoon of attrition. Kanaan
inherited the lead when Max Papis, gunning for his first victory
for Team Rahal, ran out of fuel in Turn 3 of the 2-mile Michigan
track.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's that many more things that can go wrong because of a
500-mile race,'' said Franchitti, who finished fifth at Michigan, a
sister track to California Speedway. ``The cars are pushed to their
absolute limit to run as fast as they do for that length of time.
So yeah, you've gotta work with the playing field you're given. I'm
looking forward to the 500-mile race. It's not going to be easy.
But yeah, I think it's an exciting and a fitting end to what's been
a pretty exciting season.''
</P>
<P>
   Montoya finished second at Michigan in what was his first
500-miler, and is well aware that the last 50 miles is what decides
these motorized marathons.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be interesting, you know, because it's very easy
to win the race and to finish 10th,'' Montoya said. ``Normally,
top-10 guys are running very close, so anything can happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``You gotta get to the end of the race and you gotta take care
of the equipment. But you gotta race as well. I need to get many
points, so I'm going to go for it.''
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE THE NUMBERS UPSET SPECIALS
</P>
<P>
   A review of past winners of CART's Marlboro 500 shows that a
number of pre-race longshots have found their way into Victory
Lane:
Year Winner 1981 Pancho Carter 1982 Gordon Johncock 1983 John Paul
Jr. 1984 Mario Andretti 1985 Emerson Fittipaldi 1986 Johnny
Rutherford 1987 Michael Andretti 1988 Danny Sullivan 1989 Michael
Andretti 1990 Al Unser Jr. 1991 Rick Mears 1992 Scott Goodyear 1993
Nigel Mansell 1994 Scott Goodyear 1995 Scott Pruett 1996 Andre
Ribeiro 1997 Mark Blundell 1998 Jimmy Vasser
</P>
<P>
   QUICK HITS JARRETT NEARS CLINCH
</P>
<P>
   Dale Jarrett can clinch the 1999 NASCAR Winston Cup championship
if he finishes 19th or better in the season's final three races.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett has a 246-point pad over Bobby Labonte after 31 of 34
events.
</P>
<P>
   The series is idle this weekend before heading to Phoenix
International Raceway for the Checker Auto Parts/Dura Lube 500 on
Nov. 7. Jarrett, driver of the No. 88 Quality Care Service/Ford
Credit Taurus, won at PIR as recently as 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett also can clinch on the 1-mile PIR oval if he can gain
126 points on Bobby Labonte or third-place Mark Martin. TRUCK TITLE
AT STAKE
</P>
<P>
   Roush Racing's Greg Biffle can become the youngest champion in
NASCAR Craftsman Truck Series history by finishing no worse than
third in the season-ending NAPA Auto Parts 200 at California
Speedway on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Biffle, 29, will take a 21-point lead into the race over
archrival Jack Sprague and the No. 24 GMAC Chevrolet. Dennis
Setzer, driver of the No. 1 Mopar Performance Dodge, is third, 25
points off the pace in the closest three-way title race in series
history.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was between Jack and me (for the victory) in the last race
last season,'' said Biffle, driver of the No. 50 Grainger Ford.
Sprague won that event after executing a bump pass with two laps
remaining at Las Vegas Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm real fortunate to be able to race him for the championship
this year,'' said Biffle, who has won a series-record nine races in
1999. ``But going in there with a 21-point lead doesn't give you
any cushion at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Biffle has overcome a 120-point penalty levied for a
non-approved manifold at Vegas to remain in the hunt, and perhaps
present Jack Roush his first NASCAR championship. ALLEN SEEKS
SPONSOR
</P>
<P>
   Pro Stock driver Bruce Allen and partner David Reher, both of
Arlington, still are searching for a primary sponsor to fund their
2000 National Hot Rod Association drag racing program.
</P>
<P>
   Allen said the Reher-Morrison Racing Engines team, which is
losing backing from Pennzoil's The Outlaw Fuel Additives brand,
needs approximately $500,000 to run the full schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll come up with some things where we can run our car,''
said Allen, who ran two 200 mph quarter-mile laps during the
O'Reilly Fall Nationals at the Texas Motorplex in Ennis last
weekend. ``Hopefully, it'll be with a sponsorship.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an associate deal with Pontiac and we're still working
on getting a major sponsor. We might have to do an engine rental
program with somebody next year. We're an engine-building shop.
That's what we do. And in racing, your name is what you are. You
get a lot of comments on the race car when it's running well, and
it helps you sell parts. So, we need to keep the car running.''
OUTLAWS RACE TIGHT
</P>
<P>
   Mark Kinser and Danny Lasoski are separated by 65 points in the
Pennzoil World of Outlaws standings with only ``A'' main events
remaining in California and Nevada.
</P>
<P>
   Kinser, who drives the No. 5m Mopar Performance Parts Sprint
Car, must finish ninth or better in the final two preliminary races
and ``A'' main events to clinch his second Outlaws points title.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is we need some help,'' Lasoski said. ``I
don't want to wish any bad luck on the 5m crew, but they're going
to have to help us for us to win this thing. We're going to have to
win all the races, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The series competes Saturday at Perris, Calif., with the
season-finale scheduled for Nov. 1-3 at Las Vegas Motor Speedway.
T-SHIRT NIGHT SET
</P>
<P>
   Texas Raceway in Kennedale will host Speedtek T-Shirt Night and
its annual Halloween program at the eighth-mile drag strip Saturday
night.
</P>
<P>
   The first 500 adult spectators will receive a free Texas Raceway
t-shirt, compliments of Speedtek.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the track's regular National Hot Rod Association
Bracket Racing program, children will have a chance to
trick-or-treat in the pit area. Richard House, the track's special
events coordinator, has organized that program.
</P>
<P>
   Racing begins at 3 p.m. For more information call (972)
483-8410. LAST WORDS
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great to be part of the greatest race team that drag
racing's ever seen, and I think we can say that with some certainty
so far.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Austin Coil, crew chief for nine-time NHRA Funny Car champion
John Force nn
</P>
