<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-CHASS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRUCIAL ERRORS OF OMISSION ALSO HAUNT BRAVES
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The box score of their final game of 1999 will show
that the Atlanta Braves committed no errors. The box score,
however, doesn't always tell the whole story. Ryan Klesko, the
Braves' first baseman, failed to make a makable play in the third
inning Wednesday night, and the New York Yankees, as they did the
entire postseason, capitalized on it for a 4-1 victory and two
record-tying World Series feats.
</P>
<P>
   The victory, generated by the two-run single Tino Martinez was
credited with on his hard grounder to Klesko, gave the Yankees two
successive World Series sweeps, only the third time that feat has
been achieved, and was the Yankees' 12th victory in a row in the
World Series. Both of these records, 12 consecutive victories and
sweeps in successive seasons, were set by _ who else? _ the Yankees
of earlier eras.
</P>
<P>
   As diluted as major league baseball may be as the result of
repeated expansion, the Yankees nevertheless have established one
of the great runs of all time. They have won three World Series
championships in the past four years, making them the first team
since the Oakland Athletics of 1972-'73-'74 to win that many times
in such a short period.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Braves, who played uncharacteristically poor
defense throughout the postseason, suffered another World Series
failure. They compiled the best won-lost record in the 1990s, won
eight consecutive division championships and played in five World
Series, but they have only one Series championship to show for it.
</P>
<P>
   This was the worst of their four World Series losses. They lost
in seven games to Minnesota in 1991, six games to Toronto in 1992
and six games to the Yankees in the 1996. Their only victory came
in 1995, when they defeated the Cleveland Indians in six games.
</P>
<P>
   In the National League Championship Series, the Braves committed
errors, too, but the New York Mets did not take advantage of the
misplays as liberally as the Yankees did in the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves, who led Games 1 and 3 going into the eighth inning,
didn't create the semblance of a threat in Game 4 until the eighth
inning; that made Klesko's failure to field Martinez's grounder all
the more critical.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees had the bases loaded with one out in the third
inning of a scoreless game when Martinez rapped a hard grounder
toward first. Klesko is not a good defensive first baseman, not
even an average defensive first baseman. He has played first base
this year because Andres Galarraga, one of the best defensive first
baseman in baseball, was out recovering from lymphatic cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The ball hit by Martinez bounced twice. As it shot up from its
second bounce, Klesko, who had moved slightly to his right to get
in the ball's path, put his glove on the ground, apparently
expecting it to stay down. But the trajectory never indicated that
the ball would take that direction. That was why the ball sped over
Klesko's glove and struck him on his right forearm. It then caromed
onto the grass in short right-center field as Chuck Knoblauch and
Derek Jeter scurried home with the first two runs of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Had Klesko been able to field the ball, he would have had one
out for certain and possibly a double play because the ball was hit
hard enough to get a double play. Later in the inning, Jorge Posada
singled home a third run, giving Roger Clemens an early, luxurious
three-run margin to work with. With that kind of early lead,
pitchers can pitch a different kind of game, one that usually
benefits them.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have spent the past few weeks benefiting from their
opponents' poor defensive play. In the last six innings in which
the other teams, the Boston Red Sox and the Braves, made errors,
the Yankees scored at least one run. For the entire postseason,
their opponents committed 16 errors, and the Yankees scored 13
unearned runs out of their total of 57 runs. The Braves made 13
errors in 14 postseason games.
</P>
<P>
   Opportunity is much of what the Yankees have been about the past
several seasons. They have not overwhelmed teams, but they have
left no doubt that they expect to win and much more often than not
do win. They generally have done what it has taken to win, whether
it's capitalizing on a play like Klesko's or getting a game-tying
home run from Knoblauch in the eighth inning, then a game-winning
home run from Chad Curtis in the 10th, as they did in Game 3
Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   In the first inning of Game 3, Knoblauch, the first batter, hit
a fly ball to right-center field that Brian Jordan dropped.
Knoblauch later scored. In the third inning of Game 2, David Cone
hit a soft two-out line drive to short that Ozzie Guillen dropped,
permitting a run to score. In Game 1, Brian Hunter, the Braves'
good-fielding first baseman, made two errors in the eighth inning,
the first on Knoblauch's sacrifice bunt that led to a four-run
flurry and a 4-1 victory.
</P>
<P>
   In the American League Championship Series, the Yankees took
advantage of Red Sox miscues, of which there were many.
</P>
<P>
   In the fifth and last game, Jose Offerman and Mike Stanley made
errors in the seventh inning, and the Yankees scored two runs. The
fourth game featured two such innings. Nomar Garciaparra and Bret
Saberhagen each committed an error in the fourth inning, and the
Yankees scored two runs. Errors by Offerman and Darren Lewis in the
ninth inning contributed to a six-run burst.
</P>
<P>
   Every scout who scrutinized the Yankees either during the season
or in the postseason in advance of a playoff series warned the team
that employed him that it could not give the Yankees extra outs.
They do enough damage with three outs in an inning, the scouts
wrote in great detail in their reports; they make life miserable
for their opponents when they are given a fourth or fifth out in an
inning.
</P>
<P>
   Once the Yankees capitalized on Klesko's failure to field
Martinez's grounder, the resulting runs loomed larger and larger as
the innings passed. The Braves, frustrated with their failures,
entered the game knowing they had an arduous task to snatch this
World Series from the Yankees. They never had a chance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
