r s BC-BKO-WHEELCHAIR-BASKET     10-28 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKO-WHEELCHAIR-BASKETBALL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS WHEELCHAIR TEAM FINDS HELP FROM DOWN UNDER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOBIAS LOPEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The mooring rope that tied the high-speed
ferry to the dock wrapped around Brad Ness's right ankle like an
angry boa constrictor, and an instant later he no longer had a
foot.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like breaking a stick in half. I heard the sound before
I felt anything,'' said Ness, who was a teen-ager at the time. ``I
looked down and my foot was gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Ness, now 24, began his freshman year at the University of
Texas-Arlington this fall, and the Wagin, Australia, native has
quickly become an integral part of the Movin' Mavs wheelchair
basketball team. In the process, he has formed strong bonds with
his new teammates.
</P>
<P>
   Ness learned of Texas-Arlington's program through another
Australian player on the team, Campbell Message. The chance to earn
a college education and to play wheelchair basketball brought Ness
to Arlington this fall, a little more than six years after his
accident.
</P>
<P>
   He was working as a deckhand at the ferry dock and thought he
was clear of the mooring rope when he was injured at 11:30 p.m. on
Dec. 12, 1992. After the accident, his right leg had to be
amputated below the knee.
</P>
<P>
   Before the accident, he had been an Australian Rules Football
player. He realized he could no longer play that sport at the same
level, but he wanted to remain in competitive athletics, so he took
up swimming and wheelchair basketball.
</P>
<P>
   The Movin' Mavs' 77-43 rout of the Houston Rolling Rockets
semi-professional team on Saturday was Ness' first start for
Texas-Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was awesome to play with a college team with the backing
the Movin' Mavs have,'' Ness said. ``The atmosphere the college
puts on for game night was quite special.''
</P>
<P>
   Ness, 6-foot-4, battled all night with Houston's Paul Schlobaum,
a 7-foot-1 center, and held him to 12 points without picking up a
foul.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm used to being the biggest person on the court,'' Ness
said. ``He was a man-mountain; once he was in position he was hard
to move. It was good experience to play against him.''
</P>
<P>
   Last season, the Movin' Mavs were bumped from the national
wheelchair tournament for the second consecutive season by
Illinois, mostly because they were overpowered on the inside by the
Illini's Will Waller and Pat Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   Texas-Arlington coach Jim Hayes said coupling Ness with forward
Eddie McGee should even things up in the lane.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're playing at the highest level anywhere when we're against
Illinois.'' Hayes said. ``It's going to take superior players to
play with them, but he works so well with Eddie. He sees the floor
very well.''
</P>
<P>
   McGee agrees with Hayes' assessment of Ness and said he gladly
welcomes the rebound help.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a load off my shoulders,'' McGee said. ``He's like a big
vacuum cleaner; anything that pops out he gets.''
</P>
<P>
   McGee and Ness, both single-leg amputees, have quickly become
friends off the court as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's pretty amazing. (Amputees) tend to stick together, so
there's always a few stories to be told.'' Ness said of McGee.
``He's pretty loud, so he always makes you feel welcome.''
</P>
<P>
   Ness and Message like to watch Australian Rules Football games
on cable TV together, and Ness said he doesn't miss playing too
much.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being able to play wheelchair basketball at the level we are
now more than compensates for not being able to play football,''
Ness said. ``I'd rather watch it with a few mates and a couple of
beers than go through the heartache of playing again.''
</P>
<P>
   The Movin' Mavs are scheduled to travel to Wisconsin-Whitewater
on Nov. 19 for a round-robin tournament. They'll face Whitewater
and Illinois, the teams that finished first and second in the
national tournament last season, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Ness said he's enjoying American culture, especially the team's
Sunday trips to an area restaurant and the opportunity to play for
Texas-Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   He also appreciates the living accommodations for the wheelchair
team at the school _ most of the players live in close proximity to
each other in student housing on the campus.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is by far one of the most superior setups, offering the
education and to be looked after the way we are as wheelchair
athletes,'' Ness said. ``I'm honored to be a part of the Movin'
Mavs.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
