<SLUG> BC-STAFF-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-OFFENDERS NEED A CHANCE TO BE HIRED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ninety-five percent of people who are sentenced to prison come
back out. Many think the best tool for keeping them out is a job.
</P>
<P>
   ``To break the cycle of recidivism, first and foremost, they
need a decent job,'' said Patrick Zaiss, executive director of
Volunteers in Prisons, a Kansas City, Kan., organization that,
among other things, helps ex-offenders mesh back into the
community.
</P>
<P>
   But saying they need jobs is much easier than actually landing
them.
</P>
<P>
   A survey this year by Express Personnel Services, an employment
agency, found that only one in four employers would hire a former
convict. Why take a chance when horrible, high-profile crimes
committed by ex-cons fill our news pages and make us wary of those
whose pasts include prison?
</P>
<P>
   It's a vicious circle, and perhaps a case where the crimes of a
few ruin chances for others to slide back into the work world.
</P>
<P>
   Felons, especially those convicted of violent or sex crimes,
aren't what most people would call model employee material. And
what financial institution would embrace a convicted embezzler?
</P>
<P>
   Many organizations, particularly some big businesses, have
outright policies: We don't hire ex-cons.
</P>
<P>
   Other organizations, because of the tight labor market, are
desperate for workers and are willing to take a chance _ but only
if their managers believe in rehabilitation, can be convinced it
has occurred and are comfortable with the management challenges
involved.
</P>
<P>
   When Zaiss counsels ex-offenders, he emphasizes honesty.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have a checkered past, be honest about it if asked,''
he said. ``If someone is not going to hire you, it's better to
learn it quickly and not waste time.''
</P>
<P>
   Avert Inc., a company that conducts employment background
checks, said last year that nearly one in 10 job applicants it
researched had a criminal record. With more organizations
conducting background checks, it's less likely an applicant can
hide jail time.
</P>
<P>
   Zaiss said getting to the truth quickly was important because
research finds that the first six months out of prison are pivotal.
Without a return to financial stability in that period, recidivism
is likely.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't waste time pursuing employment that isn't realistic,''
he advised parolees. ``Look at places where you have an advocate.
Depending on the nature of your crime, some places absolutely will
not consider you. But if you're up-front, honest and sincere and
can accurately describe your self-improvement efforts, a lot of
employers will give you a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Zaiss said the best job-finding success for parolees came in the
``slightly better than entry-level category _ about $7.50 an hour
or so.'' But if the ex-offender has a trade or special skill, he or
she can do far better.
</P>
<P>
   Zaiss told one ex-con to list on his resume his work as an
electrician in prison. The skill and experience landed him a job
outside.
</P>
<P>
   Hiring convicted criminals means taking a chance. But it's a
chance that some employers must be willing to take, provided
instinct and information make it seem the right thing to do.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-99 0026EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
