<HEADER>
A0848 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-ARMENIA-SLAYING-LADN     10-28 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARMENIA-SLAYING-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARMENIANS IN LOS ANGELES PLAN MEMORIAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY LEE CONDON 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES -- Armenians in Southern California, the largest
community of Armenians outside their homeland, struggled Wednesday
to understand why the country's prime minister and others were
assassinated and whether the attack heralded more bloodshed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see this as anything that will lead to an overthrow.
If it's a coup d'etat, it's a lousy coup d'etat,'' said Vicken
Sonentz-Papazian, executive director of the western region of the
Armenian National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Armen Melkonian, consul general at the Armenian Consulate in
Beverly Hills, said he knew several of those killed.
</P>
<P>
   Melkonian said modern Armenia is still a young country _ one of
the 15 independent republics that emerged from the collapse of the
Soviet Union in 1991. But he stressed that people in Armenia and
abroad today have faith in the strength of the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a terrorist act,'' Melkonian said.
</P>
<P>
   He expects local Armenians to support their homeland as it
attempts to fill the political leadership void left by the
killings.
</P>
<P>
   ``They will do more than ever to help Armenia out of this
economic crisis,'' Melkonian said.
</P>
<P>
   He added the Armenian community in Glendale and elsewhere in
Southern California is likely to hold memorials in coming days. A
condolence book will be set out at the consulate building for
people to sign, Melkonian said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the five gunmen, Nairi Unanian, said in a telephone
interview with a local television station that the attack was
carried out to protest the government's lack of attention to hunger
and the poor economy. But local Armenians said the situation in the
country was worse in the wake of such previous hardships as the
1988 earthquake and the country's struggle for independence from
the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things have been tougher in the past and it never came to
this,'' Sonentz-Papazian said.
</P>
<P>
   Sonentz-Papazian also said there was no evidence outside
Parliament or elsewhere in the country of an organized revolt.
</P>
<P>
   As news of the death of the prime minister and at least six
others trickled out, many of the 450,000 Armenians living in
Southern California were glued to their televisions and radios.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something like this really touches everyone's heart. There is
a very strong connection between Armenians living in the United
States and Armenia,'' said Levon Marashalian, a professor of
history at Glendale Community College.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm shocked and upset. It's a great loss of Armenian
leaders,'' said Glendale Councilman Rafi Manoukian.
</P>
<P>
   Marashalian said it did not make sense for the gunmen to kill
these politicians in a protest about hunger and a bad economy. The
professor said he believed Prime Minister Vazgen Sarkisian was the
leader of a government effort to finally do something about the
poor economy. Previous political leaders had ignored the economic
crisis in the country, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It reflects a lot of the anger and frustration people feel
toward a bad economic situation,'' Marashalian said. ``The irony is
the very people they took this action against were the very people
who are taking concrete action to fix the economy.''
</P>
<P>
   For many Armenians here, the attack on the Parliament is as
upsetting as an attack on the U.S. Capitol would be for Americans,
Sonentz-Papazian said.
</P>
<P>
   Local Armenians have played a key role in helping people in
their homeland before, when it suffered a devastating earthquake in
1988, struggled to gain independence from Soviet Union, fought a
war with neighboring Azerbaijan and endured economic blockade by
Turkey and Azerbaijan.
</P>
<P>
   Local Armenians have been generous in supporting frequent
airlifts of food and supplies to Armenia and many send money to
their relatives there.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. James Rogan, R-Pasadena, said he met Sarkisian when the
prime minister visited Washington, D.C., three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prime Minister Sarkisian was a patriot and cared deeply about
the cause of independence. I am saddened at the loss of a respected
leader,'' Rogan said.
</P>
<P>
   Rogan himself visited Armenia in September.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in Yerevan just over one month ago, and I saw firsthand
the Armenian government's success in expanding democracy and
developing a healthy economy,'' Rogan said. ``I am saddened that
rogue terrorists would try to compromise this work with acts of
violence.''
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
