<HEADLINE>
CATTLE OWNERS PREPARE THEIR ANIMALS FOR AMERICAN ROYAL
COMPETITION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ED FLETCHER  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today is Miss Sweetness' big day. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The 1,500-pound heifer from Mineral Point, Wis., is to show her
grace, beauty and pedigree against 208 others at an American Royal
event in Hale Arena.
</P>
<P>
   In preparation for her 8 a.m. appearance, her day was to start
at 2 a.m. She is to receive the normal wash, conditioning and blow
drying, as well as a mousse-like adhesive to help her hair stand up
in some places and sit down in others. She also will get an
oil-based spray to make her hair shine and some last-minute
tweaking to make sure she looks her best.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is kind of the finishing touches,'' said Shane Lindsey, a
consultant for Sweetness' owner, Carrousel Farms.
</P>
<P>
   Lindsey leads a team of four who prepare Carrousel Farms' eight
cattle for the competition.
</P>
<P>
   The livestock show began Wednesday and runs through Nov. 6.
Before the show ends, 2,013 competitors will display 2,126 cattle,
hogs, sheep and llamas. The 100th year of the livestock show will
draw competitors from 38 states.
</P>
<P>
   Three rows down and across the staging room isle from the
Carrousel Farms team, Adam, Matt and Casey Owen, ages 16, 14 and 8,
respectively, are to prepare their seven cattle for a showing at 2
p.m. today. The only consultants helping these Springfield, Mo.,
boys will be their father, Aaron Owen, and mother, Jennie Owen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We pretty much do all of it,'' said Adam, who has been showing
cattle since age 8. ``It is pretty much a family thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The boys will enter their cattle in the junior and open
categories. The showing for juniors is limited to minors.
</P>
<P>
   Although there are obvious disparities in the resources that the
teams commit to winning the blue ribbon, their motives are the
same.
</P>
<P>
   ``It (the competition) is basically to advertise what we have at
home,'' said Brad Bader, a Carrousel Farms owner.
</P>
<P>
   Bader, his brothers and father own Carrousel Farms, a large
family operation with divisions in Mineral Point and Monroe, Wis.
Bader, 39, said he showed animals when he was a boy. This year he
will fly into Kansas City, Mo., to see Sweetness and his other
cattle compete.
</P>
<P>
   Adam said he competed to have fun and to promote Owen Brothers
Cattle Co.'s 50-head herd. Adam said he did not have a problem with
owners who don't have time to prepare their own animals. He said he
had worked for some in the past.
</P>
<P>
   There are few trade secrets when it comes to showing animals,
Lindsey said. The real work takes place before any of the animals
arrive at the show. Breeding, feeding and handling the animals are
just as important, if not more important, than combing the hair the
right way, Lindsey said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually, the people that win have both good management and a
good animal,'' Lindsey said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are just all kinds of things that you have to do before
you get to a show to produce a winner,'' Lindsey said after
blow-drying Sweetness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spent a whole day clipping their hair,'' said Lindsey. ``All
the clipping and stuff is just to enhance their strong points and
hide their weak points.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to helping with the shows, Lindsey also helps make
breeding decisions. This is Carrousel Farms' first year at the
American Royal. Scheduling conflicts prevented Carrousel Farms from
attending previous shows.
</P>
<P>
   This year the other Limousin heifers will have to reckon with
Sweetness and all her majestic beauty. After being named supreme
champion at the World Beef Exposition in Milwaukee, Sweetness has a
good chance to take the crown in Kansas City, Lindsey said.
</P>
<P>
   The Owen Brothers raise Simmentals, so they will not compete
against Sweetness.
</P>
</TEXT>
