<SLUG> BC-EPA-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ST. LOUIS WOMAN TESTIFIES AT EPA HEARING ON RADIATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MANSUR  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's 1 p.m., and Kay Drey is still at the microphone. She's been
there for 40 minutes, testifying to federal officials. Actually,
she's reading to them now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Among the most incredible documents I have in my large nuclear
power and radioactive waste library,'' recites Drey, ``is a set of
technical reports from the 1980s about the need to meet the
challenges of warning human beings ... to avoid the lethal nuclear
electricity wastes we are leaving for them.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, how will humanity warn its progeny in 10,000
years of the dangerous wastes that may be buried in a mountain in
Nevada?
</P>
<P>
   Drey was the only person scheduled to testify Wednesday at a
national hearing in Kansas City, Mo. The U.S. Environmental
Protection Agency wanted to hear what the public thought about its
proposed limit on radiation from a nuclear waste repository,
currently proposed for Yucca Mountain in Nevada.
</P>
<P>
   Drey is a St. Louis environmentalist who has campaigned in
Missouri and across the nation for a quarter-century against
nuclear power and the disposal of nuclear wastes.
</P>
<P>
   To her, the very idea of burying the nation's nuclear wastes in
the ground raises so many questions it makes her dizzy. But the
most basic and unanswerable one, she told the federal officials, is
how to warn those who will follow us.
</P>
<P>
   Will we leave a sign? A video? How about an e-mail? What?
</P>
<P>
   ``How can we keep 300 generations of our descendants away from
these lethal wastes? Is it remotely possible?''
</P>
<P>
   Drey added that she had seen attempts at markers or signs that
could be left to warn of the buried wastes. One shows a figure with
what appears to be a shovel, a dark line slashing through it.
</P>
<P>
   Another, she added, shows a series of panels with what appear to
be men, although one person confused them as cattle, who are
standing near a hole with something liquidlike spewing out. In the
final panel, one of the figures has fallen to the ground, stricken
by some unknown danger.
</P>
<P>
   Drey held up for the federal officials other documents and a
statement she gave once in Washington to the National Academy of
Sciences. ``That day three of us testified,'' she quipped.
</P>
<P>
   Drey's talk inspired one other person to speak to the federal
officials Wednesday, expressing concerns about the hazards of
transporting the wastes through Kansas City and other urban
centers. Indeed, much of it will come through Kansas City. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Despite a turnout of just five, federal officials say the EPA's
proposed radiation limit for Yucca Mountain may be among the most
important yet resolved for one of America's most complex problems:
What should be done with the tons and tons of highly radioactive
spent nuclear fuel?
</P>
<P>
   ``It is disappointing,'' said Rafaela Ferguson of the EPA's
Radiation Information Center in Washington of the turnout in Kansas
City. ``We did expect more would testify.''
</P>
<P>
   This was the last of four hearings that the EPA has held across
the nation on its proposed radiation limit. The agency should issue
its final rule next summer.
</P>
<P>
   For years, nuclear power plants have given many Americans cheap
electricity; but now the time has come to dispose of the wastes.
The nuclear power industry wants the nation to store it in Yucca
Mountain, a 1,200-foot high volcanic ridge that extends for six
miles in Nevada.
</P>
<P>
   In its desert climate, little rain means there should be little
chance for the wastes to leak into ground water. But questions
still remain about Yucca Mountain. Yucca Mountain is still years
away from becoming the final choice for the wastes. If all
government approvals are won, the Department of Energy might seek
an application to build the site in 2002. Disposal isn't expected
to begin before 2010.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA's role is to set the limit of radiation that will be
allowed to escape from whatever repository is chosen. By law, the
agency must set a limit that is scientifically sound, reasonable to
implement and protective of human health and the environment, said
Frank Marcinowski, acting director of the EPA's radiation
protection division.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what the repository will be judged against,''
Marcinowski said of the importance of the radiation limit.
</P>
<P>
   Marcinowski led the hearing Wednesday, politely allowing the
passionate Drey to continue her remarks beyond the normal 10-minute
limit. There was, after all, no one else signed up to testify.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA has proposed a radiation limit of 15 millirem, a
radiation exposure equal to little less than two chest X-rays. The
Nuclear Regulatory Commission, however, has pushed for a less
stringent limit, one that would be easier to meet, Marcinowski
said.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA calculates the risk from exposure to 15 millirems as a 3
in 10,000 chance of developing a fatal cancer. The Nuclear
Regulatory Commission's proposal would result in a 5 in 10,000
risk.
</P>
<P>
   Drey actually supports the EPA here, although she has supported
little of what the federal government has done in its dealings with
the nuclear power industry.
</P>
<P>
   Drey's solution to the nuclear waste issue is to not ship the
irradiated fuel rods from more than 100 nuclear reactors by highway
and rail. Keep it at at the nuclear reactor sites until a better
solution is found.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Marcinowski called for a recess until someone wished to
speak.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who could that be?'' asked one woman in the sparse audience.
</P>
<P>
   All eyes fell on Drey. But Drey just sat. She had made her
point.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
