<SLUG> BC-DYSART-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARENTS SEEING RED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LORI BAKER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   All year, Dysart Elementary School's sixth-grade teachers have
complained that they can't teach science and social studies without
books.
</P>
<P>
   They made their point last week by giving every student in the
classes C's on their report cards.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mouth almost hit the floor,'' Deana Freet, who has a
sixth-grade daughter, said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they (the teachers) were being silly and stupid,''
said her daughter, Breanna, an 11-year-old honor roll student.
</P>
<P>
   The teachers, Bob Veigel and Pat Orlinski, told parents that
they decided to give the same grade, a ``C,'' to everyone in those
two subjects because of the shortage of textbooks, Freet said.
</P>
<P>
   The teachers would not comment, but their actions ignited a
firestorm of criticism from parents, teachers and their supervisors
at Dysart Unified School District.
</P>
<P>
   ``This situation is not only embarrassing, it is absolutely
unacceptable to all for us,'' Superintendent Margo Seck said
Wednesday. ``It is our strong belief that children should never be
penalized for the actions taken by adults.''
</P>
<P>
   Seck said administrative action will be taken against Veigel, a
long-term substitute teacher; and Orlinski, who started working as
a Dysart teacher this fall. But Seck didn't specify what will be
done. The Dysart Unified School Board is expected to discuss the
incident at its Tuesday meeting.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Seck issued a statement apologizing to the
students and their parents.
</P>
<P>
   Seck said there was a book shortage because there were more
sixth-graders than expected at Dysart Elementary, a new school that
opened this year in El Mirage. She said additional textbooks have
been ordered and should be on campus by early next week.
</P>
<P>
   Dysart Elementary Principal Marsha Baney said mentors, or
teaching coaches, provided lesson packets for the sixth-grade
teachers to use and photocopy because science and social studies
books had not arrived at the school at 11405 N. Dysart Road.
</P>
<P>
   ``Books are just one resource,'' Baney said.
</P>
<P>
   She is reviewing the two teachers' grade books to make sure
students are given a ``fair evaluation for their workquarter'' and will send a letter home to parents on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Parent April Allen said she wouldn't mind what grade her son,
Chris Gatti, got on his report card as long as he deserved it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so upset,'' Allen said about the teachers' move. ``I don't
feel like (Chris) is getting the same education as kids at other
schools in the district.''
</P>
<P>
   Teachers should use other resources to teach from if there
aren't enough books, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Emma Holm, a Glendale resident whose 4-year-old daughter attends
preschool at Dysart Elementary, said the two teachers were wrong to
give everyone ``C'' grades. Her son, Christopher, is a sixth-grader
at Luke Elementary, and there's a textbook shortage there, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``My son is an `A,' `B' student, and I'd be disappointed if he
got a `C,' '' Holm said.
</P>
<P>
   She said she believes what happened at Dysart Elementary is part
of a bigger problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a teacher shortage. The pay is so low that they can't
get the teachers out here to teach,'' Holm said.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Trujillo, a Surprise resident whose daughter, Alexis, is
a third-grader at Dysart Elementary, said he understands the
teachers' frustration.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are trying to do their jobs, but they don't have the
right resources,'' Trujillo said. ``What they did has drawn
attention, and now everybody knows about it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Freet said the sixth-grade teachers took the wrong approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am angry. They're not doing their job. Their job is to
teach, to challenge and prepare the students,'' she said. ``Why
should the child pay for the teachers not doing their job?'' &QL; 
The Associated Press contributed to this article. &QL; 
Lori Baker can be reached at (602) 444-7120 or at
lori.baker(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
