<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-WORLDSERIES-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: CLEMENS LEADS THE YANKEES TO THEIR THIRD TITLE IN
FOUR SEASONS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Roger Clemens earned his ring, not redemption,
Wednesday night at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   It was too late to annul 1986, or other postseason failures, if
that's what he had come here to do.
</P>
<P>
   It was too far along the trail of inevitability, which
dead-ended for the Atlanta Braves into a second straight four-game
World Series sweep for New York. The bandwagon Clemens jumped on
was too tough, too good, too focused on higher callings and
surviving actual trauma, like the death early Wednesday morning of
Paul O'Neill's father.
</P>
<P>
   ``A special day for Roger,'' manager Joe Torre said before
Clemens finally lived up to his billing. Clemens overpowered the
Braves as the Yankees won Game 4, 4-1, and unofficially captured
bragging rights to the 1990s, along with the rest of the century.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming to Yankee Stadium, in the Yankees' uniform,'' Torre
added, ``there will be a lot of emotion, but there won't be a lot
of baggage.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, for that matter, pressure.
</P>
<P>
   As it was all month, the tension created by fear of losing the
series was gone by the time Torre got around to his 37-year-old
future Hall of Fame right-hander. The Braves' manager, Bobby Cox,
had already guessed wrong too many times. The startlingly efficient
Yankees had made too many series-defining plays. All that was left
for Clemens was to toss 7 2-3 four-hit innings to punctuate the
Yankees' 25th title. The heavy lifting had already been done.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an awesome feeling to be back to have this chance
again,'' Clemens had said, 13 years after Game 6 slipped under Bill
Buckner's glove and the 1986 World Series went to the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Ancient history, yet indisputably a key element of the Roger
Clemens story. For all his 247 major league victories, his Cy Young
awards, his 20-strikeout games, the postseason had always been his
worst season. He joined the Yankees with one victory in nine
playoff starts, including an embarrassing 1990 league series
ejection against Oakland and his former nemesis, Dave Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my opinion,'' Stewart had said after Clemens left the Blue
Jays for the Yankees, ``Roger hasn't proved anything in postseason
yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart was mystified that Clemens preferred to pitch for a team
on which he would not likely be the main mound man, as opposed to
making a difference with the young Toronto staff. Stewart, it
turned out, was wrong about the Blue Jays, who never came close to
these playoffs, and right about the Yankees, who slotted Clemens
into their deep rotation as if he were Masato Yoshii.
</P>
<P>
   Orlando Hernandez became the regular and postseason ace. David
Cone threw a perfect game. Andy Pettitte stood tall after lifting
his head from the trading block. Mariano Rivera, out of the bullpen
to retire Chipper Jones with two on in the eighth and claim the
last three outs, was this team's Cy Young and the World Series most
valuable player.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't expect, you know, that Roger was going to win the Cy
Young award,'' Torre said. ``We felt he was a good fit.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens was, actually, more of a fitful presence among steady
veterans, a tightly wound Texan somewhat out of step on this
internationally flavored team. ``High-deki,'' Clemens called Hideki
Irabu during the Boston series, as if he'd just been introduced to
the roster. Monday, he was involved in a brief scuffle with a fan,
another unYankee-like occurrence during Torre's four-year reign of
tranquillity that has now brought three titles.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees digested Clemens' struggles, his ``baggage,'' as
they have everyone else's, with only a few hiccups. The true New
York angle of this team was how much it could assimilate, how much
it could absorb. The pregame news that O'Neill's father had died
was the latest in a numbing run of illness and tragedy. With a
damaged rib and an aching heart, O'Neill played on Wednesday night,
the way his team survived cancer in its clubhouse and the deaths of
three players' fathers in six weeks. It made this team's postseason
dominance, its 11-1 run, a breathtaking experience for those lucky
enough to be part of it.
</P>
<P>
   As a Yankee, Clemens had the chance to talk pitching last spring
with Catfish Hunter, months before Hunter would die of Lou Gehrig's
disease. He heard Paul Simon honor Joe DiMaggio in verse, from the
very space the departed DiMaggio once roamed. He saw Yogi Berra
come home to throw out the first ball on opening day. Before
Wednesday night's game, he went out to commune with the Babe Ruth
memorial in Monument Park.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens wore the most hallowed uniform in American sports, and
was given the ball with the ring within reach. It was too late in
the series for this to be about personal redemption. It was
something far better than that. It was about winning, as a Yankee.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-99 0055EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991028.0017 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 00:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
