u s BC-HKN-DEVILS-BLUES-NYT &LR;      10-28 0575
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-BLUES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEW THRILLS AS DEVILS TOP BLUES, 2-1
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ The New Jersey Devils were hardly at
their best Wednesday night, but they accomplished what they wanted,
a 2-1 victory over the St. Louis Blues in a game at Continental
Arena where the announced crowd of 13,347 seemed to be more
interested in the baseball game in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Brodeur was outstanding, making 23 saves and just missing
his second shutout of the season and 38th of his career with 3
minutes 50 seconds left in the game when Scott Young beat him over
the stick from the right circle.
</P>
<P>
   Brodeur was fortunate on the last play of the game, when Pavol
Demitra missed the goal as time expired with the Devils standing
around watching, thinking that Demitra was off side.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was weird,'' Brodeur said of the last play. ``Everybody
stopped. We were lucky he didn't get off a better shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Randy McKay and Brian Rolston scored for the Devils, who
improved to 5-3-1. They took 23 shots against Roman Turek, who had
a four-game winning streak coming into the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Blues came into the game having won 6 of 7 and scoring 27
goals during that span. The Devils had lost their previous two
games, both on the road, including a 3-1 loss at St. Louis on
Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   The two teams were simply awful for the most part, especially
the first two periods, and the crowd seemed more intent on
following the Yankees' World Series clincher on portable radios,
cheering at the Yanks' big moments.
</P>
<P>
   The Blues came out strong and took the first three shots in the
game, but did little after that.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils failed to capitalize on three manpower advantages,
including a two-man advantage for 1:37, but they opened the scoring
with 54.3 seconds left before the first intermission. The goal came
when McKay took a short pass from Petr Sykora and beat Turek to the
short side from the left circle. It was the second goal of the
season for McKay, who got his first last Friday night in the
overtime loss in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Rolston scored what proved to be the winner, at 1:55 of the
second period, when he skated to the front from behind the goal to
the left of Turek and scored with a shot that beat Turek between
the legs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he saw the shot,'' Rolston said. ``Sometimes we
get down on ourselves. Sure, there are a lot of things we can do
better. We wanted to go out there and get two points and that's
what we did tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   With Jason Arnott, the center for the first line, sidelined with
a broken dental bridge, coach Robbie Ftorek shuffled his line
combinations a great deal again. Sergei Nemchinov started as the
center for the first line, but he moved to another combination in
the second period.
</P>
<P>
   Another unusual line combination for the Devils was Petr Sykora
moving to left wing with Bobby Holik the center and McKay the right
wing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting better results because we're playing more
physical,'' Sykora said. ``When things don't go well we try to make
too many nice passes and it doesn't work.''
</P>
<P>
   Ftorek's line combinations will change again once Patrik Elias
and Brendan Morrison are declared fit to play after having signed
belatedly. They practiced with the team for the first time Tuesday
and there is a possibility they will return by Friday or Saturday,
when the Devils play at Carolina and then Philadelphia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
