<HEADER>
A0870 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-AMERICAN-PILOTS-TEX     10-28 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICAN-PILOTS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN AIRLINES, UNION NEGOTIATE DEBT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAN REED 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The board of American Airlines' pilots union
is considering proposals that could erase the labor group's $45.5
million debt to the carrier in exchange for changes to the current
contract, sources familiar with the discussions said Wednesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   The union and American issued a joint release late Wednesday
night, saying the changes could include an extension to the
contract, which is not scheduled to come up for renegotiation until
August 2001. Also possible is a loosening of restrictions on
American's ability to partner with foreign airlines and its
American Eagle commuter affiliate, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   The developments marked the most serious effort yet to begin
repairing the contentious relationship between the Fort Worth-based
carrier and the Allied Pilots Association, which represents
American's 10,000 pilots. That relationship exploded in February
when 2,500 American pilots engaged in what a judge later ruled was
an illegal, 11-day sickout that forced the cancellation of 6,700
flights. The dispute centered on American's plans to integrate
pilots from the newly acquired Reno Air into American's pilot
corps.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Joe Kendall assessed $45.5 million in
damages against the union and its top two officers this year after
the sickout. The damage award is to reimburse American for losses
it incurred when the union and its leadership did not respond
quickly enough to an order by Kendall to get pilots back to work.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night's vaguely worded joint release _ issued after 9
p.m. CDT _ said the union's board, meeting this week in Fort Worth,
will consider several ``concepts and proposals'' jointly developed
by management and the union board.
</P>
<P>
   The proposals are ``aimed at resolving a number of past and
current disputes and improving the working relationship between the
APA and American.''
</P>
<P>
   The announcement offered no specifics. But sources familiar with
discussions between American and the pilots leadership said the
board will consider more than one proposal.
</P>
<P>
   The board will consider steps that it could take that could lead
to American forgiving part or all of the union's debt.
</P>
<P>
   Anything that the union board considers will probably be
controversial within the board, which has a history of internal
division, and with its membership. The membership would also have
to ratify any changes to the contract.
</P>
<P>
   The sources said American is probably seeking cost savings and
revenue-boosting opportunities through a contract extension that
would more than offset American's forgiveness of the damages.
</P>
<P>
   A contract extension would allow management to lock in labor
rates over a longer period. Typically, such extensions provide
modest savings to the airline over time, and allow it to do
longer-range financial planning that can reduce financing costs.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, American currently is limited by its Allied Pilots
contract in its ability to partner with foreign airlines and
American Eagle. The APA has resisted efforts by American to align
with other carriers, because the union views such deals as threats
to its pilots' careers.
</P>
<P>
   For example, American last year had to reduce the number of
flights it offered to Canada because it mistakenly allowed its
Canadian Airlines partner to fly a greater percentage of their
jointly marketed transborder flights than was allowed under the APA
contract.
</P>
<P>
   Sources said Wednesday night that American will probably seek
more freedom to partner with other carriers. Airlines have
aggressively partnered with other carriers in recent years as a way
of expanding their networks.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the talks will lead to anything concrete is not clear.
The sides have been talking in recent weeks, officially and through
informal channels.
</P>
<P>
   American Chairman Donald Carty has said in recent weeks that he
is very reluctant to forgive the union's debt. Carty has made clear
that he won't do so unless he feels mutual trust has been restored.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, APA President Rich LaVoy and Vice President Brian
Mayhew and other union leaders met with Carty and other American
senior executives to discuss ways to repair the management-pilot
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   After the meeting, LaVoy said he made clear to Carty that the
relationship could not be repaired so long as the company insisted
on collecting the damage award.
</P>
<P>
   Sources said Wednesday night that union officials became more
interested in cutting a deal in the past two weeks at least partly
out of concern about an upcoming hearing in Kendall's court.
</P>
<P>
   In early September, Kendall ordered the two sides to appear in
his court in November. The order came a few days after final
negotiations on integrating Reno Air's 300 pilots into American's
operations broke off and American proceeded with the integration
Aug. 31 without a deal.
</P>
<P>
   The sources said one issue Kendall apparently wants to explore
in the hearing is whether additional members of the union board
should be held partially liable for the $45.5 million in damages.
Kendall has held only LaVoy and Mayhew liable, along with the
union.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
