<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 00:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0871 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-WORLDSERIES-BRAVE     10-28 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-WORLDSERIES-BRAVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAVES ARE BEATEN BUT UNBOWED 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The fans had mocked their war chant, and Queen was
warbling ``We Are the Champions'' when Atlanta's John Rocker turned
into the clubhouse as the Yankees celebrated their world
championship on the field at Yankee Stadium last night.
</P>
<P>
   But the Atlanta Braves did not exhibit the devastation that
normally accompanies a World Series loss, choosing instead to focus
on the season of remarkable adversity and triumph that had brought
them close enough for the Yankees to beat them.
</P>
<P>
   ''We came up short and it feels bad,'' said Rocker, the verbose
reliever. ``But I'm sure it doesn't feel nearly as bad as some of
the guys who watched us at home on television. I had a great time.
There's nothing like taunting people and then going out and beating
their team,'' he said referring to the Braves' victory over the New
York Mets in the National League Championship Series.
</P>
<P>
   And then Rocker laughed and this was clearly not going to be
your normal post-sweep post-mortem. Players looked more tired than
upset and there was plenty of banter among them.
</P>
<P>
   In a perverse way, the Braves' experience with losing World
Series _ this was their fourth loss in five tries in the 1990s _
helped them. Rather than dwell on the potential embarrassment of
being swept by the Yankees, they could comfort themselves with the
knowledge that they had won more games in the decade than any other
team, that few teams had gotten as close to a title once, as the
Braves had over and over.
</P>
<P>
   ''You have to be good to lose so many World Series,'' pitcher
Greg Maddux said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, but that leads to the inevitable question of what
becomes of the Braves. After a season in which they lost several
key components _ Andres Galarraga, fighting cancer, made his way
through the clubhouse, talking to his teammates _ the Braves felt
vindicated and heroic for just making it back to the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   When closer Kerry Lightenberg was hurt, Rocker emerged. With
Galarraga and Javy Lopez lost, Chipper Jones produced a most
valuable player-level season. But this is a team constructed to win
championships. They have had perhaps the best pitching rotation in
baseball and have been to the National League Championship Series
eight times, but they have won the World Series just once.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have won three of the last four championships and
the unavoidable conclusion is that the Braves expend everything
they have to be the best team of the regular season, only to come
up short in the post-season.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're asking guys all year to pick up the lead from the guys
we counted on,'' pitcher John Smoltz said. ``It can get difficult.
There is no solace or reward in knowing how much we scratched and
clawed to get here. The overwhelming feeling from everybody is we
better win or else. And that's the level we have established. We're
trying as hard as we can to win the World Series. When you lose
early it's `Oh well, we'll get `em next year.' When you lose late,
it's not get `em next year. It's a disappointment. This is a
disappointment but it's not the end of the world. The last three
days, with Payne Stewart's death and Paul O'Neill's dad should tell
you that. It's a baseball game. It's important, but it's still a
baseball game.''
</P>
<P>
   Second baseman Bret Boone figured that the mood in the clubhouse
would have been much darker had the series been closer. But the
Braves knew how much trouble they were in long before Chad Curtis
caught the final fly ball to end the series and most of them, even
in their disaappointment, repeated endlessly their admiration _
even awe _ of the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Just minutes after the end of their season, before he was even
fully dressed, Chipper Jones began to talk about spring training.
The Braves will likely return the bulk of their team and _ although
the Mets will surely work in the off-season to add the pieces to
challenge the Braves again _ the Braves will be the favorites until
proven otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've won one more championship than 25 or 26 other teams,''
Jones said. ``You can only look at this organization as a
tremendous success. It hasn't worked out in the post-season but
come spring training, and we'll still have the same goal. I don't
see a big overhaul within the organization. A lot of the core
people should be healthy. Everybody comes into spring training the
same way _ eager to start a championship season. And frankly, this
was a championship season for us. Nobody gave us a chance to be
here. We're down for the time being but we'll walk out proud.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
