<HEADER>
A0875 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BBO-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX     10-28 0879
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
 
UNDISPUTED KINGS OF CENTURY WIN IN PINSTRIPE STYLE (For use by
NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A pinstriped curtain dropped on the World Series'
first 95 years Wednesday night at Yankee Stadium. Alone, at center
stage, stands the team of the 20th century: The mighty New York
Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Take a knee and pay homage. It is highly unlikely we will ever
see another sports franchise dominate an era like the Yankees have
the one that ended Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees were the century's undisputed kings even before the
95th World Series began, but their relentless four-game sweep of
the helpless Atlanta Braves, capped by Wednesday night's 4-1
triumph, validates their place in history.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Clemens may have finally crossed the invisible threshold
that separates ordinary players and ``Yankees.'' He earned his
pinstripes Wednesday night by giving his team the kind of big-game
performance they've been expecting from him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now,'' Clemens said, ``I know what it feels like to be a
Yankee.''
</P>
<P>
   Indestructible closer Mariano Rivera, named the Series MVP,
flicked the Braves away with a minimal effort in the ninth: three
up, three down.
</P>
<P>
   When Keith Lockhart's routine pop fly settled into Chad Curtis'
glove for the final out, the players rushed the mound and the
sellout crowd went crazy, but it was a subdued celebration compared
with '96, when the entire team did a tour around the warning track
and Wade Boggs leaped up behind a mounted policeman for an
impromptu ride.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it was because this one came so easy. It was, incredibly,
the Yankees' 12th consecutive World Series victory and their 25th
World Series championship. No other franchise in the major leagues
has more than nine.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so hard to win one and now we've won three,'' first
baseman Tino Martinez said. ``I'm still pinching myself. It must be
a dream.''
</P>
<P>
   In postseason play over the past two Octobers, the Yankees are
an amazing 22-3. ``22-3!'' Obviously not all of that came at the
Rangers' expense.
</P>
<P>
   To try to measure the Yankees by mere numbers, however, would be
an injustice, for this is a team of heart and soul, of muscle and
bone, of blood and tears.
</P>
<P>
   No one exemplifies that more than manager Joe Torre, who shared
hugs with his coaching staff, then moved among his players, half
laughing, half weeping.
</P>
<P>
   Torre's third World Series championship in four years may have
been the most satisfying because he wasn't sure, when doctors told
him he had prostate cancer in the spring, that he'd be around to
see it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been an emotional year,'' Torre had said before the
Yankees clinched Wednesday night. ``I can tell you, in March,
baseball, much less the World Series, was the furthest thing from
my mind at that point in time.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hear the word `cancer' and it scares you. You think of
death. I wanted to be around more for (his daughter) than to do
this. Now (baseball) is just as important as it ever was, except
that I think I smell and feel everything more so than I did in the
past. It's' just that I appreciate every single day.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre's story is just one of the many melodramas that have
surrounded the Yankees over the last few years. Since September
three players have lost their fathers, including Paul O'Neill's
dad, who died early yesterday after a long illness. O'Neill played
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played with some heavy hearts,'' said Clemens, who carried
a shutout into the eighth. ``I don't know if I could have done what
Paul O'Neill did tonight, to go out there and play, or Luis Sojo,
whose father died last week.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Yankees simply persevere. Their four-year run of
on-field success has been woven with tragedy and illness, from
pitcher David Cone's aneurysm in 1996, to Frank Torre's dramatic
heart transplant during that year's Series, to Darryl Strawberry's
colon cancer, to the deaths of Yankees legends Joe DiMaggio and
Catfish Hunter.
</P>
<P>
   If a soap opera script writer tried to sell us this story, we
wouldn't buy it. Too fantastic. Too unbelievable.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night's victory over the Braves, who had the
misfortune of playing the role of Washington Generals to the
Yankees' Globetrotters twice in the past four seasons, was typical
of the Yanks' run.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves' defense wavered briefly in the third, when two
ground balls were misplayed into questionable hits. Martinez's
one-hopper that clanged off first baseman Ryan Klesko's glove
plated two runs and Jorge Posada's line single drove in another.
</P>
<P>
   When the Braves nicked Clemens for a run in the eighth, Torre
simply summoned Rivera to get the final four outs. Pinch hitter Jim
Leyritz bumped the Yanks' lead back to three with a solo homer in
the bottom of the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Expectations of this team were probably a little unfair after
we won 125 games last year,'' shortstop Derek Jeter said. ``We just
went out and took care of business and played every game like it
was the last one of the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night's was the last one of the 1900s.
</P>
<P>
   Who knows which sports franchise will produce the team of
destiny in the next century. As for this one, there is no question.
</P>
<P>
   All hail the Yankees, undisputed champions of the world. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
