<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-SERIES-LEDE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRIDE OF THE '90S: YANKEES SWEEP AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Team of the Decade battle is over. A convincing
knockout has been scored. Time now to place the New York Yankees of
the late 1990s among the greatest teams ever assembled.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees earned that right with devastating effectiveness in
all areas of the game, completing a four-game sweep of the Atlanta
Braves with a 4-1 victory Wednesday night in Game 4 of the World
Series.
</P>
<P>
   A crowd of 56,752 at Yankee Stadium roared their approval from
the beginning as Roger Clemens, acquired from the Toronto Blue Jays
just for this purpose, overpowered the Braves for 7 2/3 innings and
World Series Most Valuable Player Mariano Rivera finished it off.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is everything everybody said it would be,'' said Clemens,
after his first World Series victory ever and first appearance
since 1986. ``I just feel blessed to be a part of this. It's
great.''
</P>
<P>
   The end came when Rivera got Keith Lockhart to hit a weak fly
ball to left. When the ball settled into left fielder Chad Curtis'
glove, catcher Jorge Posada jumped into Rivera's embrace on the
mound.
</P>
<P>
   Third baseman Scott Brosius was right behind them and the rest
of their teammates followed. Light bulbs popped throughout the
historic stadium as fans took pictures of a team that had just won
its third World Series title in the past four years and 25th in
franchise history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say enough about this team,'' shortstop Derek Jeter
said. ``This is just a team that knows how to win.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have won the last two World Series with four-game
sweeps, the San Diego Padres last year and now the Braves, a team
that won 103 games during the regular season. The only two other
teams to sweep two consecutive World Series were the 1927-28
Yankees of Babe Ruth and Lou Gehrig, and the 1938-39 Yankees of Joe
DiMaggio and Bill Dickey.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees won an American League-record 114 regular-season
games last year, but manager Joe Torre had higher praise for this
team, even though they won 16 less games.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will never be anything like the first one in '96,''
Torre said. ``After what we accomplished last year, to come back
and win it again, it was a better team only because to do it again
to validate what we did last year. There's no question this club is
very, very special.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a strong suspicion throughout baseball that this would
happen when the Yankees acquired Clemens from the Blue Jays at the
start of spring training. Clemens himself said this was why he
wanted to play for the Yankees instead of the Rangers or Houston
Astros.
</P>
<P>
   Those hopes and fears were realized and Clemens made it happen
by holding the Braves to just four singles through 7 2/3 innings.
The Yankees got him the runs he needed in the third on a two-run
single by Tino Martinez _ a hard ground ball that clanked off the
glove of first baseman Ryan Klesko _ and a run-scoring single by
Jorge Posada off losing pitcher John Smoltz.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was the perfect way of ending the World Series,''
Torre said. ``The man came over here because he wanted a World
Series ring I couldn't see it not happening with the way his career
has gone. It just seemed like the perfect setup for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens had a chance of finishing with a complete-game shutout
until Walt Weiss, with two outs in the eighth, stepped on his foot
while he was covering first base.
</P>
<P>
   Weiss was safe on the infield grounder and Clemens tried to stay
in the game. But when Gerald Williams lined a single to left,
manager Joe Torre went to the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sure was going to let him go out in the ninth and go one
batter at a time,'' Torre said. ``But then when he was stepped on
at first base, he seemed to get a little out of whack.''
</P>
<P>
   He tried Jeff Nelson first but Bret Boone bounced a single up
the middle to score Weiss. With runners at first and third. Torre
then went with Rivera and he doused the threat by getting Chipper
Jones on a grounder to second. After Jim Leyritz homered for the
Yankees in the bottom of the inning, Rivera pitched a scoreless
ninth and the Braves were finished.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not very fun losing four straight and getting swept,''
said Braves manager Bobby Cox, whose team had to listen to mock
``Tomahawk Chop'' chants for much of the game. ``I thought we
played better than what it showed. We could have won two ... but
their pitching was excellent, they're so strong. That ballclub
deserves to be world champions. They're very good.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
