<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 01:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0877 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT     10-28 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: BRAVES' GETTING THERE IS NOT GOOD ENOUGH 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ How will history remember Bobby Cox and the Atlanta
Braves? For the last decade, the manager and his team have done
nearly everything an organization is supposed to do.
</P>
<P>
   They lost again to the Yankees on Wednesday night, this time by
4-1, and they were swept from the World Series. Was this a tribute
to the Yankees' might or did the series expose Atlanta's flaws?
Will history remember how the Yankees thoroughly dominated the four
games or will it recall how Atlanta lost much of its offense and
still won more than 100 games in the regular season?
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it depends on how we view winning. Do we recognize
greatness in the playoffs and series or consistency during the
regular season? ``We would have liked to make it a better series,''
Cox said on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   At the beginning of the decade, while the Yankees were still
struggling, Atlanta came on strong. In 1991, after finishing last
the previous year, the Braves completed one of the most impressive
turnabouts in baseball history. They finished in first place in
their division and made it to the World Series, which they lost.
</P>
<P>
   The following year the Braves also reached the World Series.
They lost.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Atlanta again made it to the Series. This time the
Braves finally prevailed, winning the city's first professional
sports championship.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996 Atlanta was back in baseball's showcase again, this time
falling to the resurgent Yankees. And, of course, this season the
Braves played their way into the Series _ their fifth of the 1990s
_ despite a succession of injuries that would have crushed a less
resilient team.
</P>
<P>
   That's a lot of World Series appearances in one decade. A lot of
losses, too.
</P>
<P>
   With the Braves now swept out of the decade's last World Series,
the question is simple: can the Braves lay claim any more to being
a great team? Or are they just a good, consistent team that could
not prevail when the games counted most in late October?
</P>
<P>
   In some ways Games 3 and Game 4 were a metaphor for what the
Braves have accomplished and failed to accomplish. After being shut
down by Roger Clemens for seven innings, Atlanta battled back and
cut the lead to 3-1. Then the Yankees went to Jim Leyritz, who
homered in the bottom of the eighth inning to put the game away.
</P>
<P>
   A series of more poignant moments took place a day earlier, when
the Yankees effectively ended Atlanta's hopes for the series in
Game 3. In the bottom of the first inning, Chuck Knoblauch led off
with a sharp line drive in the gap between right field and center
field. Brian Jordan, Atlanta's right fielder, made a great effort
to get to the ball and tried a back-handed stab. The ball popped
out of his glove for a tough error.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch wound up at second base and later scored. So which do
we reward: Jordan's effort or the outcome? The Atlanta Braves of
the 1990s are like the Minnesota Vikings of the 1970s and the
Buffalo Bills of the late 1980s and early '90s: teams that
dominated their divisions and consistently reached championship
games, but that were not so adept at winning them.
</P>
<P>
   In the silence of a devastated clubhouse late Tuesday night,
Jordan made an observation about the game that could define the
Atlanta decade. ``We felt like we had the game wrapped up,'' Jordan
said, describing the team's mood as the Yankees came to bat in the
bottom of the eighth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Down by two games to the Yankees, watching a 5-1 lead slip to
5-3, the Braves thought they had the game wrapped up.
</P>
<P>
   As they began to shut down, the Yankees geared up. Curtis hit a
home run in the fifth. Tino Martinez homered in the seventh. Then
Knoblauch completed the comeback with a two-run homer in the
eighth. Then Curtis homered again, just over Jordan's outstretched
glove.
</P>
<P>
   How will history remember Bobby Cox and the Atlanta Braves?
About 45 minutes after the game ended on Wednesday night, Chipper
Jones, the Braves' third baseman, spoke admiringly about the
Yankees. He said Wednesday night's loss was tough, but what had
convinced Atlanta that they were in over their heads was Tuesday's
defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sat on the bus after that game,'' he said. ``And I was
thinking to myself that this was the first time in my pro career
that the Atlanta Braves had done everything that they had to do and
still lost. We played decent. We hit. We got good pitching. And
they still beat us. That was kind of scary.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes good is good enough. Sometimes good enough doesn't
quite get it. In Atlanta's case, just getting there is about as
good as it gets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
