<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILSON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNCOMMON KITTEN MAKES BRIEF, BUT LASTIN IMPRESSION 
</HEADLINE>
 -COLM-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE WILSON  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - I've written dozens of obituaries in my career, but
until Wednesday none for a cat.
</P>
<P>
   Pumpkin died Saturday. The cause was feline infectious
peritonitis, an unusual but deadly viral disease. He had orange
stripes and was 6 months old. Survivors include a brother,
Marmalade.
</P>
<P>
   Cats have never been a big hit with me. I'm a dog person, but
I'm married to someone who loves cats, so they've come into my life
unbidden.
</P>
<P>
   They've also come onto my desk, pushing off everything that's
not nailed down; jumped on the breakfast table, poking holes in my
newspaper; laid claim to my recliner, where one has peed several
times; and, of course, presumed our bed exists mainly for their
comfort and enjoyment.
</P>
<P>
   Have you ever lay down to nap and, as you were drifting off,
felt something brush lightly against your cheek, then opened your
eyes to see a cat's face one inch away, staring intently at you?
</P>
<P>
   Or needed to walk downstairs during the night and tripped over a
furtive cat lying at the top of the stairs, seeing you approach and
moving not a muscle, blocking your path with absolute indifference?
</P>
<P>
   It's been said that cats are smarter than dogs because you can't
get eight cats to pull a sled through snow, but that misses a
larger point. You can't get cats to do anything.
</P>
<P>
   My wife, Debbie, adopted Pumpkin and Marmalade in June from a
young girl who was giving away a hard-to-resist litter in front of
the Wal-Mart in Payson.
</P>
<P>
   On the bell curve of cats, they were on the right extreme _
frisky, friendly, warm and well-mannered. They chased each other
through the house and, like pro wrestlers, pounced on each other in
mock aggression. They even liked to play with our dogs. When Debbie
worked at her desk at night, Pumpkin often sat in her lap.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past two weeks, however, he seemed less energetic and
looked thinner. He was still eating but wasn't himself. When
Marmalade started to roughhouse, he barely bothered to defend
himself.
</P>
<P>
   We took him to see the vet and were given the grim diagnosis of
FIP, a disease that's rare outside of multicat households and is
nearly always fatal. Dr. Mark Weaver explained there was little he
could do. Pumpkin was current on his shots, but they didn't cover
this disease. Though a vaccine has been developed specifically for
FIP, Weaver seldom recommends it because the disease is so
uncommon.
</P>
<P>
   We took the kitten home, unsure whether it was better to hope
for an unlikely recovery or put him out of his distress. He was a
gritty stalwart, making no sounds, staying alert, resting quietly
by himself in a corner. He reminded me of an observation by James
Thurber about the way many dogs handle their final days:
</P>
<P>
   ``Death, to a dog, is the final unavoidable compulsion, the last
ineluctable scent on a fearsome trail, but they like to face it
alone, going out into the woods, among the leaves . . . enduring
without sentimental human distraction the Last Loneliness, which
they are wise enough to know cannot be shared by anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday morning, he looked worse. His belly was distended, and
he seemed to wince when he walked. Though the Squaw Peak Animal
Hospital was only five minutes away, the drive seemed much longer.
He was just a kitten, he trusted us, and taking him to be put down
felt awful.
</P>
<P>
   Weaver placed him on a table and shaved the hair off a front leg
to find the vein more easily. Debbie held the kitten while the vet
injected a barbiturate called Beuthanasia into him. He didn't make
a sound or even quiver. After no more than 10 seconds, he was gone,
his amber eyes open but still.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, I went to the Arizona Humane Society in search of his
successor. Last year, the society took in 45,295 dogs and cats and
placed 16,623 of them, an adoption total that ranked No. 1 in the
nation, according to a national survey.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Beth Johnsen helped me find a 2-month-old, cream-colored
kitten we named Cloudy. He's got the makings of a fine feline but
has big paws to follow.
</P>
<P>
   Pumpkin was a prince of a kitten who gave cats a good name. I
think he somehow had a little dog in him. &QL; 
Steve Wilson can be reached at (602) 444-8775, or at
steve.wilson(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
