<HEADLINE>
DALLAS BURN ROARS BACK, ADVANCES IN MLS PLAYOFFS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BLANE BACHELOR 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ For all the pregame talk that went into Wednesday
night's decisive Game 3 of the Western Conference semifinals
between the Dallas Burn and the Chicago Fire, Burn coach Dave Dir
couldn't find the words to express his thoughts afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that was because so much went into his team's 3-2
comeback victory Wednesday night at the Cotton Bowl, sending the
defending Major League Soccer champion home and giving the Burn a
trip to the conference finals beginning Sunday against the Los
Angeles Galaxy.
</P>
<P>
   After taking its worst loss of the season in Game 2 at Soldier
Field, a 4-0 drubbing from Chicago, the Burn appeared headed for
elimination when the Fire went up 2-0 in the first five minutes.
But the Burn rallied for three unanswered second-half goals,
including a 86th-minute game winner from forward Ariel Graziani, to
the delight of 9,795 fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm actually almost out of words, which is unusual for me,''
Dir said. ``I've got two championships in the A-league, and they
weren't anything like this. I don't think there's ever a bigger win
to knock off the champion. It's incredible. I wish we had a little
bit more time to enjoy it, because we've got to get ready for Los
Angeles.''
</P>
<P>
   The Burn faces the Galaxy at 4:30 p.m. Sunday at the Rose Bowl
in Game 1 of the best-of-three Western Conference finals, but at
least for Wednesday, some celebration was understandable.
Especially considering the Burn was without two mainstays on
defense _ defender Brandon Pollard, who suffered a broken leg after
a tackle in Game 2, and sweeper Richard Farrer _ and entered the
game with an 0-10 record this season when conceding the first goal.
</P>
<P>
   The Burn opened the game seemingly still shell shocked from Game
2, as Chicago forged a 2-0 lead in a span of five minutes, leaving
the Dallas defense _ which also included goalkeeper Mark Dodd, in
just his fourth start of the season _ stunned.
</P>
<P>
   Forward Ante Razov struck first, collecting a one-touch pass
from defender Lubos Kubik near the 18-yard line and pulling off a
spin move before slamming the ball into the net. Two minutes later,
a free kick from Kubik found its mark onto the foot of Jesse
Marsch, who redirected the ball around Dodd.
</P>
<P>
   The 2-0 lead seemed to jolt the Burn into the reality of its
season on the line, and Dallas settled into a more consistent
passing rhythm. Ten minutes into the second half, midfielder Chad
Deering was on the mark for the Burn. Midfielder Oscar Pareja laid
out a rolling ball to Sergi Daniv, who chipped a cross a few yards
out of the goal for Deering to head into the net, cutting Chicago's
lead to 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   The equalizer came in the 84th minute, off a penalty kick from
Jorge Rodriguez, but not without some controversy. Chicago defender
C.J. Brown was whistled for a hand ball off a shot from Daniv to
set up the kick. The ball bounced off Brown's arm as he slid into
Daniv attempting to block the shot inside the 18-yard line, which
could have been considered an unintentional hand ball that would
not result in a penalty kick.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought (the goalkeeper) was down so I dove out to try to
stop the ball,'' Brown said. ``My arms were close to my body, and I
thought (the referee) he wouldn't call a penalty. But he saw it
differently.''
</P>
<P>
   There was plenty else to call as well, as the teams combined for
a league-record 10 yellow cards in a playoff game. Graziani was
involved in much of the early pushing and shoving, but he stayed
composed enough to break free during a late-game scramble in front
of the net to knock in the game-winner, which landed just over the
goal line after bouncing off the crossbar. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
