<SLUG> BC-BKW-BIG </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG 12 WOMEN'S BASKETBALL READY TO ASSUME ELITE STATUS
</HEADLINE>
 12-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ It is significant that a team with one of the league's
top returning stars and five other players with starting experience
from an NCAA Tournament team is picked to finish fourth this season
in the Big 12 Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Especially when that team is Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at our roster and you say we're going to be more
experienced and we're going to be better and let's see how it all
plays out,'' Longhorns women's basketball coach Jody Conradt said
Wednesday. ``Then you start looking at other teams and say, `They
didn't lose anyone and they've got all these great players back'
and it is frightening. I'm trying not to think about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Two-time defending champion Texas Tech, meanwhile, is picked to
finish fifth. A reasonable conclusion is that this is a conference
that has come of age approaching its fourth season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our growth has been dramatic,'' said Iowa State coach Bill
Fennelly, whose Elite Eight team from last spring is picked to win
the Big 12 this season.
</P>
<P>
   Five Big 12 teams won 1999 NCAA Tournament berths; four others
landed in the Women's National Invitation Tournament. Iowa State
and Tech went as far as the Sweet 16.
</P>
<P>
   Only the Southeastern Conference had more teams _ eight _ in the
NCAA Tournament. Nationally, the Big 12 was a consensus No. 2 in
ratings power indexes behind the SEC. And, the Big 12 surpassed the
SEC in total and average attendance, ranking only behind the Big 10
in both categories.
</P>
<P>
   Those kinds of numbers add credence to conference coaches'
contention that the Big 12 is due national respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone in the country recognizes how good we are except the
SEC,'' Conradt said. ``They continue to be arrogant and think
they're the best. But don't print that because this is our year to
go to Knoxville'' to play Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Conradt was smiling, sort of, when she made that comment.
</P>
<P>
   But other conference coaches didn't leave her out on the verbal
limb when it came time to boast about the Big 12. And with 10 of
last season's top 12 scorers and seven members of the consensus
All-Big 12 first and second teams returning, they can afford to
talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key to our league is that there are no weak sisters,''
said Nebraska coach Paul Sanderford, who took his 1992 Western
Kentucky team to the championship game and has 14 NCAA appearances
to his credit. ``Even in the SEC, there are certain places you go
and can expect to win. That's not true in the Big 12.''
</P>
<P>
   Amen, said Tech coach Marsha Sharp, who, like Conradt, has a
national championship in her resume.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Big 12 is the best conference from top to
bottom,'' Sharp said. ``There might be a couple of teams at the top
of the SEC who have been better in postseason play. But from the
strength of all our teams, the numbers that we had in postseason
and the kind of attendance that we're beginning to have at all the
arenas _ the Big 12 is the best. Our job is to prove that to the
rest of the country.''
</P>
<P>
   That means putting teams into the Final Four. Only Texas and
Tech have played during the NCAA Tournament's last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's our next step as a league,'' Fennelly said. ``Someone
from our league has got to get into the Final Four and contend for
the national championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we obviously have some teams this year who have a
chance to do something in the tournament. Our hope is that our team
is one of them.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
