<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLTS' MANNING LOOKS SUSPICIOUSLY FAMILIAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The old NFL quarterback was asked Wednesday about the young NFL
quarterback who has the same bloodlines and last name.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, I'm not objective,'' Archie Manning answered
softly. ``He's my son. But I really like the way he plays. I like
the way he goes about his job. Football is very important to
Peyton. Being a success at football is very vital. He reminds me of
Troy.''
</P>
<P>
   That same echo was coming from Valley Ranch this week as the
Cowboys with ``old-timer'' Troy Aikman prepare to play the Colts
with the ``QB Kid,'' Peyton Manning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of us were watching film on Peyton the other day,'' said
personnel director Larry Lacewell, ``and we were all talking about
him being a young Troy. The physical toughness, the mental
toughness, the quick release, the being drafted by a bad team,
playing as a rookie and taking that beating Peyton took last season
_ and now the progress being seen this season by Peyton and by the
team. It's a definite pattern.''
</P>
<P>
   And, according to Archie, maybe not a coincidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going back to high school, I never told Peyton to find a hero
or a role model,'' Dad said Wednesday from his home in New Orleans,
``but I did mention long ago if he wanted to pattern himself after
an NFL quarterback to take a look at Aikman. I love Troy's
disposition. He's very even-keel on the field. He's all business,
and he's prepared to handle whatever course a game takes.''
</P>
<P>
   Interesting, huh? An Archie Manning finding a strong positive in
something so many around here term a negative for Aikman _ the lack
of rah, rah, rah.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, did Peyton really need Aikman as a quarterbacking
role model? Young Manning always had a good one at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could see the Archie influence when he was in college at
Tennessee,'' Lacewell said. ``Peyton learned from his daddy. You
see all these young quarterbacks struggling, but none of them had
at that kind of counseling at their own doorstep.''
</P>
<P>
   Archie will forever be known in NFL lore as the
greatest-quarterback-who-ever-lived-who-never-won-nothing. Eleven
years with the New Orleans Saints, and never even had a winning
``season.''
</P>
<P>
   That was back in the '70s and early '80s. Yet bring up Archie's
name today in league circles, and the reverence among football
people remains immense.
</P>
<P>
   Manning was very gifted. Manning was very cursed. The luck of
the draw _ or the NFL draft _ placed him in New Orleans in 1971.
Football-wise, he was doomed to spend almost his entire career with
as woeful an organization as the league has ever known.
</P>
<P>
   Grocery sacks over heads were invented by fans of these
``Aints.'' This team was not a saintly bunch. The physical pounding
inflicted upon Archie over the years made him a poster boy for
toughness in pro football.
</P>
<P>
   Manning, however, was blessed by having a fine family. And one
of his sons, Peyton, became a much-heralded product of the
quarterbacking gene machine.
</P>
<P>
   But two Aprils ago, when Peyton found himself headed, via the
draft, for the NFL's never-never land _ Indianapolis _ Archie
admits there was an unpleasant flashback to his own career in New
Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Peyton was in high school, I distanced myself from the
football part of it,'' Archie said. ``There is nothing worse than a
daddy interfering with a high school coaching staff. It was the
same during college recruiting. Peyton could have gone anywhere.
All I told him was `I'm here for you, but you make the call.'
</P>
<P>
   ``When he was at Tennessee, I may not have said 10 words to the
coaching staff the whole time he was there. He loved it there. My
wife and I loved him being there, but that was it. I stayed out of
the football part.''
</P>
<P>
   Then came NFL draft day in 1998. Peyton going to the Colts was,
well, a worry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had my concerned parent's cap on, and my Saints cap, too''
said Archie, laughing. `Yeah, I had the flashbacks.''
</P>
<P>
   Agents and other NFL friends of Archie were advising him to
advise Peyton ``to do an Elway.'' John, of course, was originally
drafted by the same Colts, except they were in Baltimore at the
time. Elway refused to sign, and in a bitter power-play, forced a
trade to Denver.
</P>
<P>
   Archie also had top marketing firms telling him it would cost
Peyton thousands of dollars, maybe millions, if he played for the
middle-of-nowhere Colts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peyton would hear none of it,'' Archie said.''He didn't want
to do an Elway. He just did not think it was right.''
</P>
<P>
   And Archie's opinion today? ``Peyton couldn't be in a better
place,'' he said. ``From the owner, to the GM, to the coaches _ not
only Jim Mora but the offensive staff _ this is a great situation
for him to develop as a quarterback for a team that has a chance to
grow into a good one.''
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, is all this father can ask. That his son's
football career follows a different course than his own. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
