<HEADLINE>
LOS ANGELES TIMES STAFF PROTESTS MAGAZINE DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By RICHARD A. OPPEL Jr. and FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Senior editors at The Los Angeles Times met with the publisher
on Wednesday and expressed a sense ``of betrayal'' after the
disclosure that the newspaper shared profits from a special
magazine section with the subject of the section, the Staples
Center sports arena, according to a staff member at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The afternoon meeting came as about 300 editorial staff members
demanded an apology from the newspaper, contending in a petition
that the financial deal had compromised the newspaper's integrity.
</P>
<P>
   The publisher, Kathryn M. Downing, apologized for the way she
handled the arrangement, this staff member said. Ms. Downing is
expected to meet with the newspaper's staff at a meeting on
Thursday afternoon, according to the staff member.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, the newspaper acknowledged that it had earned
more than $2 million in advertising revenue from publishing a
164-page magazine devoted entirely to the new sports arena on Oct.
10. Such single-issue sections are not uncommon, but it is unusual
for a newspaper to share profits with an institution that it covers
on a continuing basis.
</P>
<P>
   Staff members circulated a petition Wednesday that sought ``a
thorough review of all other financial relationships that may
compromise The Times' editorial heritage.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As journalists at the L.A. Times, we are appalled by the paper
entering into hidden financial partnerships on editorial products
with the subjects we're writing about,'' the petition stated,
according to a staff member in the newsroom who read from it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The editorial credibility of The Times has been fundamentally
undermined by the revenue-sharing arrangement between Staples
Center and The Times Magazine issue on Staples Center,'' the
petition continues.
</P>
<P>
   ``In one swift blow, we've communicated to readers through
articles in New Times, The New York Times, and The Wall Street
Journal that we may have undisclosed financial ties with our
editorial subjects. A newspaper's reputation for integrity is hard
to earn and easy to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   The petition was signed by staff members in every editorial
department of the newspaper, the staff member said. The
profit-sharing arrangement was disclosed by New Times, an
alternative newspaper in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, the executive editor of the magazine, Drex
Heikes, said that he did not know of the arrangement until after
the issue had been published and that the editorial staff had
complete control over the content of the issue.
</P>
<P>
   The Times' editor, Michael Parks, said earlier this week that he
and the newspaper's senior vice president for advertising have
advised Ms. Downing against pursuing a similar magazine section
next year to coincide with the Democratic National Convention in
Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The new sporting arena, which cost $400 million, is home to the
Los Angeles Lakers and Los Angeles Clippers professional basketball
teams, and to the Los Angeles Kings professional hockey team.
</P>
<P>
   The Times is one of 10 ``founding partners'' of the center _
similar to a corporate sponsor _ but the Staples Center is
primarily owned by the Denver billionaire Philip Anschutz, the
real-estate executive Ed Roski Jr., and the News Corp.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-99 0126EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
