<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-WORLDSERIES-YANKEES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIVERA CLOSES OUT THE PERFECT ENDING 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When another situation turned tense for the Yankees
on Wednesday night, Joe Torre did what he has done all season. The
manager summoned Mariano Rivera, he stayed calm in the dugout and
he waited for Rivera to throttle the Braves and help the Yankees
soar to another World Series title. Been there, done that.
</P>
<P>
   It was rather appropriate that Rivera had the ball in his skinny
fingers in what naturally became the most crucial situation of the
season. The Yankees would probably not have reached this night
without Rivera buzzing fastballs past hitters for the last six
months, so it was apt for him to protect one more lead in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Rivera performed his job flawlessly again by retiring Chipper
Jones with the potential tying runs on in the eighth, dousing the
only dicey situation of the evening and helping the Yankees to a
4-1 victory, culminating their second consecutive four-game Series
sweep and their second straight championship.
</P>
<P>
   For the second October in a row, Rivera was mobbed near the
mound by his teammates after collecting the last out of a special
season. Rivera's arms were raised high, his eyes were closed and
his mouth was wide open in the picture of the 1998 celebration on
the news media guide. On Wednesday night, Rivera and his friends
posed for a new picture as the Yankees buried the closer one more
time at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in confidence, and when you feel confidence out
there you can beat anybody,'' Rivera said. ``That's what I was
doing. I feel confident enough to beat anybody. I just made my
pitches. Thank God, everything was good. I was like, `O.K., we got
it.'''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees got it because of Clemens at the beginning and
Rivera at the end. Rivera was the most valuable player of the World
Series after winning one game, saving two more and firing four and
two-thirds scoreless innings. Rivera did not allow an earned run in
121/3 innings during the post-season and went 2-0 with five saves.
After Rivera finished the regular season with 302/3 scoreless
innings, he continued to be nearly unhittable when it mattered
most.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the best closer I've ever seen,'' Joe Girardi, the Yankee
catcher, said. ``Obviously, there are some closers who I haven't
caught, but he's the best closer of any that I've ever caught.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop Derek Jeter thought about the right-handed Rivera, who
has not yielded a run in his last 252/3 innings and said, ``When Mo
goes out there, it's automatic.''
</P>
<P>
   After Clemens bagged the first two outs of the eighth, Walt
Weiss reached on an infield single to first and Gerald Williams
looped a single to left. Jeff Nelson replaced Clemens and allowed
Bret Boone's bouncing single over the mound to trim the Yankees'
lead to 3-1.
</P>
<P>
   With runners on first and third, Torre bounded out of the dugout
as if he were trying to catch a bus. It was obvious he wanted
Rivera, who had not allowed an earned run since July. Rivera tossed
fastballs and cut fastballs to push the count to 1-2 against Jones.
On the next fastball, Jones lined a ball past first base that was
foul by a few inches. On a 2-2 count, Rivera induced Jones to slap
a ball to second base that Luis Sojo handled for the final out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chipper is a dangerous guy,'' Rivera said. ``I wasn't trying
to give him nothing that he could pull to tie the game. I was just
trying to get something on the corner, and I did.''
</P>
<P>
   Rivera was wearing a tan baseball cap and a soggy gray T-shirt,
which both had ``1999 Champions'' etched across them, as he stood
in a subdued clubhouse. He is the third reliever to be named mvp of
the World Series, after his former teammate John Wetteland (1996)
and Oakland's Rollie Fingers, who won the award in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   But Rivera could be considered the best post-season reliever
ever since he has a microscopic earned run average of 0.38, the
lowest in post-season history, after yielding just two earned runs
over 471/3 innings. Rivera has been almost perfect, which is what
he was on Wednesday night, when he zipped through four Braves and
enabled the Yankees to celebrate again.
</P>
<P>
   The last time Rivera permitted an earned run in the post-season
was Game 4 of the 1997 division series, in which Sandy Alomar
belted a homer off him that helped destroy a season. When he was
asked if he recalled the last time he had been nicked for a run in
October, he smiled and said, ``I don't think about that.''
</P>
<P>
   When Rivera was told it was Alomar's memorable homer, he smiled
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alomar?'' he said. ``That was the last one? That's great. This
is incredible.''  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-99 0136EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
