<DOCNO> NYT19991028.0032 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 01:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0889 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBO-WORLDSERIES-HNS &LR;      10-28 0763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-WORLDSERIES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
NEW YORK _ End of discussion.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Call them the team of the decade, call them the team of the
century; heck, call them the team for all time.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Yankees, baseball's most storied franchise,
fittingly penned the sport's final chapter of the 1900s, clinching
their 25th World Series championship with a 4-1 victory over the
Atlanta Braves on Wednesday at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The final chapter was no more than a footnote, considering what
little effort it took the Yankees to dispose of the Braves. The
Yankees swept the Series in four games, extended their World Series
winning streak to 12 games and became the first repeat champions
since Toronto in 1992-93.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees won their third World Series championship in the
last four years, and their Series winning streak equaled the record
set by the 1927-28-32 Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how you can get much better than that,'' Yankees
shortstop Derek Jeter said.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves _ for all their regular-season dominance during the
1990s _ are not the team of the decade. This latest failing left
them 1-4 in the Fall Classic this decade, including a pair of
losses to the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   The team-of-the-decade debate might continue, although it seems
pointless. One thing is certain: For five days in October 1999,
there was no doubt which baseball team was the best. The Yankees
outhit, outpitched and outplayed the Braves in every facet of the
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would have liked to have made it a better contest,'' Braves
manager Bobby Cox said. ``That's for sure. We just didn't play as
well as we should have. You have to tip your hat to the Yankees.
It's hard to do what they've done.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's finale was the culmination of a Series that had it
all. Great pitching and exciting finishes defined the Series, which
made Game 4 an appropriate climax.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Clemens, whom the Yankees acquired for moments such as
this, pitched 7 inspired innings, allowing one run on four hits.
</P>
<P>
   The victory may have represented a small step for the Yankees,
who have the celebration _ on average _ every four years. But it
was a giant step for Clemens, who had done just about everything in
his career except win the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was a perfect way to end it,'' Yankees manager
Joe Torre said. ``The man (Clemens) wanted a World Series ring. I
couldn't see it not happening tonight. It was a perfect setup.''
</P>
<P>
   The sight of the five-time Cy Young Award winner bouncing around
the mound and pumping his fist through the air underscored the
importance of team accomplishments in relation to individual
accolades.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what everyone said it was all about,'' Clemens said.
``I finally know what it feels like to be a Yankee.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves staged a brief uprising in Game 3, but Clemens put
them back in their place Wednesday. Atlanta didn't advance a
baserunner past first until the eighth inning.
</P>
<P>
   That one run wasn't nearly enough to support a solid pitching
performance by John Smoltz, who allowed three runs in seven innings
with the critical hit coming on a ball that might have been
fielded.
</P>
<P>
   ``The story coming into this Series was how good Atlanta's
pitching was, and rightfully so,'' Jeter said. ``But we've got some
guys on our staff who know how to shut the opposition down, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees scored two runs in the third on Tino Martinez's
sharp grounder that hit the glove of Braves first baseman Ryan
Klesko and glanced into shallow center field.
</P>
<P>
   Jorge Posada's first hit of the Series, a single to right, gave
the Yankees a 3-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz retired 12 of the last 13 batters he faced after Posada's
third-inning single, and Clemens had allowed the Braves just four
baserunners entering the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   He got two quick outs to open the inning, but the Braves got a
ray of hope when shortstop Walt Weiss reached on a controversial
infield single. Television replays clearly showed Weiss was out at
first base on a play on which Clemens was stepped on.
</P>
<P>
   Torre summoned reliever Jeff Nelson after Gerald Williams
singled off Clemens to give the Braves runners at first and second.
Bret Boone's RBI single off Nelson produced a run, and closer
Mariano Rivera _ the Series Most Valuable Player _ got Chipper
Jones to ground out to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees added a run in the bottom of the eighth on Jim
Leyritz's pinch homer off Terry Mulholland. It was the 18th
pinch-hit home run in World Series history.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
