A0890 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBO-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      10-28 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
NEW YORK _ Success has followed Roger Clemens everywhere he's gone.
But always, it seemed as if Clemens was doing the chasing.
</P>
<P>
   Where there were Cy Young Awards, there also was the same old
deep sigh of frustration at the end of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Where there were strikeout records and a Most Valuable Player
Award in 1986, there also was a deep hole torn from the middle of
his career, like the final pages ripped out of a book.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens knew how he would like the final chapters of his career
to read, but not all stories end happily. He just didn't know.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens chased a World Series championship. He chased and chased
until along the way he broke relationships that seemed unbreakable
and left places that seemed perfect for him. Boston. Toronto. He
even splintered ties with his hometown when the Astros came calling
in the offseason and everything crumbled over dollars.
</P>
<P>
   But Clemens finally caught up to his happy ending on a breezy,
cool Wednesday night at Yankee Stadium. And when Yankees 4, Braves
1 finished a sweep of Atlanta, it didn't just complete a story. It
completed Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's what everybody said it would be,'' Clemens said.
</P>
<P>
   The box score said Clemens went 7 innings, struck out four and
gave up four hits, three of them ground-ball bleeders. But really,
Clemens went through a lot more than that.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning in 1986, when Clemens' Red Sox were within one strike
of winning the title but saw it slip between Bill Buckner's legs,
the chase haunted the Katy Rocket. He set record after record but
always heard about what he couldn't do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe Roger is conducive to winning,'' longtime
nemesis and Toronto executive Dave Stewart once said. ``He's good
at accomplishing individual goals, but I don't think he's capable
of bringing someone a championship.''
</P>
<P>
   It always hurt Clemens to hear such things because he knew it
was something that would haunt him forever unless he proved
otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Few players seem to have the sense of place and legacy that
Clemens always has had. As much as he sometimes shrugged and talked
of not necessarily having to win a title to be a complete pitcher,
he knew otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard people talking,'' he said. ``I knew it's in me to rise
to the occasion. This is one night when I had more pressure than I
could stand.''
</P>
<P>
   And he won. He won with a masterful performance but not in the
classic Clemens style. He got 17 groundouts. He wiggled out of
jams. He defended his position well and even had to shake off
getting stepped on on a hustling play in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just thought it was the perfect way to end the World
Series,'' Yankees manager Joe Torre said. ``We traded for him
because we felt he could help us do this. He didn't have the kind
of year we hoped he would have, but tonight I couldn't see it not
happening for him. It was perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the individual accomplishments and trophies, Clemens
finally reached what he was chasing by simply being a role player,
just another Yankee, just the fourth starter on a dominant team.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, fellow pitcher David Cone marveled at how good a
teammate Clemens has proved to be for the Yankees. Until he put on
the pinstripes, most players in the Yankees' clubhouse figured
Clemens was too cocky, too full of himself.
</P>
<P>
   But it was all about the chase, about everyone knowing that no
matter how much he stuck out his chest, he was a little empty
inside and had to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they got their (1998) rings earlier this year, I was
watching (from the clubhouse),'' Clemens said. ``They all came in
and said, `We're getting you one this year.'''
</P>
<P>
   And they did. As a team, the Yankees picked apart the Braves by
picking one another up at every turn of the Series.
</P>
<P>
   No one thought it would take this long, but Clemens couldn't
care less when the champagne was dripping over his head and he was
swarmed on the field by two of his four sons.
</P>
<P>
   It was a night so unlike what we've seen before from Clemens. It
came in a season that was not one of Clemens' best.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night was Clemens' only chance to contribute to the
World Series for the Yankees. After struggling through a 14-10
year, he knew Cone or Orlando Hernandez would get the call if it
came down to a Game 6 or 7.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens posted the highest ERA (4.60) of his career and went
through long spells of inactivity in the rotation after suffering a
hamstring injury and back problems.
</P>
<P>
   But who cares? The chase is over. Clemens is a complete player.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
