<HEADER>
A0894 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBC-BIG12FOOTBALLREPO     10-28 1681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BIG </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILL COLD NORTH WIND BLOW HOLE IN SOONERS?
</HEADLINE>
 12 FOOTBALL REPORT-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dismiss it as wishful thinking from those with less imagination.
Proclaim it as inspired insight from folks who understand football.
</P>
<P>
   Handle it any way you'd like, because no one knows which side is
right. It's much too early for iron-clad conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   But be aware that rival Big 12 football coaches envision a day
when Oklahoma offensive coordinator Mike Leach will share a common
bond with actor Clark Gable. Both, it seems, will be the lead
character in separate productions of ``Gone With the Wind''.
</P>
<P>
   Gable, of course, received an Oscar for his role in an epic
movie by that name. Leach, on the other hand, will watch his
prolific passing game disappear once the temperatures drop and the
wind comes sweeping down the plain in Big 12 outposts from Texas to
Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Naysayers predict it could happen as soon as Saturday, when the
24th-ranked Sooners (4-2, 2-1) play at Colorado (4-3, 3-1). Sloppy
weather, say the skeptics, always strikes at some point when
playing in the Big 12's northern venues. And the Sooners travel as
far north as the league allows on Nov. 13, when Oklahoma plays at
Iowa State.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas coach Terry Allen, who spent eight seasons at Northern
Iowa (1989-96) before taking over the Jayhawks' program in 1997,
knows a little bit about the perils of passing the football in
howling winds and freezing temperatures.
</P>
<P>
   ``The weather can have a devastating effect, no question about
that,'' Allen said. ``We face it more up here in the north, but
it's always a concern.''
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska, of course, built its empire around a ground game that
could function in all kinds of weather. Colorado coach Gary Barnett
plans to emulate that model with the Buffaloes, whose rushing
attack has improved by 28.4 yards per game since the departure of
Rick Neuheisel, Barnett's pass-happy predecessor.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma, on the other hand, has improved from No. 107 to No. 3
among Division I-A passing teams in its first season under coach
Bob Stoops. Leach is Stoops' right-hand man, the coordinator of a
controlled passing game that is built to maintain ball control with
short, surgical strikes to a wide collection of receivers.
</P>
<P>
   There is no questioning the Sooners' prolific success in their
new offense. Quarterback Josh Heupel completes 66.1 percent of his
passes and averages 340.2 yards per game. He has connected for
touchdowns with 13 receivers. The Sooners have topped 500 yards in
four games, including 552 in last week's 51-6 rout of No. 22 Texas
A&AMP;M.
</P>
<P>
   But there is hope for future opponents, A&AMP;M coach R.C. Slocum
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``High wind conditions would affect their offense, without a
doubt,'' Slocum said.
</P>
<P>
   Between now and the end of the regular season, the Sooners will
not play a contest farther south than Lubbock, home of perpetual 30
mph winds and _ as of Oct. 17 _ a generous dusting of snow. And
it's not even Halloween.
</P>
<P>
   Stoops shrugs off suggestions that his high-flying attack could
be grounded in adverse weather conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it has anything to do with anything,'' Stoops
said. ``You can throw the ball in all kinds of weather.''
</P>
<P>
   But effectively enough to win?
</P>
<P>
   Stoops points to the success of the wide-open passing game at
Florida, where he served as the Gators' defensive coordinator from
1996-98, as evidence. But the Gators play mostly in front of
shirt-sleeved crowds in the Southeastern Conference, even in
November. Chances are good that Oklahoma will soon lose that
luxury. But does that mean they will start losing games?
</P>
<P>
   Barnett cited another variable, one more damaging to a prolific
passing attack than an Iowa ice storm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's more vulnerable to great defenses,'' Barnett
said. ``You look at Purdue in the Big Ten, and they're able to
throw in bad weather. But when they play against Penn State, Ohio
State and Michigan, their yardage isn't the same as it is against
everyone else in the league. When you play against a great defense,
they're able to handle that stuff. That's it more than the
weather.''
</P>
<P>
   For the record, three of Oklahoma's remaining opponents rank
among the nation's top 20 teams in total defense: Oklahoma State
(13th), Texas Tech (19th) and Iowa State (20th). Then again, A&AMP;M
ranks 16th and the Sooners just scorched the Aggies for 552 yards
and 51 points.
</P>
<P>
   Color me neutral on the great weather debate. But expect the
topic to heat up in earnest for the Sooners when the temperature
cools down.
\Nsubheds:SPOTLIGHT ON
BAYLOR'S STEELE INTENDS TO REBUILD K-STATE WAY
</P>
<P>
   Imitation, they say, is the sincerest form of flattery. So,
consider yourself flattered, Kansas State coach Bill Snyder. Kevin
Steele wants his Baylor football program to look a lot like yours
when he's finished putting all the pieces in place.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't follow that template to exact specifications, but
there are things we'll follow. It's a good template,'' said Steele,
who keeps three coaching handbooks near his desk for quick
reference. One was written by former Nebraska coach Tom Osborne,
another by legendary UCLA basketball coach John Wooden.
</P>
<P>
   The third author? Snyder.
</P>
<P>
   Steele will square off against Snyder's team for the first time
in his brief coaching career Saturday in Manhattan, Kan. He said he
draws encouragement from the fact that Snyder, in 1989, ``took over
the worst progam in NCAA history and now he's got the only
undefeated team in the conference.''
</P>
<P>
   If it can be done at Kansas State, said Steele, a similar
turnaround can take place at Baylor. In fact, the first building
block already may have been laid. During Snyder's initial season,
his 1989 team finished 1-10. Its lone victory came against North
Texas. Steele's team, at this juncture, is 1-6. Its lone victory
came against North Texas.
QUICK HITS
MR. VERSATILITY
</P>
<P>
   Because of injuries in the Texas Tech backfield, Sammy Morris
has become a human Scrabble blank in the Red Raiders' game plan.
Morris, the regular fullback, may see significant time at tailback
in Saturday's game at Missouri if starter Shaud Williams is slowed
by a bruised shoulder suffered in last week's 35-7 victory against
Baylor.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, he may not. Tech coach Spike Dykes said he has a
``sophisticated system'' he uses to determine when and where to
deploy Morris, who has rushed for a team-high 88.5 yards per game
against Big 12 opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just shoot from the hip,'' Dykes said. ``We've got to be
careful not to ask Sammy to do so many things he can't do them all
well. It's tempting because Sammy has so many different
abilities.'' TOP 10 FEVER
</P>
<P>
   By climbing to No. 12 in The Associated Press rankings, Texas
has reached its loftiest status in the polls under second-year
coach Mack Brown. So Brown has given the Longhorns (6-2, 3-1) a new
goal heading into Saturday's game at Iowa State.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them what they need to do is start working on getting
to 10th in the country,'' said Brown, whose team is coming off a
24-20 victory over Nebraska. ``We've been a great team bouncing
back after losses, but we haven't always played well after big
wins. And we need to play well Saturday to have a chance. That's
why I gave them the extra challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   From his perspective, Iowa State coach Dan McCarney said the
Longhorns ``already look like a Top 10 team.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As good as they were last year, Texas is a better team this
year,'' said McCarney, who watched his Cyclones fall, 54-33, last
season in Austin. ``Their defensive line is much improved and they
have more versatility on offense.'' LOVING LIFE WITH LINDSAY
</P>
<P>
   Despite some rustiness in the passing department, Oklahoma State
coach Bob Simmons said his offense should be ``much better'' with
the return of quarterback Tony Lindsay. The third-year starter
played for the first time in six weeks during last week's 44-21
loss to No. 6 Kansas State, rushing for 33 yards and passing for
130 in his first activity since Sept. 4.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma State (3-3, 1-2) plays Saturday at No. 22 Texas A&AMP;M
(5-2, 2-2).
</P>
<P>
   ``Tony underthrew a couple of passes, but from the mental
standpoint, he was very sharp and gave us a big lift emotionally,''
Simmons said. ``He brings the experience factor to the table that
we need to do more things on offense.''
BURCH's PICKS Staff writer Jimmy Burch picks (against the line)
this week's Big 12 football games:
</P>
<P>
   Texas at Iowa State (plus 10 1/2). Pick: Texas. Longhorns avoid
emotional hangover, put brakes on Cyclones' ground game.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma State (plus 11) at Texas A&AMP;M. Pick: Oklahoma State.
Aggies win, but it is a hard-earned win.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Tech at Missouri (plus 1). Pick: Tech. Red Raiders are
rolling, Tigers are reeling. A road win beckons.
</P>
<P>
   Baylor (plus 37 1/2) at Kansas State. Pick: Baylor. Wildcats
clear final hurdle before Colorado-Nebraska stretch in ho-hum
fashion.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma at Colorado (plus 4). Pick: Oklahoma. Sooners' aerial
circus mystifies the inconsistent Buffs.
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska (plus 31 1/2) at Kansas. Pick: Nebraska. Huskers soothe
their aching egos by routing outmanned Jayhawks.
</P>
<P>
   Last week's record: 3-3. Season record: 38-22-1.
