<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOWBIZ EXEC DALY TO RUN DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Robert Daly, who spent 20 years building Warner
Bros. into one of the most powerful entertainment companies in the
world before resigning in July, will assume the day-to-day
operations of the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Daly, a lifelong Dodgers fan and close friend of former owner
Walter O'Malley and former manager Tom Lasorda, is purchasing a
minority share of the Dodgers from Rupert Murdoch's Fox Group,
several sources said. Though the deal is yet to be finalized, it is
imminent and an announcement will be made today at 10 a.m. at the
Staples Center. Daly will be vice chairman and CEO of the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Also, sources said Bob Graziano, fired as the Dodgers' CEO and
president Sept. 28, will remain with the Dodgers, likely as the
club's president. Graziano agreed to stay with the Dodgers after
his firing to help with the transition.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Daly) will have a small piece of the team, but control the
whole thing,'' a source said. ``He will be the new owner in that
he'll run everything. He's calling the shots. He's running the
team. He'll be there five, six, seven days a week at (Dodger)
Stadium.''
</P>
<P>
   Rick Welts, president of Fox Sports Enterprises and the man who
fired Graziano, said he wouldn't talk about what's going on with
the Dodgers until today's press conference. However, sources said
Welts wouldn't have a problem with Graziano remaining with the
club.
</P>
<P>
   Sources said Daly will purchase 10 percent of the Dodgers. The
value of his share is approximately $30 million. Daly's estimated
worth is $300 million.
</P>
<P>
   The move is being made, in large part, because Fox's higher-ups
reached the conclusion that it's too difficult for a large
corporation to run a ballclub on a day-to-day basis, especially by
committee, sources said. With Daly joining the front office, that
changes. Every decision with the Dodgers will stop with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think with what's gone on, one singular, strong owner works
the best,'' a source said. ``You can look at Disney as an example.
They've had some problems.''
</P>
<P>
   This isn't a new philosophy. Jerry Colangelo, a minority owner
of the Arizona Diamondbacks, is responsible for the every-day
dealings of the Diamondbacks. However, Daly will be more involved
than Colangelo.
</P>
<P>
   No longer will Fox Group chairman and CEO Peter Chernin or Fox
Entertainment Group co-COO Chase Carey, who made the Mike Piazza
deal, have a say in the every-day decisions. Welts, who oversees
Fox's sports endeavors, also won't be involved.
</P>
<P>
   Daly built Warner Bros. into a multi-billion-dollar company
during his 20-year run that ended with his being co-chairman with
Terry Semel. He was also the chief programmer for CBS television.
</P>
<P>
   But can he run a ballclub?
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows the entertainment industry, baseball is
entertainment, but I'm not sure what (Daly) knows about running a
baseball team,'' a baseball official said. ``One thing that will be
better for (the Dodgers) is having someone at Dodger Stadium day-in
and day-out instead of across the country. I just don't know what
he knows about running a baseball team.''
</P>
<P>
   Chernin and Welts will be at today's press conference. Carey is
out of the country.
</P>
<P>
   Discussions between Daly and the Fox Group began recently. Daly,
who lives in Los Angeles, knows Chernin from their dealings in the
entertainment industry.
</P>
<P>
   The Fox Group purchased the Dodgers in March 1998 from the
O'Malley family for $311 million, and there's been speculation
Murdoch would sell some of the club because of the financial
burden.
</P>
<P>
   Running the Dodgers as a spoke on Fox's entertainment wheel
hasn't worked. Even with Chernin and Carey stationed in New York
and Murdoch traveling the world, Graziano, as president and CEO,
always had the specter of Chernin and Carey hovering 3000 miles
away. That won't happen with Daly.
</P>
<P>
   In Fox's two seasons of ownership, the Dodgers failed to make
the playoffs. In 1998, the Dodgers went 83-79 and finished third,
15 games behind San Diego. The Dodgers fired general manager Fred
Claire and manager Bill Russell and traded Piazza during the
season.
</P>
<P>
   In September '98, the Dodgers hired Kevin Malone as general
manager. He hired manager Davey Johnson, and during the offseason
the club spent more than $160 million on free agents and contract
extensions.
</P>
<P>
   Still, despite the $105 million free-agent signing of Kevin
Brown and an $80 million payroll, the Dodgers went 77-85 and were
never in playoff contention.
</P>
<P>
   If Graziano stays with the Dodgers it would be as the club's
president, but his job description would change. He would be second
in command to Daly in running the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   It would also bring an end to a search for the club's president.
John Thomas, who accepted the position of president of the
Sacramento Kings, Sacramento Monarchs (WNBA) and Sacramento Knights
(Arena Football) in July, was considered the front-runner. But
Thomas recently told Welts he would be staying in Sacramento.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
