<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-HULL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`OLD' HULL FEELING REJUVENATED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ ``I feel 100,'' Brett Hull moaned, his slow and
deliberate gait lending credibility to his age assessment.
</P>
<P>
   Hull had been passing through an empty Dallas Stars locker room
a couple of days ago when he determined his aching knee, nagging
groin and bruised body necessitated a comment.
</P>
<P>
   That said, he continued walking.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way we are playing, the style this team plays, it's
extremely more fatiguing,'' Hull said later. ``Every game feels
like the seventh game of a playoff.''
</P>
<P>
   The player who brags that he didn't get hit his first 10 years
in the league is now hitting and getting hit on every shift. The
player who once was known only for his goal scoring is second on
the team with six assists and only half as many goals. The player
who Mike Keenan dubbed a locker room problem in St. Louis was
whistled for his first fighting major in his career this season
when he came to Mike Modano's defense against Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   The player who the Stars thought they were getting when they
signed Hull in July of 1998 isn't the player they got. He's better.
</P>
<P>
   Just look at his play during the Stars' recent spate of injuries
that has played like an episode of ER.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, he's a different player right now,'' Stars coach Ken
Hitchcock said. ``He's a player that for me has been asked and has
done a great job at playing not only within the system but very
hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Hull has been the Stars' best player this season, along with
goalie Ed Belfour.
</P>
<P>
   The best for Hull used to entail scoring goals. He had five
50-plus goal seasons, including three of 70 or better. Best for
Hull as a Star entails being a gritty, two-way grinder. He had 40
goals last season, one of which won the Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   His only career record being threatened since arriving in Dallas
is ice bags used in a season.
</P>
<P>
   Hull said he couldn't have imagined himself playing this way 10
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was always fighting the establishment on playing the game
the way I thought it should be played,'' Hull said. ``I can't play
the way I used to, just get loose out there and float in and out.
It's impossible to do. Sometimes, I kind of revert back a couple of
times. `Hitch' is the first guy to grab me and say `No, no, no' and
goes in about the system.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, the system. The one Hull wasn't supposed to ever be able to
fit in; the one Hitchcock said Hull has totally bought into; the
one that brought both the player and the organization their first
Stanley Cups in June.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say Hull's transition has been all rah-rah,
happy-happy.
</P>
<P>
   Hull was benched this season in a preseason game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got an assist and a game-tying goal, and I was plus-2,''
Hull explained. ``I asked (Hitchcock) the next day. I said `I can't
figure it out. I got benched. I got two points. I'm plus 2.' And he
goes, `the game isn't about stats anymore. It's the little things
you do away from the stats that really make you a player now.'
</P>
<P>
   ``That's something that within my brain is hard to grasp.''
</P>
<P>
   Only Modano said he has seen Hull's progression happen rather
quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's either that or he wouldn't be playing,'' Modano said
jokingly.
</P>
<P>
   He'd be playing all right , just not for a defending Stanley Cup
champion.
</P>
<P>
   Winning just hurts a little more than scoring. By the time he
scored the Cup-clinching goal, he had a torn groin and a torn
medial collateral ligament in his knee.
</P>
<P>
   Want to guess how Hull spent his summer?
</P>
<P>
   If you said healing, you'd be right. He wasn't able to start
skating until mid-August. So his conditioning has come in games
when injuries to other players have forced him to play more and
harder minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you lose this, halfway through the season, at least I find,
those players really suffer,'' Hitchcock said. ``So he's having to
do conditioning shifts, plus play 20 minutes, plus play a physical
game. And our biggest fear is that we're going to absolutely wear
this guy out, and we can't afford to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   The old Hull would've never let them. The new Hull doesn't mind.
Maybe, it comes with being 100.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ah, not that bad today,'' Hull said Wednesday as he walked
through the locker room with the usual ice bags and bandages in
tow. ``I feel, at least, 80. Maybe, younger.'' BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   _ Injured forward Joe Nieuwendyk (back) and injured defensemen
Richard Matvichuk (knee) and Darryl Sydor (groin) skated Wednesday.
They will practice in full pads with the coaches Thursday and with
the team Friday. Ken Hitchcock said they will be evaluated to
determine their status for Saturday's game against Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Stars will participate in the NHL skills competition at 7
p.m. Thursday at Reunion Arena. Plenty of $10 tickets remain. Call
(214) GO-STARS. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
