<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 02:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0900 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-YANKEES-BRAVES-BOS     10-28 1140
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YANKEES-BRAVES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES CLOSE OUT BRAVES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There can be only one way to draw a timeline for this
Baseball Century.
</P>
<P>
   With a pinstripe.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Yankees were a colossus when your grandparents were
in the cradle and the Babe was the original Bomber. They were
compared to US Steel when your parents were dancing to Sinatra, and
DiMaggio defined style. They reigned when The Mick was the man, and
rose up again when Reggie Jax ruled.
</P>
<P>
   And now, it is your children's turn to marvel at the
magnificence of a team that Wednesday night in Yankee Stadium swept
aside the Atlanta Braves in four straight games with an efficiency
and elan every bit as dazzling as the days when Yankee teams were
known as dynasties.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it is time, at the fin de siecle to elevate the Yankees
of Joe Torre, Boss Steinbrenner, and yes _ the newest Yankee hero,
Rocket Roger Clemens _ to that status, after they erased the
Braves, 4-1, to complete their second consecutive four-game sweep
of the National League's champions and win the Series for the third
time in the last four years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is one of the greatest because they overcame so
much,'' said Steinbrenner, reflecting on a season that began with
Torre diagnosed with prostate cancer and designated hitter Darryl
Strawberry busted in a tawdry drug incident in Tampa, and ended
with three Yankee players losing their fathers in the span of just
over a month (outfielder Paul O'Neill's father died early
Wednesday).
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe, to go through what he went through, Straw, to go through
what he went through, and three of our young men lost their
fathers,'' Steinbrenner said. ``It's a mentally tough team.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Yankees won more games (125) than any team in
history. ``This may be a better team,'' a red-eyed Torre said,
``because of the fact we had to do it again to validate what we did
last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens, a lion in winter mauled by the team to which he once
pledged sole allegiance, the Red Sox, in the American League
Championship Series, summoned echoes of past greatness
Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night. He allowed four hits in 7 2/3 innings, in which
all 23 outs came either on strikeouts (4) or infield outs (19).
</P>
<P>
   The House that Ruth Built, in the last game of the millennium,
at last was transformed into a place that Clemens, after a
torturous season, could call home. The place where he could leave
the mound, after taking a bad stumble while covering first base on
Walt Weiss's two-out infield hit in the eighth, and wave his hat to
a crowd of 56,752 according him a thunderous ovation as the newest
pride of the Yankees, the last in a glorious chain in this century.
</P>
<P>
   To a Hall of Fame resume, Clemens can now add a World Series
win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I normally don't talk about it,'' Torre said, ``but I sure as
hell was going to go with him (Clemens) in the ninth inning, go one
batter at a time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then he stepped on first base and got a bit of a whack. He was
still throwing good _ he threw a few pitches at 96 (miles per
hour).
</P>
<P>
   ``I just thought it was a perfect way to end the World Series,
with a man who came over here because he wanted a World Series
ring. I couldn't see it not happening today, the way his career has
gone. It just seemed like a perfect setup for us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves, meanwhile, cemented their status as the Brooklyn
Dodgers of their day, an exquisite team that won more games than
any other this decade but in the end, like the storied Boys of
Summer, couldn't hurdle that final obstacle, the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   John Smoltz, who, with a dozen victories has won more games than
any pitcher in postseason, was splendid, striking out 11 while
allowing six hits in seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz struck out the side in the second inning, after the
Yankees put runners on first and second on a walk and Strawberry's
single. He did not allow a hit over the final four innings.
</P>
<P>
   But, ah, the third inning, the only one in which he faltered.
That's when the Yankees scored all of their runs on four singles,
one of which _ Tino Martinez's two-run hit off the forearm of
Braves first baseman Ryan Klesko _ could just as easily have been
scored an error.
</P>
<P>
   ``This one was more emotional, and I don't usually get
emotional,'' said a disconsolate Bobby Cox, the Braves manager who
became the second manager to lose as many as four World Series.
Hall of Famer John McGraw holds the record with six.
</P>
<P>
   While the Yankees tied a record set by the Ruthian Yanks by
winning their 12th straight Series game en route to their 25th
Series title, the Braves tied the Series record for most
consecutive Series losses with eight (all to the Yankees).
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say that's pretty darn good,'' Cox said of the
Yankees' feat. ``You've got to tip your hat. It's hard. They could
have been knocked out in the first round like everybody else. It's
amazing to me. Even with a great ballclub, things can go wrong. I
think it ranks way up there, personally.''
</P>
<P>
   In winning their 25th World Series title, the Yankees won 11 of
12 postseason games, their only loss coming to Pedro Martinez in
the final sweet day of summer for the Sox. In the last two years,
they are 22-3 in the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens came out after Gerald Williams lined a single after
Weiss reached. Jeff Nelson replaced him and gave up a run-scoring
single to Bret Boone, cutting the Yankee lead to 3-1 and bringing
Chipper Jones, the odds-on favorite to be his league's MVP, to the
plate.
</P>
<P>
   Torre summoned Mariano Rivera, who cinched the deal and won
himself the shiniest trophy in the carnival _ the one that goes to
World Series MVP _ by inducing Jones to tap out to second after a
hellacious at-bat in which Jones hit a wicked liner just foul, one
that could easily have tied the score.
</P>
<P>
   There would be one final indignity for the Braves. Jim Leyritz,
whose three-run home run off Braves closer Mark Wohlers is widely
credited for turning around the '96 Series in the Yankees' favor,
hit for Strawberry in the bottom of the eighth and homered off
Braves reliever Terry Mulholland.
</P>
<P>
   From the seventh inning on, the Yankees outscored their
opponents, 26-8, in the postseason. Rivera finished with two wins
and six saves in the postseason, and a streak of 43 scoreless
innings dating to July 21.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he thought a sweep would tarnish all the Braves have
accomplished _ eight division titles, five pennants, one World
Series title _ Cox said: ``I don't really think about that.
Baseball, to me, this job is a year-to-year proposition, and that's
it. We're paid to win and if we had the best record after the 10
years, that's fine. If we don't, that's fine. I'm looking at what
happened the year before or the past year, and that's as far as I
ever get.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
