<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 02:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0901 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-YANKEES-BRAVES-BOS     10-28 1040
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YANKEES-BRAVES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLEMENS ENSURES PLACE IN HISTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ This was more than John Elway getting that first
Super Bowl ring. This was aging cowboy John Wayne winning the Oscar
for ``True Grit'' in 1969. It was Ernest Hemingway copping an
overdue Nobel Prize in 1954.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Clemens . . . Sixteen major league seasons . . . Two
hundred forty seven wins . . . Three thousand three hundred sixteen
strikeouts . . . Tens of thousands of autographs . . . Four
fortunate sons with names that start with K . . . Several
unfortunate statements.
</P>
<P>
   The Rocket. All-Century. No rings.
</P>
<P>
   Until now.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen years after his last World Series appearance _ a
controversial outing in which he left too early and watched the
most ghoulish finish in October history _ Clemens returned to the
Fall Classic Wednesday night and clinched the Yankees 25th
championship of the 20th century with 7 2/3 innings of four-hit
ball in a 4-1 victory that completed a four-game sweep of the
Atlanta Braves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel very blessed to be part of this team,'' said Clemens.
``We played with some heavy hearts out there tonight (Paul
O'Neill's father died Wednesday). I don't know if I could have done
what Paul O'Neill did. It's just been wonderful to play for these
guys. Tonight I feel I know what it's like to be a Yankee.''
</P>
<P>
   Ouch.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike that hideous night in New York 13 years ago, it took a
lot to get Clemens out of the game and there was no question about
his departure. This time, instead of entrusting his lead to Calvin
Schiraldi, the game was finished by World Series MVP Mariano
Rivera.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Clemens has played catch with Mariano Rivera. He has
traveled with Rivera and eaten lunch with Rivera. Mariano Rivera,
sir, is no Calvin Schiraldi. Four hundred miles and three years
removed from Boston, Roger Clemens would not be denied a ring this
time.
</P>
<P>
   The Rocket had a two-hit shutout going into the eighth. When he
retired the first two batters of the inning, it looked like he
might go nine and put the exclamation point on his starry career.
Unfortunately, trouble came when he hit the first base bag
awkwardly while covering on a Walt Weiss chopper to the right side.
Clemens limped around a little and the trainer came out, but the
Rocket stayed in the game and the crowd roared.
</P>
<P>
   After blowing two pitches past Gerald Williams, Clemens
surrendered a hard single to left and that was it. Sentiment took a
holiday. Yankee manager Joe Torre wasn't going to let the wounded,
weary Rocket pitch to any batter (Bret Boone) representing the
tying run. Torre came out to get him.
</P>
<P>
   Reluctantly, muttering under his breath, Clemens gave Torre the
ball and walked toward the dugout as hundreds of cameras flashed,
thousands stood, and all humanity in the Yankee dugout greeted him
at the top step. His work was done, his ring was won.
</P>
<P>
   Almost. Jeff Nelson surrendered an RBI single to Boone then the
indomitable Rivera came on to get Chipper Jones on a routine
grounder to second (routine only because Luis Sojo had replaced
skittish Chuck Knoblauch).
</P>
<P>
   It's another stinger for Red Sox Nation, of course. Clemens was
the greatest pitcher in Red Sox history. In 12 seasons he won 192
games and three Cy Young trophies. But like Sparky Lyle and Wade
Boggs before him, he had to go to the Yankees to win his World
Series hardware. His performance in the Bronx Wednesday night fuels
the irrational fears of those who believe in the Curse of the
Bambino.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard people talk about how I could be rattled,'' Clemens
said after the win. ``I don't get rattled. I've pitched in big
games and I put pressure on myself to rise to the occasion. Those
guys (his teammates) got me well. I was scuffling a little bit, but
we ran it out there and got it done.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens was asked if the ring might be enough to make him
retire. His answer made reference to his four boys.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll wait and see. This is one night and I had more pressure
than I could stand. I had my two big guys (Koby, 13, and Kory, 11)
here and two little guys (Kacy, 5, Kody, 3) back home telling me I
had to be home for trick or treat.''
</P>
<P>
   There was considerable pregame hype for Clemens's appearance.
The Yankees were on the threshold of their third championship in
four years, and a record-tying 12th consecutive World Series
victory. The Yankees are so deep they were able to turn to one of
the greatest pitchers of the century for the fourth game of the
World Series. It's like the 1985-86 Celtics having Bill Walton as
their backup center.
</P>
<P>
   After warming up, Clemens performed his usual ritual of wiping
sweat on the brow of the Babe Ruth monument in left-center field.
For Red Sox fans, the implications of this little gesture run
deeper than ever.
</P>
<P>
   As Clemens strolled in from the bullpen, Whitey Ford _ who won a
couple of World Series games _ threw out the first pitch to Yogi
Berra.
</P>
<P>
   The Rocket was cheered when he finally took the mound and threw
his first pitch at 8:24 p.m. He fanned Williams swinging on a low
fastball. It was his first World Series moment since Mike Greenwell
hit for him in the top of the eighth inning of Game 6, 13 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   He had a good fastball and kept it down in the zone. He had a
one-hitter through four and a two-hitter through seven. In the end,
he allowed only two walks and one earned run while striking out
four. All 23 of his outs came via strikeouts or on balls in the
infield. The Braves hit only two balls hard all night.
</P>
<P>
   After an insurance homer by Jim Leyritz (another ex-Sox _ is
there no end to this stuff?), the Yankees took the field for the
ninth and Clemens sat in the dugout alongside Don Zimmer. Watching
from all corners of the globe, citizens of Red Sox Nation could
only wince.
</P>
<P>
   The final out was a harmless Keith Lockhart fly to Chad Curtis
in left. When Curtis gloved the ball, the PA system blared, ``We
Are the Champions,'' and the Yankees stormed the field to begin
their celebration.
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of the pile, Roger Clemens stood holding two of
his sons aloft, one on each huge shoulder. Clemens was crying. He
was never so big and strong.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
