<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991028.0046 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 02:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0910 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-BBO-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI     10-28 0943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS TIME YANKEES' WIN A LITTLE TOO FAMILIAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ This never seemed like a World Series. Not for a New
York minute. Not for a Roger Clemens split-finger fastball second.
</P>
<P>
   And that can't be all that good.
</P>
<P>
   Not when Atlanta did a Hindenburg at home, going down 0-2 and
looking rung out by their wrenching National League Championship
Series against the killer Mets.
</P>
<P>
   The luster was gone by the time the Yankees came back to this
place they simply call ``The Stadium,'' as if there weren't any
other stadium in the world besides Yankee Stadium, the white
castle, the House That Ruth Built, the Bronx Zoo, whatever.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the Yankees stunned the Braves in the Fall Classic.
That was a World Series. Or it felt like one. The dominant team of
the early '90s ran straight into the churning, resurgent Yankees,
whose meddling but ever-wiser owner had decreed it was time for the
Yanks to take back October, take back what was rightfully theirs.
</P>
<P>
   Some of us were lucky enough to be sitting in the stands at
Yankee Stadium for Game 6 that night, a perfect autumn night in New
York. Not too hot, not too cold.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees had lost the first two games at home to the Braves,
but over the course of three wild games in Atlanta, the Braves were
a team the Yankees psyched out by winning three straight.
</P>
<P>
   When the Yankees wrapped up the 1996 World Series in New York,
there was a rush of excitment as the world watched the emergence of
a magnificent kid named Derek Jeter. There was made-for-TV drama of
seeing an old stalwart named Wade Boggs win his first ring.
</P>
<P>
   Jeter was the Rookie of the Year, and Boggs celebrated with
convulsive tears and a crazy ride around the Yankee outfield on the
back of a police horse, and manager Joe Torre was the unflappable,
paternalistic leader whose brother had undergone heart surgery.
</P>
<P>
   That was something.
</P>
<P>
   What happened in these four games of the 1999 World Series was
something else.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have become the deceptive juggernaut. They have
become General Electric, but with a nicer looking infield, more
patient hitters and a more stable stock price.
</P>
<P>
   Three rings in four years. Three World Series victories in three
tries _ the third one coming Wednesday night, as if there was any
doubt, to give the Yankees 25 World Championships.
</P>
<P>
   Team of the decade? Team of the century?
</P>
<P>
   Heck, why not just go ahead and stamp them team of the
millenium, the way adjectives and titles were being tossed around
Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, there was something a little empty about the
entire World Series procedure _ not that there weren't enough human
stories between Scott Brosius, Luis Sojo, Paul O'Neill and Joe
Torre that these Yankees handled with class and bravery.
</P>
<P>
   Even though these '99 Yanks did not reel off 125 wins like they
did in '98, there was something inevitable and exclusive about what
they did.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees spend more money, use an army of scouts, sign
bunches of position players who would start on any other team just
to sit on the bench, win everything, and the strange thing is the
Yanks still seem like the boys next door.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Jeter and Bernie Williams _ the anti-stars who look so
graceful and act so respectfully.
</P>
<P>
   Orlando Hernandez and Mariano Rivera _ the starter and the
closer who can't be beat, who were not beat, not once this
postseason.
</P>
<P>
   Even Chuck Knoblauch, with his dippy little throwing disorder,
grew endearing over the course of the postseason, even when he was
in the middle of all those controversial blown calls against the
Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   There is a toughness and a tenderness about this team.
</P>
<P>
   There is an efficiency and workmanlike attitude that let them
somehow seem better in '99 than they were in '98.
</P>
<P>
   And for all this talk of automatic performances, like that of
Rivera and that of Jeter, who rapped out a 12-game postseason
hitting streak for 1999 and extended his overall postseason streak
to 17 games, there is never anything machine-like about this team.
</P>
<P>
   That is what you have to admire about them, even when you know
George Steinbrenner spends as much as anyone in baseball and you
know he has helped raise the price of winning a World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``George has gotten better people working for him in the minor
leagues and in player development,'' old-time Yankee Whitey Ford
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has come up with a better combination of what players he
has to buy. He's just got good people working for him.''
</P>
<P>
   The story of this World Series, according to the insiders, are
the legions of scouts that the Yankees use to break down every
opponent.
</P>
<P>
   The story of this World Series is that Steinbrenner was asked
how long this dominance can continue and he said, laughing:
</P>
<P>
   ``Forever.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the Yankees were a feel-good story, a baseball team
emerging from a disastrous '80s and who used the 1995 swoon to the
Mighty Mariners to launch an all-out attack on regaining their
dominance.
</P>
<P>
   But by 1999, after dispatching the Padres in four straight in
'98 and then doing the same thing to the punchless Braves, the
Yankees have become too automatic to be true.
</P>
<P>
   Just wondering what it might be like next October if the Reds or
Red Sox, Rangers or Astros, Diamondbacks or Mariners or maybe even
the Expos, Twins, Pirates or Royals get to taste a little of this
champagne, get a whiff of this too rare World Series air.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Laura Vecsey can be reached at 206-448-8011
</P>
<P>
   or lauravecsey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
