<HEADLINE>
CLEMENS' EFFORT ENSURES SERIES SWEEP FOR TEAM OF CENTURY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It ended where it had to, in the cathedral of
baseball, a house a legend built and heroes still inhabit.
</P>
<P>
   A century of baseball concluded Wednesday night with the New
York Yankees doing what they do best. They won the World Series for
the 25th time, sweeping it for the second year in a row by beating
the Atlanta Braves, 4-1, at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're the Team of the Century,'' said Whitey Ford, who threw
out the first pitch to another Yankee Hall of Famer, Yogi Berra.
``There's nobody close.''
</P>
<P>
   Roger Clemens was the winning pitcher, adding the only line he
needed to complete his Cooperstown plaque. The 16-year veteran
forced a trade to the Yankees this spring, expressly to win his
first world championship. He accomplished that with an overpowering
performance.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens worked 72/3 innings, allowing four singles and one run.
Mariano Rivera got the last four outs and earned Most Valuable
Player honors with his second save to go with his victory in Game
3. Catcher Jorge Posada was there to greet Rivera at the mound when
Keith Lockhart's fly ball landed in the glove of left fielder Chad
Curtis for the final out.
</P>
<P>
   ``The MVP thing _ we are all MVP,'' said Rivera, whose 0.38
postseason earned-run average is the best in history. ``The whole
thing _ manager, coaches, the 25 guys that were on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   The 25th man, Jim Leyritz, agreed. Leyritz, a frequent October
giant and a two-time Yankee, ripped a pinch-hit homer in the eighth
to seal the win.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things I found out when I went away and came back
here, everyone's one of 25,'' he said. ``There's no one who doesn't
stretch, no one who takes a day off. There's no special treatment
for anybody. That's what makes this team great.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees scored three runs in the third, and that was more
than enough for Clemens. Chuck Knoblauch led off with an infield
single that shortstop Walt Weiss backhanded but couldn't snare.
Derek Jeter, who tied Hank Bauer's postseason record by extending
his hitting streak to 17 games, singled.
</P>
<P>
   With the bases loaded, Ryan Klesko couldn't handle Tino
Martinez's smash to first. It went for a two-run single, and a
single by Posada gave New York its third run off Braves
right-hander John Smoltz.
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz was mostly masterful. He struck out 11 in seven innings,
improvising with sidearm deliveries and a surprise knuckleball and
retiring 10 in a row in one stretch. Like teammate Greg Maddux in
Game 1, he pitched exceptionally. But his pinstriped opponent
pitched better.
</P>
<P>
   On a 48-degree night with a steady wind, Clemens was the only
player on either side in shirt sleeves. And as the game went on _
especially after the Yankees built a lead _ he became more
demonstrative.
</P>
<P>
   He hopped in excitement after striking out Andruw Jones to end
the fifth, and pumped his fists and raised his arms to celebrate
outs in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens pitches on emotion, and he's had problems this year
channeling it. For a few pitches in the seventh, he seemed to let
the scene overcome him. With two outs and an 0-2 count on Lockhart,
the 56,752 fans stood and shouted, and Clemens' next pitch sailed
outside and high. He missed badly later in the at-bat before
inducing a pop-up, and as soon as it was hit, Clemens strode off
the mound, looking relaxed again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard people talk about how I could be rattled and things
like that,'' said Clemens, who was hammered in his last postseason
start and bumped to the No. 4 spot in the rotation. ``I don't get
rattled. Maybe earlier in my career in big games. But what are big
games? I pitched a big game tonight and I put pressure on myself to
rise to the occasion.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens became the second member of the luckless 1986 Boston Red
Sox to find redemtion with the Yankees. Wade Boggs, who cried in
the dugout after those Sox lost the Series to the New York Mets,
rode a horse around the field after winning with the Yankees in
'96. And now Clemens has the ring he coveted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know everyone is excited for him to come up big like that
and get his first ring,'' said Knoblauch. ``He's been waiting
forever for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens' night ended in the eighth _ the inning he had not been
permitted to pitch after going seven strong in Game 6 of '86.
</P>
<P>
   With two outs in the eighth, Clemens couldn't reach an
in-between roller by Weiss. He scrambled to cover first, and
appeared to be spiked by Weiss. He stayed in the game, but when
Gerald Williams fought from an 0-2 hole and singled sharply to
left, Torre called on Jeff Nelson from the bullpen. As cameras
flashed and the crowd roared, Clemens lofted his cap and waved.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson allowed a run-scoring single to Bret Boone, who led the
Braves with a .538 average, then turned things over to Rivera. As
usual, the rest was automatic _ a ground out by Chipper Jones ended
the eighth, and a grounder, pop-up and Lockhart's fly made the
Yankees champs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so hard to go all the way every year,'' said Braves
manager Bobby Cox, whose team lost its fourth World Series in five
tries this decade. ``It's amazing to me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This team, more than any team I've had, represents what New
York's all about,'' controlling owner George Steinbrenner said.
``Nobody was better than this team for heart, courage and hanging
tough.''
</P>
<P>
   And no franchise was better this century than the one cavorting
on the Bronx green Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Tyler Kepner can be reached at 206-448-8004
</P>
<P>
   or tylerkepner &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-99 0230EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
