r s BC-FBC-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     10-28 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VAN RAAPHORST RATES COACH'S PRAISE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The soundtrack at the Coliseum on Saturday was all
wrong. Mike Van Raaphorst was having an Amazing Grace kind of day,
but the background noise was more along the lines of Anarchy in the
UK.
</P>
<P>
   It was discomfitting, to hear boos dubbed in the place of
applause. Van Raaphorst, making his fourth start in place of
injured Carson Palmer, was putting up numbers for posterity. He was
flinging the football like no USC quarterback before him.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer. Rodney Peete. Rob Johnson. Van Raaphorst outthrew them
all. In a four-point loss to Stanford, he moved the Trojans 415
yards through the air.
</P>
<P>
   The quarter-mile-high club Raaphorst joined couldn't be any more
exclusive if it was located inside the Staples Center. John Elway
had 418 yards on his most prodigious day at Stanford. No UCLA
quarterback save Cade McNown has managed more than 409.
</P>
<P>
   The redshirt junior who in August couldn't be sure he'd take
another snap was launching balls like Mr. October. If not for R.
Jay Soward's bobbling of a beautifully thrown bomb, Van Raaphorst
would have had four touchdowns instead of three, more than 450
yards passing, a huge, confidence-building win and the best table
La Barca, a favorite postgame hangout.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Van Raaphorst walked off the field to the sound of
boos, too tired to lift his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   It says here Van Raaphorst deserved better.
</P>
<P>
   Much lip service is paid to sports as a character-building
exercise, but fans' actions often suggest it's more about
dynasty-building.
</P>
<P>
   Shame on USC fans for not seeing the forest for the swaying,
celebrating Stanford tree. It's not Van Raaphorst's fault the
Trojans aren't winning like it's 1979.
</P>
<P>
   In a quainter place and time, the veteran who lost his starting
job but kept at it, who never missed a voluntary summer workout and
made enough plays to win the most critical game of the season would
be a standard bearer, not a scapegoat. His perseverance would be
lauded, his progress duly noted. The airwaves would be alive with
the sounds of a brewing quarterback controversy.
</P>
<P>
   Pete Rose vs. Jim Gray wouldn't engage us.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Tyson vs. himself wouldn't engross us.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta Braves vs. history wouldn't entice us.
</P>
<P>
   Van Raaphorst or Palmer _ that would be our topic on the table.
The Castoff vs. The Kid.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, in this day and age, athletes who never question their
coaches, who work hard because the work is its own reward, who say
things like, ``I feel like I'd be defrauding a lot of people if I
wasn't trying to get better,'' don't impress people much.
</P>
<P>
   Virtue is nice, but victories are the quickest route to
validation.
</P>
<P>
   Van Raaphorst, who was being hailed as a terrific NFL prospect
pre-Hackett, is 1-3 as a starter this year. In that span he has
completed 54 percent of his passes and is averaging one
interception every 35 throws (Palmer, before he got hurt, was
averaging an interception every 18 passes.)
</P>
<P>
   Against Stanford Van Raaphorst scrambled for one first down,
completed 25 passes, threw a ball that traveled 60 yards in the air
and showed admirable poise for someone whose offensive line offered
about as much protection as a dozing bodyguard.
</P>
<P>
   And all he was made to feel was down.
</P>
<P>
   It's a good thing Van Raaphorst derives his strength and
self-worth from his newfound spirituality and not other people's
sentiments.
</P>
<P>
   Not that everybody was a boo bird. There was the head coach who
said, ``I'm very happy for Van Raaphorst. To see the way he has
responded (after being unseated by Palmer), that's something every
coach loves to see. I'm kind of proud of the way he's played.''
</P>
<P>
   Pretty classy of Cal coach Tom Holmoe to weigh in like that,
don't you think?
</P>
<P>
   USC's second-year head coach Paul Hackett has hung his star on
Palmer and perhaps that clouds everything he says. On Saturday, the
nicest thing he could say about Van Raaphorst's performance was,
``He gave us a chance to win. (Pause) He had chances to do more and
win it himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly a rousing review.
</P>
<P>
   Three days later, after examining the game videotape, Hackett
was more effusive in his praise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say Mike's risen to the occasion well,'' he said.
``He's used his time as a backup to continue to develop his skills
as a passer and a leader. He's doing some things people said he
couldn't do. He's done some marvelous things. It wasn't enough
Saturday, but it was great football.''
</P>
<P>
   A drained Van Raaphorst told people after the Stanford game,
``I'm just kind of numb. I left everything I've got on the football
field.''
</P>
<P>
   The thing to remember is no athlete can do any more than that,
no matter what the scoreboard and the spectators say. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
