<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA LINE PLAY IS TROUBLING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ For assistant coach Mark Weber, rectifying UCLA's
offensive line problems is like playing Clue. Is it guard Mike
Saffer on the right side, with bad footwork? Or tackle Blake Worley
on the left side, missing an assignment? Or center Troy Danoff
missing his run block? Or tackle Brian Polak? Or guard Oscar
Cabrera?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one guy on a play breaking down, not three or four
guys,'' Weber said. ``The problem is, it's a different guy each
play.''
</P>
<P>
   But as the Bruins adjust to life without Kris Farris, Andy
Meyers and Shawn Stuart, two things seem certain: Most of the
mistakes are due to inexperience _ there are three first-time
starters _ and the line isn't UCLA's only problem, just the most
noticeable.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, UCLA quarterbacks were sacked six times Saturday
at Oregon State, but only three resulted from bad blocking. Other
times, the quarterbacks held the ball too long, which is a
complicated problem itself: Are they indecisive, or are receivers
struggling to get open? It varies each play.
</P>
<P>
   ``People will think this is crazy, but we had pretty good pass
protection against Oregon State,'' offensive coordinator Al Borges
said. ``We had plenty of time to throw, but it's not just the
quarterbacks. Some was due to our inability to get off bump-and-run
coverage.''
</P>
<P>
   It's impossible to separate the offensive problems, but as Weber
knows, an efficient attack starts with effective blocking. If there
are no holes, there's no running game. If there's no running game,
defenses stack the line to pressure the quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're very talented, but we need to learn to focus on
different situations,'' Weber said. ``If there's one thing I'd like
to see us do, it's cut loose and play. If we're going to make a
mistake, make it full speed.''
</P>
<P>
   Familiar faces: Saffer, the freshman guard, is a Tucson native
and knows several of the Arizona players and coaches who face UCLA
on Saturday in the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Like injured receiver Brian Poli-Dixon, Saffer attended Tucson's
Sabino High School, then opted to spend his college career in
Westwood. (Saffer's dad, Don, played basketball at UCLA for John
Wooden.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be lying if I said there wasn't something special, but it
would mean a lot more if we were going there,'' Saffer said. ``I
took a lot of flack (from friends) for leaving Tucson, and at the
very least, I'd like to show I didn't make a bad decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Stat of the day: Put the Bruins' red zone defense on red alert.
Opponents have scored touchdowns on 82 percent of their visits (23
of 28 attempts) inside UCLA's 20-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   Double-double threat: Arizona has two quarterbacks, Keith Smith
and Ortege Jenkins, and both are equally adept at running and
passing.
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins, of Long Beach, is the Pac-10's No. 2 passer (148
efficiency rating), while Smith, of Newbury Park, is the league's
No. 3 passer (147.7 rating).
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats probably will use both Saturday. Jenkins also plays
receiver.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't rotate as much as we have a starter and a substitute
who we use when we see fit,'' Wildcats coach Dick Tomey said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
