<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOWARD SHOULD BE READY, BUT ALLMOND IS WAITING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC wide receiver R. Jay Soward's strained left
hamstring isn't expected to sideline him Saturday against
California, but the emergence of freshman Marcell Allmond has made
the injury easier to handle.
</P>
<P>
   Allmond had a 64-yard touchdown reception against Stanford last
weekend and caught a career-high three passes for 90 yards against
the Cardinal.
</P>
<P>
   He will start Saturday if Soward can't play but should see
plenty of playing time anyway with Soward less than 100 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Allmond said he didn't expect the 64-yard pass play, which
included bouncing off two Stanford defenders and racing down the
sideline for the touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was kind of surprised I was that open,'' Allmond said. ``I
was working in practice on not falling down after I got hit. I feel
I'm always part of the offense but it felt great to contribute.''
</P>
<P>
   Even after his breakthrough game, Allmond expects Soward to
return against Cal.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll be back. He always finds a way to come back,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer update: Tuesday night, quarterback Carson Palmer
discarded the shoulder harness he's worn for several weeks to keep
his broken collarbone in place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to burn it,'' Palmer said.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer was examined by doctors Tuesday, and said he is
recovering ahead of schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said it's coming along well. Next week, I might start
doing upper body work and maybe even throw,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer is still sure he wants to return for the UCLA game Nov.
20. ``Definitely,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   USC coach Paul Hackett said he was ``excited'' X-rays revealed
the bone has grown back faster than expected.
</P>
<P>
   But Hackett is still reluctant to say when a decision will be
made on whether to bring Palmer back. He said when he coached in
Kansas City, Chiefs quarterback Elvis Grbac needed seven weeks to
recover, but was in poor physical condition when he returned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm open (to playing Palmer), but when you consider all the
things, and that were not in the hunt for the Rose Bowl ...,''
Hackett said. ``When you look at the big picture, everyone says
it's better to have a third year (starting at quarterback).''
</P>
<P>
   Palmer would have to redshirt to start three full seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking advice: With USC mired in a three-game losing streak,
Hackett said he spoke to Oakland Raiders coach Jon Gruden on
Tuesday, after the Raiders overcame a 17-point deficit to defeat
the New York Jets.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see what they've been through, and you hope a little
something they say will tweak you,'' Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett said he would also call childhood friend Ron Hudson, who
is the offensive coordinator at Kansas State. The Wildcats have
overcome two 21-point deficits this season.
</P>
<P>
   State of the line: Left tackle Brent McCaffrey sprained his
ankle Wednesday and was carted off the field as a precaution.
Trevor Roberts will probably start at left tackle.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett said Donta Kendrick has recovered from his sore ankle
and would probably start at left guard in place of Faasea Mailo,
who is expected to miss the Cal game with a bruised shin.
</P>
<P>
   Another Avenger: Former USC wide receiver Mike Bastianelli said
he will sign with the Los Angeles Avengers, who will play in the
Arena Football League in April. The Avengers have already signed
former USC defensive back Ken Haslip.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
