<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 02:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0931 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-WOLF-COLUMN-LADN     10-28 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-WOLF-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS MIAMI FINISHED AS BEAST OF EAST?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ While Miami's come-from-behind victory over Boston
College was thrilling viewers on CBS last Saturday, it brought up a
pressing question. Could it have been one of Miami's last Big East
telecasts?
</P>
<P>
   It's a question that has the league in a nervous posture as the
school's presidents meet next week, and with its TV contract about
to expire.
</P>
<P>
   Miami is flirting with joining the Atlantic Coast Conference and
it would affect the Big East's television negotiations with CBS and
ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   The Big East presidents want an answer on Miami's status at
their annual meeting in Philadelphia next week. Miami's position
with the league is an agenda item, and Big East commissioner Mike
Tranghese said school president Tad Foote will address the issue.
</P>
<P>
   But Foote said things are ``status quo,'' meaning Miami is a
member of the Big East, but still having informal conversations
with the ACC.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if he will give Big East presidents a definitive
answer on Miami's status with the league, Foote said, ``Until
conversations (with the ACC) end, we're not going to say
definitively what that status is.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hopeful, and I've always been optimistic, that at the end
of the day they'll realize they'll be better off with us,''
Tranghese said.
</P>
<P>
   Miami could cost the Big East its TV contract with CBS. The
league is in the process of renegotiating its football and
basketball television deals. The Big East is negotiating the deals
separately this year, but CBS and ESPN hold the TV rights to both
sports. The football contract expires at the end of the 2000
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were at a point in our negotiations where we just had to
put it on hold,'' Tranghese said. ``Both networks want to know
where Miami stands.''
</P>
<P>
   CBS is already adding more SEC games, at the expense of Big East
games, and the departure of Miami could be fatal.
</P>
<P>
   Brees leaves? Purdue junior quarterback Drew Brees said this
summer he might consider entering the NFL draft after this season
if Purdue went 11-1, went to the Rose Bowl and he was projected as
a high draft pick.
</P>
<P>
   Although Purdue has three losses, Brees said Tuesday leaving
early is still a possibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's still a lot more I'd like to do (in college), but we
still have four more games left,'' said Brees, referring to three
regular-season games and a likely bowl game. ``There's still a lot
more football to be played.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see. I'd rather not talk about it (the NFL draft)
because I don't know what's going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Upon further review: The Big Ten finally gave Purdue coach Joe
Tiller an explanation on Penn State's illegal participation penalty
last Saturday. Penn State cornerback Anthony King came off the
sidelines to make a tackle of wide receiver Chris Daniels following
a catch.
</P>
<P>
   The Nittany Lions were one man short at the time. If King had
been the 12th man, Purdue would have automatically been awarded a
touchdown. But since he was the 11th, the officials had the
discretion of assessing a 15-yard penalty or awarding a touchdown
and they chose the penalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Talking to the (Big Ten) director of officials, in all of
college football history, he said you can count on one hand the
times that has occurred and touchdowns have been awarded in the
past,'' Tiller said. ``So my response was, `Why wasn't one awarded
this time?'''
</P>
<P>
   Going to the dogs: Boston College purchased a pair of bird dogs,
Blaze and Tucker, to keep geese off its practice field.
</P>
<P>
   Geese, believe it or not, have been a big problem for BC in the
past.
</P>
<P>
   ``You couldn't even walk on the field without stepping in geese
droppings,'' O'Brien said.
</P>
<P>
   The dogs, who have a house to the side of the field and have
been known to wander around the athletic department offices, seemed
to be the most viable option for the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to do something,'' O'Brien said of the geese. ``They're
on there every morning and every evening, and that was the solution
we came up with.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien said he even interacts with the dogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I bring them a biscuit every once in a while? Yeah,''
O'Brien said. ``And, I tell them they're doing a good job.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost Oregon: But for a massive turnaround in 1993, Cal's star
linebacker Sekou Sanyika might have wound up at Oregon instead of
at Cal.
</P>
<P>
   He and his father, a Cal professor, were at the Ducks-Bears game
in 1993, and Oregon held a 30-0 halftime lead. Sanyika, a high
school junior at the time, tried to convince his dad to leave the
blowout, but his father convinced him they should stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right about that time I was starting to think about where I
might want to go to college,'' Sanyika said. ``I told my dad, `If
they come back to win this one, then I'm going to Cal.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The Bears won 42-41, ``so I guess that was it for me,'' Sanyika
said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
