<SLUG> BC-CAR-FONTANA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRUCKS AND TREATS AT FONTANA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LOUIS BREWSTER  
 Inland Valley Daily Bulletin  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FONTANA _ Racing's version of the Odd Couple _ open-wheel Champ
cars and NASCAR trucks _ promises some tricks and treats this
weekend at California Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Competition for the CART FedEx Championship Series and NASCAR
Craftsman Truck Series driving titles will provide the impetus for
the Halloween weekend activity.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, more than $3 million in prize money will be up for
grabs. Most of the money is earmarked for those competing in
Sunday's Marlboro 500, the weekend's marquee event. The winner of
the 250-lap race, the last of 20 on the 1999 CART schedule, will
take home a $1 million check.
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Vasser collected the cash a year ago, passing Greg Moore
on the start of the last lap for the win. Either Dario Franchitti
or Juan Pablo Montoya will collect another $1 million. They are the
only drivers who can win the series championship with Franchitti
holding a nine-point edge over the rookie from Colombia. Alex
Zanardi won the last two titles.
</P>
<P>
   This marks the eighth time since the series conception in 1983
that the points race has come down to the final event. It is
interesting to note that the driver in front has always emerged as
the champ.
</P>
<P>
   There's a greater point separation in the truck race, but three
drivers enter the 25th and final event with the opportunity to
succeed Palmdale's Ron Hornaday as champion. Greg Biffle enters
Saturday's NAPA 200 with a 21-point advantage over 1997 titlist
Jack Sprague.
</P>
<P>
   However, it's no longer a Ford vs. Chevrolet battle as Dennis
Setzer, driving a Dodge, trails Biffle by 25 points. That the truck
points battle will be decided in the final race of the year is
nothing surprising. Hornaday won his second crown last year by
three points, finishing second in the season finale at Las Vegas
Motor Speedway behind Sprague.
</P>
<P>
   There will be a new look for this year's truck race at Fontana.
While the first two races were conducted under the old mandatory
mid-race break rule, green flag pit stops are now allowed.
</P>
<P>
   Both series have adapted to the 2-mile, D-shaped speedway, which
will complete its third full racing season. Mauricio Gugelmin set a
world's closed-course record in 1997 when he qualified for the
Marlboro 500 at 240.942 mph.
</P>
<P>
   CART moved even quicker thereafter to slow the racers, requiring
the Handford Device in the 1998 race. While it slowed Vasser's
winning average speed to 153.785 mph, nearly 13 mph slower than
Mark Blundell's time in the inaugural, there was considerably more
passing and side-by-side racing.
</P>
<P>
   Two other championships also will be decided during race week.
Oriol Servia has a commanding margin in PPG-Dayton Indy Lights, the
developmental arm for CART. Servia leads Casey Mears 130-116 with
just one race left on the 12-race schedule. The Indy Lights race, a
50-lap effort, is set for Sunday at 9:50 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Another $50,000 will be at stake in the inaugural Craftsman Pit
Crew Challenge. Points were awarded pit crews, on the same scale
used to determine the driving champion, on total time spent in the
pits through the first 19 events.
</P>
<P>
   The four crews _ representing Max Papis, Paul Tracy, Montoya and
Michael Andretti _ will compete today at 3 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The finals will consist of a five-minute warm-up session
followed by 10 minutes of track time, with all four cars on the
track at the same time. During that time span, each driver will be
required to make at least two pits stops, during which all four
tires must be changed correctly. The best average time will win,
which may lead to more than two spots in order to lower the average
time.
</P>
<P>
   For the fans, the treat will be a special musical performance by
Peter Frampton on the infield stage Saturday night, followed by a
fireworks show.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
