<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-BOOKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FUN LOOK AT FISHING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICH MARTIN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The connection between fishing and mental health
has seldom been clearer than in Paul Quinnett's ``Fishing Lessons:
Insights, Fun, and Philosophy from a Passionate Angler'' (Andrews
McMeel Publishing; $21.95).
</P>
<P>
   Quinnett is a fisherman who also happens to be a psychologist
specializing in suicide prevention. His vocation and avocation fit
neatly together in helping him retain perspective in a fast-paced
world. Fishing is therapy, and he advocates plenty of it to stay
sane.
</P>
<P>
   Angling is not just a hobby for Quinnett, who finds time to
tackle his hobby 80 times a year despite a busy schedule. It's part
of leading what he calls the ``unencumbered'' life ... except for
fishing gear and tackle, that is.
</P>
<P>
   He diagnoses this country's ``hurry-up sickness'' and instead
touts the ``quiet time'' he gains: ``Angling is how I get
reacquainted with my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   He writes, ``When you are quiet and engaged in unfocused
focusing, things deep in the great unconscious unfetter themselves
and start to drift around, like cotton from a cottonwood tree on a
breezy day.''
</P>
<P>
   In his work, Quinnett sees stressed-out professionals who never
find time for their children or for life writ large. One chapter,
``Big Boat, No Fish,'' centers on men who buy all the right gear
but never can quite squeeze in time for fishing.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington state author takes the right angle when
discussing the lure of the outdoors and what we're all trying to
escape: ``Like a lot of stiffs who work as a slave in the city, I
rocket along, doing what I do, pacing myself against the passage of
time and the competition, as if I were in some great race to
somewhere important. Fact is, if we stand back and study them for a
moment, most of our races are not worth winning, let alone running.
Some days I worry I might just continue to pick up speed until,
around 5 o'clock, I'll just vanish into thin air.''
</P>
<P>
   Many outdoors enthusiasts will find the author's philosophy of
enjoying the present and not obsessing about work as refreshing as
a Sierra Nevada lake at sunrise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fishing Lessons'' is entirely readable _ slow-paced yet
lively. Anyone picking up the 311-page book during a leisurely
vacation would get some laughs and more than a few nuggets of
wisdom. Quinnett is a gifted storyteller whose message is never too
didactic; his avuncular, down-to-earth bedside manner is evident.
</P>
<P>
   But this is not just a philosophy book. The tales center on
fishing, and Quinnett spins them as cleverly as a skilled
fly-angler tying a Royal coachman.
</P>
<P>
   There's the story of a teen-age Quinnett who gets a lure
entangled in the sweater of a girl he has the hots for. A tale
about ``fly-fishing Nazis'' who believe there's only one way to
fish. Of piranha fishing in South America. Of the invariable good
luck of greenhorns and indifferent fishermen. Of a frustrating day
with Bonefish Felix in the Bahamas during which, like most in his
party, Quinnett voiced frustrations over the propensity of
profanity only to discover the guide was also a preacher. About a
memorable day when his casting was interrupted by three naked women
floating by in inner tubes. Of funeral chapels that sell coffins
for fly-anglers.
</P>
<P>
   While many of the stories are studies in levity, others are
sobering. He is dead serious when he writes about depression and
the madness of modern life.
</P>
<P>
   Another disturbing entry focused on a silver salmon in Alaska
that stranded itself on a beach finning upstream; Quinnett
struggled over whether to help the doomed fish, eventually deciding
to let nature run its course. ``To witness a death in the afternoon
wakes up in me the mild terror that perhaps the universe in which
we live and love and spend our lives is indeed without clever
design, without purpose or compassion, except as we humans imagine
it,'' he rationalizes. ``What we don't know about how the universe
works we invent, attribute meaning to, and call spiritual.''
Quinnett then watched the gulls ``dine high and handsome'' on the
dying coho salmon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fishing Lessons'' is deceptive. It looks and feels like a
``small'' book one would read in a day or two for sheer enjoyment.
The reader may be surprised to find that the tutorials in this book
stick, containing weighty pearls of wisdom.
</P>
<P>
   Quinnett's weakness is that often he tries too hard to be too
cute, but it's certainly a forgivable fault considering the many
merits of this fine title. Our rating: HHHH
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
