<SLUG> BC-OUT-REGULATIONS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRICTER ANGLING REGULATIONS PROPOSED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRETT PAULY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BISHOP _ A private inland-fisheries conservation group is
recommending stricter angling regulations to protect rainbow and
brown trout that spawn upstream from Crowley Lake during the early
and late stages of the fishing season.
</P>
<P>
   California Trout is proposing to the state Fish and Game
Commission _ the government agency in charge of reviewing such
matters _ that only two fish 16 inches and shorter be taken before
June and after September on the stretch of the Upper Owens River
known as ``the gauntlet,'' from its mouth at the lake north to
Benton Crossing Bridge. Also suggested is that only barbless hooks
and artificial lures or flies be used, according to a release
issued by the San Francisco-based nonprofit organization.
</P>
<P>
   General fishing regulations _ a five-trout limit without size or
tackle restrictions _ currently apply on river.
</P>
<P>
   CalTrout's proposal appears to coincide with the wishes of many
local anglers who prefer to cast insect imitations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an important issue to the fly-fishing population,'' said
Eric Hein, a Mammoth Lakes fly-angling guide. ``Allowing (general
regulations) in the first and last month of the season on the Upper
Owens, when the largest concentrations of fish are moving through
the river to spawn, is a problem for rainbows in the spring and
browns and fall-spawning rainbows in the fall.''
</P>
<P>
   By adopting the proposed regs, Hein said, ``Hopefully you are
going to get the spawning built back up _ better gene pool,
better-fighting fish, more natural fish.''
</P>
<P>
   Such proposals are part of the public process as a means to
affect change, according to the Department of Fish and Game.
``Requests are all given a due amount of attention as staff time
allows,'' said Bruce Kinney, supervisor of the Wildlife and Inland
Fisheries Program for the Eastern Sierra in the DFG's Bishop
office. ``They are not simply disregarded, regardless of the
sources.''
</P>
<P>
   Information: (415) 392-8887 or (760) 872-3581.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-99 0312EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
