<HEADLINE>
THE YANKEES' SUPERB CENTURY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The century is coming to a close next year and it is
all different now than it was in 1923 when the New York Yankees
began their mythical legacy of World Series championships behind a
rambunctious fellow named Babe Ruth.
</P>
<P>
   Airplanes and automobiles were in the curiosity stage. The
motion pictures were silent. Television and the Internet were
beyond human comprehension.
</P>
<P>
   But there is one constant that links these two diverse eras.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Yankees continue to win World Series championships.
</P>
<P>
   They earned their 25th one Wednesday night as they have so many
others in their glorious past with a poised, methodical
performance, combining opportunistic hitting with stout pitching _
and, oh, was Roger Clemens stout! _ to consummate a stirring
four-game sweep of the Atlanta Braves.
</P>
<P>
   These Yankees, so cool, so calm, so confident, so efficient, so
marvelously good, are slightly more than the Team of the '90s after
their latest bit of postseason mastery in which they impaled Texas
in three straight and beat Boston four of five before scoring their
spectacular knockout over the stunned Braves.
</P>
<P>
   They are the Franchise of the Millennium with their 36 World
Series appearances across the years in which they have provided
such sacred phenomena of sporting lore as Ruth's booming home runs,
Lou Gehrig's durability, Joe DiMaggio's grace, Mickey Mantle's
power, Reggie Jackson's dramatics, Casey Stengel's rhetoric, Billy
Martin's volatility, George Steinbrenner's impulsiveness and Joe
Torre's stability.
</P>
<P>
   It is impossible to compare teams from different epochs, but
it's now indisputable in light of what these Yankees have just done
to the proud Braves that they rank among the best ballclubs ever
and are the most successful since those Oakland A's of the early
1970s were winning their three consecutive World Series.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, when the Yankees cut a swath across their sport with
114 regular-season victories, it wasn't a surprise that they rolled
past the Padres.
</P>
<P>
   But what they did this time against the Braves was a far more
impressive accomplishment, considering the Atlantans were making
their fifth World Series appearance this decade and had just come
off a 103-victory regular season and an emotional NLCS triumph over
the New York Mets.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt the Yankees had to endure their share of adversities.
</P>
<P>
   Torre himself was sidelined a couple of months after being
diagnosed with prostate cancer and undergoing surgery. Darryl
Strawberry spent most of the season on the disabled list recovering
from colon cancer. Three players, Scott Brosius, Luis Sojo and Paul
O'Neill, lost their fathers, with the strong-willed O'Neill playing
in Game 4 even though his dad passed away early Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   These Yankees had their erratic moments the past summer on the
field and wound up with 98 wins, but Torre has had them in epic
form this month as they put on nightly hitting, fielding, pitching
and thinking clinics against the Rangers, Red Sox and Braves.
</P>
<P>
   These Yankees might not have been the overwhelming presence they
were in 1998, but they were a sight to behold in this World Series
as they took advantage of every Braves misstep and played the game
as it's supposed to be played.
</P>
<P>
   From the eighth inning in Game 1 when they erupted for four runs
against Greg Maddux to wipe out a 1-0 deficit to the 10th inning of
Game 3 when the seldom-used outfielder, Chad Curtis, crashed his
second home run of the evening for the dramatic game-winner to the
eighth inning of Wednesday night's affair when Torre once again
made the perfect decision _ he signaled in reliever Mariano Rivera
_ the Yankees never wavered and repulsed every Atlanta challenge.
</P>
<P>
   This was a quintessential team victory for the Yankees against a
Braves club that continually failed throughout the series to make
big plays at vital moments.
</P>
<P>
   Five-time Cy Young-award winning future Hall of Fame Roger
Clemens finally earned his first World Series win at 37 years old.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I know what it is to be a Yankee,'' Clemens kept saying in
the joyous Yankee dressing room afterward. ``What a team we are! A
lot of guys were playing with heavy hearts. But we never gave an
inch.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We just took advantage of every break that came our way,''
said shortstop Derek Jeter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We kept grinding away, and good things kept happening to us,''
said Torre.
</P>
<P>
   After it was over, the players went through their ritualistic
hugging and shoulder-pounding and the passionate fans sang along to
Sinatra's ``New York, New York,'' which blared over the
public-address system again and again and again.
</P>
<P>
   The House of Lords soon might be extinct in England, but the
Lords of Baseball, the New York Yankees, are flourishing and in
control of their domain as we reach the 2000's.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
