<HEADER>
A0943 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r w BC-HELMS-CONGRESSWOMEN-S     10-28 1088
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HELMS-CONGRESSWOMEN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HELMS EJECTS CONGRESSWOMEN BEARING MESSAGE
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By CAROLYN LOCHHEAD 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  WASHINGTON _ Sen. Jesse Helms ordered Capitol Hill police to
remove Lynn Woolsey, Nancy Pelosi and several other House
Democratic women from his hearing room Wednesday after they
demanded hearings on a treaty promoting women's rights.
<P>
   ``Now, you please be a lady,'' Helms, R-N.C., told Woolsey
before calling on police to escort them from the room, according to
a transcript of the exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Woolsey, who represents counties in Northern California, led a
group of 10 House women to deliver a letter to Helms calling for
hearings on the United Nations Convention on the Elimination of All
Forms of Discrimination Against Women, which Woolsey accused Helms
of bottling up in his Senate Foreign Relations committee since
1994.
</P>
<P>
   The protest drew stinging criticism from a Helms spokesman, who
emphatically singled out Pelosi for engaging in ``a juvenile
political stunt.'' Pelosi, who represents San Francisco, is a vocal
advocate of human rights in China and is now running for a
top-ranking Democratic leadership post.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were particularly dismayed to see Nancy Pelosi there as
part of this, because Nancy Pelosi and Sen. Helms have worked long
and hard together to promote the cause of human rights in China,''
said Helms spokesman Marc Thiessen. ``For her to come in and
disrupt the most important hearing of the Senate Foreign Relations
committee this year on China policy and the consideration of the
next ambassador to China to pull a political stunt like this is
appalling. She should be ashamed of herself.''
</P>
<P>
   Helms was chairing a hearing on President Clinton's nomination
of Admiral Joseph Prueher as ambassador to China, listening to
testimony from China human rights activist Harry Wu and Rep. Chris
Cox, R-Newport Beach, among others.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. treaty dates back to 1979 and has been signed by 162
countries but never ratified by the Senate, where it requires a
two-thirds majority. Often described as an ``international bill of
rights for women,'' it contains 30 articles defining discrimination
against women and calling for the establishment of international
tribunals to monitor alleged discrimination around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Helms, a powerful conservative who has often tangled with gay
activists and other liberal groups, opposes the treaty. But
Thiessen refused to discuss the objections, saying: ``That only
dignifies the stunt they pulled. They haven't handled this in a way
that deserves a substantive response.''
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi contended that the women were not disruptive, and she
defended the group's tactics. ``We walked into the room, and
whatever the subject matter was, we wanted to get an appointment
with Chairman Helms so he could receive our letter,'' Pelosi said.
``It didn't matter what the subject matter of the meeting was as
long as it was business. It wasn't as if it was a funeral; it was a
public hearing, and Harry Wu was not testifying at the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi said she could not understand why Helms ``is singling me
out,'' for criticism. Just because she agrees with Helms on China
policy, Pelosi said, he should not expect her ``to water down my
enthusiasm for any idea.''
</P>
<P>
   The incident started when the women held a news conference on
the House side of the Capitol, and then walked over to Helms'
Senate office to deliver their letter, signed by 100 House members.
Woolsey said she had been trying for more than two months to meet
with Helms to discuss the treaty but had gotten nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   Woolsey said she had notified Helms' office the day before that
the group was coming to his office. But when they got there,
Woolsey said, they were told by staff that the senator was
``indisposed'' and that no one knew his whereabouts or how to reach
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then some nice person whispered that he's down the hall in a
hearing,'' Woolsey said. ``So we went down to the hearing and
walked in and stood quietly _ it's a public hearing, you know _ and
he brought down the gavel and said, `I would like you to sit down
and act like ladies,' '' and, of course, there was no place to
sit.''
</P>
<P>
   Woolsey said she asked Helms from the back of the room if they
could meet to talk about the treaty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was talking with him; he was in the front of the room, and
that was all,'' Woolsey said. ``Nobody else said a word.''
</P>
<P>
   At that point, Helms repeatedly asked the women to leave and
then ordered police to escort them from the room.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is first time I've ever seen members of Congress barge
into a hearing room holding signs and yelling at the chairman from
across the room that they demand to be heard on an unrelated
issue,'' Thiessen said. ``If they want to be treated like members
of Congress, they should behave like members of Congress instead of
like a bunch of campus protesters. They were treated like any other
citizen who disrupted a hearing would be.''
</P>
<P>
   Woolsey said it was ``ironic that he (Helms) is talking about
human rights in China when he doesn't pay any attention to the
rights of people in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Woolsey argued that the hearing was public and that Helms had
wrongly refused all other channels of communication.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can walk in there anytime we feel like it,'' she said.
``Members of Congress are usually treated with some degree of
respect, and it is inappropriate for him not to respond to my
request to meet with him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure he didn't like it,'' she said, ``but we got his
attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi said it was Helms who was ungentlemanly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lynn Woolsey is very gracious,'' Pelosi said. ``It would have
been more appropriate and would have ended it all in a second if
the senator would have been more gentlemanly and said, `I can't
talk to you now. I'm engaged in other business, but I would be
pleased to receive your message at my earliest convenience.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The Woolsey protest was reminiscent of a similar female charge
on the Senate led in 1991 by then-Rep. Barbara Boxer, who led a
group of female House members up the steps of the Senate to protest
male senators' treatment of Anita Hill, who had accused Supreme
Court nominee Clarence Thomas of sexual harassment.
</P>
<P>
   Boxer drew enormous publicity from the incident, using it to
burnish her credentials as a feminist-barrier breaker and making it
an important part of her successful campaign for the Senate. She
later wrote a book about the protest, called ``Strangers in the
Senate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
