r a BC-DEBATE-DEMOCRATS-SFCH     10-28 0952
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEBATE-DEMOCRATS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE AND BRADLEY HOLD A GENTEEL DEBATE
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By MARC SANDALOW 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  HANOVER, N.H. _ Vice President Al Gore used his first televised
encounter with Bill Bradley Wednesday night to raise doubts about
the former senator's campaign promises, warning that the cost of
his health care plan alone could ``shred the social safety net.''
<P>
   Bradley, who seemed determined not to counterattack or appear
defensive, responded only by saying, ``We each have our own
experts, and I dispute the cost figure that Al has used.''
</P>
<P>
   The gentle clash was one of the only moments of discord during a
policy-laden town hall meeting that highlighted the candidates'
similarities _ both in style and policy _ far more than their
differences.
</P>
<P>
   Competing for attention with Game 4 of the World Series, the
debate at Dartmouth College came as the vice president is
struggling for political survival against a candidate who was once
a dark horse but is now leading him in most New Hampshire polls.
</P>
<P>
   On issues ranging from poverty and the environment to gay rights
and the United Nations, Gore and Bradley made parallel appeals to
liberals and other core Democratic voters.
</P>
<P>
   Both candidates promised to expand access to health care, enact
campaign finance reform, improve urban schools, direct resources to
poor children and protect civil rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a gay American can serve openly in the White House, in
Congress, in the courts, in the Treasury Department _ why can't
they serve openly in the military?'' Bradley said in perhaps the
most poignant response of the evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Bill was very eloquent on that issue,'' Gore said
moments later. ``The time has come for gays and lesbians to be
recognized in the circle of human dignity.''
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the oratory was nowhere near as vivid as the autumnal
brilliance on display in this first-in-the-nation primary state,
where cerebral and plodding answers to serious policy questions is
not necessarily a liability.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was aggressive, taking control of the floor 20 minutes
before the television cameras went on and asking for questions. He
remained in the hall at least 45 minutes afterward to chat with
audience members.
</P>
<P>
   It was clear Gore was trying to emulate President Clinton _
regarded as a master of such intimate forums _ by asking questions
of his questioners and trying to display empathy for their personal
situations.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley was more reserved, pacing the stage and speaking in a
more subdued manner.
</P>
<P>
   However, their similarities were evident even in their wardrobe:
Gore wore a red tie with diagonal stripes, Bradley a red tie with
horizontal stripes.
</P>
<P>
   The 60-minute forum, the first televised meeting between the two
candidates, included questions from audience members selected by
the event's sponsors, CNN and WMUR-TV in Manchester.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans were quick to lump the Democratic candidates under
the single label of big spenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both Bradley and Gore would have to spend the entire projected
budget surplus over the next 10 years to keep the promises they
made tonight in less than an hour,'' said New Hampshire GOP Party
Chairman Steve Duprey.
</P>
<P>
   The entire Republican presidential field _ minus Texas Gov.
George W. Bush _ will participate in an identical forum tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who now trails Bradley by several percentage points in
most New Hampshire polls, was quick to criticize Bradley's plan to
expand access to health care _ including a proposal to expand
health insurance to 95 percent of all children.
</P>
<P>
   Just eight minutes into the debate, Gore charged that Bradley's
plan would cost $1.2 trillion over 10 years, more than double what
Bradley has estimated.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is more than the entire surplus over the next 10 years,''
Gore said. ``We have to look ahead and save some of that surplus
for Medicare.''
</P>
<P>
   Disputing the figures, Bradley nevertheless agreed that it is an
ambitious and costly plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a big problem, and it needs a big solution,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the disagreements were over nuances in policy or prior
Senate votes.
</P>
<P>
   Gore challenged Bradley over his former support for school
vouchers, his reluctance to support U.S. involvement in East Timor
and his call to reopen the 1964 Civil Rights Act to expand coverage
to include gays and lesbians. None of the issues seemed likely to
inflame passions in either direction.
</P>
<P>
   Several questioners asked how to reduce the public's cynicism
toward politics, prompting Gore to defend his loyalty to President
Clinton during the Monica Lewinsky affair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand the disappointment and anger you feel toward
President Clinton, and I felt it myself,'' Gore said, though no
questioner actually brought up the impeachment scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I also feel that the American people want to move on and turn
the page, and focus on the future and not the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley passed up an opportunity to criticize the Clinton-Gore
campaign for the many ethical questions raised during their 1996
re-election, saying only that ``there were some irregularities that
were addressed.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked to explain why he quit the Senate after 18 years shortly
after the GOP took control _ a move that has been criticized by
Gore _ Bradley said he felt compelled to do things he could not do
as a senator, and now he thinks the time is right for him to return
to public office.
</P>
<P>
   When the debate ended, the World Series was still scoreless. At
least one local pundit didn't think the game would detract
attention from the political event.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Red Sox aren't in it,'' said Jeff Woodburn, former
chairman of the state's Republican Party. ``Who cares?'' &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
