<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 09:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1005 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN31-CO     10-28 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Corruption not just a foreign propensity
 &HT;    (For release Oct. 31, 1999.)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ As October began its waning week, Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright was off in Nigeria, telling her hosts that crime
and corruption are hampering Africa's economic potential. Somewhat
wryly, I thought to myself, crime and corruption haven't done
anything to mar the economical potential of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Not content to lecture the world on human rights, the U.S. now
is in the business of moralizing on corruption. Admittedly, there
is an enduring global epidemic of corruption. Like it or not, it
has been a way of doing business going back to biblical days. That
it has survived the eons tells me that while corruption is rampant,
Albright is spitting into the wind when she starts lecturing on it.
</P>
<P>
   There are some things the U.S., despite its military and
financial clout, cannot accomplish. One of them is the elimination
of corruption.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than stand behind a podium in Abuja, Nigeria, as she did
last week, she could fly back to the U.S. and give the same talk in
any number of cities where crime and corruption flourish.
</P>
<P>
   In the very week Albright was lecturing the Nigerians, two
elected public officials in Miami were at the mercy of the courts,
a former county commissioner having been convicted of taking a
bribe while in office, a state senator confessing to participating
in defrauding Medicare of close to $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   In the '90s, Miami public officials have been parading to the
hoosegow in growing numbers. Miami's city manager took a bribe and
so did one of its commissioners. Off to jail they went. Several
judges are in the slammer, and Miami is in its third year of
reeling politically from a ballot-box stuffing case in its last
mayoral election.
</P>
<P>
   I write of Miami because I know Miami, but I also know that
Miami does not have a monopoly on corruption. It is rife in other
cities. For every one public official who is caught, dozens are not
detected _ or at least not indicted.
</P>
<P>
   The best one can hope for regarding corruption is that it is
contained. It won't ever be stamped out.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that's all Albright wanted when she told a 14-nation
African conference in Nigeria that ``the battle against crime and
corruption must be won.'' But, really, it can't be won.
</P>
<P>
   I would be foolish to try to convince you that corruption in the
U.S. is as enormous as it is elsewhere. In Mexico, for instance,
stories have reached us in the wake of the recent earthquake that
many of the buildings there would not have collapsed if built
properly but that authorities were paid off to relax required
construction standards.
</P>
<P>
   Can we lecture the Mexicans on that, or should we still be
looking at the Miami area, where Hurricane Andrew in 1992 leveled
thousands of homes that were built with significant code violations
that had authorities looking the other way _ most likely at
someone's wallet?
</P>
<P>
   Coincidentally, an anti-corruption organization _ Berlin-based
Transparency International _ just last week released its ``Bribe
Payers Index,'' a ranking of nations vis-a-vis corruption. It was
based, according to the report, on how exporting countries commit
bribery in order to close a deal.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese, along with South Korea and Taiwan, were listed as
the greatest villains. Sweden, Australia and Canada were the
cleanest. But the United States ranked only 18th, in the middle of
the pack, a tad ahead of Chile. This corruption barometer is based
only on exports, not on the commonplace day-to-day political and
bureaucratic stealing that goes on behind closed doors in American
cities.
</P>
<P>
   It is one (useless) gesture to lecture other countries on human
rights; our record is better than most but not perfect. But when we
finish in the middle of the pack on export corruption, and when
there is a need for direct nonstop service to prison for elected
and appointed officials, perhaps we ought to think twice about our
``do as I say, not as I do'' predilection.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
