NYT-10-28-99 0948EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991028.0073 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 09:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1006 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN31-COX     10-28 0552
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Headline goes here
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pat Buchanan may be anti-Semitic, but he's got chutzpah.
Imagine: Buchanan calling for ``racial reconciliation'' as he
declared for the Reform Party presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, this is the same Buchanan, now a newly apostate Republican,
who charmed the nation with his call at the 1992 GOP convention for
a domestic cultural and religious war _ and who, never mind the
absence of much in the way of a volunteer army, has in fact been
fighting one himself ever since.
</P>
<P>
   This is the Grand Conciliator who has been trying to provoke
blue-collar workers into a fight over trade policy with the
corporations they work for. The very same fellow whom conservative
William F. Buckley Jr. concluded, as just about everybody else has
by now, is anti-Semitic.
</P>
<P>
   And the same who, ever rallying Americans against their
government, this year blisters the ``Washington elite'' as in 1995
he denounced ``Washington insiders'' _ although that's exactly what
Buchanan himself has been for 30 years, ever since his days as a
policy agitator and verbal gunsel for President Richard Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan was reconciling us to one another just a few years ago
by kissing off Hispanic Americans as ``Jose.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is precisely in the matter of race that Buchanan's call
for reconciliation is at its most
</P>
<P>
   jaw-dropping awesome. The man has spent decades eagerly
race-baiting.
</P>
<P>
   In one of his stabs at the Republican presidential nomination,
Buchanan went out of his way to visit the tomb of the unknown
Confederate soldier in Mississippi. He rhapsodized over the
Confederate battle flag and the Confederate ``cause.'' He promised
Tennessee voters he would ``settle accounts for our ancestors'' _
Buchanan had discovered a rebel great-grandfather _ ``with the
Yankees in Washington, D.C.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan has consistently opposed and disparaged civil rights
legislation, and some years ago he called for annexing western
Canada so the United States could get more white people.
</P>
<P>
   It is tempting to let all this go, dismissing Buchanan, after
his years of off-and-on quixotic presidential ambition and stints
betwixt as a hired pop-off for CNN, as the fringe crank that a
growing number of voters recognize him as being.
</P>
<P>
   But if Buchanan can rant his way to the Reform nomination, he'll
have access to $13 million in federal campaign funding. Never mind
whether his candidacy would hurt the Republican nominee by
attracting cultural reactionaries or the Democratic nominee by
luring working-class voters.
</P>
<P>
   More crucially, a Buchanan campaign would hurt the nation with
its certain demagoguery and venom. It would be one thing if
Buchanan showed any sign of real change. Instead, the
``reconciliation'' he spoke of turned out, in the same speech, to
be compounded of stopping immigration for an unspecified period,
killing any lingering efforts at affirmative action and sticking it
to new Americans with an English-only policy.
</P>
<P>
   Ross Perot, where are you now that we need you?
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
