<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 11:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1063 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-GARCIA-COLUMN29-COX     10-28 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARCIA-COLUMN29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Here's listening to you, kid
 &HT;    By Arnold Garcia
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The century was just 27 years old when the
movies learned to talk. The technological advance that allowed the
marriage of picture and sound opened a lot of doors and in many
ways, helped unite us.
</P>
<P>
   Going to the movies is an experience we share with people with
whom we might not otherwise have anything in common. I love movies
and always have.
</P>
<P>
   Movie scriptwriters have given us a cultural shorthand to
facilitate our communication. Movie dialogue can arouse an array of
reactions, from mirth to sadness.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, I asked readers to search their memories and
send me quotes from the century. As I mentioned then, these quotes
don't have to be soaring oratory or rousing rhetoric. I asked for
quotes from the arts, entertainment as well as politics, but mostly
I asked for quotes from life in general.
</P>
<P>
   What I offer today is some of my favorite quotes from the
movies. As was with my previous selection of quotes, these are not
represented as comprehensive. This is a sampler of some of my
favorites. Please send me yours at PO Box 670, Austin, TX 78767 or
at the email address below.
</P>
<P>
   OK, let's start at the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wait a minute, wait a minute, you ain't heard nothin' yet!''
</P>
<P>
   _ Al Jolson speaking the first line in a sound picture, ``The
Jazz Singer'' (1927).
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll bet your father spent the first year of your life
throwing rocks at the stork.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Groucho Marx to brother Chico in ``At the Circus,'' (1939).
</P>
<P>
   ``Dad always used to say that the only causes worth fighting for
were the lost causes.''
</P>
<P>
   _ James Stewart in ``Mr. Smith Goes to Washington'' (1939).
</P>
<P>
   Traveler: ``Is this a game of chance?''
</P>
<P>
   Twillie: ``Not the way we play.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Exchange between W.C. Fields as Cutberth J. Twillie and a
stranger asking about the poker game in progress. ``My Little
Chickadee'' (1940).
</P>
<P>
   ``As God is my witness, I'll never go hungry again.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Vivien Leigh ``Gone With the Wind'' (1939).
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, my dear, I don't give a damn.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Clark Gable in the same movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, no. Leave the rooster story, that's human interest.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Cary Grant in ``His Girl Friday'' (1940).
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how to run a newspaper, Mr. Thatcher. I just try
everything I can think of.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Orson Welles in ``Citizen Kane'' (1941).
</P>
<P>
   Ugarte: ``You despise me don't you, Rick?''
</P>
<P>
   Rick: ``If I gave you any thought at all I probably would.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Exchange between Humphrey Borgart as Rick and Peter Lorre as
Ugarte in ``Casablanca'' (1942).
</P>
<P>
   Yvonne: ``Where were you last night?''
</P>
<P>
   Rick: ``That was so long ago I can't remember.
</P>
<P>
   Yvonne: ``Will I see you tonight?''
</P>
<P>
   Rick: ``I never make plans that far ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Exchange between Bogart and Madeleine LeBeau as Yvonne in the
same movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``That'll be the day.''
</P>
<P>
   _ John Wayne in ``The Searchers'' (1956). The line inspired
Buddy Holly to write the hit song with that title.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fasten your seatbelts, it's going to be a bumpy night.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Bette Davis in ``All About Eve'' (1950).
</P>
<P>
   ``You should have shot that boy a long time ago, Bick. Now, he's
too rich to kill.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Chill Wills to Rock Hudson in ``Giant'' (1956).
</P>
<P>
   ``Gentlemen, you can't fight in here. This is the war room.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Peter Sellers in Dr. Stangelove (1964).
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, sir, in my case it was an accident of birth. But you,
sir, are a self-made man.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Lee Marvin to Ralph Bellamy in ``The Professionals'' (1966).
Bellamy called the Marvin character a bastard.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to start thinking beyond our guns. Those days are
closing fast.''
</P>
<P>
   _ William Holden in ``The Wild Bunch'' (1969). It's also good
advice for Travis County Democrats these days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll make him an offer he can't refuse.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Marlon Brando in ``The Godfather'' (1972).
</P>
<P>
   ``Politicians, ugly buildings and whores all get respectable if
they last long enough.''
</P>
<P>
   _ John Huston in ``Chinatown'' (1974).
</P>
<P>
   ``Gentlemen, we have to protect our phoney baloney jobs!''
</P>
<P>
   _ Mel Brooks in ``Blazing Saddles.''
</P>
<P>
   Darn, I just got warmed up and it's time to go, but you should
have the idea by now. Send us some your favorite quotes of the
century from the movies or plays or whatever source. We plan to
publish them later in the year.
</P>
