<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-99 1137EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991028.0100 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 11:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1068 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i BC-IRAN-REFORMER-$ADV31-     10-28 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAN-REFORMER-$ADV31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FORMER HOSTAGE TAKER NOW IRANIAN REFORMER
 &HT;    550&AMP;ADDS
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    With IRAN-$ADV31.
 &HT;    For Use. sun., Oct. 31 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service(at) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEHRAN, Iran _ As a revolutionary 20 years ago, Iranian Mohammad
Ebrahim Asgharzadeh considered it an obligation to take over the
U.S. embassy.
</P>
<P>
   Now a popular Tehran city councilman, he is in the forefront of
Iran's reformers. He says it may be time _ given the right terms _
for the two countries to resolve their disputes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were forced to take over the embassy,'' Asgharzadeh said
recently from his wood-paneled office in Tehran city hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a reaction. The Shah going to the U.S. was not
acceptable to us,'' Asgharzadeh said. ``We had to make claims
against what he had done.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, Asgharzadeh looks more yuppie than rebel. He's a
trim 44 year-old with salt and pepper gray hair. In his
wood-paneled city hall office last week, he wore a wool sport
jacket, slacks and argyle socks.
</P>
<P>
   He has three children and had to give up his executive post at a
steel company to take office.
</P>
<P>
   Asgharzadeh does not speak for all the hostage takers. Numbering
about 300, they represent the spectrum of opinions in Iran's
current political debate.
</P>
<P>
   Some are still ardent defenders of Iran's strict religious rule
and defiance of the international community.
</P>
<P>
   But, Asgharzadeh is one of several former embassy stormers
supporting Iranian President Mohammad Khatami's efforts to open up
the country's economy and strengthen its democracy. Those are just
the moves western leaders look for.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition has come from just the types of religious hardliners
who the embassy takeover helped strengthen amid anti-American
fervor. The hardliners, seeking to maintain strict religious
control over government, appear to fear that reformers like
Asgharzadeh could dilute their power.
</P>
<P>
   Last December, shortly after Asgharzadeh used the 19th
anniversary of the takeover to invite former hostages back to
visit, he was badly beaten by a gang. The attackers may have been
trying to keep him from running for the city council.
</P>
<P>
   But, Asgharzadeh is not the only former hostage-taker to speak
out. Abbas Abdi, met publicly with former hostage Barry Rosen last
year in Paris. According to Rosen, Abdi apologized for the personal
pain he caused Rosen and his family.
</P>
<P>
   ``People like Abdi were idealists. They were young and they
believed in the Islamic revolution. They believed it was the birth
of a new freedom for them,'' Rosen said. ``Over the years, they
came to realize it was the opposite.''
</P>
<P>
   Asgharzadeh denies that he has changed or mellowed, saying he
has just acted realistically with the changing times.
</P>
<P>
   As a student, he was active in the revolution that overthrew the
dictatorial Mohammad Reza Pahlavi Shah.
</P>
<P>
   When President Jimmy Carter agreed to let the Shah enter the
United States for medical treatment, Asgharzadeh was among a small
group of leaders who organized the embassy takeover. He became the
group's spokesman but says now that he had no idea the hostage
crisis would last for 14 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could not possibly predict what would be the main result
and the reaction,'' he said. ``We just wanted to do something, some
kind of a student movement. It was very unprofessional and
amateur.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We imagined that the U.S. would return the Shah to us and that
would finish the crisis,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the Shah should have faced the same fate as former
Chilean President Augusto Pinochet, who may face a trial for
massive human rights violations.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   Asgharzadeh describes a spiral of miscalculations on both sides.
</P>
<P>
   He said the students were quickly disappointed that students in
the United States did not seem sympathetic to their cause. In the
wake of the embassy takeover, he said, the public in Iran and the
United States unified around their country's positions.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, he said, the Carter administration escalated the
tensions and prolonged the crisis with economic sanctions and a
failed rescue attempt in the desert. Many in Iran think the landing
in the desert was an attempt to topple Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini
and reinstate the Shah.
</P>
<P>
   Asgharzadeh continues to be a stern critic of U.S. policy today,
saying America still seems arrogant in its dealing with other
countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.S. believes that it is the winner of the Cold War, and
if this image will be the basis of its foreign policy with Europe,
the Pacific Rim countries, countries like Iran, they will have
problems,'' he said. ``It disgraces a nation to be put down and
threatened.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, the intense animosities of the embassy crisis have
waned and public opinion has become more varied in both Iran and
the United States. That, he said, provides an opportunity for
Khatami to attempt to appeal to the American public and Clinton to
approach the Iranians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Public opinion and emotions among our peoples would be derived
from the behavior and decision-making of our officials,'' he said.
``A relationship should be based on mutual respect and recognition
of each country's rights.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact is, Asgharzadeh concludes, that America is a world
power that Iran cannot ignore and Islamic Iran has emerged as a
power that America cannot ignore _ regardless of their history of
enmity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not necessary to forget about the past to be able to
build a future,'' he said. ``We have to accept what has happened in
reality and the future should be built on facts.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
