<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 11:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1071 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i BC-GUATEMALA-ELECT-$ADV3     10-28 1181
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUATEMALA-ELECT-$ADV31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    OPTIMISM, HOPE LACKING FOR UPCOMING GUATEMALA PRESIDENTIAL RACE
 &HT;    With Photo.
 &HT;    With GUATEMALA-BOX-$ADV31.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., Oct. 31 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By MIKE WILLIAMS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service(at) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GUATEMALA CITY, Guatemala _ The candidates have blanketed the
airwaves with television and radio commercials, and plastered the
countryside with billboards and banners. Teams of their supporters
caravan almost daily through the major cities, loudspeakers blaring
catchy campaign songs.
</P>
<P>
   But away from the small crowds that gather to hear a candidate
belt out his speech, everyday citizens don't hold out much hope
that the upcoming Nov. 7 presidential elections will bring dramatic
change to this troubled Central American nation.
</P>
<P>
   With only a few free elections under their belt after a
long-running civil war left thousands dead, kidnapped or missing,
most people here are loathe to discuss politics at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to understand that just a few years ago, saying the
wrong thing could get you killed,'' said an office manager in her
20s who insisted on anonymity. ``It is better now than before, but
people are still very insecure.''
</P>
<P>
   Just three years ago, hope blossomed in this nation of 11
million when the government and leftist guerrillas signed peace
accords ending the 36-year-old civil war, which left about 200,000
Mayan peasants dead.
</P>
<P>
   The United States _ which earlier this year, was blamed by a
Guatemalan truth commission for supporting the military's campaign
of terror that caused many of the deaths _ stepped in with
international development banks to pledge $2 billion to support the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
   But little has been done to institute reforms called for in the
peace agreement, allowing the country's notoriously inefficient
bureaucracy, corrupt judiciary and entrenched military to keep
their hold on power.
</P>
<P>
   The as-yet unsolved murder of Roman Catholic Bishop Juan Jose
Gerardi, an outspoken human rights crusader killed in April 1998
after releasing a report blaming the military for many abuses, has
also left a chill. In early October, the prosecutor assigned to the
case resigned and fled the country after receiving death threats.
</P>
<P>
   Observers fear Guatemala hasn't yet emerged fully from the
troubling shadows of fear, corruption and murder that veiled it for
so many decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``We as Guatemalans must admit to ourselves that we have failed
miserably in building solid institutions _ judiciary, economic and
social _ to counter-balance the arbitrariness heretofore
characteristic of our manner of governing,'' wrote Luis Figueroa, a
columnist for The Siglo News, Guatemala's largest English-language
newspaper. ``We have spent much energy in the creation of
governments of men, instead of governments of law.''
</P>
<P>
   The men who want to take the reins for the next era are an
interesting mix.
</P>
<P>
   Opinion polls show the frontrunner is Alfonso Portillo of the
Guatemalan Republican Front, who is favored by 48 percent of
respondents in the latest survey. Guatemala City Mayor Oscar Berger
of the National Advancement Party trails with 36 percent.
</P>
<P>
   To many, Portillo's solid lead is a sign of just how troubled
Guatemala's political scene still is: in September, he admitted
killing two men in Mexico in the early 1980s, saying it was an act
of self-defense after a heated argument. He fled Mexico and was
never prosecuted.
</P>
<P>
   Such an admission might be enough to sink the candidacy of a
presidential hopeful in most countries. Instead, Portillo's stock
has risen, as he has boasted the killings prove his decisiveness
and courage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just as I defended my life, I would defend the lives of
Guatemalans,'' Portillo told supporters in his trademark gravelly
voice, which has earned him the nickname, ``the Husky Chicken.''
</P>
<P>
   Portillo is seen by many as a front man for Gen. Efrain Rios
Montt, a former dictator who ran the country for a year after a
military coup in 1983. Conducting a scorched-earth campaign against
the guerrillas, Rios Montt's regime allegedly destroyed dozens of
rural villages and executed thousands of suspected guerrilla
sympathizers.
</P>
<P>
   The one-time dictator tried to run for president himself in
1995, but was ruled ineligible by the judiciary because of his
participation in the 1983 coup.
</P>
<P>
   Portillo also ran in 1996, but lost to former Guatemala City
Mayor Alvaro Arzu of the National Advancement Party, a coalition of
conservative business interests.
</P>
<P>
   Now Berger is trying to repeat Arzu's feat, vaulting from the
mayorship of the country's largest city to the presidency. He is
campaigning on his record of infrastructure improvements in the
city _ new highways, bridges and other public works _ as well as a
promise to fight crime and increase foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
   Running a distant third is Alvaro Colom Caballeros, who
represents a leftist coalition that includes the former guerrillas.
Colom has gained a bit recently in polls but still hasn't managed
to top 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   With eight other minor candidates running, the election could go
to a Dec. 26 run-off between the top two vote-getters.
</P>
<P>
   The winner faces serious problems. Guatemala suffers widespread
unemployment, stunning poverty, poor health-care, and woefully
inadequate education and sanitation systems for most areas outside
the major cities. United Nations statistics list about 85 percent
of the population as impoverished.
</P>
<P>
   Residents cite those problems, along with a disturbing crime
wave, as their greatest concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``The unemployment causes the robberies because if people can't
find work, they will steal to feed their families,'' said Eva de
Lorenzi, a teacher who lives near the capital. ``I think most
people won't even vote for president because they are not
interested.''
</P>
<P>
   A referendum in the spring on important constitutional reforms
mandated by the peace accords drew only 18 percent of the country's
4.5 million registered voters. The reforms failed to win a
majority, leaving the status of the peace agreements up in the air
until a new president is elected.
</P>
<P>
   In still another sign of Guatemala's shaky status, U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan recommended earlier this month that a
U.N. military observer force overseeing the implementation of the
peace accords extend its mission for another year.
</P>
<P>
   Annan cited Guatemala's failure to carry out judicial, electoral
and fiscal reforms as reasons for the extension.
</P>
<P>
   With so much riding on the elections, citizens _ at least those
who can afford to focus on something more than the daily struggle
for survival _ are surprisingly resigned. Many say it makes little
difference which candidate prevails.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things are very much better than during the civil war because
there is no terror or destruction,'' said Lorenzi. ``But people
still don't have confidence in the government or the police. We
need to educate ourselves. We aren't used to living in a
democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
