<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 11:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1073 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-MCNEELY-COLUMN29-COX     10-28 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCNEELY-COLUMN29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Elizabeth Dole may be running for vice president, but not on
Bush ticket
 &HT;    By Dave McNeely
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Now Elizabeth Dole's campaign for vice president
can get rid of its camouflage and get into high gear. That's almost
certainly what she was running for anyway, though it's possible she
actually thought she could be elected president. After all, her
husband had.
</P>
<P>
   But she found out that her name identification, borrowed from
hubby Bob, was no match for George W. Bush's, borrowed from his
dad. Hers didn't carry with it anywhere near the goodwill, the
contacts or especially the fund-raising network that the Texas
governor enjoyed. And she also found that being head of the Red
Cross had very little crossover value into politics.
</P>
<P>
   A similar dose of reality leading up to the 1994 Texas
governor's race had caused several qualified would-be candidates
for the GOP nomination to back out _ including Tom Luce of Dallas
and Rob Mosbacher Jr. of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Both had run statewide before, and both wanted to run for
governor. But they had sense enough to know that running against
the namesake of a former president and vice president of the United
States would pit them against huge inherited name identification
and fund-raising base. They bit their tongues and chose not to run.
</P>
<P>
   Face it, George W. Bush ran for governor of Texas in 1994 not
because he should be governor, but because he could be. No public
record, no previous elected office. Just Daddy's name and friends.
</P>
<P>
   That is not to say he didn't run a good campaign to unseat
Democrat Ann Richards, or that he hasn't proven that he is capable
of being governor. But that's not why he was capable of winning the
job. He knows it, you know it, and the American people know it.
</P>
<P>
   George the Younger had not just the advantage of his father's
name but also the organization that his father had mustered by
being on the national ballot every presidential election from 1980
through 1992. The national press seemed somewhat blown away that
the Texas governor's first trips to Iowa and New Hampshire in June,
after the spring legislative session in Texas, came off so well.
But he had the advantage of precision advance work from some of the
same people who'd done it for his dad.
</P>
<P>
   To his credit, George the Younger has capitalized on the
combination of his own time as governor of the nation's second most
populous state and his status as former First Son to court other
Republican governors, plus a huge number of state legislators and
congressman. In a well-choreographed succession that must have been
torture for the other Republican presidential hopefuls, Bush has
day after day, week after week, added elected officials with
political organizations to his endorsement list.
</P>
<P>
   Add that to a huge amount of money, and after awhile, it becomes
so overwhelming that even Elizabeth Dole figures out it's time to
head for the sidelines, and get back to hoping to be nominated for
the vice presidential slot her husband was 23 years ago. It was not
a good sign when more women at the National Federation of
Republican Women in Seattle recently said they preferred Bush to
her.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the only major issue on which she's differed with
George W. is gun control _ she's for it, he's against it _ she's
unlikely to be Bush's choice for the second slot.
</P>
<P>
   First, the Doles and Bushes, even though they pay lip service to
each other, have never had a mutual admiration society.
</P>
<P>
   Secondly, unlike the situation when Ronald Reagan picked the
elder Bush as his running mate in 1980 after they'd opposed each
other in the primaries, the elder Bush's showing had been good
enough that Reagan considered him an addition to the ticket _
despite Bush's characterization of Reagan's balanced budget promise
as ``voodoo economics.''
</P>
<P>
   Third, and most important, Elizabeth Dole is, to use her
husband's words, ``a bridge to the past.'' Assuming George W. wins
the nomination, he can pick whomever he wants as his running mate.
And if he should choose a woman, he'd be more likely to go for
someone like New Jersey Gov. Christine Todd Whitman, who's proven
herself electorally.
</P>
<P>
   So even thoughshe's now got nothing left but the VP track, even
though George W. says nice things about her, don't expect her to be
on the ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Dave McNeely writes about politics for the Austin
American-Statesman. You may contact him at
dmcneely(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
