<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RADIO-REUNION29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `1,000-watt' girls about to be rediscovered
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Radiophiles, make sure you tune into National Public
Radio's ``All Things Considered'' on Friday. The provocative
news/features show has uncovered a long-lost creation of legendary
Sun Records founder Sam Phillips _ and it's not Elvis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lost and Found Sound'' will feature the story of the nation's
first all-female radio station, WHER-AM in Memphis. From 1955 to
1971, the ``beautiful 1,000-watt station,'' as it billed itself,
was on the air with a staff of permed and perky women at the mike,
playing the lush music of Dean Martin, Dinah Washington, Frank
Sinatra, Henry Mancini and Percy Faith.
</P>
<P>
   WHER was the brainchild of Phillips, who hatched the idea of an
``all-girl'' radio station as a novelty a year after he signed
Elvis Presley to a recording contract. While the King was wiggling
his leg on Union Street at Sun, WHER was broadcasting from a
control room decorated to look like a pastel beauty salon. They
called it ``The Doll Den.'' An early investor was Memphis, Tenn.,
millionaire Kemmons Wilson, who founded the Holiday Inn chain and
loaned WHER space at his third motel for its studios.
</P>
<P>
   To find talent, Phillips and Wilson eavesdropped on public
conversations, looking for women ``who spoke in pleasant tones with
good diction.'' WHER went off the air just as the women's movement
was breaking down gender doors in broadcasting.
</P>
<P>
   For years, the station was largely forgotten. Then NPR producers
Nikki Silva and Davia Nelson overhead Phillips talking about WHER.
Intrigued, they tracked down the original station announcers,
programmers, saleswomen and program directors, who are interviewed
on the show. They also chat with Phillips, as well as play vintage
commercials and station air checks.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been one of the most amazing stories we've
unearthed,'' Nelson said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
