<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 11:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1075 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i BC-GUATEMALA-BOX-$ADV31-     10-28 0305
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUATEMALA-BOX-$ADV31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TWO TOP CONTENDERS IN GUATEMALA PRESIDENTIAL ELECTION
 &HT;    With Photo Mugs.
 &HT;    With GUATEMALA-ELECT-$ADV31.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., Oct. 31 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By MIKE WILLIAMS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service(at) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GUATEMALA CITY, Guatemala _ On Nov. 7, Guatemala will hold its
first presidential elections since the 1996 signing of peace
accords which ended the nation's 36-year-old civil war.
</P>
<P>
   The leading candidates include:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ALFONSO PORTILLO, Guatemalan Republican Front (FRG) _ Portillo
leads in most opinion polls, despite his controversial admission in
September that he killed two men in Mexico in 1982 while working
there as a law professor. Portillo insists he acted in
self-defense, but he left Mexico without being prosecuted. Many see
Portillo, who ran unsuccessfully in 1996, as a front-man for former
dictator Gen. Efrain Rios Montt. Montt led the country during a
bloody period in 1983 that saw dozens of rural villages destroyed,
and thousands of alleged guerrilla sympathizers executed.
</P>
<P>
   OSCAR BERGER, National Advancement Party (PAN) _ Berger has been
highly popular in his four-year term as mayor of Guatemala City,
the national capital, concentrating on road construction and other
infrastructure improvements. He represents the conservative
business class, but has been hurt recently by perceived
conflicts-of-interest in the sale of the state telephone company to
a group of investors associated with his party. He hopes to succeed
current president Alvaro Arzu, the PAN candidate who defeated
Portillo in 1996, but Berger trails Portillo by about 10 percentage
points in most polls. No party in Guatemalan history has won two
presidential elections in a row.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
