<P>
   COXNET TRAVEL 1026 -- This obscure Georgia site still looks as
it did the day the explosions and screams of the Civil War battle
of Pickett's Mill filled the air. And that's what makes it so
extraordinary. (Browning, Palm Beach Post) Art includes 4-column
color photo illustration and 2-column color headline graphic.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: IF YOU GO BOX -- Directions and hours of operation for
Pickett's Mill.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: DESTINATIONS-MONTICELLO -- All my life I've wanted to
visit Thomas Jefferson's home to see his boffo vegetable garden,
his flowers and that famous dome. Now I've got my wish. (Johnson,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) Art includes color photo of
Montecello.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TRAVEL BRIEFS -- A Web site inaugurated last month by
Britain's Foreign Office details the Y2K preparedness of other
countries. (N.Y. Times News Service)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-WADESPOINT _ St. Michael's, Md. _ The view from this room
at the Wades Point Inn is no different than it was 100 years ago
when Wades Point became a popular summer resort for Maryland-area
elite. Today it is a relaxing, affordable bed-and-breakfast inn,
just a 90-minute drive from the Washington-Baltimore-Annapolis
urban corridor. Wades Point is also a great home base to explore
the Eastern Shore of Maryland, an area rich in Colonial history and
boasting some of the best seafood (especially crab cakes), sailing
and cycling on this part of the East Coast. (Laccetti Meyers,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution.)
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Oct. 31.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-EASTSHORE _ OXFORD, Md. _ The two prominent symbols of
Maryland's Eastern Shore are crabs and ducks. Both are abundant
here on the eastern side of the Chesapeake Bay, an easy drive from
the nation's capital. Artisans' wood ducks are sold in restaurants,
shops and inns in honor of the real ones that make the bay home. We
take a tour... (Laccetti Meyers, Atlanta Journal-Constitution.)
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Oct. 31.
</P>
<P>
   GETAWAY _ The private management company AmFac Parks and Resorts
has completed a major renovation program at Unicoi, Amicalola and
Red Top Mountain state park lodges. We check out the changes during
the busy fall season, and include a listing of Halloween and Xmas
events at all three. (Hamilton, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 50.
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   GETAWAY-FESTIVALS _ Southern happenings. (Thrasher, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   FASHION
</P>
<P>
   FASHION-BINDI _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Has body glitter lost
its luster? Do henna-decorated hands make you want to suppress a
yawn? Bindi may be the answer to your adornment doldrums. The art
of decorating the face and body with colored paints, powders and
jewels, bindi is this year's mendhi, the practice of henna painting
that hit celebrity hands a few seasons back. Think of bindi as a
painless alternative to tattooing and piercing. WITH Bindi do's and
don'ts at end of file. (Sturrock, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   GARYALLAN-PROFILE _ A profile of country singer Gary Allan, who
miriam is predicting is the next big thing. He performs in Atlanta
this saturday. Staff and handout photos should be available.
(MLongino, Atlanta Jounal-Constitution). 21.
</P>
<P>
   RADIO-REUNION _ Sam Phillips, the legendary founder of Sun
Records, is mostly credited with discovering Elvis. But few people
know that, in 1956 he launched the nation's first all-female radio
station, WHER in Memphis. For nearly 20 years, the 1,000-watt
station was on the air. This Friday on National Public Radio, ``All
Things Considered'' is running a special show on the history of
WHER, reuniting its cast. In other items: arts station WGKA-AM will
air the original Orson Welle's Mercury Theater broadcast of ``War
of the Worlds,'' following its own version that has Martians
invading Atlanta. (MLongino, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 22.
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   GORDON-PARKS _ In 1937, Gordon Parks was waiting tables on a
train. During a layover in Chicago, he saw a newsreel of a Japanese
attack on an American gunboat in China. He decided to become a
photographer. Who could have guessed that he'd also become a movie
director, composer, choreographer, novelist, memoirist and poet?
Indeed, who could have guessed that this largely untutored son of
the Kansas prairie _ this scion of ``confusion and poverty'' _
could achieve his dream to simply wield an artful camera? In some
secret part of his soul, Gordon Parks would have guessed. At 87,
Parks is still wielding a camera, and still earning accolades for a
lifetime of work _ and, yes, for overcoming some very long odds. A
major retrospective of his photographs, films and music opens
Saturday at the Norton Museum of Art. (Schwan, Palm Beach Post)
MOVED
</P>
