<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORDON-PARKS29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Art continues to call Parks
 &HT;    By Gary Schwan
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1937, Gordon Parks was waiting tables on a train. During a
layover in Chicago, he saw a newsreel of a Japanese attack on an
American gunboat in China.
</P>
<P>
   He decided to become a photographer.
</P>
<P>
   Who could have guessed that he'd also become a movie director,
composer, choreographer, novelist, memoirist and poet?
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, who could have guessed that this largely untutored son
of the Kansas prairie _ this scion of ``confusion and poverty'' _
could achieve his dream to simply wield an artful camera?
</P>
<P>
   In some secret part of his soul, Gordon Parks would have
guessed.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother had freed me from the curse of inferiority long
before by not allowing me to take refuge in the excuse that I was
born black,'' Parks once wrote.
</P>
<P>
   At 87, Parks is still wielding a camera, and still earning
accolades for a lifetime of work _ and, yes, for overcoming some
very long odds. A major retrospective of his photographs, films and
music opens Saturday at the Norton Museum of Art.
</P>
<P>
   The show contains roughly 180 photographs. The movies, including
``The Learning Tree'' and ``Shaft,'' will be shown at the museum
during the exhibition and at the Kravis Center in December. In
addition, the museum will host a concert of Parks' music and the
artist will appear Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   A traveling Parks exhibition appeared at the Norton in 1984, but
the museum snapped this one up because it's the first to include
all aspects of his creative life, not just photography, according
to Norton curator Neil Watson. The show concludes with a 45-minute
film made by Parks that features his photos, music and poetry.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition is called ``Half Past Autumn: The Art of Gordon
Parks.'' The title has a nostalgic ring _ elegiac even. Although
already an accomplished memoirist, Parks said the show has given
him another chance to reevaluate his life, and ``to think back on
so many friends that I have lost.''
</P>
<P>
   He calls the exhibition a ``tone poem.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is strange poetry sometimes,'' he said during a recent
interview by phone from his Manhattan home. ``Sometimes it's
contradictory. You can't tell which way it's going, but it winds up
as poetry. It's not easy, but it's truth.''
</P>
<P>
   The truth is that Parks' life and work seem intertwined more
than is the case with all artists.
</P>
<P>
   Parks was born in 1912 on a hardscrabble farm in southeastern
Kansas, the youngest of 15 children. ``The memory of that beginning
influences my work today,'' he once wrote. Despite the pain, he
remembers Kansas as his lifelong ``touchstone.''
</P>
<P>
   His mother died when he was 15, but not before putting her stamp
on his character. That fortitude would be tested. Soon after her
death, he was sent to live with a sister in St. Paul. He found work
playing piano in a brothel, and washing dishes in a greasy spoon
restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   After marrying, he got a better job as a waiter on the North
Coast Limited, a passenger train running between St. Paul and
Seattle. At a Seattle pawnshop, he bought his first camera _ a
$7.50 Voightlander Brilliant.
</P>
<P>
   Possessing an insistent urge to create, he got up the courage to
ask a white dress-store owner in St. Paul for the chance to shoot
fashion. The wife of boxing great Joe Louis saw his work at the
store, and invited him to photograph fashion in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   He accepted, but he was more interested in the black poverty of
Chicago's South Side. Those photos led to a fellowship and, in
1942, a call to work at the Farm Security Administration in
Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by the legendary Roy Stryker, the federal FSA had made
a name documenting rural poverty throughout the United States.
Ironically, the photos of migrant workers and sharecroppers by
Walker Evans and Dorothea Lange had also inspired Parks to pick up
the camera.
</P>
<P>
   In Stryker, Parks found a kindly mentor. ``He was a wonderful
man, a former professor of economics at Columbia University,''
Parks recalled. ``I had to load a camera for him. But he knew in
which direction to shoot. He always sent me off in the right
direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Parks was shocked to find segregation in the nation's capital.
``Stryker had given me some things to do as an assignment around
town, and I was chased from restaurants and couldn't buy a suit of
clothes'' at the Julius Garfinkel department store.
</P>
<P>
   Stryker wasn't surprised, of course. He gave Parks a lecture on
using the camera as a ``weapon,'' and advised him to study the
photographs in the FSA archives.
</P>
<P>
   Parks pored over the images, and made a point of talking to
members of the black community. ``Late one night, the only person
left in the building besides me was this chairwoman, Ella Watson,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Parks struck up a conversation, spotted a nearby American flag,
and had an inspiration. He asked Watson to pose with a mop and a
broom, and look straight at the camera. The flag hung in the
background. Parks called the photo ``American Gothic.'' This
poignant, ironic take on the famous painting by Grant Wood became
Parks' signature image.
</P>
<P>
   It's also one of his more ``staged'' images. Parks' reputation
as a documentary photographer lies in a kind of blunt honesty. He
never flinched. Although his photos are cleverly composed, they are
also marked by ``a grim directness,'' as Parks himself once put it.
</P>
<P>
   ``His photos are difficult, probing, yet oddly uplifting,'' said
the Norton's Watson. ``They are unblinking, but not depressing.''
</P>
<P>
   When Stryker saw ``American Gothic,'' he was impressed _ but
nervous. ``He said, 'Well, you got the right idea, but you're going
to get us all fired,''' Parks said with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   The FSA was under political attack from Southern senators
disturbed by depictions of poverty in their region. At the outbreak
of World War II, the agency was quickly absorbed into the Office of
War Information. Parks was assigned to shoot the training exercises
of the 332nd Fighter Group _ black pilots based near Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was difficult for them,'' he said. ``They were training to
fight to defend something that was fighting them _ fighting for a
country that really didn't appreciate what they were trying to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to the point of embarkation (for Europe) with some of
the pilots. A group of white pilots were there who didn't believe
there were black pilots in existence. Trouble was brewing. They had
to get the black pilots on ship and out of port in four days. I
said to myself, 'What the hell is this?'''
</P>
<P>
   Parks began looking for more lucrative work. He was hired by
Vogue magazine. Eventually, he found himself in the odd position of
shooting high fashion in New York and Paris, and low crime on the
streets of New York and Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fashion photography had its own set of problems,'' Parks said.
``It might have been the wrong time of the month for the models, or
they were staying out late with their boyfriends. If you forced
them into a session without talking to them first, you weren't
going to get much.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was always trying to be experimental. I let the models move,
and then I would move with them, often shooting at a very slow
speed.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, as a noted Life magazine photographer, Parks produced
photo essays on U.S. crime; bullfights in Madrid; the lives of the
rich and indolent in Portugal; boxer Muhammad Ali training in
Miami; and the controversial romance of actress Ingrid Bergman and
Italian director Roberto Rossellini.
</P>
<P>
   Two famous photo essays involved the Black Muslims, and a little
boy from Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   In 1961, Parks visited Brazil to shoot the squalid slums of Rio
de Janeiro. He found the da Silva family living in grotesque
poverty. A spunky 12-year-old named Flavio da Silva became his
``tour guide.'' After the article appeared, donations poured into
Life to bring Flavio to America to treat his severe asthma.
</P>
<P>
   Parks returned to Brazil to escort the boy to the United States,
and he remained in touch with Flavio and his family over the years.
He recently went back to Rio de Janeiro to visit them for an
upcoming HBO special.
</P>
<P>
   ``Flavio is still having his problems. He's 49 now, and he's not
working steadily. The house (bought by Life readers) is still
there, but it's a shambles. He wants to give it to his mother,
brother and family, but they don't have any appreciation of what
he's trying to do. It was a reunion with much laughter and tears.''
</P>
<P>
   Another family mired in poverty turned out even worse. In 1967,
Parks did a photo essay on the Fontenelle family of Harlem. The
wife scalded the husband during the week he spent photographing the
scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody in that family just about turned out badly,'' he
recalled, sadly. ``The girl died of AIDS. The father burned the
house down. The mother died of cancer ... it was just a disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1963, frustrated Life editors asked him to get a story on the
Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   ``Black Muslims were concerned about dealing with anybody from a
white publication,'' Parks said. ``One afternoon, I went up to
Harlem, and there was Malcolm X at a rally cursing out about 40
cops. I introduced myself, and said I would be interested in
writing about the Muslims. He said I would have to get permission
from Elijah Muhammad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I flew out to Arizona with Malcolm, and the first thing Elijah
Muhammad said to me was, 'Why are you working for those white
devils?'''
</P>
<P>
   Within 30 minutes, Parks and Malcolm X were back at the airport
without an answer about the article. ``On the plane, Malcolm said
to me, `I think he likes you.' I said, 'Well, he has a funny way of
showing it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Elijah Muhammad offered Parks $500,000 to do a film and
book on the Nation of Islam. Parks turned him down, but he got his
story anyway. ``I think he was impressed that a young black man
would turn down $500,000 on principle.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1963, Parks moved from photography to writing, publishing his
``novel from life'' called ``The Learning Tree,'' about a boy
coming of age on the Kansas prairie. That led to another occupation
when Hollywood came calling in the person of maverick actor and
director John Cassavetes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't try to sell the book,'' Parks recalled. ``John called
me in New York out of the blue, and said the book should be filmed
and I should direct it. I was skeptical, since I knew there had
been no black directors in Hollywood. He just said, 'How soon can
you get out here?'''
</P>
<P>
   Cassavetes introduced Parks to Warner Brothers executive Kenny
Hyman, even though the two moviemakers were on bad terms at the
moment. ``Hyman said off the bat, 'We're ready to make the movie
under your direction,''' Parks remembered. ```Who do you want to do
the screenplay?' I didn't know anybody. He said, `Why not you?'
</P>
<P>
   ``Then he said, `Cassavetes says you write music. Why don't you
do the score? And since you'll be the first black director, you'll
have to be the supreme boss. I suggest you produce it, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Parks first thought it was all Hollywood hoo-ha. But months
later, he was in the director's chair in his hometown of Fort
Scott, Kan. ``The Learning Tree'' was released to critical acclaim
in 1969.
</P>
<P>
   After ``The Learning Tree,'' Parks got another shot at directing
a groundbreaking film when he was asked to helm ``Shaft,'' which
Parks has described as a ``noisy film about a black, suave,
high-powered big-city detective.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a nice adventure for me,'' he said. ``The film created
a new role for young black kids to admire. Shaft was a hero. Some
think he was too flashy. In either case, I brought him to life.
It's become a cult film, still playing around the country.''
``Shaft'' is being remade by director John Singleton, with Samuel
L. Jackson in the title role.
</P>
<P>
   In 1976, Parks' film ``Leadbelly,'' about the famous blues
singer Huddie Ledbetter, received no support from new MGM head
Barry Diller, who preferred promoting the bomb ``Lipstick.''
``Leadbelly'' even opened in an L.A. porno house. Parks turned his
back on Hollywood, calling it an ``insane place.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Parks enjoys life with his children and grandchildren and
continues to construct new work _ abstract color photographs. He
calls them ``horizons of my imagination.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Like souls touching, poetry, music, paint and the camera keep
calling, and I can't bring myself to say no.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
