<P>
   These columns for release Friday, October 29, 1999 are moving
today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   ERNESTMURRAY-COLUMN _ LUFKIN, Texas _ I killed a snake in the
yard the other day. Guess that explains why the dogs were dancing
around on their hind legs and holding up their petticoats. For the
past few days, they had been urgently trying to tell me about the
snake, but I thought they just wanted to come in the house. Snakes,
as you know, are all 6 feet long until they are killed then they
tend to shrink. This one shrank to about 3 feet. (Ernest Murray is
managing editor of The Lufkin Daily News). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BORDERS-COLUMN _ NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ One of my most vivid
memories is of sitting under the stars in Big Bend National Park,
more than 20 years ago, miles away from light pollution, lying flat
on my back and staring goggle-eyed at a sky that one sees all too
rarely when living near a city. My college buddy and I got into
this weird riff about how maybe the whole cosmos was a celestial
planetarium in God's library/study, that what we were seeing wasn't
really light years away, and maybe we were all in miniature _ lots
of little Lilliputians running about with our self-importance and
sense of worth. (Gary Borders is editor and publisher of the
Nacogdoches Daily Sentinel.) EMBARGOED for Sunday. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   GARCIA-COLUMN _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Some of my favorite quotes from
the movies. (Arnold Garcia is editorial page editor of the Austin
American-Statesman). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MCNEELY-COLUMN _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Now Elizabeth Dole's campaign
for vice president can get rid of its camouflage and get into high
gear. That's almost certainly what she was running for anyway,
though it's possible she actually thought she could be elected
president. After all, her husband had. (McNeely, Austin
American-Statesman). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ A funny thing is happening on the
way to anointment. George Bush, the drive-through ATM candidate, is
driving off Republican candidates who could help get him nominated
and/or elected. Al Gore, the automatic Democrat _ some would say
automated _ has another Demo model sharing his showroom, and party
regulars are looking it over. I'm not prepared to answer this, but:
Is it possible that invincibility could be the downfall of both?
(John Young is opinion page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald).
MOVED.
</P>
