<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SF-REFORM-BALLOT (San Francisco) _ San Francisco voters will
decide Tuesday whether to lower the voluntary spending limits for
candidates running for the Board of Supervisors. And in March, they
may consider a proposal for public financing of campaigns in the
city. By RACHEL GORDON.
</P>
<P>
   YOSEMITE-MURDERS (San Francisco) _ The families of three slain
Yosemite sightseers have filed wrongful death suits against Cary
Stayner, the motel handyman accused of killing them, and against
the lodge where he worked and allegedly attacked the victims. By
KIM RYAN.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-REVIEW-HORROR (Houston) _ A University of Houston professor
explores how the ``allure of evil'' underpins fright films. One
major theme of Cynthia A. Freeland's book, ``The Naked and the
Undead'' (Westview Press, $25), is the way in which women are
portrayed in horror films. Assorted Q&AMP;As. (Photo available on NYT
database)
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-ROBBIE-WILLIAMS (Undated) _ Robbie Williams, British bad
boy who is already a superstar overseas, hopes to replicate the
success in the United States. By JOEY GUERRA.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-WHALEY (Toronto) _ Frank Whaley talks about his new movie,
``Joe the King, '' which has autobiographical elements to it. By
LOUIS PARKS.
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO-REVIEW (Undated) _ A review of films ``Arlington Road''
and ``Never Been Kissed,'' which are being released on video. By
BRUCE WESTBROOK.
</P>
<P>
   AUTHOR-PROFILE-BANK (New York) _ Melissa Bank was in her mid-20s
when she started to write short stories about a girl called Jane.
Today, she is a successful author (think movie rights and a
six-month international book tour) who just turned 39. By CELINA
OTTAWAY.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL/BUSINESS NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FED-TECH-ECONOMY (San Francisco) _ Extra! Extra! You read it
here first: The New High-Tech Economy is the real thing. That's the
conclusion reached by cautious soothsayers at the Federal Reserve,
America's central bank and a bastion of fiscal conservatism. By
EDWARD IWATA.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   RICE (Albany, N.Y.) _ For many people, converted rice is the
only rice there is. And there are plenty of reasons to recommend it
_ it's easy to cook, nutritious, fast to prepare. Yet a little
browsing through grocery stores, specialty shops and Asian markets
yields a variety of rices to make meals more interesting. By RUTH
FANTASIA.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBA-RATTO-COLUMN (New York) _ This is exactly how our parents
and grandparents remember the baseball of their youths _ with two
major leagues, the New York Yankees and all the other teams. Even
the scene inside the Yankee clubhouse after the 4-1 victory over
Atlanta that gave them their third championship in four years had
that look of the old Yankee teams that celebrated championships. By
RAY RATTO.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-49ERS (Santa Clara, Calif.) _ Forty Niners coach Steve
Mariucci essentially retired Steve Young on Wednesday. Reading
between the lines, it's clear that Young's season, and likely his
career, are over. By JOHN CRUMPACKER.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-KNAPP-COLUMN (Santa Clara, Calif.) _ Steve Mariucci
remembered a phone conversation with his quarterback from this
summer, just before 49ers training camp opened. Steve Young,
exhilarated by the thought of another season, told the coach that
he thought he could play past his 40th birthday, well past his 40th
birthday. ``He told me he wanted to play five more years,''
Mariucci said. By GWEN KNAPP
</P>
<P>
   FBN-JOE-MONTANA (San Francisco) _ Joe Montana knows exactly what
Steve Young is going through. He understands his resolve to play
football again. Montana incurred several concussions during his
15-year playing career. He said he's sympathetic with Young, who
announced Wednesday that he had no immediate plans to retire from
football despite four concussions in the past 35 months. By BRUCE
ADAMS.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS-MARKETING (San Francisco) _ Before long, Steve Young,
Troy Aikman, Drew Bledsoe and Warren Moon may become almost as
recognizable in American pop culture as Mickey Mouse, Elvis Presley
and James Dean. That's one of the possible upshots of a
multimillion-dollar deal in which the company headed by powerful
California sports agent Leigh Steinberg was acquired by Assante
Corp. of Canada, a financial planning firm that administers $22.3
billion in assets for high-profile and affluent clients. By DWIGHT
CHAPIN.
</P>
<P>
   HOK-SHARKS-FLYING (San Jose, Calif.) _ As pro athletes, flying
is simply part of the job for the San Jose Sharks and anyone else
associated with the day-to-day routine of an NHL team.
Nevertheless, when a tragedy occurs, as with golfer Payne Stewart's
fatal flight on Monday, players take notice. By ROSS McKEON.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Suddenly, the mayor's race is
interesting. Just imagine some of the far-out possibilities raised
by Tom Ammiano's write-in campaign. What if Mayor Willie Brown
decides the schools need more pencils, so next Monday he borrows
them from polling places? By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Bits and pieces that cannot go
by without comment: How bizarre is the uproar over the on-line sale
of a bunch of models' ovarian eggs? You would think we were a
deeply ethical and religious society instead of one that just talks
a good game and goes right on worshipping and sacrificing for its
one true deity: Money. By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET-CRASH (San Francisco) _ Seventy years ago this week _ on
Black Thursday, Oct. 24, 1929 _ the market took a huge nose dive.
The next day, President Herbert Hoover offered the nation his
famous diagnosis: ``The fundamental business of the country is on a
sound and prosperous basis.'' On Tuesday, Oct. 29, the big crash
came. It was the most devastating day in the history of the stock
market. By ANDRZEJ LUBOWSKI.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-NORWAY (Carmel, Calif.) _ For the first time in history,
a sitting American president will visit the land of lutefisk and
lefse. President Clinton travels to Norway on Tuesday to attend a
memorial ceremony for Yitzhak Rabin, the Israeli prime minister who
was assassinated four years ago. Here are some questions he may
encounter from the media there. By ALEX A. VARDAMIS.
</P>
