<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 12:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1114 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      10-28 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIGHT ON TO AMMIANO, THE WRITE-IN CANDIDATE FOR MAYOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Suddenly, the San Francisco mayor's race is
interesting. Just imagine some of the far-out possibilities raised
by Tom Ammiano's write-in campaign.
</P>
<P>
   What if Mayor Willie Brown decides the schools need more
pencils, so next Monday he borrows them from polling places?
</P>
<P>
   What if Ammiano wins a spot in a run-off election by getting
more votes than Clint Reilly and Frank Jordan? That's my bet, given
how dreary those two have been while Ammiano has been on the
sidelines. But what does it mean?
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it would start a whole trend of write-in campaigns,
getting rid of campaign consultants,'' said Ammiano.
</P>
<P>
   Sure. Write that in your dreams.
</P>
<P>
   Also consider the possibility of the two best stand-up comedians
in local politics debating each other for six weeks before a
run-off. What a gas, right?
</P>
<P>
   Don't count on it. Brown has been somber for months now, and
Ammiano suddenly isn't good for a single laugh line.
</P>
<P>
   His home answering machine no longer has a joke of the day.
</P>
<P>
   Ammiano's message gives write-in voters a spelling lesson:
``That's two M's, as in ``Mayor,' and one N, as in ``None of the
above.'''
</P>
<P>
   Give a guy 11 percent in the polls, and he becomes 99 percent
serious. The best he could do was tell me, ``Penmanship does not
count against you.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The other day we went out for soda, chips and salsa at Chevy's _
no Chardonnay at Stars, thank you very much _ and in an entire hour
Ammiano didn't say anything funny. After all, he faces some serious
questions.
</P>
<P>
   I asked him, if he thinks he can be mayor of San Francisco, why
he didn't have the guts to become an official candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it took a lot of guts not to do it,'' he said. ``I
don't want to be self-absorbed here, but you can't always give
people what they want.''
</P>
<P>
   Physician, spin thyself.
</P>
<P>
   So I asked why it was the right thing to pull a Rosie Ruiz and
enter the race at the last minute as a write-in.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea of a write-in campaign was suggested almost
immediately after I decided not to run,'' he said. ``I didn't give
it any credence until the buzz on the street and in the media
indicated that there's nobody to vote for.''
</P>
<P>
   As if there was anybody before.
</P>
<P>
   He said he wants to decrease voter cynicism and increase turnout
for his measure restricting banking fees on ATMs and other issues.
He said a regular campaign costs too much, both financially and
personally.
</P>
<P>
   If you're a write-in candidate, you can't lose. You can always
say you did pretty well, considering you weren't really trying.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Power to the people, right on, and write in. Right now, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   That might be Ammiano's motto. At times, though, he talked as if
losing was a foregone conclusion, calling his write-in effort an
``alternative campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   He sounded like a '60s student radical smoking the dean's
cigars, knowing he was about to be busted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I've shown there is political strength in my position
and my attitude,'' Ammiano said. ``That's a win, and whatever
happens above that is political gravy and hopefully will translate
into not only a successful district election campaign next year,
but also into a good base for the mayor's race four years later.''
</P>
<P>
   Give the guy credit for honesty and not acting like he's going
to beat Willie Brown, who would have gobs of big business's money
to attack the leftish Ammiano.
</P>
<P>
   But what if there are enough dissatisfied voters armed with No.
2 pencils to make him mayor?
</P>
<P>
   Ammiano said he'd like to see the power of the mayor's office
reduced, Muni put in the hands of an independent commission, a ban
on chain stores in the neighborhoods and the homeless given real
services and treatment instead of sporadic rousting.
</P>
<P>
   You know, all that leftist stuff many people in San Francisco,
left or right, agree on.
</P>
<P>
   He said he'd like to see equity in homeless services, with each
district bearing some burden.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are we ready, Pacific Heights?'' said Ammiano. ``We've got to
bite the bullet.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, we know who won't carry Pacific Heights.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Spend time with Ammiano, and you start to see similarities to
Willie Brown. They may have different taste in clothes and food,
and different attitudes toward those with big money, but they seem
fired by comparable angers, resentments, ideals and egos.
</P>
<P>
   Brown is the poor African American kid from a small town in
Texas who became mayor of a great city, and it makes him the better
mayor for it.
</P>
<P>
   Ammiano is the working-class gay kid from New Jersey who became
president of the Board of Supervisors, and the board is better for
his questioning of authority. This is a man driven by economic
issues like live-work lofts displacing the poor and a living wage
for city workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``People talk about family values, but if you're working three
jobs, you have no family life,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As Ammiano left Chevy's, a young waiter came up to me and said,
``Excuse me, sir, but I wanted to ask Mr. Ammiano how to write his
name in on the ballot.''
</P>
<P>
   I told him there will be instructions and pencils at polling
places. He went back to work in order to pay who knows what kind of
exorbitant rent.
</P>
<P>
   There are a lot of people in San Francisco like that waiter.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know how many, but I do know they all can write.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-99 1241EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991028.0120 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 12:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1115 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-MARKET-CRASH-HNS &LR;      10-28 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-CRASH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM BLACK THURSDAY TO SILICON VALLEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Filed in ``k'' and ``f'' categories.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANDRZEJ LUBOWSKI  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner _
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In the late 1920s, stock speculation had become
a national pastime, penetrating both the high salons and the low
saloons.
</P>
<P>
   Stock-market talk ceased to be considered un-feminine. Brokerage
houses created separate rooms where women could watch the ticker
tape without being distracted by men.
</P>
<P>
   The market was doing very well. The Standard Statistics index of
common stock prices doubled in the two years between September 1927
and September 1929.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could talk about Prohibition, or Hemingway, or air
conditioning, or music, or horses, but in the end you had to talk
about the stock market, and that was when the conversation became
serious.''
</P>
<P>
   That's how John Brooks, in ``Once in Golconda,'' recounted the
remarks of a British correspondent newly arrived in the New York of
1929. (Golconda, now in ruins, was a city in southeastern India
where, according to legend, everyone who passed through got rich.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It is perfectly well recognized by `insiders,''' the Journal
of Commerce observed late in 1928, ``that a market of the kind that
has been going on cannot last indefinitely but must undergo a
readjustment.''
</P>
<P>
   And then, readjustment.
</P>
<P>
   Seventy years ago this week _ on Black Thursday, Oct. 24, 1929 _
the market took a huge nose dive. The next day, President Herbert
Hoover offered the nation his famous diagnosis: ``The fundamental
business of the country is on a sound and prosperous basis.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Oct. 29, the big crash came. It was the most
devastating day in the history of the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   The frenzied selling went on for two weeks, until the value of
the stocks on the Wall Street Exchange had declined about 40
percent. In the three years between September 1929 and September
1932, General Electric stock dropped from $396 to $8, and RCA from
$101 to $2. The crash was followed by the worst depression in U. S.
history.
</P>
<P>
   By late 1932, one in every five persons in the labor force, or
about one of every seven adults, was out of a job. In three years,
the entire American economy ran steadily downhill at a quickening
and disastrous pace.
</P>
<P>
   We have again become a nation of stock traders. Demand is high
for predictions, advice and theories. Everyone can find something
pleasing, from the gloomy prediction of a catastrophic crash
knocking on our door to a promise of the Dow Jones index
skyrocketing to 36,000.
</P>
<P>
   Excluding technology stocks, valuations seem to stay within a
reasonable range. It is, however, the spectacular rise of
technology stocks in general, and Internet companies in particular,
combined with their unprecedented price volatility, that whetted
the appetites of many new investors and transformed housewives into
daily stock traders.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet boom has created unimaginable wealth for thousands
of investors and entrepreneurs (often paper wealth, at least for
the time being). It also infected millions of us with the
get-rich-quickly syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   Even some venture capitalists, however _ people who try to make
money by funding new companies _ and do well when these companies
fly high _ admit many of the Internet companies are probably
overvalued.
</P>
<P>
   Red Herring, a respected Internet-industry publication, reports
that to justify their current stock prices, high technology
companies which went public in the last four years would have to
see their revenues grow on average by more than 80 percent every
year for the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, they will have to do better than Microsoft and
Dell did during their first five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Internet stocks trade at prices that anticipate sales and
earnings growth unparalleled in financial history,'' says Anthony
Perkins in Red Herring. So what, one may argue, if there are no
parallels in financial history? Since the Internet itself
constitutes a revolution, a search for parallels is flawed at the
outset. Since the Internet so profoundly changes the way we
produce, consume, communicate and play, past patterns don't apply.
</P>
<P>
   Skeptics, on the other hand, maintain that the Internet does not
defy the law of physics and probability. While some Internet stars
may in fact do better than Microsoft and Dell did in their
adolescence, some are likely to fail, and others will do just OK.
</P>
<P>
   If that happens, there'll be a lot of wreckage, losses and
investor pain. Summing up the America he saw 70 years ago, British
correspondent Claude Cockburn denied that what he found reflected
excessive materialism.
</P>
<P>
   What he found was ``a brief enactment of what was essentially an
old American dream. If the attitude of Americans to the stock
market boom proved anything, it proved that they believed in
miracles that if you try hard enough you can make wonderful things
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   October has a bad reputation in the history of stock market. We
should be glad it is about to end. But let's remember what Mark
Twain said in ``Pudd'nhead Wilson'': ``October. This is one of the
peculiarly dangerous months to speculate in stocks. The others are
July, January, September, April, November, May, March, June,
December, August and February.''
</P>
<P>
   (Examiner contributor Andrzej Lubowski, formerly an economist
and journalist in Poland and a senior Fulbright Fellow at Stanford
University, is now a banker in the San Francisco Bay Area.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-99 1242EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991028.0121 </DOCNO>
