<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS' GM MEETS WITH GONZALEZ'S AGENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Rangers will make an attempt to sign Juan
Gonzalez beyond next season.
</P>
<P>
   General manager Doug Melvin met with Gonzalez's agent Jim
Bronner on Wednesday for preliminary discussions on what it would
take to sign the two-time American League MVP to a contract
extension.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin said Gonzalez's situation could depend on other
superstars who can be free agents after 2000, including Seattle's
Ken Griffey Jr. and Alex Rodriguez, Cleveland's Manny Ramirez, and
Carlos Delgado and Shawn Green of Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to find out in Juan's case where the industry is
going,'' Melvin said.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin refused to say the Rangers have to trade Gonzalez in
order to keep their payroll under control. He is also not concerned
about the possibility of Gonzalez playing out his final year with
the Rangers and having his contract situation become a distraction.
</P>
<P>
   The Seattle Mariners found that to be the case with Randy
Johnson in 1998 and ended up trading him to the Houston Astros at
the July 31 trade deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Houston Astros general manager Gerry Hunsicker said he's trying
to work out contract extensions with second baseman Craig Biggio,
outfielder Carl Everett and pitcher Mike Hampton before they become
free agents after next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like guys going into a season in the final year of
their contracts,'' Hunsicker said.
</P>
<P>
   But Melvin said: ``Every situation is different. It can be a
distraction if you make it a distraction, if you talk about it all
the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Bronner is declining to discuss Gonzalez's contract publicly.
Alex Rodriguez's agent, Scott Boras, said his client won't sign an
extension this off-season but Melvin said Bronner has not taken
that position with Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   ``He expressed that Juan would like to stay with us,'' Melvin
said. ``Mainly we talked in generalities.''
</P>
<P>
   As far as trading Gonzalez, Melvin said: ``The No. 1 goal is to
put the best team on the field and he's a part of that. I'd like to
sign him, he's a very good player.''
</P>
<P>
   The concern is Gonzalez, who will make $7.5 million next year,
could command $15 million or more per year, which would mean one
player could take up 20 percent of the overall payroll.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers also have other needs. They have nine potential free
agents, including pitcher Aaron Sele, third baseman Todd Zeile and
second baseman Mark McLemore. Melvin talked with the agents of all
three during the World Series, trying to gauge what it would take
to keep them.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin would like to sign one or two free-agent pitchers and
Sele is at the top of the list. But the Rangers are also
considering left-handers Chuck Finley, Darren Oliver and Kenny
Rogers.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin hasn't forgotten about closer John Wetteland, who is in
the final year of his four-year contract and can be a free agent
after the 2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd like to keep John here,'' Melvin said. ``He's never been
an issue. It's more of an issue with Juan.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-99 1303EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991028.0123 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 13:03 </DATE_TIME>
