<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-BREEDERS' </SLUG>
 CUP-TEX 
BREEDERS' CUP LURES RECORD 128 HOPEFULS (For use by NYTimes News
Service clients) 
By TIM PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fueled by the addition of a new race _ the $1 million Filly and
Mare Turf _ the Breeders' Cup championship received a record 128
horses during pre-entries Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   That includes 21 horses that made their most recent start in
Europe. Seventeen European horses raced in South Florida the last
time the Breeders' Cup was conducted at Gulfstream Park in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   There are eight races on the $13 million Breeders' Cup
championship card on Nov. 6. The races will be televised on NBC
(KXAS/Channel 5) from noon-4:30 p.m. The fields for the races will
be set Wednesday when final entries are taken and post positions
are drawn.
</P>
<P>
   Possibly the most anticipated race is the Juvenile Fillies,
where undefeated Chilukki has been entered against Surfside and
Darling My Darling. Chilukki is trained by Bob Baffert and Surfside
is the daughter of 1991 Juvenile Fillies champion Flanders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it'll be a great race,'' said D. Wayne Lukas, who
trains Surfside and also trained Flanders. ``It has a lot of fan
appeal and has great implications for deciding the (2-year-old
fillies) championship.''
</P>
<P>
   Other highlights from the pre-entries include:
</P>
<P>
   A field for the $4 million Classic that includes Behrens, Cat
Thief, Ecton Park, General Challenge and Lemon Drop Kid along with
the former claimers Budroyale and River Keen.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen horses from the barns of Baffert and Lukas. The two
races where Baffert does not have a horse is the Turf and the Filly
and Mare Turf.
</P>
<P>
   Daylami, considered by many to be the top horse in Europe, could
race in the Turf. Owned by Sheikh Mohammed's Godolphin Stable,
Daylami had a three-race winning streak snapped in the Arc de
Triomphe when he encountered a soggy course that didn't appear to
his liking. Others in the Turf are defending champion Buck's Boy,
1997 runner-up Borgia and Dark Moondancer, recently purchased out
of Italy by Oaklawn Park owner Charles Cella. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
