<SLUG> BC-FBC-WAC </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAWAII 5-2: NEVER A DOUBT ABOUT OL' JUNE
</HEADLINE>
 REPORT-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Back in August, when the Western Athletic Conference held its
football media day, first-year Hawaii coach June Jones ascended the
podium and delivered the perfect line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' he said, ``you're all probably wondering why I'm
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Why, not at all, June. We all thought it made perfect sense to
turn down the head coaching job with the San Diego Chargers to take
over a program that has lost, what _ 18 games in a row, the longest
losing streak in America? Or for that matter, the Philippines,
Indonesia and Rarotonga? A troupe that has not won a WAC game on
the road since somebody named Bush was president?
</P>
<P>
   Naw. Sounds like the work of a fertile mind, buddy. What's next,
circumnavigating Antarctica on a hula hoop?
</P>
<P>
   There was a contrite moment when Jones spoke eloquently of his
love for the islands, developed as a player and assistant coach,
and the desire for him and his family to return to his ``second
home'' near the end of his career. There were impolite snickers
when he unveiled his grand design _ resurrection via the
run-and-shoot.
</P>
<P>
   He bristled a bit, pointing out that it worked pretty darn well
for the Oilers, Lions, Falcons and Chargers when he installed it as
assistant or head coach.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, but that was when you had guys getting ``paid'' a whole
lot to be good at it, June. What you got out there in Time Zone X
are, shall we say, the rankest of amateurs.
</P>
<P>
   No problemo. In a whirlwind courtship, Jones brought in 50 new
players, including an army of walk-ons. He also informed 20
incumbents that, while their scholarships would be honored, their
services were no longer needed. The only guy in Hawaii who still
has his job is the governor.
</P>
<P>
   On opening day, those heartless toughs from Southern Cal arrived
and pretty much had their way with the residents of paradise. We
will demurely refrain from repeating the final score, as it was a
bit tacky.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the Rainbow Warriors _ yes, it is once again
appropriate to call them ``Warriors'' _ have played six games and
won five of them. The only defeat was at the hands of a Rice team
that might not lose again. The Rainbow Warriors have won twice on
the road _ acclimating themselves to the five-hour time difference
_ by ``staying on Hawaii time,'' a trick Jones learned from former
Hawaii coach Dick Tomey. ``Our games on the road are at about the
time we normally practice, so we just stay on schedule,'' Jones
said.
</P>
<P>
   They survive with a simple offensive plan _ a large, hostile
line protecting a strong-armed quarterback (Dan Robinson) throwing
selectively to one of 6,439 wide receivers, spread sideline to
sideline and executing the zig here, the zag there.
</P>
<P>
   They are 5-2 and if they win twice more they are guaranteed the
Oahu Bowl on ESPN. Another win or two and they could upgrade to the
Aloha, the same day on ABC. Win the WAC title _ still a possibility
_ and they could cause a bowl flip-flop with Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   June, you're a genius. We always said so.
AROUND THE LEAGUE
</P>
<P>
   Rice coach Ken Hatfield, on the firing of Tulsa coach Dave Rader
on Monday: ``I am saddened completely. If there's a better man to
do the job at Tulsa, I don't know who he is. He gave his blood,
sweat and tears to that program for years, and nobody in America
had less to work with. They'll probably have to give the next coach
twice what they gave him, and that just brings up the question of
why didn't they give it to a guy who loved Tulsa?''
</P>
<P>
   SMU coach Mike Cavan, on the blowout of a transformer that
rendered the San Jose State stadium lightless and caused the
probable cancellation of the Mustangs-Spartans game: ``I've been
doing this nearly 30 years and I've never seen anything like it.
But it's typical of the way our season has gone.''
</P>
<P>
   The game is rescheduled for early December ``in the event that
it has bearing on the championship or bowl eligibility,'' in the
league explanation; an unlikely possibility.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
