<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GETAWAY-29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Autumn is right before your eyes at 3 state parks in the Georgia
foothills
 &HT;    By Doug Hamilton
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Arrayed in a lopsided arc across North Georgia, Red Top
Mountain, Amicalola Falls and Unicoi state parks form sort of a
holy triumvirate for Atlantans who like to head for the hills in
the fall _ to do some hiking, view deer and other wildlife or just
sit back and watch the leaves change.
</P>
<P>
   The parks' lodges are ideal for people whose idea of roughing it
is no room service. For those who'd rather get closer to nature,
there are also RV and tent campsites and cottages.
</P>
<P>
   All three lodges are managed by Denver-based AmFac Parks &AMP;
Resorts, which took over in 1997 when the state decided to reduce
its number of ``nonessential'' workers by privatizing some park
operations.
</P>
<P>
   Early this year, AmFac invested $2 million to spruce up the
lodges, replacing carpet and lampshades, reupholstering furniture,
redesigning some common rooms and buying new kitchen appliances for
the restaurants. The company, which also runs lodges at Mount
Rushmore and the Grand Canyon, among other sites, promises ongoing
improvements, such as refurbishing more common areas at Unicoi
early next year.
</P>
<P>
   AmFac's makeover has resulted in a certain sameness among the
lodges. The rooms at each have nearly identical layouts, and the
restaurants all serve similar comfort-food buffets. Still, each
lodge clings to a distinct personality, and the parks themselves
offer very different experiences.
</P>
<P>
   Red Top Mountain Lodge
</P>
<P>
   Rooms: 33, including three handicapped accessible and one junior
suite.
</P>
<P>
   Rates: Standard rooms, $79 Sundays-Thursdays, $89
Fridays-Saturdays, April 1-Nov. 15; $69 Sundays-Thursdays, $79
Fridays-Saturdays, Nov. 16-March 31. Suite, $99-$109.
</P>
<P>
   Dining: The Mountain Cove Restaurant offers a full breakfast and
lunch menu daily. During the off-season, a limited dinner menu is
available Sundays-Thursdays; buffets are offered Friday and
Saturday nights.
</P>
<P>
   Extras: A pool, a video game room, gift shop, meeting facilities
and rope course program, access to the park's hiking trails, tennis
courts, marina and swimming beach.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby attractions: Etowah Indian Mounds State Historic Site,
Kennesaw Mountain National Battlefield Park, Pickett's Mill
Battlefield State Historic Site.
</P>
<P>
   Reservations: 1-800-573-9658 or www.Amfac.com.
</P>
<P>
   Overlooking one of Lake Allatoona's most picturesque coves, the
Red Top Mountain Lodge makes for a tranquil retreat ... for two-
and four-legged visitors. Numerous white-tailed deer roam the
grounds, noshing on grass in the dewy meadow behind the main
building, sipping from the trickling streams that run off the lake
and even pausing to pose for a picture or two.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, you just may see more deer than people this time of
year. The 1,428-acre Red Top Mountain park draws 1.2 million
visitors annually, but because the lake figures so heavily in
activities, attendance drops considerably as the weather cools,
particularly on weekdays. Services at the lodge are cut back _ the
restaurant offers only pizza on weeknights. Hungry guests are
steered to nearby Cartersville, with its ever-expanding sprawl of
chain eateries (Longhorn, Red Lobster, T.J. Applebee's ... .)
</P>
<P>
   But if you're looking for plenty of peace and quiet, along with
some gorgeous lakeside vistas, it's hard to beat Red Top in the
fall. There's something about strolling along Allatoona's banks and
not hearing the constant buzz of speedboats that does wonders for
those knots of tension. For another guaranteed soother, amble along
the loop trail that runs behind the lodge, down by the inlet and
around a reconstructed 1860s log cabin, which stands high and
lonesome in a thicket of pines.
</P>
<P>
   Leaf-watching here is a mixed blessing. Evergreen Georgia pines
dominate, so the park's color patterns aren't as vibrant as at
Amicalola or Unicoi. But that also means you can go in the dead of
winter and still see green, and the lower elevation means the fall
color season begins and ends later _ perfect for procrastinators.
</P>
<P>
   Amicalola Falls Lodge
</P>
<P>
   Rooms: 57, including one executive suite, three junior suites,
six loft suites, and four handicapped-accessible rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Rates: Standard rooms, $79-$89 Sundays-Thursdays; $89-$129
Fridays-Saturdays. Suites $99-$199.
</P>
<P>
   Dining: The Maple Restaurant serves breakfast, lunch and dinner
buffets daily. Beginning in mid-November, a la carte breakfast and
dinner on weekdays.
</P>
<P>
   Extras: Gift shop, meeting facilities and rope course program,
short hike to top of falls, access to other hiking trails
(including the Appalachian Trail approach) as well as playgrounds
and picnic shelters.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby attractions: Dahlonega, Appalachian Trail, Burt's Pumpkin
Farm, North Georgia Premium Outlet Mall, the Funky Chicken Art
Project (a chicken barn converted into an art gallery, featuring
the works of more than 200 painters, sculptors and fabric artists).
</P>
<P>
   Reservations: 1-800-573-9656 or www.amfac.com.
</P>
<P>
   There are three reasons to visit the lodge at Amicalola Falls:
the view, the view and the view.
</P>
<P>
   The four-story window that makes up the back wall of the lobby
draws leaf-lookers like flypaper. On any given weekend afternoon in
October and November, you may see a dozen or so pressed up against
the glass, gazing blissfully at the rumpled quilt of scarlet,
amber, pumpkin and sienna that blankets the Blue Ridge foothills.
Other visitors can be found making their way down the short trail
to the right of the lodge that leads to the top of Amicalola Falls
or standing on the waterfall's observation bridge, watching the
rushing water disappear into an endless expanse.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the fall color season promises to be quite a show _
for a while. ``It'll be short and sweet,'' says park naturalist
Jennifer Pack. She estimates that the leaves should be at their
best between this weekend and next, but that the trees should be
all but bare by mid-November.
</P>
<P>
   Wildlife watching is another popular pastime here. Signs along
the trail to the base of the falls, down the mountain from the
lodge, tell visitors to be on the lookout for pileated woodpeckers,
white-tailed deer and black bears. A trout pond at the beginning of
the trail beckons fisherfolk to drop a line in the water.
</P>
<P>
   The lodge encourages these outdoor adventures. Indoor activities
are scarce, limited to lingering over a buffet plate in the
restaurant or poking around the gift shop. And though the lobby
boasts that lovely view, it's not a place for a peaceful respite,
often filling up with guests checking in or out and with visitors
on bus tours. There is a common room with a fireplace and a lovely
stone patio on the first floor, but it may be reserved for
corporate meetings. Better to bundle yourself against the chilly
fall weather and head for one of the scenic trails or picnic areas
around the 1,021-acre park.
</P>
<P>
   Unicoi State Park Lodge
</P>
<P>
   Rooms: 100, including 30 loft rooms and four
handicapped-accessible rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Rates: $89-$119, Sundays-Thursdays; $109-$129,
Fridays-Saturdays.
</P>
<P>
   Dining: The Unicoi Restaurant serves breakfast, lunch and dinner
buffets daily.
</P>
<P>
   Extras: Gift shop, meeting facilities, access to hiking trails,
picnic areas, tennis courts, playgrounds and small lake.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby attractions: Helen, Brasstown Bald, Anna Ruby Falls,
Smithgall Woods Conservation Center.
</P>
<P>
   Reservations: 1-800-573-9656 or www.Amfac.com.
</P>
<P>
   You can almost hear the strains of ``Edelweiss'' drifting over
the Unicoi Lodge's sun-kissed courtyard. Just two miles north of
Helen, the sprawling inn offers quick access to the city's
faux-Bavarian excesses _ the knackwurst-and-sauerkraut emporiums,
the fudge ``shoppes'' and the beer-guzzling Octoberfest revelers.
</P>
<P>
   It also offers a refreshing retreat from same. Snuggled between
voluptuous lumps of Blue Ridge foothills, the lodge plays a serene
counternote to Helen's commercial cacophony.
</P>
<P>
   Comfortable common rooms abound. There's a huge den with plump
chairs and a fireplace in the main building and cozy lounges in
each of four outposts that house the guest rooms. The courtyard's
swings lure guests who want to finish that novel or just loll a bit
and breathe in the fresh air.
</P>
<P>
   At 1,023 acres, Unicoi State Park can't boast a single dominant
natural attraction like Red Top Mountain or Amicalola Falls;
instead, it offers a little bit of each. Its 53-acre Unicoi Lake
can't begin to match a 12,000-acre monster like Allatoona, but a
canoe or paddleboat ride on this placid pond can still be quite
pleasant, particularly as the surrounding trees reach their full
fall spectrum. The park is also adjacent to the two cascades at
Anna Ruby Falls. Neither is anywhere near as high as Amicalola, but
they're breathtaking nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   And though leaf-peepers won't find Amicalola's panoramic vistas
here, there are plenty of pretty views. Park ranger Ellie McConnell
estimates the fall colors will peak next week, noting that the
sourwoods and poplars have already shown their full reds and
yellows, respectively. Wildlife lovers will want to plan a trek
down one of the park's hiking trails, where they may spot black
bears, deer, possums, wildcats, beavers, otters or snapping
turtles.
</P>
<P>
   FALL HAPPENINGS
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Red Top Mountain. Friday and Saturday: Halloween hayrides
7:30-9 p.m. through park's old campground Iron Hill, with bonfire,
refreshments and storytelling. Reservations required. $3 ages 16
and over, $2 ages 4-15, 3 and under free. Nov. 25: Thanksgiving
feast, 11 a.m.-6 p.m.; reservations only. Dec. 4: Homestead
Christmas Celebration with boat parade, arts and crafts, photos
with Santa Claus, dinner at Mountain Cove restaurant and tours of
1860s log cabin. $2 parking fee. 770-975-0055.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Amicalola Falls. Thursday and Friday: Haunted Lodge on the
Hill featuring a Halloween carnival, a haunted loop trail,
hayrides, storytelling and costume contest. Dec. 2-4: Christmas
Open House with caroling, hayrides, a bonfire, storytelling and a
visit from Santa. $2 parking fee. 706-265-4703.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Unicoi. Nov. 5-6: Astronomy Weekend _ North Georgia College's
astronomy professors teach novices how to navigate the sky. Dec.
11-12: Deck the Halls _ Christmas celebration with caroling and
decorations. $2 parking fee. 706-878-3983.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Hamilton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
