<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 13:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1150 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-TRAVEL-EASTSHORE31-CO     10-28 1233
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-EASTSHORE31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Maryland's Eastern Shore: Crab cakes galore
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Oct. 31.
 &HT;    By Susan Laccetti Meyers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   OXFORD, Md. _ Having married a foodie, the allure of good
regional cuisine has become important to me in deciding where to
travel. That's why when visiting Washington recently, I suggested a
jaunt to the Eastern Shore of Maryland _ for the area's top-notch
crab cakes, of course.
</P>
<P>
   The two prominent symbols of the Eastern Shore are crabs and
ducks. Both are abundant on the eastern side of the Chesapeake Bay,
an easy drive from the nation's capital. Hand-carved wood ducks are
sold in restaurants, shops and inns in honor of the real ones that
make the bay home.
</P>
<P>
   Crabs reproduce in the deep waters of the Chesapeake in
unfathomable numbers, creating a flourishing industry for fishermen
and seafood dealers. Consuming and preparing crab is the talk of
the Eastern Shore. No visitor leaves without an opinion of where
the best soft-shell crab or crab cakes are served.
</P>
<P>
   Having my priorities straight, just after crossing the
Chesapeake Bay Bridge in Grasonville, I stopped for a taste of
local crab at the Narrows (410-827-8113), a restaurant on a marina
at Kent Narrows. The thick crab bisque with lumps of meat was the
creamiest I've ever had, served with a bottle of sherry, if
desired, to add flavor. I also had never seen this type of crab
cake common to the Eastern Shore _ a large crab meat ball, like a
huge scoop of ice cream, that is broiled instead of fried.
</P>
<P>
   The focus of tourism on the Eastern Shore is in Queen Anne's and
Talbot counties, south along Md. 50. The townships and villages are
reminiscent of New England with Colonial, Federal and Victorian
architecture, historic inns, churches and town squares, undisturbed
marshes and historic waterfront ports, particularly St. Michaels
and Oxford.
</P>
<P>
   The best way to take in the Eastern Shore and absorb its
serenity is by bicycle. The state has designated a wide lane on
roadsides (main and smaller streets) for cyclists to pedal the flat
countryside, planted with soybean and corn, between towns and
villages.
</P>
<P>
   Traveling by four wheels, I stopped in the town of Easton, one
of the largest on the Eastern Shore. Locals boast that Easton is
one of the best small arts towns in America. That's primarily
because of the Academy of the Arts (410-822-0455), which hosts
traveling exhibits featuring nationally respected artists. It's a
town with quiet neighborhoods and a few inns in Victorian homes,
but lacks the appeal of being on the water.
</P>
<P>
   I much preferred exploring St. Michaels, which dates to the
mid-1600s. Once a commercial boat-building center, the township,
population 1,301, is a collection of reasonably priced specialty
shops, flea markets, antiques stores and novelty boutiques along
Talbot Street. There is also the interesting 1879 Hooper Strait
Lighthouse, home to the Chesapeake Bay Maritime Museum
(410-745-2916).
</P>
<P>
   In the War of 1812, the town narrowly escaped bombardment by the
British. This area is also where abolitionist Frederick Douglass
was born. Douglass conducted clandestine schools for slaves in the
St. Michaels area before he escaped slavery and fled north. A
historical marker on Talbot Street notes his contribution to the
area.
</P>
<P>
   Most visitors to St. Michaels congregate at the marina and the
waterfront inns. Several inns, including the luxurious Inn at Perry
Cabin, have views of the Miles River and the town's little harbor.
The Inn at Perry Cabin is the place to stay if money is no object.
Rooms average about $500 a night on weekends at this manor, sold
earlier this year by Sir Bernard Ashley, co-founder of the Laura
Ashley Co. It is bedecked accordingly, with eclectic European and
American antiques and the exclusive company floral and check
fabrics _ from the window treatments to rugs.
</P>
<P>
   Many day-trippers and weekenders end their journey along the
Eastern Shore at St. Michaels. In doing so, they deprive themselves
of quiet little crossroads like Royal Oak or Bellevue, with
traditional country stores and historic chapels. They also miss the
15-mile bike ride or drive to the sailing hot spot of Tilghman
Island.
</P>
<P>
   To get onto Tilghman, cyclists and motorists frequently have to
wait for the short drawbridge to close, as sailboats often move in
and out of Knapps Narrow Marina, separating the mainland Eastern
Shore from the four-mile-long island. Tilghman was settled in 1608
and is home to 700 residents. This is where visitors can sign up
for a sail on a skipjack boat or a fishing charter.
</P>
<P>
   Since there is little commercialism on Tilghman, there are only
four places to eat _ but several places to spend the night. The
Black Walnut Point Inn is on the island's southern tip and is
almost entirely surrounded by the bay, dotted with sailboats and
featuring breathtaking scenery. A waterfront inn with a touch of
Southern hospitality is the Chesapeake Wood Duck Inn, owned by a
couple formerly of Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The village I hope to visit again soon is Oxford, on the Tred
Avon River where it feeds into the Chesapeake. One route there is
to drive through Royal Oak to Bellevue and catch the
Oxford-Bellevue ferry. The ferry has been running since 1683 and
takes bicyclists and automobiles for the 15-minute crossing.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1683, Oxford is one of the oldest towns in Maryland.
Its Colonial architecture and brick sidewalks leave visitors
looking for men dressed like George Washington in knickers and
white tights. It is home to the Robert Morris Inn (410-226-5111),
the place James Michener, the
</P>
<P>
   late author of historic novels such as ``Chesapeake,'' cited as
having the best crab cakes. I couldn't
</P>
<P>
   agree more.
</P>
<P>
   The crab gumbo served at the inn's dark tavern is legendary. And
the broiled Morris crab cakes, served with homemade potato salad
and local green beans, were so tender I ordered an extra one. I had
never tasted such pure, delicate crab meat.
</P>
<P>
   After a filling meal at the Robert Morris Inn, Oxford and its
handful of shops can be explored on foot or by bike. Bicycles can
be rented at the Oxford Mews Bike Boatique (410-820-8222). The
streets offer million-dollar views of the bay, a waterfront park
and homes with white-picket fences.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Getting there: To Baltimore, fly nonstop for $162.50 round
trip on Delta and USAirways. To Washington-Dulles, it's $118 round
trip for nonstops on AirTran, Delta, United and USAirways. To
Washington-National, it's $178 round trip for nonstops on Delta and
USAirways. (All of these fares require a 14-day advance purchase.)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Lodging: Wades Point Inn, $110-$230. 1-888-923-3466,
www.wadespoint.com.
</P>
<P>
   Inn at Perry Cabin, $295-$795. 1-800-722-2949,
www.perrycabin.com.
</P>
<P>
   Black Walnut Point Inn, $120-$150. 410-886-2452,
www.tilghmanisland.com/blackwalnut.
</P>
<P>
   Chesapeake Wood Duck Inn, $135-$215. 410-886-2070,
www.woodduckinn.com.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Morris Inn, $100-$240. 410-226-5111, robertmorrisinn.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Oxford-Bellevue ferry: $5 one way for automobiles; $8 round
trip; $2 one way and $3 round trip for cyclists. 410-745-9023.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: Talbot County Office of Tourism, 410-770-8000.
www.talbgov.org.
</P>
<P>
   Tilghman Island information, www.tilghmanisland.com.
</P>
<P>
   Oxford information, 410-226-5730, www.oxfordmd.com.
</P>
<P>
   St. Michaels, www.stmichaelsmd.org.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
