<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1153 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-TRAVEL-WADESPOINT31-C     10-28 0521
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-WADESPOINT31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Settle into the past at quiet B&AMP;B on Chesapeake
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Oct. 31
 &HT;    By Susan Laccetti Meyers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. MICHAELS, Md. _ As I'm lying in bed with the windows open,
dawn breaks and an orange sky illuminates the Chesapeake Bay.
Seventeen swans float by the barrier rocks that separate the grassy
property from the water _ just 30 yards from my window. Three
stragglers swim by a minute or two later, then two more of these
graceful beauties.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly, I see a handful of sailboats cruising by. Despite the
lack of wind, they're heading for a day of sailing on the navy
waters of the mighty Chesapeake.
</P>
<P>
   The view from this room at the Wades Point Inn is no different
from 100 years ago, when Wades Point became a popular summer resort
for Maryland-area elite. Today it is a relaxing, affordable
bed-and-breakfast inn, a 90-minute drive from the Washing-
</P>
<P>
   ton-Baltimore-Annapolis corridor.
</P>
<P>
   Wades Point is also a great home base to explore the Eastern
Shore of Maryland, an area rich in Colonial history and boasting
some of the best seafood (especially crab cakes), sailing and
cycling on this part of the East Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Thankfully, urban sprawl has not consumed the fabled Eastern
Shore. The Chesapeake serves as a natural barrier, and despite the
Chesapeake Bay Bridge, the Eastern Shore and Wades Point have
remained somewhat isolated.
</P>
<P>
   Wades Point Inn is on the outskirts of the vintage port town of
St. Michaels. The 120-acre estate was dedicated by the king of
England as a land grant to Zachary Wade, an early British explorer
of Maryland, in 1657. The house was not built until 1819, when the
farm and natural area along the bay were purchased by Baltimore
shipbuilder Thomas Kemp of clipper ship fame.
</P>
<P>
   Additions made to the house in 1890 include the rustic summer
wing where I lodged. For almost a century, Wades Point served as a
summer resort and guest house. The present owners turned it into an
inn in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Wades Point is pleasing not only because of its views _ all 23
rooms face the bay _ but because of its isolation down a country
lane. Hosts Betsy and John Feiler, who don't go out of their way to
chat it up with the guests, offer visitors a map of the waterfront
farm. You can take a walk on the nature trail and see the old
family cemetery, crops (organic soybeans, corn, tomatoes) and farm
animals, including chickens and goats.
</P>
<P>
   Wildlife you may spot include deer, rabbits, raccoons,
terrapins, eagles, herons, egrets, geese and ospreys. A red fox
startled me as I hiked the one-mile nature trail one morning,
crossing 10 yards ahead.
</P>
<P>
   After exploring the two-story home _ with its many balconies,
aging porches, Colonial art and antiques _ guests are always drawn
to the water. Here, you can settle into an Adirondack chair and
pass the day soaking in the changing scenery on the bay. Or you can
fish or crab off the inn's pier.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Laccetti Meyers writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
