<HEADER>
A1158 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e BC-IVOR-BOB-HOSKINS-IN-F     10-28 1318
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IVOR-BOB-HOSKINS-IN-FELICIAS-JOURNEY-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOB HOSKINS: BRING ON THE BAD GUYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's Hollywood Stars
entertainment column) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly entertainment column with color and black-and-white art.)
 Includes black-and-white photos and color slides of Bob Hoskins
with Elaine Cassidy in a scene from ``Felicia's Journey.'' 
 By IVOR DAVIS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Not much scares British actor Bob Hoskins.
 &HT;    Actually, he's usually the one who does the scaring _ with a
series of almost impossibly diverse roles, he's become a maestro of
menace on the big screen, though he's also proven that he can be
sweet and tender if the role calls for it.
 &HT;    But even maestros of menace have their fears, and Hoskins admits
that he was plenty scared when he met Atom Egoyan, the Cairo-born,
Canadian-based director of Hoskins' newest film, ``Felicia's
Journey.''
 &HT;    Egoyan, the independent filmmaker who won rave reviews for his
dark drama ``The Sweet Hereafter'' (1998), wanted Hoskins to play a
serial killer who preys on young prostitutes.
 &HT;    ``Atom knew I expected to meet this intense Armenian, which is
the perceived reputation he has through his films,'' Hoskins
recalls during an interview at the recent Toronto Film Festival.
``So, the moment we were introduced, he came on like Bela Lugosi.
He was babbling on about how he wanted me to find the soul of the
character, all the time riveting his eyes on me. He frightened the
life out of me.
 &HT;    ``Then he started to laugh. He was sending me up, and he could
see it had worked,'' Hoskins says with a laugh. ``At that moment I
knew I had to work with him.''
 &HT;    Hoskins may not have known what to expect from Egoyan, but he
was under no illusions about ``Felicia's Journey,'' a dark
psychological thriller about a lonely, middle-aged bachelor named
Hilditch (Hoskins), who conceals his inner torment as he befriends
a young girl (Elaine Cassidy) who has come to an industrial area of
England to track down the father of her baby.
 &HT;    ``I'd read the novel when it first came out. `Felicia's Journey'
is every parent's worst nightmare, especially if you have daughters
_ and I have two,'' says Hoskins, who has been married to
schoolteacher Linda Banwell since 1982.
 &HT;    The scariest aspect of the story, Hoskins says, is that
``monsters like Hilditch exist all over the place. England has more
than its fair share. I've met men like him _ they're nice, boring
people who seem so noble, kind and caring. You just know there are
some dark recesses in their lives.''
 &HT;    Exploring those dark recesses was tricky business, the actor
adds. It would have been easy to have gone over the edge into
slasher-movie excess, or to have been so realistic as to be boring.
 &HT;    ``It was a bit like building a house of matches without any
glue,'' he says. ``It's so delicate that, at any moment, everything
could fall apart.''
 &HT;    It was Egoyan who ultimately supplied that glue, Hoskins adds.
 &HT;    ``He didn't treat the material simply as a thriller, which is
what most directors would have done,'' the actor says. ``Instead,
Atom wanted to show that both Hilditch and Felicia are victims _
she is a victim of his kindness, he is a victim of her innocence.
He's an emotional cripple, very, very damaged, and Atom and I
discussed his different mental states.''
 &HT;    Always a versatile actor, Hoskins continues to tackle a wide
variety of roles, with ``Felicia's Journey'' _ which will open Nov.
12 _ representing possibly his best chance of picking up a second
Oscar nomination to match his nod for ``Mona Lisa'' (1986). He's
one of the busiest international actors around, but he remains
devoutly devoid of prima-donna attitude.
 &HT;    ``There is always a huge separation between my work and my
life,'' he says.
 &HT;    Actually, Hoskins says, he's an accidental actor. One evening in
London, back in the 1960s, he tagged along when a pal went to a pub
to try out for a local theatrical group. The director suggested
that Hoskins also audition. He got the part, and has never looked
back.
 &HT;    ``The moment I stepped on the stage for the first performance, I
knew I was supposed to be an actor,'' he says. ``That stage was the
most peaceful place on Earth.''
 &HT;    The barrel-chested Cockney credits his pal Michael Caine with
breaking down class barriers for actors in Britain, thereby making
Hoskins' own ascent possible.
 &HT;    ``He opened doors for people like me who dropped their Hs and
didn't speak in Shakespearean, stentorian tones,'' he says. ``There
was a time when, as soon as you opened your mouth, they'd lock up
the silver and send the women upstairs.''
 &HT;    Hoskins has moved well beyond playing Cockneys, however. He
played a Napoleonic London mobster in ``The Long Good Friday''
(1979) and a tough-guy private detective in ``Who Framed Roger
Rabbit?'' (l988). He was a genial Smee in Steven Spielberg's
``Hook'' (1991) and a gay J. Edgar Hoover in Oliver Stone's
``Nixon'' (1995). He's played both Mussolini and Churchill, and
essays another former world leader in Showtime's ``Noriega: God's
Favorite,'' which will air next year.
 &HT;    Playing Panamanian dictator Manuel Noriega was a stretch for
Hoskins, especially in Roger Spottiswoode's intricate film, which
is told in flashbacks after Noriega, surrounded by American troops
and tanks, has taken refuge in the Vatican Embassy in Panama City.
 &HT;    The style is darkly comic, which is pretty much the way Hoskins
recalls his first dinner with Spottiswoode.
 &HT;    ``He told me, `Listen, Bob, this was the ugliest man in South
America,''' the actor recalls. ```He was a total megalomaniac, an
appalling man, and you are the only actor in the world that can
play it.'
 &HT;    ``I didn't know whether to be flattered or to hit him.''
 &HT;    But after reading the script, Hoskins says, he realized that
Noriega was ``absolutely insane.''
 &HT;    ``Insanity has always attracted me,'' the actor says cheerfully.
``He was quite a ridiculous figure. He was funny _ I mean, whether
the audience like him more because he's funny, it's up to them. I
just played what was there.
 &HT;    ``But what interested me about this character was that he was
capable of every kind of extreme,'' he adds, ``extreme cruelty and
extreme violence and extreme tenderness at the same time. And it
was great to play all those elements.
 &HT;    ``I love playing bad guys,'' he concludes with a smile. ``Good
guys are boring.''
 &HT;    Well, maybe not all good guys. Surely Hoskins would offer an
exemption to the character he only recently finished playing, in a
film recently shot in Spain for Turner Network Television and due
to air early next year. It's a part Hoskins seems born to take on:
the loyal-if-befuddled Sancho Panza to John Lithgow's ``Don
Quixote.''
 c.1999 Ivor Davis  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ivor Davis is a Hollywood-based reporter and columnist.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Felicia's Journey,'' consult
the official Website at www.feliciasjourney.com. And don't forget
to visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on Hollywood Stars
and other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly entertainment column with color and black-and-white art.)
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
