<DOCNO> NYT19991028.0148 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 13:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1171 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-NEWSPAPER-NOVEL-chap9     10-28 1539
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSPAPER-NOVEL-chap9-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIN'T DONE YET: WASHED IN BLOOD, HEALED BY FIRE  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (ATTENTION EDITORS: Hearkening back to the era of Dickens and
other serial novelists, The New York Times Syndicate is offering
for purchase ``Ain't Done Yet: A Newspaper Novel About the
So-Called End of the World '' _ 29 suspenseful installments, by ROY
PETER CLARK, the Poynter Institute senior scholar and well-known
writing coach. The novel, set in St. Petersburg-Tampa, chronicles a
burnt-out investigative reporter on the trail of a cult, ``The
Watchers,'' and its charismatic leader. The novel was commissioned
as a millennium project by The New York Times Regional Newspaper
Group. Chapter nine is below. The series is a wonderful way to
celebrate the millennium with your readers. For purchase
information, contact one of these New York Times Syndicate sales
representatives:
 &HT;    (_ U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at 732-390-4480;
fax, 732-390-4697.
 &HT;    (_ Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 33-1-47-42-17-11;
fax, 33-1-47-42-80-44 or 33-1-47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942.
 &HT;    (_ Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (PLEASE NOTE: All 29 chapters have been sent to the ``l''
lifestyle category code.)
 &HT;    
 By ROY PETER CLARK 
 (Worldwide rights) 
 c.1999 Roy Peter Clark  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Max watched in fascination as the young woman, Angela Powers,
stepped elegantly down a ladder off the side of the boat and into
the water of the Gulf, which came up almost to her chin. She
executed an athletic surface dive and took three strong strokes,
stood, the water was now waist high, and walked unself-consciously
naked toward the shore.
</P>
<P>
   She looked maybe 21 years old, thought Max, about 5-foot-7, with
chestnut hair, wet and pulled back now, and skin that emitted a
healthy translucent glow even in the moonlight.
</P>
<P>
   Max imagined the most beautiful model and the best woman athlete
merged into a single body. No gaunt, skeletal clothes hanger here,
but a woman who looked both voluptuous and chiseled _ how was that
possible? _ and as comfortable with her own body as a person could
be. Her eyes glowed blue, very blue.
</P>
<P>
   All the Watchers on shore stepped forward to greet her, and one
wrapped her in a dark red robe, the same color worn by Raoul
Glaber, who watched with a toothy smile from the boat. He began:
</P>
<P>
   ``Angela, our special angel, is now sheathed in red. It is the
color of blood, flame, Pentecost, the rising sun, the new
millennium, and, of course, the Florida State University football
team.'' The crowd burst into laughter at this unexpected bit of
humor.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see before you the bridge. A bridge to the sky. But also a
bridge of death, the place where too many have ascended and then
thrown their lives into the deep. It is a symbol of our times, of
our century.'' His voice was soft and steady, amplified perfectly
by an invisible sound system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ours is the century that created the automobile and the
airplane and the television and the computer. Alan Shepard landed
there,'' he pointed to the moon, ``and hit a golf ball into space
right there. We created penicillin and cures for thousands of
diseases. People have hope of living longer and happier lives. So
maybe we should call our time the Age of Hope and Creativity.''
</P>
<P>
   He paused, not to think of something to say, but as if preparing
to lift some great weight.
</P>
<P>
   ``But what have we done with the powers that have been given us?
We have become the masters of disasters. In 1915 the Ottoman Turks
killed a million Armenians. By 1933, Josef Stalin had caused the
death of more than 11 million of his countrymen, through systems of
starvation and torture. In three years, Pol Pot murdered more than
2 million, one out of every four Cambodians. If you committed the
crime of having a high school education, you could have been one of
his victims. In Uganda, thousands of victims of Idi Amin could be
found, their bodies mutilated, floating down rivers. In this very
decade hundreds of thousands of Rwandans have been hacked to death.
</P>
<P>
   ``And what can we say of Hitler and the crimes of the Third
Reich? Just 22 Nazis were tried at Nuremberg for grotesque crimes
against humanity, crimes that separated, deported, tortured,
starved, gathered into concentration camps, gassed, and incinerated
6 million Jews and 5 million others. How do we begin to understand
this without declaring ours the Age of Hatred and Genocide?
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up believing in the God of Christians and Jews, but no
more. How does a just and merciful God rest amid the glories of
heaven, angelic music ringing in his ears, in the face of such
atrocities? Would a loving father permit such pain to be visited on
his children? How can this race of people think of itself as saved
or redeemed?
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not worthy. And we cannot be worthy until this age
passes away, as a man walks across a bridge and leaves one side
behind and heads off for another. Our time must come to an end, and
a new age begin. An age of blackness must be purified, washed in
blood, healed by fire, before we can achieve an age of purity,
peace, and harmony.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are false prophets who have come before me with similar
messages. But salvation cannot be found in the poisoned potions of
Jonestown. Heaven is not behind the Halle-Bopp comet. It is not on
a faraway planet. You will not be whisked away there by friendly
aliens patting you on the back. And salvation is not in the
violence of Waco, or Oklahoma City, or Ruby Ridge. If I lead you
down those paths, walk away from me.
</P>
<P>
   ``About 2,000 years ago, a Jewish child was born in a tiny
village and given the name Joshua, although we know that man as
Jesus. His followers believe he died and rose from the dead and
ascended into heaven, but that he would return. One of them _ his
beloved friend John _ had a vision and wrote down what he saw in
what we now call the Book of the Apocalypse:
</P>
<P>
   ``And I saw an angel come down from heaven, and he laid hold on
Satan, and bound him a thousand years, and cast him into the
bottomless pit, and shut him up, and set a seal upon him. And I saw
the souls of them that were beheaded for the witness of Jesus, and
they lived and reigned with Christ a thousand years. And when the
thousand years expired, Satan shall be loosed out of his prison,
and shall go out to deceive the nations which are in the four
quarters of the earth, Gog and Magog, to gather them together to
battle. And fire came down from God out of heaven and devoured
them. And the devil that deceived them was cast into the lake of
fire and brimstone. And I saw the dead, small and great, stand
before God; and the books were opened. And whosoever was not found
written in the book of life was cast into the lake of fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Children, look, I have inscribed your names into my book of
life.'' He held up what looked like a laptop computer. ``I accept
you as my own. I embrace you as a father. I gather you up and
shield you. I sit and watch with you for the time that is coming. I
heal you from the wounds placed upon you by your parents. Wounds of
abuse. Wounds of neglect. Wounds of addiction and dependency.
Wounds of crass materialism. They left you alone. They let you be
raised by strangers. While you were crying with grief or
loneliness, they dropped you off at the mall. They stood by while
you scarred your own bodies, or stuffed them to obesity, or starved
them to oblivion. They aborted you before you were born. And then
they went out and bought themselves a nice dinner, some dessert, a
carafe of wine. They created the Age that Hated Children.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I love you, and I'LL LOVE YOU FOR A THOUSAND YEARS.''
</P>
<P>
   This was the first time that Raoul Glaber raised his voice, and
the crowd echoed back its cheers. Max looked and saw people holding
each other, tears streaming down faces.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come,'' he said, ``and follow me.''
</P>
<P>
   He stepped down into the cabin of the boat and disappeared from
sight. In the next few minutes, his original 11 disciples, with
Angela Powers, waded out to the boat, climbed aboard, and prepared
to embark. The engines roared to life, the boat turned back toward
the bridge and sped off toward the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   Back on shore, the new initiates greeted and hugged each other,
and were approached and congratulated by friends in the crowd, like
Jewish kids after their bar mitzvahs. Then they marched across the
park, stepped into three white vans _ with Conquistador Hotel on
the side _ and drove away.
</P>
<P>
   Max and Sherry walked slowly, heads bowed, not touching now,
back toward her Harley, their every stepped being watched my a man
sitting on the branch of a nearby oak tree.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   NEXT INSTALLMENT: THE RAINBOW MADONNA
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Roy Peter Clark is a senior scholar and an associate at the
Poynter Institute for Media Studies. He was commissioned to do this
newspaper novel as part of the New York Times Regional Newspaper
Group's Celebrate 2000 project.) &LR;  &QL;
