<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   LAST INSTALLMENT: Max meets up with Daisy, the dog that survived
a fall from the Skyway Bridge, and then is summoned to a meeting
with Sam Lockhart, chief of police.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   ``You want me to do what?'' Max Timlin squinted his eyes and
scratched what was left of his hair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want you to screw your courage to the sticking post,'' Sam
Lockhart, police chief, reciting this line in a mock Shakespearean
accent as if rehearsing for a Mel Brooks production of Othello,
``and I want you to go in amongst the Watchers and interview Raoul
Glaber, their king.'' He bowed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why don't you just send your best detectives in there? Or why
not just bring him in?''
</P>
<P>
   ``We think he's much too dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   Max looked at him, his eyes now wide in disbelief. ``He's too
dangerous for the cops, so you want me to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sam relaxed his demeanor and pointed to the chair across from
him. He called to someone in the kitchen and began ordering Cajun
food, large steaming bowls of it: red beans and rice, andouille
sausage, shrimp jambalaya, crawfish etouffe, blackened grouper, all
washed down with sweet iced tea.
</P>
<P>
   The talking and the eating took almost two hours. Some of Max's
favorite music played in the background: Fats Domino, Professor
Longhair, Dr. John, the Neville Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Listen to the sweet voice of Aaron Neville, Max, you've just
got to `Tell it like it is....' You're a macho newspaper man,''
said Sam, pushing back from the table. ``You'll get a big story out
of this.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't cut deals with cops,'' said Max, eating a bite of
bread pudding soaked in rum. ``And I don't do their work for
them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And I don't like reporters,'' said Sam, ``but we've got
something important here, and I'm willing to dispense with some of
the old rules.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Like what?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a huge file on our ongoing investigation of The
Watchers. It goes back more than a year. And I'll open it just for
you. It's got loads of stuff in there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And what do I have to do in return?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Just be yourself. Go in and ask for an interview. Get as close
as you can, which will not be easy. Light a little fire under him
and see if he jumps. Just be your old, stank reporter self. And
then just answer a few of our questions about what you saw.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You get no access to my notes. I tell you whatever I want to
tell you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Fine.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And I get to see the file anytime I want to from now until the
Second Coming.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You're a good man, Max Timlin, and deserve a fine cup of
chicory coffee.''
</P>
<P>
   Max debated the big cop's proposal with himself for two days
before meeting up with his editor.
</P>
<P>
   Kate Banks showed up at the condo on Saturday evening, just in
time to enjoy a bright-orange sunset, which she and Max watched
from the balcony while sipping Heineken from bottles and nibbling
on slices of Sicilian pizza. They fought over the crust.
</P>
<P>
   ``I bought you a present,'' said Kate, reaching into her purse.
``Call it a bonus for your good work so far.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a video copy of ``Goldfinger,'' which Max had told her
was one of his favorite movies. He peeled off the plastic wrapper,
popped it into the VCR, and curled up on the couch to watch it.
About 90 minutes and two beers later, by the time James Bond is
rolling in the hay with Pussy Galore, Kate had kicked off her
sandals, pulled up her knees, and rested her head against Max's
shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is the coolest thing,'' Max clapped his hands in delight
as Bond defeated Odd Job, and the counter on the nuclear device
stopped at exactly 007. ``Fort Knox and the economies of the Free
World _ saved!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Goldfinger was not your average terrorist,'' said Kate. ``I
wonder what Bond would do if he encountered Raoul Glaber?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably go right into the lion's den.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the same phrase that Sam Lockhart had used, and it gave
Max a moment's pause. He had told her over the phone the details of
the plan, and she now approved, ``As long as you report to me first
_ before you talk with the cops.''
</P>
<P>
   She opened a folder filled with photos, the ones Sherry Darling
had shot at the initiation ceremony. They were splendid. The
cigarette boat in the moonlight, with the Skyway Bridge as a frame.
The initiates lined up on the beach. Raoul Glaber waving from the
boat. And Angela Powers, like a postmodern Venus, rising from the
water.
</P>
<P>
   ``I assume you'll want to keep this one for your private
collection,'' said Kate.
</P>
<P>
   Max raised his hand in honest protest.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is the most beautiful girl I've ever seen, but she's
young enough to be my daughter. Father Ralph thinks I've been put
on this earth to save her.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you,'' said Kate, and looked into his eyes earnestly.
``Thank you, Max. You're one of the good guys.'' And with that she
kissed him, first lightly on the cheek, and then lightly on the
lips. And again. He kissed her back, very softly, like a beginner,
then more firmly, and then, as if a door had finally opened, with
passion.
</P>
<P>
   He took in the warmth of her breath, the smell of her hair, and
the wonderful feel of a strong woman's body pressed against his.
They kissed nonstop for what might have been 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The phone rang. It was on the near table, and it startled them
both, so that they separated, looked at each other and laughed.
Kate picked it up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, hello, Father Ralph. Yes, this is Kate Banks. Yes, Max is
here. We were just watching a movie.'' Kate winked at Max, who took
the phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Max, tell me again, the name of this Watcher guy.''
</P>
<P>
   The priest's voice was loud and excited.
</P>
<P>
   ``Raoul. Raoul Glaber.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Spell it for me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``R-a-o-u-l G-l-a-b-e-r.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I've got two pieces of news for you, buddy boy. First,
that's not his real name.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What's the second piece?''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in more trouble than we thought.''
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   NEXT INSTALLMENT: A BLAST FROM THE PAST
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
