<HEADER>
A1177 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-NEWSPAPER-NOVEL-chap1     10-28 1190
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSPAPER-NOVEL-chap15-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIN'T DONE YET: AN ECLIPSE OF THE SUN  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (ATTENTION EDITORS: Hearkening back to the era of Dickens and
other serial novelists, The New York Times Syndicate is offering
for purchase ``Ain't Done Yet: A Newspaper Novel About the
So-Called End of the World '' _ 29 suspenseful installments, by ROY
PETER CLARK, the Poynter Institute senior scholar and well-known
writing coach. The novel, set in St. Petersburg-Tampa, chronicles a
burnt-out investigative reporter on the trail of a cult, ``The
Watchers,'' and its charismatic leader. The novel was commissioned
as a millennium project by The New York Times Regional Newspaper
Group. Chapter 15 is below. The series is a wonderful way to
celebrate the millennium with your readers. For purchase
information, contact one of these New York Times Syndicate sales
representatives:
 &HT;    (_ U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at 732-390-4480;
fax, 732-390-4697.
 &HT;    (_ Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 33-1-47-42-17-11;
fax, 33-1-47-42-80-44 or 33-1-47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942.
 &HT;    (_ Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (PLEASE NOTE: All 29 chapters have been sent to the ``l''
lifestyle category code.)
 &HT;    
 By ROY PETER CLARK 
 (Worldwide rights) 
 c.1999 Roy Peter Clark  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   THE STORY SO FAR: Reporter Max Timlin is hired by editor Kate
Banks to investigate a doomsday cult called The Watchers and their
leader, Raoul Glaber. Max witnesses a Watcher initiation rite and
hears Glaber's dark view of the world and its future. Max seeks the
counsel of Father Ralph who becomes suspicious that Glaber is not
who he says he is. Police Chief Sam Lockhart persuades Max to enter
The Watcher's inner sanctum.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   Max's adrenaline had kicked in now, and his heart raced as he
was escorted through a glass automatic door, down a narrow hallway
and through two heavy wooden doors. A burly, grimacing attendant
pointed him through.
</P>
<P>
   Max looked up to see Raoul Glaber wearing a red University of
Alabama T-shirt, sitting at the far side of a round table and
holding Max's index card in one hand and flipping it with the
middle finger of his other.
</P>
<P>
   I KNOW YOUR NAME IS NOT RAOUL GLABER!
</P>
<P>
   SURRENDER DOROTHY.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very amusing, Mr. Timlin. That's an interesting name, Max
Timlin. Just add a few letters and you could become Maximum
Timeline.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You seem fascinated with names, Mr. Glaber, and with time. Or
shall I call you by your real name?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you know my real name?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, no. But I do know that Raoul Glaber was a
10th-century French monk who saw Satan standing by his pillow.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't be so harsh on visionaries, sir. I believe in Satan _
how can you look at the world and not _ but I don't see him as an
ugly little gremlin. I think that he takes a much more reassuring
human form, like yours, for instance, ... or mine.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What is your real name?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Please call me William, if you like, William Miller. How's
that for a classic American name. Don't you love those double l's
in the middle? Almost like the Latin word for one thousand: mille.
I love beautiful and interesting names. But I've told you that.''
</P>
<P>
   He reached for a button near his chair. Max flinched.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, not to worry, sir, there is no shark pool under your
feet.'' A side door opened. Max was not prepared for the sight of
Angela Powers (though he had her in mind when he wrote ```Surrender
Dorothy'').
</P>
<P>
   She, too, was dressed in red: tank top, soccer shorts, and
thongs. She padded gracefully into the room, holding a tray with
glasses of cold iced tea and some ginger snaps.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Timlin. This is Angela Powers, but I assume you already
know that. Isn't that a wondrous name _ the power of angels _ she
is my helper and my archangel.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pleasure to meet you _ please, help yourself,'' said
Angela to Max. ``Aren't you broiling in that black suit? You look
like one of the Blues Brothers.''
</P>
<P>
   Glaber or Miller or Whoever came around the big table and took a
seat with Max and Angela near a window overlooking the water.
</P>
<P>
   Glaber took some hard swallows of tea. ``I like it Southern
style,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you not from the South?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' some impatience passed through the charm. ``I'm from the
West. And I don't talk to the press.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And why not? Some publicity might gain you more followers.
Isn't it natural that, given your message, people would turn their
interest toward you as we approach the millennium?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, come now, Mr. Timlin,'' the voice came from Angela Powers.
It was deep for a young woman, and filled with character and
intelligence. ``The interest of the press is not in informing or
enlightening, no matter what you say. It is to appeal to the
largest and the lowest audience. Is any other institution more
responsible for the decline in standards, for cynicism about the
country, for spreading hopelessness, for fear of crime, for a
picture of the world that debases anything noble?''
</P>
<P>
   ``But, Ms. Powers, don't The Watchers espouse a philosophy that
is the ultimate pessimism, that the world as we know it will
disappear?''
</P>
<P>
   ``God is no magician, Mr. Timlin. He's not into vanishing acts.
We see the world as it is. You see it as better than it is _ and
then portray it as worse than it is.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You fascinate me, Ms. Powers.'' Max was sweating profusely.
Why had he worn this darn black suit? And why did he choose a chair
in the direct sunlight? He finished his tea, and held the frosty
glass to his forehead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you a good writer, Mr. Timlin?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Not if you listen to my old editors. But I am fast. I think
for reporters fast is better than good. Are you a writer, Ms.
Powers? You are very well spoken.''
</P>
<P>
   Glaber smiled at the compliment to Angela like a proud parent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought about becoming a writer, but I saw what it did to my
mother.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Your mother's a writer?''
</P>
<P>
   ``She was. But she's an editor now. Mr. Timlin, are you all
right? You look a little pale. Can I get you some more tea?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Your ... mother?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, perhaps you know her. Her name is Kate Banks.''
</P>
<P>
   It must have been this revelation that unsettled him because the
image of her, the beautiful image, suddenly went out of focus.
There were two magnificent angels in red _ no there were three, and
then someone must have turned the lights out, or closed the blinds,
because wasn't it just daylight _ a moment ago _ or maybe an
eclipse of the sun _ or maybe this room was a revolving bar at
night _ spinning, darker and ... darker.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   NEXT INSTALLMENT: SIGN OF THE WATCHERS
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Roy Peter Clark is a senior scholar and an associate at the
Poynter Institute for Media Studies. He was commissioned to do this
newspaper novel as part of the New York Times Regional Newspaper
Group's Celebrate 2000 project.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
