<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991028.0156 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 13:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1179 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-NEWSPAPER-NOVEL-chap1     10-28 1212
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSPAPER-NOVEL-chap17-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIN'T DONE YET: THE BITTER END  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (ATTENTION EDITORS: Hearkening back to the era of Dickens and
other serial novelists, The New York Times Syndicate is offering
for purchase ``Ain't Done Yet: A Newspaper Novel About the
So-Called End of the World '' _ 29 suspenseful installments, by ROY
PETER CLARK, the Poynter Institute senior scholar and well-known
writing coach. The novel, set in St. Petersburg-Tampa, chronicles a
burnt-out investigative reporter on the trail of a cult, ``The
Watchers,'' and its charismatic leader. The novel was commissioned
as a millennium project by The New York Times Regional Newspaper
Group. Chapter 17 is below. The series is a wonderful way to
celebrate the millennium with your readers. For purchase
information, contact one of these New York Times Syndicate sales
representatives:
 &HT;    (_ U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at 732-390-4480;
fax, 732-390-4697.
 &HT;    (_ Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 33-1-47-42-17-11;
fax, 33-1-47-42-80-44 or 33-1-47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942.
 &HT;    (_ Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (PLEASE NOTE: All 29 chapters have been sent to the ``l''
lifestyle category code.)
 &HT;    
 By ROY PETER CLARK 
 (Worldwide rights) 
 c.1999 Roy Peter Clark  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   LAST INSTALLMENT: Max regains consciousness and makes his way
home, struggling with the idea that Angela Powers is really the
daughter of Kate Banks.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   Sam Lockhart, police chief, had seen a lot in his day, but
nothing quite like this. A man stood in front of his desk, his
pants around his ankles.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my reward for doing your dirty work,'' said Max
Timlin. ``The letter `W' tattooed on my rear end.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be laughing if it weren't for this.'' Sam slid an
investigative file across his desk. It contained autopsy photos,
and they were gruesome _ a young man and woman so broken apart they
look like they had imploded.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what happens after you've jumped off the Skyway
Bridge, and flown like a birdie 200 feet or so, and hit the water,
which is like concrete from that height. They were probably in the
water for a couple of days before they washed up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you know about them?''
</P>
<P>
   ``White male and female. Probably a suicide pact. Drugs in the
system. Speed _ the kind of stuff that makes you aggressive and
paranoid. And check out this little detail.''
</P>
<P>
   The chief slid another photo across the desk. A close up showed
that each victim had the letter ``W'' tattooed above an ankle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm starting to hate the look of that tattoo, so what say,
when this is over, the department springs to laser your sorry ass
and remove that nasty thing and all that it stands for.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you think it stands for, Sam?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe nothin' but a bunch of folks who like to dress up in
white for a New Year's Eve party. But my responsibility is to be
suspicious and stay that way. I don't know what Glaber is watchin'
for _ but I'm watchin' him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What is he capable of? That's what I can't figure.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll just assume he could blow up a federal building, or burn
down his hotel with everyone in it, or hold a big party at the Dome
and make everyone drink poisoned lemonade, or that he might blow up
a 747, or car-bomb an embassy in Africa. Now that the Commies are
all gone, these nuts are turning their anger against their own
countries _ even their own people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember how I thought the Oklahoma City bombing was caused
by terrorists from the Middle East.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And, surprise, it turned to be some pasty lookin' white boy
with a grudge against his own country.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But how vulnerable are we here? We're just a quiet little city
in West Florida. The land of snowbirds and retirees and tourists.
The city of the newly wed and nearly dead.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got no imagination, Max. You want doomsday scenarios.
They could poison the water supply. Or hijack nerve gas or
biological weapons. They could sabotage our Air Force base _ which
would appeal to fellow terrorists around the globe since we have a
special strike force stationed in Tampa. On any given day, how many
people are in one of our amusement parks? What's the Big Mouse
gonna do, let Goofy carry an Uzi?''
</P>
<P>
   ``When I write this story _ if I write it _ I'm gonna put all
that stuff in it _ make you sound a lot smarter than you are.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you mean if you write it?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well I may not have a job after I tell my boss what I think of
her.''
</P>
<P>
   Max drove now as fast as the Mustang would carry him across town
to the offices of the Florida Sun, a 10-story marble tower
overlooking Tampa Bay, housing Florida's best and biggest
newspaper. Max had always wanted to work there. And now he did _
sort of.
</P>
<P>
   He strode briskly through the lobby and right past the security
guard, who was looking down reading the paper, and into the
elevator. A large woman eating a doughnut told him Kate Banks'
office was on the ninth floor. He walked in through a cluster of
secretaries, ignored their questions, and strode into Kate's
office. She looked up from her desk and sensed right away that Max
had learned the truth. In fact, she had hoped he would.
</P>
<P>
   ``Angela Powers is not her real name,'' said Kate. ``It's
Cassandra Powers. Cassie. Powers was my husband's last name, but
this Glaber guy got off on the idea of `angelic powers,' and she
must have gone along for the ride. I've been desperate about her,
Max. This girl has been messed up since her father's death. Please.
Don't walk out on this. I couldn't bring myself to tell you about
her and make you think I was hiring you as some kind of private
eye. I'm up to my ears with conflicts. How could my own paper cover
this when my daughter's so involved?''
</P>
<P>
   ``How about full disclosure _ and then trusting your people to
do the right thing?''
</P>
<P>
   ``You've never been a parent, Max. You saw my daughter, didn't
you?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she spiked my ice tea.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean in the water, without her clothes, with Glaber and the
others looking on.'' Max nodded.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Sherry showed me those photos, I turned to ice. I've lost
my husband. I'm afraid of losing my daughter. And now I don't want
to lose you, at least as a dance partner. At least as a friend.''
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, Kate. I could use a pal. But one who, from now on, tells
me the whole truth. I know you've been hurting for your daughter,
so let's just say that I'll stay on the story ...,'' he dropped his
pants to show her the tattoo, `` ... to the bitter end.''
</P>
<P>
   Kate picked up the phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russell, this is Kate. Please assemble the staff for a
meeting. I'll be down in an hour. There's something I want to tell
them, and someone I want them to meet.''
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   NEXT INSTALLMENT: A PLEASANT SURPRISE
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Roy Peter Clark is a senior scholar and an associate at the
Poynter Institute for Media Studies. He was commissioned to do this
newspaper novel as part of the New York Times Regional Newspaper
