<HEADER>
A1180 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-NEWSPAPER-NOVEL-chap1     10-28 1086
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSPAPER-NOVEL-chap18-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIN'T DONE YET: A PLEASANT SURPRISE  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (ATTENTION EDITORS: Hearkening back to the era of Dickens and
other serial novelists, The New York Times Syndicate is offering
for purchase ``Ain't Done Yet: A Newspaper Novel About the
So-Called End of the World '' _ 29 suspenseful installments, by ROY
PETER CLARK, the Poynter Institute senior scholar and well-known
writing coach. The novel, set in St. Petersburg-Tampa, chronicles a
burnt-out investigative reporter on the trail of a cult, ``The
Watchers,'' and its charismatic leader. The novel was commissioned
as a millennium project by The New York Times Regional Newspaper
Group. Chapter 18 is below. The series is a wonderful way to
celebrate the millennium with your readers. For purchase
information, contact one of these New York Times Syndicate sales
representatives:
 &HT;    (_ U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at 732-390-4480;
fax, 732-390-4697.
 &HT;    (_ Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 33-1-47-42-17-11;
fax, 33-1-47-42-80-44 or 33-1-47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942.
 &HT;    (_ Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (PLEASE NOTE: All 29 chapters have been sent to the ``l''
lifestyle category code.)
 &HT;    
 By ROY PETER CLARK 
 (Worldwide rights) 
 c.1999 Roy Peter Clark  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   LAST INSTALLMENT: Max shows Sam Lockhart his Watcher tattoo and
gets a lecture on the potential dangers of a doomsday cult. Max
then confronts Kate about her daughter, but promises to stay on the
story.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   A great thing happened to Max. His new friend Evie Hamilton
called him. She was going to visit her daughter in Santa Barbara,
Calif. Would Max like to take care of Daisy the dog for a week or
so? ``Of all her visitors, she liked you the best.''
</P>
<P>
   Daisy loved the beach, but shied away from the water. She walked
along the sand beside Max with a slight limp, which disappeared
when she broke into a jog. She was so attentive and so pleased to
be out, sniffing dead fish and clumps of seaweed, that Max didn't
bother with a leash.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sir, there are no dogs allowed on the beach. We can't make the
sign any bigger. Are you a German tourist who can't read English?''
The harsh words came from a tall beach cop with a mean sneer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I read the sign. And I ignored it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You what?''
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't any ordinary dog, copper.'' Max did a bad imitation
of Edward G. Robinson. The cop looked at him in disbelief.
</P>
<P>
   Max said in his own voice, ``This is Daisy _ the dog that
survived the fall from the Skyway Bridge.''
</P>
<P>
   The cop's features changed instantly. In a second he squatted to
pat Daisy's head, and apologized to Max, and walked with them down
the beach, explaining to sunbathers that they were in the presence
of royalty.
</P>
<P>
   By the time they returned to the condo, Daisy collapsed on the
cool tile, sated with exercise, attention and affection.
</P>
<P>
   A knock at the door announced the arrival of Violet Rose,
looking smashing in a purple sun dress and strappy sandals. Her
long black hair was pulled into a ponytail, drawn neatly through
the back of a St. Pete Rays baseball cap.
</P>
<P>
   She flashed him a bright smile, her face glowed, which could
mean two things at the same time: She was glad to see Max, and her
research had discovered something important. She arrived with a
chew toy for Daisy, some Chinese takeout for her and Max, and a
file under her arm.
</P>
<P>
   ``You were right, Max, about the name William Miller _ if that
is Glaber's real name, it's another weird coincidence.''
</P>
<P>
   The photocopies in Violet's file revealed that William Miller
was the most famous American doomsday prophet of the 19th century.
He claimed 100,000 followers. From his reading of the Bible, Miller
predicted that the Second Coming would occur on Oct. 22, 1844.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, they waited and waited and the day came, and it
went, and the Millerites, what was left of them, referred to that
time as `The Great Disappointment.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had a few of those in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So have I.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to try out the hot tub? Kate's got some stuff out
there you can wear.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Can Daisy join us?''
</P>
<P>
   ``She seems a little shy of water right now.''
</P>
<P>
   But Daisy surprised them, hopping right in and splashing around
a minute and hopping out and shaking hard, sending a healthy spray
over Max and Violet.
</P>
<P>
   Max told her now about the Watcher tattoo, but did not show it
to her, and she did not ask to see it. He told her that Sam
Lockhart, feeling a little guilty about what had happened to Max,
had the entire police investigative file on The Watchers
photocopied for Max.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why don't you take it, Violet, and have another copy made for
yourself? Pay special attention to Glaber. I have a hunch that if
we can find out who he is, even a little something about his
background, some big mystery will be solved.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Max, there are lots of ways to track someone's background
online. You know that. It helps, of course, to have a real name or
date of birth or Social Security number. But I'll start with a
cross check of the names Glaber and Miller and see what turns up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you get this guy's real name, I'll buy you a dozen roses _
violet roses.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll settle for a foot massage. Right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Max granted her wish, a job that took a surprising length of
time. Each foot demanded careful attention. This was no hard labor,
he decided early on, but work that still commanded his best effort,
which meant not ignoring the Achilles tendon stretching up to a
firm but slender calf, and pressing his thumb hard up into the
arch, so that Violet closed her eyes and tilted back her head and
moaned and told him that it hurt but not to stop, and then pulling
on the dainty toes until they popped and making sure not to forget
to slide his fingers through the slips of skin between them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything else?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``How about a kiss?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Should we get Daisy to join us?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Not this time.''
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   NEXT INSTALLMENT: THE BRIDGE TO NOWHERE
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Roy Peter Clark is a senior scholar and an associate at the
Poynter Institute for Media Studies. He was commissioned to do this
newspaper novel as part of the New York Times Regional Newspaper
Group's Celebrate 2000 project.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
