<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991028.0158 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 13:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1181 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-NEWSPAPER-NOVEL-chap1     10-28 1296
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSPAPER-NOVEL-chap19-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIN'T DONE YET: THE BRIDGE TO NOWHERE  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (ATTENTION EDITORS: Hearkening back to the era of Dickens and
other serial novelists, The New York Times Syndicate is offering
for purchase ``Ain't Done Yet: A Newspaper Novel About the
So-Called End of the World '' _ 29 suspenseful installments, by ROY
PETER CLARK, the Poynter Institute senior scholar and well-known
writing coach. The novel, set in St. Petersburg-Tampa, chronicles a
burnt-out investigative reporter on the trail of a cult, ``The
Watchers,'' and its charismatic leader. The novel was commissioned
as a millennium project by The New York Times Regional Newspaper
Group. Chapter 19 is below. The series is a wonderful way to
celebrate the millennium with your readers. For purchase
information, contact one of these New York Times Syndicate sales
representatives:
 &HT;    (_ U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at 732-390-4480;
fax, 732-390-4697.
 &HT;    (_ Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 33-1-47-42-17-11;
fax, 33-1-47-42-80-44 or 33-1-47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942.
 &HT;    (_ Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (PLEASE NOTE: All 29 chapters have been sent to the ``l''
lifestyle category code.)
 &HT;    
 By ROY PETER CLARK 
 (Worldwide rights) 
 c.1999 Roy Peter Clark  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   LAST INSTALLMENT: Max takes care of Daisy the dog, then receives
a visit from Violet Rose, who is tracking down the real identity of
Raoul Glaber. A foot rub leads to something more.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   Max Timlin woke up with a warm breath on his neck and rolled
over to see Daisy the dog on the next pillow. He let out a laugh
that startled Daisy from her sweet doggie dreams. Max offered her a
good morning ear rub and took a licking in return.
</P>
<P>
   This display of affection caused him to reflect on his
surprising good fortune with women, not a condition, after two
divorces, that he was used to.
</P>
<P>
   He got up and looked into the mirror and could not imagine what
anyone might see in him. A once athletic body had gone to seed.
Thinning blondish hair was down to a cluster of unruly stalks. He
had random scars from skin cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's invisible, he mused, or my after-shave. Kate Banks
was more attentive and earnest than ever before, but Max could look
into her dark brown eyes and see, clearly circumscribed, the
difference between friendship and love. That was fine with him. He
needed her passion and intelligence in mounting the investigation
against The Watchers. And she clearly needed him, at least for her
daughter's sake.
</P>
<P>
   He enjoyed his meetings with Sherry Darling, who continued
surreptitious photographing of The Watchers, not only around the
Conquistador Hotel, but also around the Star Dome, where
preparations were under way for an international gathering of
Watchers, now just a fortnight away. Sherry had become a great
buddy, a kindred spirit, a true partner to Max.
</P>
<P>
   And now came the delicious surprise of one Miss Violet Rose, who
had visited him for evening walks on the beach, each night for the
last five nights. Her purported mission was to fill him in on the
day's search. Along with gathering string on Glaber's background,
Violet was vacuuming the Internet landscape on news of the upcoming
Watchers event, billed as ``The New Awakening.''
</P>
<P>
   But along the way, Violet taught Max some yoga stretching
exercises, which he found relaxing, cooked a meal for him, and
grabbed his hand during their sunset strolls.
</P>
<P>
   And, finally, came the news from Evie Hamilton in California
that she would extend her visit to her daughter for a while. Max
assured her that Daisy would be in good hands until her return.
</P>
<P>
   The week had brought one disturbing development. Two more
Watchers were found floating face down in Tampa Bay. The couple _
another man and woman _ lacked the identifying tattoos, but they
were clean cut and dressed in white.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Sam Lockhart had sent his investigative unit into the
Conquistador Hotel, but the detective turned up little to indicate
why two healthy young people _ just before the New Awakening _
would choose to sleep with the fishes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We presume they jumped,'' Sam told Max, ``except for one
little detail. There was no abandoned vehicle near the top of the
Skyway. How the hell did they get up there? Take a little stroll?
Or did someone give them a lift? And maybe a little push?''
</P>
<P>
   Max was writing furiously now every day, sometimes as much as
5,000 words or more. Kate had arranged a small team to cover the
daily activities of The Watchers. It was agreed that Max would
write the blockbuster, which would appear after the first of the
year, or the first of the millennium.
</P>
<P>
   The world was a month away from the biggest New Year's Eve party
of all time, and you could not turn on TV without seeing Dick Clark
hyping the annual Times Square event.
</P>
<P>
   ``Join us for The Biggest Ball of All,'' he said, still looking
like the world's oldest teen-ager. And you couldn't turn on the
radio without hearing Prince or the Artist Formerly Known As _
heck, he had more names than Glaber _ singing ``1999'': ``Two
thousand zero zero, party over, oops, out of time ... We're gonna
party like it's 1999.''
</P>
<P>
   Max sang along to the radio as he drove the Mustang toward the
St. Pete Municipal Airport, a flying club for rich people, really,
but convenient for journalists.
</P>
<P>
   There he met Sherry and a pilot. They boarded a helicopter _ Max
hated helicopters and high places _ but in he went after a
reassuring hug from Sherry. They circled the beautiful waterfront
district, and shot across the city, hovering over the roof of the
amazing Star Dome.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is where The Watchers will be gathering,'' said Sherry.
``This is the site for the New Awakening.''
</P>
<P>
   The great white roof was a structural marvel: six acres of
strong but flexible fiberglass coated with Teflon, translucent to
affect the light in the stadium, supported by 180 miles of cables
connected by struts, yet puffy, like the world's largest throw
pillow.
</P>
<P>
   The chopper banked and cut south. Max's heart raced and his
mouth went dry and he gripped his seat and closed his eyes.
Meanwhile, Sherry was gabbing and pointing and leaning out to shoot
images of the Skyway.
</P>
<P>
   Max found the courage to look down at another engineering marvel
_ a gorgeous bridge, its golden cables rising to the heavens in two
steeples, as if to sanctify the blue-green marriage of sky above
and water below.
</P>
<P>
   But he could never view this without thinking of the destruction
of the old bridge, and the 35 people in cars and a bus who had gone
off the end to their deaths.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is it about bridges?'' he wondered aloud. He knew many
people had nightmares about bridges. He had interviewed people who
could not drive across the Skyway themselves. They needed friends,
or chauffeurs, or Valium to get them across.
</P>
<P>
   Then he thought of those who had made their way to the top, who
had looked down at this beauty, only to feel betrayed by it and the
world. Then it came to him in a flash of images. Maybe the drowned
Watchers hadn't jumped. Maybe they hadn't been driven to the top
and pushed over. Maybe they had been flown over and dropped from
the sky.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   NEXT INSTALLMENT: ON TOP OF THE WORLD
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Roy Peter Clark is a senior scholar and an associate at the
Poynter Institute for Media Studies. He was commissioned to do this
newspaper novel as part of the New York Times Regional Newspaper
Group's Celebrate 2000 project.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-99 1351EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991028.0159 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 13:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1182 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-NEWSPAPER-NOVEL-chap2     10-28 1228
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSPAPER-NOVEL-chap20-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIN'T DONE YET: ON TOP OF THE WORLD  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (ATTENTION EDITORS: Hearkening back to the era of Dickens and
other serial novelists, The New York Times Syndicate is offering
for purchase ``Ain't Done Yet: A Newspaper Novel About the
So-Called End of the World '' _ 29 suspenseful installments, by ROY
PETER CLARK, the Poynter Institute senior scholar and well-known
writing coach. The novel, set in St. Petersburg-Tampa, chronicles a
burnt-out investigative reporter on the trail of a cult, ``The
Watchers,'' and its charismatic leader. The novel was commissioned
as a millennium project by The New York Times Regional Newspaper
Group. Chapter 20 is below. The series is a wonderful way to
celebrate the millennium with your readers. For purchase
information, contact one of these New York Times Syndicate sales
representatives:
 &HT;    (_ U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at 732-390-4480;
fax, 732-390-4697.
 &HT;    (_ Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 33-1-47-42-17-11;
fax, 33-1-47-42-80-44 or 33-1-47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942.
 &HT;    (_ Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (PLEASE NOTE: All 29 chapters have been sent to the ``l''
lifestyle category code.)
 &HT;    
 By ROY PETER CLARK 
 (Worldwide rights) 
 c.1999 Roy Peter Clark  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   LAST INSTALLMENT: Two Watchers are found floating in Tampa Bay.
Max ponders if they jumped off the Skyway Bridge, or were pushed?
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   Tipped off by Max, the police began an inquiry into whether the
dead Watchers could have been dropped from a plane or helicopter to
make it look like a suicide leap off the Skyway Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   ``The injuries on these folks were unusually devastating,'' Sam
reported to Max over the telephone. ``The medical examiner says the
injuries are consistent with a drop of more than 200 feet _ but so
many things can affect this.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Any comment from Glaber?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Through a spokesman he said that young people, even Watchers,
killing themselves was a horrible thing, and a clear sign of a
troubled world tumbling toward its end.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What an ass----.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He says The Watchers don't own a plane or helicopter. Only
boats, vans and cars.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I saw something that could be a landing pad for a
helicopter _ out beyond the dunes near the Conquistador.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll check it out. What are you up to?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm writing like crazy, but today I'm going to call on a
friend, so I can get into the Star Dome and view the New Awakening
with my own eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   That evening, Max found himself on the southern tip of St.
Petersburg, in a neighborhood called Pinellas Point, where great
oak trees hung shade over lovely wide streets that for decades had
been paved with pink concrete. Most people called this place ``The
Pink Streets.''
</P>
<P>
   Max's face was as pink as the streets. He was jogging _ feeling
flabby and out of breath _ next to a tall, young black man, who
happened to be one of Florida's most beloved athletes, James
``Choirboy'' Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Jones had grown up in St. Pete, one of the nation's only
five-sport athletes and an honors student at Lakewood High. At
6-foot-4, both nimble and strong, James played quarterback, point
guard and center field. He ran track. And he once joined the soccer
team to step in for an injured goalkeeper. He went to Florida
State, where he decided to concentrate on baseball. He was now in
his second season playing with the St. Pete Pelicans.
</P>
<P>
   Max had written about him after James' father was murdered in a
convenience-store robbery. The father, Charles Jones, was a great
preacher and pastor _ earning his son the nickname ``Choirboy'' _
and his death stunned the community.
</P>
<P>
   In his father's honor, James had committed half of his huge
salary to charitable work. He built houses for the working poor,
sponsored the construction of athletic fields in the poorest
neighborhoods, purchased books for a new library branch and could
often be seen on Sunday mornings at local churches, working with
pastors on their most pressing needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``So you want me to sneak you into the Dome for this Awakening
event. Don't you know I'm the Choirboy. I'm not exactly the sneaky
kind.''
</P>
<P>
   ``James, I didn't know where else to turn. You know everybody in
that place _ and The Watchers are barring the press, and they know
me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Max. I like you, my friend. The story you wrote made my mother
cry her heart out over my father _ but in a good way. So I'll help
you. But, to ease my Choirboy conscience, I must impose two
conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Name them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, you have to come with me to church early Sunday
morning. Then for the rest of the day, you have to help me build a
house. Then, if you can still stand up _ by the way, you are way
out of shape _ we'll go to the Dome.''
</P>
<P>
   By late Sunday afternoon, every muscle in Max's body, including
some he didn't know he had, ached. Seven hours of bending, lifting,
hammering, lifting, bending, had taken their toll.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a long time since I've worked like that, James. I
think I remember now why I became a writer. No heavy lifting.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Words can be heavy, very heavy. But this is good for your
body, Max, and your soul. I can see that God ain't done with you
yet.''
</P>
<P>
   They hugged and Max remembered that Father Ralph had said the
same thing, using almost the same words.
</P>
<P>
   It was no trouble for James to get into the Dome, even on a
night when the building was closed to the public. They trusted him
with his own key. ``Max, you came to church with me. You helped me
build a house.''
</P>
<P>
   They were standing at home plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I'm gonna add one more stipulation. I've got a great idea
for how you can get in here, see everything you need to see and
still not be seen by a single Watcher. But it's gonna cost you.''
</P>
<P>
   Max could see mischief in the eyes of the Choirboy. ``Max,
you've got to beat me in a race around the bases.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You mean I run and you crawl.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No, easier. You start at second base and I'll start out at
home.''
</P>
<P>
   Max lost. His legs, tight from the day's work, slid out from
under him rounding third base, and by the time he recovered, he
could hear the fastest man in baseball whooshing by him. ``You've
got to promise you'll write about this, Max. Not now. But someday,
when I enter the Hall of Fame.'' Coming from the Choirboy, it did
not sound like bragging.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll write your life story, James Choirboy Jones. I've never
met an athlete _ a man _ like you. Now where are you going to hide
me?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Up there.''
</P>
<P>
   Max lifted his eyes from the tip of his friend's finger, up, up,
up, till his head was bent back, staring at a thin catwalk leading
to a circular bank of huge speakers. Up, up, up, more than 250 feet
to the domed roof of the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Up there?''
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   NEXT INSTALLMENT: GONNA TAKE YOU HIGHER
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Roy Peter Clark is a senior scholar and an associate at the
Poynter Institute for Media Studies. He was commissioned to do this
newspaper novel as part of the New York Times Regional Newspaper
Group's Celebrate 2000 project.) &LR;  &QL;
