</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSPAPER-NOVEL-chap23-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIN'T DONE YET: THE GREAT DEBATE  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (ATTENTION EDITORS: Hearkening back to the era of Dickens and
other serial novelists, The New York Times Syndicate is offering
for purchase ``Ain't Done Yet: A Newspaper Novel About the
So-Called End of the World '' _ 29 suspenseful installments, by ROY
PETER CLARK, the Poynter Institute senior scholar and well-known
writing coach. The novel, set in St. Petersburg-Tampa, chronicles a
burnt-out investigative reporter on the trail of a cult, ``The
Watchers,'' and its charismatic leader. The novel was commissioned
as a millennium project by The New York Times Regional Newspaper
Group. Chapter 23 is below. The series is a wonderful way to
celebrate the millennium with your readers. For purchase
information, contact one of these New York Times Syndicate sales
representatives:
 &HT;    (_ U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at 732-390-4480;
fax, 732-390-4697.
 &HT;    (_ Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 33-1-47-42-17-11;
fax, 33-1-47-42-80-44 or 33-1-47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942.
 &HT;    (_ Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (PLEASE NOTE: All 29 chapters have been sent to the ``l''
lifestyle category code.)
 &HT;    
 By ROY PETER CLARK 
 (Worldwide rights) 
 c.1999 Roy Peter Clark  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   LAST INSTALLMENT: The Watcher convention is a giant party for
Raoul Glaber until it is crashed by a little man with silver hair _
Father Ralph.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, time meant nothing for Max. It did not matter to him
whether it took two minutes or two days to climb down from his
crow's nest atop the domed stadium. When he got down during his
rehearsal, he had Rocky Como's back to stare at, and his
encouragement. But now it was just Max in an empty stadium, the
event he had witnessed so extraordinary, he couldn't get it out of
his head, even as he inched down the gangplanks and across the
catwalks towards the safety of sea level.
</P>
<P>
   He even prayed, which was not his style. ``Dear Lord, who so
inspired Father Ralph, please get me down off this damn thing.
Sorry about the damn.''
</P>
<P>
   As he descended _ always trying to look out, not down _ Max
replayed the events of the last few hours, again. He could not even
estimate how long they took. Time stood still. Or it sped up. Or it
reversed its field, creating a moment fit only for history,
mythology, or literature: the Knight playing chess with the figure
of Death; Christ facing the Grand Inquisitor; Clarence Darrow
cross-examining William Jennings Bryan during the Scopes Monkey
Trial; Don Juan in Hell.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you Satan?'' Raoul Glaber had asked Father Ralph, who
stood safe and solitary on a catwalk above the crowd, wearing the
orange jumpsuit of a sound engineer, clutching a wireless mike.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I'm just a man. I'm not Satan. I'm not an angel. I'm not a
prophet. Just a man.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And why have you come here?''
</P>
<P>
   ``To save that young woman.''
</P>
<P>
   He pointed to Angela Powers, who stepped back from Glaber and
looked down, as if in shame.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is loved here. But she is free to leave,'' said Glaber,
who gestured to the crowd. ``They are all free to leave.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you know about freedom, Mr. Bigshot Watcher, Mr. Red
Tuxedo? There is no true freedom without responsibility. And you
act with no responsibility toward that woman, or to any of these
young people. If you did, you would not hide behind a false mask
and a false name. You would not offer them despair in the guise of
hope.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How do I offer them despair, old man?'' Max sensed a subtle
shift in Glaber's voice, an erosion of his arrogance and
self-assurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``You say that the human race has proved unfit for saving. I say
you're wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You say this, old man, in the last days of a century that gave
us Hitler and Stalin and Pol Pot.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not deny it. But can you deny that it also gave us Gandhi
and Mother Teresa and Nelson Mandela and Jonas Salk and Dr. King
and my mother _ the woman was a saint.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Look around you, old man, look at the world with your eyes
opened, and not through the nostalgic blindness of your senility.
Your generation left these children with ashes.'' This brought
scattered applause from a crowd that seemed unsure how to respond
to this debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``What year were you born, oh great leader of The Watchers?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should I tell you?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you afraid of me? An old man, as you say. Can't you answer
a simple question? The truth cannot harm you here _ with your many
followers, surrounded by your guards and cronies.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was born in 1950.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, so you'll turn 50 in the year 2,000. And you've chosen a
bride young enough to be your daughter.''
</P>
<P>
   Ralph paced as he spoke now, and raised his arms to the crowd
melodramatically. ``Kids. Don't you get it? Your leader is about to
turn 50. He's over the hill. He's playing the back nine. He wants a
trophy bride. He rides around in a power boat. Your prophet is not
ushering in a new millennium. He's having a midlife crisis!''
</P>
<P>
   This remark brought some scattered bursts of laughter, but these
were shouted down, until an angry murmur spread throughout the
stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why shouldn't I send my helpers up there and have you thrown
into the street?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Because you are afraid of me, son.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I an NOT your son.''
</P>
<P>
   Glaber lost his cool, Max could hear it in his voice and see it
in his body language. ``You are NOT my father.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You're God's son. Just love God, and love these children
enough _ love that young woman enough to free her. Free them all.
Let them go. Young lady ...''
</P>
<P>
   Ralph's voice was comforting now, as if he were sitting across
the table from her, sharing a cup of coffee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Young lady. You're free to go. Go ahead. Go.''
</P>
<P>
   With that Angela Powers dashed off the stage, her hand across
her face, as if to hold back tears. She ran like an athlete, even
in that slinky red dress and high heels, past a confused palace
guard, down a runway and out of sight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have tolerated your intrusion, old man _ I think you are
Satan _ but now you have gone too far.''
</P>
<P>
   Glaber was beginning to rant. He gestured to three burly blond
men at the edge of the stage who ran off. To find Angela? To get
Ralph? Max couldn't tell.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing you can do to harm me,'' said Ralph. ``I do
not fear you. And, children, I do not fear the world. Embrace it.
Do not hate it. Walk out now. Go find a phone. Call your parents.
Wish them a Merry Christmas. Go visit them on New Year's Eve. Bring
some nice pastry. Buy them a Tony Bennett or a Frank Sinatra CD.
Watch the football games. Enjoy. Listen to that word. Enjoy. It has
joy in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Glaber stared up, speechless.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those fingers in my hair, That sly come hither stare, That
strips my conscience bare _ It's witchcraft.'' Max was laughing
now, wanting to leap from his perch down to Ralph, to hug him and
lift him up like a prizefighter and raise his hand in victory.
Ralph was breaking into his Frank Sinatra medley. ``I've got the
world on a string, Sittin' on a rainbow, Got the string around my
finger, What a world, What a life, I'm in love.''
</P>
<P>
   Glaber screamed and twisted around, ``Is there no one here who
will rid me of this Satan in the guise of an old man?''
</P>
<P>
   At that remark the crowd grew angry. People stood and shook
their fists at Ralph, or threw cups or plastic water bottles at
him. But it appeared as if a few others were trying to restrain
them. A fight broke out in the upper deck, and then another in the
mezzanine. Glaber's entourage tore off the stage, running to the
trouble spots.
</P>
<P>
   Max looked down at the chaos. From his vantage point, it looked
like an illuminated manuscript of Dante's Inferno, a vibrating mass
of humanity, trapped in its own confusion and agony. And there, in
the middle, standing on the stage alone, his arms held wide, his
head down, like a crucified icon, was Glaber.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just one more thing before I go,'' said Father Ralph. ``A
little something from the poet T.S. Eliot: `In the end is my
beginning ... In the beginning is my end ... And the end of all our
exploring / Will be to arrive where we started /And know the place
for the first time.' Have a nice day.''
</P>
<P>
   Just then, a group of Glaber's men appeared on the lower
catwalk, and just as quickly Ralph disappeared through a doorway,
his voice an echo in the great stadium.
</P>
<P>
   More fights broke out in the stands, with two men clutching at
each other, leaning dangerously over a high railing. A new
commotion raised the decibel level higher as city police streamed
into the stadium, wearing yellow vests and riot gear.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   NEXT INSTALLMENT: MAX TAKES A NAP
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
