<HEADER>
A1186 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-NEWSPAPER-NOVEL-chap2     10-28 1311
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSPAPER-NOVEL-chap24-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIN'T DONE YET: MAX TAKES A NAP  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (ATTENTION EDITORS: Hearkening back to the era of Dickens and
other serial novelists, The New York Times Syndicate is offering
for purchase ``Ain't Done Yet: A Newspaper Novel About the
So-Called End of the World '' _ 29 suspenseful installments, by ROY
PETER CLARK, the Poynter Institute senior scholar and well-known
writing coach. The novel, set in St. Petersburg-Tampa, chronicles a
burnt-out investigative reporter on the trail of a cult, ``The
Watchers,'' and its charismatic leader. The novel was commissioned
as a millennium project by The New York Times Regional Newspaper
Group. Chapter 24 is below. The series is a wonderful way to
celebrate the millennium with your readers. For purchase
information, contact one of these New York Times Syndicate sales
representatives:
 &HT;    (_ U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at 732-390-4480;
fax, 732-390-4697.
 &HT;    (_ Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 33-1-47-42-17-11;
fax, 33-1-47-42-80-44 or 33-1-47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942.
 &HT;    (_ Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (PLEASE NOTE: All 29 chapters have been sent to the ``l''
lifestyle category code.)
 &HT;    
 By ROY PETER CLARK 
 (Worldwide rights) 
 c.1999 Roy Peter Clark  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   LAST INSTALLMENT: Father Ralph debates the leader of The
Watchers, and, along the way, secures the freedom of Glaber's young
bride-to-be.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   Max rushed back to the newspaper office, where Kate and her team
had assembled. They debriefed him on what he had seen at the
stadium, but not before he had a quick private conversation with
Kate about how Glaber had announced that Angela would become his
bride, how Father Ralph had dramatically intervened, how Angela was
last seen running out of the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Kate crossed her arms and bit her lip, worried more than ever
about her daughter's safety and her mental state.
</P>
<P>
   Exhausted but driven by adrenaline, Max wrote a 3,000-word memo
on what he had witnessed and turned it over to an editor. He picked
up the phone and dialed Violet's extension.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, Max,'' she said sweetly. ``I guess this means you made it
down from the dome ceiling safe and sound.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Check your e-mail for my memo, Violet. It was amazing. I'm
heading back to the condo. But I want to see you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to see you, Max,'' said Violet, and then, ``and not
just see you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Violet. Glaber says he was born in 1950.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If he's telling the truth, that will help.''
</P>
<P>
   Max cruised home, still replaying the events of the day. The
police had arrested 50 Watchers. Angela Powers was missing. Raoul
Glaber had to be led from the stage by one of his followers. Father
Ralph Rizzo was _ well, for all Max knew _ he was eating lasagna
and listening to a Frank Sinatra CD.
</P>
<P>
   When Max let himself in to the condo, he knew right away that
something was wrong. All the lights were on, and the television
blared, turned to the local station, which was reporting news of
the arrests at the Dome. He heard music coming from the back.
</P>
<P>
   Max suddenly wished Daisy had been there as a watchdog, but Evie
had returned from California and retrieved the famous Skyway pup.
``HEY!'' barked Max, ``who's here?''
</P>
<P>
   He grabbed a golf club _ a 2-iron _ from the front closet and
hefted it with two hands over one shoulder as if it were a baseball
bat. He stepped cautiously through the place, peeking around
corners, into one bathroom, the bedrooms, the office. All the
lights were on.
</P>
<P>
   Then finally he poked a door open with the end of his club. It
squeaked, and Max could see that someone had lit candles beside the
Jacuzzi and was listening to classical music. Bach, he thought. The
candles flickered from the gulf breeze, sending odd shadows across
the room, shadows of a human figure, whose body now made ripples in
the water.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can come in, Max. It's only me.''
</P>
<P>
   He took one more step, and there she was, still beautiful and
once again in the water without the benefit of clothes. He gazed on
the face and body that could distract even the head of The Watchers
from his millennium watch. Angela Powers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do me one favor, please,'' said Max. ``Put something on.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, she turned a dial which sent bubbles across the surface
of the water, concealing her nakedness. She slid down, so only her
face and kneecaps were visible. ``How's that?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Fine. Why did you drug me at the hotel?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know they put a drug in your ice tea, Max. I swear I
didn't. I didn't know a lot of things.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Like what?''
</P>
<P>
   ``That he wanted me to marry him, for goodness sake. There's
been nothing like that between us. That came out of the blue.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What else?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Or that Watchers were going to start jumping off the bridge. I
knew those four people. I thought they were looking forward to a
new life _ I can't imagine what drove them to suicide. When I
started asking questions, all I got back were strange vibes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't understand one thing. From what I've learned, you
could be a brain surgeon or an Olympic athlete or a Victoria's
Secret model. What drove you to a windbag like Glaber?''
</P>
<P>
   ``If I could answer that, a lot of my problems would be solved.
Maybe my mother could tell you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Does she know you're here?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No. But she gave me a key to the place. I'm glad I kept it. I
love my mother. Can you believe that?''
</P>
<P>
   ``She's heartsick over what's happened to you. And frightened.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I went off the deep end when my father died. I admit it. We
were so close. He raised me, directed me, coached me, cared for me,
while my mom was off working.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So Glaber became your substitute daddy?'' Max said it with
sarcasm, and then regretted it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't ridicule me, Max. It's not that simple. Raoul was
charming and persuasive _ and his challenges about the world
stimulated my thinking. Why not become part of something big and
important? When he took an interest in me, started calling me
Angela, it raised my status in the group. It was like I was Chelsea
Clinton, or a beautiful princess.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You've hurt a lot of people for a little bit of attention and
celebrity, Angela Powers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Please call me Cassie. I want my old name back. And my old
life.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a good first step.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Could you hand me that robe, please?''
</P>
<P>
   Max picked the blue one, instead of the white, handed it to her
and turned away, and closed his eyes for good measure as she slid
out of the water.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sorry you were hurt, Max. And I'm sorry my mom ...'' She
began to sob. ``And I'm afraid something really bad is going to
happen on January 1st _ and if anyone else gets hurt _ I'm sorry.
So sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   She dropped her head straight forward till her forehead hit Max
in the shoulder blade. It hurt. Max put his arm around her and
ushered her back inside. ``Come on. Let's call your mother and let
her know you're all right.''
</P>
<P>
   But as they stepped through into the living room, there stood
three burly blond men, dress in white. Angela screamed. Max grabbed
the lamp and threw it at them. One blocked it with his forearm then
grabbed Max, spun him around and locked the vice of his arm against
Max's windpipe until the room got darker and slipped from under
him.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   NEXT INSTALLMENT: THE FLIGHT BEFORE CHRISTMAS
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
