<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 14:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1202 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-VIDEO-COLUMN-LADN &LR;      10-28 0721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DELIVERANCE' AND MORE ON DVD 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
By ROB LOWMAN 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Director John Boorman's career is one that is not easy to
categorize or assess. In his 30-plus years as a filmmaker he has
made one genuine critical and commercial success _ ``Deliverance''
(1972). Meanwhile, the rest of his films have ranged from the
sublime, such as ``Hope and Glory'' (1987); to the sloppy (to be
kind), such as ``Exorcist II: The Heretic'' (1977); to the simply
odd, such as ``Zardoz'' (1974).
</P>
<P>
   Early in his career, Boorman was thought of as a man's director,
especially with his two films with Lee Marvin, ``Hell in the
Pacific'' (1968) and the marvelous ``Point Blank'' (1967), which
was remade into this year's Mel Gibson film ``Payback.''
``Deliverance,'' which was recently released on DVD, hammered home
the perception, though Boorman would prove to have a warm side as
shown in ``Hope.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Deliverance,'' which starred Jon Voight, Burt Reynolds, Ronny
Cox and Ned Beatty, tells the story of four Atlanta businessmen's
ill-fated rafting trip in the wilds of Appalachia. What begins as a
fun adventure, an attempt to relate to nature, turns dark as the
wilderness becomes their enemy. As they are pursued by vengeful
mountain men, the businessmen's fight for survival tests their
notions of what being civilized means as they are confronted with a
brutality in nature and in themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deliverance,'' based on the late James Dickey's novel, is a
visually stunning film, thanks to the cinematography of Vilmos
Zsigmond, and remains as provocative and shocking as it was at the
time of its release. The DVD (Warners, $24.95) includes a making-of
featurette called ``The Dangerous World of Deliverance,'' which
shows the arduous task of making the film, which was shot along the
Chattanooga River in Georgia. It also has a remastered soundtrack.
Remember ``Dueling Banjos''?
</P>
<P>
   After a few filmmaking detours, Boorman returned to form with
``Excalibur'' (1981), a retelling of the legend of Arthur. With
clanking armor, knights being whacked in half, betrayal, lust,
liberal sex and dollops of mysticism and magic, ``Excalibur'' is a
lusty sword-and-sorcery treat. Based on Sir Thomas Malory's ``Le
Morte D'Arthur,'' Boorman's film is a much more intelligent use of
myth than ``Star Wars,'' which is just a sword-and-sorcery fable
set in space. The reason the legend of Arthur has survived for so
long is that it is a quintessential tale of good vs. evil as man
tries to find grace (or deliverance?) in the wilderness.
</P>
<P>
   The film was a return to form (and themes) for Boorman, and it
was apparent that he relished the challenge. While ``Excalibur''
can be a bit confusing at times on first viewing, the director (he
was also co-writer) managed to turn a complicated story into an
entertaining and thoughtful film.
</P>
<P>
   ``Excalibur'' has also been released on DVD (Warner; $24.98). It
includes an audio commentary by Boorman. In one interesting tidbit,
the director talks about how the studio originally didn't want
Nicol Williamson for the key role of Merlin and how Williamson
didn't want the part when he found out Helen Mirren had been cast
as Morgana (Arthur's half-sister). When Mirren found that out, she
said she wouldn't work with Williamson. Eventually Boorman
persuaded the British stage stars to join the film, and it's
interesting to note that the pair, who play an antagonistic
cat-and-mouse magic game, give the most interesting performances in
the film _ with Williamson at his twitchy best and Mirren at her
most devilish. The film is also notable for early performances by
Patrick Stewart, Liam Neeson and Gabriel Byrne.
</P>
<P>
   During the summer, Boorman's latest film, ``The General'' was
released on video. It is also a return to form after a while out of
the public eye, winning Boorman the best-director award at Cannes.
It tells the true story of Irish crime boss Martin Cahill, who
actually burgled Boorman's house. The film shows Cahill (Brendan
Gleason) trying to fence Boorman's gold record of ``Dueling
Banjos.'' In another tie to ``Deliverance,'' Voight plays the man
in pursuit of Cahill. And, as with ``Deliverance,'' it's among
Boorman's best, and that means it shouldn't be missed. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
