<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-NORWAY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON IN NORWAY: SOME QUESTIONS FOR THE VISITOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ALEX A. VARDAMIS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARMEL, Calif. _ For the first time in history, a sitting
American president will visit the land of lutefisk and lefse.
President Clinton travels to Norway on Tuesday to attend a memorial
ceremony for Yitzhak Rabin, the Israeli prime minister who was
assassinated four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The tribute will once again position Oslo in the center of the
Middle East peace process. Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and
Palestinian leader Yasir Arafat plan to attend.
</P>
<P>
   The Norwegians invited Clinton. He declined. On Oct. 15,
Norwegian Prime Minister Kjell Magne Bondevik, during a visit to
Washington, repeated the invitation. Again, Clinton was too busy.
</P>
<P>
   But four days later, on Oct. 19, came the surprising
announcement that the president had changed his mind. Sandy Berger,
the national security advisor, spoke of a new American summit to
take place in Oslo. Suddenly, it seemed as if a guest at a party
had declared himself the host.
</P>
<P>
   Startled Norwegians are scrambling to prepare for the visit.
That a busy American president would take time to visit Oslo is
seen by the Norwegian press as a tribute to the Land of the
Midnight Sun and to its role in bringing together the Palestinians
and the Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   Why has Clinton changed his mind? Could there be a breakthrough
in the peace process? Or could it be that presiding over a
handshake between Arafat and Barak is a photo op too good to pass
up?
</P>
<P>
   Other factors might be in play. A respite from the quotidian
congressional salvos might seem tempting. A cruise on the fjords
might be more soothing than midnight golf. And what is more calming
than a nostalgic trip into the past? Certain it is that the always
polite but ever tenacious Scandinavian press will have an
opportunity to address a number of unresolved issues.
</P>
<P>
   These are a few of the questions the American president might be
asked. The responses would, of course, be of interest only to
Norwegian admirers.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. President, we Norwegians are a modest bunch, reluctant to
enter the spotlight. However, we have occasionally noticed that our
own efforts in advancing the peace process in the Middle East seem
to have been subsumed into the achievements of your administration.
</P>
<P>
   We were disappointed, for example, that the Oslo peace accords
were signed, not in Oslo, but in Washington. Will these current
negotiations similarly be transferred across the Atlantic after the
heavy lifting is over?
</P>
<P>
   Must we always take the risks while others hog the glory? We
Norwegians, as you know, Mr. President, are proud of our socialist
lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   All of us, from the Labor Party to the Conservatives, believe
that it is the government's duty to provide citizens with
cradle-to-grave security. Universal health care is a basic human
right.
</P>
<P>
   You, as a good liberal, share our views. You do, don't you? Open
up, Mr. President. Acknowledge the debt you owe to Scandinavian
socialism. Explain why you've fallen so far short in implementing
reforms in your own country.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. President, you know that Norway and the rest of the
civilized world consider capital punishment a crime against
humanity. We are sure that you, as a closet socialist, share our
views.
</P>
<P>
   But Mr. President, we're confused. Rumors have surfaced on the
Internet that, in 1992, during the presidential campaign, you flew
back to Little Rock to attend the execution of a mentally retarded
inmate. Say it isn't so.
</P>
<P>
   Tell us that you oppose the death penalty. Assure Norwegians
that you loathe the barbaric yen for vengeance that seems to plague
so many of your citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. President, in 1997, your fellow American, Jody Williams,
here in Oslo, received the Nobel Peace Prize on behalf of the
International Campaign to Ban Land Mines. Williams later excoriated
you for your refusal to sign the Land Mine Treaty. Why did you do
that? Don't you know that all right-thinking nations have signed
onto the treaty? You say you'll sign up in 2006. Won't you be out
of office by then? Will your successor be bound by your promise?
</P>
<P>
   Here's a pen. Sign the Land Mine Treaty right now. Surely you'll
have no problem convincing Congress to ratify it when you get back
home. That's what moral leadership is all about.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. President, there are rumors that you, yourself, are hoping
to accept a Nobel Peace Prize one of these years. Could that be why
you've come visiting us? Are you looking forward to schmoozing with
the committee?
</P>
<P>
   Here's a word of advice. Anyone who campaigns for the award is
guaranteed not to receive it. We Norwegians are pragmatic and
unemotional. Spin does not decide who wins the Nobel Peace Prize.
</P>
<P>
   A willingness to take risks might. Ask Mr. Arafat about that. He
and Rabin were recipients in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Mr. President, we understand that this is your second
visit to Norway. Some say that, when, as a student at Oxford, you
visited the land of the fjords in the late 1960s, it was to confer
with Scandinavian peace activists opposed to U.S. military
involvement in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   Could you provide us with a list of names? Surely some of your
Norwegian friends are still alive and would be happy to shed light
on your youthful exuberances.
</P>
<P>
   Also, word has it that the American ambassador is planning a
wing-ding of a reception in your honor. Wouldn't it be fun to get
together with old comrades and reminisce about the past over a
bottle of aquavit and a platter of pickled herring?
</P>
<P>
   (Examiner contributor Alex A. Vardamis was the defense attache
at the U.S. embassy in Oslo for three years and recently taught
American literature as a Fulbright Fellow in Stavanger, Norway.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
