 Thursday, Oct. 28, 1999     
 Editors      The Hearst News Service has filed or will file the
following for Friday. If you have questions, please call Susie
McBee or Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.    (The ``HNS'' tag appears in
all sluglines.)   
<TEXT>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GOP-DEBATE-ANALYSIS (Undated) _ Republican presidential
contenders _ minus Texas Gov. George W. Bush _ will square off in a
``town meeting'' tonight. Bush has begged off, saying he has to be
in Texas when his wife is presented with an award by Southern
Methodist University, her alma mater. By STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-MINORITIES (Washington) _ At a time when the AIDS epidemic
is increasing among minorities, the House is expected to pass today
a proposal to cut federal funding for AIDS programs aimed at
helping them. The measure would cut the programs by $25 million a
year, down to $139 million. By JUDY HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-MEXICO-CARS (Washington) _ House members from areas along
the southwest border are calling on the Mexican government to
forego its plan to require people driving into the country beyond
15 miles to leave a deposit with border officials for their cars.
By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN.
</P>
<P>
   SECRET-EVIDENCE (Washington) _ A Palestinian immigrant
mistakenly held by the Immigration and Naturalization Service for
19 months on secret evidence accusing him of terrorism urges
Congress to outlaw such detainment. The immigrant, Hany Kiareldeen,
who was released from a Newark, N.J., jail Monday, asked lawmakers
to pass legislation barring the government from detaining
noncitizens without showing them the evidence against them. By MARK
HELM.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ It's BOO time again. Halloween is
just around the corner, bringing with it what has become a routine
argument between those who think the holiday is just for fun and
those who read darker meanings into it. Why can't we just sit back
and enjoy the silliness? By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
</TEXT>
