</P>
<P>
   SCI-FLOWER-ORIGINS (Undated) _ Scientists report solving what
Darwin described as ``the abominable mystery'' _ what are the
origins of flowering plants? The oldest surviving relative, DNA
analysis now shows, is a scrubby, primitive looking flower in New
Caledonia. By Carol Kaesuk Yoon. (900 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SEX-CHROMOSOMES (Undated) _ On the evolution of the human
sex chromosomes (which of course are far older than people). By
Nicholas Wade. (1200 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MAMMOTH-DNA (New York) _ A biologist at the American Museum
of Natural History has retrieved snippets of ancient DNA from a
mammoth. But the DNA is badly degraded and he says it would be
impossible to clone anything from it. By Nicholas Wade. (850 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Undated) _ Economic growth surged 4.8 percent in
the third quarter, higher than expected and the fastest pace this
year, as companies built up inventories and exports strengthened.
While the pace of growth raises the prospects of another increase
in interest rates by the Fed, other data showed inflationary
pressures remarkably tame. The Labor Department's Employment Cost
Index rose just 0.8 percent in the quarter following a 1.1 percent
second-quarter gain, which was the biggest in eight years. And the
GDP price deflator grew at a 0.9 percent pace in the third quarter,
down from a 1.4 percent rate the previous quarter. Stock and bond
prices surge in early trading after the reports. By Louis
Uchitelle.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   ECON-IMPACT (Undated) _ For millions of prospering Americans,
the economy has seemed stronger and more generous than the official
statistics have acknowledged. Now there is confirmation from the
government that they are right. But the revised numbers still fall
short of the prosperity achieved in earlier booms. The ``new
economy'' proclaimed by more than a few optimists is still a vision
rather than a reality. By Louis Uchitelle.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At 1:45 p.m., stocks were sharply higher.
The Dow Jones industrial was up 196 points, the S&AMP;P 500 up 36
points and the Nasdaq composite up 47 points. The 30-year Treasury
bond is up nearly a point, yielding 6.26 percent. European markets
were also higher. By Robert D. Hershey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   NORRIS-COLUMN (Undated) _ The weekly column. By Floyd Norris.
</P>
<P>
   AETNA-OUTLOOK (Undated) _ Looking at Aetna and its woes even as
it reports a 27 percent rise in third-quarter earnings, more than
expected, after it raised employers' premiums and left some
Medicare markets. Company also says that the SEC is reviewing its
accounting for some acquisitions, including the purchase of a
Prudential Insurance's health-care unit. By Milt Freudenheim.
</P>
<P>
   LA-TIMES-DISPUTE (Los Angeles) _ The publisher of The Los
Angeles Times meets with an angry staff following the disclosure
that the newspaper shared profits from a special magazine section
with the subject of the section, the Staples Center sports arena.
By Felicity Barringer.
</P>
<P>
   KOREA-DAEWOO (Tokyo) _ The long reorganization of Daewoo Group
of South Korea appears to be bogging down yet again as foreign
creditors meet in Tokyo. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
