<HEADLINE>
AUTHOR OF `JANE' STORIES RELATES TO HER CHARACTER'S LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CELINA OTTAWAY  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Melissa Bank speaks with a voice that runs from soft
(``I have a black Lab'') to fast and edgy (``follow my advice and
you'll be sleeping with a black Lab'') to paced and contemplative.
Like when she talks about love.
</P>
<P>
   Banks was in her mid-20s when she started staying late at her
advertising job to write short stories about a girl called Jane.
Twelve years and a headline-making book deal later, the Jane
stories entered the national talk fest about single angst as ``The
Girl's Guide to Hunting and Fishing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Girl's Guide to Hunting and Fishing'' debuted this year, a
collection of short stories that track Jane Rosenal from her
14-year-old tortured teen-age self through her 20s.
</P>
<P>
   The reader follows Jane through her father's death. Boyfriends
who flirt with ex-girlfriends. An older lover. Other people's
weddings. And an editorial cartoonist who is turned off when Jane
forsakes her natural sense of humor and tries to snag him with the
lure of female mystery and manipulative wiles.
</P>
<P>
   The book is autobiographical in parts _ both Jane and Bank have
doctors for fathers, both grew up in suburban Philadelphia, both
have had a relationship with an older man. But Banks says it goes
both ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``In writing a book you sort of live through everything your
characters live through,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In the first story, Jane speaks in the unmistakable voice of a
14-year-old:
</P>
<P>
   ``Julia chose her words carefully and used ones I'd never heard
spoken _ she sounded to me like she was trying out for a job as a
dictionary.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably wrote more than 1,000 pages before I found that
voice,'' Bank said.
</P>
<P>
   To find the voice _ slightly bored, but full of longing masked
in wry wit _ meant going back to being 14 again, said Bank.
</P>
<P>
   In the later stories when Jane falls for a guy, Bank found
herself falling, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was writing that last story, I was so in love with
Robert (Jane's love interest),'' the author said.
</P>
<P>
   Bank caught herself wishing Robert would call. Down in the dumps
when Jane was lonely. High when Jane was caught up in a fresh new
romance.
</P>
<P>
   Bank was in her mid-20s when she started the Jane stories.
Today, she is a successful author (think movie rights and a
six-month international book tour) who just turned 39. Love looks
different now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really thought that a man would save my life,'' Bank said,
in an interview from her home in Manhattan. ``I guess I don't
anymore. It's not that I don't think that I'll fall in love or get
married. It's just that I'm not expecting the same thing. ... I
really thought a man would change my life in a way that would help
me not have to live with myself. I thought a man is actually going
to lift you outside yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Bank isn't looking to be lifted anywhere anymore.
</P>
<P>
   She lives in a apartment building she loves in Chelsea. Her
brother and his wife live in the same building, as do several of
her best friends. The community is friendly, Bank said. People get
to know each other through their daily walks with their dogs.
</P>
<P>
   Bank's success has allowed her to write full time. She just
finished the screenplay for the book's title story, ``A Girl's
Guide to Hunting and Fishing,'' a story about Jane's experiment
with ``The Rules''-like dating advice. Bank plans to write more
fiction, but hasn't settled on a story yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm single,'' she said. ``But I guess I don't think of myself
as single. I mean I know that I am, I've got a black Lab in my bed,
but I just sort of think of it as a good life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
