<HEADLINE>
THERE'S MORE TO LIFE THAN CONVERTED RICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RUTH FANTASIA  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ For many, Uncle Ben's is the only rice there is.
And while there are plenty of reasons to recommend it _ it's easy
to cook, nutritious, fast to prepare _ converted rice isn't the
only amazing grain out there.
</P>
<P>
   A little browsing through grocery stores, specialty shops and
Asian markets yields a variety of rices to make meals more
interesting. But before deciding which rice to buy, it's best to
know a few things about rice in general.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rice grains are the fruit of the rice plant,'' write Jeffrey
Alford and Naomi Duguid in ``Seductions of Rice'' (Artisan books).
</P>
<P>
   Each stalk bears many grains of rice, each grain encased in a
protective outer layer known as the husk. Inside the husk is the
whole grain, known commonly as brown rice because the outer bran
layer of the grain gives the rice its color. Brown rice can be a
variety of hues, from light tan to mahogany. Red rice is rice that
happens to have a red bran layer.
</P>
<P>
   White rices are milled to remove the bran layer, and
subsequently the color, leaving the endosperm, which makes up most
of the grain's weight and volume. Converted rice is rice that has
been boiled prior to milling to force nutrients out of the bran
layer and into the endosperm.
</P>
<P>
   When buying any kind of rice, look for grains that are clean,
free of stones and mostly unbroken. Uncooked rice should be stored,
tightly sealed. Since the bran on unmilled rice contains oils that
can become rancid, it should be stored in the refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   Many varieties of cooked rice can be stored in the refrigerator
also, but not for more than three days. Most rices will harden
slightly if they are refrigerated after cooking but sticky rices
will become too difficult to revive the next day. Therefore, it's
best not to cook more sticky rice than you need.
</P>
<P>
   If using another type of rice, the more you cook, the better.
Leftover rice can be added to soups and stews, used in fried rice
dishes, combined with beans or used to make pilafs. To reheat
leftover rice, add 2 tablespoons liquid to each cup of cooked rice.
Cover and heat 4 to 5 minutes on top of the stove or microwave on
high power for 1 to 1 1/2 minutes per cup.
</P>
<P>
   One cup of uncooked rice will yield 2 to 3 cups of cooked rice,
depending on the variety of rice used. A single serving of plain
rice is equal to 1 cup.
</P>
<P>
   Here are descriptions of a few rices and how they are used:
</P>
<P>
   _ Arborio, the most widely available Italian rice, has short,
squat, white kernels. It's frequently used for making risotto and
as a base for other dishes. Look for arborio labeled superfino to
buy the top grade.
</P>
<P>
   _ Basmati is a milled, long-grain, needle-shaped rice that stays
separate and firm when cooked. South Asian and Indian-grown basmati
rices are more fragrant than the American-grown varieties.
</P>
<P>
   _ Brown rice is unmilled grain with the outer covering of bran
still intact. Brown rice takes longer to cook than milled rice and
has a chewier texture. Brown rice's nutty flavor combines well with
salty cheeses such as feta, crisp peppers and winter squashes.
</P>
<P>
   _ Himalayan red rice is one of the many rices with a red-colored
bran layer. Chefs like it for its unusual color. Use it in salads
and other mixtures where it can show off against other ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   _ Jasmine rice is usually one of a group of aromatic rices that
cook to a soft, clingy texture.
</P>
<P>
   _ Pecan rice is an aromatic long-grain rice harvested in
Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sticky rice is also known as glutinous rice or sweet rice
since it is often served sweetened in puddings and other desserts.
</P>
<P>
   _ Texmati rice is a basmati-type rice harvested in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   _ White rice is rice that has been milled to remove its bran.
</P>
<P>
   _ Wild rice isn't actually rice but the rice-like seed of a
certain type of grass. Though marketed as ``wild rice,'' much if it
is cultivated.
</P>
<P>
   For more information on rice, check the USA Rice Federations Web
site at www.usarice.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   RED RICE SALAD WITH NUTS AND FRUIT
</P>
<P>
   (Makes 6 servings)
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups Himalayan red rice
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup basmati or jasmine rice (see Note)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup toasted chopped pecans
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup green grapes, halved
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup red grapes, halved
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup chopped fennel
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup seeded, diced cucumber
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup pitted kalamata olives
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup dried tart cherries
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup diced scallions
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup fresh marjoram
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons balsamic vinegar
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper
</P>
<P>
   Place red rice and 3 cups water in saucepan, bring to a boil,
reduce heat, cover and simmer for 40 minutes. In a separate pan,
cook white rice according to package directions. Let both rices
stand for 5 minutes after cooking.
</P>
<P>
   Combine rice in a large bowl. Add nuts, grapes, fennel,
cucumber, olives, cherries, scallions and marjoram. Toss well.
</P>
<P>
   Add olive oil lemon juice and vinegar. Toss again. Season with
salt and pepper to taste. Chill for 1 hour before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Jasmine or basmati rice is added for visual interest. If
desired, use 2 cups red rice instead.
</P>
<P>
   _ From DaLeah's Specialty Foods, Albany, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   EGG FRIED RICE
</P>
<P>
   (Makes 2 servings)
</P>
<P>
   2 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoon peanut or vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup finely chopped ham or lean bacon
</P>
<P>
   2 large scallions, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup finely chopped carrots
</P>
<P>
   3 1/2 cups cooked rice, cold or at room temperature
</P>
<P>
   Cucumber slices for garnish
</P>
<P>
   In a small bowl, whisk the eggs, salt and soy sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Heat a wok or large skillet over high heat. When hot, add oil
and bacon, if using. When the oil is hot, add the scallions and
carrots and stir-fry for 30 seconds. Add the egg mixture and cook
another 30 seconds, using your spatula to break up the egg mixture
so it cooks evenly.
</P>
<P>
   Add the ham, if using, and the rice, using the spatula
aggressively to break up the rice, making sure that all the rice
some in contact with the wok.
</P>
<P>
   Stir-fry for 3 minutes. Turn the rice out onto 2 plates and
garnish with cucumber.
</P>
<P>
   _ From ``Seductions of Rice,'' by Jeffrey Alford and Naomi
Duguid (Artisan)
</P>
</TEXT>
