<HEADLINE>
EGGS FOR SALE: THERE'S HYPOCRICY IN THE UPROAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Bits and pieces that cannot go by without
comment: How bizarre is the uproar over the on-line sale of a bunch
of models' ovarian eggs? You would think we were a deeply ethical
and religious society instead of one that just talks a good game
and goes right on worshipping and sacrificing for its one true
deity: Money.
</P>
<P>
   How can anyone in a country where thousands of people have no
homes and thousands of others drive around in $35,000 sport utility
vehicles cry ``Foul!'' at the sale of a few dozen ovum?
</P>
<P>
   Every year Americans spend more on cosmetics ($8 billion-plus)
than it would take to provide a basic education for the illiterate
of the entire globe ($6 billion). But it's immoral for a Playboy
photographer to peddle the eggs of physically beautiful women to
anybody who chooses to pay for them?
</P>
<P>
   If we really held conception and its probable human result as
something above all mercenary taint, why isn't in vitro
fertilization free, or at least cheap, instead of an option for
only the upper-middle class and rich? In other news . . .
</P>
<P>
   Make way for the latest entry in the Tell Me Something I Didn't
Already Know hall of fame _ also known as the ``No (bleep),
Sherlock'' place.
</P>
<P>
   (A recent entry was the revelation by the National Center for
Health Statistics that _ quelle surprise! _ middle-age, suburban
white men are the least likely of all Americans to suffer from
depression or other negative moods.)
</P>
<P>
   This week, the Women's Leadership Fund announced that, in a
recent study, surveyors found that the news media are inclined to
highlight the appearance, personality and domestic life of female
political candidates more than they do male candidates. Imagine!
</P>
<P>
   Here are two examples, gleaned from 3,326 paragraphs and 891
quotations in 311 newspaper stories:
</P>
<P>
   Arizona Gov. Jane Hull was described as a ``grandmotherly
red-head.'' Elizabeth Dole was chronicled on the campaign trail in
``a red suit and matching pumps.'' Nowhere did a reporter feel the
need to mention Bill Bradley's black wing-tips and two-color
striped tie or depict John McCain as a ``patronly silver-head.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of politics, did anyone else's skin crawl at hearing
Pat Buchanan _ the doubting Thomas of our role in defeating Nazi
Germany _ bark at his Reform Party candidacy kickoff: ``You don't
know this peasant army! We have not yet begun to fight!''?
</P>
<P>
   Another spine chiller . . .
</P>
<P>
   In a long essay in the morning paper on what life will be like
as baby boomers age, psychologist Ken Dychtwald examined the
estimated 44 million American households that will be involved in
``elder care'' in the next two decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though today's business leaders and government policy
makers avoid this issue,'' he wrote, ``caring for elders and
lovingly supporting them in their final years could become the
social and economic ``sinkhole' of the 21st century.''
</P>
<P>
   Given how little our current U.S. culture already values the
infirm old _ people who can no longer carry their economic load,
let alone produce at ``optimum'' levels _ the prospect of such a
sinkhole conjures up sci-fi nightmare scenarios.
</P>
<P>
   By 2020, U.S. society may well be 100 percent converted to the
corporate model that has so enthralled our business folks and
legislators.
</P>
<P>
   What does the corporate model dictate be done with ``non-
performing assets,'' people and things that do not contribute to
maximized profit? Pronounce them ``liabilities'' and cut them
loose.
</P>
<P>
   How pretty do you think the cutting will be for the many of us
geezer millions who'll have caused what is viewed by the productive
young as ``the social and economic sinkhole of the 21st century''?
How much money do you expect they'll want to spend on caring for
and lovingly supporting us in our final years?
</P>
<P>
   Why, we'll look back on the era of marketable models' eggs and
see a humanitarian belle epoque.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
