<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-PREPARE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING READY FOR BEDTIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE HATCH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bedtime is nigh in the garden. And like other children,
gardeners facing bedtime suddenly get active.
</P>
<P>
   GardenPathways
</P>
<P>
   This gardener has been busy getting things ready for winter. And
I haven't been alone.
</P>
<P>
   Removing a pile of stones, I notice a tiny snake with a yellow
band around its neck (a deadly banded krait, no doubt, or perhaps
just a ringneck snake, common hereabouts). The pile of stones is
perfect winter cover for a small serpent. It wiggles down among the
stones, and, fearing I will accidentally cleave the poor thing, I
abandon that job.
</P>
<P>
   A job I had abandoned for too long was the removal of pots of
poinsettias that I had thrown into a corner of the deck when their
time had passed last winter. Leaves and dirt had accumulated there
over the summer, and by the time I removed the sodden mass, it
resembled the forest floor (not good to replicate on wooden decks).
It was such a close match that it attracted three red salamanders,
which wriggled about, perturbed at having been disturbed as they
prepared for their seasonal slumber. They got tossed under the
``Golden Showers'' rose, where they can burrow to their tiny
hearts' content.
</P>
<P>
   A closer encounter, at least a mammal, was with a mouse that
stood its ground in a crate I was emptying in the shed. It had
built itself a nice fluff-and-stuff nest and looked at me with
proportionately huge black eyes. It ran off as I removed the items
I needed from the crate, but I know it is back there now, curled
up, snoozing.
</P>
<P>
   In animals, shorter days and cooler nights trigger instincts to
hunker down. They trigger plants to suck nutrients from leaves,
shut them off, and let them go. They trigger the gardener to
reseed, rework, remove _ really a lot of work, the busiest time
since spring.
</P>
<P>
   The devil may be in the details of what is to be done, but even
more so in the priorities. Manuring the veggie garden is vital, but
that can be done later, much later, January even. Removing plant
detritus, especially any that might have been diseased, is more
pressing. More urgent still is digging tender bulbs that have to be
stored for the winter.
</P>
<P>
   That's because once their tops have died down and disappeared,
the only way to find them is to dig. And sure as shooting, every
trowel thrust will be right through a big, fat,
up-until-then-healthy canna rhizome.
</P>
<P>
   The caladiums are all but gone, the tuberoses are tender and
wanting no further cold, and the gladiolas would like to come in
now, please. I must get at this chore. After removing the rhizomes
and corms (it is tempting to simply call them all bulbs), they will
dry in the shade for a couple of days, then get popped in boxes
filled with that ubiquitous plastic-foam packing ``popcorn.''
They'll spend the winter in a cool, dry spot in the cellar. (I
check once or twice to make sure they're not too dried out; I can
give them a spritz of water from a spray bottle.)
</P>
<P>
   The lawn has rebounded from the drought, except for some dead
patches, which I have reseeded (rake, add topsoil, rake, scatter
seeds, water for two weeks). With autumn rains, everything has
rebounded. The garden has a certain lushness in a decadent way, for
while some plants thrive, others are yellowing and shriveling.
Rugosa and English roses are in bloom and fill the October air with
heady scent. The hibiscus, which were tall and spectacular with
giant tropical-looking pink flowers, are withering.
</P>
<P>
   It's a ``between time.'' Not winter, not summer; not on, not
off; not grow, not go.
</P>
<P>
   Except for the gardener. The veggie garden must come out.
Collapsed, slimy squash vines, brittle, dead bean stalks. Into the
compost with them. Peppers may bear a flower or two, but they'll
produce no fruit. Nor will the cucumbers. Unreasoned greed prompts
me to leave the tomatoes; those cherries may ripen.
</P>
<P>
   Garlic goes in now. Two inches deep, in good soil. First,
though, I remove the garlic missed in the harvest, for some of
those tops, too, had disappeared. Recent wet cool weather prompted
regrowth, so I dig those bulbs; they get dried and go to the
kitchen, not the cellar.
</P>
<P>
   Small boulders come out, headed for the front stone wall that,
chunk by chunk, is taking shape. A pile of boulders half up the
hill is surrounded by poison ivy, but I take care to not bruise the
foliage and get those rocks out, too.
</P>
<P>
   There is still weeding to do, plant locations to mark on my
garden plan, plant absences to note on my list of plants to
replace. All the beds must be patrolled, inspected (imprinted
mentally for long winter nights), readied for next season.
</P>
<P>
   It's bedtime, and the gardener is getting tuckered.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
