<HEADER>
A1241 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-NEWSPAPER-NOVEL-chap1     10-28 1512
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSPAPER-NOVEL-chap1-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIN'T DONE YET: THE END OF THE WORLD  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (ATTENTION EDITORS: Hearkening back to the era of Dickens and
other serial novelists, The New York Times Syndicate is offering
for purchase ``Ain't Done Yet: A Newspaper Novel About the
So-Called End of the World '' _ 29 suspenseful installments, by ROY
PETER CLARK, the Poynter Institute senior scholar and well-known
writing coach. The novel, set in St. Petersburg-Tampa, chronicles a
burnt-out investigative reporter on the trail of a cult, ``The
Watchers,'' and its charismatic leader. The novel was commissioned
as a millennium project by The New York Times Regional Newspaper
Group. Chapter One is below. The series is a wonderful way to
celebrate the millennium with your readers. For purchase
information, contact New York Times Syndicate Sales Director Bob
Farnell by phone, (212) 499-3335; fax, (212) 499-3382; or e-mail
farnellb(AT)nytimes.com.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (PLEASE NOTE: All 29 chapters have been sent to the ``l''
lifestyle category code.)
 &HT;    
 By ROY PETER CLARK 
 (Worldwide rights) 
 c.1999 Roy Peter Clark  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Crossing the Sunshine Skyway Bridge never failed to depress Max
Timlin, even on this perfect morning when squadrons of brown
pelicans flew across a sky so blue it looked digitally enhanced.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate nature!'' he screamed at the windshield and smacked the
palm of his hand against the steering wheel so hard it stung.
</P>
<P>
   Max sat in his dream car, a 1965 Mustang convertible, black with
a cream-colored interior, purchased as a consolation prize after
his second divorce. The top was down, and as he gunned the car's
famous oversized 289 engine, a balmy breeze became a windstorm that
whipped through the ravaged wasteland that once was his hair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate nature, I really do,'' he said calmly now, and clicked
on the radio.
</P>
<P>
   It was tuned to 92.1, the ``Rock Till You Drop'' station, but
instead of the Stones he got the whiny voice of Skeeter Davis,
``Don't they know, it's the end of the world? It ended when you
said goodbye.''
</P>
<P>
   He turned the tuner in disgust to National Public Radio only to
hear some windbag doctor singing the praises of another new miracle
drug to cure male impotence.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to revive a lot of dead marriages,'' said the
voice with an ugly little laugh.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too late for me,'' thought Max, whose male potency drug of
choice had always been the Apalachicola Bay oyster. Suddenly his
favorite restaurants stopped serving them or served them with
doomsday warnings: ``If you eat these oysters, you'll enjoy the
hell out of them, but then they'll make you sick and you'll die.
Still hungry?''
</P>
<P>
   As he flipped a few random stalks of dirty blond hair out of his
blue eyes, his hand brushed against the scar on his forehead, a
result of a surgical procedure to remove skin cancer, basal cell
carcinoma. It was his sixth, nothing more than a disfiguring
nuisance, he thought, adding some twists and turns to the road map
of his face.
</P>
<P>
   His dermatologist would be furious to know that Max was riding
with the top down, but Max would not deprive himself of one of his
few remaining pleasures. He never worshipped the sun, but as a
teen-ager he had suffered from pizza-face acne, a condition his
parents hoped to ameliorate with weekly treatments under a sun
lamp.
</P>
<P>
   ``All that burning and peeling may have helped your acne,'' said
Dr. Fishbine, some 35 years later, ``but they also gave you skin
cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't blame it on the hole in the ozone, said the mischievous
doctor, blame it on your parents.
</P>
<P>
   Fishbine explained how years ago there were these shoe stores
called ``X-Ray'' shoes. You'd put your new shoes on and then slip
your feet into an X-ray machine to see how the shoes fit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing we don't have a generation of people whose toes
are falling off,'' said Fishbine. ``How many things have we thought
were really good for us,'' he said, ``and they turned out to be
really bad?''
</P>
<P>
   Max thought about a generation of men taking male potency drugs.
Who could predict what one day would fall off?
</P>
<P>
   He was at the top of the Skyway now, and his mood darkened.
Forget the view of the Gulf of Mexico flowing into Tampa Bay, and
forget the bright white triangles of sailboats, followed by
dolphins at play. All he could remember now _ he shuddered when he
thought about it _ was that this was the spot in 1980 that the old
bridge was hit by a huge oil tanker.
</P>
<P>
   Blinded by gale-force winds, the harbor pilot steered the Summit
Venture into the Skyway, a sledgehammer crushing a sculpture made
of toothpicks. Much of the towering bridge was destroyed, and 35
people, most of them on a Greyhound bus, rode over the jagged end
of the bridge on a collective bungee jump without a cord, more than
175 feet down to their deaths.
</P>
<P>
   It took years and millions of dollars, but they built a
beautiful new bridge, one with a system of bumpers to protect
against runaway tankers.
</P>
<P>
   The bridge was so attractive, in fact, that more than 60 people
had killed themselves jumping off of it, nine in the last six
months alone. They were young and old, rich and poor, black and
white, straight and gay, drunk and sober, all coming and parking
and climbing the rail and looking down and letting go and falling
into that eternity or abyss that, in the end, is the only equality
the world offers.
</P>
<P>
   The last guy to jump tried to take his dog with him, but the
Rottweiler, named Daisy, survived. Max had tried to adopt that dog,
but the county didn't think, with his lifestyle, that he could give
the dog a good home. Why couldn't he get that Skeeter Davis song
out of his head?
</P>
<P>
   As he crossed the bridge north into St. Petersburg, he couldn't
rid himself of a pervasive sense of dread that the good things in
his life were behind him, that his hopes and aspirations had
expired, that he was driving off the 18th tee after playing a
miserable round.
</P>
<P>
   He was bright enough to recognize these as middle-aged angst, he
knew the Mustang was part of that, but they combined now in 1999,
with the end of a decade, the end of a century, the end of a
millennium. He was tired of things ending: his youth, his
marriages, his reporting job in Sarasota.
</P>
<P>
   That's why he was headed to St. Pete Beach, to meet a man named
K.J. Banks, a new editor with the Florida Sun, a newspaper Max very
much admired. Max had received an e-mail message the day before
asking him to meet Banks at the Gold Coin on a stretch of beach
called Pass-a-Grille, where, legend has it, pirates once landed to
grill their meat and drink their rum. The pirates were replaced by
tourists, the meat by grouper and shrimp, the rum by margaritas and
pina coladas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Meet me at 11,'' said the message. ``I've heard good things
about your work and know you are at loose ends. We can have a late
breakfast or early lunch. _ K.J. Banks.''
</P>
<P>
   Max had been speeding, and the traffic was light, so he arrived
early. He remembered the Gold Coin from years ago, a delightful
little hole-in-the-wall now replaced by a grotesque three-story bar
with connecting restaurants, lounges and discos.
</P>
<P>
   He sat at a patio table overlooking the Gulf and waved at the
sea gulls diving at scraps left behind by previous customers. Max
pointed his finger and cocked his thumb at one and made a sound as
if he was firing a gun. K-choww! The noise scared the gull away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nice shot,'' said a woman's voice. Max turned and looked up to
see the figure of a tall woman standing between him and a blazing
sun. He shaded his eyes to block out the sunlight not already
eclipsed by a crown of dark wavy hair. She stepped aside so Max
could see her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hello, Max, I'm K.J. Banks. My friends call me Kate.''
</P>
<P>
   From experience, she knew that he was expecting a man, an
old-fart of an editor with patches on his sleeves and nicotine
stains on his fingers, or maybe one of those young corporate types
with the hundred-dollar haircuts and thousand-dollar suits. She
enjoyed his surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Max stood to shake her hand, which met his firmly. She looked
like someone famous, Susan Sarandon, maybe, but not the voluptuous
Atlantic City lemon-bath model. The woman before him was his age,
perhaps, but not _ like him _ a burnt-out shell of a human being.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in a tan pantsuit over a white silk blouse, she looked
healthy and successful and could project both intelligence and
humor in a single ironic smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've come with a proposition,'' she said, still shaking his
hand, ``and I know you won't disappoint me.''
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   NEXT INSTALLMENT: RETURN OF THE ATOMIC MONSTERS
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
