<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 14:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1242 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-NEWSPAPER-NOVEL-chap2     10-28 1375
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSPAPER-NOVEL-chap2-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIN'T DONE YET: RETURN OF THE ATOMIC MONSTERS  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (ATTENTION EDITORS: Hearkening back to the era of Dickens and
other serial novelists, The New York Times Syndicate is offering
for purchase ``Ain't Done Yet: A Newspaper Novel About the
So-Called End of the World '' _ 29 suspenseful installments, by ROY
PETER CLARK, the Poynter Institute senior scholar and well-known
writing coach. The novel, set in St. Petersburg-Tampa, chronicles a
burnt-out investigative reporter on the trail of a cult, ``The
Watchers,'' and its charismatic leader. The novel was commissioned
as a millennium project by The New York Times Regional Newspaper
Group. Chapter two is below. The series is a wonderful way to
celebrate the millennium with your readers. For purchase
information, contact New York Times Syndicate Sales Director Bob
Farnell by phone, (212) 499-3335; fax, (212) 499-3382; or e-mail
farnellb(AT)nytimes.com.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (PLEASE NOTE: All 29 chapters have been sent to the ``l''
lifestyle category code.)
 &HT;    
 By ROY PETER CLARK 
 (Worldwide rights) 
 c.1999 Roy Peter Clark  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   ``Do you like the movies, Max?'' said Kate Banks as if she were
going to ask him on a date.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed like a trick question, and he wondered if there was a
right answer. Maybe she was going to offer him a job as a movie
critic. He had filled in years ago for an aging critic recovering
from retinal surgery.
</P>
<P>
   At first Max had liked the idea of taking this little vacation
from real journalism, until the Christmas week he had to view 12
films _ no, not films, movies _ in six days. It turned his eyes to
black holes, his mind to mush, and his fingers to stone, and it
made him increasingly cranky about each movie, so that the ones he
saw early in the week got five stars, down to three, down to one,
down to a minus 2 for a Barbra Streisand flick, a grade his editor
refused to register.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll just run the wire synopsis,'' she said, and never asked
him to review again.
</P>
<P>
   Max later came to see that time as an emblem for his life, that
experiences once chosen freely and with joy became soured by
obligation. It had happened with his two marriages and a cycle of
newspaper jobs. He wondered why this woman _ he was suddenly
intimidated by her _ would be interested in him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I like the movies, especially the old ones, so I mostly
rent.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What's your favorite movie, Max?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always liked the early Bond flicks, but I'd be hard
pressed to choose between `Goldfinger' and `Thunderball.' How about
you?''
</P>
<P>
   ``My three older brothers would take me to the movies almost
every Saturday, and they liked the horror and monster movies, and
they would scare me to death, so that I would be crouching down
between the seats and looking with one eye through the cracks. My
favorite was `Godzilla,' the one with 10,000 Japanese actors and
extras and Raymond Burr.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The big lizard is back.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I know, Max, that's what bothers me.''
</P>
<P>
   She stopped talking for a minute and took a dragon-sized bite
from a blackened grouper sandwich, and wiped a stream of sauce from
the corner of her lip with the back of her hand. Max decided that
he liked her, even though he could not imagine where this
conversation was going or what she wanted of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Japanese released `Godzilla' in 1954,'' she said, ``a
decade after we dropped the atomic bomb on them.''
</P>
<P>
   She reminded Max that the movie was about a prehistoric monster
brought back to life by the testing of hydrogen bombs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched all the sequels, Max: `Godzilla vs. the Thing,'
`Godzilla vs. King Kong,' `Godzilla vs. the Sea Monster,' `Godzilla
vs. the Smog Monster,' `Rodan,' `Mothra,' I couldn't get enough.
When I got older, my friends told themselves I was being weird or
ironic, that I thought movies dubbed badly into English were funny.
But they weren't funny to me, Max. They weren't funny because
underneath all the rubber monster suits, they were all about
Hiroshima and mushroom clouds and radiation and mutations and, the
destruction of cities and civilizations, and the end of the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   Not knowing what to say, Max took a long slug from his glass of
ice tea and leaned forward as if about to hear the solution to some
ancient puzzle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Godzilla's back, Max. You can't go to the freakin' movies
anymore without something destroying the world. If it isn't
lizards, it's dinosaurs. It if it isn't dinosaurs, it's aliens. If
it isn't aliens, it's comets, or meteorites, or asteroids. Next
thing it'll be hemorrhoids.''
</P>
<P>
   Max coughed and let out a laugh, and Kate Banks was laughing
too, and she took off her sunglasses, and revealed eyes so dark you
couldn't make out the pupils. She was close to his age, the
wrinkles around her eyes told that story, but the eyes themselves
were bright and youthful. This woman, 30 years ago, might have
inspired Van Morrison to write a song.
</P>
<P>
   ``What about `Titanic?''' he asked. ``A nice, sweet love
story.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Forget about the love story, Max. The ocean and the dark sky
full of stars _ that's the universe. The ship is the world. The
poor people are in the bottom, the rich on top. But nothing can
save them. Not hope, ambition, money, or technology. The ship goes
down, Max. The world goes down.''
</P>
<P>
   She took a breath and changed her tone, back from the doomsday
prophet to the teaching editor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're sitting here on the beach Max, and God has not made a
more perfect day, and it's the middle of 1999, the last year of a
decade, the last year of a century, the last year of a millennium.
Do you know what that word means, Max, I mean the Latin roots?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, I was an altar boy once. It means a thousand years.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And how about the word millenarian?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Is that someone who is a thousand years old or someone who
makes women's hats?''
</P>
<P>
   She knew he was joking.
</P>
<P>
   ``A millenarian is someone who is waiting for the world to end.
Who looks for a date like the year 2000 and expects the end will
come, that history, time, life as we know it, is over. In the eyes
of these people, any bad things that happen are signs of the last
days. Floods. Famines. War. A bear market. A shooting star. Or Ken
Starr.''
</P>
<P>
   To his surprise, she reached over across the table and grabbed
one of his hands with her hand, pressed her nails into his flesh
and looked him straight in the eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes these people are not just waiting for things to
happen. They want the world to end, and they can't wait for God to
make it happen. They're ready to take action themselves. They lead
others astray.''
</P>
<P>
   She read his look.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not paranoid, Max. I know what I'm talking about. It
happened with Jonestown and Waco and Oklahoma City. And I think
it's happening again _ and I think it's happening here _ now.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you want from me, Kate?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I know your work, Max. You're not afraid of dangerous stories.
You covered the narco-terrorists in Miami. And everyone knows that
you were responsible for bringing to justice the church burners in
Alabama.''
</P>
<P>
   Max shook his head modestly. Like other reporters he found it
hard to give or receive praise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have you ever heard of a group called The Watchers?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Weren't they a rock group from the British Invasion?''
</P>
<P>
   ``You're thinking of The Searchers. They did `Needles and Pins.'
The Watchers are an international group that set up shop in town
about two years ago, and word is they are recruiting young people,
and that their numbers are growing. I want you to investigate them
for me. Here's everything you'll need to get started.''
</P>
<P>
   She reached into her purse and pulled out a silver key and a
single black computer disk and placed them carefully in his hand.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   NEXT INSTALLMENT: A SNAKE IN THE GRASS
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
