<HEADER>
A1243 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-NEWSPAPER-NOVEL-chap3     10-28 1504
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSPAPER-NOVEL-chap3-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIN'T DONE YET: A SNAKE IN THE GRASS  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (ATTENTION EDITORS: Hearkening back to the era of Dickens and
other serial novelists, The New York Times Syndicate is offering
for purchase ``Ain't Done Yet: A Newspaper Novel About the
So-Called End of the World '' _ 29 suspenseful installments, by ROY
PETER CLARK, the Poynter Institute senior scholar and well-known
writing coach. The novel, set in St. Petersburg-Tampa, chronicles a
burnt-out investigative reporter on the trail of a cult, ``The
Watchers,'' and its charismatic leader. The novel was commissioned
as a millennium project by The New York Times Regional Newspaper
Group. Chapter three is below. The series is a wonderful way to
celebrate the millennium with your readers. For purchase
information, contact New York Times Syndicate Sales Director Bob
Farnell by phone, (212) 499-3335; fax, (212) 499-3382; or e-mail
farnellb(AT)nytimes.com.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (PLEASE NOTE: All 29 chapters have been sent to the ``l''
lifestyle category code.)
 &HT;    
 By ROY PETER CLARK 
 (Worldwide rights) 
 c.1999 Roy Peter Clark  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   LAST INSTALLMANT: Max and Kate discuss why every movie seems to
be about the end of the world, then Kate offers Max a job
investigating a millennium cult called The Watchers.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   It was almost a perfect morning, and no one was more surprised
at his cheeriness than Max Timlin. He was not a morning person _ or
an afternoon person, or an evening person, for that matter. But on
this summer morning, his coffee was strong and sweet, the breeze
off the Gulf was comforting, and an item in the morning paper made
him laugh:
</P>
<P>
   Television evangelist Curtis Woodson criticized the city of
Orlando for permitting gays and lesbians to carry rainbow-colored
banners, symbolizing diversity, in a Fourth of July parade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm no prophet,'' said Woodson, ``but I would not be waving
those flags in God's face if I were you. It'll bring about
terrorist bombs; it'll bring earthquakes, tornadoes and possibly a
meteor!''
</P>
<P>
   Max did not like Orlando much _ too much traffic, and too many
mouse ears. He chuckled at the idea of a meteor striking a theme
park, and how quickly it would take Disney to turn the huge crater
into a new attraction.
</P>
<P>
   He was still laughing _ he was almost giddy _ as he stood,
stretched, and leaned forward on the balcony rail. He looked to the
left and could see the Skyway Bridge, close enough to make out tiny
cars heading south.
</P>
<P>
   One week ago, he lived on that side of the bridge, but now he
had a new place on St. Pete Beach. Kate Banks, editor of the
Florida Sun, had handed him a key to a condo on a stretch of sand
called Land's End.
</P>
<P>
   It was a gorgeous place, with cathedral ceilings, polished wood
floors, and expensive Florida art on the walls. He had never lived
anyplace like it. The place had two huge bedrooms, each with a
bath, one bath with a hot tub, a fancy office, a well-stocked
kitchen, and a living room extended onto a balcony with a
fifth-story view of the Gulf of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   If the world was about to end, this was the way to go.
</P>
<P>
   That thought slapped him sober, like the old after-shave
commercial, and reminded him of why he was here. He had accepted a
strange proposal from Kate Banks, to investigate a group of
doomsday types called The Watchers. That was not so strange _ he'd
investigated and written about wackos and Wacos before. He
considered it a specialty. But Kate had added some stipulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want you to work out of my beach condo, not the newspaper
office. I live in a great old house not far from the paper. You can
phone me there. Only two people at the paper besides me will know
you are on the job: a photographer and a researcher. Here are their
names and numbers. You'll love working with them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why the secrecy, Kate?''
</P>
<P>
   ``You may remember that we won a Pulitzer in the 1970s for
covering the activities of the Science of God cult. They
infiltrated the newspaper. Stole files. Gathered dirt on the
reporters and editors, not a hard thing to do as it turns out, and
are still, after all these years, a pain in the butt. So just think
of us as a little gun-shy.''
</P>
<P>
   Max was not to come into the Florida Sun at any time. He could
access the newspaper's files and records electronically. The condo
office was completely wired. He could call Kate with any special
needs, and she would visit him once a week to check on him, and to
deliver his pay _ in cash.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed more than cautious to Max; it seemed paranoid. But he
was not about to complain. He had a wallet bursting with money,
paradise for a pad, and, most important, a story to cover.
</P>
<P>
   Max reached into a desk drawer for an unlabeled black disk and
slid it into the slot in his computer. He called up a file named
``Leader.'' A color image slowly rolled from top to bottom until it
filled the screen and sharpened into focus. It was the face of a
man in his early 40s, perhaps a bit older. He had black wavy hair
atop an oval face. The jaw was strong, a cleft in the chin. The
eyes were narrow, deep-set, and dark brown, framed by dark brows.
The complexion was very pale, almost white.
</P>
<P>
   The full effect was severe, even threatening, except for the
smile, which was wide and inviting, so wide you were tempted to
count the teeth.
</P>
<P>
   A text file revealed that this was Raoul Glaber, sometimes
called Roy Glaber, the founder and leader of The Watchers. There
was little known about Glaber outside of his association with his
religious group. He seemed almost like a man without a history. He
had turned down many requests for interviews, and became
increasingly reclusive, even as the work of The Watchers became
more public.
</P>
<P>
   Kate Banks was right. This was, by all its manifestations, a
millenarian group. From its creation, in 1977, Glaber had targeted
the year 2000 as climactic and apocalyptic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The day is coming,'' he had written in an early pamphlet
``when the world as we know it will be shaken to its foundations.
The house of this world will crumble so that a new house can be
created. We will watch for the signs of the new world. We watch for
signs in the heavens, and for signs in the hearts of men. We, The
Watchers, will be ready when the Great Day comes. The date of the
Great Day is no mystery, but comes into our sight, only 23 years
down a narrow road which will end at a bridge which will cross from
a dark, decaying world into a bright new one.''
</P>
<P>
   Max clicked on an audio file enabling him to hear the voice of
Raoul Glaber.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will come as a thief in the night,'' the voice said,
evoking what sounded like a biblical text familiar to Max. ``Woe
unto you who are working in the fields. Woe unto you if you are
great with child. Woe unto you who are not watching and waiting,
waiting and watching. For only those who watch will be ready, and
only those who are ready will cross over to a world remade. A world
washed in water. A world washed in fire. A world washed in blood.''
</P>
<P>
   Max was mesmerized. His mind carried him back to a fifth-grade
class in Catholic School when Brother Brian Mahoney played
recordings of speeches by Hitler. Max didn't understand German, of
course, but the rising and falling intonations of the speaker
hypnotized and energized at the same time. When Der Fuhrer reached
a crescendo, the crowd roared _ how many people would it take to
raise such a cheer? When the recording ended, it snapped Max out of
what seemed like a trance.
</P>
<P>
   Then Brother Brian explained that this man had used his gift of
oratory for an evil purpose, to kill millions and millions of
people he hated: Jews, Gypsies, political opponents, homosexuals,
the physically handicapped.
</P>
<P>
   Brother Brian turned off the lights. For a dramatic minute the
room remained dark until he clicked on a slide projector. On a
white wall flashed image after image from something he called a
``concentration camp'': piles of skeletal bodies ready for plowing
into a mass grave, soldiers pointing rifles at terrified children,
naked women, old and young, being herded into a brick buildings,
living corpses standing behind barbed wire.
</P>
<P>
   Raoul Glaber's oratory had the same mesmerizing effect as
Hitler's_ but with one important difference: Glaber didn't sound as
if he were speaking to thousands upon thousands. His voice was not
thunder, but a zephyr. He sounded as if he were talking to one
person. He sounded, Max thought, as if he were whispering in your
ear. The Serpent in the Garden.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   NEXT INSTALLMENT: THE SIDEWALK SAVIOR
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Roy Peter Clark is a senior scholar and an associate at the
Poynter Institute for Media Studies. He was commissioned to do this
newspaper novel as part of the New York Times Regional Newspaper
Group's Celebrate 2000 project.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
