<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 14:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1244 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-NEWSPAPER-NOVEL-chap4     10-28 1694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSPAPER-NOVEL-chap4-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIN'T DONE YET: THE SIDEWALK SAVIOR  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (ATTENTION EDITORS: Hearkening back to the era of Dickens and
other serial novelists, The New York Times Syndicate is offering
for purchase ``Ain't Done Yet: A Newspaper Novel About the
So-Called End of the World '' _ 29 suspenseful installments, by ROY
PETER CLARK, the Poynter Institute senior scholar and well-known
writing coach. The novel, set in St. Petersburg-Tampa, chronicles a
burnt-out investigative reporter on the trail of a cult, ``The
Watchers,'' and its charismatic leader. The novel was commissioned
as a millennium project by The New York Times Regional Newspaper
Group. Chapter four is below. The series is a wonderful way to
celebrate the millennium with your readers. For purchase
information, contact New York Times Syndicate Sales Director Bob
Farnell by phone, (212) 499-3335; fax, (212) 499-3382; or e-mail
farnellb(AT)nytimes.com.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (PLEASE NOTE: All 29 chapters have been sent to the ``l''
lifestyle category code.)
 &HT;    
 By ROY PETER CLARK 
 (Worldwide rights) 
 c.1999 Roy Peter Clark  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   LAST INSTALLMENT: Max begins his research on The Watchers, and
their charismatic and menacing leader, Raoul Glaber.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   Max Timlin couldn't remember a better meal, or a more congenial
partner, Ralph Rizzo, an iconoclastic Catholic priest with an
appetite for Cuban food. Their hunger brought them this Saturday
night to a favorite eatery, No Dinero, in the historic Ybor City
district of Tampa.
</P>
<P>
   Father Rizzo was one of several friends Max had met in St. Pete,
people he had written about while working in Gainesville, Miami and
Sarasota.
</P>
<P>
   Although he was known for his dogged investigations, tracking
down bad guys, Max was no cynic. He knew that cynic was the Greek
word for ``dog.'' It was true, Max liked dogs, and sometimes felt
like a 14-year-old bloodhound, his best hunting days behind him,
but with a nose that could still pick up a scent.
</P>
<P>
   But Max was no cynic. In his own view of things, he was a
skeptic. A cynic could not believe that human beings were capable
of goodness. A skeptic doubted they were, but was always willing to
be surprised.
</P>
<P>
   ``If your mother says she loves you,'' Max would quote an old
newspaper saying, ``check it out.'' But if it checks out, send her
flowers.
</P>
<P>
   There were no saints and no heroes, thought Max, but there were
people of virtue and they were worth writing about. Sometimes he
had to fight his editors to make sure the story didn't get buried
deep in the paper, with the tire ads. But Max was stubborn and
liked the challenge of going against the grain.
</P>
<P>
   After a series of stories, ``Breach of Trust,'' came out about
priests and ministers who molested children, Max did a profile of
Father Ralph Rizzo, who in Max's words, ``combined the intellect
and sensibilities of a college metaphysics professor with the guts
and instincts of a union leader.''
</P>
<P>
   Father Ralph, Brooklyn-born and the son of a longshoreman and a
schoolteacher, had abandoned university teaching and scholarly
writing for community organizing. He preached that there were only
two ways of reforming institutions: ``through the ear or up the
rear.'' He was good at both approaches.
</P>
<P>
   In five years, he had set up a free medical clinic, a food bank,
an AIDS hospice, a last-chance school for dropouts and an emergency
shelter for runaway teens. One television reporter dubbed him
``Father Teresa.'' Ralph bloodied his nose. This act won him
national attention, and no few admirers. Father Ralph was 62 years
old, wore a halo of curly, snow-white hair, and weighed about 140
pounds, but you didn't mess with him. He was Billy Martin in a
cassock.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ralph, you ever heard of The Watchers?'' Max and Ralph began
their postprandial stroll down Seventh Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doomsday cult, no doubt about it,'' said Ralph. ``We've seen
kids at the shelter with Watcher T-shirts, even one with a `W'
tattooed on his arm. It's a sin to lure young people into something
like that, Max. These children need comfort and hope. When you're
16 and addicted to crack and HIV positive and living on the street,
it's pretty easy to believe that the world is coming to an end.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you believe it, Ralph? I mean that something big is about
to happen. In the year 2000?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Max. Read the gospel. Jesus says the Kingdom is now. If you
don't believe me, ask the Man Himself.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Who?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Jesus.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Where?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Over there.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, Max looked down the street to see a man
surprisingly like Jesus in appearance, long brown hair and full
beard, a robe made of rough tan cloth, tied at the waist with a
rope. The man wore sandals. And, here was the real tip-off. He was
carrying a cross.
</P>
<P>
   The cross bore written messages, on both the vertical and cross
beams. ``Unless a man be born again in water and the spirit,''
``The Kingdom of God is at hand,'' and ``God so loved the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Behind him, on the long street in the heart of Ybor spread a
scene that was ripe for redemption. Hundreds of tourists,
teen-agers, music lovers and street people patrolled a district
that tried hard for a Bourbon Street effect, but came up
considerably short.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Ybor was without its charms. Once the bustling center
of the Cuban-American cigar industry, Ybor still projected a quirky
ethnicity, including Latin dance clubs and wonderful little
restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Max and Father Ralph were sluggish from a feast of chicken and
rice, washed down with too much sangria, and polished off with a
delicious custard desert, and some sips of strong Cuban coffee.
</P>
<P>
   But as they made their way down the street, they walked past
strip clubs and tattoo parlors and thrift stores that gave the
place a seedier, more Bohemian flair. Father Ralph loved it.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the people Jesus would be hanging with,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On one corner stood a nameless shop that sold holy objects,
blending traditional Catholic candles and sacramentals with the
trappings of voodoo and Santeria.
</P>
<P>
   Across the street was a nudie bar called Anytime Atoll, a garish
storefront awash in neon lights the color of lilacs. A young woman,
her hair dyed shoe-polish black and packed into a black-leather
body suit, stood, looking bored, in the doorway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would you look at that,'' said Father Ralph. ``That young girl
has implants. I'd bet my collar on it.'' He wasn't wearing one.
``God gave that woman a beautiful body, and look whats she's done
with it.''
</P>
<P>
   This was the kind of offbeat perspective that Max found charming
about Ralph. In fact, an evening with Father Ralph was enough to
tempt even as lapsed a Catholic as Max back into the fold. ``Check
this out, Ralph.''
</P>
<P>
   A framed newspaper clipping in the window reminded passers-by
that this club was the home of an exotic dancer named Thrill Hills,
a woman who boasted a 65-25-35 figure.
</P>
<P>
   A Tampa man was suing her for a ``whiplash injury incurred at a
bachelor party, where the curvaceous Ms. Hills allegedly whacked
him on the head with the most pendulous parts of her anatomy.''
Even Ralph was speechless.
</P>
<P>
   Down the block they stopped at a shop called The Branding Iron,
which might best be described as a tattoo and body piercing
factory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baptism leaves an indelible mark upon the soul,'' said Ralph.
But why would someone want to leave indelible marks upon the body?
``Perhaps I can understand it in the young, given their desire to
set themselves apart as members of a group, but look at that.''
</P>
<P>
   They stared at a photograph in the front window _ three women of
three different generations with matching rose tattoos on their
butts. A caption said they were grandmother, mother and daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Compared to all this, a sidewalk Jesus seemed almost normal, so
Max and Ralph rushed over to greet him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I make a hundred dollars a night, plus tips,'' said the man,
who, after brief conversation, said his real name was Jacob
Coleman. He wore Birkenstock sandals. ``I'm Jewish,'' he offered.
</P>
<P>
   ``So was Jesus,'' said Father Ralph, ``a good Jewish boy, real
name Joshua, with a wonderful Jewish mother.''
</P>
<P>
   Just then it happened. The front doors of The Branding Iron
burst open, almost as if there had been an explosion, and a group
of about a dozen young people rocketed out, so loud and so animated
they seemed part of the same reptilian organism, like Medusa's
head.
</P>
<P>
   The overall impression was black and white, boys and girls,
shaved heads, pierced nostrils, and serpentine tattoos. One carried
a music blaster, and it played something that sounded less like
music than a jagged, metallic vibration. A few toted skateboards
and roared, clumsily, into the street toward the three of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Watch out, hippy dude,'' shouted what might have been the
leader and clipped the sidewalk Jesus at the ankles. Jacob Coleman
fell backwards and hit his head against the pavement. Max and
Father Ralph twisted out of the way to avoid the collision.
</P>
<P>
   A girl in the back of the pack held something that looked like a
toy rifle _ a super squirt gun maybe _ and pointed it at the prone
figure. Pop. Pop. Pop. Three paint balls hit Jesus in the chest,
soaking his robe in red. Just as quickly they turned the corner and
were gone.
</P>
<P>
   A figure stood on a nearby roof with a video camera and took in
the scene through the viewfinder. There, in the harsh street
lights, the camera captured the image of Father Ralph cradling the
body of the sidewalk savior in his arms, the poor man's Pieta. And
on one knee beside them, carrying the fallen cross over one
shoulder, was a dazed Max Timlin.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   NEXT INSTALLMENT: DANCING IN THE DARK
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Roy Peter Clark is a senior scholar and an associate at the
Poynter Institute for Media Studies. He was commissioned to do this
newspaper novel as part of the New York Times Regional Newspaper
Group's Celebrate 2000 project.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
