<HEADER>
A1252 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-NEWSPAPER-NOVEL-chap1     10-28 1513
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSPAPER-NOVEL-chap11-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIN'T DONE YET: WALKIN' THE DOG  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (ATTENTION EDITORS: Hearkening back to the era of Dickens and
other serial novelists, The New York Times Syndicate is offering
for purchase ``Ain't Done Yet: A Newspaper Novel About the
So-Called End of the World '' _ 29 suspenseful installments, by ROY
PETER CLARK, the Poynter Institute senior scholar and well-known
writing coach. The novel, set in St. Petersburg-Tampa, chronicles a
burnt-out investigative reporter on the trail of a cult, ``The
Watchers,'' and its charismatic leader. The novel was commissioned
as a millennium project by The New York Times Regional Newspaper
Group. Chapter 11 is below. The series is a wonderful way to
celebrate the millennium with your readers. For purchase
information, contact New York Times Syndicate Sales Director Bob
Farnell by phone, (212) 499-3335; fax, (212) 499-3382; or e-mail
farnellb(AT)nytimes.com.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (PLEASE NOTE: All 29 chapters have been sent to the ``l''
lifestyle category code.)
 &HT;    
 By ROY PETER CLARK 
 (Worldwide rights) 
 c.1999 Roy Peter Clark  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   LAST INSTALLMENT: Max meets up with Father Ralph and questions
the priest about the millennium, but Ralph dispels a doomsday
attitude with acts of kindness.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   As Max cruised down Gulf Boulevard through Madeira Beach and
toward Treasure Island, he glanced down and noticed the odometer
had, some miles ago, crossed the 99,000-mile barrier. He reached
out and patted the dashboard of the old Mustang as if he were
stroking a pony's mane.
</P>
<P>
   Although exhausted from his encounter with Father Ralph, Max
decided to keep another appointment he had made for that afternoon.
He turned toward the beach and stopped at a lovely house with
weathered shingles and a xeriscaped yard. Dr. Evelyn Hamilton lived
here, a retired veterinarian.
</P>
<P>
   Max had read in the Florida Sun that this kind woman had adopted
Daisy, the Rottweiler who survived a fall from the Skyway Bridge.
Daisy's former owner, quite deranged, had tossed her over on his
own journey toward the big deep.
</P>
<P>
   ``Call me Evie,'' she insisted and extended her hand. She was a
lovely woman with dark eyes and silver hair who had been chosen
from among more than 100 suitors to take care of Daisy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can always tell how a person will treat people by how they
treat animals,'' she said. Daisy was doing fine, except for the
slightest limp, the effects of neurological damage to one of her
paws.
</P>
<P>
   Max lowered himself to one knee, reached into a bag and took out
a handful of gourmet doggie yummies. Daisy devoured these and
nuzzled Max's hand for more. The next half hour was spent on the
rug with generous amounts of ear rubbing, back scratching and
slobbery kisses.
</P>
<P>
   Evie told Max he could visit any time. He congratulated her on
her fine work and said he'd like to write Daisy's story some day.
He waved from his Mustang _ the top was down _ and drove happily
down the beach until his thoughts turned to the young man who had
ended his own life and wanted to take his dog with him.
</P>
<P>
   What had she done for him but be a faithful companion even into
the abyss? Did he think he needed her in the afterlife like some
Egyptian pharaoh? Could he not stand the thought of someone else
taking care of her? Maybe God watched over the sparrows and the
Rottweilers, the lilies of the field and the Daisies. Maybe that
cagey Father Ralph was getting to him.
</P>
<P>
   Back on the road, Max heard an amusing story on National Public
Radio. A man entered a betting emporium in London, where they'll
lay odds on almost anything: ``What are the chances my 5-year-old
son will grow up to play for England in the World Cup?'' A 100,000
to 1, minimum bet 100 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   But one man wanted to bet 1,000 pounds that the world would end
on Jan. 1, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sorry,'' explained the manager, ``we can't take a bet where we
couldn't pay the winner.''
</P>
<P>
   The bettor looked puzzled. ``If the world did end, how would we
pay you?''
</P>
<P>
   That bit of British honesty _ along with his visit to Daisy _
lifted Max's spirits, a feeling that intensified when he thought
again of Angela Powers, a young girl so beautiful and strong, whose
physical presence projected a sense of purity and purpose
inconsistent with her attachment to Raoul Glaber and The Watchers.
</P>
<P>
   As he made his final turn toward Land's End, his thoughts moved
to Kate Banks. He needed to see her again to report on all he had
learned about the Watchers and _ more urgently _ to test whether
there was anything between them.
</P>
<P>
   Max clicked the radio to a music station, only to hear Michael
Bolton's overwrought version of ``When a Man Loves a Woman.'' He
took it as a bad sign. He changed stations and a true miracle
occurred: It was Percy Sledge's original version of the same song.
</P>
<P>
   Inspired, he pressed his foot on the accelerator and, in the
three minutes it took to finish the song, he looked in his rearview
mirror to see the lights of a police car. He pulled over and a
tall, imposing officer with ebony skin approached the Mustang.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sorry if I was speeding, officer, I ...''
</P>
<P>
   ``Not to worry about that, Mr. Timlin. You are Max Timlin. Or
have you just stolen his car?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I'm him. I mean he.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Please, sir, could you follow me?''
</P>
<P>
   More curious than fearful, Max followed the police car for about
a mile, then turned down a side street in front of a tiny
restaurant called Red Beans. The officer held the front door open
without a smile and Max walked in, his eyes adjusting to the
darkness. Finally, at an isolated corner table he saw a familiar
figure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Max, my man, what the hell are you doin' muckin' around with
The Watchers?''
</P>
<P>
   The question was so direct and had such conviction behind it, it
caught Max off guard. He decided on a counterattack.
</P>
<P>
   ``How the hell do you know that, Sam? You been followin' me?''
</P>
<P>
   Sam was Samson Lockhart, one of the top cops in the state of
Florida. Max had written a long profile of Lockhart, who had
arrived in St. Pete from New Orleans, La., to become its first
African-American chief of police.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart was the son and grandson of police officers, and had
been credited with easing tensions between the police and the black
community.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have to follow you, little brother. We been watchin'
the Watchers. Special investigative unit. We've got you on tape in
Ybor City when those kids knocked over the Jesus guy, and we got
you during the latest initiation ceremony.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart let out a big laugh. He was almost 6-foot-5, and the
laugh echoed through the empty restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Funniest thing I ever seen. You looked like a candy-ass
dressed in that biker stuff. But the lady you were with looked
mighty fine. Who was that?''
</P>
<P>
   ``A woman named Sherry ... '' Max regretted it as soon as the
name left his lips.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sherry Darling? So you workin' for the Florida Sun now?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Not exactly, I ...''
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you not exactly work for a newspaper? Do you hear
that?'' he turned to the other officer, ``He doesn't exactly work
for the Sun. Well, who the hell are you workin' with, then? I know
you ain't datin' Sherry Darling because she's a bright and talented
woman who wouldn't be seen dead with a burnt out old dog like
you.''
</P>
<P>
   Max couldn't bring himself to laugh under this harangue though
he wanted to. ``Sam, I can't tell you any ...''
</P>
<P>
   ``Max, why don't you call me Chief Lockhart, just for today,
just so I know you're payin' attention.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, sir, Chief Lockhart, sir.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You still drivin' that old piece of junk? When you gonna get
yourself a proper car?''
</P>
<P>
   ``What does this have to do with The Watchers?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well if you're gonna catch Raoul Glaber and those pretty blond
boys he hangs with, you're gonna need a car that goes more than 45
miles per hour and gets better than eight miles to the gallon.''
</P>
<P>
   `You know the kind of car Glaber drives?''
</P>
<P>
   ``We know what kind of toothpaste he uses, but we ain't gonna
tell you unless you start tellin' us some things.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you, Sam, I mean Chief Lockhart, that I'm working
as a journalist. It's not some personal thing. But I can't tell you
who hired me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have to tell me. It's Miss Kate Banks, another fine
woman who should know better than to have anything to do with the
likes of you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you want from me?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothin' much. I just want you to go to the Conquistador Hotel,
go into that lion's den, and interview Raoul Glaber, the Number 1
Big Daddy Watcher himself.''
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   NEXT INSTALLMENT: RED BEANS AND RICE
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Roy Peter Clark is a senior scholar and an associate at the
Poynter Institute for Media Studies. He was commissioned to do this
newspaper novel as part of the New York Times Regional Newspaper
Group's Celebrate 2000 project.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
