<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSPAPER-NOVEL-chap13-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIN'T DONE YET: A BLAST FROM THE PAST  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (ATTENTION EDITORS: Hearkening back to the era of Dickens and
other serial novelists, The New York Times Syndicate is offering
for purchase ``Ain't Done Yet: A Newspaper Novel About the
So-Called End of the World '' _ 29 suspenseful installments, by ROY
PETER CLARK, the Poynter Institute senior scholar and well-known
writing coach. The novel, set in St. Petersburg-Tampa, chronicles a
burnt-out investigative reporter on the trail of a cult, ``The
Watchers,'' and its charismatic leader. The novel was commissioned
as a millennium project by The New York Times Regional Newspaper
Group. Chapter 13 is below. The series is a wonderful way to
celebrate the millennium with your readers. For purchase
information, contact New York Times Syndicate Sales Director Bob
Farnell by phone, (212) 499-3335; fax, (212) 499-3382; or e-mail
farnellb(AT)nytimes.com.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (PLEASE NOTE: All 29 chapters have been sent to the ``l''
lifestyle category code.)
 &HT;    
 By ROY PETER CLARK 
 (Worldwide rights) 
 c.1999 Roy Peter Clark  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   LAST INSTALLMENT: Police Chief Sam Lockhart persuades Max Timlin
to infiltrate The Watcher headquarters and obtain an interview with
the secretive Raoul Glaber.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   It took Max Timlin three full days in the musty old library of
St. Pius College, north of Tampa, to make sense of Father Ralph's
revelations: Raoul Glaber was not the real name of the leader of
The Watchers. Max wasn't as convinced as Ralph that this was true,
but he devoured the evidence.
</P>
<P>
   He began by reading the Book of Revelation, sometimes known as
the Book of the Apocalypse. He always thought the word
``apocalypse'' meant some great final cataclysm, as in the movie
``Apocalypse Now.'' But it was actually the Greek word for
``revelation.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Father Ralph's tutelage, Max came to realize that the
revelations of the last book of the Christian scriptures are
shrouded in mysterious and symbolic language.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's as if the Apostle John was dropping acid with Picasso,''
said Max, irreverently.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dreamlike visions of this book have left so much open to
interpretation that any tinhorn prophet can use it to predict just
about anything,'' explained Ralph. ``One thing we know for sure,
that for at least a thousand years, people who look at their own
times, and see dark things, return to this book as a kind of
mystical map.''
</P>
<P>
   Max pored over the text and some commentaries on it. In one
tradition, he learned, Christ would return to rule over the Earth
for 1,000 years. The Latin word for this was ``millennium.'' The
story of this return contains several subplots, including the
appearance of false prophets and antichrists, a time when Satan
would rule, a great battle between God and his enemies, and the
Last Judgment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The great problem,'' explained Ralph, looking at Max over his
reading glasses, ``was how to calculate the time when Jesus would
return. There's evidence in the Gospels that the disciples thought
it would happen right away _ perhaps in their lifetime. But when it
didn't happen, it opened the door for people to reinterpret the
Scriptures for their own purposes.''
</P>
<P>
   Max learned that the historical Jesus was actually born between
6 and 4 B.C. _ the first calendar makers goofed _ which means that
even if you were thinking about an era of 1,000 years, what would
be the starting point? The moment Christ was conceived? His birth?
His death and resurrection?
</P>
<P>
   Max read a gospel passage in which Jesus describes a time of
judgment when ``the sun will be darkened, and the moon will not
give her light, and the stars will fall from heavens.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Look,'' said Max to Ralph, ``Jesus said that `this generation
will not pass away till all these things have been accomplished.'
</P>
<P>
   ``But listen to this next part,'' said Ralph pointing down the
page and reading aloud: ```But of that day and hour no one knows,
not even the angels of heaven.' Jesus is urging his followers not
to calculate the precise time, but to do good all the time, to be
prepared for their own deaths and the end of the world, which would
sneak up on them, `like a thief in the night.'''
</P>
<P>
   That led Max and Ralph to a discussion of the year 1000, the
only historical precedent for what the world was about to
experience. Ralph stood on tiptoes and pulled a thin volume off a
high shelf. ``This is the smoking gun,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The innocent book was called ``The Year 1000,'' written by a
French art historian named Henri Focillon. The text tried to settle
an ancient intellectual argument: Was there any hard evidence that
people living in 10th century Europe were obsessed by the terrors
of the last days? Did they think they were living in a time when
the end of the world was at hand?
</P>
<P>
   The simple answer was no. The historical records and artifacts
do not reveal a population in panic. Early in the next century,
after the millennium had passed, there was an intense period of
church building.
</P>
<P>
   ``That might suggest,'' said Ralph, ``that some people were
holding their breath, waiting a bit before undertaking any big
projects.''
</P>
<P>
   But there were some notable exceptions, some 10th century
``lunatics,'' as Ralph called them, who were prophets of doom, who
saw signs of the last days everywhere. The most notable of these
was a radical French monk. ``His name was Raoul Glaber.''
</P>
<P>
   Glaber wrote of a great meteor or comet he saw in the night sky
in the year 1000: ``It appeared in the month of September, not long
after nightfall, and remained visible for nearly three months. It
shone so brightly that its light seemed to fill the greater part of
the sky, then it vanished at cock's crow. What appears established
is that this phenomenon in the sky never appears to men without
being the sure sign of some mysterious and terrible event.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you think Glaber saw Halley's comet?'' asked Max.
</P>
<P>
   ``Focus on the more important point, Max. We're not talking
ancient superstitions here. Remember what the Heaven's Gate cult
did upon the appearance of the Hale-Bopp comet. They followed to
the death a wacky old guy, who apparently had himself castrated,
who told these bright young people _ they were computer experts,
for God sakes, they had their own Web site! _ that there was a
spaceship waiting for them behind the comet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All they had to do to get there was to put plastic bags over
their heads.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Read this,'' said Ralph and pointed to a passage in the text.
It said that the old French monk saw Satan everywhere, including
right beside his pillow, and that Satan was a ``small black monster
of human shape,'' and that ``Satan will soon be unleashed because
the thousand years have been completed.''
</P>
<P>
   Max leaned toward Ralph and whispered: ``Isn't it possible that
Glaber's daddy just named him Raoul?''
</P>
<P>
   ``And what? That just by coincidence he turned into Doomsday
Dick? Have you been able to track back on this guy? Do you know his
family's history?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a researcher at the Sun working full blast on it. So
far there's just a black hole.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tell you, Max, this guy, whoever he is, adopted the name
of a man who, 1,000 years ago, was trying to scare people to death.
And I predict that this guy will do the same. Unless we stop him.''
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   NEXT INSTALLMENT: INTO THE LION'S DEN
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Roy Peter Clark is a senior scholar and an associate at the
Poynter Institute for Media Studies. He was commissioned to do this
newspaper novel as part of the New York Times Regional Newspaper
Group's Celebrate 2000 project.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
