<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 14:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1258 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-NEWSPAPER-NOVEL-chap1     10-28 0999
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSPAPER-NOVEL-chap16-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIN'T DONE YET: SIGN OF THE WATCHERS  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (ATTENTION EDITORS: Hearkening back to the era of Dickens and
other serial novelists, The New York Times Syndicate is offering
for purchase ``Ain't Done Yet: A Newspaper Novel About the
So-Called End of the World '' _ 29 suspenseful installments, by ROY
PETER CLARK, the Poynter Institute senior scholar and well-known
writing coach. The novel, set in St. Petersburg-Tampa, chronicles a
burnt-out investigative reporter on the trail of a cult, ``The
Watchers,'' and its charismatic leader. The novel was commissioned
as a millennium project by The New York Times Regional Newspaper
Group. Chapter 16 is below. The series is a wonderful way to
celebrate the millennium with your readers. For purchase
information, contact New York Times Syndicate Sales Director Bob
Farnell by phone, (212) 499-3335; fax, (212) 499-3382; or e-mail
farnellb(AT)nytimes.com.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (PLEASE NOTE: All 29 chapters have been sent to the ``l''
lifestyle category code.)
 &HT;    
 By ROY PETER CLARK 
 (Worldwide rights) 
 c.1999 Roy Peter Clark  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   LAST INSTALLMENT: Max meets Raoul Glaber and the beautiful
Angela Powers, but a sweet glass of ice tea and a startling
revelation render him unconscious.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   Maybe there had been an eclipse, or maybe Max had fallen asleep,
because when he awoke the sky was still dark, but now a light rain
splattered across his face. He wiped it with his hand and clumsily
sat up.
</P>
<P>
   He looked around to get his bearings and found himself in the
back seat of his Mustang with the top down, and yes it was raining
and his head hurt and his leg hurt, too.
</P>
<P>
   This must be what a migraine felt like: a pain both dull and
sharp, pressing a thousand pounds against the side of his skull.
But he had never had a migraine before.
</P>
<P>
   His memory came back slowly now and then snapped into focus: the
visit to the pink hotel, the incursion into enemy territory, a cool
drink with Raoul Glaber and Angela Powers. The drink.
</P>
<P>
   He had been drugged, carted to his car, driven to an empty spot
on Cosmos Key, and left there for how long? Hours? His face felt
sunburned. This was the punishment for his arrogance. But at least
he was alive.
</P>
<P>
   He looked at the dashboard. ``They left the keys,'' he said
aloud to no one. ``My head hurts! And my leg!''
</P>
<P>
   Max drove slowly back to the condo, gripping the wheel and
blinking his eyes. He let himself in, clicked on the lights, and
looked around suspiciously. He blamed himself for letting down his
guard against Glaber _ not Glaber, but William Miller _ and what
had Angela Powers said to him, just before the eclipse? Now he
remembered. He picked up the phone and dialed the home number of
his researcher, Violet Rose.
</P>
<P>
   ``Violet, this is Max.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What time Max?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sorry, Violet, it's 1 a.m. I've had a bad day. Violet, I
talked to Glaber today. Got him to admit his real name was William
Miller. But I don't believe it. Look up that name. Check not only
personal and legal stuff _ it's a common name _ but look at
historical references _ check the damn World Book Encyclopedia.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Max, you woke me up to tell me to look something up in the
encyclopedia?'' She was groggy, but laughing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stick with me, Violet. He named himself after one doomsday
guy. Let's see if he picked another. One more thing. Do you know
much about Kate Banks? I mean her personal life?''
</P>
<P>
   ``What's this about, Max?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Stick with me, Violet. Does she have a daughter?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, one daughter. Cassandra.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Is her middle name Angela?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Max.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Kate Banks was married, right. Her husband died. What was his
name?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael, I think, Michael Powers. Max, are you all right?
Please. Do you want me to come over?''
</P>
<P>
   Her concern made Max feel guilty that he had awakened her. There
was something special about her, he had discovered. He had met
highly intelligent people before. And compassionate ones. But never
in quite the combination that Violet offered.
</P>
<P>
   ``A megabyte mind,'' Kate had said of her, ``and a heart of
gold.'' Sherry offered her own appreciation of Violet's character:
``She's got the hardware and the software.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Max, are you hurt? I'll come over if you need me to.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you, Violet. You are a kind person. I'm sorry I woke you
up. It could have waited until tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell me what happened, Max.''
</P>
<P>
   And he did. Detail by detail in chronological order. It helped
him clear his memory, make sense of the day, and rehearse the long
memo he would write to himself tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, and one more thing, Violet. He says he's from the West.''
</P>
<P>
   ``William Miller. From the West. Well that narrows it down.''
Max found Violet's laugh comforting.
</P>
<P>
   Max hung up. He stripped quickly, leaving his clothes in a pile
on the tile floor. He turned on the water in the shower until it
steamed up the room. The water hit his face _ he was sunburned _
just what a guy with skin cancer needed. But in a minute it felt
great, down into his muscles to the bone, steaming the pain and
poison from his body.
</P>
<P>
   Max turned to let the water hit his back. He let out a howl. As
the water sprayed the top of his leg, it stung like a horde of red
ants. ``What the ...?''
</P>
<P>
   He turned off the shower and stepped out onto the floor. A
full-length mirror on the back of the door was steamed up. He wiped
his hand across it and turned his body. And there it was. On his
right hip. A tattoo. The letter ``W.'' Sign of The Watchers.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   NEXT INSTALLMENT: THE BITTER END
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Roy Peter Clark is a senior scholar and an associate at the
Poynter Institute for Media Studies. He was commissioned to do this
newspaper novel as part of the New York Times Regional Newspaper
Group's Celebrate 2000 project.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
