<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 14:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1272 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      10-28 1864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE OTHER SCREEN THAT NEEDS MONITORING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA F. MELTZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the American Academy of Pediatrics issued a statement last
summer about children and the media, the &UR;  &LR; press glommed onto the
most sensational item, a recommendation that children under 2 not
watch TV. What went virtually unnoticed, however, was equally
important: Children's bedrooms should be media-free.
</P>
<P>
   Not just no TV, but also no computers. Not just for children
under 2, but for children of all ages.
</P>
<P>
   Most parents already know not to put a TV in a child's room. But
many readers tell me they purposefully put the computer there,
thinking it opens the door to the child's personal technological
age. All it opens the door to is problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Putting the computer in a public room is the single most
important thing parents can do,'' says educational psychologist
Jane Healy, who has spent 35 years studying &UR;  &LR; how children learn.
</P>
<P>
   Public placement enables parents to monitor not only the time a
child spends at a terminal but also how he sits when he's there and
what's on the screen. This is important at all developmental
stages:
</P>
<P>
   Toddlers and preschoolers. Although it didn't say so explicitly,
the TV ban for 2-year-olds was intended to extend to computers,
says Children's Hospital adolescent physician Michael Rich,
co-author of the academy position paper. Neither he nor Healy has
anything kind to say about lapware, the new software for infants
that is getting good write-ups in some of the parenting press.
Indeed, Healy calls software for infants ``preposterous.'' Her
newest book, ``Failure to Connect: How Computers Affect Our
Children's Minds and What We Can Do About It'' (Touchstone), is the
most comprehensive look so far at how computers can harm cognitive,
social, and emotional growth.
</P>
<P>
   The later the better
</P>
<P>
   Researchers and clinicians say the longer we wait to put kids on
computers, the better. Psychologist Maressa Hecht Orzack, a
specialist on computer addiction, says 5 is plenty young; Healy
recommends 7, an age parents may consider shockingly old.
</P>
<P>
   ``Educators have begun to realize that computers in and of
themselves are not necessarily a good thing, but parents are slower
in getting that message,'' Healy says. ``Unless there's a specific
task to be done _ downloading a picture with you, dictating a
thank-you note to you _ they shouldn't be on.''
</P>
<P>
   Time spent on the computer is time away from the primary task of
early childhood: socialization. Even if a 4-year-old is playing a
computer game with you _ and note that Healy's exhortation is for a
child to download with you or dictate to you _ the social
interaction is extremely limited. And even if a young child is on
your lap, Orzack worries. ``Nobody knows how it changes brain
connections or what it does to a kid's sense of reality to connect
to an image rather than a person,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   School-age. This is typically when parents scoop up so-called
educational software, a.k.a. skill &AMP; drill, to give a child an edge
in math or reading. In fact, at this age it is more likely to
detract from learning. For evidence, Healy points to an increase in
the reporting of learning problems at early ages.
</P>
<P>
   ``Children learn best from hands-on experience,'' says educator
Bob McCannon, director of the New Mexico Media Literacy Project.
``Their brains grow in relation to the quality of the stimuli
coming in through the senses. When the computer provides the input,
the ability to think things up in your own mind is compromised.''
</P>
<P>
   A veneer of learning
</P>
<P>
   Healy says the problem is with the software. ``The people who
create it know how to make it glitzy so it appeals to kids, and
they paste a veneer of learning on it so it appeals to parents. But
they don't understand what motivates a young child to learn,'' she
says. She tells parents to avoid programming where children receive
rewards for trivial amounts of work. ``It erodes their internal
motivation: `Why should I choose a harder problem? It'll just take
me longer to get to the reward.' ''
</P>
<P>
   This affects classroom learning because it shortens attention
spans. Teachers report that children are more likely to give up
rather than work harder when faced with a challenge. ``They're
programmed for immediate gratification,'' says Healy.
</P>
<P>
   There are dangers to physical health _ ``Most kids would rather
be on the computer than outside getting exercise,'' McCannon says _
and dangers of addiction, even to 8-year-olds, says Orzack, founder
and coordinator of the computer addiction service at McLean
Hospital in Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   Young children can get hooked on all kinds of computer games,
from Pokemon to SimCity. ``If you try to talk to your child while
he's playing a hand-held computer game and you can't get his
attention; if the game comes at the expense of play with friends;
if homework or chores are getting squeezed; you're looking at a
computer addiction,'' Orzack says.
</P>
<P>
   Rich's advice is to set limits on how much and when computers
are used. ``It's a matter of prioritization,'' he says. ``After
homework, after family time, after friends, sports, exercise.''
</P>
<P>
   Peer pressure
</P>
<P>
   Middle-school age. In about fifth grade, the need for peer
approval fuels children's behavior, from what they wear to what
they say. If all her friends are doing chat rooms after school, you
can be sure your child will want to, too, says occupational
therapist and ergonomist Karen Jacobs of Boston University, who
teaches about computing at West Middle School in Andover.
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand, there are benefits at this age from chat rooms.
``They can be a b self-esteem for kids who don't fit in, who
feel awkward or uncomfortable for any reason,'' says Jacobs. She is
president of the American Occupational Therapy Association, which
has targeted middle-school age children for a national healthy
computing initiative.
</P>
<P>
   But the downside can be treacherously slippery, as parents in
Townsend discovered last week.
</P>
<P>
   Middle-school students at Hawthorne Brook School who had logged
into a chat room were terrorized allegedly by a teenager in
Missouri who gained access to their chat and directed children to
pornographic sites. Last Friday, police say, he threatened to blow
up the school. Police were able to track the teen to his home and
charged him with disseminating child pornography and threatening to
commit assault.
</P>
<P>
   Thankfully, dangers like these so far are extreme, but Rich says
it's not unusual for children to be unaware that there can be
``lurkers'' _ people who hang out in chat rooms and get information
but never talk _ or to realize that people in a chat room are not
always who they say they are. He says even buddy chats, where
participants invite people they know to join, are only slightly
safer. There also have been many reported cases of chats leading
children to real-life meetings and dangerous activities. More
typically, what parents need to know, however, is how seductive
chats are. ``Kids get sucked in and neglect other parts of their
life,'' Rich says.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs's concern is that a lot of what goes on in a chat room is
putting down of peers. ``It can be hurtful and destructive,
especially because kids can't read the nuances that might be more
obvious in spoken conversation,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Potential for injury
</P>
<P>
   Because preteens spend more time on the computer than any other
age, they are at greatest risk for muscle and skeletal problems.
She spends a good chunk of class time on ergonomics. ``Children
sharing chairs and keyboards with adults at home need to readjust
to avoid injury,'' she says. She recommends a backpack as a
footrest, a jacket rolled up for back support, yellow pages under
the monitor and stretches every 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The Townsend case, coupled with all the other risks, offers
frighteningly concrete proof why computers need to be in public
spaces where parents can monitor activities. Rich says his
children, 13 and 11, are only allowed on the Internet for school
research and if an adult is with them. ``With some of the search
engines,'' he says, ``you can put in something innocuous and come
out with something bizarre or pornographic.'' He says chat rooms
can work in moderation if parents negotiate rules and limits around
them, for instance, that they are a reward, not an entitlement, and
come after homework, dinner, chores, etc.
</P>
<P>
   Teenage. Instant gratification, a feeling of belonging, and the
excitement of risk-taking (for hacking, for being in sites you know
you shouldn't be in) are what motivates teens, who are most at risk
for addiction. ``If you're bringing him dinner into the computer
room, you're an enabler,'' says Orzack. Other tips that your teen
is in trouble: slipping grades, truancy, falling asleep in class,
irritability, missed meals, and, if the computer is in his room,
hours spent behind a closed door. Sites that are most addictive are
multi-user domain game sites (MUDs) where a user takes on an
identity that some teens have trouble shaking off; teenage chat
rooms; Internet games such as Everquest and Quake; hacking and
pornography. Blocking software will not deter a teen who wants to
find whatever he wants, says Jacobs.
</P>
<P>
   Parental involvement
</P>
<P>
   As simple as it sounds, the best antidote to teen addiction is
constant conversation about computer use. But don't wait until your
child is 15, says Orzack. Begin in the elementary years: ``Show an
interest in their computer use: `Show me your favorite sites. Can I
sit with you while you do a chat, just to see what it's like?' ''
Her favorite question to a teen is, ``When you open your computer,
what do you expect to find?'' Answers that tip off trouble include:
``a place where I belong,'' ``a place to make money,'' ``a place
for excitement.''
</P>
<P>
   Computer use with older children is largely an issue of values,
says Jacobs. ``He knows I trust him to do his work first,'' she
says of her son. ``I also know there are times when that trust gets
abused. Is it a problem? No so far.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all children find the computer so enticing, of course.
Rich's daughter, Desta, 13, finds chat rooms boring. ``I'd much
rather talk on the phone to a real person,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   CYBER SUGGESTIONS FOR PARENTS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Be sure that a child of any age knows that if he's in an
on-line site where he feels uncomfortable and he can't seem to
exit, he can just turn off the computer.
</P>
<P>
   --The American Occupational Therapy Association has a free
screen saver that offers computer posture tips for children.
Download it at http://www.aota.org.
</P>
<P>
   --More than an hour a day playing on the computer is considered
excessive.
</P>
<P>
   --Your computer use is a powerful model and predictor of your
child's.
</P>
<P>
   --Teens who get caught up in risky computer activity are
frequently very smart but bored and marginalized at school. For
them, the computer provides positive, immediate gratification.
</P>
<P>
   --If you think your child of any age is addicted to any on-line
behavior, seek professional guidance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
