<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSPAPER-NOVEL-chap20-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIN'T DONE YET: ON TOP OF THE WORLD  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (ATTENTION EDITORS: Hearkening back to the era of Dickens and
other serial novelists, The New York Times Syndicate is offering
for purchase ``Ain't Done Yet: A Newspaper Novel About the
So-Called End of the World '' _ 29 suspenseful installments, by ROY
PETER CLARK, the Poynter Institute senior scholar and well-known
writing coach. The novel, set in St. Petersburg-Tampa, chronicles a
burnt-out investigative reporter on the trail of a cult, ``The
Watchers,'' and its charismatic leader. The novel was commissioned
as a millennium project by The New York Times Regional Newspaper
Group. Chapter 20 is below. The series is a wonderful way to
celebrate the millennium with your readers. For purchase
information, contact New York Times Syndicate Sales Director Bob
Farnell by phone, (212) 499-3335; fax, (212) 499-3382; or e-mail
farnellb(AT)nytimes.com.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (PLEASE NOTE: All 29 chapters have been sent to the ``l''
lifestyle category code.)
 &HT;    
 By ROY PETER CLARK 
 (Worldwide rights) 
 c.1999 Roy Peter Clark  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   LAST INSTALLMENT: Two Watchers are found floating in Tampa Bay.
Max ponders if they jumped off the Skyway Bridge, or were pushed?
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   Tipped off by Max, the police began an inquiry into whether the
dead Watchers could have been dropped from a plane or helicopter to
make it look like a suicide leap off the Skyway Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   ``The injuries on these folks were unusually devastating,'' Sam
reported to Max over the telephone. ``The medical examiner says the
injuries are consistent with a drop of more than 200 feet _ but so
many things can affect this.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Any comment from Glaber?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Through a spokesman he said that young people, even Watchers,
killing themselves was a horrible thing, and a clear sign of a
troubled world tumbling toward its end.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What an ass----.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He says The Watchers don't own a plane or helicopter. Only
boats, vans and cars.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I saw something that could be a landing pad for a
helicopter _ out beyond the dunes near the Conquistador.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll check it out. What are you up to?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm writing like crazy, but today I'm going to call on a
friend, so I can get into the Star Dome and view the New Awakening
with my own eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   That evening, Max found himself on the southern tip of St.
Petersburg, in a neighborhood called Pinellas Point, where great
oak trees hung shade over lovely wide streets that for decades had
been paved with pink concrete. Most people called this place ``The
Pink Streets.''
</P>
<P>
   Max's face was as pink as the streets. He was jogging _ feeling
flabby and out of breath _ next to a tall, young black man, who
happened to be one of Florida's most beloved athletes, James
``Choirboy'' Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Jones had grown up in St. Pete, one of the nation's only
five-sport athletes and an honors student at Lakewood High. At
6-foot-4, both nimble and strong, James played quarterback, point
guard and center field. He ran track. And he once joined the soccer
team to step in for an injured goalkeeper. He went to Florida
State, where he decided to concentrate on baseball. He was now in
his second season playing with the St. Pete Pelicans.
</P>
<P>
   Max had written about him after James' father was murdered in a
convenience-store robbery. The father, Charles Jones, was a great
preacher and pastor _ earning his son the nickname ``Choirboy'' _
and his death stunned the community.
</P>
<P>
   In his father's honor, James had committed half of his huge
salary to charitable work. He built houses for the working poor,
sponsored the construction of athletic fields in the poorest
neighborhoods, purchased books for a new library branch and could
often be seen on Sunday mornings at local churches, working with
pastors on their most pressing needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``So you want me to sneak you into the Dome for this Awakening
event. Don't you know I'm the Choirboy. I'm not exactly the sneaky
kind.''
</P>
<P>
   ``James, I didn't know where else to turn. You know everybody in
that place _ and The Watchers are barring the press, and they know
me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Max. I like you, my friend. The story you wrote made my mother
cry her heart out over my father _ but in a good way. So I'll help
you. But, to ease my Choirboy conscience, I must impose two
conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Name them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, you have to come with me to church early Sunday
morning. Then for the rest of the day, you have to help me build a
house. Then, if you can still stand up _ by the way, you are way
out of shape _ we'll go to the Dome.''
</P>
<P>
   By late Sunday afternoon, every muscle in Max's body, including
some he didn't know he had, ached. Seven hours of bending, lifting,
hammering, lifting, bending, had taken their toll.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a long time since I've worked like that, James. I
think I remember now why I became a writer. No heavy lifting.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Words can be heavy, very heavy. But this is good for your
body, Max, and your soul. I can see that God ain't done with you
yet.''
</P>
<P>
   They hugged and Max remembered that Father Ralph had said the
same thing, using almost the same words.
</P>
<P>
   It was no trouble for James to get into the Dome, even on a
night when the building was closed to the public. They trusted him
with his own key. ``Max, you came to church with me. You helped me
build a house.''
</P>
<P>
   They were standing at home plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I'm gonna add one more stipulation. I've got a great idea
for how you can get in here, see everything you need to see and
still not be seen by a single Watcher. But it's gonna cost you.''
</P>
<P>
   Max could see mischief in the eyes of the Choirboy. ``Max,
you've got to beat me in a race around the bases.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You mean I run and you crawl.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No, easier. You start at second base and I'll start out at
home.''
</P>
<P>
   Max lost. His legs, tight from the day's work, slid out from
under him rounding third base, and by the time he recovered, he
could hear the fastest man in baseball whooshing by him. ``You've
got to promise you'll write about this, Max. Not now. But someday,
when I enter the Hall of Fame.'' Coming from the Choirboy, it did
not sound like bragging.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll write your life story, James Choirboy Jones. I've never
met an athlete _ a man _ like you. Now where are you going to hide
me?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Up there.''
</P>
<P>
   Max lifted his eyes from the tip of his friend's finger, up, up,
up, till his head was bent back, staring at a thin catwalk leading
to a circular bank of huge speakers. Up, up, up, more than 250 feet
to the domed roof of the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Up there?''
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   NEXT INSTALLMENT: GONNA TAKE YOU HIGHER
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Roy Peter Clark is a senior scholar and an associate at the
Poynter Institute for Media Studies. He was commissioned to do this
newspaper novel as part of the New York Times Regional Newspaper
