<HEADER>
A1263 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-NEWSPAPER-NOVEL-chap2     10-28 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSPAPER-NOVEL-chap21-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIN'T DONE YET: GONNA TAKE YOU HIGHER  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (ATTENTION EDITORS: Hearkening back to the era of Dickens and
other serial novelists, The New York Times Syndicate is offering
for purchase ``Ain't Done Yet: A Newspaper Novel About the
So-Called End of the World '' _ 29 suspenseful installments, by ROY
PETER CLARK, the Poynter Institute senior scholar and well-known
writing coach. The novel, set in St. Petersburg-Tampa, chronicles a
burnt-out investigative reporter on the trail of a cult, ``The
Watchers,'' and its charismatic leader. The novel was commissioned
as a millennium project by The New York Times Regional Newspaper
Group. Chapter 21 is below. The series is a wonderful way to
celebrate the millennium with your readers. For purchase
information, contact New York Times Syndicate Sales Director Bob
Farnell by phone, (212) 499-3335; fax, (212) 499-3382; or e-mail
farnellb(AT)nytimes.com.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (PLEASE NOTE: All 29 chapters have been sent to the ``l''
lifestyle category code.)
 &HT;    
 By ROY PETER CLARK 
 (Worldwide rights) 
 c.1999 Roy Peter Clark  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   LAST INSTALLMENT: Max makes plans to sneak into the huge Watcher
convention, with the help of James ``Choirboy'' Jones, a great
athlete and champion of social justice.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   To get Max to the top of the Dome would require three things: a
guide, a rehearsal and a counter-phobic energy he did not believe
he possessed. James Choirboy Jones hooked Max up with the Dome's
master sound engineer, a short, silver-haired Italian man named
Rocky Como. From a distance, Rocky was the spitting image of Father
Ralph.
</P>
<P>
   ``You ain't the first guy to say so,'' said the man known as The
Rock. ``In fact I know the Good Father. If you are friends with the
Good Father and the Choirboy, maybe I can be your friend some day,
cause you got great taste in friends.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Rocky, I'm afraid of heights.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Not to worry. You don't look down. You follow me and stare
right into the middle of my back. And breathe nice and steady.
Don't forget to breathe, or you'll die. But first you wear this.''
</P>
<P>
   Rocky gave him a bright orange jump suit that said Star Dome
Sound on the back. It was a little big for Max, but he found it
light and comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   He stared up at the Dome roof. He saw four concentric circles _
metal catwalks that allowed workmen access to different parts of
the roof. The outer ring was the lowest, circling most of the
inside of the stadium. Only a few hitters could reach that catwalk.
The next ring in was also a home run, requiring a long, high fly to
reach it. The next ring in was higher still. A high pop-up could
reach it, but not often. The ball was in play.
</P>
<P>
   And then at the center, like the bull's eye in a target, was the
smallest and highest circle, home of the Dome's speaker system. A
person could hide behind those speakers, invisible to the crowd
below.
</P>
<P>
   Each circle was connected to the next by a thin metal gangplank
_ with protective sides _ acting as a kind of ladder.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll come in through the service entrance, wearing that
gear. If anyone stops you, have them call me. I'll clear you.
You'll take Service Elevator 11 _ that's this one _ and it will
take you to the first catwalk. From that point on, it's a piece of
pizza.''
</P>
<P>
   The march that followed looked like a dog trying to follow a cat
across a circus tight rope.
</P>
<P>
   ``Slow down, Rocky. Take it easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Max gripped the hand rails on the first ramp so tight it gave
him blisters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stare at my back,'' Rocky said, over and over.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen minutes later, they had reached the final ramp, steeper
than the others, but shorter in distance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't look down!'' But Max couldn't help it. Step, step ...
step ... step ... step.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come on, you got here. One more step. Look up.''
</P>
<P>
   And there he was, but his heart raced like a fast ball, a
burning sweat stung his eyes and soaked through his clothes all the
way through the jumpsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``There, that ain't so hard,'' said Rocky, pointing to a safe
platform.
</P>
<P>
   Max regained his breath and composure.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is perfect, Rocky. I'll be able to see everything. But
just one thing? How do I get down?''
</P>
<P>
   That night Max Timlin had a dream, and it was a doozy. It began
with the sound of a helicopter: tucka tucka tucka tucka tucka, and
he was the only passenger, but no one was at the controls. He was
sitting next to an open door, gaping wide, and the copter _ it was
black _ circled and circled over the Star Dome, till Max was dizzy
from the motion.
</P>
<P>
   An unseen hand pushed him in the back and he tumbled over, down,
down, head first, but then upright, waving his arms. He looked down
to see the great white roof of the Dome, like a lovely marshmallow
pie.
</P>
<P>
   He would be safe, he thought. But his body sliced like a hot
knife through the marshmallow, through layers of roof, and into the
stadium where he grasped at air until his hands locked on a piece
of metal, the third catwalk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now batting for the Pelicans, James Choirboy JONES!'' But Max,
facing home plate could see it wasn't the Choirboy, but Glaber _
only huge _ on steroids.
</P>
<P>
   The pitch. The crack of the bat _ deafening _ and a shot like a
missile, the ball hit so hard it traced a path in the air, coming
at him, at him, hitting his right hand with the force of a grenade
explosion.
</P>
<P>
   Hanging by one hand now, and all the fans dressed in white
cheering as Glaber rounded the bases, the fans looking up at him
and laughing and pointing and chanting his name in derision:
``Max-well, Max-well.''
</P>
<P>
   Losing the grasp now and falling down, down, and gazing down, in
this dream, he saw not the green of the outfield turf, but the
night-black waters below the Skyway Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   NEXT INSTALLMENT: STRANGERS IN THE NIGHT
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Roy Peter Clark is a senior scholar and an associate at the
Poynter Institute for Media Studies. He was commissioned to do this
newspaper novel as part of the New York Times Regional Newspaper
Group's Celebrate 2000 project.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
