lifestyle category code.)
 &HT;    
 By ROY PETER CLARK 
 (Worldwide rights) 
 c.1999 Roy Peter Clark  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   LAST INSTALLMENT: Max returns to the condo, where Angela Powers
is hiding. There they are attacked by Glaber's henchmen. Angela is
kidnapped.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   When Max came to, someone was leaning over him. A woman, he
surmised, or a man with long, sweet-smelling hair that tickled the
side of face. In fact, the person was blowing air into his mouth.
</P>
<P>
   It was a woman, and Max pushed her aside, turned his head and
coughed, leaning up on one elbow and rubbing his throat with his
free hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw them load Angela Powers, she was wearing a blue
bathrobe, into a white van.'' It was Violet. ``And I could see your
front door was open. I ran up and found you on the floor.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you save my life, Violet?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know. I'm not sure you were breathing.'' Her hands
started to shake. ``Should I call 911? Are you all right, Max?''
</P>
<P>
   She helped him to his feet. ``Let's call the cops, Violet. In
fact, let's call Sam Lockhart. I've got his direct number.''
</P>
<P>
   Sam issued an all-points bulletin for Cassandra ``Angela''
Powers. He sent detectives to the Conquistador Hotel to question
Glaber, but neither he nor his henchmen could be found. The
rank-and-file Watchers claimed no knowledge of their whereabouts.
</P>
<P>
   Violet stayed at the condo with Max, who was dizzy. She fixed
him a cup of tea, rubbed the soreness out of his neck and
shoulders, and even tucked him into bed, kissing him a gentle good
night, and running a hand through what was left of his hair. He
dropped off immediately and fell into a deep, dreamless sleep.
</P>
<P>
   He woke up feeling refreshed, even though this December morning
brought another wave of heat and humidity. Before noon it would hit
well into the 90s. Such weather was common from May through
October, but this December blast was both unusual and demoralizing.
</P>
<P>
   Christmas in Florida was hard enough, no snow for years, but
this weather smelled like tropical funk. El Nino by way of Jimmy
Buffett.
</P>
<P>
   He made a quick list of possible icons of the bizarre holiday
season: Scrooge wearing Bermuda shorts. Gingerbread men baking on
the beach. Rudolph with zinc oxide smeared on his nose. Frosty the
Snowman getting a fatal suntan. Suzy Snowflake becoming a crispy
cornflake.
</P>
<P>
   Max filled the passing days with work, writing and reporting,
until Christmas Eve arrived, one week until New Year's Eve, until
Millennium Eve. All the big parties would be next week. But he
decided on a small one, in the afternoon, so people could meet
their family and church commitments.
</P>
<P>
   His guests rolled in to the condo about two in the afternoon,
dressed more for Labor Day than Christmas, carrying cookies, and
salads, and casseroles, bottles of cold beer and wine.
</P>
<P>
   Violet had arrived early to help Max get the place ready. She
wore green shorts and matching halter top, with a red ribbon and
bow draped across her body, beauty queen style.
</P>
<P>
   Kate Banks arrived next, looking somber, like she needed a
drink. Still no word about her daughter, but every cop and reporter
in town was on the lookout. Violet did her best to comfort and
reassure her.
</P>
<P>
   Sherry Darling arrived wearing a Santa hat and carrying a
disposable camera, which actually brought a little laugh from Kate.
Sherry, as was her habit, hugged the breath out of each of them _
twice.
</P>
<P>
   Father Ralph came next, wearing his favorite Hawaiian shirt,
lugging pastries and a gift for Max, a Frank Sinatra CD. Kate shook
his hand firmly and thanked the priest for helping her daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Next came James ``Choirboy'' Jones, who posed for a picture next
to Father Ralph. They made a comic couple: Wilt Chamberlain
towering over the mayor of Munchkin Land.
</P>
<P>
   They were joined next by the police chief, Sam Lockhart, who
gave them an update on the search for Kate's daughter, and the
investigation of Glaber and The Watchers. Everything was being done
that could be done, he assured them. He would update Max each day,
personally. It was unlikely that Glaber would have escaped the
area. ``We think he's still here. And I'll wager we find him
soon.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Father Ralph,'' said Kate. ``How did you pull that stunt at
the Dome? How did you get in with the sound crew?''
</P>
<P>
   ``You think Max is the only one with connections?'' he smiled.
``You think it's possible that an old priest might call up a young
superstar like the Choirboy and maybe ask a little favor? And, I'm
not afraid of heights either.''
</P>
<P>
   They all turned and laughed at Max, who affected a sheepish
look.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone filled their plates with the holiday grub and took
seats on the couch or on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Father,'' said Sherry, who was Catholic. ``Do you want to say
grace?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nah,'' he said, ``Let's eat.''
</P>
<P>
   The doorbell rang. Evie Hamilton walked in, dressed immaculately
in a gold holiday frock, with Daisy, wearing a red bow around her
neck, bounding in behind her. It took Daisy, who would be spending
the week with Max, a good hour to make the rounds, gathering hugs,
pats and belly rubs wherever she could get them.
</P>
<P>
   By about six o'clock, the gathering had run out of gas, with
people beginning to stretch their legs, collect their plates, and
discuss their family plans for the rest of the evening.
</P>
<P>
   Kate would hang out with friends. Max, Violet and Daisy would
work the beach, looking for Santa to come in on water skis, being
towed by dolphins. Father Ralph invited everyone to midnight Mass
at the clinic. Choirboy and his mom had the family over. Sam and
his wife were hosting an annual party for his top assistants.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want you all to know how important all of you have been to
me in the past months,'' said Max, adopting a voice he was not used
to.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes me happy to have you all together here with me for
just a little while. When Kate hired me to work on this story, I
was feeling more than a little burned out. But, I don't know,
something about this story, and all of you, have brought me back.
I've been drugged. I've been choked. I've had to listen to Ralph do
his Sinatra imitation.'' They all laughed. ``I've slept with a
great dog. A dog that survived a drop from the Skyway Bridge.''
More laughter and then the sound of a cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Lockhart answered.
</P>
<P>
   ``When did this happen?'' he said, and then several ``uh-huhs.''
He looked around the room as he listened. ``And where is he now?
I'll be damned. Any sign of Glaber or the girl? We'll be right
down.'' He hung up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Max, you were right. Those Watchers didn't jump off the Skyway
Bridge, they were dropped from a small plane.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you know.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They just dropped another one. No, Kate, not your daughter.
It's a tall, skinny white boy without any hair.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that kid,'' said Max. Sherry nodded. ``We saw him at
the initiation. Is he dead? Did they fish him out of the water.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No. I guess this is a Christmas miracle, but he's alive. He
was pushed out of a small plane. Or he jumped.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Where did he land.''
</P>
<P>
   ``On the roof of the Star Dome. Hit near the top, took one big
bounce like a trampoline, and slid down and hooked on to the ledge.
Folks drinking on the patio of Jake's Sports Bar saw the whole
thing. They're taking him down now.''
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   NEXT INSTALLMENT: FALL DOWN AND GO BOOM
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Roy Peter Clark is a senior scholar and an associate at the
Poynter Institute for Media Studies. He was commissioned to do this
newspaper novel as part of the New York Times Regional Newspaper
Group's Celebrate 2000 project.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
