<DOCNO> NYT19991028.0206 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 14:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1277 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      10-28 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRANTICALLY PURSUING HAPPINESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA WELTNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I've got to do something about my appetite. Not my appetite for
food. For stimulation. I'm like a magpie, grabbing at anything that
glitters, dazzled by anything that shines.
</P>
<P>
   I keep clipping reviews of books I want to read and movies I
want to see. I keep writing down lectures I want to attend and
courses I want to take. I keep making dates with people I want to
see and making lists of errands I have to run. I have a file of
places I plan to take my grandchildren and a collection of articles
about countries I intend to visit. Every time I read the newspaper,
I scan the listings for interesting things to do. Every time I talk
with friends, I generate new projects. My hunger for experience is
so great I could fill up every block in next month's calendar in
one afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, it's already filled.
</P>
<P>
   Friday there's a meeting of our Unitarian Church's Ministry
Committee, and on Tuesday nights I teach an adult education class
on the evolution of the human brain, based on a video series by
cosmologist Brian Swimme. Thursday mornings the Marblehead Cancer
Prevention Project meets, and all those dates circled in purple
marker signify talks I'm giving to various women's and library
groups this fall. Saturday night we're having folks over for
dinner. Sunday afternoon we're seeing the stage version of ``The
Last Hurrah.'' My daughter Julie's birthday is a week before Jack
and I take both of our grandkids for the weekend, and then comes
Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   Those are only the special events.
</P>
<P>
   In case I have a free moment between trips to the supermarket,
the post office, and the chiropractor, I have a cabinet full of
material for various craft projects. I've committed myself to
making doll furniture for our church's dollhouse raffle. As if that
weren't enough, I'm in the process of putting up low-cost
affordable housing for birds on the wall of our garage. My grandson
and I are building one birdhouse together, and I've purchased
several unfinished ones that we have to polyurethane and put up
before winter arrives. I'm also knitting my daughter a sweater . .
.
</P>
<P>
   I don't even want to think about the adventures that are going
to show up, unexpected and unplanned, which I'll be unable to
resist.
</P>
<P>
   I must be out of my mind.
</P>
<P>
   I look forward to every one of those things, but I'm not looking
forward to all of them. Each one individually is highly enjoyable,
pleasurable, and gratifying. All together, they're exhausting.
</P>
<P>
   Which ones am I willing to give up? None.
</P>
<P>
   What am I going to do? I don't know.
</P>
<P>
   This is where we all find ourselves at the end of the 20th
century, drowning in a sea of too many good choices and too many
exciting opportunities. If it were only obligations and demands
that were killing us, it would be a lot easier to plot our way out
of the compressed activity that stuffs our lives to the fullest.
Unfortunately, we're also at the effect of all the ways it's now
possible to be entertained, distracted, informed, and uplifted.
Even if we never leave our houses, the Internet lies in wait to
seduce us with great Web sites while the TV undermines our
resistance with good programs. Waves of stimulation crash over us
from every direction, leaving us awash in an ocean of irresistible
possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Is it any wonder that everyone I know feels like they're going
down for the third time?
</P>
<P>
   This is my Achilles' heel: I like the rush of adrenaline that
comes with purposeful activity. I feel a surge of triumph when I
survive an impossibly busy day. There's a certain
master-of-the-universe thrill in feeling like one of the most
productive people on earth. No one could ever say I'm wasting my
life or missing out on what the world has to offer. I'm never
bored.
</P>
<P>
   I'm also never completely relaxed.
</P>
<P>
   This is what's so difficult: In order to take back my life, to
cushion it with liberal amounts of uncommitted time, to give myself
a margin for flexibility, I not only have to fight the culture, I
have to wrestle myself to the mat. I'm too curious, too
enthusiastic, too human for my own good. I have seen the enemy and
I both love and resent her.
</P>
<P>
   She is my own craving for impact.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
