r l BC-NEWSPAPER-NOVEL-chap2     10-28 1229
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSPAPER-NOVEL-chap27-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIN'T DONE YET: THE DEAD OF NIGHT  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (ATTENTION EDITORS: Hearkening back to the era of Dickens and
other serial novelists, The New York Times Syndicate is offering
for purchase ``Ain't Done Yet: A Newspaper Novel About the
So-Called End of the World '' _ 29 suspenseful installments, by ROY
PETER CLARK, the Poynter Institute senior scholar and well-known
writing coach. The novel, set in St. Petersburg-Tampa, chronicles a
burnt-out investigative reporter on the trail of a cult, ``The
Watchers,'' and its charismatic leader. The novel was commissioned
as a millennium project by The New York Times Regional Newspaper
Group. Chapter 27 is below. The series is a wonderful way to
celebrate the millennium with your readers. For purchase
information, contact New York Times Syndicate Sales Director Bob
Farnell by phone, (212) 499-3335; fax, (212) 499-3382; or e-mail
farnellb(AT)nytimes.com.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (PLEASE NOTE: All 29 chapters have been sent to the ``l''
lifestyle category code.)
 &HT;    
 By ROY PETER CLARK 
 (Worldwide rights) 
 c.1999 Roy Peter Clark  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   LAST INSTALLMENT: Max and the police chief rush to the domed
stadium to find a young Watcher has jumped out of a plane and
landed on the stadium roof.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   Max watched Sam Lockhart and his men spend Christmas Day
emptying out the Conquistador Hotel. Sam called in the FBI, alerted
the National Guard and the Coast Guard, which began an elaborate
search for Glaber's boat.
</P>
<P>
   Every corner and crevice of the pink hotel was inspected, every
shadow illuminated, every Watcher and every tourist interviewed,
and then asked to leave.
</P>
<P>
   It appeared as if Glaber, his dozen closest followers and the
kidnapped Cassandra ``Angela'' Powers had been teleported to
another galaxy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't forget to check behind the nearest comet,'' said Max to
Sam sarcastically.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel came up clean, not even a cache of weapons, no double
secret sub-basement filled with missiles or nerve gas. The search
went on for days, including a small army with metal detectors on
the beach. They pulled up lots of coins, wristwatches, gold chains
and beer cans _ but nothing that could blow up a bridge.
</P>
<P>
   The break came Wednesday night, Dec. 29, just two evenings
before the new year and the new millennium. It was Sam Lockhart
himself who figured it out.
</P>
<P>
   Standing on the roof of the hotel, in increasingly stormy
weather, he looked down the beach to a place Max had once described
for him: ``A big circle, like a landing pad for hang gliders or
helicopters.'' Detectives told him no one had ever seen anything
landing there. ``Dig it up,'' Sam ordered.
</P>
<P>
   They found six metal containers carrying enough plastic
explosives to do quite enough damage, thank you, to a bridge, or
federal building, or hotel, or police station, or newspaper office,
or nuclear power plant. The bad news was that one container was
empty.
</P>
<P>
   ``How much is missing?'' asked the chief.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably enough to fill a boat the size of Glaber's.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Damn him,'' said the chief, one of his strongest expletives.
``And damn this weather.''
</P>
<P>
   The weather between Christmas and New Year's was apocalyptic _
no one could remember anything quite like it _ with effects more
dramatic and unpredictable than those produced by the Pacific
warming known as El Nino.
</P>
<P>
   Two tropical storms had formed in the Atlantic, with tropical
waves hopscotching east across Mexico and reforming in the Gulf.
Although none of these were yet of hurricane strength,
meteorologists worried about the unpredictability of such storms a
month after the end of the normal tropical storm season.
</P>
<P>
   Max spent New Year's Eve morning with a weather eye on the sky
and on television news reports. Storm warnings were being issued on
both Florida coasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the next two days, we're likely to get lots of rain,
wind, lightning, maybe even some tornadoes. You folks living in
low-lying areas pay special attention for locally heavy flooding,
when the tides are high. These patterns are common for us in
September, but never as late as New Year's Eve. Maybe this is
Mother Nature's way of joining the Big Party.''
</P>
<P>
   There would be no big millennium party for Max.
</P>
<P>
   He and Daisy the dog and maybe Violet would be at the condo,
parked cozily in front of the television set, watching the weather
and news of the festivities around the world as the Year 2000 broke
first over the International Dateline and then swept west, time
zone by time zone, until it reached Florida and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   Max would also be in constant touch with Kate at the newspaper
for news of her daughter, and with Sam for news about Glaber and
The Watchers.
</P>
<P>
   The phone rang.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hello, Max, it's Violet. I need to come over.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well I need you to come over. And so does Daisy. We wouldn't
want to usher in the new millennium without you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, Max, I'm one of those who believe the new millennium
doesn't begin until Jan. 1, 2001. But why let logic and mathematics
get in the way of a good orgy?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Orgy? Could this be my lucky millennium?''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you play your cards right. But that's not why I called,
Max. I'm working on an important angle on Glaber. I think I know
who he is. I'm waiting for one more piece of information _ an old
obituary.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't keep me in suspense, Violet. What have you got?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well I looked for connections between the names Glaber and
Miller, like you suggested, but came up empty. Then I made an
assumption _ that his name might really be William Miller, like he
told you, and that he's really 50 years old, like he told Father
Ralph, and that he's from California _ he said he was from the West
_ because he just sounds like a Californian _ his voice, all that
New Age stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's some funky hunch for a logician.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Stick with me, Max, as you like to say. For days I've been
checking birth records, death certificates, old phone books,
microfiche newspaper stories, out of the big California cities: San
Diego, LA, San Francisco.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Violet, don't make me jump through this phone.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I found an oddity, a birth and a death, in San Francisco. In
the same family. On the same day. On New Year's morning, to be
exact, 1950. The father's name was William Miller. The son's name
was Michael.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You are telling me that the son was born and the father died.
On New Year's morning. At the exact midpoint of the century.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, not the exact midpoint, but never mind Max. Here's the
kicker. The father threw himself off the Golden Gate Bridge.''
</P>
<P>
   The wind off the gulf blew gusts that shook the condo. Lightning
flashed like a strobe light. Daisy slithered under the bed and
began to whimper. The lights flickered and went out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Violet. We just lost our electricity. How about you? Violet?''
</P>
<P>
   The phone line was dead.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   NEXT INSTALLMENT: HEY, KIDS, WHAT TIME IS IT?
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Roy Peter Clark is a senior scholar and an associate at the
Poynter Institute for Media Studies. He was commissioned to do this
newspaper novel as part of the New York Times Regional Newspaper
Group's Celebrate 2000 project.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
