<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 14:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1270 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-NEWSPAPER-NOVEL-chap2     10-28 1264
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSPAPER-NOVEL-chap28-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIN'T DONE YET: HEY, KIDS, WHAT TIME IS IT?  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (ATTENTION EDITORS: Hearkening back to the era of Dickens and
other serial novelists, The New York Times Syndicate is offering
for purchase ``Ain't Done Yet: A Newspaper Novel About the
So-Called End of the World '' _ 29 suspenseful installments, by ROY
PETER CLARK, the Poynter Institute senior scholar and well-known
writing coach. The novel, set in St. Petersburg-Tampa, chronicles a
burnt-out investigative reporter on the trail of a cult, ``The
Watchers,'' and its charismatic leader. The novel was commissioned
as a millennium project by The New York Times Regional Newspaper
Group. Chapter 28 is below. The series is a wonderful way to
celebrate the millennium with your readers. For purchase
information, contact New York Times Syndicate Sales Director Bob
Farnell by phone, (212) 499-3335; fax, (212) 499-3382; or e-mail
farnellb(AT)nytimes.com.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (PLEASE NOTE: All 29 chapters have been sent to the ``l''
lifestyle category code.)
 &HT;    
 By ROY PETER CLARK 
 (Worldwide rights) 
 c.1999 Roy Peter Clark  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   LAST INSTALLMENT: The police search for Raoul Glaber and his
henchmen to rescue Angela and destroy a plot to blow up the Skyway
Bridge. Max and Violet get closer to Glaber's true identity.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   The lights were off, the phone was dead, the dog was under the
bed and sheets of rain raged against the windows of the condo. When
the rain subsided intermittently, Max Timlin could see waves
crashing across the rocks of Land's End, over the dunes, over the
sidewalk and into the street.
</P>
<P>
   Reports on the weather radio said that, for now, everyone should
stay put, that the barometric pressure was dropping like a brick
off a skyscraper, that winds were approaching hurricane speed, that
there were reports of fallen trees and power lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are at a millennium party, stay where you are. Repeat.
Do not try to get home.''
</P>
<P>
   Max looked at his watch. It was 12:09 a.m. Jan. 1. The Year
2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, after all this, I missed it. I missed the millennium.''
His cell phone rang.
</P>
<P>
   ``Max. Max. Can you hear me? It's Kate. I'm still at the
newspaper.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Any word about Glaber and your daughter?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I just got a call from the cops. The Coast Guard found
Glaber's boat about two hours ago in a wharf over in the Port of
Tampa. They've arrested six men. The boat was loaded with
explosives. But there is no sign of Glaber and Cassie. Max. What's
going to happen? I'm so scared.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You want me to try to get over there?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No, Max, I'm staying here through the night, just in case a
call comes in. Now that they've found the boat and the explosives,
they can't spend time looking for Cassie. All their attention is on
people threatened by the storm.''
</P>
<P>
   Max heard a noise and thought it was the wind, but realized
someone was pounding on the door. He looked out. He saw Violet's
lovely face, framed by the hood of a yellow rain slicker.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, Max helped her out of her wet clothes, and even Daisy
ventured out of hiding for a hug.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's getting treacherous out there, Max. It almost looks like
the end of the world. Thank God for the sports utility vehicle.''
</P>
<P>
   Max gave her a good long hug, sat her on the couch and poured
her a glass of cabernet. Violet reached into her little backpack
and pulled out a file folder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Max, I think I've got the final two pieces of the puzzle. One
e-mail message came in just before the lights went out.''
</P>
<P>
   She showed him an obituary of William Miller, Glaber's father.
It said that Miller was born in 1900, the son of German immigrants,
that he was a college athlete and honor student, that he graduated
first in his class in medical school, and decided to become a
career army officer.
</P>
<P>
   Here it got interesting. Miller rose to the rank of colonel, and
after World War II served as an advisor to the justices conducting
the Nuremberg war crimes tribunal. Miller spoke German, and was
free to interview the Nazi leaders, even as he took their blood
pressure or gave them an aspirin.
</P>
<P>
   ``So now we know that Glaber's father happened to have the name
of a famous 19th-century American doomsday prophet, that he met the
perpetrators of the Holocaust up close, and that three years later
he jumped off the Golden Gate Bridge.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's one more thing, Max. I had to wait to get this
translated into English. It's a footnote from a German book on the
Nuremberg trials.''
</P>
<P>
   Max read it. It said that after the suicide of Dr. William
Miller, police found a note in his study addressed to his wife, who
was in the hospital giving birth to their first son, Michael.
</P>
<P>
   ``To have seen what I have seen. To have cared for those whose
hearts were pure evil. I'm not worthy to be the father of a son in
such a world. I'll meet you _ and my son _ in heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   Max read and re-read the words of the suicide note. It was as if
a large black curtain had been pulled back to reveal a giant
tapestry _ on which a grand but terrible story had now fully
unfolded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Poor Raoul Glaber,'' said Max, shaking his head, Violet's hand
on his shoulder. ''Poor Michael Miller. How could he possibly
escape his destiny? The son of a man turned mad by the Holocaust.
To come into the world on New Year's Day, only to have your father
leap to his death. No wonder he wanted to blow up a bridge. Even
his initials. Michael Miller. MM. The Roman numerals for 2,000.''
</P>
<P>
   Violet and Max made sure the doors and windows of the condo were
secure and fell asleep by candlelight, curled up on the couch, her
head against his shoulder. It was a lovely sleep in the storm until
Max awoke to the sound of Daisy's whimpering.
</P>
<P>
   He reached out and patted her with his left hand, and realized
that his right arm was numb, the circulation cut off by the weight
of Violet's sleeping body. He carefully pulled the arm out from
under her and rested her head against a pillow. He stood up, yawned
and rubbed the blood back into his arm.
</P>
<P>
   ``What time is it?'' he whispered to Daisy, and looked at his
watch. It was 4:35 a.m. New Year's Day. His mind exploded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Violet, Violet, wake up honey.'' He shook her harder than he
meant to. ``Violet, what time did Michael Miller's father jump off
the bridge? What time? Do you know?''
</P>
<P>
   Violet rolled off the couch and grabbed the materials from the
file, which they had left spread out across the floor. It took only
a minute or two for the fog of Violet's sleep to clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, we know that Michael Miller was born at 1:15 a.m. The
news story doesn't give an exact time, but police estimated the
father killed himself less than an hour after the birth of his
son.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So about 2:15 a.m. Pacific Time.''
</P>
<P>
   Violet got the picture.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's 5:15 a.m. Eastern Standard Time. What time is it now,
Max?''
</P>
<P>
   ``About 4:45.''
</P>
<P>
   He dashed toward the door.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where are you going, Max?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Violet, stay here with Daisy. Try to raise Sam Lockhart and
Kate Banks on the cell phone. I'm headed for the Skyway Bridge.''
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   NEXT INSTALLMENT: SAVE THE LAST DANCE FOR ME
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Roy Peter Clark is a senior scholar and an associate at the
Poynter Institute for Media Studies. He was commissioned to do this
newspaper novel as part of the New York Times Regional Newspaper
Group's Celebrate 2000 project.) &LR;  &QL;
