<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLEGE-BOARD-SHIFT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLEGE BOARD TO WIDEN ROLE, PLAY DOWN SAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE ZERNIKE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The College Board, for decades associated mostly with the test
that has held so much sway over college admissions, is redefining
its mission, recognizing that it has focused too much on the SAT.
</P>
<P>
   Under a new leader, the board now says it wants to concentrate
on preparing students for college, instead of simply measuring how
well they are prepared.
</P>
<P>
   The move reflects the declining influence of the Scholastic
Assessment Test, notwithstanding the dread the SAT still inspires
in parents and students or the way it has shaped college admissions
for the last half century.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the College Board's new mission has the
potential to reshape education from kindergarten to high school.
</P>
<P>
   The College Board, which is based in New York City, has already
announced plans to start an on-line college advising and
preparation service, like Kaplan or the Princeton Review. Over the
next few years it wants to drastically expand Advanced Placement
courses, making sure they are in every school in the nation, with
curriculum preparing for Advanced Placement tests starting in
middle and junior high schools.
</P>
<P>
   The board also plans to expand membership to include hundreds of
thousands of teachers whom it wants to teach preparation programs.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the proposed reforms may lead to changes in the SAT
that might better measure the skills needed in a new economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a new College Board,'' proclaimed Gaston Caperton, the
self-made millionaire and former West Virginia governor who became
president of the board in July. ``It no longer sees itself as a
gatekeeper, a tester. . . . Our mission is to prepare, inspire, and
connect students to college and to opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   The shift is largely necessary, reflecting changes in the
demographics of who goes to college and the economics of the board
itself.
</P>
<P>
   For years, the nonprofit College Board earned most of its
operating income from the SAT, which is taken by millions of high
school students in their junior or senior years. But the average
age of college students has risen to 26.6 years, and less than half
of college students fit into the traditional ages of 18-22. With
more people taking time off before they pursue their degrees, fewer
are taking the SAT to get into college.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the College Board is losing its virtual monopoly on
testing college entrants, as almost every state has imposed a
graduation test. And public universities, which enroll 80 percent
of US college students, have started their own entrance exams, in
Massachusetts and many other states.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we are only in the business of sorting and selecting, we'll
be out of business, because there are lots of other ways to sort
and select now,'' acknowledged Howard Everson, the board's vice
president of research.
</P>
<P>
   By expanding the Advanced Placement program, originally started
to provide a more challenging, college-level curriculum to bright
high school students, the board also increases the number paying to
take the Advanced Placement test.
</P>
<P>
   And by expanding its membership, now at about 15,000, to include
high school teachers who teach Advanced Placement courses, the
board can increase its membership dues.
</P>
<P>
   But board officials say the expansion is not purely economic.
The Advanced Placement program has the potential to raise academic
standards in the lower grades, and by becoming a larger
organization, the College Board plans to take on a larger advocacy
role.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the education organizations are very specific in what
they're doing,'' Caperton said. ``What we think we have is a
mission that pulls all of those people together for student
opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   The board's expected new income will also provide capital to
launch the Internet college preparation service, which Caperton
says will help get students who can't afford expensive preparation
programs to get into college.
</P>
<P>
   Building on its study of minority high achievement, started
under former College Board president Donald Stewart, the board
wants to find and promote programs that help black and Hispanic
students to achieve at the highest levels.
</P>
<P>
   Everson says the board's changes may also mean changes to the
SAT, with more focus on math and verbal reasoning skills and
possibly a writing portion. However, the board emphasizes that such
changes may be far off.
</P>
<P>
   Through such changes, ``we want to be the organization that
provides access to more and more students,'' said Lee Jones, who
Caperton brought in to run the Advanced Placement program.
</P>
<P>
   That is a far cry from the beginnings of the College Board,
which started as a tweedy association of Ivy League admissions
directors who wanted the SAT to identify the best and the
brightest.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholas Lemann, who writes about the early days of the board in
his book, ``The Big Test,'' sees two ways to interpret the changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The non-cynical approach is to say that this has been a dream
rattling around the College Board for 50 years,'' Lemann said.
``There's a vision behind the SAT that involved democratically
picking the 1 percent of the population to lead, and the people who
started it didn't really care about everyone else. That's not what
the College Board top brass are into now.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cynical view is that they need SAT fees to survive. From a
business standpoint, they are way too dependent on a test that's
under fire politically.''
</P>
<P>
   There is, some truth in both interpretations, board officials
concede.
</P>
<P>
   The break with the past was reflected in the choice of a new
leader. In the past, the board has chosen its presidents from a
pool of college presidents or academics, largely from the
Northeast. Caperton has no doctorate but does have a record of
success in business and in improving the educational system of one
of the poorest states in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Caperton admits to being surprised when he got a call asking him
to head the board.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the woman who called me said she thought it could be the
best job in education, and I think she's right,'' he said. ``Here
is a place that can impact education, that can really infect it
with things.''
</P>
<P>
   Change came quickly, with Caperton getting rid of 26 people the
first week. He announced the Internet service, which reversed a
long-held College Board tenet that preparation courses don't help
improve scores.
</P>
<P>
   ``What people have said about the College Board in the past is
not what the College Board is today,'' Caperton says. ``Anybody who
prepares is going to do better than somebody who doesn't prepare.''
</P>
<P>
   Boston School Superintendent Thomas W. Payzant, chairman of the
College Board trustees, says the board has always promoted access
and equity. But he and other trustees acknowledge that the board is
shifting its emphasis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never wanted to define ourselves as a testing agency,''
said Michael McPherson, president of Macalester College and a
trustee. ``Gaston (Caperton) came in and took the view that we're
not going to be able to do what we've always wanted to do unless we
make really fundamental changes in our methods.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't take a step like this we're yielding up the
responsibility to connecting kids to college to places like the
Princeton Review and Kaplan,'' McPherson says. ``We think that's
part of our mandate and we ought to be players.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
