<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 14:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1287 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-HOME-KITCHEN-ART-BOS &LR;      10-28 1492
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-KITCHEN-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A KITCHEN SETS THE STAGE FOR CHEF'S ART 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRISTINE TEMIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The floor in Lydia Shire's kitchen is gray concrete, mottled
like a stormy sea. The ceiling is also gray, the color of
thunderclouds. The overall effect of the room is anything but dank
or chill, though.
</P>
<P>
   Between ceiling and floor is a large infusion of Shire's
favorite color _ red. A red Murano glass chandelier with
antler-shaped branches hangs over the kitchen table. The
floor-to-ceiling windows, a whole curved wall's worth, are outlined
in red steel. The stove is likewise red: It's a restored, 1940-ish
Chambers brand that Shire bought in Los Angeles before she owned a
house to put it in. Of the quartet of lighting fixtures hanging
over the island counter, just one is red: As much as Shire loves
that color, she loathes symmetry and things that match.
</P>
<P>
   People who have eaten at Shire's two celebrated Boston
restaurants, Biba and Pignoli, might feel a stab of deja vu in
seeing her home kitchen, which shares the commercial
establishments' playful design, sinuous lines, and color scheme as
carefully balanced as the flavors of a great meal. An invitation to
dine chez Shire is no longer necessary to get a glimpse of that red
stove, etc.: She's one of 26 high-profile pros featured in the
lavish new coffee-table tome ``Great Kitchens: At Home with
America's Top Chefs.''
</P>
<P>
   Shire's suburban farmhouse
</P>
<P>
   Her kitchen sits at the back of her circa 1820 Greek Revival
farmhouse in a Boston suburb. She and her husband, Uriel Pineda,
moved here in 1994, leaving their Bay Village condo in order to
find a place with a yard where their young son, Alex, could play.
The house hadn't been lived in for five years when Shire and Pineda
found it. They didn't want a place where the design was already a
fait accompli, so they asked their realtor for ``a rattletrap,''
Shire recalls, and the broker produced this classic derelict with
leaky roof and squirrels living in the walls.
</P>
<P>
   To collaborate on the complete overhaul it needed, Shire signed
on her daughter, New York architect Lisa Shire, one of three grown
children by her first marriage. The house's columned facade was
inviolate. But inside the red front door Lisa Shire created a
series of curves _ graceful bends in both walls and staircase _
that bounce the eye back to the kitchen and beyond, out those
red-rimmed windows and over the lawns, which end in woods that, at
this time of year, also oblige by turning red _ the orangey shade
that is Shire's favorite. ``I don't like reds with blue in them,''
she says. This sort of certainty made working with her mother
relatively simple, Lisa Shire says. ``Mom knew what she wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   What she wanted before she became a chef was to be an artist.
The Brookline, Mass., native went into cooking partly because she
didn't get into the School of the Museum of Fine Arts. Her parents
were both commercial illustrators: A Campbell's soup ad by her
father hangs on her kitchen wall, extolling the virtues of a
steaming bowl of canned soup, a cheese sandwich on white bread, and
a big glass of milk. A page from Pignoli's menu it's not. But Dad
was also an ace cook, and little Lydia was chopping garlic for him
from the age of 4. She picked up that childhood experience later
on, enrolling in London's Cordon Bleu and then working in top
restaurants in Boston and Beverly Hills.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Performance artist
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In her home kitchen, she's a performance artist, cooking in a
galley-shaped area that's deliberately confined, both to cut down
on the number of steps she has to take and to maximize space for
guests to meander in the rest of the room. She works at a counter
38 inches high, taller than the norm, so she doesn't have to bend
over to chop and mix. ``It's the difference between whether your
back hurts or not,'' she says. Her sink is outsize, because it
tends to fill up fast. Ditto for the 30-gallon garbage can.
</P>
<P>
   The working half of the kitchen island is covered in green-black
Ubatuba granite. ``When that tree outside turns yellow,'' she says,
looking out from the windowed wall, ``it's reflected in the
counter, which turns completely gold.'' The other half of the
counter, where guests perch, is even more visually compelling, an
irregular rounded concrete form designed by Boston artist Tom
O'Connell. This ``island'' could be in Greece, and it could be the
site of an archeology dig. Fragmentary staircases, pilasters,
canals, and windows with colored glass insets are built into this
little world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love miniatures,'' Shire says. Toothpick-size farm tools,
hatchets to shovels, adorn the arch of the kitchen fireplace where
Shire roasts meat on a multispeed spit: She serves it on an antique
wooden sled that waits nearby. A white plaster relief of tiny
kitchen tools, whisks to ladles, hangs on the wall. A 1930s German
model of a store features minute scales and bins. Shire also owns a
teensy antique toy stove you could actually light and use. (She
hasn't.)
</P>
<P>
   ``My brother says I have more tchotchkes than anyone else in the
world,'' she says, standing in the middle of Tchotchke Central,
a.k.a. her pantry. ``It gets so crowded in here that every so often
I have to edit, and send things to the basement.'' Currently
crammed onto the shelves are stoneware jars labeled ``Fly Feet''
and ``Bug Eyes''; a copper teapot so slim it's virtually 2-D,
designed to sit in a vent on the back of a wood-burning stove; a
plethora of plates of different patterns, many with gold rims,
chosen to reflect the gold-leaf ceiling in the adjacent dining
room; and an old Dutch breadbox bought because ``the color drove me
nuts,'' Shire says. ``It's close to celadon, but more intense. More
a spring green. But not quite.''
</P>
<P>
   The shelves in the pantry are held up by curly wooden brackets
that represent a rare point of disagreement between homeowner
mother and architect daughter. Lydia liked their look; Lisa wanted
something simpler, translucent and modern-looking. Lisa Shire got
her transparency, though _ in the pantry walls. Pantries, for most
people, are places to hide stuff away; this one is walled in
mesh-patterned glass that turns it into a vault to look into.
</P>
<P>
   Passion for asymmetry
</P>
<P>
   Lydia Shire's passion for asymmetry and pattern-mixing continues
in the kitchen proper, where the chairs are as diverse-looking as
the people who might sit in them and where cabinet doors and
drawers are of different sizes, with mismatched hardware. Their
wood is pale golden sycamore, with a striped grain further
complicated by little squares of ebony. The effect is jewel-box
opulent.
</P>
<P>
   As in other matters, Shire has definite views on equipment.
She'd lusted after a Chambers stove since childhood: Her aunt who
lived in Newton had one, in green. Shire's red model has its own
built-in sconces, which give it an altar-like feel. She makes
pancakes on the Chambers's griddle and makes Alex's favorite
haddock with crumb topping on the lever-operated stovetop broiler.
</P>
<P>
   The other appliances aren't period pieces. She has two huge
Gaggenau burners to accommodate oversize pots, and a Gaggenau oven
in addition to the one on the Chambers. She favors ASKO dishwashers
because they're quiet and Traulsen refrigerators because she likes
the taste of their ice.
</P>
<P>
   Fussy about major appliances, she dismisses the minor ones. ``I
hate gadgets,'' she says. ``I don't have a microwave. And a
breadmaker is the silliest thing I've ever heard of. The whole
point of making bread is the tactile sensations involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of her objection to gadgets, she says, is that ``I can't
stand clutter.'' She likes either a visual feast, as in that pantry
or the living room cabinet where she stashes her treasured
collections of glass, Murano to Japanese, or just one focal point
isolated on a table.
</P>
<P>
   An artist's passion
</P>
<P>
   The chef who couldn't get into the Museum School _ and
subsequently concluded that cooking was of course an art itself _
retains an artist's passion for putting together colors and shapes.
She's got hundreds of props, from Lady with Unicorn plates she uses
for hors d'oeuvres to the straight cylindrical Hoya glasses from
Japan she proclaims ``the sexiest champagne flutes ever.'' (Her
preferred brand is Deutz Blanc de Blancs.) Fondling a miniature
metal wheelbarrow she uses as salt cellar, Shire announces, ``When
I set my table, I have the most fun in the world. It's the biggest
high of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``GREAT KITCHENS: AT HOME WITH AMERICA'S TOP CHEFS'' is written
by Ellen Whitaker, Colleen Mahoney, and Wendy A. Jordan, with
photographs by Grey Crawford. Published by Taunton Press, it sells
for $34.95.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-99 1440EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
