<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 14:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1290 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      10-28 0616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAUNTED BY DIANA'S LOVER, HOWARD'S SPLIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was heartening to learn James Hewitt didn't write his memoir
of his affair with Princess Diana for the money, a reported $1
million or so, but ``as a necessary correction to the historical
record.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I gave Diana a lot, and that seems to have been forgotten,''
Hewitt selflessly confesses in People magazine this week.
</P>
<P>
   How can we forget if he won't stop reminding us?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, indeed, he did give Diana a lot, in a manner of speaking.
We can read his most recent version of their story in his book,
which has an appropriately Barbara Cartland-ish title, ``Love and
War.'' I plan to devour it as soon as I manage to settle some of
this other stuff I've been obsessing about lately. Martha's IPO.
Pat Buchanan's ravings. My plans for the eve of the False
Millennium. And that models' eggs thing. I was so disappointed to
hear it's a publicity stunt.
</P>
<P>
   It's such a wonderful idea. ``Beautiful struggling models,'' as
one story described the alleged donors, auctioning their eggs on
the Internet for big money. What would they be struggling with, I
wonder? Surely, not their consciences. But, of course, it turns out
they're not struggling with anything, since they don't exist, and
the whole thing is a scam.
</P>
<P>
   Still, that doesn't mean the idea isn't viable. Why shouldn't
beautiful people make the world a lovelier place by sharing their
DNA with the rest of us? Selling your eggs is no different than
selling your children, and let's be honest, who hasn't wanted to
sell theirs, on occasion?
</P>
<P>
   It would be interesting to dwell further on the possibilities of
DNA-for-sale, but I am too distressed about the Howard Stern
situation to think too much about anything else. As the entire
world knows by now, Howard and Alison, his wife of 21 years, have
split.
</P>
<P>
   The pain. The anger. The recriminations. And that's just me. God
knows what Howard is going through. And Alison? We don't hear much
about Alison. It's all about Howard, as it should be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a crummy spouse, a burnout, and I always have been,''
Stern told his listeners on his nationally syndicated radio show
Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   This admission came as a dreadful shock to the faithful fans who
assumed the Sterns had a perfect marriage. Well, that Howard, at
least, had a perfect marriage.
</P>
<P>
   What could be more ideal than Howard's situation? He makes $20
million or so a year titillating himself and his listeners _ and
his TV viewers, too _ bantering with half-dressed porn stars and
centerfold models. Then he goes home to his faithful wife.
</P>
<P>
   It's a lifestyle many men envy. Howard knows he's a role model.
``My long marriage has kept a lot of guys in line,'' he told the
New York Post.
</P>
<P>
   You have to admire the sensitivity and humility of the man, and
the degree of his self-awareness. He knows he's personally
responsible for keeping so many marriages together. The burden must
be nearly intolerable. He knows that without his marriage to look
to, his fans are bound to leave their wives and spend their days
talking to porn stars.
</P>
<P>
   But it was his career that came between him and Alison, Howard
confessed, not the bevy of sexy women he has as guests on his show.
``I think I'm married to my career in a lot of ways,'' he said on
his Monday show. How could any woman hope to compete with something
as fabulous as Howard's career?
</P>
<P>
   For the sake of the national divorce rate, I hope the Sterns
will find a way to reconcile. If she'll have him back. There's too
much at stake.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Diane White is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
