<SLUG> BC-FED-TECH-ECONOMY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FED ANALYST SEES TECHNOLOGY PLAYING BIGGER ROLE IN ECONOMY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EDWARD IWATA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A Federal Reserve analysts said the central bank
has wrestled with how to gauge the impact of technology on the
nation's economy and has reached the concluded that it's becoming a
major influence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new economy and technology are fundamentally real, it's
not hype,'' said Jack Beebe, director of research at the Federal
Reserve Bank in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a staff, we've dragged our heels on studying the impact of
technology on the economy,'' he said in an address Wednesday before
the Commonwealth Club, an organization of business and civil
leaders in San Francisco. ``But now it's leading to fundamental
shifts in our analysis and thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   The government traditionally has relied on factors such as
factory production and worker output to gauge the health of the
economy. But the influence of the Internet and technology, which
allow more people to work at home and have their own businesses,
are harder to grasp.
</P>
<P>
   Beebe said that many signs point to an economy that will remain
strong in the coming months, led by billions of dollars in
technology spending and investments.
</P>
<P>
   The national economy may grow at a healthy 4 percent to 5
percent clip over the next year, he said. Consumer spending may
hover at 5 percent to 6 percent. Unemployment remains low. And
labor costs and inflation are not rising dangerously.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Beebe hedged his bets and preached caution,
noting that the economy also might slow a bit.
</P>
<P>
   Factors such as a rise in long-term interest rates, higher
wages, a slower housing market and a dip in consumer buying could
slow the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Beebe spoke enthusiastically of the impact of computer hardware
sales on wage inflation and growth of the gross domestic product.
His conclusion? The economy will go up _ or down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, technology is fueling a huge expansion of the economy,''
he said. ``But it's also an immutable law that some day we'll have
a recession. The question is: When?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-99 1441EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991028.0214 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 14:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1295 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-COMPUTERS-CYBERSPACE-     10-28 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-CYBERSPACE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIGITAL SCRATCH 'N SNIFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI HARTIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Be forewarned: This column is about a new technology that really
stinks. And if it actually works, that's a compliment.
</P>
<P>
   Two California entrepreneurs, Dexster Smith and Joel Lloyd
Bellenson, have invented a form of digital Scratch 'n Sniff, making
it possible to transmit smells over the Internet. If their company,
Digiscents Inc., takes off, you will be able to send stink bombs
that really stink, receive spam that really smells like Spam, and
transmit steamy love letters that really emit the scent of, well,
steam.
</P>
<P>
   This may sound like something out of a wacky sci-fi novel (or a
John Waters movie), but it isn't a hoax. The device attaches to
your computer and picks up coding embedded in Web pages, e-mail,
video games, or DVDs. It converts the digital signals into a full
spectrum of scents that breeze out of the box. The gizmo, which
won't be released until spring of 2000, is simply called iSmell.
That's not a joke either.
</P>
<P>
   The in-your-face name conjures up images of kids sending
messages sprinkled with a certain toilet water. ``Obviously, people
will get a hoot out of it for a while, but hopefully we can satisfy
the juvenile impulses enough so people can focus on it as an art
form,'' says Bellenson.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to imagine how digital smell could be used by the
advertising industry _ as well as the adult entertainment industry.
``You had to bring that up,'' Smith says with a groan. ``Sex is a
natural thing.''
</P>
<P>
   But an art form? ``Smells transport you to another place
mentally,'' says Bellenson. ``Say you've just come back from Bali
or Paris or wherever you've been. You remember the smells of the
meat on the sticks, the incense, the diesel of the car, the bakery.
The smells intensify the memories.''
</P>
<P>
   The folks at Digiscents have even hired a staff psychologist as
vice president of research and development. ``People invest smells
with meaning,'' says Dr. Avery Gilbert, an expert in human odor
perception. ``We are going to open up a whole new area of
creativity as we take smell as a symbol and unhinge it from its
literal origins.'' A pause. ``Oh God, I sound like a French
philosopher.''
</P>
<P>
   French philosophy, it's not. But it is a scientific fact that
smell operates differently from the other senses; smells
communicate directly with the limbic system, the part of the brain
associated with emotions. As such, the addition of smell to a
multimedia event can heighten the experience. The entrepreneurs
have already created what they call ``scent tracks'' to accompany
such vintage movies as ``The Wizard of Oz,'' in which viewers can
actually smell the forest, as well as the flying monkeys. They're
not saying what perfume the Wicked Witch wears, but you can only
just imagine.
</P>
<P>
   Word has it that they're already working on a signature for
video game superstar Lara Croft. Talk about total immersion.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't the first time the entertainment industry has flirted
with scentsational effects. Back in the 1950s, Hollywood producers
experimented with Scentavision and Smell-a-Vision, in which odors
were released in synch with a film. Needless to say, that
experiment took a quick nosedive. Then, in 1981, Waters released
his campy spoof ``Polyester,'' starring Divine and presented in
what the flamboyant director called ``Odorama.'' It was about as
high-tech as it was highbrow: Audience members received Scratch 'n
Sniff cards to be used during particularly fulsome moments.
</P>
<P>
   Bellenson, 35, never saw ``Polyester.'' ``I was never into
Scratch 'n Sniff either, but I was made fun of as a kid for having
a big nose,'' he admits. ``Really. The nose knows.''
</P>
<P>
   He and Smith came up with the idea for the iSmell when they were
vacationing at Miami's South Beach. You know the scene: beautiful
people. Scanty clothes. Sweet scents. Sensory overload. ``The
smells were hitting us, and it had a profound impact,'' Bellenson
recalls. ``It really affects your body.''
</P>
<P>
   And so Digiscents was born. ``We should get out more often,''
says Bellenson of the original epiphany. Since the company issued a
press release last week and hit the cover of Wired magazine, it has
been inundated with queries. Some callers are incredulous. Others
are fascinated. Some are horrified: Aren't those perfume ads that
fall out of magazines bad enough?
</P>
<P>
   The Digiscents partners point out that users will always have
the option of turning the device off. But Bellenson is convinced
that a new art form is about to emerge. ``This is a whole new
sensory aspect that you're not used to having stimulated,'' he
says. ``When the first telephone was developed it was bizarre. When
the phonograph came out, people thought there were little tiny
people in it.''
</P>
<P>
   The telephone, the phonograph, and the iSmell? We're not holding
our breath, at least not yet. But if this column had a scent track,
Bellenson would be wearing Aqua de Gio, and Smith would emit the
scent of Basala by Shiseido. As for the psychologist, his scent
remains anonymous, although it's probably something French.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Along with the rest of the world, we were thrilled to learn that
Encyclopaedia Britannica had opened its vault of information to the
world on a new free Web site. But the site was so overwhelmed with
traffic on its first day of operation that it crashed within a few
hours. The site (www.britannica.com) posted a note of apology,
reporting a ``tidal wave of activity'' and a promise to resolve the
technical problems. Luckily, we could look up ``limbic system'' the
old-fashioned way.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
