<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REMEDIES FOR CLEANING STAINED ENAMEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. My 1951 cast-iron bathtub is in great shape except that it is
stained a dingy brown. I have tried bleach and other cleaners
without success. How can I get it clean?
</P>
<P>
   GLENN MEISTER, Wellesley, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Cast-iron tubs will last indefinitely, but the porcelain
enamel surface does not, especially under decades of scrubbing with
abrasive cleansers containing fine sand or pumice. The abrasives
wear off the surface of the enamel, but not the enamel itself,
making it easily dirtied and difficult to clean.
</P>
<P>
   You will never restore the gloss to the enamel, but you can
clean it this way: Wet the finish with hydrogen peroxide (sold in
drugstores) and sprinkle lots of cream of tartar (sold in grocery
stores) on top. Leave it for an hour, then scrub and rinse. I think
SoftScrub will do the same, and it can be smeared heavily on the
stain.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, a reader once told the handyman that Ivory shampoo will
also work. The caller had spilled a bottle of the stuff in the tub
but didn't see it until an hour or so later. Lo! Where the shampoo
was, the tub was pristine white.
</P>
<P>
   So, take your pick.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My manufactured house has an attached aluminum porch. The
aluminum ceiling is loaded with mold. I plan to power wash, then
put a light coat of insulation to keep the roof warmer than it was,
preventing condensation of water vapor on the ceiling and
subsequent growth of mold. Would that keep the mold away?
</P>
<P>
   JOHN HART, Carver, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. It might, but the water vapor is likely to condense on the
walls or other parts of the porch, with mold as a consequence,
especially if the porch is closed in with windows. To get rid of
the mold, power washing is OK, but better is to wash it with a
bleach solution, then rinse, to kill the mold.
</P>
<P>
   It won't hurt to insulate the ceiling just to keep it from
getting too hot in summer. Glue inch-thick polyisocyanurate to the
ceiling. This will provide an R factor of 7, pretty good for a thin
layer of insulation.
</P>
<P>
   However, ventilation is the only way you will keep the moisture
away and prevent future mold. Put louvered vents in the walls, as
high up as possible, and put them on opposite walls to provide
cross-ventilation. Put vents in the high end of the roof if
possible. The more air flow, the less moisture and mold.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. The porcelain is chipped on the old Tappan cooktop that is
set into my kitchen counter. Can it be repaired or replaced? I
called Tappan, who said there are no replacements available.
</P>
<P>
   TOO NICE TO THROW AWAY
</P>
<P>
   A. Ain't it the truth. You get a good thing and everything is
hunky-dory for a while, then when you need help, or even a part,
there is none forthcoming. It's a throwaway world, which saves
manufacturers money, but at the price of their good name.
</P>
<P>
   One thing you might try, if chipping and wearing of the
porcelain is severe, is to spray it with a high-heat-resistant
(HHR) spray enamel. It is widely sold in hardware and paint stores
in a number of colors. I suggest the HHR enamel if the cooktop gets
hot in use. If not, an ordinary latex undercoater and spray enamel
finish will do wonders. But you must sand the top thoroughly first
to make sure the primer and enamel stick.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My family room in the basement is 25 years old, and some of
the square floor tiles are broken. How can I make the floor look
relatively decent without spending a lot of money?
</P>
<P>
   TONY BARBERE, Billerica, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Those tiles are probably vinyl asbestos and should not be
fiddled with until they are analyzed for the amount of asbestos
they contain. But here is your best bet: Put the broken tiles back
where they were, then put down wall-to-wall indoor-outdoor
carpeting. The carpeting will allow water vapor rising through the
concrete to continue through the rug, where it can be ventilated
away. It was the water vapor that popped off the tiles in the first
place. There is little you can do to stop the water vapor, so you
have to accommodate it, and that is what the carpeting does.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am painting my front door, and although it is gray, it is
not a metal door. I bought latex paint. Can I use that?
</P>
<P>
   AN ANXIOUS RITA
</P>
<P>
   A. Yes, you can use the latex paint, if it is labeled exterior,
trim, or house paint. That gray is a prime coat. So, put on the
latex, but make sure you use thin coats. Two will do well, and
should last for many years, even 20 if the door is protected,
either under a roof or behind a storm door.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader
questions. Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-99 1444EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
