<SLUG> BC-FBC-IVY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IVY LEAGUE RACE OPENS UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Harvard and at least three other teams can thank Dartmouth for
turning the Ivy League title race into a more inclusive affair. But
the Crimson will likely display more hostility than charity when it
plays host to Dartmouth on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Dartmouth (1-5 overall, 1-2 Ivy) upset Cornell, 20-17, last
week, dropping the Big Red (4-2, 3-1) into a tie with Brown (5-1,
3-1) for first place. Harvard (4-2, 2-1), Pennsylvania (3-3, 2-1),
and Yale (5-1, 2-1) are also in contention.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard scored on the game's last play to defeat Princeton,
13-6, in its fourth successive game decided by a touchdown or less.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any team is good enough to beat you if you are not playing
with intensity and focus,'' Harvard coach Tim Murphy said
Wednesday. ``We haven't handled prosperity very well. We've played
better with our backs to the wall.''
</P>
<P>
   Harvard is only 4 points away from an unbeaten record. Brown is
5 points removed from an undefeated season. Yale is only 1 point
away from being undefeated. But the league race could open up after
this week's games: Columbia (2-4, 0-3) at Princeton (2-4, 0-3) and
Pennsylvania at Yale. Brown visits Fordham and Cornell plays host
to Wagner in nonconference games.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you watch Dartmouth on film, they look like everyone else
in the league: very good,'' Murphy said. ``They are physical and
aggressive, and if they play like they did against Cornell it is
going to be very difficult. They have a good quarterback in Brian
Mann and their defense is strong and physical. The defense has had
a tendency to get worn out in the second half, but that was because
they were spending so much time on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Harvard will rely on running back Chris Menick, who has 3,037
career rushing yards (36 shy of Eion Hu's school record) and the
passing combination of Brad Wilford to Terrence Patterson (122
career receptions, five short of Colby Skelton's school mark). The
Crimson have scored 143 points, 7 more than it scored last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to continue to play well on both sides of the ball,''
Murphy said. ``We had an outstanding defensive effort last week. We
ran the ball well and we have to continue to present a balanced
attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel that if you can run the ball you're a real football
team. That means you can compete in bad weather, tough situations.
You need to be able to run well to be a complete and confident team
and, fortunately, we can do that. We didn't throw well last week _
the wind was a factor _ but that's when you want to have a good
running team.''
</P>
<P>
   Against Cornell, Dartmouth snapped a 10-game losing streak,
scoring first on a blocked punt and stopping Cornell's passing game
with seven sacks and two interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Brown is averaging 35.3 points per game behind James Perry, who
was 31 for 50 passing in a 44-37 win over Pennsylvania last week.
</P>
<P>
   Holy Cross (2-4, 1-1 Patriot League) will try to bounce back
from a 62-8 loss at Lehigh when the Crusaders meet St. Mary's (1-7)
in Moraga, Calif.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
