<HEADLINE>
TIPS ON WINTERIZING YOUR HOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   So far, so good. We've hardly had a day or night when the heat
came on.
</P>
<P>
   But don't hold your breath. The cold will come, and it can be
pretty uncomfortable if you and your house are not ready for it.
You want to be ready so you don't run around trying to fix things
at the last minute.
</P>
<P>
   And, we are not talking about just saving fuel and being snug as
a bug in your house, but also about winterizing your house and
doing things to make it survives the ravages of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a checklist to help with that preparation. Most of the
chores are easy and will not take much time, or are to be done by
professionals.
</P>
<P>
   Heating systems
</P>
<P>
   If you have a heating contract (one that pays for repairs and
maintenance), your furnace or boiler has already been checked and
tuned, and that goes for the burner as well as the boiler (hot
water) or furnace (hot air) itself.
</P>
<P>
   What you can do: For a hot-air furnace, check the filters and
change them if necessary. But remember, a dirty filter is more
efficient than a clean one because it will stop more dust and other
particles. Eventually, enough dirt will build up to block the
system completely, and there goes the heat, not in your house. So
change the filter when necessary, usually three or four times a
season.
</P>
<P>
   Oil burners need checking and tuning more than gas burners.
</P>
<P>
   For wood or pellet stoves or fireplaces, have the chimney
cleaned regularly.
</P>
<P>
   If you are not getting any heat, call the pro.
</P>
<P>
   Check the chimney to make sure all flues are open. During the
off-season the chimney might have deteriorated and dropped debris
down a flue and partially blocked it. Animals and birds might have
done the same thing, without your knowing it. A chimney sweep can
inspect your chimney, and clean it if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   One thing you can do all winter long to save heat and fuel is
turn down the thermostat at night and turn it up in the morning. Of
course, getting your roommate to cooperate is another matter.
</P>
<P>
   That dilemma could be solved with a programmable thermostat,
with the changes preselected. Now if you can only agree to those
preselected changes.
</P>
<P>
   Windows
</P>
<P>
   Make sure windows are tight. Check the weatherstripping and
replace it or add new if there is none there or what is there has
deteriorated. Good weatherstripping can stop the shake, rattle, and
roll of your windows.
</P>
<P>
   You can caulk inside frames (but not the movable sash) with a
caulking gun. Avoid caulking outdoors; it may be ineffective, and
improper caulking can trap water around windows, causing decay.
</P>
<P>
   And, check the aluminum storms, if you have them. Lower or raise
them to the proper position. And the proper position is this: The
top sash goes toward the outside, the bottom sash goes toward the
inside. Sound weird? Not at all: These storms slide up and down in
grooves in the frame, making it easy to remove them for washing and
to raise and lower them according to the season.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes someone will lower the upper sash instead of the
bottom sash, leaving the bottom sash in the ``up'' position. If
that happens, the checkrail will be wide open and water, snow, and
cold air will go in there as sure as you can say ``darn!''
</P>
<P>
   Still confused? Look at your regular double-hung window, one
that slides up and down vertically. You will see that the top sash
is the outer sash, the bottom sash the inner sash. The storm sash
works the same way.
</P>
<P>
   Make sure the little weep holes at the bottom of the storm are
open; they should be open all year long to allow water to drain and
to keep the windows from fogging up. If they are clogged, open them
with a coat hanger wire. If there are none, make some; drill
1/8-inch holes as close as possible to the bottom of the frame
where it meets the wood sill, four inches in from each side.
</P>
<P>
   If you have no storms, you can buy and install them yourself, or
you can hire a contractor to do it. Be sure to get a quality storm;
a top-rated storm costs about $100 each.
</P>
<P>
   For a stopgap storm, buy a plastic kit, for one-time use on the
inside, for a lot less money.
</P>
<P>
   All the above applies to doors as well as windows, except for
the weepholes and plastic storm. And make sure the bottom of the
door has a good sweep or threshold that blocks leaks.
</P>
<P>
   To check the bottom seal, belly down to the floor to see if you
can see daylight through the crack. If no daylight, forget it. If
daylight shows, you have to do something about it; door bottoms are
notorious losers of heat.
</P>
<P>
   The best way to fix a leaky door bottom is to install a movable
threshold, one that pops up when the door is open, and pops down
snugly when it is closed.
</P>
<P>
   Water lines
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and don't forget to shut off your outside faucets. If they
freeze in winter, you will have a big pipe repair job.
</P>
<P>
   Most outside faucets are shut off indoors. Usually it takes just
turning the handle and opening the outside faucet so water can
drain out.
</P>
<P>
   Older faucets may require not only shutting off the inside valve
but opening a small drain cock on the faucet (one with a little cap
on it, usually turned with pliers) to allow proper drainage.
</P>
<P>
   If you do all these things, and pay attention to insulation,
caulking, and tight windows, you may find that you won't have to
turn the thermostat up so high.
</P>
<P>
   If this all turns you off, you can always move to Florida, where
people whine a lot if the temperature drops below 40. Then you can
tell them, in a superior tone, ``You ain't seen nothin' yet!''
</P>
<P>
   And, there are a few other things you should do, if you don't go
south, although they have nothing really to do with keeping warm
and saving heat, but rather making sure the house gets through the
winter.
</P>
<P>
   Gutters, painting, and cracks
</P>
<P>
   Clean out the gutters; after all, they do a lot of their work in
winter, and a clogged gutter or downspout will simply not work, and
can cause backup of water under the roof shingles. Install gutter
guards to prevent more debris from clogging them.
</P>
<P>
   If there are any trim pieces with exposed bare wood, be sure to
prime and paint them before the cold really sets in. Pine, the wood
of choice for woodwork and trim, does not stand up to weather, even
for a short tme. If you can't paint it, at least try to get a coat
of primer on it before it's too cold.
</P>
<P>
   See to cracks anywhere: in driveways, sidewalks, and
foundations.
</P>
<P>
   Cracks in these places will fill with water, and in winter will
freeze and expand, making the cracks bigger and bigger until major
repairs are needed.
</P>
<P>
   For asphalt pavement, fill cracks with asphalt crack filler,
which comes in a caulking cartridge for easy installation.
</P>
<P>
   For concrete, chip out the crack to at least 3/4-inch wide and
deep, and fill with mortar, packing it in compactly.
</P>
<P>
   Vertical cracks in foundations are less likely to cause
problems, so can be left alone, as long as they are not leaking.
</P>
<P>
   OK, this all should keep you busy for the weekend.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-99 1446EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991028.0218 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 14:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1302 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-COMPUTERS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      10-28 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELECTRONIC BANKING FITS THE BILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's getting tough to be a member of the Internet elite, now
that 40 percent of Americans are on line. Snobs like me find it
more difficult to stand apart from the common herd. Almost every
time I learn of some flashy Internet service, it turns out many of
you have gotten there ahead of me.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's on-line banking, a wonderfully useful concept
that most of you have ignored. It seems that only 4.5 percent of us
paid bills over the Internet last year, according to the Yankee
Group, a Boston research firm. I'm one of that happy few; I began
using an on-line banking service in 1996, and I've never regretted
it.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, I'm not quite at the cutting edge. I don't use one of
the true Internet banks, like Security First Network Bank. Now
owned by Royal Bank of Canada, Security First (www.sfnb.com) was
the first bank to exist entirely on line. No offices, no vaults, no
teller windows, nothing but Net. No thanks.
</P>
<P>
   I prefer the reassurance of bricks and mortar. But my bank, like
dozens of others, allows me to check balances and write checks from
my home computer, with the aid of Intuit Corp.'s Quicken financial
software package.
</P>
<P>
   When bills show up in the mailbox, I start up Quicken. The
addresses and account numbers are already typed in. I just fill in
the amounts, weep quietly over my depleted bank balance, then log
onto the Net and electronically issue the payments.
</P>
<P>
   And here's where it gets interesting. If you're paying bills
electronically, shouldn't the money arrive instantly, sort of like
an e-mail message? Well, it doesn't. Many companies have no way of
accepting electronic payments. In that case, Intuit sends the
payments to a facility in Utah, which prints and mails the checks.
If you're paying your local plumber, the payment would arrive
quicker if you'd mailed it yourself. You may need to pay your bills
earlier if you do it electronically.
</P>
<P>
   Some big companies now accept direct electronic payments, which
helps, but not as much as you'd think. Electronic payments are
handled by a clearinghouse system that processes the data in
batches. Your payment won't just get zapped directly to the phone
company _ it still has to ``clear.'' And that can take a couple of
days.
</P>
<P>
   So why bother with electronic bill payment? The sheer
convenience of it. Your software remembers addresses, account
numbers, and amounts; you have a permanent record of the bills
you've paid. Sending out a new batch of checks is as easy as
pushing a few buttons.
</P>
<P>
   It's so convenient, in fact, that a horde of companies are
offering up Net-based bill payment systems that don't require
special software like Quicken. Any old Web browser will do.
</P>
<P>
   Electronic Funds &AMP; Data Corp. of Southampton, N.Y., offers a
service called Jackdough (www.jackdough.com) that aims to create a
new generation of electronic bankers. Jackdough is available
exclusively to college students. And unlike other computer
bill-paying services, it's free. The site provides links to music
and book stores, and even a credit counseling service. Chief
executive Gary Glanz is hoping to turn young kids into lifelong
customers, then try to peddle them mortgages and car loans when
they graduate.
</P>
<P>
   Another high-profile competitor, Paytrust.com of Princeton,
N.J., hopes to transform the bill-paying process.
</P>
<P>
   For $7.95 a month, Paytrust subscribers won't get bills in the
mail. Instead, they all go straight to Paytrust (www.paytrust.com),
which displays them on an encrypted, password-protected Web page.
The system also fires off an e-mail notice. To make a payment, the
user types in the amount and the payment date. Paytrust deducts the
money from an existing bank account. Users can even tell the
service to make certain payments automatically _ rent or mortgage,
say.
</P>
<P>
   The company is also trying to take the next step in the process
_ the complete elimination of paper bills. They're working to
develop a system to let companies submit their bills
electronically.
</P>
<P>
   With computers in more than half of all homes, it's a mystery to
me why we aren't all using some form of on-line banking. And yet,
if everybody did it, it just wouldn't be as cool.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Hiawatha Bray at bray(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
