<HEADER>
A1305 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIES-BLACKS-BOS &LR;      10-28 1150
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-BLACKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEDDING BLACK PROFESSIONALS, RELATIONSHIPS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By VANESSA E. JONES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Four men sit at a table playing cards. Like a male version of
the war council scene in the film ``Jungle Fever,'' where a group
of women engage in frank talk about men, the guys discuss their
ideal woman.
</P>
<P>
   Lance is looking for an angel who will forgo her career in favor
of marriage and children. For Quentin, there is no ideal, he plows
through women like a lawn mower. Murch doesn't mind having a
powerful mate who makes more money than him. And Harper's friends
call him the serial monogamist.
</P>
<P>
   The discussion is one that any group of male friends could have.
But in this case, the four men are African-Americans in the
romantic comedy ``The Best Man,'' which opened last Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The film, which was number one at the box office and made $9
million during its first week of release, centers on Harper (Taye
Diggs), an author whose dishy novel is peppered with characters and
experiences based on his college days. The book causes Harper's
school buddies to address issues of fidelity, friendship, and love
when they reunite in New York for Lance's wedding.
</P>
<P>
   With scenes like the card game, ``The Best Man'' delves into
relationships in a realistic way that camp sex comedies like
``Booty Call,'' ``Sprung,'' and ``How To Be A Player'' have not.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think for women it's a real (chance) to peek into a world
that they rarely get to see,'' says Malcolm Lee, writer and
director of ``The Best Man.'' `` `Is this what they talk about? Is
that how they talk?' And the answer is, `Yes, we do.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Movies aren't the only medium dissecting male/female
connections. An increasing number of songs, television shows, and
books are examining relationships.
</P>
<P>
   Hit songs like TLC's ``No Scrubs'' and Destiny's Child's
``Bills, Bills, Bills'' denounce men with no money. The
relationship book ``What Brothers Think, What Sistahs Know''
entered the Black Board Bestseller List, which tracks sales of
African-American books, at number one when it was published earlier
this year.
</P>
<P>
   In September, the BET cable channel debuted the first of 10
feature films based on the African-American romance novel line,
Arabesque. And ``The Best Man'' follows on the heels of ``The
Wood,'' a $6 million film that has made $25 million since its July
debut. Both movies are ensemble comedies centering on young male
friends who explore the complexities of romance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Relationships are a good subject matter,'' says Lee, 29.
``People are trying to figure out why men do this and why women are
like that. It's a wonder how we even hook up in the first place. So
I think there's a lot of gold to be mined there.''
</P>
<P>
   African-American films tend to be released in genre waves, says
Todd Boyd, a professor of critical studies at the University of
Southern California's School of Cinema and Television. There were
the blaxploitation films of the 1970s, the inner-city ``hood''
films of the early 1990s, and the hip-hop sex comedies of the late
1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Best Man'' and ``The Wood'' may be the beginning of a new
genre cycle, says Boyd, who co-wrote the screenplay for ``The
Wood.'' ``But I think instead of having one genre be popular at one
time, we need to have multiple genres popular at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   Love has always had a place in African-American films, but it's
usually been a peripheral position. In recent years, a smattering
of films, like ``Boomerang,'' ``Love Jones,'' ``Soul Food,'' and
``Waiting to Exhale,'' have put the spotlight on relationships.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, there's still a feeling that when positive romances are
depicted on the large and small screen, viewers are seeing
something rare.
</P>
<P>
   Eriq LaSalle took the writers of the television series ``ER'' to
task earlier this year because the show didn't portray healthy
relationships between blacks. LaSalle's character, Dr. Peter
Benton, had an affair with a married African-American woman, then
had a child out of wedlock with another black woman.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Chiles, co-author of ``What Brothers Think, What Sistahs
Know,'' sees how such images affect children. He teaches a writing
program for teenagers on weekends with his co-author and wife of
two years, Denene Millner.
</P>
<P>
   ``They truly think that this is the way things work,'' says
Chiles as Millner sings the chorus of ``Bills, Bills, Bills,'' a
song where a woman asks her boyfriend pay her bills or pack his
bags. ``To have a counter to that like `The Best Man' is so very
important.''
</P>
<P>
   The stereotypes perpetuated in songs and television can have a
larger impact, as well, adds Diggs, who made his film debut in
another romance, ``How Stella Got Her Groove Back.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You get pigeonholed into thinking this is how black people are
if you only have only one representation of them,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Lee, cousin of filmmaker Spike Lee, says ``The Best Man'' was
inspired by ``The Big Chill,'' ``Diner,'' and ``Waiting to
Exhale.'' It's filled with African-American professionals,
something that Lee, a graduate of Georgetown University and New
York University's film school, felt he hadn't seen often on
television or in movies.
</P>
<P>
   There's the ambitious television producer Jordan Armstrong (Nia
Long), who draws criticism from her male friends for pursuing a
career rather than love. The author (Diggs) who leaves his
girlfriend Robin (Sanaa Lathan) in love limbo because he hasn't
gotten over his college crush (Long). And there are Lance (Morris
Chestnut) and Quintin (Terrence Howard) who have a long history of
sleeping around and push Harper to do the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Best Man'' gave Millner, 31, a feeling of familiarity she
hadn't felt since she saw ``Love Jones,'' a 1997 film about a
Chicago couple doing the mating dance.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the way my friends and I act,'' she says. ``We fall in
love, we have relationships, we fall out of love, we have
friendships, we bond, we fight, we get mad, we get glad. But it's
so rare to see it on the screen.''
</P>
<P>
   There were some characters Chiles, 34, found stereotypical, like
Lance and Quentin.
</P>
<P>
   ``They always have the dog in there trying to push everyone to
be unfaithful,'' he says. ``I'm not sure that guys do that to each
other. Guys stay out of relationships.''
</P>
<P>
   But the film's take on professional women was on point, Millner
says: ``When we're out talking to audiences (on book tours), `Why
can't black men deal with strong black women?' turns into an
hourlong discussion.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee is so confident relationships will continue to transfix
people that he's already writing another romantic comedy for
Universal Pictures, the studio that released ``The Best Man.''
Tentatively titled ``Sex and the Married Man,'' the film, Lee
promises, will delve even deeper into the eternal conundrum of love
between the sexes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-99 1451EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
