<SLUG> BC-TREK-JAMES-MARSTERS-IN-BUFFY-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VAMPING WITH JAMES MARSTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Inside Trek, a
weekly science-fiction column with color and black-and-white art.)
 (Includes a color slide and a black-and-white photo of James
Marsters in a scene from ``Angel.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    James Marsters likes vampires as much as the next guy _ he just
never counted on making his living playing one.
 &HT;    But as the ferocious Spike on both ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer''
and ``Angel,'' the 28-year-old actor is doing precisely that.
 &HT;    ``How could I imagine any of this?'' Marsters says by telephone
from his ``Buffy'' trailer during a lunch break. ``Spike was
supposed to die within three to five episodes. The original idea
was that I was kind of an ornament for Dru (Juliet Landau). Angel
(David Boreanaz) would go and kill me, presumably as one of his
first acts of evil, then take Dru as his new paramour.
 &HT;    ``So I was very surprised to be asked to come back after my
fifth `Buffy' episode,'' he says. ``I think (series creator/writer)
Joss Whedon just said, `You don't suck so bad.'''
 &HT;    Actually, Marsters sucked so well that Whedon kept summoning the
Slayer-slaying vamp. Spike _ whose penchant for torturing people
with railroad spikes inspired his nickname _ wreaked havoc
throughout much of season two, beginning with ``School Hard.''
 &HT;    He was eventually left burned to a crisp and wheelchair-bound,
but recovered enough to raise some hell in season three's ``Lovers
Walk.'' Now that Angel has landed his own show, Whedon elected to
spike ``Buffy'' with more Spike.
 &HT;    Starting on Nov. 16, with the episode entitled ``The
Initiative,'' Marsters joins ``Buffy'' as a regular, co-starring
with title slayer Sarah Michelle Gellar. He'll also make his bite
felt on ``Angel,'' guest-starring on another one or two episodes
during that series' freshman season.
 &HT;    So what's on tap on ``Buffy'' _ besides a new gal (Mercedes
McNab as Harmony) and a likely visit from a sure-to-be-jealous Dru?
 &HT;    ``I don't know,'' Marsters says. ``I don't mean to be an
a--hole, but I really only get details script to script. Also, I'm
shackled by Joss' need for secrecy, which I completely respect _ as
a storyteller, he needs to be able to deal the cards as he wants
to.
 &HT;    ``Suffice it to say that I was more evil and violent than ever
in the `Buffy'/`Angel' crossover, and we'll take it from there,''
he says. ``Whatever happens with Spike, he'll be the same on both
`Buffy' and `Angel.' Everything will be the same _ the hair, the
makeup, the attitude.
 &HT;    ``I haven't been on Buffy's side so far, but I assume that
something will have to change or they'll have to stake me,''
Marsters adds. ``I've given up trying to second-guess what they're
going to put on my plate, because every time I think I know where
they're going, they go in the exact opposite direction and, of
course, mine much more gold than I ever would have found.
 &HT;    ``If it were up to me,'' he concludes, ``I'd only be killing a
lot of people and quipping. And they're taking the character in a
lot of different directions.''
 &HT;    Though the California native counts among his credits episodes
of ``Northern Exposure'' and the as-yet-unreleased indie feature
``Winding Roads,'' he's done his share of genre work: ``Buffy''
buffs remember his guest-star spot in a ``Millennium'' hour and
know that he appears briefly in the upcoming horror flick ``The
House on Haunted Hill.''
 &HT;    Right now, though, Spike is Marsters' calling card.
 &HT;    ``People who meet me on the street want me to bite them,''
Marsters says. ``I'll get girls who say, `Bite here, baby!' _ and
then my girlfriend kicks their a--.
 &HT;    ``In general, I get a lot of `You look like Spike' comments,''
he says. ``People think the character is British _ and I, of
course, am not _ so they'll inch forward and listen to my accent,
and sometimes they'll get a disappointed look in their eyes and
leave.
 &HT;    ``Sometimes they'll come up to me and say I look like Spike.''
Marsters adds. ``I'll turn around and say, `But, love, I am
Spike.''' 
 c.1999 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer,''
consult the Warner Bros. Network Website at www.thewb.com. And
don't forget to visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on Inside Trek and
Sci-Fi and other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to Inside Trek, a
weekly science-fiction column with color and black-and-white art.)
