<HEADER>
A1317 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MEDIA-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      10-28 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRUG `STORIES' ACTUALLY MAY GIVE BUSH A LIFT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This summer, George W. Bush looked like a prizefighter slumping
into the ropes. On the nagging issue of past cocaine use, Bush
began drawing movable lines in the sand. First, he hadn't used
drugs in seven years. Then he amended it to 25 years. It was the
kind of backing, filling, and parsing that invites
character-hunting journalists in for the kill.
</P>
<P>
   Yet a few months later _ given the fresh fiasco over the book
``Fortunate Son'' and its now-disbelieved allegations of a 1972
Bush cocaine bust _ Bush's strategy looks like the ``Rope-a-dope''
tactic Muhammad Ali used to knock out George Foreman.
</P>
<P>
   With every mighty swing that fails to produce legitimate
evidence of a Bush-cocaine link, the media not only damage their
credibility, they make Bush appear to be the victim of a witch hunt
while taking the political sting out of the drug issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, the story has gone so well for Bush, I suspect he's
driving it,'' notes Craig Crawford, editor of the political Hotline
newsletter. ``It makes him look like he's been hounded by the
irresponsible media . . . It's all about the messenger.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a story that seems to have leapfrogged the simple
question of whether there is any truth to it or not,'' adds Paul
Taylor, the former journalist who once asked presidential candidate
Gary Hart whether he committed adultery and who is now executive
director of the Alliance for Better Campaigns. ``The only thing
that's going to make this an interesting story is a set of facts.
And that hasn't arrived yet.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest chapter in this saga began to unravel last week with
the anonymously sourced drug allegations in ``Fortunate Son.''
While many news outlets didn't bite at that tidbit, Bush's
subsequent denials made headlines everywhere. Yet, those denials
paled in comparison to the damage done to ``Fortunate Son'' when
publisher St. Martin's Press recalled the book after it was learned
that author J. H. Hatfield was a former convict who once hired a
hitman. And on Tuesday, St. Martin's editor in chief Robert Wallace
resigned over the ``Fortunate Son'' fallout (see accompanying
story). In an e-mail posted on The Drudge Report, Hatfield
complained that he has become the victim of a ``smear campaign''
and ``character assassination.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The (`Fortunate Son') incident could not have been designed
better by the Bush campaign itself,'' says ``Feeding Frenzy''
author Larry Sabato. ``It's hard to believe.''
</P>
<P>
   The most recent false alarm notwithstanding, unsubstantiated
allegations of Bush drug use have managed to reverberate inside the
media culture for months. In May, The Wall Street Journal ran an
extraordinary piece investigating the rumors and concluding that no
one had yet offered ``a shred of proof.'' Still, that didn't stop
the paper from rehashing gossip that Bush had used cocaine at his
father's inauguration. And jokes about the Texas governor's drug
use are now a staple of Jay Leno's ``Tonight Show'' shtick.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, all this public airing of a rumor may have the
effect of desensitizing voters to the once potentially explosive
subject of drug use by a presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like when the Exxon Valdez spills oil all over Alaska.
And the Exxon stock doesn't change, and someone says it's already
been factored into the market,'' says Brookings Institution senior
fellow Stephen Hess. ``I have the same feeling in political terms.
The (Bush drug matter) has already been factored into the market.''
</P>
<P>
   A recent Quinnipiac College poll revealed that by a 56-41
percent majority, voters felt they had a right to know about a
candidate's past cocaine use. But that was viewed as a less urgent
matter than news of a candidate cheating on taxes, avoiding
military service, and having past alcohol problems. And in a
September Pew Research Center poll, only 35 percent felt that
cocaine use by a politician almost always merited media scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   Some observers suggest that this apparent tolerance on the
cocaine issue is a reflection of changing mores and the legacy of
Bill Clinton's foibles of the flesh. But Taylor disagrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are we becoming more like the French?,'' he says. ``There's no
question we've been exposed to more. But I don't think our
fundamental character has changed that much.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the explanation lies in the column that Arizona Republic
reader advocate Richard de Uriarte wrote this week criticizing the
media for running the kind of ``shaky'' sex and scandal story
``that only confuses and desensitizes people.''
</P>
<P>
   Crawford puts it another way. ``You know who'd be the most
regretful'' to see the media stop publishing gossip and rumor about
drug use, he asks? ``The Bush campaign.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
