<SLUG> BC-BBA-RATTO-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES TRADITION EXTENDS TO A NEW GENERATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RAY RATTO  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ This is exactly how our parents and grandparents
remember the baseball of their youths _ with two major leagues, the
New York Yankees and all the other teams.
</P>
<P>
   Even the scene inside the Yankee clubhouse after the 4-1 victory
over the Atlanta Braves that gave them their third championship in
four years had that look of the old Yankee teams that celebrated
championships. There wasn't a lot of howling and screeching like
they'd hit the lottery, as there was three years ago or even last
October in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   This time, they all looked like smart investors who just found
out about a stock split. Happy, but fully expecting the reward they
were celebrating. There was champagne, but it was used more for
drinking than for spilling. There were smiles, but not shrieks.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees of the '90s acted as the Yankees of the '50s did,
and the '40s and '30s before them _ as though they knew more than
everyone else, and could prove it to anyone who wanted to argue the
point.
</P>
<P>
   Even Paul O'Neill, the right fielder whose father had died that
very morning and ran off the field rubbing tears from his eyes,
kept it Yankee-like.
</P>
<P>
   He told Fox broadcaster Steve Lyons not to ask about his
tragedy, gave a few Yankee-like responses about winning and being a
proper teammate (``We came into the playoffs wanting to get off the
right way, and we're used to playing close games, and big games,
because we've done it all year''), and then disappeared to face the
bleakness of the next few days.
</P>
<P>
   But the Yankees know that, too. Scott Brosius' father died.
</P>
<P>
   So did Luis Sojo's. Manager Joe Torre had cancer. There were
subplots everywhere, but the main story was the baseball team.
</P>
<P>
   Just as it always seemed to be when the Yankees were baseball,
and everyone else seemed only to be renting space.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what everyone said it was all about,'' said Roger
Clemens, the All-Century pitcher who chased the demons that only a
man who played in Boston for a decade can truly know. ``Now I know
what it really feels like to be a Yankee.''
</P>
<P>
   He earned his pinstripes by constructing a masterwork that was
every bit as Yankee-esque as anything Whitey Ford, Allie Reynolds
or Red Ruffing ever erected. Clemens allowed the Braves only four
hits in 7 2/3 innings, and none of those 23 outs reached the
outfield. He allowed 17 ground outs, four strikeouts and two
infield popups, and were it not for his being bundled over on a
close play at first base in the eighth and the presence of Mariano
Rivera, the closer for the end of millennium, Clemens might even
have finished.
</P>
<P>
   That, though, might have been gilding the lily a bit.
</P>
<P>
   Rivera deserved his moment, too, just as second baseman Chuck
Knoblauch did, as Brosius and Sojo and O'Neill and Derek Jeter and
all the other champions. The Yankees won bragging rights to the
decade because they understood, as their forbears had, that the
Yankees at their best stand as a collective.
</P>
<P>
   For this, they have Torre to thank, and Jeter, the obvious focal
point who doesn't act like one, and even owner George Steinbrenner,
who provides as much as he ever did without the concomitant
preening that soiled the Yankees of the '80s.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, these Yankees live off their history. For them, the
gruesome '80s never really happened, or the decaying '60s, either.
They reach back to the days when the Yankees won 11 American League
pennants in 13 years under Casey Stengel, or seven of eight titles
under Joe McCarthy in the '30s and early '40s.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, many people, perhaps carried away by the immediacy of
the moment, said this Yankee team was better than the one that won
125 games and swept San Diego last year, or the one that beat the
Braves after losing the first two games in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Those people see the tragedies overcome, the more mundane
struggles endured (Darryl Strawberry's fall from and rise to
sobriety, Knoblauch's throwing problems, the Andy Pettitte trade
rumors) and see this Yankee team as a model of excellence through
melodrama.
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe. But it is the excellence rather than the melodrama
that will endure. They blew through the postseason with only one
loss, the first team to do so under the present format, and they
became the third team in history to sweep successive Series. That
is the kind of history that sticks to a fellow's head.
</P>
<P>
   Even the Braves, all blank looks and shaking heads, understood
at least that much. They had overwhelmed National League
opposition, as the Dodgers of the '50s and the Cardinals of the
'40s and the Giants of the '30s had, and they had no more complaint
about their fate than those teams did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe we were outmatched,'' said pitcher John
Smoltz, once again the unlucky loser. ``But I believe we were
outplayed. Every play you make, everything you try, they have an
answer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If I pitch like I did tonight (six hits, 11 strikeouts, three
runs allowed on two infield plays unmade) 10 times, I think I'd win
nine of them. But I didn't win tonight. It's amazing. That's why
they're who they are.''
</P>
<P>
   A team for the decade, yes. More than that, though, a reminder
of the teams and decades that preceded them. At the end of the
century, the Yankees showed a new generation what two earlier
generations saw. History doesn't get better than that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
