<HEADLINE>
THE VIEW FROM `MALKOVICH' A WACKY ONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anyone who happens to wander into ``Being John Malkovich''
expecting a documentary about, or maybe a one-man show by, the
noted and often pompously serious actor whose name is so
prominently mentioned in the title is in for one big surprise.
</P>
<P>
   The film is actually a body-changing farce, a revival of that
prototypically '80s subgenre (``Big,'' etc.), and one that's a
little more goofy and bizarre than anything that's come before it
in this strange category. It's quite a lot of fun.
</P>
<P>
   It's about a dedicated but failed puppeteer named Craig Schwartz
(John Cusack) who takes a job as a file clerk in a Manhattan
office. One day he discovers a secret portal that leads directly to
a view window of the world as observed from John Malkovich's
consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   That's right. And before long, the puppeteer, his sexy co-worker
(Catherine Keener) and his shy pet store-owner wife (Cameron Diaz)
are making regular 15-minute trips into the actor's brain and
selling tickets to the public at $200 a pop.
</P>
<P>
   It's essentially a one-joke situation, but screenwriter Charlie
Kaufman and first-time director Spike Jonze definitely make the
most of it, carrying the gag to ever more absurd and sexually kinky
lengths, and even flirt with turning it into a profound existential
statement.
</P>
<P>
   Good sport Malkovich himself is along for the ride, gradually
taking center stage, poking fun at himself in the process and
bringing in pals Charlie Sheen, Sean Penn and Brad Pitt for cameos.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the cast is even better. Keener and Diaz, each going
against their customary type, are delightful; Cusack has never
created a more likable loser; and old pro Orson Bean steps out of
oblivion to almost steal the movie. Everyone in this clever, funny
film seems to be having a great time, and so do we.
</P>
<P>
   Being John Malkovich. Directed by Spike Jonze. Written by
Charlie Kaufman. Cast: John Cusack, Cameron Diaz, Catherine Keener,
Orson Bean, John Malkovich, Charlie Sheen. USA Films. 120 minutes.
Rated R for sexual situations.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-99 1513EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
