<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-HEART-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MUSIC OF THE HEART' IMPARTS AN AUTHENTIC LUMP IN THE THROAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Oscar-nominated 1996 documentary ``Small Wonders'' was a
moving parable about an inexperienced but gutsy divorcee named
Roberta Guaspari who steamed into the East Harlem elementary school
system one day and single-handedly created a nationally recognized
violin-instruction program.
</P>
<P>
   Fans of this inspired film may find a few things to quibble
about in ``Music of the Heart,'' a somewhat fictionalized,
big-budget, dramatic version of the same story.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, however, it takes us to the same place as its model _ a
teary appreciation of the value of a good teacher, the joy of music
and the payoffs of discipline and hard work _ while offering yet
another irresistible performance by Meryl Streep.
</P>
<P>
   The first half of the film chronicles how Guaspari (Streep)
convinces a disbelieving principal (Angela Bassett) to let her
start a large-scale program to teach an instrument that seems, at
first glance, highly irrelevant to inner-city life.
</P>
<P>
   The second half is set 10 years later, and basically tells the
``Small Wonders'' story: The well-established program is suddenly
axed due to insensitive budget cuts, and Guaspari and her students
try to save it with a gala fund-raiser that turns into a convention
of violin superstars.
</P>
<P>
   In the process, Pamela Gray's script is smart enough to
re-create the documentary's best characters, more inspiring moments
and climactic concert finale. It also avoids most of the sappiness
inherent in the ``inspiring teacher'' genre to impart an authentic,
well-earned lump in the throat.
</P>
<P>
   In a big career change of pace, horror director Wes Craven does
a competent enough job, but he could often use a lighter touch, and
he never can figure out what to do with Gloria Estefan in her brief
but billed-above-the-title movie debut.
</P>
<P>
   As Guaspari, Streep seems much softer than the hard-charging
real thing, and she dissolves into tears in almost every scene, but
she's ultimately quite convincing and more than likely to ride the
performance to a record-tying 12th Oscar nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Music of the Heart. Directed by Wes Craven. Screenplay by Pamela
Gray. Cast: Meryl Streep, Aidan Quinn, Gloria Estefan, Angela
Bassett, Jane Leeves. Miramax. 123 minutes. Rated PG.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
