<HEADER>
A1363 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e BC-FILM-BOYS-SPI &LR;      10-28 0580
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-BOYS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RADICALLY DISTURBING, `BOYS DON'T CRY' IS A BOLD CAUTIONARY TALE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``What were you like before all this?'' asks Lana (Chloe
Sevigny), the young woman who has fallen hard for Brandon Teena
(Hilary Swank), a heartbreakingly handsome youth passing through
the dreary Nebraska landscape where Lana lives.
</P>
<P>
   She asks because she's just learned the boy of her dreams is
really a young woman named Teena Ray Brandon.
</P>
<P>
   Brandon just wanted the freedom to wander the world without fear
so she dresses as a boy. But that desire has led to mayhem and
murder.
</P>
<P>
   First-time feature director Kimberly Peirce was mesmerized by
the real-life tragedy of Teena Ray Brandon, who became a gay icon
after her 1993 death. As a graduate thesis, Peirce wrote a script
based on Brandon's last days, focusing on the less iconic and more
humane aspects of this young teenager from Lincoln, Neb.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who was he, really?'' she wondered. ``And why had he incited
such a violent reaction?''
</P>
<P>
   What emerged was the idea that Brandon was an imaginative,
capricious, danger-loving character who had committed petty theft
but was, according to the women he befriended, ``a perfect
gentleman,'' ``so cute'' and a guy who ``knew how a woman wants to
be treated.''
</P>
<P>
   Peirce has captured that essence triumphantly as well as
instilling Brandon with a loyal heart and a huge capacity to love
and be loved.
</P>
<P>
   But Brandon's ability to love women well worked against her in
the end. Brandon became the victim of a heinous hate crime after
Lana's ex-con boyfriend, John Lotter (Peter Sarsgaard), and his pal
Thomas Nissen (Brendan Sexton III) decided to stop the charismatic
youth from testifying against them.
</P>
<P>
   Like the stark, restless and chafing films of Terrence Malick
(``Days of Heaven,'' ``Badlands'') or the anti-hero, true-crime
classics ``Bonnie and Clyde,'' ``In Cold Blood'' and ``The
Executioner's Song,'' Peirce's film has captured the mystique and
eerie loneliness and isolation of the Midwest, with its dusty
desolation and nowhere-to-go frustration that propels people to
violence and despair.
</P>
<P>
   But despite her talent with a camera and script, Peirce may
never have made Teena Ray Brandon's story come so vibrantly and
poignantly to life had she not found the right actress for the
role.
</P>
<P>
   Hilary Swank, a tall beauty who is just androgynous enough to
pass for a young man, inhabits the character and gives her
heartbreaking conviction, ardor and vulnerability.
</P>
<P>
   It's a marvelous performance that is supported ably by Sevigny
as the smitten Lana, Sarsgaard as the unpredictable, sociopathic
Lotter and Jeanetta Arnette as Lana's good-time-gal mom.
</P>
<P>
   Even better, Peirce has evoked larger issues.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than producing a true-crime thriller, she's taken on
gender, class, sexual identity and cultural _ as well as political
_ themes and tied them together so compellingly that ``Boys Don't
Cry'' emerges as a radically disturbing and memorable movie whose
images don't easily fade or diminish in power. The film is a
cautionary tale about ignorance and intolerance.
</P>
<P>
   Boys Don't Cry. Directed by Kimberly Peirce. Written by Peirce,
Andy Bienen. Cast: Hilary Swank, Chloe Sevigny, Jeanetta Arnette,
Peter Sarsgaard, Brendan Sexton III. Fox Searchlight Pictures. 114
minutes. Rated R for violence, sexual content, language.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-99 1528EDT &QL; 
