<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 15:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1365 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-THESUBURBANS-TEX     10-28 0508
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-THESUBURBANS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SUBURBANS' DRAGS ALONG TOO MUCH OF `TOO SOMETHING'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VH1's Behind the Music/Where Are They Now? craze, the '80s-music
revival, and MTV are all subjects ripe for parody. Heck, if you
want to make fun of 'em, they give you a running head start. So
it's pretty astonishing when the opportunity is botched, and ``The
Suburbans'' is a botch of record-breaking proportions.
</P>
<P>
   The fictional Suburbans of the title are a band that had one
hit, ``By My Side,'' way back in 1981. Let's introduce you to the
guys: Rhythm guitarist Danny (Donal Lardner Ward) has matured into
a dude terrified of commitment to his long-suffering girlfriend
(Amy Brenneman). Lead guitarist Mitch (Craig Bierko) has a
predilection for women _ and girls _ in uniform. Drummer Rory (Tony
Guma) is trying to make things work with divorcee Lara (Bridgette
Wilson) and her two bratty kids. And sweet, vacant bassist Gil
(Will Ferrell) is ... well, sweet and vacant.
</P>
<P>
   The movie opens during the early '80s _ a few years before
``This is Spinal Tap'' did this material much better _ with the
guys telling Dick Clark on ``American Bandstand'' that they don't
think MTV will ever catch on. Considering their skyscraper
hairstyles and cerulean-blue vinyl suits _ their image is
none-too-subtly modeled after The Romantics _ they seem more like
the type of guys who were sitting around just waiting for someone
to invent MTV.
</P>
<P>
   The Suburbans fade into oblivion, until they're coerced into
doing an impromptu reunion gig at Gil's wedding. A record exec
(Jennifer Love Hewitt) catches their performance, and persuades
them to attempt a comeback, even though ``By My Side'' appears to
be the only song they know.
</P>
<P>
   The screenplay, which was written by Guma and Ward, is supposed
to be funny. But, as with his earlier projects, ``My Life's In
Turnaround'' (a not-dissimilar take on indie filmmaking) and the
blink-and-you-missed it Fox sitcom ``Too Something,'' Ward has
demonstrated two things: 1. He is a sometimes-clever writer with
potential; 2. He is absolutely the wrong person to direct his
material or act in it.
</P>
<P>
   He has, however, provided opportunities for actors _ ``Too
Something'' helped introduce ``Ally McBeal's'' Portia de Rossi to
the world. ``The Suburbans'' provides opportunities for its cast,
also, for example, Brenneman, who breathes a sigh of relief that
her TV series ``Judging Amy'' is a hit.
</P>
<P>
   For some reason, TriStar decided to release this video-bound
movie to theaters in a few markets, including Dallas. Big D gets to
baby-sit this loser. It's not obnoxious, it's just clueless.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``The Suburbans''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 1 1/2 on a 1-5 scale
</P>
<P>
   Director: Donal Lardner Ward
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Donal Lardner Ward, Amy Brenneman
</P>
<P>
   Length: 81 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is a film critic for the Star-Telegram. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
