<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-49ERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR 49ERS, IT'S FAREWELL TIME FOR A DEDICATED QB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN CRUMPACKER and DWIGHT CHAPIN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA CLARA, Calif. _ San Francisco 49ers coach Steve Mariucci
has essentially retired Steve Young. Reading between the lines,
it's clear that Young's season, and likely his career, are over.
</P>
<P>
   The quaterback's denouement came over an eight-day period in
September in which he was battered by the New Orleans Saints and
absorbed a flagrant helmet-to-helmet hit by safety Chris Hewitt,
followed by a high-velocity shot from St. Louis Cardinals
cornerback Aeneas Williams that knocked the quarterback out briefly
and resulted in his fourth concussion in 35 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would all love him to be healthy and playing again,''
Mariucci said Wednesday, the day Young said he would like to play
again. ``However, it may be very unlikely he gets back into a 49er
uniform. There's always a glimmer of hope. It's really a long shot.
I have to be prepared to play without Steve indefinitely.''
</P>
<P>
   That said, it's time to thank Young for all he accomplished in
his eight-plus years as San Francisco's starter, as he helped
perpetuate nearly two decades of brilliance at the quarterback
position begun by Joe Montana late in the 1980 season.
</P>
<P>
   Young led the 49ers to victory in Super Bowl XXIX and was named
the game's most valuable player for throwing a record six touchdown
passes. He has been to the Pro Bowl seven times and has passed for
more than 32,000 yards, with 232 touchdown passes and 4,239 yards
rushing.
</P>
<P>
   Young said he would make ``a 1,000-percent recovery.'' But at
38, with a history of concussions, the risk is too great for Young
to continue playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very competitive but I also recognize all the potential in
the future, all the things that can be accomplished outside of
football,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been preparing for retirement since I started playing
football. ... You have to come to some realization that there are
more important things. There never was a question for me.''
</P>
<P>
   All of which makes playing again a risk, one the 49ers certainly
will not take after all they have been through on the matter. Young
has seen three outside specialists in addition to his own
neurologist, Dr. Gary Steinberg of Stanford Medical School, and
none of the four has cleared him to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a small part of me that would love to see him running
around throwing touchdown passes again,'' Mariucci said. ``The
whole world would love to see that. There's a larger part of me
that has to prepare for him not doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   Young's agent, Leigh Steinberg, has advised Young to retire
since 1997. But he understands his client's competitive desire.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not going to retire this season, so the retirement watch
can be called off,'' Steinberg said. ``He feels way too committed
to the team. He feels he needs to be there on the sidelines,
helping Jeff Garcia or helping in any way he can.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue of whether Young goes on injured reserve is immaterial
at this point. Putting him on injured reserve would free up a
roster spot, but Mariucci said the 49ers do not need another player
at the moment, especially not during a bye week. The 49ers return
Nov. 7 against Pittsburgh at Candlestick Park.
</P>
<P>
   In the four games he has missed, Young has remained involved
with the team he said has become ``imprinted'' on him. He has
practiced a little, attended meetings and has been encouraging
Garcia, his replacement.
</P>
<P>
   Going on the injured reserve list would mean Young could not
practice with the team but he could remain involved in everything
else.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very important to stay integrally involved with the team
and continue to practice,'' Young said. ``At the moment we are at a
critical part in the season. I wish I could be on the field. Right
now I can't. I'll do whatever I can to help the team, help Jeff,
help the coaches.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
