<HEADER>
A1372 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-MUSICOFTHEHEART-     10-28 0690
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-MUSICOFTHEHEART-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STREEP PLAYS IT IN THE KEY OF ANGER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Probably the scariest thing to most of horror film director Wes
Craven's fans is his casting Meryl Streep in one of his movies. It
could have been even scarier; original star Madonna dropped out
before shooting began. In ``Music of the Heart,'' Streep plays
Roberta Guaspari, trapped in a terror that's out of her hands at
the beginning of the movie. (Roberta's husband has abandoned her
with two young sons.)
</P>
<P>
   She weeps continually for the first 10 minutes of the film. Then
she hardens. With a mop of crimped hair and a face often twisted by
frustration, she doesn't try to contain her rage. It's hard to tell
whether her quick-to-anger attitude has always been in her or is
the aftereffect of her suddenly single status. No matter _ she's as
combative as Stone Cold Steve Austin.
</P>
<P>
   When Roberta shows up at the East Harlem school where she's
taken a job as a part-time music teacher, she finds an environment
as hostile as she is. Her fellow teachers ignore her, figuring she
won't be around long enough to get to know. The principal (Angela
Bassett) is just as no-nonsense as Roberta, and so is Roberta's mom
(Cloris Leachman). It's no wonder Roberta gets mad so often.
</P>
<P>
   At some point, almost everybody tells Roberta to pull herself
together. Even Aidan Quinn, as a boyfriend unwilling to commit,
offers a few pearls of wisdom. Finally, Roberta settles and is able
to instill her love for the violin in the kids she teaches. (Gloria
Estefan turns up as a parent who appreciates Roberta's efforts.)
Much of ``Music'' comes from the 1996 documentary ``Small
Wonders,'' which details the success that the hard-driving and
impolitic Guaspari had with the kids she taught violin.
</P>
<P>
   The subject is probably closer to Craven's purview than you
might believe initially, because his movies tend to place a value
on family and emotional attachment and to punish cynicism. In a
peculiar way, Craven's movies are about spiritual and psychological
testing; there can really be no other deconstruction of ``Nightmare
on Elm Street.''
</P>
<P>
   So, his attraction to the subject matter here makes sense.
Roberta is constantly being tested, with no otherworldly figures to
challenge her. The real specters of loss and failure are demons
enough.
</P>
<P>
   Craven also lightens the load with gallows humor. During a phone
conversation, Quinn asks Streep if she'll tell her co-workers she
quit her job because her husband left and nothing else matters. She
nods a vigorous, wordless yes on the other end of the phone. Most
of the time, Streep's performances suggest a prodigy on autopilot,
each moment having been plotted out a week before. (Example: In
nearly every movie in which Streep has a love scene, she seems to
open her eyes wide with delight during a kiss.) Maybe because she's
working with kids in many scenes here, her performance doesn't feel
as carefully planned; she looks natural with a violin, as if she's
lived with one under-chin all her life.
</P>
<P>
   There's not much anyone could do to pump the moisture out of
this melodrama, given the obvious uplift of the material. Because
of a funding shortage, the music program is to be dropped by the
school system, and Roberta and her friends and the parents get
together to put on a benefit concert that ends up being staged with
the help of Itzhak Perlman, Isaac Stern and Mark O'Connor _ playing
themselves _ at Carnegie Hall. Craven and writer Pamela Gray stick
closely to the events as they happened in ``Wonders,'' where they
had an almost magical quality. Here, things are low-key but
sentimental. It's ``Mrs. Holland's Heartstrings,'' or ``Rocky''
with violins.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Music of the Heart''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 on a 1-5 scale
</P>
<P>
   Director: Wes Craven
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Meryl Streep, Aidan Quinn, Angela Bassett
</P>
<P>
   Length: 124 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG _ mild profanity
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is a film critic for the Star-Telegram. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
