<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEART-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MUSIC OF THE HEART': THE TRIUMPH OF TALENT OVER TENURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Production notes at end) 
(jt) 
 By JANET MASLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a director best known for his ``Nightmare on Elm Street'' and
``Scream'' series, Wes Craven has long been associated with
violence. Now he has made a film about violins. This may appear to
be a fabulous typographical error, if not such a hot movie idea.
</P>
<P>
   But times appear to be changing, to the point where creeping
cinematic squareness actually looks like a new wave. Incredibly,
the same kind of spiritual U-turn that drew a lawn mower adventure
out of David Lynch (``The Straight Story'') has also made a niceguy of Craven. His ``Music of the Heart,'' about how a real woman
named Roberta Guaspari (whose story has also been the subject of a
documentary, ``Small Wonders'') evolved from a rejected wife into
an inspired violin teacher, turns out to be thoroughly appealing.
Not many of us enjoy being lectured by dressed-down Hollywood stars
in gritty classroom situations, but Ms. Guaspari's story has been
given a blunt, no-nonsense tone that works.
</P>
<P>
   Boring as it may have become for Meryl Streep to show up for
awards ceremonies, count on her to be doing it again. Her
rock-solid performance here is strong and convincing, and the film
offers her an unusually well-drawn role. Without undue
sentimentality, it shows how a single mother with little work
experience or confidence managed to help a lot of children and
create a meaningful new life for herself in the process. Despite
its elements of the predictable (does anyone doubt that the boy who
announces ``I don't wanna learn about no stupid violins'' will
become a dedicated student?), the story is given substance and
naturalness by Ms. Streep's down-to-earth manner.
</P>
<P>
   The screenplay is by Pamela Gray, who also wrote such involving,
recognizable women's roles for ``A Walk on the Moon.'' Ms. Gray
again shows a talent for summoning the familiar so well that it
seems fresh. Yes, the film's Roberta has a mother (Cloris Leachman)
who tells her: ``You're a beautiful and talented woman. You have
your whole life ahead of you.'' And yes, Aidan Quinn pops too
automatically into the story as the obligatory new boyfriend. Ms.
Gray writes her share of cliched lines, but what she gets so right
is the everyday complexity of Roberta's situation. The rapport
between this tough-talking single mother and her two sons, for
instance, has a nicely authentic flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Literally and figuratively, Roberta begins the movie in a
bathrobe and curlers. She is feeling worthless after being ditched
by her husband, and has no professional prospects until Quinn, as
an old friend, suggests a teaching job at an East Harlem school.
Presided over by Angela Bassett as its stern but glamorous
principal, the school is at first unreceptive to Roberta's
unconventional ideas about teaching. There's a memorably noxious
performance from Josh Pais as the whiny, unhelpful music teacher
who doesn't have Roberta's talent but does have tenure.
</P>
<P>
   Dropping her g's and barking orders to her reluctant students,
Ms. Streep's Roberta is shown learning the ropes: getting to know
the children, bullying them into submission and occasionally
glimpsing the kind of urban tragedy that doesn't have much place in
the movie. A fatal mugging and a drive-by shooting are mentioned,
but the movie keeps its emphasis on music. And it follows the
students' progress until the inevitable Big Event, a benefit
concert that is filmed here with Isaac Stern and Itzhak Perlman
among the stellar violinists playing with the schoolchildren.
Perhaps the truest measure of Ms. Streep's performance is that by
the time she gets to Carnegie Hall, it takes some effort to recall
that she is merely a brilliant actress and not a violin teacher
after all.
</P>
<P>
   One admirable aspect of ``Music of the Heart'' is its way of
avoiding the maudlin; another is the nature of Roberta and her
students' accomplishments. There was a time when a movie like this
would have had to end with a prize or a big victory, a sense of
somebody's having gone for the gold. The reward here is simpler:
just an affirmation of the power of music to provide beauty,
pleasure and a sense of accomplishment. Not a bad reason for Craven
to have sidelined the claws and hatchets this time.
</P>
<P>
   In subsidiary roles, Ms. Bassett is ever-dazzling, while Gloria
Estefan acquits herself gracefully as another faculty member and
mother. A large, eager group of violin-playing children account for
much of the film's charm.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `MUSIC OF THE HEART'
</P>
<P>
   Rating: ``Music of the Heart'' is rated PG (Parental guidance
suggested). Though it includes mild profanity, references to
violence and one brief sexual situation, it should work well for
viewers of all ages.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Wes Craven; written by Pamela Gray, based on the
life story of Roberta Guaspari and inspired by the documentary
``Small Wonders''; director of photography, Peter Deming; edited by
Patrick Lussier; music by Mason Daring; production designer, Bruce
Miller; produced by Marianne Maddalena, Walter Scheuer, Allan
Miller and Susan Kaplan; released by Miramax Films. Running time:
110 minutes. This film is rated PG.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Meryl Streep (Roberta Guaspari), Aidan Quinn (Brian
Sinclair), Gloria Estefan (Isabel Vasquez), Angela Bassett (Janet
Williams), Jane Leeves (Dorothea von Haeften), Cloris Leachman
(Assunta Guaspari), Kieran Culkin (Teen-age Lexi), Charlie
Hofheimer (Teen-age Nick) and Josh Pais (Dennis Rausch).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
