<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASSAD-HEIR-APPARENT-FISK-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SONRISE OVER DAMASCUS: ASSAD CLEARS WAY FOR SON BASHAR  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This insightful 725-word ``separate buy'' article is from THE
INDEPENDENT newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By ROBERT FISK  
 c.1999 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT _ It looks like the final suppression of Rifaat Assad's
power in Syria. With the closure of Rifaat's illegal port at
Lattakia _ not to mention the reports of the killing of his
retainers _ his brother, President Hafez Assad, appears to have
cleared the way for his son Bashar as undisputed successor to the
country he has led for almost three decades.
</P>
<P>
   Even the Syrians admit that a number of Rifaat's heavily armed
praetorian guard _ the remnants of his once-powerful Defense
Brigade _ have been ``returned to their units'' after the closure
of his private harbor.
</P>
<P>
   And although Damascus denies that Syrian troops stormed Rifaat's
residence and killed his security guards _ a story put about by
Rifaat's own son Summar on his satellite television station _ they
acknowledge that the port was shut down because it had been built
on state land.
</P>
<P>
   During Lebanon's civil war, illegal Mediterranean ports made
millionaires of rival militia leaders, many of whom traded in guns
and drugs.
</P>
<P>
   President Assad's eldest son Basil _ killed in a car accident in
1994 _ won widespread popularity in Syria by suppressing much of
the corruption which had spread from Lebanon. But Rifaat Assad's
own private port was never touched.
</P>
<P>
   Who, after all, would tangle with the heavily-armed retainers of
the president's brother? Last week, however, the authorities acted
with their customary ruthlessness.
</P>
<P>
   Put very bluntly, Rifaat is finished as a political force in
Syria.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since he tried to stage a coup against his brother in 1983
and was confronted by an outraged President Assad who announced _
according to his biographer, Patrick Seale _ ``I am the regime,''
Rifaat's days were numbered.
</P>
<P>
   Although a vice-president, he chose an extraordinary luncheon at
the Sheraton Hotel in Damascus in 1984 to denounce his brother's
policies, announcing plaintively to 500 guests that ``my brother
doesn't seem to like me any more.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with many of his loyal officers, Rifaat was packed off to
Moscow for a ``cordial working visit''; a few days later, he took
up exile in Geneva with a retinue of more than a hundred servants,
subsequently wandering between estates in Spain and France.
</P>
<P>
   Disputes with local European police forces and rumors of
drug-running did nothing to dispel Rifaat's earlier reputation as a
gregarious and often dissipated man, operating nightclubs in
Damascus as well as a restaurant in the Mezze boulevard of the
capital which sold modest helpings of Arabic cuisine at
extortionate prices.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder the ascetic president with his iron determination and
austere Baathist ideals could not allow Rifaat to hold any power in
Syria.
</P>
<P>
   The demise of his Lattakia port _ the harbor was built opposite
his luxurious private residence in the Damssarkhou district of the
old Roman city _ tells the story of Rifaat's decline.
</P>
<P>
   He was still vice-president when the Syrian minister of
transport, Dr. Mufeed Abdel-Karim, ordered its removal on Jan. 27,
1995. If Rifaat refused to abide by the ruling, the minister added,
``it would be removed at Rifaat el-Assad's expense.''
</P>
<P>
   In September the same year, abdel-Kareem _ obviously acting with
the president's permission _ ordered the port chairman to ``proceed
with the removal of structures built on public maritime property by
the vice-president due to the unavailability (sic) of the required
permit.'' Rifaat ignored the minister.
</P>
<P>
   But the president removed his brother from the nominal post of
vice-president and Rifaat was expelled from the Baath party,
forbidden ever to return.
</P>
<P>
   And so this last week, the one-time aspirant to the leadership
of Syria was told that Syrian government officials had turned up to
clear the equipment from his private harbor and order most of his
bodyguards to close up shop and report back for duties in their old
military units.
</P>
<P>
   As for those reports of shooting and killings at Rifaat Assad's
summer residence _ the ``intense gunfire'' allegedly heard near the
former vice-presidential complex, the Syrian resident in London
whose friends told him that ``tanks and armed boats'' had attacked
the building _ Damascus refuted them all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Highly exaggerated and imprecise,'' a government ``source''
was quoted as saying. As for Summar's television station, which is
based in London, it claimed ``hundreds of deaths, including those
of women and children.''
</P>
<P>
   Someone, it seems, is telling a lie. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 725-word article from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in
London, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
