<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 16:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1395 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-CENTURY-FILM-REVIEW-N     10-28 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENTURY-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MAN OF THE CENTURY': CUB REPORTER IN THE WRONG DECADE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Plop an eager-beaver 1920s newspaper reporter onto the streets
of contemporary Manhattan, make him blissfully unaware that he has
landed in the wrong decade, film his adventures in black and white,
and you have Adam Abraham's amusing one-joke film, ``Man of the
Century.''
</P>
<P>
   This farcical riff on movie nostalgia echoes early Woody Allen
(and Stanley Tucci's recent comedy, ``The Impostors'') in its
lampooning of the hoariest celluloid stereotypes. The movie is also
shrewd enough to avoid wearing out its welcome. It's only 77
minutes long.
</P>
<P>
   The title character, Johnny Twennies (Gibson Frazier), is an
unflappably chipper columnist for The Sun-Telegram, a creaky New
York daily so low on the journalistic food chain its reporters
still pound away on battered old upright typewriters.
</P>
<P>
   Frazier's Johnny is the comic distillation of every cocky,
freshly scrubbed cub reporter who ever chased down a scoop in a
'30s B-movie. Imagine the very young Jimmy Stewart as a hybrid of
Clark Kent and Jimmy Olsen, mouthing quaint soft-boiled slang in a
voice that carries a helium lilt: that's Johnny heroically standing
up to '20s-style mobsters whom he calls ``bub'' and ``buster.''
</P>
<P>
   The movie's cleverest running joke is the way the screenplay (by
Abraham and Frazier) unfurls a dictionary of vintage street slang
(from the '30s as well as the '20s) in funny, cartoon-balloon sound
bites.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man of the Century'' is best appreciated as a stylistic
juggling act. After a silent introduction (with organ music
swelling over subtitles as Johnny jauntily performs his morning
ablutions), the movie breaks into sound as soon as he leaves the
house.
</P>
<P>
   From here, it see-saws back and forth between the '20s and late
'90s, pretending they coexist in a celluloid time warp. One minute
Johnny is skulking through a speak-easy, the next he is doffing his
hat at the Ubu Roi Gallery, the chic SoHo art emporium run by his
girlfriend, Samantha (Susan Egan).
</P>
<P>
   The trick of a movie like ``Man of the Century'' is to keep its
pins in the air and to string out the joke for as long as possible.
The movie comes up with just enough silly variations on its premise
to keep it afloat until its desperate madcap finale at a stuffy
'20s dinner party.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man of the Century'' is at its cleverest portraying Johnny's
crossed-signals romance with Samantha. Our hero, who is the soul of
chivalry, plies his sweetie with bouquets and compliments until one
evening, fed up with his courtliness, she pounces on him, only to
be rebuffed.
</P>
<P>
   When she demands to know if he's gay, he replies that of course
he's a carefree fun-loving guy. The joke is underscored by Johnny's
utter lack of comprehension when witnessing the bitter breakup of
Samantha's cynical gallery assistant, Richard (Dwight Ewell), and
Timothy (Anthony Rapp), the photographer assigned to Johnny's beat.
Timothy is the kind of shutter-bugging prima donna who, when sent
to cover the ribbon-cutting at a library, takes hopelessly arty
photos unrelated to the event.
</P>
<P>
   Our hero also rescues a disaster-prone opera singer (Cara Buono)
from a mugging and later from bondage and imminent molestation at
the hands of a leather fetishist posing as an impresario (Frank
Gorshin). Oh yes, there's also a half-baked plot in which Johnny,
pursuing the scoop to end all scoops, busts a gangland kingpin who
is none other than _ you'll never guess. And it doesn't matter.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `Man of the Century' is rated R (Under 17 requires accompanying
parent or adult guardian). It has sexual situations and some strong
language.
</P>
<P>
   `MAN OF THE CENTURY'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Adam Abraham; written by Abraham and Gibson Frazier;
director of photography, Matthew Jensen; edited by Frank Reynolds;
music by Michael Weiner; production designer, Zeljka Pavlinovic;
produced by Frazier and Abraham; released by Fine Line Features.
Running time: 77 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Gibson Frazier (Johnny Twennies), Cara Buono (Virginia
Clemens), Susan Egan (Samantha Winter), Dwight Ewell (Richard
Lancaster), Anthony Rapp (Timothy Burns), Frank Gorshin (Roman
Navarro), Madame Du Froid (Margaret Twennies), Lester Lanin
(Lester) and Bobby Short (Chester).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-99 1600EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991028.0256 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 16:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1397 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-CLINTON-INTERVIEW29-C     10-28 0970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-INTERVIEW29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON: SEARCH FOR COMMON GROUND IS 'CENTRAL TRUGGLE'
 &HT;    700&AMP;add. With CLINTON.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton sank into a yellow upholstered
armchair, crossed his legs and cast his thoughts back toward his
own beginnings in rural Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   It was a place, Clinton recalled in an interview Wednesday(cq)
night, where a young boy was quickly forced to either embrace or
reject the racial fault lines running through the American South.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned when I was very young that people fear what they
don't know,'' he said. As he grew older, Clinton said, ``I had to
keep telling myself, you have to find ways to reaffirm what you
have in common, and that's the way you can let go of whatever fear
you have.''
</P>
<P>
   As he approaches the twilight of his presidency still struggling
with issues such as peace in the Mideast, ethnic slaughter in the
Balkans and racial divisions at home, Clinton is searching for the
common ground to resurrect a spirit of community.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what I believe,'' he said in the half-hour session in
the Oval Office. ``That's the message I've got to get to society,
and I still think it's the central human struggle.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the president takes his message to Atlanta, where he
will address members of the Anti-Defamation League of B'nai B'rith
on the need to strengthen federal hate crime laws.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton contended that such laws are part of a larger set of
institutions the country needs to protect against the human
instinct for one group to target the differences of another.
</P>
<P>
   As Americans, ``We think, 'Well gosh, you know, we'd never go
back to race wars,' '' said Clinton. ``Well, I think that's true.
But I think it's true, not only because basically the American
people are good people, but because we've set ourselves on a good
path. We've made a legal and a societal commitment to a good
direction.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to have a climate where you are always encouraging
people to do the right thing and discouraging them from doing the
wrong thing,'' said Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   He suddenly appeared to acknowledge the irony of such a
statement from a man nearly thrown out of office because of his
personal conduct involving former White House intern Monica
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not a person in the United States _ some are more
saintly than others _ but nearly everybody is vulnerable to
defining themselves in terms of other people who are different,
where we say, 'Well, I may not be the best person in the world, but
thank God I'm not that.' We all almost need that from time to
time,'' said Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not a human being that sometime or another in his or
her life is not disappointed in themselves, doesn't feel like
they've failed in some way or another,'' he continued. ``So this is
something that will never go away.''
</P>
<P>
   The president, wearing a gray wool suit, a blue and white
checked shirt, a burgundy necktie and black western boots,
discussed his attempts to place the theme of resurrection of
community near the center of roach to governance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The central work of citizenship in a democratic society is
finding ways to respect other people and their differences and even
celebrate the differences,'' he said. ``But you can only celebrate
the differences,'' he said, ``if you believe that what you have in
common with them is more important.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When it works there's nothing more wonderful in life, you
know, seeing (former South Africa President) Nelson Mandela
reconcile with the people that kept him in jail for 27 years,''
said Clinton. ``There's nothing more beautiful in life.''
</P>
<P>
   The challenge remains, he said, to prevent ideals from being
smothered by fear, a lesson he often implores in speeches to gay
and lesbian groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes a young gay man or a lesbian woman will come to me
at one of these events and say, 'You've given me more respect than
my parents.' It happens with some frequency. They're estranged from
their parents,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   His voice lowered to a near whisper as he leaned out over the
edge of his chair and made a bowl with his hands as if to cradle
the thought. ``And I always tell them the same thing, I say 'Your
parents are scared. You have to keep loving them, you have to to
keep giving them a chance. They're scared.' ''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Against long odds, Clinton is pressing the Republican majority
in Congress to widen the activities existing statutes would cover
and to broaden federal definitions of hate crimes to include
attacks based on gender, disabilities or sexual leanings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pushing hard for it,'' said Clinton, whose view on the
need for such legislation was hardened by the torture and murder of
a gay student last year in Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
   ``Society as a whole suffers a particular burden from these
kinds of crimes,'' Clinton said. ``It's a very important thing for
our elected representatives to say that we want special focus on
these crimes.''
</P>
<P>
   On this fight, at least, Clinton's prospects seem dim.
</P>
<P>
   He vetoed a spending bill Monday in part because it had been
stripped of his hate crime proposals. He has stopped short of
threatening to hold up the amended version of that bill, whether it
contains his proposals or not.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., opposes the
proposals, said his spokesman John Czwartacki.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically we are very reluctant to get into the business of
federalizing the notion that one individual is less valuable than
another is, just because of the group they belong to,'' said
Czwartacki. ``That's just not a healthy thing, especially in our
society.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
