<HEADER>
A1399 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-SF-REFORM-BALLOT-HNS &LR;      10-28 0646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SF-REFORM-BALLOT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
S.F. VOTERS TO DECIDE ISSUE ON CAMPAIGN SPENDING LIMITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RACHEL GORDON  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Demonstrating the tenacity of the campaign
finance reform issue, San Francisco voters will decide Tuesday
whether to lower the voluntary spending limits for candidates
running for the Board of Supervisors.
</P>
<P>
   And in March, they may consider a proposal for public financing
of campaigns in the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politics really has become the playground for millionaires,''
said Holli Thier, co-president of the League of Women Voters here,
who supports both plans. ``Our goal is to level the playing field,
to allow average citizens to run for office.''
</P>
<P>
   But the courts have tossed out attempts by the voters and the
Board of Supervisors to restrict campaign financing in the past two
mayoral elections.
</P>
<P>
   Proposition K on next week's ballot is the simpler of the two
ideas. It would lower the spending caps for supervisorial
candidates who, starting next year, will be running for office by
district, rather than citywide. The proposal would amend the city's
current spending cap law for those running for supervisor.
</P>
<P>
   Now, under citywide elections for supervisors, the spending
limit is $250,000 for each candidate. Prop. K calls for lowering
the amount to $75,000 for the general election, and adding another
$20,000 for candidates who get into a run-off election.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Marsteller of Common Cause, a group advocating campaign
finance reform, said candidates don't need as much money under
district elections because they have fewer voters to reach and less
territory to cover. Under district elections, the city will be
divided into 11 geographic sectors with roughly 65,000 residents
each.
</P>
<P>
   City law allows candidates who agree to the voluntary cap to
accept individual contributions of up to $500. Those who don't
comply are limited to $150 individual contributions. However, that
portion of the law which lowers contributions for those who don't
comply with the spending cap has been challenged in federal court
by mayoral candidate Clint Reilly, and it is unclear whether that
provision will remain on the books.
</P>
<P>
   There is little official opposition to Prop. K, but some
campaign consultants think it will favor incumbents over newcomers
who need more money to gain the attention of the public.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents, though, say the district campaigns likely will rely
more on bus-stop and door-to-door campaigning, which cost virtually
nothing, rather than expensive efforts that rely on mail and
commercials.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the more ambitious proposal to publicly finance
campaigns in San Francisco got a boost at the Board of Supervisors
Finance Committee on Wednesday. The committee wants the full board
to urge the city's Ethics Commission to hold hearings on public
financing, and if there's interest, to place a measure on the March
ballot.
</P>
<P>
   The idea behind taxpayer support of political races is to
remove, or limit, the influence of special interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``The voters strongly support curbs on the influence of money in
local and national elections,'' said Board of Supervisors President
Tom Ammiano, who's championing the plan.
</P>
<P>
   He also wants the Ethics Commission to look into curbing
campaign contributions from businesses with city contracts or those
that bid for city business.
</P>
<P>
   Several cities, among them Long Beach, New York, Los Angeles and
Tucson, already provide matching funds to candidates' campaigns.
The amount of money varies from about 5 cents to 80 cents per
resident. New York City spent close to $6 million in the 1994-97
election cycle; Long Beach spent about $41,000.
</P>
<P>
   Common Cause estimates the cost to San Francisco for providing
candidates with 50 percent financing would be $1.2 million a year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
