<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Friday, Oct. 29, 1999.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   BLUEANGELS _ MOODY AIR FORCE BASE, Ga. _ A jet from the Navy's
Blue Angels precision flying team crashed Thursday while trying to
land during a training flight, killing two team members. (Staff,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH POSSIBLE GRAPHIC OR LOCATOR
MAP.
</P>
<P>
   ADL-HATE _ ATLANTA _ ADL leaders meeting in Atlanta discuss
whether this summer's surge of anti-Semitic violence is an
aberration or a harbinger of a change in attitudes in Americanand
consider whether additional hate crime legislation would be
effective tool to fight it. (Martz, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
12.
</P>
<P>
   GINGRICH-DIVORCE - ATLANTA _ Marianne Gingrich is filing a
response to her husband's request for an accounting of their
finances. She also is requesting an independent auditor. (Stanford,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 12.
</P>
<P>
   FALLING FROM THE SKY
</P>
<P>
   Part Six of a six-part investigative series by The Dayton Daily
News on the the recent rise in military air crashes and their
causes. The Daily News found that the U.S. military routinely sends
planes and helicopters in the air that it knows are plagued with
deadly safety problems. The series is based in part on
never-before-seen information from three databases from the Army,
Navy and Air Force safety centers.
</P>
<P>
   CRASH-KNIGHTS _ The military's handling of the hydraulic
problems on the CH-46 Sea Knight helicopters is typical of the way
it handled numerous other mechanical failures in many types of
aircraft. Costs are wegainst risk. Some 70 incidents,
spanning more than 11 years, can be traced to hydraulic problems on
the Sea Knights. (Carollo, Dayton Daily News).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   CRASH-MCNALLY _ Anatomy of a crash. A detailed analysis of a
1994 crash in California involving a pilot named Randall McNally.
No cause was ever determined, but a Daily News examination found
that mechanics had detected problems with the plane's stabilizer
augmentor eight days before the crash. The augmentor was never
found. (Carollo, Dayton Daily News).
</P>
<P>
   IMMIGRANTS _ ATLANTA _ Long lines of immigrants needing legal
help form twice a week at Catholic Social Services on Peachtree
Street in Atlanta, site of one of the few free immigration clinics
in the Southeast. The immigrants need help applying for citizenship
or asylum or working out a problem with an employer, school or the
dreaded Immigration and Naturalization Service. (Bixler, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 20. WITH PHOTOS. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   GOP-DEBATE _ HANOVER, N.H. _ Five Republican presidential
candidates _ absent front-runner George W. Bush _ meet for their
second debate. Bush plans an interview with a local television
station to explain his absence to New Hampshire voters. (Crowley,
Palm Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: The debate begins at 7:30 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-INTERVIEW _ WASHINGTON _ Speeding toward the twilight of
his presidency, Bill Clinton is a man on a crusade. Whether the
goal is to build peace in the Middle East, end ethnic slaughter in
the Balkans or bridge the racial divide within his own nation,
Clinton is searching, again and again, for the common ground he
believes can resurrect communities and reconcile people riven by
history, hatred and fear. ``That's the message I've got to get to
society,'' he said in an Oval Office interview with Cox Newspapers,
``and I still think it's the central human struggle.'' (Deans, Cox
News Service). 20.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   ADL-HATE _ ATLANTA _ ADL leaders meeting in Atlanta discuss
whether this summer's surge of anti-Semitic violence is an
aberration or a harbinger of a change in attitudes in Americanand
consider whether additional hate crime legislation would be
effective tool to fight it. (Martz, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
12.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in the (a) General News category.
</P>
<P>
   SAVINGS _ WASHINGTON _ The Consumer Federation of America and
Primerica release a survey on how middle class Americans ``have no
savings and little wealth and believe that a lottery or a
sweepstakes will be more beneficial for their retirement than
saving and investing.'' (Dart, Cox News Service). 20.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (w) Washngton and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   VENDING _ WASHINGTON _ Lobster bisque. Fully inflated helium
balloons. Even airline tickets These and other unusual
machine-vended items are featured at the annual convention of the
National Automatic Merchandising Association. (Hill, Cox News
Service). 18. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON _ WASHINGTON _ President Clinton holds a late afternoon
joint news conference with the leader of Nigeria. (Deans, Cox News
Service). 30.
</P>
<P>
   BEST-LAWMAKERS _ WASHINGTON _ Three Georgians have been included
in CQ's list of 50 most effective legislators _ Sen. Paul
Coverdell, Rep. John Lewis and Rep. Bob Barr. (Carr, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   IMMIG-EVIDENCE _ WASHINGTON _ House Minority Whip David Bonior,
D-Mich., and Rep. Tom Campbell, R-Calif., hold a news conference to
call on Congress to pass their legislation repealing the use of
``secret evidence'' in Immigration and Naturalization Service
deportation cases. (Schultz, Cox News Service). 18.
</P>
