<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 16:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1413 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-GRIMSLEY31-COX     10-28 0601
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-GRIMSLEY31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Grimsley's tidings of sadness and salvation
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Oct. 31
 &HT;    By Wendell Brock
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Love is shelter, a physical space as palpable as two bodies
coiled in slumber. More than sex or religion or art, it is the
thing that ennobles the spirit and salves the heart. In ``The
Unbearable Lightness of Being,'' Milan Kundera called it ``shared
sleep.'' In the new novel by Jim Grimsley _ the Atlanta writer
whose pure style and heart-rending storytelling has earned him an
international reputation _ it becomes ``Comfort &AMP; Joy.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither as eloquent nor as artfully structured as his three
previous stories, this book is Grimsley writing at his best, and
worst. Dramatically clumsy, structurally confusing, with a
cumbersome central section that tries to fill in the gaps of the
past, the volume reads at times like a 291-page short story. Yet
for all its awkwardness and thinness of plot, it's difficult to put
down this bittersweet and affecting tale of heartbreak, sacrifice
and redemption.
</P>
<P>
   This sequel to ``Winter Birds,'' Grimsley's dark and highly
autobiographical first novel, is a prototypical tale of lovers from
opposite ends of the track. After growing up with hemophilia in an
impoverished North Carolina family and barely surviving the abuse
of his alcoholic father, Dan Crell is now a Grady Hospital worker.
A fragile man with a ``collarbone like two wings'' and a voice like
an angel, he falls for Ford McKinney, a young doctor from a family
of Savannah bluebloods. So imagine what happens when the two drop
in, unannounced, on the stodgy McKinneys at Christmastime. It's too
bad the dialogue often reads like a gay ``Love Story'' or a bad
``Dynasty'' episode (or am I thinking of ``ER''?).
</P>
<P>
   But as weak as some of the novel is, the section in which Danny
returns to a house of his childhood, and the trailer where his
mother now lives with his stepfather, is beautifully told. Danny's
mother warms to Ford, and though she is somewhat unsure about the
ring Danny plans to give his partner on Christmas Day, she
volunteers to wrap it. Moreover, there's something wonderfully
authentic about a Southern mother who asks: ``Do you boys ever cook
at your house, or do you eat out all the time?''
</P>
<P>
   Marriage, in whatever form, is a universal condition. But what
makes Dan and Ford's a wholly honorable (not to mention rare) union
is that it's based on kindness and nurturing. That redeems them,
and the novel.
</P>
<P>
   ``They slept peacefully, side by side, and the body of one
became adjusted to the rhythm of the other, and the breathing of
one slowed the breathing of the other, and they dreamed in tandem
and shared fragments of each other's dreams, and they grew more
like each other day by day, not in personality but in the fissures
of the brain, because, seeing the same things every day, day after
day, they laid crevices in themselves that were the same shape,
that were the same events written into memory, and this was enough,
without words, to keep them silent about the fact of their hates
and their fears, their deep concerns about each other, and the
certainty that one of them would die first and neither of them knew
which one it would be.''
</P>
<P>
   In such remarkable passages, Grimsley gets it absolutely right.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  FICTION
</P>
<P>
   Comfort &AMP; Joy. By Jim Grimsley. Algonquin. $21.95. 291 pages.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Flawed but affecting.
</P>
<P>
   Wendell Brock is an arts writer for The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
