<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 16:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1415 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-GARYALLAN-PROFILE29-C     10-28 0719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARYALLAN-PROFILE29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gary Allan set to make it after being true to himself
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Country singer Gary Allan stopped giving a flip about Nashville,
its ponytailed executives and their stuffy resistance to change
sometime in January.
</P>
<P>
   That's when his label, historic Decca Records, unexpectedly
closed its doors, leaving most of its roster without record deals.
Allan, a California honky-tonker who had never quite crawled out of
the pack of post-Garth hat acts, was one of four artists offered a
contract by MCA, Decca's parent label. Frustrated with the music
business, particularly what he perceived as a lack of creativity
and risk-taking on Music Row, Allan stunned industry insiders with
his eat-my-dust response: ``No thanks.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Just let me go.' I didn't want to be there,'' Allan
said. ``I told 'em, `When I first came to this label, you guys were
excited about me because I was different. Then you started tweaking
on me, and now I feel like you're scared of what I do. If I can't
make the record I want to make, I don't need to be here.'''
</P>
<P>
   MCA producer Tony Brown persisted, and hard-core country fans
should dedicate a Tabernacle of Twang to him. With ``Smoke Rings in
the Dark,'' Allan has made what could be the record of his career.
The title song is an aching tune of obsession and regret, the kind
that establishes a career and blasts Allan out of anonymity. From
the first call/response notes of a lonesome guitar crying out to
pedal steel, the tune sounds classic, fueled by Allan's sandpaper
vocals and strong lyrics: ``The night is like a dagger / Long and
cold and sharp / As I sit here on the front steps / Blowin' smoke
rings in the dark.''
</P>
<P>
   The accompanying video captures the aura of late-night anguish,
featuring a hatless Allan in a custom-made, vintage 1940s Nudie
suit. If fans were unclear about just who he was on his first two
albums, this push is likely to make him a major star.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only will it put Gary Allan on the map as a player; I
think the kind of music that's on this album will help country
evolve,'' said Y-106.7 program director Steve Mitchell. ``Like the
Dixie Chicks, it's going to open the doors for country radio to
take a chance and play something that's different.''
</P>
<P>
   At a recent private concert for the Atlanta country station,
Allan kicked back confidently in an overstuffed chair and said,
``This is the best buzz I've ever had on a record.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to make a record for radio. I want to make
something I would want to listen to,'' he said. ``It's really hard
for me to find songs that are straight down the middle for radio
that I can live with singing. I'm one of those people who sits
around and plays guitar until four in the morning, and I listened
to a lot of Roy Orbison and Chris Isaak this year. All that stuff
is in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, ``Smoke Rings in the Dark,'' which arrived in stores
Tuesday, draws heavily from the Isaak/Orbison school of
tear-stained lyrics and V-8 guitar. But it is traditional in many
ways, jerking country's reins back to heartfelt basics as well as
experimentation. Three tunes _ ``Bourbon Borderline,'' ``Sorry''
and ``Learning to Live With Me'' _ were born during a guitar pull
at Allan's house with songwriting greats Harlan Howard, Harley
Allen and Guy Clark. Allan has even thrown in a
wreck-on-the-highway tune in which a battered and bloodied truck
driver's last words are something any Southern Baptist would
understand: ``Don't Tell Mama (I Was Drinkin').''
</P>
<P>
   The 31-year-old Californian seems to sense the potential career
explosion before him, and plans to spend most of the winter on the
road promoting the album. His private concert for Y-106.7 will air
at 9 p.m. Sunday. The show at Cowboys is his first appearance in
Atlanta since the album hit stores, and the honking Kennesaw club
may be his kind of place.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best vibe I get is the bar scene. I love it when that
energy gets going,'' he said. ``My favorite is when it's just
packed, everybody's sweaty, no air conditioning _ and a lot of
beer.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Allan
</P>
<P>
   11 p.m. Saturday. $10. Cowboys, 1750 N. Roberts Road, Kennesaw
(Ga.). 770-426-5006.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
