<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-THIRD29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Shadowy `Third Man' stands test of 50 years
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There was a time when Orson Welles as Harry Lime struck as
familiar a chord in movie-lovers' memories as Marlon Brando as Don
Corleone. But somehow director Carol Reed's 1949 masterpiece, ``The
Third Man,'' has gotten lost in its own noir shadow. Ask for it at
your neighborhood Blockbuster and all you're likely to get is a
blank stare.
</P>
<P>
   But here's the good news. In honor of its 50th anniversary, the
film is back in all its elegantly cynical, gorgeously photographed
glory. The print has been restored, as have 11 minutes that
producer David O. Selznick cut from the American version. (Reed,
who won an Oscar two decades later for ``Oliver!'' was British.)
The film wasn't gutted, just trimmed, so the extra footage mostly
means more of an already good thing.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest change is in the opening narration. Originally it
was spoken by the film's American protagonist, Joseph Cotten. Now,
screenwriter Graham Greene's distinctively arch words are voiced by
the director himself, thus more effectively setting the picture's
richly mocking tone, and providing a better match for the
celebrated zither score.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Third Man'' takes place in postwar Vienna, Austria.
Divided into five zones overseen by the different Allies, the city
is a patchwork of corruption and crumbling rubble. The damp streets
seem deserted, but the closer you look, the more you see. ``We'd
run anything,'' Reed's anonymous narrator says of the thriving
black market. ``If people wanted it, and they could pay.''
</P>
<P>
   Holly Martins (Cotten), a hack writer of pulp westerns with
titles like ``The Lone Rider From Santa Fe,'' is summoned to Vienna
by his old friend Lime, whom he hasn't seen in years. Almost the
moment he arrives, he learns that Harry is dead; he was hit by a
car. But eyewitness accounts of the accident don't add up; the
title refers to one glaring discrepancy.
</P>
<P>
   So, behaving like one of his cowboy heroes, Holly naively
decides to find out the truth. In doing so, he's drawn into Harry's
sinister circle of friends and falls for his dead (or is he?) pal's
lover, Anna (Alida Valli). Meanwhile, capable but cold Major
Calloway, played by Trevor Howard in full stiff-upper-lip mode,
watches to see if Holly's blundering will, perhaps, unearth Lime,
whom he regards as ``the worst racketeer who ever made a dirty
living in this city.''
</P>
<P>
   There is so much to admire here, from the exquisite
shadows-and-sidestreets cinematography to the expert performances _
especially that of Welles, who appears in only about 10 minutes of
the film yet dominates almost every frame.
</P>
<P>
   Further, seen through the prism of half a century, the movie
comes off as even more world-wearily correct about the death of a
certain kind of white-hat idealism. It is, in a sense, a
bittersweet eulogy for a lost moral compass in which right and
wrong were clearly defined. In ``The Third Man,'' even the shadows
tell lies.'
</P>
<P>
   ``The Third Man''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   Starring Joseph Cotten and Orson Welles. Directed by Carol Reed.
Not rated, but there is implied violence.
</P>
<P>
   1 hour, 44 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Not to be missed.
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Ringel Gillespie writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
