<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-PREGANCY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AVOIDING UNWANTED PREGNANCIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The battling factions in the abortion debate ought to agree on
the need to decrease the 49 percent of pregnancies in the United
States that are unintended. New research points toward strategies
to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Half of those unintended pregnancies end in abortion. The other
half frequently lead to maternal complications and poorer outcomes
for infants, which can drive up health care costs.
</P>
<P>
   Too often the culprit in unwanted pregnancy is seen as simple
carelessness. But more-thoughtful research has linked unwanted
pregnancies to a variety of abusive environments. The Journal of
the American Medical Association recently reported a study of
almost 1,200 adult women in which 20 percent of unintended first
pregnancies were associated with a ``history of abuse and household
dysfunction during childhood.''
</P>
<P>
   The abuse studied included psychological, physical, and sexual
abuse, having a mother who was physically abused by her partner,
substance abuse, and living with a household member who was
depressed, mentally ill, or had attempted suicide. Almost 66
percent of the women reported exposure to at least two types of
abuse. And frequent abuse or exposure to four or more types of
abuse made women 1 1/2 times more likely to have an unintended
first pregnancy than other women.
</P>
<P>
   How can this research be applied? Patricia Dietz of the Centers
for Disease Control and Prevention, the article's first author,
calls for more study to clarify exactly how past abuse and
household dysfunction contribute to unwanted pregnancies. There's
also an expanded role for medical providers. Many screen for
current abuse, Dietz points out, but fewer look for past abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than create a new class of victims, the work should
improve pregnancy prevention efforts. In 1994, the article points
out, ``women 20 years and older accounted for 76 percent of all
unintended pregnancies.'' They need the best insights into
prevention that research can offer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-99 1621EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
