<DOCNO> NYT19991028.0275 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 16:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1422 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-FILMS4KIDS-NYT &LR;      10-28 1080
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILMS4KIDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MAN AND HIS LAWN MOWER: DETERMINATION AND A SMILE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE STRAIGHT STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Richard Farnsworth, Sissy Spacek, Wiley Harker, Harry Dean
Stanton &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by David Lynch &QL;
</P>
<P>
   G 110 minutes
</P>
<P>
   ``What the gol darn are you doing lying on the floor?'' a friend
asks the elderly Alvin Straight ( Farnsworth), whom he finds unable
to rise from the kitchen linoleum one afternoon. Taken to the
clinic by his retarded daughter, Rosie (Ms. Spacek), Alvin learns
what he knows already: his hips are gone, his eyes are going,
diabetes threatens and he's in the early stages of emphysema.
</P>
<P>
   Time to lay off the cigars and braunschweiger. But Alvin is a
stubborn fellow. When he learns that his estranged brother, Lyle (
Stanton), has had a stroke, he determines to go see him. Denied a
driver's license because of his eyesight, he decides to drive
anyway _ on his rider lawn mower.
</P>
<P>
   Alvin lives in Iowa, Dean in Wisconsin. The mower, hauling a
homemade trailer with a few belongings, goes three or four miles
per hour. All day Alvin chugs along the shoulder of the two-lane
road. At night he pulls off into the fields and sleeps under the
stars.
</P>
<P>
   An open, gracious man, he charms everyone he meets with his
gentle humanity, self-sufficiency and determination to finish the
trip the way he started it.
</P>
<P>
   As the journey proceeds, so does the story of Alvin Straight:
his boyhood, his experiences as a sniper in World War II, his
marriage and 14 children (seven of whom survived), his resilience,
sagacity and love of family. The mower gives out on several
occasions, but never Alvin.
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE None in the usual sense, but a deer is hit by a car and
there's one brush with danger when the mower's brakes fail on a
steep hill and send Alvin racing, so to speak, into town. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX None. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY None. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOOTNOTE Almost eerily in a movie by Lynch (``Blue Velvet,''
``Twin Peaks''), the only bizarre moment comes after the car hits
the deer. Deeply distraught, the driver tells Alvin that no matter
what warning she issues _ honking her horn, yelling out the window,
banging on the car door _ she can't avoid hitting a deer every week
on her drive to work. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDER AGE 12 A G-rated film by Lynch is almost occasion enough
to take the little ones, especially a film as warmly rich and full
of family values as this one. Unfortunately, it moves very slowly. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 12 AND UP OK, on the face of it a movie about an old man
and his lawn mower has little appeal to teen-agers. This one,
though, could grab hold with viewers willing to suspend themselves
for a short while (the 110-minute length is tolerable) and settle
in with Alvin (a true winner), not to mention a finely wrought film
in every respect.
</P>
<P>
   BATS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lou Diamond Phillips, Dina Meyer, Leon, Bob Gunton, Carlos
Jacott &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Louis Morneau &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PG-13 91 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Bats can be as small as bees, but these are fox bats, which come
with five-foot wingspans, have heads like gargoyles, crash through
windshields and rip down chain-link fences. One night about a
million of them come whizzing down on Gallup, Texas, and make a
mess out of the citizenry.
</P>
<P>
   Fox bats are ordinarily fruit eaters, but some biological
tinkering suddenly has them eating anything. Call out the troops,
evacuate Texas, consult the Central Intelligence Agency. Eradicate
those bats or they'll be in New Orleans in time for Mardi Gras.
</P>
<P>
   The government favors diving bombing all the caves in the
region, but that approach has the disapproval of Dr. Sheila Casper
(Ms. Meyer), a ravishing zoologist and bat person (``What got you
into bats in the first place?'' she is asked.).
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Casper says an aerial attack will kill everything but the
bats. Pointing out that bats perish in temperatures under 32
degrees, she favors freezing them. Fine, but it's now in the 60s.
It turns out, though, that the CIA has developed just the machine
for the job, a big chuffer that it is claimed could turn Cairo into
icicles in three days.
</P>
<P>
   But then the bats eat the Army, which complicates installation
of the device in the bat lair in an abandoned mine. Looks as if the
doctor and Sheriff Emmett Kimsey ( Phillips) will have to lower
themselves down there and jump-start the air-conditioning.
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE All the gore and wildly violent bat battles could well
have earned an R rating. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX None. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY Bat attacks excite expletives. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDER AGE 11 The answer should be obvious, particularly for the
younger ones in this category. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 12-13 They'll survive. Parents' decision, that is, if the
children haven't already gone with their friends. Actually, no one
is likely to take this piece of silly business very seriously. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 14 AND UP If they must.
</P>
<P>
   THREE TO TANGO &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Perry, Neve Campbell, Dylan McDermott, Oliver Platt,
Cylk Cozart &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Damon Santostefano &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PG-13 115 minutes
</P>
<P>
   And now for a 20-something screwball sex comedy. Angling to
design a $90 million cultural center, the architect Oscar Novak (
Perry) allows himself to be perceived as gay by the entrepreneur
Charles Newman ( McDermott) who controls the project. A crass
schemer, Charles wants a ``safe'' male around to keep tabs on his
girlfriend, Amy (Ms. Campbell), a glass sculptor and attractive
loose cannon.
</P>
<P>
   Oscar, of course, falls for Amy, and she somewhat for him.
Charles is married, but that's nothing compared to the gyrations
Oscar goes through to declare his homosexuality to the world on one
hand and then swear up and down that he's straight to friends and
family.
</P>
<P>
   Could any one architectural project be worth all this?
Absolutely. Gradually, though, Oscar tires of the subterfuge and
determines to declare himself heterosexual. But where's Amy?
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE None. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX Some raunchy talk. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY See above and throw in some other swear words. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOOTNOTE Like many Hollywood films, this one is so awkwardly
self-conscious about depicting homosexuality that one wonders why
studios even bother with the subject. Suffice it to say that every
leering cliche is firmly in place. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDER AGE 12 Unsuitable. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 12 AND UP Rest assured that there is nothing worth an R
rating, but in keeping with the PG-13 many parents will consider
the subject matter worthy of strong caution.
</P>
</TEXT>
