<HEADLINE>
HOME-BASED MEDICAL BUSINESSES ENJOY VARIABLE HEALTH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: There are tons of ads to file medical claims at home using a
PC. Are any of these offers legitimate?
</P>
<P>
   _ G.B., Burleson, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: ``There are far more bad companies than good ones out
there,'' said Rick Benzel, author of ``Making Money in a Health
Service Business on Your Home-Based PC.'' ``I am very frustrated by
the number of companies that tout medical billing as an easy
business. It's very difficult and competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruth Zemek, the director of trade practices at the Phoenix
Better Business Bureau, said that some companies sell
claim-processing software for thousands of dollars but offer no
support when you try to find clients for your new business. ``The
people that are successful are the ones who've gone out and beaten
the doors to get contracts themselves,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Benzel's book describes the pitfalls and benefits of three
medical work-at-home businesses: billing, claims assistance and
transcription. ``You need a good medical or accounting background
to understand how a doctor's business makes money,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His book is available at bookstores under ISBN 0-0791-3139-5,
and you also can order it for $37.50 from Rick Benzel, 11670
National Blvd., PMB 104, Los Angeles, CA 90064.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a discussion forum for people running such
businesses at the Web site www.claimtek.com/wwwboard/wwwboard.html.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When are the WB Radio Music Awards going to air?
</P>
<P>
   _ R.C., via the Internet
</P>
<P>
   A: The awards will air live at 7 p.m. CDT Thursday on WB
stations.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first year for the awards show, which will be held
at the Mandalay Bay Resort and Casino in Las Vegas. Performer and
song nominees are based on radio airplay during the past year, and
winners are chosen by a vote of 400 radio programmers.
</P>
<P>
   Nominees include the Dixie Chicks, Lenny Kravitz, Lauryn Hill
and Cake. Some scheduled performers are David Bowie, Faith Hill,
Destiny's Child and BWitched.
</P>
<P>
   Five award categories will be decided by votes cast on the Radio
Music Awards Web site at www.thewb.com/rma.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's the name of the tiny symbol used at the end of a
magazine article to let you know it has ended?
</P>
<P>
   _ L.P., Arlington, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: The symbol is called a ``dingbat,'' a term that's commonly
applied to any border, separator or decorative character on a
printed page. That definition dates to at least 1904, according to
Webster's Ninth New Collegiate Dictionary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dingbat'' originally referred to an early coin and other forms
of currency, but now is used most often to describe a stupid,
eccentric or crazy person.
</P>
<P>
   The Random House Historical Dictionary of American Slang credits
that meaning to The Dingbat Family, a comic strip by George
Herriman, published from 1910 to 1916.
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
