<SLUG> BC-JOHNSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WE REALLY NEEDED AN AMENDMENT THAT WOULD ...
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CECIL JOHNSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Texas voters will soon complete the process of determining how
many of a batch of 17 proposed amendments to the Texas Constitution
will be added to the 377 that already have been attached to the
fundamental document of the state's government.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the ladies and gentlemen who labor in the
legislative vineyards in Austin could not summon up the wisdom and
fortitude to include another proposition that many Texans believe
to be way past due.
</P>
<P>
   Putting that omission aside for a moment, it does seem
appropriate to complement the esteemed members of the state House
and Senate for their extraordinary display of collective ability to
communicate their wishes to the voting and nonvoting public
concisely.
</P>
<P>
   No proposition on the ballot contains more than 34 words. And
yet those terse sentences cover, in some instances, very
complicated issues. And passage of those propositions would have
broad and highly significant repercussions.
</P>
<P>
   The economy of language used by the legislators, as has been the
case in most previous constitutional amendment elections, suggests
that the senators and representatives harbor strong faith in the
willingness and ability of the voters to educate themselves on the
ramifications of all those propositions.
</P>
<P>
   They also appear to have placed a great deal of trust in the
news media to analyze the propositions and explain them to
concerned citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, some cynics take the view that the legislators don't
care whether the voters understand what they are being asked to do.
They just want enough of them to endorse those propositions and
embed them in the state constitution.
</P>
<P>
   As that skeptical crowd sees it, amending the state constitution
is to the Texas Legislature as punting is to football.
</P>
<P>
   They make a good case that when the legislators are reluctant to
do the job they were sent to Austin to do, they kick the issue back
to voters packaged in such enigmatic terms that most voters either
don't vote on them or guess.
</P>
<P>
   That disillusioned perspective is gaining ground, which bodes
ill for voter turnout for such elections and for public confidence
in state government. Under the circumstances, it is not easy to
make a case that voters need to pay serious attention to Tuesday's
constitutional amendment election.
</P>
<P>
   If they don't, however, some undesirable consequences could
occur. It is conceivable that majorities could guess wrong and
reject some of those that are needed, such as:
</P>
<P>
   _Proposition 17, which would allow the regents of the University
of Texas and the Texas A&AMP;M University systems to manage the
Permanent University Fund more creaand generate some
industrial-strength profits for the benefit of the schools in those
systems.
</P>
<P>
   _Proposition 7, which would allow garnishment of wages for
spousal maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   _Proposition 13, which would permit the issuance of $400 million
in tax-supported bonds for student loans.
</P>
<P>
   By the same token, wrong-guessers might approve the highly
deceptive Proposition 9, which would allow the legislators to
establish a ``judicial compensation commission.'' That nine-member
commission would recommend changes in judges' salaries. Unless
either the House or the Senate rejected the commission's salary
recommendations, they would become law.
</P>
<P>
   The ostensible purpose of the commission would be to take the
politics out of state judges' pay. And why is politics in it? Well,
that goes back to 1972, when the legislators pegged their pension
benefits to the salaries of state judges.
</P>
<P>
   Legislators, over the years, have been somewhat reluctant to
raise judicial salaries out of fear of being perceived to be
feathering their own nests. If, however, a supposedly disinterested
commission makes the judges' salary recommendations, the
legislators can passively increase their retirement benefits
without voting.
</P>
<P>
   What about those tangled webs we weave when we study to deceive?
</P>
<P>
   There is no need to have such an appointed committee making law.
The legislators can simply do their duty and risk the appearance of
self-interestedness, or they can disentangle their retirement
benefits from judicial pay. It would be a lot easier to do that
than to remove the commission from the constitution once it gets in
there.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, the other amendments appear to be harmless at
worst, although it's pretty clear that Proposition 1, pertaining to
the succession to the governor and lieutenant governor, would not
be on the ballot this year were it not for the possibility that
Gov. George W. Bush will be elected president.
</P>
<P>
   Now to that omitted 18th proposition: The legislators should
have proposed an amendment stating that the constitution will be
amended no more until the whole unwieldy mess has been reduced to a
concise and comprehensible body of basic doctrine.
</P>
<P>
   (Cecil Johnson is a columnist and editorial writer for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. You can reach him at
cecil(at)star-telegram.com or (817) 390-7663. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
