<SLUG> BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANAGEMENT GURU TOM PETERS HAS WRITTEN THREE NEW BOOKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TERESA MCUSIC 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tom Peters has things to say. The problem is sifting through his
whiz-bang writing to get to those nuggets of wisdom.
</P>
<P>
   Case in point is the management guru's latest series: threl books at $15.95 each that have more explanation points,
boldface type, capital letters and dashes than a typing lesson, yet
have something to say. You just have to wade through a lot of
punctuation to get there.
</P>
<P>
   The author made his name years ago with the bestseller ``In
Search of Excellence,'' written with Robert Waterman Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Peters has been in high demand on the lecture
circuit, and his writing reflects that. I suspect that much of his
work sounds better read aloud and that the books are transcribed
versions of his speeches.
</P>
<P>
   His latest efforts are the first of a series Peters calls
Reinventing Work.
</P>
<P>
   The titles are:
</P>
<P>
   ``Professional Service Firm 50: Fifty Ways to Transform Your
Department into a Professional Service Firm Whose Trademarks are
Passion and Innovation!'' (Knopf, 227 pages, $15.95).
</P>
<P>
   ``The Project 50: Fifty Ways to Transform Every Task into a
Project That Matters!'' (Knopf, 208 pages, $15.95).
</P>
<P>
   ``The Brand You 50: Fifty Ways to Transform Yourself from an
Employee Into a Brand That Shouts Distinction, Commitment, and
Passion!'' (Knopf, 204 pages, $14.95).
</P>
<P>
   That's three exclamation points without even cracking the books.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his writing style, Peters occasionally comes up with
real jewels.
</P>
<P>
   For example, in ``Project 50,'' he tells readers that in the
next century, 95 percent of everyone's work will be in defined,
white-collar, professional projects. He calls it the White-Collar
Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``The high-impact project is the gem ... the nugget ... the
fundamental atomic particle from which the new white-collar world
will be constructed and/or reconstructed,'' he writes (in boldface,
of course).
</P>
<P>
   Such a project-centered synergy is occurring on the leading edge
of business in Silicon Valley, Peters reports.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, professional firms such as lawyers, accountants,
architects and financial services have yet to be seriously studied,
Peters says. His books are attempts to fill that gap and show
readers where work is headed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once at the periphery _ and seen, frankly, as parasites of the
manufacturing-based economy _ these outfits are now front and
center and role definers in the so-called knowledge economy,''
Peters writes. ``They're all dedicated to the same thing: providing
services and making money by leveraging knowledge. Period.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Project 50,'' Peters discusses topics from making deadlines
to celebrating failures as ways to redefine jobs in light of
professional projects.
</P>
<P>
   Such a shift is necessary for workers to survive in the next
century, Peters says in all three books.
</P>
<P>
   ``The White-Collar Revolution will envelop 90-plus percent of
us. And quickly,'' Peters writes. ``The commonplace, if traumatic,
changes that came to the factory, the distribution center, and the
London docks are now racing toward the relatively unscathed world
of purchasing, finance, etc.''
</P>
<P>
   Peters definitely has things to say, but it may take a few days
of tough reading to find them.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Jacket blurbs
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Global Business: 308 Tips to Take Your Company Worldwide''
</P>
<P>
   By Lawrence E. Koslow and Robert H. Scarlett
</P>
<P>
   Gulf Publishing, $26.95
</P>
<P>
   This book, written by two consultants, is an excellent how-to
for those wanting to expand globally. It covers the basics, such as
transporting goods, planning operations, international financial
management, tax planning and marketing and sales. The book also
covers areas not normally found in a primer, such as how
family-owned businesses can go global by developing family
networks. Another section is devoted to cultural differences in
international ethics. Finally, the authors provide their take on
international trends.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Action Coaching: How to Leverage Individual Performance for
Company Success''
</P>
<P>
   By David L. Dotlich and Peter C. Cairo
</P>
<P>
   Josey-Bass, $28
</P>
<P>
   Although other coaching methods may focus strictly on
performance improvements, Action Coaching takes a step back to
tinker with employees' self-awareness. Consultants and educators
David Dotlich and Peter Cairo have developed this method for large
corporate clients such as AT&AMP;T, Colgate and Merck.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Million Dollar Prospecting Techniques''
</P>
<P>
   By the Million Dollar Round Table Center for Productivity
</P>
<P>
   John Wiley &AMP; Sons, $16.95
</P>
<P>
   This book joins ``Million Dollar Closing Techniques'' and
``Million Dollar Selling Techniques.'' The authors are from the
Million Dollar Round Table, an international association made up of
the world's top 6 percent of life insurance producers. These 19,000
people from 400 companies probably know a thing or two about deals.
The books are full of interesting tips from those who are on the
line and have succeeded.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Teresa McUsic reviews business books for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
