<HEADER>
A1436 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-FBN-KNAPP-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      10-28 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-KNAPP-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME IS ON THE SIDE OF 49ERS' QB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GWEN KNAPP  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA CLARA, Calif. _ Steve Mariucci remembered a phone
conversation with his quarterback from this summer, just before
49ers training camp opened. Steve Young, exhilarated by the thought
of another season, told the coach that he thought he could play
past his 40th birthday, well past his 40th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me he wanted to play five more years,'' Mariucci said.
</P>
<P>
   The coach told this story as a reminder of why Young won't be
able to walk away from football as casually as so many people have
suggested.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday was a month to the day since Young lay silently on a
field in Arizona, knocked unconscious by his fourth concussion in
three years. Since then, he has been advised, sermonized and
editorialized on the issue of retirement. In just 30 days, he has
been expected to find a way to surrender his goals for the next
five years.
</P>
<P>
   It is an absurd expectation. He needs time, lots of it. This is
a decision that easily could, and probably should, carry into next
summer. There's no hurry.
</P>
<P>
   The one realistic expectation is that he will shut down the 1999
season, becoming a de facto assistant coach rather than a player.
Young hasn't come to that conclusion yet. Mariucci is driving him
there, though, taking the scenic route.
</P>
<P>
   ``If time and patience is something he feels is really important
to him to make that decision, then we owe him that,'' Mariucci
said.
</P>
<P>
   There will be shouts of protest over this, over whether Young
should quickly vacate his roster spot, moving onto injured reserve,
to accommodate another player. The shouts will be a lot of empty
noise. Be clear on this: Young, 38, isn't being selfish or arrogant
when he refuses to give up on 1999. He's just being himself.
</P>
<P>
   If you've appreciated his energy, his skill, his zeal and his
graciousness over the years, it's impossible to criticize him now
for holding on to the tiniest of hopes.
</P>
<P>
   The legendary ruthlessness of the 49ers won't apply here.
</P>
<P>
   The team that dumped Joe Montana and jettisoned Ronnie Lott
doesn't exist anymore. This team is 3-4. It has been outscored by
more points than any other NFL team outside of Cleveland,
Cincinnati and Atlanta. Slapping Young on IR and then signing a
player recently waived by someone else won't turn the Niners into
contenders again.
</P>
<P>
   As they look to rebuild, the 49ers have to convince free agents
that they are still a great organization. Shoving aside Steve Young
for some castoff special-teamer will do nothing for their image.
</P>
<P>
   Mariucci admitted that Young might be getting special treatment,
extra time to think things over, because of who he is. Then again,
Young has always taken on special responsibilities, extra burdens.
The double standard works both ways. In the end, the 49ers will get
far more than they've given.
</P>
<P>
   At his news conference Wednesday, Young said he realized that
young people looked up to him, that recklessness with his health
could encourage them to take chances with their own. He alluded to
the death of a San Jose high school football player who had
suffered a concussion and then been hit hard again last week, this
time fatally. The teen-ager's death, he said, affected all of the
49ers.
</P>
<P>
   Young kept saying that he did not want to trivialize concussions
by any of his actions. He advised all athletes to take
neuropsychological exams regularly to see whether any of their
cognitive skills are faltering. That may seem like a token
suggestion, but doctors have had a difficult time persuading pro
football players to submit to the exams. They and their agents tend
to be uncomfortable with the idea that teams might be able to
quantify mental decline.
</P>
<P>
   Young has seen at least three doctors now about his condition,
in what appears to be a scavenger hunt for clearance to play. But
he doesn't seem to be following the most desperate and reckless
course of all: disguising his symptoms. He has revealed publicly
that he has had headaches, grogginess and sleeplessness since the
Arizona game. He tried running during practice to stay in shape and
found himself woozy, so he stopped.
</P>
<P>
   Mariucci knew all about this. Young didn't try to hide it.
</P>
<P>
   He says the post-concussion complications have subsided. He is
able to do some running again. Mariucci said he recognized the old
feistiness in Young again, saw him smiling more. He said he would
love to see him on the field again, running around, making plays.
He'd love to give Young five more years. But Mariucci also wants to
be realistic, so he'll settle for the feistiness and the smiles
right now, hoping that they will last a lifetime.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
