<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 16:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1439 &Cx1f; taf-z
u t BC-APPLES-CINCINNATI-ART     10-28 1236
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPLES-CINCINNATI-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON THE ROAD: CINCINNATI: NORTHERN, SOUTHERN, SLEEPY AND DYNAMIC 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By R.W. APPLE Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI, Ohio _ This old river town, with a site of uncommon
beauty and a populace of uncommon civility, has a reputation as a
stick-in-the-mud all the same. Mark Twain suggested that he'd like
to come here for the apocalypse because it was always 20 years
behind the times. Decades later, John Gunther detected ``a certain
stately and also sleepy quality'' in the place.
</P>
<P>
   Even Gov. Bob Taft of Ohio, a member of the city's (and the
nation's) longest-lasting political dynasty, told me when I ran
into him at a football game that Cincinnati has ``an inbred
resistance to rapid change.'' Longfellow, on the other hand,
described this as the ``Queen City of the West,'' and in hard times
Cincinnati has clung to that phrase like a life raft.
</P>
<P>
   The most celebrated outcropping of the city's conservatism in
recent years was the indictment on April 7, 1990, of the
Contemporary Arts Center and its director on obscenity charges
arising from an exhibition of 175 Robert Mapplethorpe photographs.
A few of them depicted explicit homoerotic subjects. Much less
attention was paid when a local jury, largely working-class in
makeup, acquitted both defendants six months later.
</P>
<P>
   Which was par for the course. People also tend to overlook the
city's cultural traditions, especially its rich musical heritage,
and its record of innovation in many fields. It had the first
professional baseball team: the Cincinnati Red Stockings, now the
Reds, founded in 1869. John A. Roebling's suspension bridge across
the Ohio River, which remains in service to this day, opened in
1866, 17 years before the Brooklyn Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   It was in Cincinnati as well that Rabbi Isaac Mayer Wise of the
Plum Street Temple, born in Bohemia, gave shape to modern Reform
Judaism through the Hebrew Union College, the Central Conference of
American Rabbis and the Union of American Hebrew Congregations. The
rabbi called his Byzanto-Moorish temple ``my Alhambra.''
</P>
<P>
   Play-Doh was invented here, and Formica, and soap that floats.
Rather more significantly for human well-being, Dr. Albert Sabin
developed his oral polio vaccine while working here, and Dr. Henry
Heimlich perfected his life-saving maneuver for choking victims.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years several local institutions, notably the
University of Cincinnati, have commissioned new buildings from a
galaxy of groundbreaking architects, including Frank O. Gehry,
Michael Graves, Peter Eisenman, Cesar Pelli and Harry Cobb, among
others. The Contemporary Arts Center, focus of the Mapplethorpe
flap, and not some elite organization in California or New York,
gave the highly regarded Iraqi-born architect Zaha Hadid her first
big commission in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Gehry's Vontz Center for Molecular Studies, which opened on
Sept. 23, looks like one of those cartoon buildings that are
jumping off their foundations, almost ready to burst. The red-brick
structure is defined by its bulges and the metal grids of its
windows. It forms a vivid if startling gateway to the university,
which Herbert Muschamp has described in The New York Times as ``one
of the most architecturally dynamic campuses in America today.''
</P>
<P>
   A little bit Northern, a little bit Southern, Cincinnati comes
close to the national average by a number of standards, including
cost of living and median family income.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Civil War, some Cincinnatians with extensive business
dealings in the South defended that region's Peculiar Institution.
But local abolitionists helped thousands of slaves escape across
the Ohio River to freedom, defying apostles of the status quo.
Lyman Beecher, a fiery Presbyterian preacher, spent two decades as
president of a seminary here, and his daughter, Harriet Beecher
Stowe, drew on her experiences in Ohio and Kentucky in writing the
enormously influential anti-slavery novel ``Uncle Tom's Cabin.''
</P>
<P>
   That history will be celebrated in an $80 million National
Underground Railroad Museum, now in the planning stage. It will be
a major element in the ongoing reinvention of the riverfront, the
place where the city began. A pair of new sports stadiums will be
there, too _ one for the Reds, to be finished in 2003, the other
for the football Bengals, to open next year.
</P>
<P>
   The Ohio was one of the main highways west, and that made
Cincinnati a boom town in the years after the Revolution. Founded
in 1788, it was given its name by Arthur St. Clair, governor of the
Northwest Territory. Having fought as commander of the New Jersey
militia at the battles of Trenton and Princeton, among others, and
attained the rank of major general, St. Clair became a member of
the Society of the Cincinnati, an organization of Revolutionary
officers founded by George Washington. The society was named for
Cincinnatus, a Roman patriot who returned to his farm after saving
his city in battle, and this city, in turn, was named for the
society.
</P>
<P>
   The twin post-modern headquarters towers of Procter &AMP; Gamble,
the nation's largest producer of products for use in the household,
dominate the eastern part of downtown Cincinnati. The company has a
new chief executive, Durk I. Jager, reputedly installed to shake
things up, and the company still reaches into every city, town and
hamlet in America with Tide, Ivory, Pampers, Crisco, Folger's, Old
Spice and dozens of other brands.
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati is also home base for Federated Department Stores,
the retailing leviathan that operates more than 400 stores
nationwide, including Macy's, Stern's and Bloomingdale's in the New
York area; Chiquita Brands, the world's biggest banana company, and
Kroger, which grew from a single grocery store started in 1883 by
Barney Kroger, with $372 of his own and $350 borrowed from a
friend, into the nation's biggest supermarket chain.
</P>
<P>
   General Electric, which makes more jet aircraft engines than
anyone else in the world, makes many of them in a huge plant in
suburban Evendale. And who could overlook the weirdly named Fifth
Third bank, formed in a 1908 merger between institutions that
insisted on retaining their identities?
</P>
<P>
   But Cincinnati missed what may have been its biggest economic
opportunity. At the turn of the last century, it was the world's
biggest manufacturer of carriages; when a couple of entrepreneurs
named Henry Ford and J.W. Packard came looking for capital to start
their auto factories, the local bankers turned them down. So they
went to Detroit instead.
</P>
<P>
   Having already missed the information technology boom, business
and medical leaders here are now working hard to make the city a
leader in biotechnology. Led by Procter &AMP; Gamble and the University
of Cincinnati, a task force is talking about the investment of
years of effort and hundreds of millions of dollars. A study
released by the group cited among the city's assets its quality of
life; but in entrepreneurial culture _ the willingness to take a
chance _ the study ranked this region 18th among 21 nationally.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps because the region reminded them of the Rhineland,
Germans flooded into the Ohio Valley in the 1840s and '50s,
eventually constituting a quarter of Cincinnati's population.
German-language newspapers were founded, beer gardens sprang up in
every neighborhood and German was taught in the public schools. All
that came to a swift end with World War I.
</P>
<P>
   But the Teutonic flavor lingers. The arty neighborhood north of
downtown is called Over-the-Rhine. Oktoberfest (inexplicably
scheduled for mid-September) is one of the city's many annual
fetes. Graeter's ice cream, dished up in shops around the city, is
another, super-delicious survivor of the city's Germanic past.
</P>
<P>
   Zoology is a German passion, too, and Cincinnati has long
boasted one of the nation's premier zoos, under Edward J. Maruska,
its widely respected executive director. Lately it has opened a new
Manatee Springs exhibit, home to Douglas and Stoneman, a pair of
the endangered cowlike marine mammals from the Florida coast.
</P>
<P>
   The most important legacy, however, is the city's love of music.
The May Festival, which dates from 1873, grew out of Saengerfests,
or songfests, that were given starting in 1849, with up to 2,000
volunteer chorus members. The Music Hall, a sauerbraten Gothic
palace that seats 3,400 people, with spectacular chandeliers and a
lovely lobby in cream and gold, was completed in 1878 as a home for
the festival. It now houses the Cincinnati Symphony Orchestra,
Cincinnati Pops and Cincinnati Summer Opera as well.
</P>
<P>
   A distinguished roster of European conductors have taken charge
of the festival, which still concentrates on choral music. Among
them have been Eugene Goossens, Fritz Busch, Josef Krips and Max
Rudolf. In 1906, Edward Elgar traveled to Cincinnati to conduct his
``Dream of Gerontius.''
</P>
<P>
   Since 1974, Americans have been at the festival's helm:
Cincinnati-born James Levine until 1979, James Conlon for the two
decades since then. Maestro Conlon is one of those American
musicians who have made their careers largely in Europe (mostly
France and Germany, in his case), but Cincinnati recognized his
gifts early. Now he is the principal conductor of the Paris Opera
and the Cologne Philharmonic, but he nonetheless returns to Ohio
each year.
</P>
<P>
   The Cincinnati Symphony, founded in 1895, also has a
distinguished history, having had Leopold Stokowski, Fritz Reiner
and Thomas Schippers as conductors; Schippers, who died young, was
a great local favorite who also worked at Bayreuth and, notably, at
Spoleto in Italy. The Spaniard Jesus Lopez-Cobos is the current
music director, and the orchestra, which plays a full
September-to-May season, remains more adventurous than most.
</P>
<P>
   This year the Cincinnatians are playing Glinka, Korngold,
Honegger, Nielsen, Griffes, Scriabin, Weill and Zwilich in addition
to more conventional musical fare.
</P>
<P>
   The Pops, probably the best-known such ensemble after Boston's,
has gained an international reputation under Erich Kunzel. It has
made no fewer than 65 records for Telarc, which have sold more than
seven million copies worldwide and earned the charismatic Kunzel
enough in the process to buy houses in the Bahamas and on Swan's
Island off the Maine coast.
</P>
<P>
   In the summer the Pops moves to Riverbend, a complex along the
Ohio River five miles east of town that was designed for the
orchestra by Michael Graves.
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati's theatrical pride and joy is the Aronoff Center for
the Arts, built in the heart of downtown to a design by Pelli. It
has three halls that can house everything from touring Broadway
musicals to the productions of the Cincinnati Ballet to small-scale
experiments.
</P>
<P>
   The Playhouse in the Park, a professional company with the good
fortune to perform in a leafy aerie overlooking the city, will
present 10 productions this season, ranging from ``Much Ado About
Nothing'' to ``Wit,'' Margaret Edson's 1999 Pulitzer Prize winner.
The small but enterprising Ensemble Theater performs in a converted
bank building in Over-the-Rhine; Edward Albee has directed several
of his plays there. And the Cincinnati Opera puts on nine
performances of four operas every June and July (``Pelleas and
Melisande'' is one of the features in 2000) in the Music Hall.
</P>
<P>
   As for the visual arts, the city has not one but two important
museums _the Cincinnati Art Museum and the Taft Museum _ both
linked with the remarkable Taft family. The fact that both lent
important works to the Ingres exhibition in Washington and New York
this year, a connoisseur's show if ever there was one, suggests the
quality of their best holdings.
</P>
<P>
   Across town, the old Union Terminal, a railway station that
looks like a Bakelite Art Deco radio rendered in concrete, has been
turned into the Cincinnati Museum Center. A landmark of Deco
architecture, it continues to evoke the drama of travel in the
golden age of rail, while sheltering a history museum, a children's
museum, a museum of natural history and science and an IMAX movie
theater under its soaring half-dome.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Here is a sampling of local attractions, as well as other
information about Cincinnati: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Where to Stay  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE CINCINNATIAN, &LR;  601 Vine St., (513) 381-3000. Designed by
the city's favorite fin-de-siecle architect, Samuel Hannaford, and
thoroughly rebuilt in 1987, this is now Cincinnati's pre-eminent
hotel. Double room: $240 weekdays; $180 weekends.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OMNI NETHERLAND PLAZA, &LR;  35 West Fifth St., (513) 421-9100. The
decor is the thing in this Art Deco classic, built in 1930 and
embellished with Rookwood tiles, chromium torchiers and a sea horse
fountain. A 1983 renovation swept away a half-century's wear and
tear, and the place sparkles as it did when Churchill and Roosevelt
stayed there. Double room: $210 to $230 weekdays; $130 to $150
weekends.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WESTIN, &LR;  Fountain Square, (513) 621-7700. The location is
perfect, the tastefully redecorated rooms have plenty of elbow
room, and the hotel can even claim a footnote in history: the
infamous ``Jerry Springer Show'' originated from the premises in
its early days. Double room: $109 to $220 weekdays; $105 to $135
weekends.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Where to Eat  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMP WASHINGTON CHILI, &LR;  3005 Colerain Avenue, (513) 541-0061.
Created in 1922 by a Bulgarian immigrant, Cincinnati-style chili
took the town by storm. This improbable passion has never abated,
and now there are three chains with 150-odd outlets, plus
independents. Lean over when you eat; the stuff stains.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MAISONETTE, &LR;  114 East Sixth St., (513 721-2260. This is the
Maisonette's 50th anniversary year. You can return to the 1960s in
this traditional, formal, softly lighted place, ordering things
like Dover sole along with the city's famously stodgy movers and
shakers. Superb desserts and wonderful wines.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE PALACE, &LR;  Cincinnatian Hotel (see above). The best of the
city's hotel dining rooms serves the closest thing Cincinnati has
to New American cooking. The menu includes seasonal regional
offerings like a soft-shell crab po' boy as well as many standard
items like grilled swordfish.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; JEFF RUBY'S, &LR;  700 Walnut St., (513) 784-1200. A brash
transplant from New Jersey, Jeff Ruby wore spats to the opening
benefit at this addition to his chain of Cincinnati watering holes.
Beef and lamb is dry-aged in a glass-walled cooler (cf Gallagher's,
New York), and smokers can enjoy their Delmonico steaks and Bibb
salads, their Jordan cabernet or Ducru-Beaucaillou and their cigars
in the Toots Shor room.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRIO, &LR;  7565 Kenwood Road, Kenwood, (513) 984-1905. A lot of the
culinary action in Cincinnati is in the suburbs, and Trio stands
out from a slew of other restaurants there for its mostly American
wine list (three Ridge zinfandels, 36 selections by the glass,
gentle prices). The food runs the middlebrow gamut from meatloaf to
designer pizzas to fine wood-grilled salmon.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Attractions &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MUSIC HALL, &LR;  1241 Elm St., (513) 381-3300. ``Pops Weekend:
Thanksgiving With the Pops,'' Cincinnati Pops; Erich Kunzel,
conductor, with the gospel singers Sandy Patti and John Schneider,
the actor Richard Thomas, members of the Cincinnati Ballet and the
May Festival Chorus. Music of Aaron Copland, traditional
Thanksgiving hymns and a narration of the First Thanksgiving; the
event will be taped for broadcast on PBS on Nov. 19. Cincinnati
Symphony Orchestra; John Adams, guest conductor, with the May
Festival Chorus. Nov. 5 and Nov. 6, at 8 p.m. Cincinnati Symphony
Orchestra; Paavo Jarvi, conductor; Yumi Hwang, violin; works by
Sibelius and by John Adams, who will conduct his composition. Nov.
12 at 11 a.m. and Nov. 13 at 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ARONOFF CENTER FOR THE ARTS, &LR;  650 Walnut St., (513) 621-2787. A
performing arts complex with three theaters.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PLAYHOUSE IN THE PARK, &LR;  962 Mt. Adams Circle, (513) 421-3888.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENSEMBLE THEATER, &LR;  1127 Vine St., (513) 421-3555.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CONTEMPORARY ARTS CENTER, &LR;  115 E. Fifth St., (513) 345-8400.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CINCINNATI ART MUSEUM, &LR;  953 Eden Park Dr., (513) 639-2995.
Hours: Tuesdays through Saturdays, 10 a.m. to 5 p.m.; Sundays, noon
to 6 p.m.; closed Mondays. Admission: $5; $4, students and those 55
and over; free for children under 18.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TAFT MUSEUM, &LR;  316 Pike St., (513) 241-0343.
</P>
<P>
   ``Small Paintings From the Taft Collection,'' through Jan. 17.
Hours: Mondays through Saturdays, 10 a.m. to 5 p.m.; Sundays, 1 to
5 p.m. Admission: $4; $2, the elderly and students; free for
children 18 or younger and for everyone on Wednesdays.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CINCINNATI MUSEUM CENTER, &LR;  1301 Western Avenue, (800) 733-2077
or (513) 287-7000. Includes the Cincinnati History Museum, the
Cinergy Children's Museum, the Museum of Natural History and
Science, the Robert D. Lindner Family Omnimax Theater and the
Cincinnati Historical Society Library. Hours: Mondays through
Saturdays, 10 a.m. to 5 p.m.; Sundays, 11 a.m. to 6 p.m. Admission
to one museum or Omnimax: $6.50; $5.50, the elderly; $4.50 for
children 3 to 12; $3.50 for children 2 and under.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CINCINNATI ZOO, &LR;  3400 Vine St. (entrance on Dury Avenue), (513)
281-4700. Hours: 9 a.m. to 5 p.m.; the park closes at dusk.
Admission: $10; $7, the elderly; children 2 to 12, $4.75; children
under 2, free.
</P>
</TEXT>
