<HEADER>
A1441 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-HOMEVIDEO-2TAKES-NYT &LR;      10-28 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMEVIDEO-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`VIDEO HOUND,' NEW AND BIGGER; JAMES BOND ON DVD; NEW RELEASES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even with the Internet, some of the most formidable video guides
are still measured in pounds and numbers of pages. In the case of
the new 2000 edition of ``Video Hound's Golden Movie Retriever''
(Visible Ink Press), that's 5 pounds and 1,700 pages (with 12 blank
ones for notes or whatever).
</P>
<P>
   Jim Craddock, who edited the ``Hound'' with Martin Connors, said
that about 1,000 movies have been added to this year's collection,
bringing the total to 24,000 or so. The guide lists 2,000 movies on
digital videodisc, which accounts for much of the growth. Also, he
said, people are watching a lot of old films on cable stations like
the American Movie Channel and Turner Movie Classics and requesting
that they be brought out on video if they aren't available already.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Hound'' lists only movies that are on tape and disc.
``We'd get calls all the time asking, `How come that movie isn't in
the book?''' Craddock said, adding that now many more of those
movies are on video.
</P>
<P>
   Category lists are always a highlight in the ``Hound'' and run
almost 200 pages in this edition. ``Adventure drama'' is one of the
more prosaic classifications, but categories roam from ``Bad Dads''
and ``Big Rigs'' to ``Sanity Check'' and ``Wonder Women.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the Internet, the ``Hound'' lists the Web sites for
dozens of studios, actors, directors, films, film guides, cult
movie resources, film magazines, festivals, reviews and video
outlets. The price is $21.95.
</P>
<P>
   Bond, James Bond  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DVDs have plenty of room for extras (though the average release
is often bereft of them), but a new set of seven James Bond movies
from MGM has gone the extra step. For example, with ``Goldfinger,''
the inventory includes one movie-length commentary by Guy Hamilton,
the director, and another commentary by the cast and crew; a
making-of-``Goldfinger'' documentary and another documentary about
the film's popularity; a large collection of stills; radio
interviews with Sean Connery, and promotional spots and features.
</P>
<P>
   All of this can run to overkill, but it is frequently
entertaining. On one ``Goldfinger'' documentary, Hamilton says that
his long-delinquent London parking tickets inspired the idea for
the famous revolving license plates on the Bond car. Theodore Bikel
is shown reading for the role of Goldfinger. He lost hands down to
Gert Frobe. And for Shirley Eaton, recipient of perhaps the most
famous paint job in movie history, a doctor was on hand in case of
skin suffocation.
</P>
<P>
   The other films are ``Thunderball,'' ``Live and Let Die,'' ``For
Your Eyes Only,'' ``License to Kill,'' ``Goldeneye'' and ``Tomorrow
Never Dies.'' Some of the discs have even more extras than
``Goldfinger,'' including music videos, interviews with composers
and story boards. ``Live and Let Die'' even has a commercial for
the British milk board. The price is $34.98 each or $199.98 for the
set.
</P>
<P>
   NEW RELEASES
</P>
<P>
   `LOLITA'
</P>
<P>
   Although rejected by American theater exhibitors for fear of
backlash against the subject of pedophilia, Adrian Lyne's
adaptation of Vladimir Nabokov's novel appeared last year on
Showtime. As Humbert Humbert, Jeremy Irons conveys astonishing
complexity, and the film's masterstroke is that this is Humbert's
story told in his own lyrical voice and from his own tortured
perspective. As the nymphet who is the object of his desire, Ms.
Swain is long-limbed, petulant and wisecracking. ``Rich beyond what
anyone could have expected,'' Caryn James wrote in The New York
Times, ``the film repays repeated viewings.''
</P>
<P>
   1997. Trimark. $14.99. 137 minutes. R.
</P>
<P>
   `ARLINGTON ROAD'
</P>
<P>
   Headed home one day, Michael Faraday (Jeff Bridges) finds a boy
wounded in the roadway and later, after rushing him to the
hospital, becomes friends with his parents, the Langs (Tim Robbins
and Joan Cusack), who happen to live next door. A professor who
specializes in urban terrorism, Farraday eventually has reason to
wonder where the diabolically pleasant Langs came from and then to
connect them to the kind of crimes he lectures about in the
classroom. The strength of Mark Pellington's well-paced and
cleverly constructed film ``lies in a string of ingenious little
surprises and in an overall deviousness that doesn't show until the
story is over'' (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   1999. Columbia Tri-Star. $107.37. 119 minutes. Closed captioned.
R.
</P>
<P>
   `BIG DADDY'
</P>
<P>
   A fine specimen of belching young movie manhood, a highway toll
taker named Sonny (Adam Sandler) suddenly finds himself responsible
for a 5-year-old named Julian (alternately played by Cole and Dylan
Sprouse). Seems the boy's mother has reneged, and his father, a
friend of Sonny's, doesn't feel up to the task. That leaves the
caretaking to Sonny, who accepts in the belief that it will impress
his girlfriend, who promptly dumps him. A cut above a total
imbecile, Sonny perseveres, but that leads to another problem.
Normally flourishing on infantile, anarchic moments, Sandler is too
much the nice guy, which ``gives the film tepid predictability
instead of cutting edge'' (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   1999. Columbia Tri-Star. $21.96. 95 minutes. Closed captioned.
PG-13. Release date: Next Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   `JACK FROST'
</P>
<P>
   In snowy Colorado a struggling rock musician named Jack (Michael
Keaton) leaves his wife (Kelly Preston) and 12-year-old son (Joseph
Cross) to play a New Year's gig. One car wreck later, he has
departed this life, but then his boy discovers something odd in the
front yard. Yes, it's Dad, back as a snowman to romp with the son
he never had time for when he was flesh and blood. Bring on the
heavy emotional artillery in ``a film so sugar-coated that it makes
other recent efforts in this genre look blisteringly honest''
(Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   1998. Warner. $19.96. 95 minutes. Closed captioned. PG. Release
date: Next Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Other new titles of interest, some of which may have had a
theater release, appeared on television or been on videocassette in
earlier editions.
</P>
<P>
   `THE OGRE'
</P>
<P>
   In Volker Schlondorff's film, a French misfit (John Malkovich)
becomes a lackey for high-ranking Nazis and is sent to round up
young boys as conscripts. ``Malkovich gives an understated
performance that captures the ambiguity of a character who does
monstrous things yet remains a tenderhearted innocent,'' Stephen
Holden wrote in The New York Times. 1996. Kino. $79.95. 117
minutes. No rating.
</P>
<P>
   `THE PASSION OF JOAN OF ARC'
</P>
<P>
   Carl Theodor Dreyer's silent masterpiece of 1928, starring Maria
Falconetti, focuses on Joan's trial for heresy. Richard Einhorn's
oratorio ``Voices of Light'' accompanies the film, released on
videocassette by Home Vision ($29.95, 82 minutes) and on DVD
($49.95, Nov. 9) by the Criterion Collection.
</P>
<P>
   `JOAN OF ARC'
</P>
<P>
   The CBS mini-series, with the 16-year-old Leelee Sobieski as
Joan, John Malkovich as Charles VII and Peter O'Toole as Bishop
Cauchon, covers the tale from her birth in 1412 to the burning at
the stake in 1431. Artisan. $19.98; DVD, $19.98. 140 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   `ON THE ROAD AGAIN: DOWN HOME BLUES, JAZZ, GOSPEL AND MORE'
</P>
<P>
   A 1963 documentary travels the country in search of traditional
American music. In Texas, Mance Lispcomb sings ``Goin' Down Slow''
on his front porch, and Hop Wilson plays steel guitar in Miss
Irene's Tavern. In San Francisco, Lowell Fulsom, a shaper of West
Coast blues, is filmed at the Blue Mirror Club, and King Louis H.
Narcisse leads his congregation of gospel rockers. In Nashville,
the Blind James Campbell String Band plays ``John Henry.'' And In
New Orleans the clarinetist George Lewis renders ``I Ain't Gonna
Give Nobody None of My Jelly Roll.'' 1999. Shanachie. $19.95. 50
minutes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
