<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-ROBBIE-WILLIAMS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITAIN'S ROBBIE WILLIAMS INVADES THE U.S. 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOEY GUERRA 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Don't mind Robbie Williams: He's simply being himself.
</P>
<P>
   The British pop star, who is on his first U.S. tour, is heralded
in his native land as much for his music as his bad-boy behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Williams first made headlines as the rebellious member of the
U.K. boy-band Take That, a phenomenally successful outfit that sold
17 million albums and scored nine No. 1 singles.
</P>
<P>
   Williams grew tired of pre-packaged pop, however, and left the
band in 1995. He indulged in alcohol and drugs, popped up in
tabloids that reveled in his post boy-band weight gain and ranted
constantly about Gary Barlow, his former Take That bandmate.
</P>
<P>
   Things changed, however, with the 1997 release of Williams'
debut solo album, ``Life Thru a Lens,'' in the U.K. It faltered on
the charts before the 1997 Christmas single, ``Angels,'' was
released. Almost singlehandedly, that song revived Williams'
career, spending weeks at the No. 1 spot and solidifying the
performer's reputation as a solo force to be reckoned with.
</P>
<P>
   The album eventually sold more than 4 million copies, and a
second CD, ``I've Been Expecting You,'' met with similar success.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Williams is aiming for stateside listeners with ``The Ego
Has Landed,'' his U.S. debut album, which compiles the best tracks
from his two U.K. efforts. It's a joyous affair, full of glittering
pop melodies and witty lyrics.
</P>
<P>
   The first single, ``Millennium,'' made a few waves on MTV but
barely dented the pop charts. No matter _ Williams has been down
that path before. ``Angels,'' which he says is his favorite of the
songs he's written, was recently released as the second U.S.
single.
</P>
<P>
   ``After being in America for a week, I sort of pinch myself and
go, `Why do you feel so good?''' said Williams, 25, in a call from
London. ``It's because nobody knows me there. Then I'm thinking,
`You're here to promote a record that's gonna blow your anonymity
in America.' I'm wrestling between the two things.''
</P>
<P>
   In conversation, Williams is a barrage of paradoxes and
contradictions. He's sweetly insecure one minute (``I'm sort of
getting used to the fact that I'm good at what I do'') and raving
about his James Bond fixation the next (``You get to shoot
everybody, sleep with people and basically save the world''), which
he plays up in the tongue-in-cheek video for ``Millennium.''
</P>
<P>
   He even admits an affection for Australian pop diva Kylie
Minogue (``I've got this crush onnd it's doing me in. It's
not professional. I can't even look her in the eyes.'') with whom
he recently recorded a duet.
</P>
<P>
   What's most refreshing about Williams, however, is his sincerity
and honesty regarding his ever-unpredictable career. He admits the
path he's reading isn't one he initially envisioned for himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was at school,'' he said. ``I didn't really know what I
wanted to do. I didn't wanna go to college and university to get an
education and do a 9 to 5. I still think I'm in the wrong job. I'm
just here because nobody else wanted to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Given Williams' unique way with a song, it's doubtful that just
any former teen idol could have accomplished so much.
</P>
<P>
   As for his own experience as part of the well-scrubbed hit
machine that was Take That, Williams remains vague. Much of the
problem undoubtedly stemmed from personality clashes between
Williams and Barlow (who also embarked on a solo career) and the
taut strings pulled by Take That puppet-master and manager Nigel
Martin-Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've done all the talking I could probably handle about Take
That,'' he said. ``All I will say in the matter is that something
happened to me when I was in the band that really messed me up. The
whys and wherefores of that I don't really want to go into because
it will probably be too painful for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Take That _ which was conceived as the British answer to New
Kids on the Block _ scored a U.S. hit with the breezy ballad ``Back
for Good'' in 1995, but the band's major successes occurred
overseas.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Williams is competing with boy bands on the pop charts
all over again, and he has some pointed opinions about such groups
as the Backstreet Boys and 'N Sync (who have problems of their own
regarding record contracts).
</P>
<P>
   ``You can see the inner struggle for supremacy that these boys
have and these girls have _ this struggle and this complete
mistrust of their own ability,'' Williams said. ``It's funny
because all of them are trying to be the supreme one in the band
but also have no self-worth, no confidence, at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams is even more candid about his bouts with alcohol and
drugs. He cleaned himself up for the most part, but it wasn't for
the usual reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vanity saved my life, I think, at one point,'' Williams said.
``I can't stand having an extra millimeter on my stomach, let alone
having a whole yard. When I was growing up, I lived for love, and I
lived for life. Very quickly, that was taken away from me through
drugs and through drink. With responsibility, I became a cripple. I
couldn't do it, and that's not me. I faced up to it, and I'm doing
all right today.''
</P>
<P>
   Considering Williams' success, that would be a serious
understatement. Along with album sales and hit singles, Williams
was recently named ``Sexiest Man in the World'' by a reader's poll
in the British edition of Cosmopolitan magazine. He also signed a
$3.2 million promotional deal with Pepsi Cola.
</P>
<P>
   Conquering America, then, seems the next logical step. Or maybe
not.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all a bit too much to handle for me right now, to be
honest with you,'' Williams said. ``America's such a big place, and
it brings its own thing into your life that I'm a bit scared of.
I'm a bit insecure about the thought of going to America and
tackling it and if I want the responsibility of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if Williams doesn't ascend to superstar status here, he can
always enjoy the scenery.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives me a good excuse to travel,'' he said. ``People think
that I'm actually there to promote the single or an album. I'm not.
I'm there to eat food and see people. Golf spoils a good walk, and
fame, and what I do for a living, spoils a really nice travel card
around the world.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
