<HEADER>
A1447 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-VIDEO-REVIEW-HNS &LR;      10-28 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DREW `NEVER' SEEMED THIS SWEET 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BRUCE WESTBROOK 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   `NEVER BEEN KISSED'
</P>
<P>
   1999, PG-13, Fox, CC, VHS priced for rental, DVD $34.98
</P>
<P>
   Drew Barrymore is trying too hard.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Wedding Singer'' and ``Ever After,'' she shed her
bad-girl image. Fine _ but now she's pandering so much to sweetness
and light that she seems bent on being a modern-day Shirley Temple.
</P>
<P>
   Here she plays a young Chicago woman who had been mistreated by
classmates in high school. (Her four-year college experience is
disregarded as irrelevant.)
</P>
<P>
   Her crime? She was a wallflower.
</P>
<P>
   She gets a chance to make up for it in her 20s when her
newspaper sends her undercover to pose as a high schooler and get a
vague story on what kids are like.
</P>
<P>
   As in ``Message in a Bottle,'' Chicago newspapers are shown here
to be absurdly cushy. Barrymore, a copy editor, has a private
office _ with a window, at that _ and an assistant outside! Right.
</P>
<P>
   She also edits on paper, not a computer. Uh huh. And when she's
tabbed for field work, she's tracked by costly spy cameras, giving
the film a needless nudge toward ``EDtv'' and ``The Truman Show''
territory.
</P>
<P>
   Her school escapades start badly but inevitably turn toward
vindication and true love via a handsome teacher played by Michael
Vartan.
</P>
<P>
   As in too many movies, kids' vicious cruelty toward each other
is appalling and overdone. While showing less acting range than an
automated computer voice, the vulnerable Barrymore suffers
mightily, and her humor of haplessness goes only so far.
</P>
<P>
   Compensating are fun supporting players _ Molly Shannon and
David Arquette _ and an appealing sentimental side. ``Kissed'' may
miss in the brains department, but it certainly has a heart.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 1/2 stars &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `ARLINGTON ROAD'
</P>
<P>
   1999, R, Columbia TriStar, CC, VHS priced for rental, DVD $24.95
</P>
<P>
   This provocative film concerns anarchists bent on toppling the
federal government while concealing their cause by pinning
terrorist acts on crazed individuals.
</P>
<P>
   As a history professor whose wife, an FBI agent, was killed in a
Ruby Ridge-style conflict, Jeff Bridges is suspicious of both the
feds and his new neighbors (Tim Robbins and Joan Cusack), whose
wholesome facade seems to hide evil intent.
</P>
<P>
   As he struggles to expose the truth, Bridges goes too far off
the deep end for our sympathies. In some ways he's his own worst
enemy.
</P>
<P>
   But director Mark Pellington still tells a vivid and compelling
tale that bravely resists feel-good Hollywood formulas.
</P>
<P>
   On DVD, ``Arlington Road'' has a 20-minute ``making of''
documentary that's far from illuminating. Mostly, the filmmakers
sing each other's praises.
</P>
<P>
   No mention is made of the death of Bridges' father, actor Lloyd
Bridges, during production. Nor is any mention made of Houston,
where 90 percent of the movie was shot.
</P>
<P>
   Houston subbed for Washington, D.C., and its suburbs. The gated
community used for many scenes was in Pearland.
</P>
<P>
   The DVD also has an intriguing alternate ending, whose expanded
footage gives the movie more resonance.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 stars.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `LIFE'
</P>
<P>
   1999, R, Universal, CC, VHS priced for rental, DVD $29.98
</P>
<P>
   With Eddie Murphy and Martin Short on the marquee, this looks
like a comedy, and its marketing campaign hits hard on our funny
bones. But ``Life'' is more of a dramedy.
</P>
<P>
   It concerns two 1930s New Yorkers who wind up in a Mississippi
prison with life terms for a crime they didn't commit.
</P>
<P>
   Behind bars, the injustices continue, but the bickering, feisty
pair spark bursts of mirth with all the bluster they can muster.
</P>
<P>
   Don't stop to rewind before the end credits roll. The outtakes
offer the most sustained humor of the movie.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 1/2 stars.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MORE HORROR RELEASES &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To tap the popularity of horror hits ``The Blair Witch Project''
and ``The Sixth Sense,'' Elite Entertainment has issued two films
on DVD for $29.95.
</P>
<P>
   ``Horror Hotel'' (1960) begins with witch burnings in colonial
New England, then jumps to a '60s college student researching the
topic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lady in White'' (1988) has a boy (Lukas Haas) who sees visions
of a girl being killed and begging for her spirit to be put to
rest.
</P>
<P>
   Sound familiar?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
`PINOCCHIO' ON DVD &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Disney issues its first animated classic on DVD this week with
the bow of 1940's ``Pinocchio.'' That also happens to be the first
Disney animated film that hit sell-through _ on tape _ back in
</P>
<P>
   Pinocchio will be followed quickly by DVD releases of
``Hercules,'' ``Mulan'' and ``101 Dalmatians,'' Nov. 11; ``Peter
Pan,'' ``Lady and the Tramp'' and ``Lion King II,'' Nov. 23; and
``The Little Mermaid'' and ``The Jungle Book,'' Dec. 7.
</P>
<P>
   The discs' cost is a bit high _ a suggested $39.99 _ but you can
find them for less in some stores and online.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A RETURN FOR `OZ' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you bought ``The Wizard of Oz'' in 1996 when it was hyped as
the final video release of the century, you may feel burned: ``Oz''
is back, with deluxe new editions on VHS and DVD.
</P>
<P>
   Problem is, MGM made the promise, but Warner now owns the
rights.
</P>
<P>
   If you're not irked, no need to shirk this trip down the Yellow
Brick Road. It offers the restored ``Oz,'' which showed in theaters
last fall, and loads of extras for both tape and disc.
</P>
<P>
   On VHS ($24.99) the film offers an extra 50 minutes of features,
including a documentary and studio outtakes. The DVD ($24.98) has
those, plus unseen trailers and behind-the-scenes footage.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
VIDEO RATINGS &QL; 
 &QL; 
4 stars _ Excellent &QL; 
3 stars _ Good &QL; 
2 stars _ Fair &QL; 
1 star _Poor &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
