<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-WHALEY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ART IMITATES LIFE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LOUIS B. PARKS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ One of the most famous films of the French New Wave is
``The 400 Blows,'' Francois Truffaut's first feature work.
</P>
<P>
   Based on Truffaut's own youth, it's the starkly real and
unsentimental story of a young boy with little parental control or
affection. He has trouble in school and elsewhere, and eventually
winds up in a juvenile center.
</P>
<P>
   When watching ``Joe the King,'' the first film from actor Frank
Whaley, those familiar with Truffaut are immediately struck by the
similarities.
</P>
<P>
   Whaley's film, about a young boy (Noah Fleiss) growing up poor,
is also stark and almost as unsentimental. The boy has no parental
guidance, although his mother loves him. His drunken father, played
by Val Kilmer, gives him plenty of angry, worthless advice. A
thief, the boy is always on the verge of trouble, and finally faced
with reform school.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, ``Joe the King'' is close to the life of writer and
director Whaley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very much like Joe,'' said Whaley, whose more than three
dozen films and TV movies have included roles in ``The Doors''
(guitarist Robby Krieger), ``JFK,'' ``Pulp Fiction'' and the
upcoming CBS miniseries ``Shake, Rattle and Roll'' (Nov. 7).
</P>
<P>
   ``I was somewhat of a criminal mind, and I was always late for
school. But deeper than that, I was always alienated,'' Whaley
said. ``I was constantly very lonely as a child.''
</P>
<P>
   You get into trouble fast telling a filmmaker, ``Gee, your film
sure seemed a lot like some other guy's,'' even if that other guy
was Truffaut. So it was a relief that Whaley was more than ready to
acknowledge the resemblance and debt.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was in Syracuse in the mid-'70s, there was not a lot of
exposure to movies. There was for a brief period of time a revival
house, and my mom, for some reason, took my brother and me to ''The
400 Blows.``
</P>
<P>
   ``I had never seen a foreign film, but that film really had an
impact on me. Not at first _ I was 16 _ but I couldn't stop
thinking about it. Afterward, I realized it paralleled my life so
much. I related to that boy, because it was like looking in a
mirror.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why I became fascinated with Truffaut and other French
New Wave directors. When I got into my 20s, I rented it and studied
it and decided some day, I'm gonna make my version of `The 400
Blows.'''
</P>
<P>
   Whaley, 36, has come up a bit from the poor kid with a drunken
father (just like Joe's), always in trouble in school. We're
sitting in his room at the Toronto Four Seasons, where he is
alternating talking about ``Joe the King'' with trying to raise
money for his next movie. But Whaley is still dressed for the
streets, in black T-shirt, jeans and heavy black shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Whaley admits he could not have gotten the low-budget ``Joe the
King'' made without a little help from his friends. Ethan Hawke,
Austin Pendleton and John Leguizamo came aboard to do cameo roles
in the film. But Whaley still was way short of the needed financing
just two days before the film was to go into production.
</P>
<P>
   Kilmer, who met Whaley on ``The Doors,'' saved the day at the
last minute by agreeing to play Joe's drunken, abusive, but not
entirely uncaring father. (It's probably Kilmer's best performance
in years.)
</P>
<P>
   Kilmer was not a close pal, but he liked the script.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were close when we were doing `The Doors,' but we lost
touch,'' Whaley said. ``Somebody told me they saw him walking
around in Manhattan, so I sent my script to his hotel. I'd been
sending everybody my script.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout Truffaut's life, he returned to the character from
``The 400 Blows,'' following him into adulthood in four films.
Whaley isn't sure he wants to go that far, but his next film as
writer and director will be an adaptation of a play about a
character who could be Joe when he grows up. So who knows?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
