passionately debated and narrowly approved a measure making theirs
the first state in the country, and one of the few places in the
world, to allow physician-assisted suicide. And now, a day after
the U.S. House of Representatives passed a measure that would
effectively overturn the Oregon law and thus amounts to an
extraordinary rebuke of a single state, many people here said they
were deeply angry over federal interference in the issue. By Sam
Howe Verhovek.
