<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 16:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1451 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ART-NOTES-NYT &LR;      10-28 0974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON THE ART WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After 71 Years, an Expansion
</P>
<P>
   When it opened in 1928, the Philadelphia Museum of Art was the
largest art museum in the United States. But while museums all over
the country have expanded, Philadelphia's hasn't grown at all.
</P>
<P>
   So the the museum's purchase of a 1926 building on two acres
across the street, at 2501 Benjamin Franklin Parkway, qualifies as
a major milestone.
</P>
<P>
   The building has been home to the Reliance Standard Life
Insurance Co., a subsidiary of the Delphi Financial Group, since
1989. Reliance is seeking larger quarters in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   The building went for $17 million, of which $2 million will be
contributed by the city. (The city of Philadelphia owns the
museum's buildings and gives it some operational support, but
private money makes up most of the museum's budget.)
</P>
<P>
   The building will give the museum an additional 100,000 square
feet of space. ``Now that we've managed to acquire the new
building, we will start work on a master plan,'' said Anne
d'Harnoncourt, director of the museum. ``We don't take possession
until late spring, early summer, so we have time to think about all
our spaces.''
</P>
<P>
   The museum has hired the Vitetta Group, an architectural firm
based in Philadelphia that specializes in renovating historic
buildings. Ms. d'Harnoncourt said the building would probably house
some of the museum's administrative offices, a large library and
archives as well as public gallery space.
</P>
<P>
   That the museum chose the building across the street is fitting,
not only geographically but also architecturally. Both were
designed by the same Philadelphia firm, Zantzinger, Borie &AMP; Medary.
</P>
<P>
   But their styles are different. The Reliance building was
completed two years earlier than the museum and is considered one
of Philadelphia's finest Art Deco structures. It features gilt
panels, inlaid windows and sculpture and ornamental work by Lee
Lawrie, an artist whose work can be seen in the Library of Congress
and the National Academy of Sciences in Washington. The museum, on
the other hand, is a neo-classical temple inspired by ancient
Greece.
</P>
<P>
   The museum had a chance to acquire the building in 1981 when it
was owned by the city. But museum officials declined because they
thought the expense of another building would be a financial
strain.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time the building hadn't been renovated,'' Ms.
d'Harnoncourt said. ``Now it's been thoroughly modernized and kept
up very well.''
</P>
<P>
   A Gift for Sale
</P>
<P>
   When Betsey Cushing Roosevelt Whitney died last year, much of
the art she and her husband, John Hay Whitney, had collected was
inherited by museums. While alive (Whitney, who was called Jock,
died in 1982), the couple had extensive discussions with the
museums to determine which works each wanted.
</P>
<P>
   But one of the bequests to the Museum of Modern Art turned out
to be a surprise. In addition to works by Picasso, Matisse, van
Gogh and Cezanne, the Modern received a 1909 George Bellows
sporting scene, ``Polo Crowd.'' It was the last of the three polo
paintings the artist did and the one experts consider his best.
</P>
<P>
   How did a work by Bellows, an artist that the Modern has never
featured, end up as a gift to a museum whose collecting mission is
modern art beginning with European Post-Impressionism?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not sure,'' said Kirk Varnedoe, the Modern's chief
curator of painting and sculpture. He added that if Alfred H. Barr
Jr., the museum's founding director, had asked Whitney for the
painting his request was not in the Modern's records. Whitney was
on the Modern's board.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no sense burying it in our basement,'' Varnedoe said.
So the museum is offering the painting at Sotheby's in New York on
Dec. 1. It is estimated to fetch $10 million to $15 million.
</P>
<P>
   Dara Mitchell, director of American paintings at Sotheby's, said
she hoped the sales price would break the record for an American
painting at auction, which was set in 1996 when John Singer
Sargent's ``Cashmere'' sold for $11.1 million at Sotheby's in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   The Whitney collection included three paintings by Bellows, who
is known mainly for his early 20th-century sporting subjects; the
other two were bequeathed to the National Gallery of Art in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``Polo Crowd'' which is highly colorful, with dynamic brushwork,
depicts horses and riders in a polo match against a friezelike
arrangement of spectators. ``It's such an impressive painting we
believe it will appeal to collectors in areas other than American
paintings,'' Ms. Mitchell said.
</P>
<P>
   What the Modern will do with the money has not been decided. ``I
do have some ideas but I can't talk about them yet,'' Varnedoe
said. ``I have to wait and see how the picture will do.''
</P>
<P>
   Going Uptown
</P>
<P>
   It took the Studio Museum in Harlem less than a month to appoint
Lowery Stokes Sims its new director. Ms. Sims, a 24-year veteran of
the Metropolitan Museum of Art and its curator of 20th-century art
since 1995, is replacing Kinshasha Holman Conwill, who resigned
this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we began our search and found out that Lowry was
interested, we stopped,'' said George Knox, chairman of the
museum's board. ``We knew we couldn't do better.''
</P>
<P>
   When she begins her new job on Jan. 3, Ms. Sims plans to name
Thelma Golden chief curator. Ms. Golden was a curator at the
Whitney Museum of American Art until her resignation last year.
``She's certainly part of my dream team, and it's safe to say
she'll be coming,'' Ms. Sims said.
</P>
<P>
   Philippe de Montebello, director of the Met, said that Ms. Sims
had agreed not to sever all ties with her old home. ``She has
agreed to remain as a consultant to us in the area of outreach and
multicultural diverse audiences,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
