<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 16:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1454 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-HORROR-WOMEN-HNS &LR;      10-28 1685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HORROR-WOMEN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S A SCREAM: NEW BOOK SHOWS HOW FAR WOMEN HAVE COME IN HORROR
GENRE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Photo available on NYT database) 
 
By MELISSA FLETCHER STOELTJE 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Mild-mannered philosophy professor Cynthia A. Freeland
has always loved horror movies.
</P>
<P>
   Devours them, in fact.
</P>
<P>
   But the Aristotelian philosophy expert and former women's
studies director had never turned her scholarly lens on the dark,
gruesome world of monsters, vampires and things that chew their way
out of you in the night.
</P>
<P>
   Not, that is, until she started reading feminist critiques of
slasher movies and found them to be tortured, convoluted things
that miss the obvious when it comes to why we love horror movies,
even as they scare the devil out of us.
</P>
<P>
   And so Freeland _ quite possibly the only philosophy professor
in the world with a picture of Pinhead, the demon from
``Hellraiser,'' taped to her file cabinet _ wrote ``The Naked and
the Undead'' (Westview Press, $25), which explores how the ``allure
of evil'' underpins all fright flicks.
</P>
<P>
   One major theme of her book is the way in which women are
portrayed in horror films, and how that portrayal has changed. We
caught up with Freeland in her office at the University of Houston
and asked her to explain.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You write in your book that women and monsters are often
``paired.'' What do you mean?
</P>
<P>
   A: Very often women are sympathetic with the monster and somehow
can understand where the monster is coming from, because he's also
in an ``outsider'' position. One good example is ``The Creature
From the Black Lagoon,'' where the creature is the Gill Man from
South America. The male scientists just want to get him on a big
fish hook and take him back to the aquarium to demonstrate him as a
curiosity, but the women _ he's attracted to the women, following
them around with his goggle eyes _ are sympathetic to him, saying
things like, ``Poor guy, he's the only one of his kind; he must be
very lonely.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Has the role of women in horror changed?
</P>
<P>
   A: I do think it's changed. Women have gone from being pure
victims who just scream a lot and are the target of the advances of
the male monster, to being heroines sometimes, and sometimes even
the scientists themselves who create the monster.
</P>
<P>
   One change we haven't seen enough of, though _ and it's a little
paradoxical to say I would want this _ is more female monsters.
What you're interested in, after all, in horror are the monsters,
the vampires, the Pinhead, the Jason, the Freddy, the Leather Face.
Look at Hannibal Lecter: He's what's interesting. And maybe female
monsters would be somehow different and would teach us different
things about evil.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Maybe the idea of a female monster is too threatening? Or is
it that most directors, writers and producers are male?
</P>
<P>
   A: I think it's both, but especially the second. The monster is
creative, and the filmmaker tends to empathize with the monster _
he's the source of the creative play, after all, the visual
spectacle in the movie. When there are female monsters, they're
usually either bugs _ and the problem with bugs is they don't
usually talk _ or female vampires. There're quite a few female
vampires, and they're often pretty interesting, like Catherine
Deneuve in ``The Hunger.''
</P>
<P>
   You have a few other instances (of female monsters), like the
Borg Queen in ``Star Trek: First Contact,'' which is not quite
horror but comes close. The problem with female monsters is the
only sphere for their monster-ness is sexuality, and so there could
be some other spheres.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You write that vampires are ``gender-benders.'' Is that why
we can have female vampires?
</P>
<P>
   A: That's true. A lot of vampires are kind of like transvestites
_ Bela Lugosi was almost a woman in some ways, with all the
lipstick and eye shadow and the cape and the elegant dressing.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is there such a thing as a true feminist horror film?
</P>
<P>
   A: I think perhaps the ``Alien'' series, up until the fourth
one, anyway, and (the '50s-era) ``Them!,'' even though (Dr. Pat
Medford, a female scientist who goes up against giant killer ants)
is still kind of subordinate to her father. Another is Roman
Polanski's ``Repulsion,'' a psychological thriller with a slasher
killer in it played by a woman. It doesn't look at all feminist,
and a lot of people see (the killer, played by Deneuve) as just
sexually repressed, but I read the movie as incredibly sympathetic
to her point of view. And it shows the sort of atrocities she
experienced in her life that drove her mad. It's all centered on a
remembrance she has of childhood sexual abuse. I've watched all
these videos, and I couldn't watch this one alone. I was so
frightened and disturbed by it, I had to get a friend to watch it
with me. ... It's every woman's nightmare, in a way: When you walk
alone into your apartment, go into the bathroom and all of a sudden
there's a man's face in the mirror behind you. ...
</P>
<P>
   Q: How have monsters changed through time?
</P>
<P>
   A: The big change is that horror is so much more graphic. I
don't know that the monsters themselves are different _ Pinhead is
really just an update of the vampire. The ``Alien'' creature is so
high-tech and very realistic, done with digital imaging. On the
other hand, (Alfred) Hitchcock's ``The Birds'' seemed pretty
believable; Frankenstein's makeup was said to be so frightening it
made people run from the theater. But I don't think the real nature
of monsters has changed as much as the use of special effects. That
and the explicit gore, which has just multiply increased.
</P>
<P>
   Q: And don't all ``bad'' girls die in these explicit slasher
flicks?
</P>
<P>
   A: Actually, studies have been done on the body counts on all
those mainstream (teen slasher) series of the '80s, and contrary to
popular belief, there are more males killed than females, sometimes
far more males killed. The big difference is that the death scenes
of the girls last longer. The hypothesis is that you have a largely
teen-age male audience, and (such audience members) empathize more
with the pain and suffering of the girls, because it's like their
female side. If it was a boy up there suffering and screaming, they
would feel uncomfortable, because boys aren't supposed to scream.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You talk a lot about evil in your book and its relation to
horror movies. Please explain.
</P>
<P>
   A: Horror came about in the 1800s as a kind of secular
replacement of the formerly dominant religious framework. You
didn't really have horror back in the medieval world. You had
devils; you had hell. Then the new scientific, enlightenment era
comes in, and a lot of that gets naturalized. Where do all those
emotions go? They start to go in the direction of worrying about
the supernatural, or the undead. That, and science that you can't
predict and control, whether it's Dr. Frankenstein sewing parts
together or (Mira Sorvino) engineering giant cockroaches in
``Mimic.''
</P>
<P>
   (Horror) gives an explanatory system that enables you to
confront evil. Horror makes evil emotionally real. And it's the
only genre where evil can really win in the end. In all the other
genres _ detective, action-thriller, romance, western _ the good
guys invariably win. In horror, there's often a suggestion at the
end that we're doomed.
</P>
<P>
   Q: So horror movies give us a safe way to explore evil?
</P>
<P>
   A: It sounds banal to say you have to go to a horror movie to
see evil, when there's evil all around us _ Jasper, the Waco
conflagration, KKK rallies and so on. We can certainly see evil in
the world. Yet I think we avoid feeling the feelings about it. It's
kind of in the news, then off, and you watch something else on TV.
(Horror films) enable you to have thoughts and feelings and allow
yourself to go through the process of really thinking about what is
the attraction of evil. If I met Pinhead, would I be able to
resist? If I met Frank Langella, would I run away with him?
Probably! (She laughs.)
</P>
<P>
   Q: You also have a part in your book titled `Women and Bugs.'
What's that about?
</P>
<P>
   A: In the '50s, there was the baby boom, the move to the
suburbs, the end of Rosie the Riveter, the return of men to the
factories, this new idea of the family as the father, the mother
and two kids, and this new idea of women being in the nice suburban
home with all the nice appliances. What could threaten this
environment? In '50s movies, it was all about alien invasion. Some
people link this to the Cold War and communism _ the aliens always
come in hordes as faceless, collective monsters like ants, roaches
or termites. I don't know why this gets feminized into (female)
bugs. That might be the subject of another book.
</P>
<P>
   But the surprising thing about '50s (horror) movies is the
number of strong, independent women. They tend to be the sidekicks
of the men, but they still get to go along on the trip to capture
the creature. There must have been some kind of social phenomenon
happening _ remember, this was before Betty Friedan wrote ``The
Feminine Mystique.'' But the women were allowed to be strong and
brave because they were protecting their own young. Again, it's
maternal.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do scary movies scare you?
</P>
<P>
   A: Not anymore. I'm hardly ever bothered by them. But ``The
Sixth Sense'' really got under my skin. There was something about
that little boy and his face and what he had experienced, and the
horror of what you learn in the end.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's your all-time favorite horror movie?
</P>
<P>
   A: I've gotten increasingly fond of the movies in the '50s, and
I love the black-and-white classics, but (director David)
Cronenberg's movies are my favorites. I think ``Scanners'' is kind
of the perfect horror movie. It doesn't have a wasted moment in it;
it's very intense and gripping, with moral complexity. You have
empathy for the characters. It's got this epic dimension to it,
this battle between brothers who don't know they're brothers, who
don't know their father. It's got a Greek tragedy aspect to it. And
the exploding head is completely shocking.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
