<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JOE-MONTANA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOE MONTANA FEELS YOUNG'S PAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BRUCE ADAMS   
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Joe Montana knows exactly what Steve Young is
going through. He understands his resolve to play football again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a difficult decision because his body is telling him he's
fine,'' Montana said of his successor as the starting quarterback
of the San Francisco 49ers. ``His head about now is probably
starting to feel better too.''
</P>
<P>
   Montana incurred several concussions during his 15-year playing
career. He said he's sympathetic with Young, who announced
Wednesday that he had no immediate plans to retire from football
despite four concussions in the past 35 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're dealing with a very volatile part of the body, the
brain, and there's not a lot of history about these injuries,''
Montana said. ``It's not an easy decision either way for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday was also the day that Montana was among the 71 NFL
former players, coaches and others named to this year's Hall of
Fame ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Montana spent 13 years with the 49ers, winning four Super Bowls.
He spent his last two years with the Kansas City Chiefs and retired
in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Young, 38, took over the 49ers' starting job in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Montana, who said he has not talked with Young about his former
teammate's health problems, said he started getting headaches near
the end of his playing career as a result of his concussions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was getting headaches for a long time, migraines,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're starting to slow down. I spent at least three or four
days a year in bed. Black. I didn't want to see sunlight. I didn't
want to hear any noise. I'd put my head under the pillow.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it was the aftereffects of violent NFL injuries that
prompted Montana to give several media interviews Wednesday on
behalf of the Arthritis Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   He has osteoarthritis in his often-injured left knee. He said
he's lost track of the number of surgeries on the knee (``I think
six or seven''). He also is troubled by arthritis in his right
shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was something that was directly affecting me,'' he said.
``And you look around and see it's the No. 1 crippling disease in
the country.''
</P>
<P>
   He was diagnosed 10 years ago, while he was still playing, but
he just made it public earlier this year. He said his arthritis was
a direct result of his numerous football injuries.
</P>
<P>
   The arthritic pains were just part of the everyday life of an
NFL player.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's different because as a football player you live with a
lot more pain,'' he said. ``You never heal from one week to the
next.''
</P>
<P>
   He noted that quarterbacks are especially vulnerable to injury,
as during sacks when large defensive linemen often drive the
quarterback into the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Montana, 43, said he still stays active, working out four to six
days a week. He's given up running for low-impact aerobic work on
the treadmill and stationary bike and does light weightlifting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
