<DOCNO> NYT19991028.0293 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 16:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1458 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BROOKLYN-JOHNSON-EXHI     10-28 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROOKLYN-JOHNSON-EXHIBIT-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EASTMAN JOHNSON: CAPTURING THE MOODS OF A NATION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Seattle, San Diego, Maine, Wis., Mass.)   (bl)  
 By GRACE GLUECK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ While the court battle continues over ``Sensation,''
the show of work by young British artists at the Brooklyn Museum of
Art that has drawn fire from Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, it is nice to
know that the museum continues to go about its business of mounting
exhibitions.
</P>
<P>
   The latest, ``Eastman Johnson: Painting America,'' set in the
19th century, is a comfortable distance from controversy and a good
foil for the visual ballistics of the ``Sensation'' show. Johnson
(1824-1906) is represented here by 70 paintings and 32 drawings, a
mix of corny stereotype and original observation heavily influenced
by 17th-century Dutch genre painting.
</P>
<P>
   If he wasn't the most exciting of painters, Johnson was a solid
one, with a narrative focus on rural and domestic life; women,
children and old men, and a group of important African-American
subjects. Among his signature works are ``The Old Stage Coach,'' a
merry, multifigured scene of children at play that may have
inspired Winslow Homer, and ``The Boy Lincoln'' (1868), an
inspirational childhood portrait of Lincoln perusing a book in the
glow of firelight (only a sketch for it appears in this show).
</P>
<P>
   Although his name is now overshadowed by those of Homer and
Thomas Eakins, Johnson was for a couple of decades (1860-1880) the
leading figure painter in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, his boldest endeavor, before and during the Civil War,
was painting antislavery scenes, like his powerful canvas, ``A Ride
for Liberty _ The Fugitive Slaves'' (circa 1862). It focuses
intensely on a black man, his wife, child and baby on a single
horse, dashing toward the safety of Union lines. This and some
poignant individualized studies of black children follow the
beautifully composed but more cliched painting that first earned
him a name, ``Negro Life at the South'' (1859), later known as
``Old Kentucky Home.''
</P>
<P>
   In this populous scene, set in a seedy courtyard, a black man
strums his banjo for a casual, sympathetically portrayed black
audience as the mistress of the plantation looks in. But by 1870,
according to an interesting catalog essay by the art historian
Patricia Hills, Johnson, like other abolitionists during of
backlash of Reconstruction, lost interest in the course of black
lives and more or less dropped them as subjects.
</P>
<P>
   This show, the first Johnson retrospective in more than 25
years, was organized by Teresa Carbone, associate curator of
American art at the Brooklyn Museum, and Ms. Hills, chairwoman of
the art history department at Boston University. Billed as a
``full-scale critical re-examination'' of Johnson's work, the show
ties in handily with the growing revival of interest in figurative
painting.
</P>
<P>
   As an aspiring young artist in Maine, Johnson traveled from town
to town ``doing faces'' in crayon. In 1846 he followed his father,
a minor government official, to Washington, and quickly racked up a
roster of famous sitters, among them Dolley Madison, Mrs. Alexander
Hamilton and John Quincy Adams. Invited to Cambridge, Mass., by
Henry Wadsworth Longfellow to draw his portrait and others _ among
them Nathaniel Hawthorne and Ralph Waldo Emerson _ Johnson did his
subjects graceful justice. The lively crayon-and-chalk likenesses
that resulted are hung together in the exhibition with that of the
Massachusetts antislavery Senator Charles Sumner. All were done in
1846.
</P>
<P>
   By 1849, however, the restless crayoneer was off to Europe for a
six-year stay that would give his career a substantial boost. After
studying in Duesseldorf with the American expatriate Emanuel Leutze
(1816-1868), painter of the grandiose ``George Washington Crossing
the Delaware'' (1851), Johnson moved on to The Hague, where he
settled in for four years, steeping himself in the work of
Rembrandt and genre painters like Pieter de Hooch. By 1853
Johnson's skills at portraiture and the figure were well honed. He
returned to Washington in 1855 as an accomplished painter ready to
take on American subjects.
</P>
<P>
   A detour in 1856 to Superior, Wis., where he joined his oldest
brother in Northwest land speculation, aroused his interest in
frontier life and the Ojibwa Indians, who still frequented the Lake
Superior territory they had ceded to the U.S. government. The
best-schooled of all the midcentury Indian painters, Johnson used
his traditional European training in shading and line to make a
series of individual portraits _ a selection is included in the
show _ that, for their accuracy of facial detail and reading of the
sitters' character, rank among the memorable Indian studies of the
period.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   With his real estate investments wiped out by a financial panic
in 1857, Johnson left Ojibwa country to raise cash by means of more
conventional portraits. He never returned to his Indian subjects.
But after the success of ``Negro Life at the South,'' shown at the
annual spring exhibition of the National Academy in New York in
1859, he became one of the New York art world's brightest lights.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1859 and 1866 he sent a number of well-received
paintings on black themes to the National Academy's spring
exhibitions. The few he did on the Civil War and its aftermath
included the popular ``Pension Claim Agent'' (1867), a
heart-wringer that depicts the visit of a pension agent to the home
of an amputee veteran.
</P>
<P>
   But, always aware of his market, Johnson turned to more topical
subjects. After the draining war an exhausted country began to
savor home and hearth, an interest also fueled by Susan Warner's
earlier domestic novel, ``The Wide, Wide World'' (1850). Images of
kitchens, firesides, farms, shops and other settings of ordinary
life found wide acceptance.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, a bachelor until his mid-40s, began to produce a series
portraying domestic interiors and familial relationships that were
fed by his close acquaintance with Dutch genre painting. The works
ranged from big, upscale group portraits with a cast of thousands,
like ``The Hatch Family'' (1871), commissioned by Wall Street
broker Alfrederick Hatch, to more intimate interior scenes, like
``Not at Home'' (circa 1873), a portrait of Johnson's young wife,
Elizabeth, hurriedly leaving her light-filled parlor on a staircase
in deep shadow.
</P>
<P>
   Around 1870 Johnson discovered the old whaling port of
Nantucket, where for more than two decades he summered with his
family. He plumbed the island deeply for subject matter: old sea
captains, New England barns, farm life and simple kitchens. His
most highly praised work of the 1870s was ``Husking Bee, Island of
Nantucket'' (1876), a tableau of volunteer farm labor that showed
again his deftness in multiple figure orchestrations. The painting,
with its freer brushing and focus on composition rather than
narrative, was seen as a response to a new generation of American
realists returning from study in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1870s Johnson began to feel heel nips from Homer, a
friend and competitor 12 years his junior whose interest was also
in American genre. It is unclear who was influenced more by whom;
certainly their work at this point drew close in style and subject
matter. Johnson did his Nantucket extravaganza, ``The Old Stage
Coach,'' rife with children romping over the wheel-less carcass of
a coach, in 1871; Homer produced his equally exuberant childhood
playfest, ``Snap the Whip,'' in 1872, almost certainly cued by the
Johnson work.
</P>
<P>
   Striking silhouette-style figures of women outdoors, alone or in
groups, also frequent the work of both men in the mid-1870s.
Johnson's ``Woman on a Hill'' (1875-80), a single figure of a
fashionably dressed young thing looking out to sea from dunes,
roughly corresponds with Homer's ``Fresh Air'' (1878), a similar
figure with the addition of grazing sheep. And at first glance
Johnson's ``Hollyhocks'' (1874-76), a prettily deployed group of
women in a garden that evokes the French Impressionists, might have
been painted by Homer.
</P>
<P>
   Homer has long overtaken Johnson in the pantheon of American art
history. But this show, a worthy tribute to an artist who
successfully fused home-grown talent with European training to
convey a vision _ albeit a well-varnished one _ of real American
life, gives Johnson his due.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eastman Johnson: Painting America'' is at the Brooklyn Museum
of Art, 200 Eastern Parkway, at Prospect Park, Brooklyn, (718)
638-5000, through Feb. 6. It then travels to the San Diego Museum
of Art (Feb. 26 through May 21) and the Seattle Art Museum (June 8
through Sept. 10).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
