<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LOST FOR WORDS': A MATERNAL BOND GLOWS IN THE DYING OF THE LIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By RON WERTHEIMER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Life may not be as perfectly bittersweet as it is painted in
``Lost for Words.'' But it ought to be.
</P>
<P>
   This little gem of a drama, Sunday's ``Masterpiece Theater''
presentation, is an extraordinary dual portrait of two rather
ordinary people, an elderly woman and her middle-aged son. It
begins at a hospital, where the mother has just died, then doubles
back to recount the end of her life. That's all. It could be
anyone's story. Which is why it's so affecting.
</P>
<P>
   The script is by Deric Longden, based on his memoir. Longden
will be familiar to some viewers. This book was a follow-up to his
account of the prolonged illness and death of his first wife, who
showed her appreciation for his years of devoted attention by
selecting a suitable second wife, Aileen. She is blind and is
blessed with strength and good humor; she is never less than
stalwart during the crisis at hand.
</P>
<P>
   The film's Deric and his slightly dotty Mum, Annie, are probably
a bit more charming than the real-life Longdens. Real or not, they
live vividly in the understated performances of Pete Postlethwaite
and Dame Thora Hird, 83, a British national treasure. Under the
direction of Alan J.W. Bell, they touch your heart without ever
trying to bonk you on the head.
</P>
<P>
   Dame Thora's assignment is by far the tougher. She must hold the
film together by proceeding from spry self-confidence to frightened
frailty without ever breaking the spell. Or breaking a sweat. Her
performance is so seamless that you never notice her consummate
skill until the final credits are rolling. Then you remember the
little touches _ the way she eats an ice cream cone, for instance _
and marvel at them.
</P>
<P>
   When you first encounter Annie, she is preparing to sell her
house and move to a smaller one around the corner. The real-estate
agent has told her to show the house by appointment only. So she
makes appointments with all the prospective buyers at the same
time, turning the event into a jolly tea party at which she keeps
pointing out all the house's defects, most of them results of her
late husband's shoddy handiwork. Despite her unorthodox sales
pitch, or because of it, the house sells immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless Deric is worried about his mother. He begins
spending more time with her, observing her funny little habits,
like her fondness for the tonic she buys several bottles at a time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I only have a teaspoonful,'' she tells her worried son with a
twinkle.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many?'' he demands, bemused, not angry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just one at a time.''
</P>
<P>
   Their conversations reveal an enduring bond, forged in the
shadow of Deric's overbearing father. ``I've been so happy since he
died,'' Annie confesses to her son. ``It's taken me a long time to
be able to say that.''
</P>
<P>
   Later Deric tells Annie's doctor: ``She never let me down, you
know. Taught me to believe in myself all the time that my dad was
chipping away at my self-confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Now he can't let her down, as a series of strokes begin to rob
her independence and eventually her ability to speak coherently.
(Hence the title.)
</P>
<P>
   When the neighborhood pharmacist asks Deric to send his regards
to Annie and adds, ``She's a lovely woman,'' Postlethwaite pauses
to ponder this offhand remark. His reply is simple: ``Yeah. She is,
isn't she?'' But the actor's careworn face delivers a wordless
soliloquy.
</P>
<P>
   Aileen, played by Penny Downie, is rendered too upbeat to be
true. And the incidental characters are all cardboard cutouts. But
these shortcomings are on the margins. At the center, the film
looks squarely at the final indignities sprung by this mortal coil
and laughs at them ruefully.
</P>
<P>
   You'll laugh, too. Then you'll be moved; not by death, but by
life. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MASTERPIECE THEATER &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lost for Words  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PBS, Sunday night &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Channel 13, New York, at 9)  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Written by Deric Longden and based on his book by the same
title. Alan J.W. Bell, director; Sita Williams, producer; Keith
Richardson and Margaret Matheson, executive producers. A Yorkshire
Television Production presented on PBS by WGBH/Boston. Rebecca
Eaton, series executive producer; Russell Baker, series host. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Dame Thora Hird (Mother), Pete Postlethwaite (Deric),
Penny Downie (Aileen), Jennifer Luckraft (Nurse One), David
Shimwell (Young Man), Anne Reid (Gloria), Keith Clifford (Fred),
Eddie Caswell (Widower), Tom Higgins (Doctor), Diana Flacks (Mrs.
Corey) and Malcolm Hebden (Pharmacist). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
