<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALBUM-OF-THE-WEEK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPOTLIGHT ON A NEW ALBUM 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ANN POWERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE TIGER LILLIES: ``Shockheaded Peter: A Junk Opera'' (NVC
Arts/Atlantic). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Parents flustered by the horrors of the video arcade should
examine the classics of kiddie literature. Children's tales have
long incarnated the dark corners of the littlest psyches, from
Grimm's dark forest to Roald Dahl's rotting giant peach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shockheaded Peter,'' the English ``junk opera'' at the New
Victory Theater in Manhattan, is a delicious reminder of kiddie
culture's gory heart. It respectfully, and therefore audaciously,
reworks ``Struwwelpeter,'' a parody of children's cautionary tales,
by the Victorian psychiatrist Heinrich Hoffmann.
</P>
<P>
   In those verses, mischievous children meet outrageously cruel
fates. The id-stimulating mayhem reminds us that moral rectitude
can be a vengeful, life-squashing force.
</P>
<P>
   The lurid circus sideshow atmosphere of ``Shockheaded Peter'' is
effectively mirrored in its music, written and performed by the
Tiger Lillies. That trio of accordion, stand-up bass and portable
drum kit is led by Martin Jacques, a born carny with a
hermaphroditic castrato voice and a penchant for lurching rhythms
and creaky melodies.
</P>
<P>
   Songs like ``Snip Snip (Suck a Thumb)'' and ``Fidgety Phil''
hardly seem contemporary, except in their atmospherically rich
production and their obvious debt to Tom Waits.
</P>
<P>
   Jacques' piping voice can be hard to decipher in person, and
this recording makes it possible to catch every creepy detail of
his songs. It well captures the show's naughty mood. It also stands
as a resurrected classic for children, and grown-ups, with open
minds and stout stomachs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
