<HEADLINE>
CANADIAN COMPANY ACQUIRES SPORTS MANAGEMENT FIRM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DWIGHT CHAPIN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Before long, Steve Young, Troy Aikman, Drew
Bledsoe and Warren Moon may become almost as recognizable in
American pop culture as Mickey Mouse, Elvis Presley and James Dean.
</P>
<P>
   That's one of the possible upshots of a multimillion-dollar deal
announced Wednesday in which the company headed by powerful
California sports agent Leigh Steinberg was acquired by Assante
Corp. of Canada, a financial planning firm that administers $22.3
billion in assets for high-profile and affluent clients.
</P>
<P>
   Assante reportedly paid $120 million in cash and convertible
stock to acquire Steinberg, Moorad &AMP; Dunn, which has offices in
Berkeley and Newport Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world of sports and business is changing dramatically,''
said Steinberg, who will become chief executive officer of Assante
Sports Management Group. ``Sports now have become content and
product for multiple platforms of entertainment delivery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yo150 TV stations on 24 hours a day. There are video
games, the Internet, videotapes, all of which demand a lot of
content. We plan to move into the TV production business, using our
athletes in all sorts of TV shows, Internet programming and a
variety of other media and marketing uses. There are any number of
applications for athletes besides what they do on the playing
fields.''
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition of Steinberg's company continues a trend of
consolidation in the business, with the focus on marketing of the
athletes. SFX Entertainment Inc. earlier bought out high-powered
agents Arn Tellem and David Falk.
</P>
<P>
   The deal with Assante, Steinberg said, has the backing of the
stable he and partners Jeffrey Moorad and David Dunn manage _ a
150-member list that includes football stars like Aikman, Bledsoe,
Moon, Young and Jake Plummer; baseball players such as Ivan
Rodriguez and Matt Williams; and basketball player John Starks.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to give them some exciting bridges to the
entertainment community,'' said Steinberg, who already has made the
leap himself as a technical consultant on several Hollywood movies.
``I've talked with Warren, Drew, Steve and Troy, and they're
excited about this opening new doors for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Steinberg said several things were in the works as the
traditional contract negotiations he's handled for his clients were
combined with marketing and financial-service opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to buy 10 or 11 more sports agencies in football,
basketball, hockey, soccer, wrestling and boxing, and in the next
phase we'll go into motor sports, skating, tennis and golf,'' he
said. ``Over the next six months, we'll be rolling out these
companies through a series of announcements.''
</P>
<P>
   Marty Weinberg, chairman and chief executive of Assante, which
is moving into the sports field for the first time, said, ``We're
very excited about this new partnership. I think this firmly
establishes us with the finest people in the sports management
business. We started looking into this marketplace more than two
years ago, and we selected Leigh's firm because nothing was even
close to it. Every arrow we saw directed us toward Steinberg and
Moorad.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-99 1710EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
