<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAMAGES-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PUNITIVE DAMAGE': IF THE KILLING IS OVER WITH, IT'S TOO LATE FOR
ONE STUDENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   East Timor won its independence from Indonesia a couple of
months ago. You probably heard. President Suharto had already been
gone for more than a year. Indonesia's new president has now
appointed a ``national unity Cabinet,'' and the security council
has just created a United Nations mission to govern East Timor for
now. The killing and the destruction that began when Indonesia
annexed East Timor in 1975 may finally be over.
</P>
<P>
   The timing couldn't be better _ or worse _ for ``Punitive
Damage,'' Annie Goldson's worthy documentary about a Malaysian
college student who died in East Timor for his cause.
</P>
<P>
   You see a lot of Helen Todd in ``Punitive Damage.'' A New
Zealander who has lived in Malaysia since the 1960s, Ms. Todd is
the mother of the film's subject, Kamal Bamadhaj. ``My worst
nightmare,'' she says early in the film, remembering his departure
for that final trip, ``was that he would end up in jail.'' He was
``the most cool and calm'' and logical young man, she recalls, and
she believed he could handle anything he encountered.
</P>
<P>
   Kamal (everyone in the film seems to call him, affectionately,
by his first name) was 20 and a student at New South Wales
University in Australia when he went to East Timor in 1991. It was
his second visit, and he was there on a political errand.
</P>
<P>
   He became one of the 270 unarmed demonstrators killed by the
Indonesian military that day in a massacre in Dili, East Timor's
capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``Punitive Damage,'' which opens Friday in New York City , is
the story of Kamal's political activism and Ms. Todd's unusual
search for justice. In 1994 she traveled to the United States
(world capital of litigation) and sued the Indonesian general who
had authorized the massacre for the wrongful death of her son.
</P>
<P>
   The story is illustrated by old photographs of Kamal, film of
the actual massacre, re-creations of courtroom testimony and a
variety of talking heads. The most effective interview subject is
Allan Nairn, a journalist who has long covered East Timor and
witnessed the Dili massacre.
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, some of the other subjects and the recreations are quite
stiff. But Ms. Todd has a particularly gripping scene, one in
which, having talked to many people who saw Kamal the day he died,
she reconstructs and recounts the events of her son's last hours.
</P>
<P>
   His youthful political fervor now stands for that of all those
who died alongside him, and Ms. Goldson has given him a respectful,
meaningful memorial.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `PUNITIVE DAMAGE'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Annie Goldson; director of photography, Leon Narbey;
edited by John Gilbert; music by Stephen Taberner; produced by Ms.
Goldson and Gaylene Preston; released by First Run/Icarus Films.
Running time: 77 minutes. This film is not rated.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Helen Todd, Michael Ratner and Beth Stephens and
Constancio Pinto.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-99 1720EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991028.0299 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 17:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1474 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      10-28 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HALLOWEEN SPOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The nation's capital can be a spooky place, but
this is the time of the year when it's not only okay but expected.
</P>
<P>
   That unique blend of costumed hi-jinks, make-believe and free
candy called Halloween is just around the corner. It's a rare
opportunity for children and adults to act silly without fear of
being sent to an asylum.
</P>
<P>
   But this is America, land of free speech and freer opinions.
Nothing is simple here, not even an excuse to party.
</P>
<P>
   Halloween brings its own brand of politics, featuring what has
become a routine argument between those who think the holiday is
just for jollies and those who read dark, ominous meanings into it.
</P>
<P>
   And there is always a cultural war between Halloween-friendly
souls who love to hand out stuff to kids and grumpy sorts who
regard the occasion as a candy ripoff by masked midgets from
unknown neighborhoods far away. Plus, there's the gulf between
modernists who will go for the new blue pumpkin and traditionalists
who think jack-o-lanterns only come in orange.
</P>
<P>
   Smart retailers discovered Halloween long ago and turned it into
a huge commercial venture, second only to Christmas in
revenue-raising. The National Retail Federation says all those
pint-sized ghosts and goblins going door to door begging for
handouts and the hordes of masked adults out for a good time
produced $2.5 billion in related sales last year.
</P>
<P>
   Since costumes can cost $50 a pop (without the mask), it's no
wonder. And costumes matter.
</P>
<P>
   My middle granddaughter, who graduated over the years from a
pumpkin to a princess to a leopard to Darth Vader, is this year
going as a roll of Lifesavers in a colorful tube she bought with
her own allowance. She's no longer happy in a simple outfit sewed
by her mother. She looks much cuter, I'm told, than she did as
Darth Vader.
</P>
<P>
   But some fundamentalist religious groups don't see the fun in
it. They take the whole thing very seriously, warning against
satanic practices based on pagan rituals bound to corrupt our
youngsters. They try to counter the Halloween tradition of trick
and treat with sermons and substitute events that extol the virtues
of clean living.
</P>
<P>
   In some places, schools and churches will hold supervised
children's parties forbidding costumes that are scary or that might
be politically incorrect. On both counts that means, presumably,
pirates with guns are out, and so are Al Gore, Hillary Clinton or
George W. Bush masks.
</P>
<P>
   These sanitized events are often called ``autumn festivals'' and
feature happy drawings, pumpkins and nutritional nibbles rather
than the traditional ghoulish music, sweets and grapes passed
around in the dark as eyeballs. Costume parades are the big
attraction, usually with parents and cameras in attendance.
</P>
<P>
   In other places, there will be Christian band concerts, morality
plays (script copies available for $150) and sermons against movies
and television programs that glorify witchcraft or at least make it
sound benign.
</P>
<P>
   It is a shame that Halloween is being dragged into modern
religious politics, although it doesn't hurt if the costumes become
more imaginative and the emphasis more on good cheer than imagined
scares. But to the extent that the holiday is used as a vehicle to
lecture about morality, abortion and other favorite conservative
causes, the spirit will go out of it.
</P>
<P>
   The event has its roots in a festival of the dead that
originated roughly 1,500 years ago, before reading and writing and
civilized thought. Druids and Celts danced and practiced horrible,
bloody rites that honored Satan in hopes of warding off further
evil.
</P>
<P>
   But for something like 50 generations Druids and Celts have not
been either revered or feared as functioning religious
institutions. This craziness did not happen yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Ancient nonsense plays no threatening role in modern life. Over
the centuries, Halloween lost its overt religious message and
became a secular celebration, uncomplicated by the serious
overtones of Christmas, Hanukkah and Easter.
</P>
<P>
   And that has been its endearing charm. This is strictly for fun.
A chance to dress up and parade around is a hoot for all ages.
There's no harm in it, and everybody gets a big kick afterward out
of looking at the photographs of how silly our friends appear. It's
truly a great ``remember when.''
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached by e-mail at means(at)hearstdc.
com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
