<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    REPEAL URGED IN USE OF SECRET EVIDENCE AGAINST NON-CITIZENS
 &HT;    BY SUE SCHULTZ
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Washington _ Federal lawmakers and Arab organizations Thursday
urged Congress to repeal a law allowing the use of secret evidence
in the arrest and detention of non-citizens within the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   House Minority Whip David Bonior, D-Mich., and Rep. Tom
Campbell, R-Calif., joined Hany Kiareldeen, (CQ) a Palestinian
immigrant, at a news conference to protest the use of secret
evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Kiareldeen was arrested in March 1998 and detained for 19 months
by the Immigration and Naturalization Service because he was
suspected of having ties to a terrorist group. During that time,
his lawyers were not permitted to review the charges or to evaluate
the evidence of his case.
</P>
<P>
   A 1996 anti-terrorism law allows the INS to detain immigrants
suspected of being a threat to national security without revealing
any of the evidence or charges against them.
</P>
<P>
   Kiareldeen was released last week after a federal judge declared
his incarceration unconstitutional and a violation of his rights to
due process and fair treatment under the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ruling in this case will be a limited victory if we in
Congress fail to repeal the law that makes the use of secret
evidence legal in the first place,'' Bonior said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the court ruling, Bonior said, the INS is detaining 20
immigrants on the basis of secret evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost all of the two dozen detainees are Muslim and Arab,''
said Aly Abuzaakouk, executive director of the American Muslim
Council. ``Their detention on the basis of secret evidence leads
many to question whether it is national security, or politically
motivated bias, that is at issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonior and Campbell introduced a bill, co-sponsored by 50 other
members, that would eliminate the use of secret evidence and would
extend the constitutional rights of due process and fair treatment
to non-citizens within the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The immigration service defends the use of classified evidence,
but has not taken a position on the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``The elimination of the use of classified evidence could result
in a significant risk to national security,'' said Russ Bergeron,
INS' director of media relations.
</P>
<P>
   Bergeron added that the Supreme Court has previously ruled that
the INS may use classified evidence in certain cases where there is
a danger to national security. The INS will continue the practice
until legislation or a Supreme Court ruling changes it, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Lamar Smith, R-Texas, chairman of the Judiciary
subcommittee on immigration and claims, said he will hold a hearing
on the bill in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
