<HEADER>
A1476 &Cx1f; ttg-z
u k BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-N     10-28 0652
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COSTUME IDEAS FOR THE MILLENNIUM
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you're still unsure what you're going to wear to that
Halloween party, you might consider going as a Millennium Bug.
</P>
<P>
   There are several reasons why this would be a great costume:
</P>
<P>
   1) It's topical.
</P>
<P>
   2) It's scary.
</P>
<P>
   3) You don't have to actually make a costume.
</P>
<P>
   The Millennium Bug is superior to other Halloween costumes like,
say, Austin Powers or Jar Jar Binks, because no one has ever seen a
Millennium Bug, therefore there is no pressure to make your costume
``authentic.'' If I say the Millennium Bug looks like an
avocado-shaped humor columnist wearing a stained golf shirt and
pants that should have been made into dust rags five years ago,
then, by golly, that's what the Millennium Bug looks like.
</P>
<P>
   (I should probably warn parents that this ``look'' might be too
frightening for young children. You might want to ``soften'' it a
bit by placing a grocery bag over your head or, better yet, a
body-length sheet.)
</P>
<P>
   Most people, I suspect, will go with some sort of insect-related
theme when making their Millennium Bug costume which, of course,
plays right into the hands (mandibles?) of those of us who live in
Florida. Insects are a fact of life in Florida, much like tourists,
but after you've lived here a while, you lose your natural
revulsion. Toward insects, I mean.
</P>
<P>
   It is entirely possible that the Millennium Bug is related to
our state bird, the Palmetto Bug, which looks to the untrained eye
like a cockroach on steroids. Since ``millennium'' means
``thousand,'' Millennium Bug could just be a shorthand way of
saying ``1,000 cockroaches'' as in, ``It's a good idea to wear
shoes if you go into the kitchen late at night. We've got a
Millennium Bug'' or ``We find if our Millennium Bug flaps its wings
at the same time, we don't need air conditioning.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the Millennium Bug could just as easily resemble some
other kind of insect. A killer bee is one possibility, or maybe a
fire ant. (I have never seen just one fire ant; the smallest
denomination seems to be a millennium, though 10 times 10
millenniums of fire ants is not an uncommon sight, particularly if
you are foolhardy enough to walk across your yard barefoot.)
</P>
<P>
   Or you could decide that the Millennium Bug is not an insect at
all, but rather a bacterium. (Like fire ants, bacteria seldom if
ever operate alone, but for the purposes of a Halloween costume you
might be able to get away with it.) I don't know what a bacterium
looks like, though I'm imagining a sort of avocado-shaped blob
minus the stained golf shirt and frayed pants. You might want to
check with the Halloween party's host or hostess beforehand to make
sure the nude-infectious-tropical-fruit look doesn't ``clash'' with
what the other guests are wearing.
</P>
<P>
   If you are the literal sort, you might conclude that the
Millennium Bug is not a living creature of any kind, but simply a
particularly unfortunate computer-programming oversight. I'm not
sure how you would illustrate this in the context of a Halloween
costume. Maybe come as Bill Gates banging his fist on a fried
automatic teller machine, though I'm betting that more people would
be able to guess what you are if you come as a fashion-challenged
bacterium.
</P>
<P>
   The only bad thing about the Millennium Bug costume is that it's
only good for this year (we hope). Next year, you'll be back to
making the same dreary choice between Tinky-Winky and Stone Cold
Steve Austin. (Though a mix-and-match might be interesting.)
</P>
<P>
   Unless, of course, you decided that the Millennium Bug is really
nothing more than a whole lot of Palmetto Bugs. Because
cockroaches, like tourists, never go out of style.
</P>
<P>
   (The Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
