<SLUG> BC-TV-SEASON-ASSESS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FALL FALLOUT: `AMY,' `WWF' AMONG EARLY HITS _
`ACTION,'  `WASTELAND' TOP LOSERS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a scarcely noticed television oddity last Thursday, little
UPN was the third-rated network in prime time.
</P>
<P>
   Being third-rated isn't usually a cause for celebration. Look at
the words _ third rate. But UPN is the sixth network. So ... (set
ital)yippee!(end ital)
</P>
<P>
   The show that did the trick was ``WWF Smackdown!'' It's not
exactly ``Playhouse 90,'' but UPN will take progress where it can
find it. So in its first season, ``WWF Smackdown!'' is a big hit by
UPN standards. It's boffo. It's a monster. It's just plain buff.
</P>
<P>
   For that two-hour wrestling spectacle to succeed, something else
had to fail, woefully. The chief victims in this case were two
other new shows, ABC's abysmally low-rated ``Wasteland'' and Fox's
``Action.''
</P>
<P>
   Though baseball has been a wrench in the ratings gears, the
1999-2000 TV season is finally forming enough of a pattern to sort
out winners and losers.
</P>
<P>
   It pains me to say it, but the winners emphatically include
``WWF Smackdown!'' and ``Judging Amy,'' and the losers apparently
include ``Action.''
</P>
<P>
   CBS' ``Judging Amy'' is, excuse the language, a chick show. It
isn't quick or strident or action-packed. It seems to be tapping
the same spongy audience that coalesced around NBC's
``Providence.'' It's way too much like ``Providence,'' to tell the
truth. Frizzy-haired, female professional, about 30, sheds
spouse/lover, leaves big city and returns to her roots in her
smaller-city hometown.
</P>
<P>
   The Nielsen numbers speak plainly. ``Judging Amy'' isn't a top
show among young men, but it is among girls and women in the key
18-to-49 demographic. That's all a show needs to win a place at the
table.
</P>
<P>
   CBS has extended full-season pickups to all its new dramas.
Besides ``Judging Amy,'' that means ``Family Law,'' perking along
nicely on Mondays, and ``Now and Again,'' delivering full-blooded
demographics on Fridays.
</P>
<P>
   As for the acerbic comedy ``Action,'' it hasn't exactly enjoyed
kid-glove handling. It's marooned on Thursday nights, it bounced on
and off the schedule because of postseason baseball, and it will be
consigned to inaction during the November sweeps.
</P>
<P>
   But there's no denying that after all the August buzz and
near-unanimous critical raves in September, ``Action'' tanked in
its series premiere. That set a fearful course, and the show hasn't
recovered.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's the time slot, maybe it's the absence of an admirable
central character, maybe it's the showbiz insider humor, maybe it's
the bleeped expletives, or maybe it's just the usual lack of
audience enthusiasm for satire. Whatever it is, it's powerful. The
American public is sitting with its arms folded and its teeth
clenched; it won't watch ``Action.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox is struggling generally this fall, aside from ``Action.''
``Get Real'' is going nowhere. Neither is the half-hour rerun
version of ``Ally.'' ``Manchester Prep'' was aborted before it even
aired. This week, ``Ryan Caulfield: Year One'' and Chris Carter's
``Harsh Realm'' were axed.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's performance is a blow to Doug Herzog, the erstwhile
``Comedy Central'' guru who was brought to Fox to restore the
network's reputation for edgy, youthful programming. Instead Fox
has tumbled off the edge of the ledge.
</P>
<P>
   ABC is having a down year too, though it hasn't cashiered
anything yet. ``Snoops'' was given a full-season order at its
inception, but it isn't exactly setting Sunday night ablaze.
``Wasteland'' is vast, and not in a good way. ``Oh Grow Up'' and
``Odd Man Out'' are yawns. ``Then Came You'' is out of commission
until midseason, and then came (set ital)peee-uw(end ital) _ the
unfortunate time-slot flap over ``NYPD Blue'' and ``Once and
Again.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Once and Again'' has dropped behind ``Judging Amy'' in the
household ratings and will move to Mondays later in the season. It
also seems to have stalled creatively. But its female demographics
are still strong, and it has to be scored as a qualified success.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jack &AMP; Jill'' and ``Popular'' appear to be on the bubble at
the WB, which is having a so-so year. The animated ``Mission Hill''
hasn't been canceled yet, but it's by far the WB's lowest-rated
show. ``Roswell'' and ``Angel'' have won full-season pickups, with
decent numbers.
</P>
<P>
   UPN is positively giddy about its wrestling-inspired 2.7 rating
average for the young season, which translates into an average
audience just shy of 3 million households. The reason is that UPN
averaged a 2 rating last season. The jump to 2.7 looks spectacular
on graph charts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Parkers'' and ``Grown Ups'' are on order for the whole
season at UPN, along with ``WWF Smackdown!'' There's no call yet on
``The Strip,'' and ``Shasta McNasty'' is experiencing rocky
ratings.
</P>
<P>
   The season race is between NBC and last season's household
ratings champ, CBS. NBC, the leader this fall, has cause for
optimism even though it was the first network to cancel a series _
``The Mike O'Malley Show.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Third Watch,'' ``The West Wing,'' ``Law &AMP; Order: SVU'' and
even ``Stark Raving Mad'' are alive with full-season orders. ``Cold
Feet'' is a candidate for cancellation, and the critically praised
``Freaks &AMP; Geeks'' isn't having an impact. All in all, though, it
has been
</P>
<P>
   a comeback year for the bully Peacock.
</P>
<P>
   CBS has its three dramas to cheer about, but it's dicey after
that. ``Work With Me'' has been canceled, with ratings identical to
``Ally McBeal'' reruns on Fox. ``Love &AMP; Money'' is on the bubble.
So is ``Ladies Man,'' which is failing to hold its ``King of
Queens'' lead-in on Mondays. In fact, the progression from ``King
of Queens'' to ``Ladies Man'' to ``Everybody Loves Raymond'' looks
too much like the letter ``V.''
</P>
<P>
   Lessons? For one thing, dramas are obviously in vogue in a
medium where comedy is usually king. The sitcom genre is ailing,
and no one has cured it yet.
</P>
<P>
   It's interesting that the two networks with the sexiest, edgiest
new shows, Fox and ABC, are foundering. The theory was that you had
to give viewers the electric buzzer treatment to get their
attention. Could be that the theory is wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Also, there's no mistaking the fact that in a season that seemed
tailored for viewers in their teens and 20s, it's the shows with
older stars that are demonstrating traction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Judging Amy,'' ``Family Law,'' ``The West Wing'' and ``Once
and Again'' emphasize character and life experience over
callowness. They're the shows that are sticking to the wall, while
a ``Wasteland'' slides to the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Or perhaps there were just too many young-skewing shows crowding
the fall schedule, leaving a clearer path for a ``Family Law.''
</P>
<P>
   If you know the answer to this and other mysteries of the
enigmatic tube, you too could be programming your very own
television network. And looking forward to being fired the first
time you guess wrong.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
