<P>
   WORLD SERIES FOLLOW-UP
</P>
<P>
   BBN-BRAVES _ Follow-up on Braves World Series loss. (Rogers,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 18.
</P>
<P>
   BBO-ATLFANS _ ATLANTA _ Despite repeated disappointments in the
World Series, Atlanta fans have had a remarkable run in the past 10
years _ not only of good baseball, but a Super Bowl football team,
the Olympics, NBA playoffs and, soon, a Super Bowl and an All-Star
Game to host, not to mention the return of the NHL. (Kempner,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BBO-YANKEES _ NEW YORK _ Yankees celebrate third world title in
four years. (Stinson, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 18.
</P>
<P>
   GOLF
</P>
<P>
   GLF-TOURLEDE _ HOUSTON _ After an early-morning service honoring
Payne Stewart on the first tee, golfers at the Tour Championship
deal with their emotions and play the first round. (Sheeley,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 13.
</P>
<P>
   FOOTBALL/COLLEGES
</P>
<P>
   FBC-QUINCYCARTER _ ATHENS, Ga. _ Georgia quarterback Quincy
Carter, whose season has not been as outstanding as expected, goes
into his biggest game of the year off his best performance. But
Carter is not saying how he is feeling and what he is thinking - he
asked coach Jim Donnan to be excused from media responsibilities
this week so he can concentrate on the game. Last year was the
22-year-old sophomore's first game against the Gators, and Georgia
lost 38-7. Donnan and Carter's teammates talk about how they see
the QB's state of mind. (Towers, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 14.
</P>
<P>
   FBC-GATORS _ GAINESVILLE, Fla. _ This week's game with Georgia
means a lot to Florida. If the Gators win, they basically are in
the SEC championship game. (Their remaining games are against South
Carolina and Vanderbilt.) They were in the same position in 1997,
and Georgia beat them. That's what the Gators are thinking about
this week. (Barnhart, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 20.
</P>
<P>
   FOOTBALL/PROS
</P>
<P>
   FBN-MANNING _ Interview with Indianapolis Colts quarterback
Peyton Manning. Colts play host to the Dallas Cowboys Sunday.
(Cantu, Austin American-Statesman). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-SALAAM _ ATLANTA _ Ephraim Salaam was the toast of the
Falcons offense last season during the team's run to the Super
Bowl. He played great as a rookie tackle. But the sophomore jinx
has hit hard. Salaam has been a revolving door this season, best
evidenced by the bruises on QB Chris Chandler. (Winkeljohn, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 20.
</P>
<P>
   RACING
</P>
