<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-99 1730EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991028.0308 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 17:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1485 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-NY-MEATPACKING-DISTRI     10-28 1172
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MEATPACKING-DISTRICT-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: 10th Avenue.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It could take a week to experience the two dozen bars and
restaurants here, not to mention the spacious new shopping
emporiums like Jeffrey New York, where Pellegrino evening bags
barely big enough for a pork chop go for $395. I opted instead for
a party platter, trying some of the old and some of the new, or as
much as my appetite would allow in one weekend.
</P>
<P>
   And like my limited wardrobe, coordinating it all would prove to
be the biggest challenge.
</P>
<P>
   I chose two compatriots for the first night of the tour: Gabe,
my younger brother, and Anthony, a freelance journalist. The first
stop was to be Fressen, a handsome new lounge and restaurant on
West 13th Street. But the locals had schemes of their own.
</P>
<P>
   Turning onto West 13th, we stumbled into an elaborate display of
used goods arrayed on a deflated cardboard box; the inventory
included a copy of ``Death of a Salesman,'' a bottle of VO-5
shampoo and an empty Beaujolais bottle. But this wasn't an ordinary
street sale. There were appetizers. Chips, nuts, bagels, three
bananas, a miniature can of Bumblebee tuna, all laid out by a
gentleman who apparently lives under a makeshift tent behind the
display.
</P>
<P>
   ``I give back,'' the tent man said, declining to give his name.
Just then, a well-dressed man and two female companions walked by
and tossed a dollar in the tent man's direction.
</P>
<P>
   He thanked them and turned to us. ``Eat up,'' he said. We
continued on.
</P>
<P>
   West 13th Street is the home to two of the neighborhood's older
establishments: the Lure, a leather bar for gay men, and Hog and
Heifers, a denim bar for straight ones.
</P>
<P>
   In between is Fressen, which opened in June and whose clientele
runs from the nicely groomed to the well maintained. The food has
received mixed reviews, but the bar had a strong buzz all summer.
</P>
<P>
   Thus it was of little surprise when we received an earnest
warning from the model-cum-doorman that it would be a 20-minute
wait . . . for a drink.
</P>
<P>
   The bar was crowded, to be sure, but we were served quickly and
efficiently. The bartender apologized as he handed over three
generous drinks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sorry about the wait,'' he said, adding with a tone that
suggested alien invasion: ``We're starting to get a nightclub
crowd.''
</P>
<P>
   Eeek.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd was late 20s and early 30s: laid back, attractive and
chatty. Between the austere decor (branches, not flowers) and the
minimalist lighting, it's a nice place to begin an evening or end
one. So we drank up and left.
</P>
<P>
   From civil pleasures to, well, something completely different.
</P>
<P>
   Hogs and Heifers represents itself as a genuine
country-and-western bar, and so it seems from the outside, where
the husky bikers and the proud-to-be-American crew hang out. On
this particular Friday night, however, the crowd inside consisted
of an unwieldy number of young men in jeans and button-down shirts,
all guzzling Budweiser and looking for some good old-fashioned
country boy experience.
</P>
<P>
   Hogs and Heifers was made famous when young women (heavily
encouraged young women) took to shedding their brassieres as they
danced on the bar. And indeed there are several thousand bras
hanging batlike behind the bar.
</P>
<P>
   After the aggressive bar mistress demanded that my brother buy a
trio of bourbon shots with Budweiser chasers, we settled near the
jukebox. The music was deafening, but I caught a few plaintive
lyrics about damaged love and bad pickup trucks. (Or was it the
other way around?)
</P>
<P>
   Soon thereafter, true to form, eight (count 'em, eight) young
women jumped on the bar and began to boogie to ``Sharp Dressed
Man,'' by Z.Z. Top. The crowd whooped a little, the ladies danced,
and nervous boyfriends looked on.
</P>
<P>
   The bar mistress was not pleased. ``If you can't drink and
appreciate the ladies,'' she shouted into a mike, ``there's a gay
bar around the corner.'' (And miss this riveting entertainment?)
</P>
<P>
   The insults seemed to work. Men pushed to the bar to buy drinks,
while above, the clomping reached a fevered pitch, capped when the
dancer chosen as the belle of the bar got a hefty tequila shot
poured down her throat by the now-appeased bar mistress.
</P>
<P>
   There was much rejoicing.
</P>
<P>
   The next stop was Oriont, the Asian fusion restaurant and bar on
West 14th Street whose ``soft opening'' last month was a must for
the city's swank set. The reason? The restaurant's designer is
Christopher Ciccone, Madonna's brother, famous for his furniture
design and for being Madonna's brother.
</P>
<P>
   Ciccone has done admirable work. The two-story establishment,
which sports no sign but has a friendly doorman, has the feel of an
upscale opium den, with elaborately filigreed Chinese screens
separating the rooms and a dark, simple decor. A sushi bar at the
front gives way to a long, classy bar and a room full of small
tables, topped by candles and straight-backed chairs.
</P>
<P>
   Vintage photographs of 1930s geishas hang on the walls, and a
wide range of world music, blues, reggae and salsa plays on the
sound system. By the time we left, around 1:30 a.m., the chairs
were pushed against the wall, the diners were dancing, and a bongo
player accompanied the prerecorded beats.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd, the most beautiful and ethnically diverse of any we
had seen thus far, seemed impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know who designed this place?'' said a woman at the bar,
conspiratorially. ``Madonna's brother.''
</P>
<P>
   We dipped into two music spots on the south side of the street.
Baktun is a self-described ``multimedia lounge'' featuring ``live
instrumental and electronic music, visual projection installations,
DJs, wordsmiths, live video mixes and ISDN broadcasts.'' Oh yes,
and beer and wine and stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Next door is the Cooler, a well-respected music club, a cool,
converted basement meat locker known for its devotion to live
music, whether it be reggae or rock. The night we went, the Boston
garage band the Lyres ripped into a late-night hourlong set for a
large appreciative crowd, while a few quiet slackers sipped beers
in the back-room bar.
</P>
<P>
   The last stop of the night was the Village Idiot, perhaps the
world's most aptly named bar and a chief cause of hangovers for
college students citywide. We stumbled in at 3 a.m. and immediately
met the owner, Tom McNeil.
</P>
<P>
   He was hard to miss. McNeil, a Santa Claus-size man, was
standing against the bar. Well, leaning against the bar. OK, fallen
against the bar. He was naked from the waist up, hairy from the
shoulders down, and the view from behind was just that. He said he
had just finished a drinking contest.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy,'' he said, turning to a young man at the bar,
``thought he could beat me at a pint of Guinness.''
</P>
<P>
   Fool.
</P>
<P>
   McNeil scooped his fallen opponent, my younger brother and
myself into an embrace and began gently butting heads with each of
us. ``Who's the oldest?'' he said. ``You're buying the drinks.'' I
broke away to purchase, leaving my brother in the belly of the
beast (almost literally).
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
