<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 17:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1488 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-NY-MEATPACKING-DISTRI     10-28 1701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MEATPACKING-DISTRICT-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: (almost literally).  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Village Idiot, which moved from a smaller location in the
East Village in 1995, has a strict drink-and-be-drunk policy;
teetotalers are frowned upon. The beer-scented bar up front gives
way to an airier back room, which resembles a low-rent German beer
hall. Frat-house decor (beer signs, street signs) and classic
country-and-western are standard fixtures.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, college and post-college crowds are a
mainstay, perhaps drawn by nostalgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``It reminds me of school,'' said Jennifer Young, 23, a law
student. ``Undergrad, I mean.''
</P>
<P>
   Returning to the front, I retrieved my brother and headed out.
When what to our wondering eyes should appear? The jolly McNeil.
</P>
<P>
   He spoke not a word but went straight into traffic, hailing a
cab and defying all logic.
</P>
<P>
   But I heard him exclaim as he rode out of sight: ``Don't leave
the bar, and have a good night.''
</P>
<P>
   The next afternoon _ please don't ask about the morning _ I set
out to explore the more refined pleasures of the area.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the galleries here are small, some of them offshoots of
larger establishments elsewhere. Still, the geographic
concentration is impressive. The Katzen-Stein Gallery is at 421 W.
14th St., the Cynthia Broad Gallery at No. 423, Long Fine Art at
No. 427. And so on.
</P>
<P>
   Farther down the block looms Jeffrey, the white-hot clothing and
shoe retailer that opened earlier this year and has label mavens
flocking to it like wildebeests to a water hole. The mood inside is
one of high-end ecstasy: scores of young women clutch Manolo
Blahnik shoes as if they were long-lost children, as young men
stand transfixed by smooth black-leather jackets. All the while a
disk jockey spins tunes, and the register rings. I was scared for
my credit rating.
</P>
<P>
   But as with much of the area, some of the pleasures come in
small, out-of-the-way packages. At Bahay, at 9 Ninth Ave., an
artist, Argie Bucot, creates sleek ceramic plates, vases and bowls
in a studio in the back of the shop. Passerby, a casual cocktail
lounge, sits nearly hidden at the side of Gavin Brown's Gallery on
West 15th Street. And on the always-shadowed south side of
Gansevoort Street, the Gansevoort Gallery deals out antiques and
designer housewares.
</P>
<P>
   For sheer simplicity's sake, it's worth a visit to the Shin Budo
Kai, a martial-arts studio at 425 W. 14th St., a narrow,
well-lighted space where visitors are welcome to watch as
instructors teach wood swordplay and other forms of the art. After
the night I had had _ and the night to come _ I needed a little
tranquillity.
</P>
<P>
   Food in the area breaks pretty much into two camps: meaty and
less so.
</P>
<P>
   In the former are the older places like the Old Homestead, the
venerable steak palace, and the Hog Pit, where barbecue is a
religion. Newer, harder-to-spell joints like Markt, Le Gans, Petite
Abeille, Oriont and Fressen have more varied menus (i.e, vegetables
and such) and more stylish design.
</P>
<P>
   Plunked perfectly in between is Florent, a meatpacking
institution that opened in 1986 and is still the neighborhood's
preferred late-night hangout. Ostensibly the place is French, the
decor is high diner and the food comfortably familiar. I would eat
my last supper (of the weekend) here, and wash it down with a drink
from Hell, a swank SoHo-style lounge down the block.
</P>
<P>
   First, however, I would attempt to go to Markt, heading to that
eight-month-old establishment at 401 W. 14th St. With its windows
open to the street, Markt is breezy and boisterous and Belgian:
mussels and beer are plentiful. On Saturday night at 9:30 there was
a half-hour wait for a table and a half-dozen languages being
spoken at the bar.
</P>
<P>
   My companion, Nina, and I moved on to Rio Mar, a homey Spanish
restaurant farther south on Ninth Avenue, where the streets are
brick and the crowds smaller. No luck here, either: patrons were
packed in tight, chowing on paella and tapas under paint-by-number
portraits of bullfighters mid-dance.
</P>
<P>
   We finally settled at Le Gans, across Gansevoort, a pretty
French bistro with French doors, French posters and a waiter who
spoke with a lilt straight out of ``Casablanca.'' After many
``monsieurs'' and ``madames,'' we headed to the final destination
of the weekend, the big daddy of meatpacking clubs, Mother.
</P>
<P>
   Crouched on the corner of West 14th Street and Greenwich Street,
Mother is host to a rotating series of weekly parties, each geared
to a specific crowd. Of late that has meant the drag revue ``Jackie
60'' on Tuesdays, an all-girl night on Fridays and (you got it)
``Click and Drag,'' home to the cyber-festish gang on Saturdays.
</P>
<P>
   I had been told about the black-only policy and had dressed
appropriately. But when I approached the front door, I had second
thoughts. There, guarding the entrance, was a man in a translucent
silver cape and reflective sunglasses with his head wrapped in
blinking blue-neon string. He didn't look happy with my attire,
which included a tie with just a tiny, little, itsy-bitsy bit of
gray on it.
</P>
<P>
   His co-gatekeeper let me in. And then things got really odd.
</P>
<P>
   Just inside the door I was met by Abby, the evening's hostess,
who was handing out a promotional freebie, a copy of ``Extreme
Fetish,'' a pornographic monthly that caters to proclivities like
high heels, house paint and ladies' undergarments.
</P>
<P>
   Abby led me through the Versailles Room, populated by sequined
drag queens, a middle-aged man in head-to-toe latex, young women in
fish-net tights and bustiers, and several young men who looked like
would-be Marilyn Mansons.
</P>
<P>
   We entered the darkened back room, where a dozen like-minded
folk danced to highly amplified trance and electronica music while
a projected image of a busty computer-generated sexpot contorted on
an overhead screen.
</P>
<P>
   The emphasis at ``Click and Drag'' is on the juncture of
technology and sexuality. But as I peered into the room, I noticed
something: Each of the dancers was dancing alone.
</P>
<P>
   We went downstairs to the Dom Lounge, a sinister-sounding name.
And true enough, what was happening defied expectations: there,
dressed to the nines, or maybe to the Nine Inch Nails, were about a
dozen otherwise normal young men and women . . . playing with
computers!
</P>
<P>
   Dotted around the lounge were four computers, each with fetish
and Goth Web sites at the ready. The lounge also had a bar and a
television showing explicit sexual videos; nobody was paying much
attention to either.
</P>
<P>
   Father Todd, 24, talked me through the scene, even as he chatted
like a proud parent about his Web site, www.sabretooth.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is last refuge of really alternative fashion,'' Todd
said, showing off a female friend's fish nets and her removable
acrylic vampire teeth. ``These people are really eccentric, but
they have day jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the regulars, apparently, was Gekko, a smiley dominatrix,
and Mike the Robot, a young man dressed like a cut-rate cyborg, who
strutted around stiffed-armed, saying things like ``You talkin' to
me?'' in a cheesy ``Lost in Space'' accent.
</P>
<P>
   I wasn't scared of his robo-machismo, and the more I talked to
Todd and his black-clad buddies, the more comfortable I felt. These
people, after all, were, well, kind of nerdy. I felt at home.
</P>
<P>
   Like other groups who convene in the meatpacking district, this
one had simply gathered to feel part of a community, to be with
people who like the same music, the same clothes and the same
ideas.
</P>
<P>
   It was the same ritual that was going on among the bachelor boys
at Hogs and Heifers, and the hipper-than-thous at Oriont. Only in
the meatpacking district, they're doing it ``side by side by
side.''
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL SIDEBAR BEGINS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Here is a listing of places in the article about the meat-market
district in Manhattan:
</P>
<P>
   Restaurants
</P>
