<HEADLINE>
U.S. LAWMAKERS CALL ON MEXICO TO SCRAP CASH CAR-DEPOSIT PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Members of Congress from along the U.S.-Mexico
border urged the Mexican government Thursday to drop a plan to
require people driving into the country beyond 15 miles to leave a
deposit of up to $800 in cash for their vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican officials say the policy, slated to go into effect Nov.
1, is designed to discourage people from selling their
U.S.-registered cars in Mexico, depriving the Mexican government of
taxes paid on car sales. The car deposit would be refunded once a
person leaves Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Mexican Ambassador Jesus Reyes Heroles, the
lawmakers from border districts in California, Arizona, New Mexico
and Texas said the new policy conflicts with the spirit of free
trade between the two nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``While the motivation to implement this program is to combat
the problem of auto theft along the border and reinforce duties
paid on new vehicles sold in Mexico, we strongly believe that this
will be counterproductive to cooperation between the United States
and Mexico,'' said the letter, written by Reps. Henry Bonilla,
R-Texas, and Solomon Ortiz, D-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The letter was sent to the Mexican ambassador on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Under the car-deposit policy, people crossing the border into
Mexico with plans to drive more than 15 miles into the interior
would be required to leave a deposit with Mexican border guards.
The fee would range from $400 for cars produced in 1994 or earlier,
$600 for models from 1995 to 1998 and $800 for cars made this year
or later.
</P>
<P>
   Ortiz said the fee will hurt families living in the United
States with relatives in Mexico, many of whom can hardly afford to
travel to Mexico let alone leave a deposit at the border.
</P>
<P>
   He said the plan ``flies in the face of the spirit of free
commerce'' and will discourage trade and investment from the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   ``North America is supposed to be a free-trade zone, but here we
are with another proposal to bottle up the commerce and travel at
the southern border,'' Ortiz said.
</P>
<P>
   Ortiz agreed with Mexican officials that many cars are being
illegally imported into Mexico from the United States, or stolen
here, and then improperly sold in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had problems with cars on both sides of the border,''
Ortiz said. But, rather than impose a car deposit, Ortiz said
Mexican and United States law enforcement agencies need to work
together to combat the car problem.
</P>
<P>
   Also signing the letter were Reps. Brian Bilbray, R-Calif., Bob
Filner, D-Calif., Duncan Hunter, R-Calif., Ed Pastor, D-Ariz., Jim
Kolbe, R-Ariz., Joe Skeen, R-N.M., Ruben E. Hinojosa, D-Texas, Ciro
Rodriguez, D-Texas, and Silvestre Reyes, D-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Jennifer Corbett Dooren can be reached at 202-298-6920 and at
jennifer(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
