<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLONDIE-FLORIDA-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUMSTEADS VISIT UNIVERSITY OF FLORIDA 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BOB ARNDORFER   
 The Gainesville (Fla.) Sun   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAINESVILLE, Fla. _ Driving a nondescript sport utility vehicle,
one of the world's most famous couples slipped into town Monday for
a leisurely tour of the University of Florida. The Bumsteads did
not draw crowds but their visit was noticed.
</P>
<P>
   In the opening panel of Monday's ``Blondie'' comic strip, the
Bumsteads drive by what local readers immediately recognized as
University Auditorium and Century Tower.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doesn't the college campus look beautiful right now?'' Blondie
says to Dagwood.
</P>
<P>
   It was meant to be Anywhere U., and the street they're driving
on isn't anatomically correct for UF. But there's no doubt about
the identity of the spired, gabled auditorium standing under the
watchful gaze of the carillon tower. No doubt to locals, at least.
</P>
<P>
   Nor, it turns out, to its creators.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ha! Ha!'' Dean Young laughed heartily into the phone from his
studio near Tampa. ``We wondered if anybody would pick up on
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Young, 60, writes the comic strip his late father, Chic Young,
introduced in 1930 and drew until his death in 1973. Dean Young's
partner, Denis Lebrun, illustrates the story lines Young comes up
with.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed a beautiful campus, and I always thought the
University of Florida had a beautiful campus, so I thought, shoot,
let's use it,'' Young said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes we try to disguise things. If people get a chuckle
out of it, then they may think those cartoonists are just having
fun. That's the whole point of doing a comic strip, to have fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Young said he attended UF ``for a bit,'' laughing and saying
he'd like to leave it at that. ``It was a long time ago.''
</P>
<P>
   His partner, however, has a more personal connection to UF:
Denis Lebrun's son is a student there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't seen it yet, but I knew in advance about it,'' said
Devin Lebrun, a junior in electrical engineering from Tampa. ``I
went home to visit last month and my father told me to look for
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Young said ``Blondie'' strips are completed about two months
ahead of the publication date. About three months ago, Denis Lebrun
visited his son in Gainesville. The concept for Monday's strip was
in place and the artist knew what was needed to illustrate it. So
while on campus, his son said, he probably took notes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't see him drawing anything while he was here, but he
might have sketched something,'' he said. ``Or he might have just
taken some mental pictures. He's really good at that.''
</P>
<P>
   Another sly detail in Monday's strip is in the middle panel. The
building the ageless Bumsteads drive by is identified in a sign as
``Engineering.''
</P>
<P>
   The young Lebrun isn't among the students shown walking by the
building. It's been a few years, he said, since his dad put him in
the funny papers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in the strip a couple of times,'' said Lebrun, who
turns 20 on Nov. 6. ``I had long hair then, and was shown in my
high school letter jacket. That was kind of neat. I have one of
them framed upstairs in my room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now it's my stepsister's turn,'' he said. ``Her name is
Courtney, and that's the name of Alexander's girlfriend now.''
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally, Young said, his old letter sweater from Van Nuys
High in California makes an appearance. And he thinks he probably
has a shirt in a closet somewhere like Dagwood's, the one with the
curious circle on the tummy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dagwood is like my alter ego,'' Young said.
</P>
<P>
   UF President John Lombardi said he wasn't surprised that UF
appeared in ``Blondie.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, of course,'' he said, ``anyone who wants a world-class
background would think to put it at the University of Florida.''
</P>
</TEXT>
