A1532 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-WINTER-$ADV31-COX     10-28 1153
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINTER-$ADV31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BILLIONS OF BITS OF INFORMATION MAKE A WEATHER FORECAST
 &HT;    For release Sunday, Oct. 31.
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Most days Louis Uccellini enjoys reading the
columns of Washington Post sportswriter and humorist Tony
Kornheiser.
</P>
<P>
   But the thought of one Kornheiser column _ devoted to an
unforecast Washington snowstorm last March that caught morning
commuters on the capital's expressways _ causes Uccellini to grit
his teeth.
</P>
<P>
   Uccellini is director of the National Center for Environmental
Prediction, which includes the National Weather Service. After the
service predicted with some confidence that Washington was in for a
snowstorm beginning sometime in the afternoon that day, he arrived
at his office early. At around 7 a.m., he opened the blinds.
</P>
<P>
   He saw heavy snow falling on the parking lot and said to
himself, ``We're going down.''
</P>
<P>
   Television meteorologists had used data and analysis from
Uccellini's weather service to assure thousands of trusting
Washington commuters that they could expect a ``dusting'' of rush
hour snow.
</P>
<P>
   ``People always remember the times we miss it,'' Uccellini said.
</P>
<P>
   The indignant Kornheiser declared in his column that ``a baboon
in a leisure suit'' could have done as well on the weather
forecast.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, nothing to it.
</P>
<P>
   Just divide the surface of the Earth into 1.4 million squares,
each about 12 miles on a side, then divide the atmosphere into 70
layers, so that each square becomes the bottom of a stack of 70
thin blocks of air, around 100 million blocks altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Put in numbers for temperature, pressure and humidity for each
block _ or for as many blocks as you can obtain data. Change all
the numbers every few minutes and figure out what the combined
effect will be as the air iblock expands or contracts, heats
up or cools down, rises or falls, takes on moisture or releases it.
</P>
<P>
   Although several billion dollars worth of new satellites,
computers, ocean buoys and software have dramatically enhanced the
Weather Service's forecasting skills in the past five years, the
resolution of the system is not fine enough to forecast snowstorms,
Uccellini said.
</P>
<P>
   If the blocks were smaller and computers powerful enough to
handle the calculations, forecast confidence would rise
accordingly. But improving the resolution to squares one mile on a
side, rather than 12, would increase the total number of blocks by
a factor of 144. Computers would have to keep a running computation
of interlocked conditions within something like 14 billion blocks
of air, rather than 100 million.
</P>
<P>
   But while the resolution is too coarse to forecast individual
snowstorms with great confidence, the center's predictions for
overall weather conditions this winter, issued last week, have a
confidence level of about 70 to 80 percent, Uccellini said.
</P>
<P>
   The seasonal forecast began with conditions in the Pacific
Ocean, along the Equator.
</P>
<P>
   The condition of these equatorial waters _ described in the
now-familiar terms ``El Nino,'' for years when the water is warm,
and ``La Nina,'' for years when it is cooler than average _ sets in
motion the circumstances that eventually define seasonal outlines
of winter weather in the United States, said National Weather
Service meteorologist Gerald Bell.
</P>
<P>
   Using reading from satellites, a network of buoys and ships at
sea, the Weather Service modelers plug in the temperature of the
water, both at the surface and for several feet down.
</P>
<P>
   Bell described the links between Pacific water and weather in
the United States in terms of the transport of heat.
</P>
<P>
   During El Nino, the warm ocean surface sends towers of water
vapor rising all along the Equator, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The vapor condenses as it rises, releasing heat, which generates
thunderstorms that cool the lower atmosphere while they heat the
upper atmosphere. The cooler air near the surface attracts more
heat from the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   Along a zone of ocean that reaches more than halfway around the
planet, the water and the air become a huge machine to pump heat
upward.
</P>
<P>
   As it warms, air in the upper atmosphere above the Equator
expands, generating high-altitude north-south winds. As these winds
are caught by the rotation of the Earth, they feed into a
west-to-east jet stream that flows from Asia to the west coast of
North America.
</P>
<P>
   Thus reinforced, the jet stream brings cold and wet weather to
California and pulls warmer, moist air over the Southwest.
</P>
<P>
   This year, for the second winter in a row, the meteorologists
expect to see the opposite conditions, ``La Nina.'' Except for the
region around Indonesia, on the western side of the Pacific, the
water will almost certainly be cooler than normal this year,
meteorologists say.
</P>
<P>
   With cooler-than-normal water during the Northern Hemispheric
winter, thunderstorm activity over the ocean will be at a minimum,
so there will be less transfer of heat to the upper atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   There will be no El Nino winds from the tropics. Relatively
motionless air over the Pacific Ocean west of California will
develop into ocean storms and high pressure in that portion of the
upper atmosphere, the computers indicate. The storms and pressure
will deflect the jet stream northward.
</P>
<P>
   From Alaska, it will swoop down across western Canada, bringing
cool air into the Midwest and Ohio Valley before turning back to
the northeast, pulling warm air up through Louisiana, Mississippi,
Alabama and Georgia, Uccellini said at a press conference last
week. The U-shaped jet stream path across the continent will
generally define overall winter conditions in the United States,
Uccellini said.
</P>
<P>
   There are still ``wild cards,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The North Atlantic Oscillation is one. Like the El Nino-La Nina
shifts over the equatorial Pacific Ocean, the temperature of water
in the North Atlantic periodically swings from below normal to
above normal and back again.
</P>
<P>
   The changes influence a portion of the jet stream that flows
from the eastern United States to Europe. And interactions between
the Atlantic jet stream and the Pacific jet stream can change La
Nina winters in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995-1996, a La Nina winter was cold and snowy across the
eastern United States, for example. Last year, also a La Nina year,
the same region had a mild winter.
</P>
<P>
   Opposite phases of the North Atlantic Oscillation were a major
factor in the difference, Uccellini said. So far, there is no clear
signal from the North Atlantic for the coming winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Code breakers and weather forecasters are the two largest
markets for mathematicians in the government,'' Uccellini observed.
``What we do is very mathematically based. We're getting much
better, but we'll never be perfect, no matter how good we get.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
