<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, Oct. 29, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(bl) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fueled by moisture streaming northward from the Gulf of Mexico,
moderate to heavy rains will develop across the southern Plains
later Friday. A compact but potent jet stream disturbance arriving
from the southern Rockies on Friday night will act as a spark,
igniting the fuel and setting the stage for an inch or more of rain
by Saturday morning in parts of northern Texas, Oklahoma and
eastern Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   Before these rains materialize, scattered showers will develop
near a cool front across the Middle West, the upper Mississippi
Valley and the western Great Lakes. But these showers will pale in
comparison to the heavier rains slated for the southern Plains on
Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Heavy rain and high winds will lash the coast of British
Columbia on Friday as a potent disturbance arrives from the
Pacific. Though British Columbia will take the brunt of the
disturbance, moderate to heavy rains are possible in the Olympics
of northwestern Washington, where moist Pacific air is forced to
ascend the sloping terrain.
</P>
<P>
   Farther south, warm weather will bathe the southern California
coast as offshore breezes associated with a high pressure system
over the Great Basin keep cool Pacific air at bay.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, warm weather will embrace much of the East from the
Deep South to the Ohio Valley, southern Great Lakes and Middle
Atlantic states as a warm ridge of high pressure holds steady over
the region. In the Northeast, a chilly early morning will be
followed by a milder afternoon as the ridge slowly builds
northward. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Meaningful Rain &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The first meaningful rain in 201 days fell Wednesday at
Sacramento, Calif., with a modest 0.13 inches measured at the
airport. The last time meaningful rain fell in Sacramento occurred
on April 19, when 0.19 inches fell. The 201-day period marked the
city's fourth longest spell without at least one-tenth of an inch
of rain. Moreover, Wednesday's rain brought to an end the city's
144-consecutive day streak without any measurable rain. The jet
stream, which migrates north over Canada during the warm season,
shifted south this week, steering a wet Pacific disturbance ashore.
</P>
</TEXT>
