<SLUG> BC-MISSING-TUGBOATS-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUDGET TUG OF WAR CENTERS ON TALE OF MISSING TUGBOATS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Tenn.) (rk) 
 By CATHERINE HOLLINGSWORTH   
 New York Times Regional Newspaper Group   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In trying to nudge the public toward supporting
their idea of an across-the-board spending cut to balance the
budget, House Republicans have employed a tugboat. Two of them, as
a matter of fact.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've lost two tugboats,'' House GOP Whip Tom DeLay of Texas
declared in amazement on national television Sunday, citing missing
Navy vessels as examples of waste that could easily be eliminated
to provide the necessary savings. ``My goodness. How in the world
can you lose a tugboat? It is bigger than a house.''
</P>
<P>
   Turns out, it could be DeLay and others who missed the boat. The
Pentagonhe Navy tugs were never missing though some
paperwork accounting for them was. According to the Navy, one of
the boats was scrapped, another sunk in an exercise.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't lose the boats,'' said exasperated Pentagon
spokeswoman Susan Hansen, who has built a file and spent months
trying to debunk the myth of the missing boats. ``We just didn't
have the records on the things.''
</P>
<P>
   The missing harbor tugs first made headlines in March 1998 when
an agencywide audit turned up egregious examples of government
waste and put the Defense Department in the hot seat.
</P>
<P>
   Priced between $583,000 and $875,000 each, the financial loss of
the tugboats and several other spectacular assets outraged
government watchdog groups as well as Sen. Fred Thompson, R-Tenn.,
chairman of the Senate Government Affairs Committee.
</P>
<P>
   But when the Pentagon dug deeper, it found records for the
boats. And that is not all it found. Also located was an Avenger
surface-to-air rocket launcher that was tagged with the wrong
serial number and couldn't be traced at the time of the audit _
another piece of missing hardware cited by Republicans. Two hundred
cruise missiles listed as lost had been destroyed in compliance
with a treaty with the former Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in the superheated political climate on Capitol Hill,
Republicans seized on the story of the tugs as a metaphor for
government waste. Rep. Pete Sessions, R-Texas, showed a picture on
the House floor Tuesday night of the tugs, offering a reward for
their safe return.
</P>
<P>
   ``These cannot be found,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When told the Pentagon said the boats were not lost, Sessions
spokesman Adrian Plesha said the department was still in error by
failing to account for the boats at the time of the audit and
losing countless other assets.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't about the tugboats,'' Plesha said. ``In every
federal department and agency it's easy to find waste, fraud and
abuse and these are just larger examples of this.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, DeLay conceded the tugboats had been located. But
he credited the GOP focus on the subject with motivating the
Pentagon into quickly determining their whereabouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``They went to work under the pressure of getting their budget
cut and the pressure put on by the Republican Congress and today we
have great news that the tugboats have been found,'' DeLay told a
press conference.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Joe Lockhart was not amused, accusing the
GOP of ratcheting up the rhetoric. He compared the Republican
tugboat claim to saying ``you won't be able to find your house if
you can't find the deed ... I think it's time for them to get
serious.''
</P>
<P>
   Sticking up for the Pentagon, Lockhart suggested lawmakers
themselves don't always run a tight ship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could find, probably, equipment that has been lost by
senators and congressmen,'' he said. ``I don't think that would be
too much of a stretch.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
