<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASCAR-RUDD-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RICKY RUDD'S STREAK ON THE LINE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By PATRICK ZIER   
 The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For Ricky Rudd, the countdown is on, and it is almost at zero.
</P>
<P>
   As the Winston Cup circuit heads for Phoenix, Ariz., Rudd has
three races left to keep the longest winning streak in the series
alive.
</P>
<P>
   For the past 16 years, Rudd has won at least once every season.
Closest to him is Rusty Wallace.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace, who has already won in 1999, has at least one victory
for 14 straight years.
</P>
<P>
   Dale Earnhardt had a run of 15 straight winning campaigns broken
in 1997 and Mark Martin has won 10 of the last 11 years.
</P>
<P>
   If Rudd can keep the streak intact, he stands a good chance of
extending it.
</P>
<P>
   Rudd, who owns his own team, is selling his equipment and moving
to Robert Yates nex where he will replace Kenny Irwin.
</P>
<P>
   Yates has one of the strongest teams in the sport, while Rudd,
who had to shut down his operation when his primary sponsor, Tide,
deserted him, has been scrambling.
</P>
<P>
   But he has scrambled before. In 1995, Rudd was winless with two
races remaining and snatched a victory at Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   This year, he's supposed to have one of Yates' engines for the
Phoenix race on Nov. 7, which will give him a boost. Running a
Yates engine for the first time at Talladega, Rudd qualified second
and finished third, his best overall '99 effort.
</P>
<P>
   Rudd says he has not thought too much about the final three
races, but he has thought about his streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though our team and ownership days are winding down, my
biggest thoughts are on we need to win,'' Rudd said. ``I'd like to
go out of the sport with the win streak from day one as an owner
until the last day.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to be able to say we were able to win a race every
season. There's not many owners who can make that claim,'' Rudd
said. ``It might not happen, but we're giving it 120 percent trying
to make it happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Having a Yates engine could give Rudd the edge he needs. Over
the last two years in particular, Rudd has made several changes at
the top of his team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're gearing up for an auction right now that will be
Thanksgiving weekend,'' Rudd said.
</P>
<P>
   He said there were three people interested in buying his team.
``if they can come up with the money before the auction, then we
can work something out, but I'm looking forward to closing this
chapter and starting a new one,'' Rudd said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, there's a race to win.
</P>
<P>
   (The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla., is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-99 1753EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991028.0323 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 17:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1541 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-HOK-SHARKS-FLYING-HNS     10-28 0502
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOK-SHARKS-FLYING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLANE CRASHES MAKE FREQUENT-FLYING ATHLETES THINK TWICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROSS McKEON  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ As professional athletes, flying is simply
part of the job. There is no room for fear or apprehension when it
comes to stepping aboard and putting your complete trust in pilots
and an aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, when an accident occurs, as with the crash of
plane carrying golfer Payne Stewart and five other people on
Monday, players take notice.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't really sit back and think about it until you hear
something as terrible as this,'' said Ron Sutter of the San Jose
Sharks, a National Hockey League team. ``Then it makes you think.''
</P>
<P>
   Sutter has appeared in more than 1,000 regular-season National
Hockey League games, as have several of his teammates, including
Murray Craven, Vincent Damphousse and Bob Rouse. That's a lifetime
of flying for each. Between the exhibition and regular season, the
Sharks are scheduled to make 68 flights this season alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully we use a good, reliable company,'' said Mike Vernon,
who admitted he thinks about the risks of flying more now that he
has a wife and children. ``Those things can happen. You just hope
it's not your day, I guess.''
</P>
<P>
   Vernon spent the first 14 years of his career with Calgary and
Detroit. Since most of the air travel he's experienced is in the
dead of winter, Vernon recalls more than a couple of scary moments.
</P>
<P>
   Once he was aboard a plane struck by lightning. Another time
high winds forced a flight he was on to make three attempts at
landing in Chicago before finally touching down safely.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was so bad, we were tossing and turning. That was probably
the worst flight we've ever been on,'' Vernon said. ``We had good
pilots and all, but it was a scary scenario. ... I seriously
thought we were maybe going to go down.''
</P>
<P>
   Craven, meanwhile, is looking forward to the day he gets a
pilot's license because flying a small plane is a goal he wants to
pursue. On Monday, Craven was driving his small Porsche to practice
when a cement truck traveling alongside was forced to lock up its
breaks after a third vehicle cut him off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get to the rink, after hearing about Payne Stewart and guys
are asking, `Do you still want to be a pilot?''' Craven said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, I could have been killed on that highway just as easily.
That truck would have demolished my car.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Woodcock recalled a time _ early in his 33 years as an NHL
trainer _ when the St. Louis Blues were taking a flight from
Winnipeg, Manitoba, to Minnesota. Shortly after liftoff, a flock of
birds flew into one of the plane's engines and forced an emergency
landing. Once a runway was covered with foam, the plane returned to
Winnipeg and landed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scotty Bowman was the coach there then,'' said Woodcock, the
Sharks' athletic trainer, ``and as soon as we get on the ground he
says, `We're taking the train.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-99 1756EDT &QL; 
