<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 18:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1543 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-VENDING29-COX     10-28 0318
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENDING29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    VENDING MACHINES WILL OFFER MORE PRODUCTS
 &HT;    Moving in Washington (w) and Financial (f) categories
 &HT;    By Raven Hill
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- Aluminum cans of film from a vending machine?
Cameras? T-shirts? It's coming.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of new products and technological advances by vending,
office coffee service and food service providers are the highlights
of this weekend's National Automatic Merchandising Association
National Expo.
</P>
<P>
   The last decade has experienced an explosion of product
offerings from vending machines, said Bill Hurley, NAMA spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   While soft drink, candy and snack machines still make up the
bulk of the market, non-traditional items, such as microwaveable
frozen food and bottled water, appear to be the ``next big thing,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are getting creative,'' Hurley said.
</P>
<P>
   Hurley said the industry is excited about the upcoming release
of the new dollar coin by the U.S. Mint in March, expecting it to
spur sales.
</P>
<P>
   The popularity of gourmet coffee drinks have also increased
vending opportunities, he said. Newer coffee machines can grind
beans while you wait.
</P>
<P>
   Other technology highlights include refrigerated machines with
backup systems for power failures. Insulated machines were created
partially to put candy machines outdoors, said Robert Mara, a Mars
Inc., spokesperson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where else can you get a Snickers bar that doesn't melt in the
summer?'' Mara said.
</P>
<P>
   Other machines come equipped with a device that won't let it
take your money without giving you the item you paid for. Some
machines can accept credit cards, an ideal option for more
expensive vending items, said Mike Lawlor, a spokesman for USA
Technologies.
</P>
<P>
   ``This can take vending to another level,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
