<DOCNO> NYT19991028.0325 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 18:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1544 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-WOMEN-FILM-REVIEW-NYT     10-28 0668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WOMEN': MORE FEMALES ON THE VERGE OF A NERVOUS BREAKDOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: production notes at end of review)  
 (bl)  
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Women'' (``Elles''), a sensuous but overstuffed soap opera
about women of a certain age confronting the usual insecurities,
offers one solution to the problem of how to cram five personal
dramas into the same movie. You hang them on the transparently
mechanical premise that one of the five characters is a television
personality preparing a documentary in which she asks her friends
what they would do if they had three wishes.
</P>
<P>
   It helps some that the journalist, Linda, is played by Carmen
Maura, a Pedro Almodovar favorite who sashays through the film with
a leonine authority and curses up a storm when betrayed. Ms. Maura
heads a formidable international cast that includes Miou-Miou,
Marisa Berenson, Marthe Keller, and Guesch Patti. The movie's
international crosscurrents (it was filmed in Lisbon by the
Portuguese director Luis Galvao Teles) lend it the slightly
baffling flavor of a French comedy seasoned with Iberian melodrama:
Rohmer crossed with Almodovar, but on a much lower artistic plane.
</P>
<P>
   Although the characters' problems include rebellious children,
ill health and unfaithful husbands, all five suffer from
40-something jitters about encroaching age and diminishing sex
appeal. Linda is so busy with her career that she takes her
reasonably happy marriage to her husband, Gigi (Joaquim de
Almeida), far too much for granted and barely notices at first when
he acquires a much younger girlfriend (Mapi Galan). Branca (Ms.
Patti), a narcissistic age-obsessed actress, singer and eternal
gamine, compulsively takes lovers right and left while ignoring her
troubled, resentful grown-up daughter, Tiago (Florence Loiret), who
turns to drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Eva (Miou-Miou), a widowed university teacher, throws herself
headlong into an affair with Luis (Morgan Perez), a student 25
years her junior and the son of Barbara (Ms. Keller), a recently
divorced caterer who is still in love with her ex-husband, Edgar
(Didier Flamand). The most enigmatic and least credible of the five
women is Chloe (Marisa Berenson), a bisexual beautician and former
heroin addict who mopes through much of the movie and seems more
like a connecting device than a real person.
</P>
<P>
   Not all the personal dramas add up. But Miou-Miou as a lonely,
anxious teacher surrendering her heart to a besotted student who
happens to be a friend's son, then recoiling from him, strikes a
poignant note. So does Ms. Keller's Barbara, a hypochondriac who
flies into a panic when she begins having headaches and fainting
spells, and learns from her ex-husband, an ophthalmologist, that
she is indeed gravely ill.
</P>
<P>
   As seriously as it takes its characters ``Women,'' is so
determinedly upbeat that it subscribes to a phony quick-fix
mentality about several of their problems. It's really an upscale
version of the instant solutions to crises broadcast on daytime
television.
</P>
<P>
   But can a big hug and a promise to care more and do better
really turn around the bitterest of relationships? Like a soap
opera, ``Women'' ends with a wedding (of Barbara's daughter) at
which everyone is momentarily misty-eyed and forgiving. If only
life were that simple.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `WOMEN' (`ELLES')
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Luis Galvao Teles; written (in French, with English
subtitles) by Teles and Don Bohlinger; director of photography,
Alfredo Mayo; edited by Regina Bartschi; music by Alejandro Masso;
production designer, Veronique Sacrez; produced by Jani Thiltges;
released by Winstar Cinema.
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 97 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: This film is not rated. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CAST: Carmen Maura (Linda), Miou-Miou (Eva), Marisa Berenson
(Chloe), Marthe Keller (Barbara), Guesch Patti (Branca), Joaquim De
Almeida (Gigi), Morgan Perez (Luis), Didier Flamand (Edgar), Mapi
Galan (Raquel) and Florence Loiret (Tiago).  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
