<P>
   (gm) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Friday, Oct. 29 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Lynn Hoogenboom. (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   SPEND-CONGRESS (Washington) _ The House on Thursday will pass in
a party-line vote the last spending bill of the year, an $85
billion measure for health and education programs, along with a
nearly 1 percent across-the-board cut in federal spending.
President Clinton says he will veto the budget cut and the spending
bill, setting the stage for the final act in this year's budget
battle _ negotiations between the White House and Congress that
will go into high gear next week. By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   ORE-SUICIDE (Portland, Ore.) _ Oregonians pride themselves on
being in the forefront on social issues. Five years ago, they
passionately debated and narrowly approved a measure making theirs
the first state in the country, and one of the few places in the
world, to allow physician-assisted suicide. And now, a day after
the U.S. House of Representatives passed a measure that would
effectively overturn the Oregon law and thus amounts to an
extraordinary rebuke of a single state, many people here said they
were deeply angry over federal interference in the issue. By Sam
Howe Verhovek.
</P>
<P>
   FRISCO-MAYOR (San Francisco) _ Mayors all over the country are
sailing the friendly waters of prosperity. But despite a booming
economy, low unemployment and plunging crime rates that mirror the
trend across the nation, voters in politically obsessed San
Francisco are not happy. San Franciscans are notoriously hard to
please, ousting the last two mayors after single terms, but Willie
Lewis Brown Jr., who entered office as Mr. San Francisco, as
colorful and irrepressible as the city considers itself, has
disappointed voters on all sides. By Evelyn Nieves.
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-DEBATE (Hanover, N.H.) _ Though he won't be standing side
by side with the other Republican candidates for president, George
W. Bush will still make his presence known in New Hampshire with a
live interview with the TV station sponsoring the debate two hours
before it begins. While the interview will give him an opportunity
to make his own pitch to New Hampshire voters, it won't spare him
the barbs and accusations of the other contenders who feel that
Bush is snubbing them. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Undated) _ Economic growth surged 4.8 percent in
the third quarter, higher than expected and the fastest pace this
year, as companies built up inventories and exports strengthened.
While the pace of growth raises the prospects of another increase
in interest rates by the Fed, other data showed inflationary
pressures remarkably tame. The Labor Department's Employment Cost
Index rose just 0.8 percent in the quarter following a 1.1 percent
second-quarter gain, which was the biggest in eight years. And the
GDP price deflator grew at a 0.9 percent pace in the third quarter,
down from a 1.4 percent rate the previous quarter. Stock and bond
prices surge in early trading after the reports. By Louis
Uchitelle.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   ARMENIA-ATTACK (Moscow) _ The standoff at the Armenian
parliament ends as the gunmen who assassinated the prime minister
and others surrender and release their hostages. By Michael Wines.
</P>
