<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1563 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-WORLDSERIES-VECSE     10-28 1124
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-WORLDSERIES-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: A MIGHTY TEAM WITH A MORTAL TOUCH, THE YANKS REMAIN
HUMAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ They win. They feel.
</P>
<P>
   They go from first to third on a single. They surround a
teammate who has lost a father.
</P>
<P>
   These Yankees are transforming the record books with their
deeds, while remaining human and fragile. Perhaps that will be the
legacy of this team that George Steinbrenner and Joe Torre directed
in the second half of the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   The players whose names are being etched into the record books
are still young and accessible. What they are accomplishing has a
mortal touch.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps we all should thank Oprah Winfrey for putting emotions
on television in a tasteful setting. We live in a different world.
Ruth and Gehrig always seemed physically wary of each other, a
dozen yards apart even when they were side by side.
</P>
<P>
   These Yankees not only win World Series (in pairs, now), they
also hug in public. The older he gets, the more Joe Torre becomes
kindly Uncle Joe, Zio Beppe, who is not afraid to put his cheek to
his lads' cheeks.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps we can thank the zoom cameras and the freeze frames that
capture Derek Jeter's impish smile as he twits his Jedi grandpa,
Don Zimmer, or the reflective glance of Bernie Williams as he takes
it all in, or the intense stare of Joe Girardi, whether through the
mask or in the dugout, or the pained look of Paul O'Neill as he
performs his job hours after the death of his father.
</P>
<P>
   This franchise won 25 World Series in one century. Given the
advances of technology and media, we will have more intimate
memories of these boys of autumn _ the way they are _ than we do of
Ruth and Gehrig and DiMaggio and Mantle. It is a different age.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people depend on us for their daily feelings,''
Steinbrenner said Wednesday night. ``Our job is to make them
happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Happiness takes different forms. There is the sheer joy of a
city celebrating a championship from out of a void _ a Stanley Cup
in Detroit or Dallas, a basketball title in San Antonio, a Super
Bowl in Denver. There is nothing like a first time in any
generation.
</P>
<P>
   Happiness is different around the Yankees, with all the
championship banners and the monuments in center field, the echo of
history still booming under the eaves.
</P>
<P>
   Yankee fans have their form of happiness, a loud and lusty
celebration of excellence. In 1996 it was fresh and new, but by
this year, inevitably, it has matured or hardened a bit, into a
sense of entitlement, totally justified by the way the Yankees just
stomped all over the Braves in four games.
</P>
<P>
   To a neutral outsider, the totality of the Yankees can almost
come off as operatic, what with all the championships, all the
ancients, all the memories, all the veneration of Yankees who
passed from this world old or young.
</P>
<P>
   This year there was the ``5'' on the uniform sleeve for Joe
DiMaggio and the black band on the left arm for Catfish Hunter in
1999, and then three fathers of Yankees dying late in this season,
and the cancer operations of Joe Torre and Darryl Strawberry.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, this might have seemed heavy, but the grace of this
team is that it seems real and even luminous to people who are not
true Yankee fans or even baseball fans.
</P>
<P>
   The old, old Yankees always had the faint whiff of cigars and
booze and pomade, straight from Toots Shor's or some other guy
place. This changed somewhere during the time of Donnie Baseball.
The other night there were wives and children and parents in the
clubhouse, right after the champagne shower.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, the dousing is truly a bad message all around.
Baseball ought to get serious and ban it. (Plus, the stuff reeks
and stings; Steinbrenner seemed physically repulsed when Jeter
doused him Wednesday night.) Still, beyond the sodden ritual, there
is a wholesome feel to this club.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way the camera follows us in slo-mo,'' as Paul Simon
wrote, we see them putting their arms around Paul O'Neill, infusing
him with their love and energy. When this happens, the Yankees jump
from being a century's worth of glory and gloom, and they become
what they are, humans who persevered and excelled. And won. And
won. And won.
</P>
<P>
   ``What people don't realize is how hard it is to win a World
Series these days,'' Steinbrenner said Wednesday night. ``In the
old days you played the World Series. Now there's the division
series, the championship series and then the World Series. It's not
three times harder. It's five times harder.''
</P>
<P>
   With fans and the surrogate press prying into their lives,
peering into their dugout, lurking by their lockers, the players
have won three World Series in the last four years. They have won
12 straight World Series games.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's pretty amazing, when you think about it,'' said Brian
Cashman, the youthful general manager currently being bullied by
his boss.
</P>
<P>
   They have earned the right to be considered among the great
Yankee teams of all time.
</P>
<P>
   Rudy from Gracie Mansion, you're on the air:
</P>
<P>
   ``I always said that if I could pick a Yankee team, it would be
the team from the early '50s that replaced DiMaggio with Mantle and
won five straight World Series,'' said this fan in his 50s in a
Yankee jacket, with a young son in tow, who somehow wound up in the
Yankee clubhouse Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then there was the 1961 team, with all it did,'' Rudy from
Gracie Mansion continued. ``But now if you ask me, I would say this
was the best  &UR; team &LR;  the Yankees ever had. They didn't just win.
They demolished a great baseball team like the Atlanta Braves.''
</P>
<P>
   Yankee fans and Braves fans don't want to hear how inherently
unfair it is that franchises with vast television income can
outspend small-market franchises. But at least these teams have
won, unlike the laughingstock rich franchises in Baltimore and Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The latest result of all this money and all this expertise will
soon be flapping in the breeze at the entirely outdated Wagnerian
edifice alongside the Harlem River. Twenty-five and counting.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nice part is seeing our organization's players like Bernie
and Derek and Mariano move up in the lists of all-time Yankees,''
Cashman said.
</P>
<P>
   The record book is a work in progress. Jeter just might have
helped win a fourth World Series in 1995 if club officials had
believed their eyes and instincts and gone with the mature kid at
shortstop in October.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever. Time is on their side. They have won three world
championships in four years, and they have not yet turned into
crusty louts. Rudy from Gracie Mansion was onto something. They are
a team. The slo-mo and our curious eyes await them in the next
century.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-99 1812EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991028.0334 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1565 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-WORLDSERIES-BRAVE     10-28 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-WORLDSERIES-BRAVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH DROPPED JAWS, BRAVES RECOUNT THEIR UNDOING BY YANKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Chipper Jones was shaking his head and chuckling a
little at the absurdity of the situation. The most consistent team
of the 1990s had just been rendered road kill by the Yankees, and
Jones could not even find it in himself to be terribly upset.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta Braves may have painted a beautiful picture for
themselves this decade _ the best record over that span, the finest
pitching rotation of their generation _ but it was as if they had
just got a glimpse of Picasso at work. They could only stand back
in wonder, dazzled by the masterpiece.
</P>
<P>
   ``They played pretty much a perfect Series,'' said Jones, the
Braves' third baseman. ``They were awesome, from the starting
pitching to the relief to defense to clutch hitting. They did it
all. If they play a perfect Series, they're going to sweep just
about anybody. They were awesome. We lost to a superior team.''
</P>
<P>
   There is little bitterness between these two teams, none of the
animosity that existed between the Braves and the Mets that
prevented them from saying a kind word about each other except
through tightly clenched teeth. It was telling, in the aftermath of
the Yankees' Game 4 victory Wednesday night, that only Manager
Bobby Cox _ who undoubtedly will have to answer questions about why
his team repeatedly dominates the regular season only to collapse
in the post-season _ seemed truly traumatized by the result.
</P>
<P>
   Cox admitted that he was unusually emotional after the loss _
more so than in 1996, when the Braves won the first two games at
Yankee Stadium, only to lose the next four. The rest of the team,
as second baseman Bret Boone explained afterward, had seen this
coming. Perhaps if the Braves had made this more of a Series, if
they had lost a Game 7, it would have been more difficult to
accept. Instead, the Braves simply gushed at what the Yankees do,
the patience they show at the plate, their discipline in executing
a game plan seamlessly.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you give any pitcher of his stature the chance to close out
the World Series, you'll see foam coming out of their mouth,'' John
Smoltz said of Roger Clemens, the pitcher who outdueled him for the
Game 4 victory. ``If I pitch 10 more games like this, I think I'll
win nine. Every hit they got was amazing. What amazes me is how
some guys lay off pitches. I couldn't believe some of the pitches I
threw and they laid off. I was throwing a ton of pitches they
should have swung at.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a team plan. They attack the pitcher with the same plan
no matter who's there. They are so disciplined. They don't go up
free-hacking. The Yankees play like a National League team. They do
all the things they have to do to win. I don't know in 1996 if I
felt this way. I thought we should have won. You can't say we
should have won this Series. You can't feel we were the better team
_ no way.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones, especially, was overwhelmed by the Yankees' pitching
staff, which held the Braves' hitters to a desperate .200 batting
average. He likened Clemens' pitches to a chainsaw slicing through
the strike zone, and paid homage to a team that had had to battle
the long shadow cast by last year's record-setting season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played that team they had last year,'' Jones said. ``I
didn't think I'd ever seen a ball club stronger from 1 to 25 than
they were. If it's possible, I think this team is better. They
didn't win as many games in the regular season, but they were just
as dominant in the post-season. It was their pitching. We've got
some guys who are capable of swinging the bats and they shut us
down. Roger Clemens was as good as I've ever seen him. It's a
dominant performance by the staff that earned them the sweep.''
</P>
<P>
   Greg Maddux joked that the Braves had to be pretty good to lose
so many World Series _ four of the five they played in the 1990s.
But he was more impressed with the Yankees' phenomenal number: 12
straight victories in World Series games, dating to the four games
in a row the Yankees won from the Braves in 1996 after the Braves
had taken a 2-0 lead in the Series. The Yankees have not lost in
the World Series since and have lost just three playoff games in
the last two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing that they've won 12 straight,'' Maddux said.
``It's hard enough just to play in 12 games, let alone win them
all. That's something I would stick my head up really high about,
if I had that number on my side.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
