<HEADER>
A1571 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-LEES-FILM-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      10-28 0546
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEES-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DREAMING OF JOSEPH LEES': A LOVE TRIANGLE IGNITED BY WHAT MIGHT
HAVE BEEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: production notes at end of review)  
 (bl)  
 By JANET MASLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Though Samantha Morton proved herself a raw, electrifying
actress in ``Under the Skin,'' she now turns up in the kind of
tremulously carnal shy-flower role that once would have been played
by Sarah Miles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dreaming of Joseph Lees'' casts her as a prim-looking spinster
who works at a sawmill and sends a lusty pig farmer named Harry
(Lee Ross) in pursuit of her. Harry courts Eva (Ms. Morton) so
unabashedly that he makes her blush, which is to say that he gets
her attention. Harry's sister teases Eva about this, claiming that
Eva is ``lookin' at him like he was  &UR; burnin' &LR;  you from the inside
out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Dreaming of Joseph Lees'' is set in 1958, when such thoughts
qualify as dangerously naughty. And it is shot on the Isle of Man,
where lonely, rugged panoramas replete with stone, mud and timber
create rebellion-ready mood. So Eva is eventually tempted to flee
the household of her stern, disapproving father and move to Harry's
house. But as the title suggests, Eva yearns for something more.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, she thinks about her distant cousin, a geologist
who lost a leg while working in an Italian quarry. (The sawmill's
way of cutting logs may be an unfortunate metaphor.) She has not
seen him since she was a 14-year-old with a schoolgirl crush. Then,
at a family wedding, Joseph Lees shows up in the form of Rupert
Graves and looks not at all the worse for wear. Unfortunately
Joseph is not an option, now that Harry is on the scene.
</P>
<P>
   But Joseph, who sends his cousin books about Italian art, has an
undeniable effect on her. ``You and me, my darling, are made for
love!'' exclaims Harry, only to have Eva snap ``You and I, Harry.''
Eventually, she and the handsome geologist wind up entwined
together, talking about the earth's crust and other matters that
are beyond Harry. And Harry begins behaving differently, as if the
screenplay (by Catherine Linstrum) had flipped a switch.
</P>
<P>
   As directed by Eric Styles, this earnest first feature pays
careful attention to drably authentic details (Harry's sweaters
have moth holes) and tells its glumly bodice-ripping tale with
somber sensitivity. Ms. Morton succeeds in seeming volatile and
alive even when the material is all too strained. Not content with
metaphorical import, the sawmill also becomes part of a suicide
attempt near the film's shrilly contrived ending. The screenplay
asks viewers to believe that a character would willingly get in the
way of a whirring blade.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `DREAMING OF JOSEPH LEES'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Eric Styles; written by Catherine Linstrum; director
of photography, Jimmy Dibling; edited by Caroline Limmer; music by
Zbigniew Preisner; production designer, Humphrey Jaeger; produced
by Christopher Milburn; released by Fox Searchlight Pictures.
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 92 minutes.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rating: ``Dreaming of Joseph Lees'' is rated R (Under 17
requires accompanying parent or adult guardian). It includes sexual
situations and implicit gore.
</P>
<P>
   CAST: Rupert Graves (Joseph Lees), Samantha Morton (Eva) and Lee
Ross (Harry).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-99 1820EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991028.0339 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1572 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-PATCO-SUIT29-COX     10-28 0455
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATCO-SUIT29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FIRED PATCO WORKERS SUE FOR OLD AIR CONTROLLER JOBS
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Five air traffic controllers, fired for going out
on strike nearly 20 years ago, are suing the Clinton administration
for failing to rehire them.
</P>
<P>
   The group, all Florida residents, are members of PATCO (the
Professional Air Traffic Controllers Organization), the union that
lost a dramatic showdown with President Reagan in 1981. When PATCO
flouted federal no-strike rules and staged a walkout, Reagan fired
all 11,000 strikers and banned them from being rehired.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton lifted the ban in 1993. However, the lawsuit
claims that the Federal Aviation Administration has refused to hire
most of the approximately 5,000 controllers who applied for their
old jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The legal complaint, a copy of which was provided by attorney
John T. Kennedy of Stuart, Fla., was expected to arrive Friday at
the Court of Federal Claims in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Taylor, an electrical contractor and president of the PATCO
Local in Stuart, said that he decided to lead a lawsuit effort
because the FAA had declined to recall him, although he had a
decade of experience as a controller and was a military veteran.
Taylor said that he first sought his old job in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, which seenspecified amount of damages,
wages, benefits and reinstatement, charges that the FAA passed over
the PATCO veterans to hire younger workers with far less or no
traffic controller experience. The lawsuit accuses the FAA of
hiring convicted felons in some cases instead members of the PATCO
group.
</P>
<P>
   Joining Taylor are other Stuart residents, each with at least 11
years of controller experience. One plaintiff, James Black, is a
military veteran with 44 years as a controller. He continues in
that field under a federal contract, according to the legal
complaint.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for the FAA declined to comment on the pending
lawsuit. However, a report to Congress from the agency last summer
said that 4,500 of the strikers had sought re-employment and that
the FAA had hired 715. The report also states that military
veterans are given preference.
</P>
<P>
   The PATCO group is asking the federal court to grant them class
action status, which would allow them to represent all PATCO
controllers who sought reinstatement, as well as their heirs and
survivors.
</P>
<P>
   PATCO was largely destroyed as a union after its run-in with
Reagan. Current FAA controllers are represented by the National Air
Traffic Controllers Association.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-99 1820EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
