<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 18:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1577 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx14;  BC-BBO-WORLDSERIES-YANKS     10-28 1198
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-WORLDSERIES-YANKS-ART-850(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TEAM OF THE '90S PLAYS COY AT THE MERE MENTION OF DYNASTY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ George Steinbrenner ignored some of the questions
shouted at him in the Yankees' clubhouse after his team completed
its World Series sweep of the Atlanta Braves on Wednesday night,
but the mention of a particular word turned his head, a word rarely
heard in baseball in the last quarter century: dynasty.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have won the World Series in three of the last four
years, averaging 100 victories in the regular season. If
championships and dominance are prerequisites, then they are
baseball's first dynasty since the advent of free agency 23 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   The system that gives established players the right to solicit
contract offers and jump from team to team _ as well as the amateur
draft and the multiple layers of post-season playoffs _ has made it
much more difficult for teams to repeat as World Series winners.
The vast majority of the teams that are deep in cash, like
Steinbrenner's, have failed to secure success. ``To have a dynasty
today under free agency,'' said Tal Smith, a longtime baseball
executive and currently the president of the Houston Astros,
``you've got to have unlimited resources and good management.''
</P>
<P>
   Teams won back-to-back championships 17 times in the first 73
years of World Series play, but in the last 23 years, title-winning
teams have repeated just 3 times. The Yankees won four consecutive
championships from 1936 to 1939 and five straight from 1949 to
1953, and the Oakland Athletics won three straight from 1972 to
1974. No team has won three consecutive World Series since then.
</P>
<P>
   But the Yankees of '96-'99 are the first team since free agency
began to win three titles in four seasons, and they will pursue
their third consecutive title next year; presumably, they will be
poised to continue their dominance.
</P>
<P>
   Their best position player, shortstop Derek Jeter, is 25 years
old, and their best pitchers, Mariano Rivera and Orlando Hernandez,
will be tied to the team for at least the next two seasons. Bernie
Williams, their cleanup hitter, has six years remaining on his
current contract. The organization's infrastructure and farm system
are among the strongest in the majors: baseball scouts say
infielders Alfonso Soriano and Nick Johnson will become stars after
they reach the big leagues within the next two years.
</P>
<P>
   David Cone, the Yankees pitcher, was asked about the team's
place in history. ``It makes you wonder,'' he said. ``I don't think
a lot of us are that far along in our mind with what this means,
how do we compare, what did we just do. I think it's more about
enjoying the moment for what it is, and let you people talk about
history and where we fit in.''
</P>
<P>
   Through collective bargaining between the players' union and
baseball owners, free agency _ the system within which players
could leave their team after six years of service time and sign
elsewhere _ began after the 1976 season. Free agency, as well
arbitration rights for players with between three and six years of
service time, rapidly escalated salaries, and players began
changing teams constantly. Maintaining a particular collection of
players became far more difficult, either because key players
wanted to go elsewhere once they became free agents, or because of
budgetary constraints. Dynasties, as they were loosely defined,
largely became a thing of the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prior to free agency, if you were able to assemble talent
through scouting and development and judicious trades, you were
able to retain that talent,'' Smith said. ``Today it's a much
shorter span of control. It becomes increasingly difficult to
maintain continuity.''
</P>
<P>
   In the first seasons after the advent of free agency,
Steinbrenner seized on the newly created system and blended stars
like Reggie Jackson and Goose Gossage with an already formidable
team that included Thurman Munson, Ron Guidry, Chris Chambliss,
Willie Randolph and Graig Nettles. The Yankees, who had won the
American League pennant and been swept by Cincinnati in the World
Series in 1976 _ the last season before free agency _ won
back-to-back World Series in 1977 and 1978.
</P>
<P>
   They finished fourth in their division in 1979, won the division
but lost in the playoffs to Kansas City in 1980, and returned to
the World Series in 1981, where they lost to the Dodgers.
Steinbrenner's insatiable appetite for dominance then drove the
Yankees into the decline that lasted more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Before the current group of Yankees, the Oakland Athletics of
1988-92 may have been the most awesome club of the free agency era,
averaging 102 victories over three regular seasons from 1988-90 and
playing in the World Series in those three seasons. Rickey
Henderson was their leadoff hitter and Jose Canseco and Mark
McGwire powered their run production, and Oakland had an
experienced pitching staff that included the starters Dave Stewart
and Bob Welch and the closer Dennis Eckersley.
</P>
<P>
   As good as they were, the Athletics won the World Series once
(1989), and in their other two appearances, they lost to the Los
Angeles Dodgers in five games (1988) and the Cincinnati Reds in
four (1990).
</P>
<P>
   The Toronto Blue Jays won back-to-back championships in 1992 and
1993, only the second team of the free agency era to do so, spurred
by a deep and patient lineup (Roberto Alomar, John Olerud, Joe
Carter and Paul Molitor) and solid pitching (Tom Henke, Duane Ward,
a late-season hired gun named David Cone). The Blue Jays, playing
in the competitive American League East, were not as dominant
during the regular season as the Athletics, or the current Yankees,
averaging 94 victories from 1991 to 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta Braves have made it to the post-season in every year
since 1991, and they have been baseball's most consistently
successful team in the last decade. But the albatross history will
hang on them is their record in the World Series: they won in 1995
and lost in 1991, 1992, 1996 and 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The amateur draft, which began in 1965, helped to make it more
difficult for teams to stockpile talent; if the draft had been in
place years before, Joe DiMaggio and Mickey Mantle would almost
surely have played elsewhere. The leagues were split into divisions
before the 1969 season, and then into thirds before the 1995
season; now four teams from each league qualify for the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   But even though there is added opportunity to appear in the
post-season, there is greater risk, as well. The Yankees of Babe
Ruth, DiMaggio and Mantle went directly into the World Series after
taking the pennant. The current Yankees went through two rounds of
playoffs before winning the World Series; despite those obstacles,
they have won 9 of 10 post-season series in the last four years,
including 12 consecutive World Series games, and 22 of 25 games in
the last two post-seasons.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have an enormous financial advantage over most
teams; they have a greater margin for error in making personnel
decisions, and have more freedom in taking chances on amateur free
agents, like Hernandez, who is turning out to be a huge bargain
after signing a four-year, $6.6 million deal. But the Los Angeles
Dodgers spend millions and millions and have not won consecutive
championships, and neither have the Baltimore Orioles, the
Cleveland Indians, the Atlanta Braves or the other big-budget
teams.
</P>
<P>
   In the first years after free agency, players wanted to sign
with the Yankees because they paid the highest salaries and offered
a winning tradition; in the latter half of the '80s, however,
Steinbrenner's often reckless restructuring and the pressure he
placed on players scared free agents away.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent years, the Yankees have developed and paid to keep
their own talent, like Bernie Williams and Derek Jeter, and the
resulting success and clubhouse culture _ the players generally
have a strong respect for each other, their opponents and the sport
itself _ is viewed as a model by other teams and players. Stars
like Chuck Knoblauch and Roger Clemens have forced their teams to
trade them to the Yankees. The Yankees have lots of money, have
used it wisely, and have earned the right to be called a dynasty.
``They've completely demonstrated their superiority,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner joked about the word, laughed it off. But
re-creating the Yankees' dynasty he followed as a child is what he
has wanted since purchasing the team and promising to be a
hands-off owner 26 years ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
