<DOCNO> NYT19991028.0348 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1584 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-NYT &LR;      10-28 1463
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE SILVER SCREEN: FILM PROMOTION FROM A DISTANCE; FINDING
THE DRAMATIC THREAD; FRENCH DIRECTOR LIKES AMERICANS; CREDIT-CARD
FILMMAKING 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By RICK LYMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Chris O'Donnell has been in New Zealand for the last
four months, up on top of a mountain most days, and he's only
halfway through shooting ``Vertical Limit,'' a thriller about
trapped climbers that is set for release next summer. This is
making it very difficult for O'Donnell to promote his new film,
``The Bachelor,'' which opens on Nov. 5 and which happens to be the
first film he produced. But it's also keeping him out of Hollywood
during the final anxious days before the movie's release.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to do as much as possible for the movie, but it's
kind of nice not to be too involved with all the hoopla around
it,'' he said. ``You know, when you're an actor you come onto a
movie, do your part and then you're finished. But when you're the
producer, too, it's different. `The Bachelor' I was on for two
years, and it really became a part of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   As part of O'Donnell's deal to play Robin in the last two Batman
movies _``Batman Forever'' in 1995 and ``Batman and Robin'' in 1997
_ he was given a production deal and a suite of offices on the
Warner Brothers lot. Such deals were once quite common in
Hollywood, almost part of every rising actor's status pack, but in
the current cost-cutting climate they are becoming much less so.
Often, they resulted in no films and turned out to serve little
purpose other than providing the actor's friends a place to flop.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of those deals where they give you some offices and
some overhead expenses,'' O'Donnell said. ``So I thought, well, I
might as well take advantage of it. I may as well try to build a
business here. My idea was to hire some really young, hungry people
and get some projects going.''
</P>
<P>
   What he found, he said, was that hiring the young, hungry people
was easy, and getting projects moving only slightly less so. But
actually getting the movies made was a long, frustrating process.
``Setting up a movie and getting it greenlit is a whole different
deal,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bachelor'' is based on the old Buster Keaton feature,
``Seven Chances,'' about a man who learns that he has 24 hours to
get married or lose a huge inheritance. The story, and the dollar
figures, were all updated from Keaton's version, but it is still at
heart a comedy, one that includes a shot of hundreds of women in
wedding gowns chasing O'Donnell down a San Francisco street.
</P>
<P>
   After New Line bought the script on spec, O'Donnell said, ``we
had to deal with everyone's notes on it.'' More writers were
brought in for rewrites, a director was hired and the setting was
changed from New York to San Francisco, for fear that the filming
would stretch into an East Coast winter.
</P>
<P>
   O'Donnell has also just produced a television movie for CBS,
``The Miracle on the 17th Green,'' which is set for broadcast in
December. ``The whole TV side of the business is exciting,'' he
said. ``Business-wise, there's a lot of money to be made in TV, and
it is a business, after all.''
</P>
<P>
   Drama in the Real
</P>
<P>
   When making a film based on an actual incident, it is necessary
to find the dramatic thread that holds the story together, that
allows it to be not merely a recitation of facts but a living drama
with characters who are fully rounded and who speak to that drama.
For Michael Mann, the director of ``The Insider,'' that discovery
came when he grasped some fundamental truths about the story's two
main characters: Jeffrey Wigand, the former tobacco executive
turned whistle-blower, and Lowell Bergman, the ``60 Minutes''
producer who persuaded him to spill the beans and then fought to
get the interview broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I was looking for with Jeffrey was his psychology, what
he is obsessive about, what drives the man, why he did what he
did,'' said Mann. ``You don't look for how this man is like
everybody else. You look for how he's different.''
</P>
<P>
   The goal was not to make a documentary with actors, but to make
a drama.
</P>
<P>
   ``The film, as it relates to Jeffrey, has one and only one
motive _ to put you under the skin of Jeffrey, walking in his
shoes, through a dramatized battlefield and minefield of the
heart,'' Mann said. ``We don't pretend to be, nor do we want to be,
the complete historical record.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Insider,'' which is to be released on Nov. 5 and is
generating a lot of early Oscar buzz, is not just Wigand's story,
though. It is also about the relationship between the
whistle-blower, played by Russell Crowe, and the producer, played
by Al Pacino. And, Mann said, it was in thinking about the
characters of the two men that he had the central insight that made
the story click for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an answer that was terribly interesting to me,'' he
said, ``which gets to the moment when I thought, `This truly is a
drama and I should make this film.' It's when I realized that
Jeffrey and Lowell are total opposites _ even their rhythms were
different _ that it was kind of a beautiful dramatic counterpoint.
They had only one thing in common.''
</P>
<P>
   And that, Mann said, was that the identities of both men were
deeply tied up in their actions, in what they did in life, and that
each of them had very definite limits beyond which he would not go.
Yet at the same time, he said, he did not want to present the men
as one-note heroes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not my intent that these are heroic moments at all,''
Mann said. ``It is a failure to read the film accurately to say
that these are romantic characters and heroic moments. They're not.
Jeffrey's character in the film is as flawed as everybody else, and
that's what made him attractive.''
</P>
<P>
   Buy American
</P>
<P>
   For the French director Luc Besson, one of the advantages in
making his most recent films in English is that it allows him to
work with American actors. Francophiles may not like what he has to
say.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are really so much better than French actors,'' said
Besson. ``When you can have a John Malkovich or a Dustin Hoffman or
a Faye Dunaway in your film, it is really so much stronger. We have
some good actors in France, but not like here.''
</P>
<P>
   All three of those actors are in ``The Messenger: The Joan of
Arc Story,'' Besson's latest film and something of a departure for
the director of ``The Professional'' and ``The Fifth Element.''
Besson said he began reading books about Joan of Arc a few years
ago and became obsessed with the subject. In the film, he hoped to
re-create as much as possible the reality of life and warfare in
medieval France, as well as the atmosphere of court intrigue and
spirituality. In the end, though, he found that he had to tone down
the violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you see in the film is really so much milder than it
actually was,'' he said. ``It was horribly brutal, really. You
couldn't show it.''
</P>
<P>
   Have Card, Will Film
</P>
<P>
   ``What's the term they use, credit-card filmmaking?'' Glen Goei
asked as he made his way to the airport in Los Angeles after
several days of feverish promotion on ``That's the Way I Like It,''
his film about romance and disco dancing in Singapore in the 1970s.
``I took credit-card filmmaking to the absolute limit.''
</P>
<P>
   Goei lives in London, his parents are still in Singapore and he
has brothers in Australia, so he applied for and received credit
cards from each country, then ran them up to the limit to finance
his film, which the authorities in Singapore told him was the first
feature film to be shot there since 1990. ``The budget of the film
was a half million, and everything was in overdraft,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Goei had trouble finding a competent crew and decent, trained
actors; indeed, outside of the male lead, all of the roles in the
film were played by people who had never acted before. ``We had a
radio disk jockey, a guy who just left the army _ we just placed an
open call for auditions,'' Goei said. ``Now, all of them are acting
full time. I have that to answer for.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the film, Goei had directed only some small-scale theater
pieces in London. So it took a leap of faith to mortgage himself to
the hilt and shoot a disco movie back home in Singapore. Then,
through serendipity, someone saw his film in a lab in Sydney and
asked if he could take a copy and try to market it at the Cannes
Film Festival.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the very first day, Harvey Weinstein happened to stumble
into a screening and bought the film,'' Goei said. ``He called me
up. At the time, I didn't know who Harvey Weinstein was.'' Goei
soon found out, and the check from Miramax helped him pay off his
entire credit-card debt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was all quite surreal,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
