<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1592 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-THEATER-NOTES-ART-NYT     10-28 1057
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-NOTES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLOSINGS SCHEDULED; KNOWN FOR HIS EYEBROWS; CANDIDATES ON
BROADWAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 BY JESSE McKINLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   One Closing, a Second Likely
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a move likely to set off a Broadway theater grab,
one major Broadway musical confirmed a January closing while
another seemed poised to do the same.
</P>
<P>
   The first is ``Ragtime,'' the Tony-winning epic of
turn-of-the-century America. The show, producers said, will end its
run at the Ford Center for the Performing Arts on Jan. 16.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is never easy to make the decision to close a show,'' said
Scott Zeiger of SFX Entertainment, the producer. ``This is
particularly true of `Ragtime.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ragtime'' still regularly ranks as one of Broadway's
highest-grossing shows. But it also carries one of the industry's
steepest weekly costs, sometimes more than $600,000, part of a
legacy of the fallen impresario Garth Drabinsky, who liked
grandiose effects and even grander contracts. The high cost was
acceptable when the show was grossing over $800,000, as it did for
much of last year. But of late the show's sales have slipped; last
week the gross was $600,240.
</P>
<P>
   Drabinsky, whose bankrupt company, Livent, was bought by SFX in
August, has been indicted on federal fraud charges and is fighting
extradition from Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Zeiger's statement did not speak about creating a slimmed-down
version of ``Ragtime,'' although SFX officials have said that is a
possibility.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, officials for ``The Scarlet Pimpernel'' said this
week that they told their cast on Tuesday that it was likely the
show would close in January, before a national tour. Tim Hawkins,
its executive producer, said no final decision had been made.
</P>
<P>
   Based on Baroness Orczy's 1905 tale of deception and derring-do
in the French Revolution, ``Pimpernel'' opened at the Minskoff
Theater in November 1997 to mixed reviews and sluggish box-office
figures. It soldiered on, however, until the fall of 1998, when its
original producers sold it to Cablevision, which hired new stars
and a new director and reworked several trouble spots.
</P>
<P>
   It reopened in November to better reviews and box-office sales.
But the blush was soon off the rose, and in April the show closed
to make way for ``Saturday Night Fever.'' The plan was to cut its
ensemble to 29 actors from 41 and reopen a slimmer and better
version at the Neil Simon Theater this fall. All that fell into
place except for the bit about making the show better. Critics
called the latest ``Pimpernel,'' which opened on Sept. 9 and was
informally dubbed ``Version 3.0,'' an anemic imitation of the
musical's previous incarnations. Box-office sales, while slowly
improving, have hovered around $340,000 a week this month, just
below breaking even.
</P>
<P>
   Both closings would make Broadway houses available as several
musicals are looking for homes, including the revival of ``Jesus
Christ Superstar,'' rumored for the Ford Center, the revival of
``The Music Man,'' and ``Wise Guys,'' the new Stephen Sondheim/John
Weidman musical, which starts a ``developmental workshop
production'' Friday at New York Theater Workshop.
</P>
<P>
   An Eyebrow Fan Club
</P>
<P>
   You probably don't know Jason Antoon's name, but if you've seen
``Contact,'' now playing at Lincoln Center, you know his eyebrows.
</P>
<P>
   Antoon, 27, plays several characters in the musical, but the
most memorable is a knowing barkeep whose undulating brow signals
that something a bit unusual might be going on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I now have an eyebrow fan club,'' Antoon said deadpan. ``I
have it on my resume as a joke, but I think it clinched the part.''
</P>
<P>
   A Los Angeles native and a former surfer, Antoon studied acting
at Carnegie Mellon University before coming to New York in the
mid-1990s. (His uncle was the late A.J. Antoon, the director,
though the two met only once.)
</P>
<P>
   In New York he found work as an understudy on two off-Broadway
shows, covering three roles in ``Picasso at the Lapin Agile'' and
four characters in ``Scapin.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess ultimately I'm a character actor,'' Antoon said. ``I'm
not the blond-haired, blue-eyed guy. I'm not the guy staring at the
tree and falling in love with the girl. I'm his friend.''
</P>
<P>
   Those character skills are put to good use in ``Contact,'' where
Antoon also takes turns as a glowering husband and as the voices of
three other characters on an answering machine: a British agent, a
drunk friend and a passive-aggressive therapist.
</P>
<P>
   Considering his previous gigs, Antoon says he is as surprised as
anyone to have a leading role in a musical. ``When I walked into
the first rehearsal, I'm in my actor clothes, which are basically
my clothes, and everybody else is in tights with their legs over
their head,'' he said. ``I'm like, `Why is everybody singing?'''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley to Broadway
</P>
<P>
   The theater season is becoming a political season.
</P>
<P>
   On the heels of Monday's ``Broadway for Hillary'' bash, which
raised $1 million for Mrs. Clinton's as-yet-unannounced Senate
campaign, another prominent Democratic candidate, this one for
president, is coming to see a show _ and collect some checks.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday Bill Bradley will attend a benefit performance of
``Kiss Me, Kate'' at the Martin Beck Theater, with tickets running
from $250 to $1,000 (similar to Mrs. Clinton's rates). The
performance is being organized by the producers Rocco Landesman,
Emanuel Azenberg and Roger Berlind.
</P>
<P>
   It will also, presumably, include the type of quality face time
that donors love; at Mrs. Clinton's event, a 15-minute intermission
ran long as a throng descended on the first lady and President
Clinton, who also attended. They sat house right; no word yet on
Bradley's position.
</P>
<P>
   Along the Way
</P>
<P>
   _ Leave it to Spalding Gray to open a show on Halloween. Gray's
latest monologue, ``Morning, Noon and Night,'' opens at the Vivian
Beaumont Theater in Lincoln Center on Sunday. It will be seen on
Sundays and Mondays through Jan. 10.
</P>
<P>
   _ Edgar Oliver, the East Village's crepuscular performance poet,
will lead a creepy ensemble in a one-night-only showing of ``Chop
Off Your Ear'' on Tuesday at the Angel Oransanz Foundation, 172
Norfolk St.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
