<HEADER>
A1607 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-SECRET-EVIDENCE-HNS &LR;      10-28 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SECRET-EVIDENCE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELEASED IMMIGRANT URGES CONGRESS TO END USE OF SECRET EVIDENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A Palestinian immigrant mistakenly held by a
government agency for 19 months on secret evidence accusing him of
terrorism Thursday urged Congress Thursday to outlaw such actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just could not believe that something like this could happen
in America,'' said Hany Kiareldeen, who was detained by the
Immigration and Naturalization Service in two New Jersey jails on
allegations that he had links to terrorists and had plotted to kill
Attorney General Janet Reno.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to tell them they were wrong, but they wouldn't listen
and then they wouldn't even show the evidence against me,'' said
Kiareldeen, who has lived in the United States since 1990 and who
worked in an electronics store in Passaic, N.J., before he was
jailed.
</P>
<P>
   Kiareldeen, 31, had become a national test case of the INS's
ability to detain and deport immigrants based on evidence they are
not allowed to see and witnesses they cannot question.
</P>
<P>
   The INS arrested Kiareldeen in March 1998 for overstaying a
student visa. Soon afterward, the agency accused him of plotting to
kill Reno and of hosting a meeting with the New York World Trade
Center bombers a week before the 1993 attack. But he was never
charged with any crime.
</P>
<P>
   During his immigration hearings, Kiareldeen, a native of Gaza,
used rent receipts, phone records and other testimony to show that
he did not live at the address of the alleged meeting and that he
was not planning to kill Reno.
</P>
<P>
   Last week in Newark, N.J., U.S. District Judge William Walls
ruled that detaining an immigrant on the basis of secret evidence
was unconstitutional, and Kiareldeen was ordered freed. A
three-judge immigration appeals board delayed Kiareldeen's release
until Monday to give the Justice Department _ the INS' parent
agency _ a last chance to decide if it wanted to continue pressing
its case. The department declined to do so.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement Tuesday, the Department said that it and INS
Commissioner Doris Meissner believed ``that after submitting the
evidence to an immigration judge and the board, the process has
taken its course, and as a result the department has decided not to
take the extraordinary step of appealing the board's decision.''
</P>
<P>
   The INS, which has about 300,000 removal proceedings pending,
has used secret evidence in about two dozen cases to detain
immigrants in recent years, according to agency officials.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Rep. David E. Bonior, D-Mich., speaking at a news
conference here, called on Congress to pass the Secret Evidence
Repeal Act of 1999, which would ban the secret evidence in
immigration cases.
</P>
<P>
   Bonior said Congress mistakenly gave the INS authority to use
secret evidence when it passed the 1996 Anti-terrorism and
Effective Death Penalty Act in the wake of the April 19, 1995,
bombing of the Alfred P. Murrah Building in Oklahoma City that
killed 168 people.
</P>
<P>
   He said the only effective solution to cases like Kiareldeen's
would be to eradicate the practice of using secret evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hany Kiareldeen's release will be a hollow victory unless we
permanently discard this law,'' said Bonior, a co-sponsor of the
bill.
</P>
<P>
   The bill's other co-sponsor, Rep. Tom Campbell, R-Calif., said
he was confident Congress will pass the proposed legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most members of Congress have no idea that this is allowed,
and when I tell them about it, they're outraged and ask immediately
how they can help,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Thursday Kiareldeen reiterated his previous testimony
that he is not political or religious, does not know any of the men
convicted in the bombing, and did not know who Reno was until he
was arrested.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to live my life,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kiareldeen's lawyer, David Cole, a law professor at Georgetown
University, said it was ``unbelievable'' that the INS is continuing
to use its secret evidence authority after a judge ruled it was
unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the two dozen similar INS cases in recent years,
Cole said it was a ``tragedy'' that Kiareldeen ``lost more than a
year of his life, and, yet, there are many others still sitting in
jail without the right to even see the evidence that's keeping them
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Aly R. Abuzaakouk, the executive director of the American Muslim
Council, a Washington-based advocacy group, applauded the release
of Kiareldeen, but said he believed it would not force the
immigration agency to change its policy. He said the only thing
that would end those practices and repair the damage they had done
to Arab-Americans and Muslims would be the passage of the
Campbell-Bonior bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``People in our community are aware of secret evidence, and it
is having a chilling effect on their expressing themselves on
issues,'' Abuzaakouk said.
</P>
<P>
   But Donald Mueller, a spokesman for the immigration service,
said the agency's decision to release Kiareldeen did not mean that
it would abandon the use of secret evidence altogether.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to continue to use this authority when national
security is at stake,'' Mueller said.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
