<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 18:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1610 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-WORLDSERIES-CONE-     10-28 1066
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-WORLDSERIES-CONE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONE STAYS, BUT WILL HE REALLY 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By JACK CURRY    
 c.1999 N.Y. ews Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The New York Yankees were 90 minutes into their new
yet continuous reign as World Series champions and David Cone was
standing near the first-base line at Yankee Stadium doing
television interviews. Except for some reporters, security guards,
police officers and the ever-accommodating Cone, the Stadium was
mostly barren.
</P>
<P>
   But that did not stop Cone from staying on the field and trying
to squeeze something more out of an amazing Wednesday night that
had turned into Thursday morning. For Cone, who does not know if he
will pitch again for the Yankees, the experience could go on and
on. He did not want to think about removing his champagne-soaked
pinstripes, so he prolonged the festivities.
</P>
<P>
   Cone was ushered from the interviews by two security guards, but
they might as well have been mannequins to the player who is the
Yankee of the people. When he reached the dugout, a few fans pushed
baseballs toward him and he deliberately signed each one, squeezing
a few more minutes out of the early morning.
</P>
<P>
   A dozen police officers surrounded Cone on the top step of the
dugout and begged him to pose for pictures with them. Like a
gregarious New Yorker, he was not just in the picture. He was the
picture. He inserted himself into the middle of this blue wall,
leaned into the officers and played to the cameras like he was at
the annual family reunion.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's going through my mind is to enjoy this night for what
it is and really soak it up,'' Cone said. ``I honestly don't know
what's going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   There was elation and confusion in his voice _ so excited to win
a second straight World Series, so puzzled about where he will
pitch next season. For five years he has been the most vocal Yankee
and one of many reasons they have won three of the last four World
Series titles; this season, he provided a signature Yankee moment
when he pitched a perfect game against Montreal on July 18.
</P>
<P>
   But the future is fuzzy. Early Thursday morning, he was still a
Yankee, still squeezing out memories.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel lucky,'' Cone said. ``I feel very privileged and very
humbled to be a part of this.''
</P>
<P>
   As he spoke, he was standing in the runway between the dugout
and the clubhouse, a quiet place that had been raucous two hours
earlier. The police had finished snapping pictures with him, so now
he stopped and chatted with a handful of reporters. He was about 15
feet from a blue and white sign above the runway that includes a
quotation from Joe DiMaggio: ``I want to thank the good Lord for
making me a Yankee.''
</P>
<P>
   It was appropriate that Cone stopped so close to the quotation
because Cone has indicated he would love to stay with the Yankees.
But the Yankees have numerous off-season decisions to make to keep
their payroll in control, and George Steinbrenner and Cone have
both admitted the decision over his status will be delicate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to talk about that at this moment,''
Steinbrenner said Thursday. ``We have to sleep on what we're going
to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Cone added: ``It's pretty unpredictable. I've had the time of my
life playing for the Yankees.''
</P>
<P>
   Cone was emotional during the American League division series,
discussing how he might not fit in anymore and hinting that a
Yankee official had told him he would not be part of plans for next
season. Cone rambled for almost an hour that day, using reporters
as amateur psychologists and wondering why his 12-9 record and 3.44
earned run average might not be enough to keep him with the team.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks ago, it seemed more than conceivable that Cone would
not return. But he went from not pitching in the division series to
pitching two impressive games in the league Championship Series and
the World Series, going 2-0 with a 1.29 ERA. Even Cone admitted
that the postseason is what really matters to the Yankees and those
starts ``really can determine your future here.''
</P>
<P>
   One person who has spoken to Cone said he would surely return if
the Yankees offered him the same contract he had this season, for
$8 million and an additional $1.5 million in incentives.
</P>
<P>
   Cone will be 37 in January. Though a two-year offer from the New
York Mets or the Baltimore Orioles might seem tempting, he is in
the midst of an historic period with a team that should be favored
to win the World Series again. But Cone, who admitted the Yankees
``probably could have gotten me for less last year,'' will most
likely have to accept less than $9.5 million to stay.
</P>
<P>
   If Steinbrenner had seen how Cone meandered from television
camera to television camera on the field, then stopped in the
dugout with the fans and the officers, and then remained in the
runway with the reporters, it would have been especially apparent
to him how much Cone loves being a Yankee.
</P>
<P>
   Cone said he felt ``very blessed'' because for four months in
1996 he did not know if aneurysm surgery would prevent him from
throwing a baseball again. But after having the aneurysm removed
from his right armpit, he helped lead the Yankees to their first
world championship in the '90s. Now, after career-threatening
surgery, arthroscopic surgery, several cortisone shots and a
perfect game, he leaned against a wall in the runway and discussed
the magnificence of three World Series rings within four years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This just seems like the culmination of so much emotion and so
much drama,'' he said. ``Back to my aneurysm surgery, to Joe
Torre's situation in spring training, all the way up to today with
Paul O'Neill's father dying. The clubhouse was a little eerie after
the victory. There was so much relief and grown men crying.''
</P>
<P>
   Cone let loose some of those emotions in his own way. He kept
buzzing from place to place at the Stadium, grabbing for more and
more images while slowly winding down another special season.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year was much more difficult,'' he admitted. ``There was
so much emotion. I think everyone feels such relief that we were
able to continue this run that we had.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he glanced ahead and said, ``And now, nobody knows what's
going to happen.'' With that, he cruised up the runway and into the
clubhouse, where some of his teammates still remained, to squeeze a
little more out of part of his that he did not want to end.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-99 1851EDT &QL; 
