<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INS-PROCESSING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INS CUTS TIME IT TAKES TO PROCESS APPLICATIONS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Immigration and Naturalization Service, which
faces a persistent backlog in citizenship requests, said Thursday
it now takes immigrants just one year to have their applications
considered.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as last October, the INS took an average of 28
months to consider an application fully, the agency reported.
</P>
<P>
   INS Commissioner Doris Meissner told reporters that the agency's
efforts to expedite requests are not complete and that she plans to
cut the processing time further, to six months, by next October.
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Lamar Smith, R-Texas and an outspoken INS critic,
assailed as a ``gross misrepresentation'' Meissner's claim that the
agency ever took an average of 28 months to process applications.
Instead, the INS has taken on average 14 months, said Smith, who
chairs the House Judiciary Subcommittee on Immigration and Claims,
which oversees the INS.
</P>
<P>
   ``Additional resources provided by Congress combined with a
declining number of citizenship applications have helped the INS to
process more citizenship requests,'' Smith said. ``But this (issue)
is not about statistics and bar charts; it is about serving people,
which this administration needs to do better. It seems to me a
reasonable goal to process citizenship applications in 90 days.''
</P>
<P>
   But Meissner rejected the claim that the number of applications
has declined, noting that more than 6.4 million immigrants applied
for citizenship between 1993 and 1999, exceeding the total number
of applicants during the previous 37 years.
</P>
<P>
   INS received 720,468 citizenship applications during fiscal year
1999, which ended Sept. 30, and expects to receive 700,000 this
fiscal year, she said.
</P>
<P>
   In fiscal year 1999, 872,485 immigrants became naturalized U.S.
citizens, the INS reported.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to increasing the speed of processing, INS has
raised the number of citizenship requests it considers annually,
Meissner said. The agency handled more than 1.25 million of the
approximately 2.6 million pending applications in fiscal year 1999,
compared to handling 610,547 during the prior year, the INS chief
said.
</P>
<P>
   Meissner attributed the INS' improved processing time to an
enhanced computer system, additional federal funding to handle
applications and the hiring of 200 more adjudicators.
</P>
<P>
   ``An avalanche of applications had overwhelmed understaffed
offices'' by last October, Meissner said. ``An agency needs to
react, and we've reacted.''
</P>
<P>
   INS has been under heavy pressure from members of Congress,
particularly those who represent large immigrant districts, to
expedite citizenship requests. Congress, at Meissner's request,
earmarked $175 million to the INS last year to help the agency
handle applications.
</P>
<P>
   This year the INS seeks an additional $124 million for
application processing. But President Clinton and Congress have yet
to reach accord on INS funding.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton this week vetoed funding legislation for the departments
of Justice, Commerce and State, saying the measure lacked
sufficient funds for police and for paying off the U.S. debt to the
United Nations. The INS is a Justice Department agency.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
