<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE HIGH ART OF SHOPPING
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   We launch our holiday guide with a Christmas tree ornament from
the Miles Kimball catalog: cell phone ornament, $4.98, ``3 1/2'' x
1'', has a display window and great details; lettered buttons,
antenna, power, send, and clear buttons.''
</P>
<P>
   Further suggestions for gift items in that warm and fuzzy
holiday spirit are welcomed.
</P>
<P>
   P.S.  &UR; Dina Bernardin &LR;  says that when her husband showed her the
new pants he'd bought at one of those outdoor-clothing specialists
in Berkeley, they discovered a used concert ticket stub in one
pocket. In the other was a piece of paper folded around a small
amount of marijuana.
</P>
<P>
   ``Also worth noting'' she writes; ``the folded piece of paper
was the previous owner's paycheck stub, with full name, address and
Social Security number. Should we send this person a citation from
the Stupid Police?'' Consider it done.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POWER PLAYS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Apparently  &UR; Frank Jordan &LR;  or  &UR; Clint Reilly &LR;  has paid to have
 &UR; President Clinton  &LR; do radio ads endorsing  &UR; Willie Brown &LR;  for
re-election,'' writes  &UR; Dario Oakley &LR; . ``Now, that's sneaky! This is
a political trick that would have made political trickster Dick
Tuck sit up and applaud with admiration.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Nancy Levine &LR;  suggests that ``If  &UR; Jimmy Carter &LR;  is successful
in winning  &UR; Patty Hearst &LR;  a pardon, maybe  &UR; Pete Rose  &LR; should give
Jimmy a call.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Armies of computer whiz kids must be on  &UR; Al Gore &LR; 's payroll.
When KQED-TV reporter  &UR; Scott Shafer &LR;  arrived at work he had 15
e-mails, ``sent in rapid-fire succession during a two-hour span
before and after last night's debate,'' rebutting Bradley and
boosting Gore on topics they discussed.
</P>
<P>
   _ During a Madison Square Garden concert in New York the other
night,  &UR; Bette Midler &LR;  said she wasn't surprised that  &UR; Elizabeth &LR; 
 &UR; Dole &LR;  had wanted to run for president. ``She was trying to get out
of the house, away from the horrors of Viagra. ... They never
actually tell you about the other side, about the person who's on
the receiving end.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; JUST SAYING NO &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The clothing house Swish, which is based in Rome, didn't use
 &UR; Naomi Campbell  &LR; for recent shows in Milan, reports W, and gave the
money it saved to an African relief organization, Amani. ``Instead
of dressing Naomi this season,'' said a Swish spokesman, ``we're
going to dress 16 Kenyan children.''
</P>
<P>
   The company made a symbolic presentation of the money to a
priest from Amani just before the show began. Then the models
started walking down the runway, to music ``that blended the voice
of  &UR; Pope John Paul II &LR;  with the sounds of a woman apparently in the
throes of ecstasy,'' said W. Whereupon the priest walked out. The
Archdiocese of Milan later issued a statement questioning Swish's
taste.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Organizers of the monthly bicycle revel Critical Mass, which
takes place on the last Friday of each month in San Francisco, have
put out a call for participants to show up in costume for
Halloween.
</P>
<P>
   _ Showtime has announced plans for ``Dirty Pictures,'' a movie
about the 1990 controversy over the showing of  &UR; Robert &LR; 
 &UR; Mapplethorpe  &LR; photos in the Cincinnati Contemporary Arts Center.
 &UR; James Woods &LR;  will play  &UR; Dennis Barrie &LR; , director of the museum, who
was indicted on (and eventually acquitted of) charges of pandering.
Woods told artnet.com that he is opposed to censorship, but that
``in an age of self-entitlement, I do wish people had a sense of
responsibility commensurate with their First Amendment rights.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Artist  &UR; Mark Kostabi &LR; , who lives alternate months in Rome and
New York, proudly told  &UR; Baird Jones &LR;  that he's been robbed in both
places a total of 25 times, and he's so careful about his
possessions nowadays that the latest thieves got only a box of
extra-large condoms, which he had to reorder ``directly from
Norway,'' where they are manufactured.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``I once wrote to Thomas Pynchon and asked for his permission to
write an opera based on `Gravity's Rainbow.' I didn't really expect
an answer from this famously silent man. However, a few weeks
later, a letter arrived. He graciously complimented me on my idea
and said of course I could do it; his only condition was that the
whole opera be scored for solo banjo.''
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR;   &LR; From Laurie Anderson's program notes for ``Songs and Stories
From `Moby Dick,''' at Zellerbach Hall this week.
