A1622 &Cx1f; gen-z
u f BC-STATES-WILDLIFE-NAT     10-28 0454
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-WILDLIFE-NAT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        BILL TO FUND VALLEY WILDLIFE REFUGE HANGS IN BALANCE
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Alex Canizares  
 &HT;    c. 1999 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Oct. 28 - An Interior Department spending bill that
funds the Lower Rio Grande National Wildlife Refuge and Corpus
Christi's coastal bend does not do enough for the environment,
according to President Clinton, who is expected to veto the measure
next week.
</P>
<P>
   The way the bill stands now, the wildlife refuge would receive
$2 million for land acquisition, a 25 percent increase over last
year's funding. It also includes $823,000 for the construction of a
wastewater treatment facility at the Padre Island National Seashore
at Corpus Christi.
</P>
<P>
   The president and Democrats don't like the bill because Congress
cut $196 million from the $442 million that Clinton requested for
the Land and Water Conservation Fund, which funds land acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of a veto, Congress would have to reconsider the
measure.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Solomon Ortiz, D-Corpus Christi, who had pushed other
lawmakers to fund the two projects, said both the refuge and the
water facility deserve to be included in whatever final spending
bill is approved.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to the economy, it brings a lot of tourism to
the area, and at the same time, you are working for the
environment,'' Ortiz said of the refuge.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Fish &AMP; Wildlife Service uses federal money to buy
property bordering on the 100,000 acre, four-county refuge. The
service and environmental organizations would like to acquire up to
132,000 acres, most of which is now farmland.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the principal (land tract) that we are interested in
finishing out now,'' said Mary Lou Campbell, an environment
advocate from Mercedes who is conservation chair for the Sierra
Club's Lower Rio Grande Valley. ``It's very important that congress
appropriate this money.''
</P>
<P>
   The refuge is one of the most biologically diverse areas in the
nation -- home to nearly 500 different species of birds.
</P>
<P>
   The area is threatened by the rampant clearing of trees so that
the land can be used for agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than 95 percent of the four-county area has been cleared
or altered,'' said Nancy Brown, public outreach specialist for the
U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service.
</P>
<P>
   The interior bill lacked funds for land acquisition at the Palo
Alto Battlefield National Historic Site, which has a battlefield
from the Mexican-American War.
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen whether Congress will add this money when
it takes reconsiders the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Ortiz said he was disappointed the historic site was overlooked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Budgets are tight,'' he said. ``But this is part of our
history, so we are going to try [to fund it].''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
