u f BC-JAPAN-NIKKO-NYT &LR;      10-28 0538
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-NIKKO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARGAIN-HUNTING INVESTORS POUNCE ON BANKRUPT NIKKO ELECTRIC  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ The vultures are coming! The vultures are coming! The
``vultures'' are investors who specialize in buying bankrupt and
distressed assets, and two of the top vultures are Rothschild
Recovery Fund, a private equity fund run by Rothschild Inc., and
Japan Recovery Capital Partners, which is managed by a joint
venture of Daiwa Securities and Sumitomo Bank.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, they are expected to announce plans for a
reorganization of Nikko Electric Industry Co., an automotive parts
supplier that has the distinction of being the first Japanese
company this century to be put into bankruptcy by its employees.
</P>
<P>
   Such investors, most of them Americans, have been circling Japan
for the last few years, but most have limited themselves to making
investments related to real estate.
</P>
<P>
   So Rothschild's move to take over Nikko Electric is yet another
foray by a foreigner that would have been unthinkable in the
Japanese economy of even two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this will open a new direction for other bankruptcies
and distressed corporations in Japan,'' said Wilbur Ross, senior
managing director of Rothschild Inc. and an eminence grise of the
U.S. bankruptcy system.
</P>
<P>
   But Ross and his partners intend to modify the standard U.S.
blueprint for reorganizing a bankrupt company. They are inviting
some of Nikko Electric's biggest suppliers, which include Delco
Remy International, Komatsu, Isuzu Motors and Mitsubishi Heavy
Industries, to become investors along with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would make it more like the Japanese system, where
customers and vendors traditionally have counter-invested in each
other,'' Ross said. ``We're trying to blend American techniques
with the historical way things are done in Japan.''
</P>
<P>
   The plan runs counter to current trends in Japan, where even the
most staid companies are starting to shed their
cross-shareholdings.
</P>
<P>
   Rothschild and Japan Recovery say, however, that giving Nikko's
customers a stake in the potential upside of the deal will insure
their good will _ and continued business.
</P>
<P>
   Whether they can coax Nikko Electric's lenders into writing off
a substantial portion of the outstanding debt may be a bigger
challenge, although Ross said the banks in general had been
supporting his plans.
</P>
<P>
   The Nikko Electric bankruptcy is known in Japan because of the
unusual way the company ended up under the administration of a
court-appointed trustee. Japan is one of the few countries in the
world where employees can petition the court to put their company
under its care without management's agreement; Nikko Electric's
employees did just that earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   They contended that the company, which has annual revenue of
roughly 90 billion yen ($864 million ) and about 15 billion yen
($144 million) in liabilities, was badly mismanaged and too focused
on gaining market share at the expense of products.
</P>
<P>
   After going to the company and doing an assessment of the
employees' claims, the judges at the Tokyo District Court decided
to dismiss the management and appoint Jinjiro Suzuki, a lawyer, as
trustee.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-99 1908EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
