<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ATLFANS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    No time of mourning for Atlanta sports fans
 &HT;    By Matt Kempner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Time for a brief pause in weeping over the World
Series.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta has captured a bevy of top sports events in the 1990s
and more is on the way, from the Super Bowl next year to the NCAA
Men's Basketball Final Four in 2002 and again in 2007. And
Atlanta's boosters say they will bid for more, including The
Goodwill Games in 2005 and Super Bowls in 2005 and 2006.
</P>
<P>
   ``Atlanta has every right to be proud,'' says Frank Stadulis,
president of the United Sports Fans of America, a Florida-based
national association for fans. ``They are overall a fan-friendly
city.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1990s made for a remarkable turnaround in a city dubbed
Losersville by Sports Illustrated in 1988. The magazine was taking
aim at what up to then had been the pathetic performances of
Atlanta's professional sports teams.
</P>
<P>
   Things have changed. This year, the Atlanta Falcons made it to
the Super Bowl. The Atlanta Braves have been in five of the last
eight World Series, though they have a record there of 1-4.
</P>
<P>
   ``You name me another city that has had two of its teams in the
finals in the same year,'' says Gary Stokan, president of the
Atlanta Sports Council, which has helped lead the charge to host
more events.
</P>
<P>
   But Stokan likes best talking about sporting events that have
come to Atlanta regardless of which teams are playing.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta, according to the local sports council, is the sports
capital of the world. That's the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``No other city in the world has had the Olympics, the Final
Four and the Super Bowl,'' Stokan says, pausing only briefly to
acknowledge that the Final Four and the Super Bowl aren't played in
other countries. ``Debate me. Look at the events we are bringing
in. Look at the economic impact.''
</P>
<P>
   The sports council says that in the five years leading up to
2003 the area will bathe in $4.5 billion worth of economic impact
from regular season games to big name events like the Super Bowl,
the PGA Championship and Major League Baseball's All-Star Game.
That's not much less than the estimated impact of the 1996 Summer
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   There are other reasons this is good for metro Atlanta, Stokan
says.
</P>
<P>
   Except for the Super Bowl, where tickets are notoriously
difficult for regular fans to come by, metro Atlantans will have a
chance to see top sporting events up close if they can pony up the
ticket money.
</P>
<P>
   Top sporting events also usually capture prime TV audiences.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's priceless,'' Stokan says. ``There is no other way Atlanta
could get the kind of positive national and international media
exposure.''
</P>
<P>
   Talk of the value of TV images should be taken with a grain of
salt, says John Bevilaqua, an Atlanta sports marketing consultant
who sat on the sports council shortly after it was formed in the
mid 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I question how much substantive value it really does have,''
says Bevilaqua, though he does see it as generally positive.
</P>
<P>
   As for the pronouncement that Atlanta is the world's, or even
the nation's, top sports city, Bevilaqua says, ``We have had some
pretty good success, but so have some other cities.''
</P>
<P>
   He cites Los Angeles, New York, Chicago, Denver, Phoenix, even
Orlando, which has the Disney sports complex.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sorry, Atlanta,'' says Mark Jaffe, executive director of the
Greater New York Chamber of Commerce. ``Not only are we the world
champions of baseball but we are the sporting-event capital of the
world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just by sheer number of teams alone and events we should claim
that title above any city,'' says Jaffe, who figures the New York
metropolitan area has at least 10 professional sports teams.
</P>
<P>
   The Sporting News came up with its own list of best sports
cities earlier this year. Based on won-lost records of major sports
teams, the publication concluded that New York is at the top,
followed by Dallas, Denver and then Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone has his own measures. Last summer the Travel Industry
Association of America found that Atlanta tied with Chicago in
attracting the largest percentage of the nation's sports-related
travelers in the previous five years.
</P>
<P>
   The competition to host big sporting events has grown far more
intense since the 1984 Olympics in Los Angeles highlighted the
potential economic and image payoffs from sports. In 1985, when
Atlanta created its sports council, there were 10 similar
organizations in the nation. Now, there are more than 200.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta boosters have their hopes set on the coming decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are calling it the decade of the destiny where we truly
will be recognized as the sports capital of the world,'' says
Stokan of the sports council, which recruits businesses and local
governments to put up money to host events.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to events Atlanta has already been selected to host,
Stokan says local boosters will bid for more, including:
</P>
<P>
   The Super Bowl in 2005 and 2006. Bids go out in May.
</P>
<P>
   The Goodwill Games in 2005. Bidding begins either later this
year or early next year.
</P>
<P>
   NCAA Men's and Women's soccer finals in 2002 and 2003.
</P>
<P>
   The ESPN X Games in 2001 and 2002.
</P>
<P>
   For some of the biggest events, like the Super Bowl, Stokan says
he expects Atlanta's top competitors will be New Orleans, Los
Angeles, Indianapolis and New York.
</P>
<P>
   There are still a few holes in what Atlanta has to offer
sportswise, Stokan acknowledges. It doesn't yet have the facilities
necessary to attract a Major League Soccer team or top outdoor
track and field events. The sports council is hoping to win backing
to add professional soccer facilities near Stone Mountain.
</P>
<P>
   Add continued financial support from business and government,
and Atlanta might be able to continue hosting big sporting events.
Of course, that doesn't guarantee some things _ like the Braves
winning a World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
