<SLUG> BC-KOREA-DAEWOO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS LIABILITIES MOUNT,   THE REORGANIZATION OF DAEWOO BOGS DOWN  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)   By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Efforts to overhaul Daewoo, the huge South Korean
conglomerate that the Korean government pulled back from the brink
of bankruptcy this summer, are losing momentum.
</P>
<P>
   Investors and analysts are increasingly skeptical that the
government can meet its self-imposed year-end deadline for
beginning a solid reorganization of the group.
</P>
<P>
   Plans to sell Daewoo's assets are bogging down. Creditors are
bickering among themselves, as well as with the company and the
government.
</P>
<P>
   ``Daewoo is so much bigger, more troubled and more inaccessible
than any of the other companies that have been sold here that it's
hard for people to come to grips with it,'' said Taesoo Jung, head
of Arthur D. Little's Seoul office.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the company's liabilities seem to keep
growing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only now are the government and the lenders starting to
appreciate the enormity of the probable discrepancy between asset
values and liabilities,'' said Wilbur L. Ross Jr., senior managing
director of Rothschild Inc. and an adviser to and investor in
several South Korean companies and financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Concerns about Daewoo have pulled the benchmark South Korean
stock index down 17 percent since the group flirted with bankruptcy
at the end of July, even though the nation's economy continues to
rebound.
</P>
<P>
   Korea First Bank, which is leading the group representing
Daewoo's domestic creditors, recently finished valuing the assets
and liabilities of Daewoo Corp., the group's trading and
construction business. Its research suggested that 11.8 trillion
won, or $9.8 billion at current exchange rates, of the $24 billion
in assets the unit said in August it had were viable.
</P>
<P>
   The corporation's debts, on the other hand, came to 26.3
trillion won, or $21.95 billion, more than double the assets.
</P>
<P>
   Roughly 85 percent of Daewoo's debts to foreign lenders were
made to Daewoo Corp. and Daewoo Motor Co., the group's
car-manufacturing business. ``The principal issue for foreign
creditors is whether Daewoo Corporation gets treated fairly or
not,'' said Jeffrey D. Jones, a lawyer at Kim &AMP; Chang in Seoul, who
represents many foreign companies doing business in South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   He said many loans were made to Daewoo Corp. that were then
funneled to other Daewoo group projects that might have had more
value than the corporation itself.
</P>
<P>
   Daewoo's financial crisis was the subject of a meeting at the
Imperial Hotel in Tokyo Thursday, attended by 125 people
representing 71 of Daewoo's 200 foreign bankers, bondholders and
other lenders. Daewoo and its advisers at Ernst &AMP; Young sought to
lay out to the creditors the assets and liabilities of the 12 major
group affiliates selected for reorganization.
</P>
<P>
   Daewoo is trying to persuade its foreign creditors to freeze
repayment of the roughly $7 billion in debts they hold to give it
some breathing room.
</P>
<P>
   But the committee that represents those lenders, headed by Chase
Manhattan, has insisted on veto power over Daewoo's plans.
</P>
<P>
   Both Daewoo and its Korean creditors, whom it owes more than $50
billion, are reluctant to give the foreign creditors so much
influence. After the formal presentation Thursday, the foreign
representatives who attended were invited to break into small
groups for discussions with representatives from Daewoo's Korean
creditors. But the meeting still resulted in a stalemate.
</P>
<P>
   A statement issued by the foreign bankers' committee said this
occurred because ``domestic banks were proceeding with
restructuring plans for the affected Daewoo entities without the
active involvement of foreign creditors.''
</P>
<P>
   But the foreigners face an even bigger hurdle among themselves.
Because loans to South Korean companies are not typically extended
by a syndicate of lenders led by a bank that makes decisions for
the group, each foreign lender is effectively an independent
operator.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to reach a consensus among 200 lenders, owed an average
of $28 million each, is a herculean task.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mechanics of achieving even a consensus _ and technically
you need unanimity _ are going to be horrific,'' Ross said, ``and
therefore it raises a very significant question about what is going
to come out of this meeting.''
</P>
<P>
   That matter aside, there are signs that sales of Daewoo assets
are not proceeding as smoothly as the government had anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   A widely publicized sale of Daewoo's electronics group to Walid
Alomar &AMP; Associates, a private equity fund in Beverly Hills, has
foundered since the deal was announced two months ago. Daewoo's
domestic creditors expressed doubt that Walid Alomar had assembled
the money to complete the deal and added that it had placed too low
a value on the assets it wanted to purchase.
</P>
<P>
   Alomar has argued that the creditors have an unrealistic
expectation about the value of what they are trying to sell.
``We're waiting to see what the creditors feel the company is worth
and how our deal relates to that value,'' said Steven Kalabat, a
Walid Alomar director.
</P>
</TEXT>
