<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-NOTES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NASCAR-NOTEBOOK
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The NASCAR world also was saddened by Monday's plane crash that
killed Payne Stewart. Also aboard the aircraft were a pair of
business agents: Robert Fraley, who represented Joe Gibbs, owner of
the No. 18 and 20 teams; and Van Arden, who represented Ray
Evernham, former crew chief of Jeff Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a tremendous tragedy, and our thoughts and prayers are
with their families,'' Evernham said. ``(Arden and Fraley) did a
lot for NASCAR and our sport.''
</P>
<P>
   Halloween treat
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR gave Winston Cup drivers a treat in their Halloween bags:
No race this weekend after 12 consecutive weeks of races. Points
leader Dale Jarrett plans to go trick-or-treating with his kids.
Jeff Gordon and his wife plan to catch up on the latest movies.
Dale Earnhardt will celebrate his wife's birthday. Steve Park will
trade his stock car for a motorcycle. ``I just want to relax a
little bit,'' Park said. ``Take a deep breath, then come back and
finish out these last (three) races.''. . .
</P>
<P>
   Bill Elliott, Mike Skinner, Jeremy Mayfield and Ricky Craven
will test on Monday and Tuesday at Atlanta Motor Speedway in
preparation for Winston Cup's final race of the season on Nov. 21
at the track. . . . A.J. Foyt has succeeded with his intentions of
attracting a ton of attention for his full-time entry into Winston
Cup next year, but it is for the wrong reasons. The 2000 Daytona
500 is slightly more than three months away, and Foyt has not found
a driver.
</P>
<P>
   Elvis in Memphis
</P>
<P>
   There will likely be an Elvis Sighting in Sunday's Busch race at
Memphis Motorsports Park. Hut Stricklin, whose day job is driving
of the No. 38 Ford, also is well-known as an Elvis impersonator.
``It all started a few years ago at one of my New Year's Eve
parties,'' Stricklin said. ``I dressed up as Elvis and sang a few
songs, and since then everyone thinks I'm an Elvis fanatic.'' . . .
Ron Young of Conyers has a simple goal for the Sam's Town 250: Just
make the field. Young is trying to qualify for the first time in a
Busch event after 10 years of racing in the Slim Jim All-Pro
Series. ``This is our first experience at this level, so making the
show and running a few laps would be a big accomplishment for us,''
said Young, 29, who will also attempt to qualify the No. 71 Chevy
for the season-ending race in Miami on Nov. 13.
</P>
<P>
   Nerve-wracking race
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR might have inscribed Dale Jarrett's name on the Winston
Cup trophy, but it can't do the same for with the Craftmans Truck
Series. Points leader Greg Biffle has two other drivers, Jack
Sprague and Dennis Setzer, within 25 points heading into the last
race at California Speedway on Saturday. ``I have fun racing all
the guys, and this just goes to show you how competitive this
series is,'' Biffle said. ``I certainly hope that it is the three
of us duking it out in California with 25 laps to go. That would be
the ultimate goal, I think, for all three of us to be in position
to win the thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Extra laps
</P>
<P>
   Goodyear has removed its tires from CART and IRL racing, but the
tire company remains firmly committed to stock-car racing. ``(Our
withdrawal from open-wheel racing) will have no impact on our
strong relationship with NASCAR,'' said Stu Grant of Goodyear. ``In
fact, it may even serve to strengthen the relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
