r s BC-FBC-QUNICYCARTER-COX     10-28 0607
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-QUNICYCARTER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Carter's silent before Gator game
 &HT;    By Chip Towers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ Georgia's Quincy Carter hasn't said a word this
week. But the sophomore quarterback's silence speaks volumes.
</P>
<P>
   Carter, the 10th-ranked Bulldogs' marquee player and the most
frequently interviewed member of the team, went to coach Jim Donnan
on Monday night and asked to be excused this week from his media
responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   He has no gripe with newspapers or television stations. Carter
told Donnan he wanted to dedicate his time and energy to preparing
for Saturday's game against fifth-ranked Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `What are the chances of me not doing (any
interviews) this week?' I said, `Pretty good; I'm the coach,'''
Donnan said.
</P>
<P>
   That shows how important beating Florida is to Carter. But his
desire has nothing to do with a deep-seated dislike of the Gators
or with Georgia's lack of success in the series this decade. For
Carter, his reputation is on the line.
</P>
<P>
   Going into the Tennessee game Oct. 9, Carter pointed out that he
was 0-for-3 against the ``Big Three,'' Tennessee, Florida and
Georgia Tech, and noted that Georgia quarterbacks ultimately are
judged on how they perform in those games.
</P>
<P>
   The Volunteers manhandled the Bulldogs 37-20 as Carter was
chased all over the field, sacked three times and pressured
countless others. Despite the harassment, Carter completed 20 of 34
passes for 228 yards and two touchdowns, and he was not
intercepted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you, I've seen Quincy play going all the way back to
Southwest DeKalb High School, and he's the most unbelievably poised
guy I've ever seen,'' Georgia running back Jasper Sanks said.
``Nothing gets to him, even when things aren't going good. And when
we really need something to happen, that's when he's going to make
a play. He's a warrior.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia and Carter got through the next two games unscathed, and
Carter put together his best game of the season Saturday against
Kentucky. He passed for 304 yards and two touchdowns and rushed for
87 yards as the Bulldogs rolled up 577 yards on offense en route to
a 49-34 victory.
</P>
<P>
   But it was clear immediately after the game that Carter's mind
was already on the Gators.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played great on offense, but we've got to put away those
turnovers,'' he said. ``We can't beat a team like Florida making
mistakes like that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs had five turnovers against Kentucky, including a
40-yard return of a Carter interception that led to a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   The Gators' defensive preparations this week have focused on
Carter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're concerned about him just like we were Tee Martin,''
coach Steve Spurrier said. ``They both can pass and run, and that
can present a lot of problems when you go against somebody mobile
like that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gators lead the SEC with 28 sacks for minus-200 yards. But
Donnan did not seemed overwhelmed with their ability to pressure
the passer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they've played against a quarterback who can
negate the rush like ours can,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Seven games into the season, Carter's Heisman Trophy candidacy
seems a faint memory. But it would get a boost with a spectacular
performance in Saturday's nationally televised game if Georgia
wins.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't have been nearly the team we have been the last
two years without (Carter),'' Donnan said. ``Just looking at the
stats doesn't do him justice. If you watch tape on him, it's just
unbelievable some of the things he does. We just need to give him
some help.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
