r s BC-GLF-TOURLEDE-COX     10-28 0652
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-TOURLEDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Emotions running high at Tour Championship
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ No shot could have been struck to approach the moment
established in an early morning mist at Champions Golf Club
Thursday. Commenced and then culminated by the solemn sounds of a
lone bagpiper, a stirring memorial service to Payne Stewart on the
No. 1 teebox will be the 1999 Tour Championship's lasting vision.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Lehman, who gave the eulogy, choked out the words in
grief-stricken fragments, sobbing but somehow getting through it.
Many of the other 28 competing players were seated in front of the
podium, some fighting back tears and others failing to. The
bagpiper played ``Going Home,'' a Scottish hymn, in his errie
entrance through the mist, then ``Amazing Grace'' at the finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``Payne was a very emotional guy,'' Lehman said. ``He loved to
laugh and he wasn't ashamed to cry. So I'm not going to be ashamed
of my tears this morning.''
</P>
<P>
   Lehman said he was up all night worrying about his remarks,
afraid he would ``completely collapse, blubbering, and not be able
to say a word.'' But Lehman's words were as soothing as they were
sad.
</P>
<P>
   ``Six people got on a Lear plane Monday and today there's wives
without husbands, there's kids without fathers, there's a golf
world missing a hero, a tour missing a great champion and a bunch
of people missing a great friend,'' he said. ``All of us were a
part of Payne and Payne was definitely part of us. And when he died
on Monday, a big part of us died, too.''
</P>
<P>
   When they finally got around to golf, which wasn't easy for
anyone, another of Stewart's close friends, Sea Island's Davis Love
III, took the lead at 7-under par 99 after 27 holes of the $5
million event. Play will be suspended today for services in
Orlando, then resumed with 27 holes on Saturday and 18 on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The only other golf-related story of any meaning became Tiger
Woods, who trailed by a stroke at 6-under, injuring his left wrist
and shoulder on the 15th hole, while trying to advance his ball
after it came to rest in front of a large rock.
</P>
<P>
   Although Lehman somehow regrouped after the service to shoot
even par for 27 holes, he admitted, ``I feel like I'm running on
empty emotionally. There's not much gas left in the tank.''
</P>
<P>
   All the players wore black ribbons, some an extra swatch of
tartan fabric pinned to caps or bags.
</P>
<P>
   Love and Justin Leonard had ``PS'' on the back of their caps.
</P>
<P>
   Comfortable with the decision to play, Commissioner Tim Finchem
said, ``We play in testimony to Payne. We hope that by showcasing
his absence on this golf course and among his peers, we will bring
focus to all of his fans around the world that at his core, Payne
Stewart, the champion, is irreplaceable.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Estes offered a bizarre, symbolic gesture for Stewart. On
his opening shot at the 10th teebox, he struck the ball with his
putter, moving it 16 feet. Turning around, he said softly, ``The
first shot's for Payne.'' Estes hit a 3-wood second shot from there
and double-bogeyed, but finished 2-under. Estes said he was
symbolizing the 15-foot putt Stewart made at Pinehurst in June to
win the U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   While Love said he admired Estes' thoughts, he added, ``I don't
think Payne wants us throwing away strokes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a tough time gathering up enough emotion to play,'' said
Love, who lost his father in a 1988 plane crash. ``When that little
airplane flew over with that banner (saying `We will remember you,
Payne.'), I had a little 4-footer straight in, and I think it took
me about 10 mintues to putt. You shouldn't have to play golf with
tears on your eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Andy Martinez, Lehman's caddie, ``I've never felt so
unmotivated on a golf course. I don't care if we were playing for
$50 million.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
