<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1657 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-NFL-MATCHUPS-2TAKES-N     10-28 1182
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NFL-MATCHUPS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL MATCHUPS FOR WEEK 8 
</HEADLINE>
  (A Macintosh graphic of this chart has been sent electronically to
NYT graphics clients. Call 888-603-1036 for information.) 
(jt) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; GAME OF THE WEEK (MONDAY NIGHT) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Seattle (4-2) vs. Green Bay (4-2)
</P>
<P>
   Mike Holmgren was 84-42 in seven seasons as Green Bay's head
coach, a .667 winning percentage, second only to Vince Lombardi's
.758. But it got boring for Holmgren. He became itchy. He wanted to
run his own team with total authority and Seattle was happy to
oblige. Through six games he has the Seahawks moving in splendid
direction and now returns to Green Bay for the first time. He will
find Ray Rhodes in his old job and several familiar faces,
particularly Brett Favre at quarterback. Holmgren helped to mold
Favre. Favre wants to show Holmgren what he now misses. Expect a
huge game from Favre (he has passed for 608 yards, second most in
the National Football Conference) and an equally large one from
back Dorsey Levens (he averages 4.0 yards per carry and has caught
26 passes). Watch end Green Bay end Keith McKenzie (5 sacks)
explode for big plays. Watch the Packers and their delirious fans
stick it to Holmgren. Packers, 30-17.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SUNDAY, 1 P.M. GAMES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo (4-3) vs. Baltimore (2-4)
</P>
<P>
   These teams have never played and both enter off losses, Buffalo
by 10 points at Seattle and Baltimore by 27 at home against Kansas
City. Tony Banks, the former Rams' quarterback, makes his first
Baltimore start. The Ravens certainly have a capable defense.
Baltimore has not allowed a 100-yard rusher or receiver this
season. Its 3.1 average yards per carry allowed ranks second in the
American Football Conference to only San Diego's 2.9. If Banks can
play turnover-free, the Ravens can swipe this game. He will
struggle early but flourish late.
</P>
<P>
   Ravens, 17-16.
</P>
<P>
   Jacksonville (5-1) vs. Cincinnati (1-6)
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't play very well. They got after us on a lot of long
plays. The one long play we had double coverage and he still got
out. You can't do that to a heck of a player. So many thing went
wrong I don't know where to begin.'' That was Bruce Coslet, the
Bengals' head coach, trying to explain how Colts' receiver Marvin
Harrison ripped his pass defense and how the Bengals were so
hapless in their 31-10 loss last week to Indianapolis. Coslet is
running out of explanations. And excuses. And time.
</P>
<P>
   Jaguars, 29-10.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego (4-2) vs. Kansas City (4-2)
</P>
<P>
   Erik Kramer, the Chargers' quarterback, has completed a spiffy
19 of 25 fourth-quarter passes for 240 yards. Nice numbers. Problem
is, overall, he has completed only 76 of 138 passes and has thrown
only 2 touchdown passes and 9 interceptions. That ruins the
Chargers' wonderful defense, one that has not allowed a 100-yard
rusher in 25 consecutive games. Kramer will likely give way to Jim
Harbaugh and he will face a pass defense that has gained at least
two interceptions in each of its last five games. San Diego won the
first meeting between these divisional rivals, 21-14, earlier this
month. This is Kansas City's time as it surprisingly gains sole
control of first place in the AFC West.
</P>
<P>
   Chiefs, 21-14.
</P>
<P>
   Carolina (2-4) vs. Atlanta (1-6)
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons have disintegrated. They have become a shell of
their Super Bowl team. They are committing turnovers at an alarming
rate, are gaining only 288 yards of offense per game and even
sure-footed kicker Morten Andersen is struggling, having connected
on only six of 11 field goal attempts. Their meltdown on Monday
night against Pittsburgh _ where the Falcons twice in the fourth
quarter were inside the Pittsburgh 5 with a chance to win but could
not _likely sapped the life from this team. It requires a major
effort from the Atlanta coaching staff to keep this team from
completely sinking. For at least another week, there are few
answers.
</P>
<P>
   Panthers, 24-21.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago (3-4) vs. Washington (4-2)
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Synder, the Washington owner, was seen storming toward
the Redskins' locker room after their debacle in Dallas, a 38-20
loss. Synder was not happy. After a 30-minute meeting with Norv
Turner, the Washington head coach, Synder exited with a red,
flushed face. Synder was not happy. The Redskins strode into Dallas
full of bravado and left embarrassed and perplexed. They collapsed
in a big game and now return home to heal open wounds. Chicago
gains the return of quarterback Shane Matthews but it matters
little. Washington is on a mission.
</P>
<P>
   Redskins, 33-17.
</P>
<P>
   Giants (4-3) vs. Philadelphia (2-5)
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles have two fewer victories than Washington but have
allowed 38 fewer points than Washington. Philadelphia can play
defense. It leads the league in takeaways with 19. Its 14
interceptions are second-most in the league. But on offense, behind
quarterback Doug Pederson, Philadelphia has crawled. The Giants
were lucky to beat the Eagles the first time _ a raw 16-15 victory
in New York earlier this month _ and will need another champion
effort from its defense to repeat the feat. It gets it, especially
from linebacker Jessie Armstead, roaring toward another pro bowl
season.
</P>
<P>
   Giants, 17-13.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland (0-7) vs. New Orleans (1-5)
</P>
<P>
   Did you know the Browns have committed the fewest penalties in
the AFC? They also have the fewest victories _ zilch. Fewer
mistakes usually means more victories but the Browns problems are
complex. Their offense averages only 198.7 yards gained per game.
Their defense allows 405.9 yards per game. They are minus 8 in
turnover differential. Cleveland can begin to look toward next
year's draft, another No. 1 pick, and free agent help that can plug
holes. New Orleans, too, is a team with complex issues. Though
Ricky Williams leads all rookie NFC backs with 403 rushing yards,
his injuries hampered his early-season impact. The Saints are
recovering from a 31-3 beating at the Giants and appear in
disarray. This could get ugly, a game featuring two teams with one
total victory. New Orleans postpones expansion Cleveland's
first-ever victory.
</P>
<P>
   Saints, 23-13.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis (6-0) vs. Tennessee (5-1)
</P>
<P>
   This is a break-out game for both teams, a marquee matchup and
attention-grabber that neither franchise or it players are
accustomed to gaining in recent years. The balls should fly high
and often, especially if Steve McNair returns from his back injury
at quarterback for the Titans. The Rams have scored 217 points, the
Titans 142. Thus, the Rams are far more explosive. It will be a
tantalizing matchup at running back where Marshall Faulk of the
Rams battles Eddie George of the Titans. Two factors will nudge the
game Tennessee's way: 1) The Titans' battle-tested early season
where five of their six games have been decided by 3 or fewer
points (they are 4-1 in those game) and the fact they have erased
second-half deficits in four of their five victories. 2) Tennessee
comes off a bye week, having enjoyed two weeks of preparation. It's
a thriller.
</P>
<P>
   Titans, 25-24.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SUNDAY, 4 P.M. GAMES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Miami (5-1) vs. Oakland (4-3)
</P>
<P>
   Miami starts Damon Huard at quarterback again, on the road this
time against Oakland. The Raiders will be ready and waiting. In
facing cornerbacks Charles Woodson and Eric Allen, Huard will be
overmatched. Oakland will make a statement early, shoving Tyrone
Wheatley right at the Dolphins and attempting to become the first
team to score a rushing touchdown on them. That is a statistic that
the Raiders simply will not let stand. The Raiders receivers vs.
the Miami secondary is also favorable for Oakland. Nearly
everywhere the Raiders look, they find matchups that they like.
</P>
<P>
   Raiders, 23-16.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas (4-2) vs. Indianapolis (4-2)
</P>
<P>
   Are the Colts all grown up and ready for Dallas? That is what
this game is all about _ growing pains. Indianapolis owns the
league's best passing game, averaging 277.2 passing yards per game.
It ranks fourth in total offense at 365.0 average yards gained per
game. It has outscored its opponents 41-9 in the first quarter. The
matchup of receiver Marvin Harrison vs. Dallas cornerback Deion
Sanders will be a joy. This will be a signature game for the Colts.
Dallas, though, won't make it easy.
</P>
<P>
   Colts, 22-20.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota (3-4) vs. Denver (2-5)
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota appears to have found its groove, scoring 40 points on
the 49ers. The Vikings' 147 first downs gained (89 passing) are the
most of any NFC team. Minnesota is 3-1 in its last four road games
vs. AFC teams and its new quarterback, Jeff George, has 5 touchdown
passes, 2 interceptions and a 119.3 quarterback rating. Though
Denver lost a close game last week at New England, it will rebound
at home. What turns this game is the Broncos' ability to rush
George, creating havoc and turnovers. Watch Denver's rookie kick
returner Chris Watson, exciting, elusive and dangerous with a 27.9
kickoff return average.
</P>
<P>
   Broncos, 27-25.
</P>
<P>
   New England (5-2) vs. Arizona (2-4)
</P>
<P>
   This is a game Arizona could win with Jake Plummer at
quarterback. It is a game they can't win with Dave Brown at
quarterback. Brown starts for the injured Plummer and faces a team
still celebrating its big victory last week over Denver that
stopped a Denver hex over New England. Now the Patriots travel to
Arizona and will start slowly and sluggishly. They are depleted at
linebacker but have enough left to deal with Brown. Tight end Ben
Coates (10 catches, 3 touchdowns in three career games vs. Arizona)
usually gives the Cardinals fits.
</P>
<P>
   Patriots, 19-17.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SUNDAY NIGHT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay (3-3) vs. Detroit (4-2)
</P>
<P>
   Tony Dungy, the Tampa Bay head coach, has seen enough of
quarterback Trent Dilfer. After a victory, albeit a ho-hum 6-3
victory over Chicago last week, Dungy benched Dilfer. Eric Zeier is
the new Tampa Bay starter. This is not a game for a frolicking
debut. Detroit is solid at home and in prime time games where the
lights shine bright. They are eager to show the nation how they
have overcome the loss of Barry Sanders to leap into first place in
the NFC Central. Expect a strong game from Lions' quarterback,
Charlie Batch. At running back, with Ron Rivers injured and out,
Greg Hill will produce. A glimmering victory for Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Lions, 20-9.
</P>
</TEXT>
