<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Oct. 29 and thereafter. For questions about stories, please contact
Lori Stassi at (818) 713-3705.
</P>
<P>
   BUYOUT-LAUSD (Los Angeles) _ (story will move late) A power
struggle over Los Angeles Unified leadership peaks with the school
board vote to buy out Superintendent Ruben Zacarias or fire him if
he refuses to leave. Zacarias, at a news conference, vowed to fight
any attempt to remove him from his $188,000-a-year-job. Citing
President Harry S Truman, he said that he will stay in the kitchen
because he can stand the heat. During hte late-afternoon and
evening board meeting, members are expected to name former Pasadena
school district Ramon Cortines as interim superintendent, pending a
nationwide search for a new leader. The board also will consider
the appointment of Howard Miller as chief operating officer. Dozens
are expected to speak against the move. By Greg Gittrich and Rick
Orlov (Will move on the ``a'' national and ``n'' California news
wires.)
</P>
<P>
   CORTENES-LAUSD (Los Angeles) _ Ramon C. Cortines, the
front-runner for Los Angeles Unified superintendent, has a history
of run ins with school boards and political leaders over control,
and he faces a lawsuit from his tenure in Pasadena. He was
chancellor of New York City schools until a run-in with the mayor
over who runs the city. He was superintendent of Pasadena schools,
until the board fired him when he refused to work with a newly
hired deputy superintendent. Cortines is being sued by the parents
of a boy who was molested by a track coach in Pasadena. The suit
claims Cortines was present during a meeting during which the
molestation allegations were discussed, but the information was
never passed to the police. By Sherry Joe Crosby (Will move on the
``a'' national and ``n'' California news wires.)
</P>
<P>
   SKULL-AUCTION (Los Angeles) _ Just in time for Halloween, a
75-million-year-old dinosaur skull, a fake one used in ``Jurassic
Park'' and a menagerie of taxidermy from the Fillmore Museum of
Natural History are on the auction block. A preview of items
including those from the Fillmore Museum of Natural History are on
display Friday. By Amy Raisin (Will move on the ``a'' national and
``n'' California news wires.)
</P>
<P>
   PARTNER-BENEFITS (Los Angeles) _ A city panel on Thursday moved
to broaden its own requirements on benefits to domestic partners to
include companies that do business with Los Angeles. Under a
recommendation from the City Council's Personnel Committee, all
firms that do business with the city and offer benefits to workers
and their spouses will be required to make those available to those
in partnership relationships. By Rick Orlov (Will move on the ``a''
national, ``n'' California and ``f'' financial news wires.) &QL;
</P>
