<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-JETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAEL'S EL AL OPTS TO BUY JETS FROM BOTH U.S. AND EUROPEAN
MANUFACTURERS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wash.)   (bl) 
 By WILLIAM A. ORME Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ After 10 months of internal debate over whether it
should buy its next jets from Boeing or Airbus, El Al, Israel's
national airline, has come up with a Solomonic solution: It will
purchase three Boeing 777s and three or four Airbus A330s.
</P>
<P>
   The unexpected decision, made in a marathon board meeting that
concluded early Thursday, ends a battle that pitted the United
States against the European Union and the airline's management
against its politically appointed board.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got a good price, we got the best aircraft for our needs,
and we hope we made everybody happy,'' said El Al spokesman Nachman
Kleiman.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing, the Seattle-based aviation giant that built every
current plane in El Al's fleet, was favored by the company chairman
and its board and, it was widely believed, by the Israeli
government. Airbus, the European consortium that is Boeing's only
rival, was reportedly favored by El Al's professional managers on
the grounds of relative cost and access to the West European
market. The company and Israeli leaders were lobbied intensively on
the sale by senior U.S. and European government officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``The decisions were reached on the basis of professional
statistics and figures which were set before the decision makers
and did not reflect any outside influences whatsoever,'' the
airline said.
</P>
<P>
   The hotly contested contract had been presented byEl Al as a
choice between three wide-body Boeing 777s and an Airbus package of
two two-engine A330s and two four-engine A340s, for a purchase of
about $400 million. Instead, the company will buy from both
companies and spend up to $700 million, an expenditure it said was
justified by a re-evaluation of the potential cash flow from
operating the new aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies had argued that keeping the purchase all with one
brand of airplane would cut maintenance and pilot training costs,
and many industry analysts agreed.
</P>
<P>
   Both aircraft manufacturers had cut prices in making final
offers to El Al earlier this week, and both had pledged to spend at
least half the value of the order on suppliers and subcontractors
in Israel's aviation industry.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing sweetened the deal further by awarding El Al a new $40
million contract for overhauling jets owned or leased by Boeing, El
Al disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   The Boeing purchase was authorized immediately, and the planes
are expected to be delivered in 2001. The El Al board will convene
in two weeks to approve the purchase of either three or four Airbus
planes, with delivery by 2003.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-99 1930EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991028.0382 </DOCNO>
