<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 19:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1662 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-CLINTONNIGERIA29-COX     10-28 0631
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTONNIGERIA29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON PLEDES ASSISTANCE TO NIGERIAN PRESIDENT
 &HT;    By Bob Deans
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton welcomed the leader of Nigeria's
fledgling democracy to the White House on Thursday, saying the
first steps away from military rule in Africa's most populous
nation sent a signal across the developing world.
</P>
<P>
   Saying that ``Nigeria is a pivot point on which the future of
all Africa and much of the world will turn,'' Clinton pledged to
assist the new government of President Olusegun Obasanjo with
efforts to step up U.S. foreign aid, trade and investment in
Africa's most populous nation.
</P>
<P>
   Obasanjo's election last February ended more than 15 years of
often harsh autocratic control of Nigeria, one of this country's
largest suppliers of crude oil. It was viewed by many analysts as
the most significant political development in Africa since the 1994
toppling of apartheid rule in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   With Obasanjo standing by in long, flowing traditional Nigerian
attire, Clinton told reporters at a White House news conference
that Obasanjo's government ``has signaled a new day for Nigeria,
and new hope for Africa _ a fitting capstone to a decade of
remarkable democratic revolutions from
</P>
<P>
   Poland to South Africa, to the important transition now underway
in Indonesia.''
</P>
<P>
   Obasanjo, a former military officer who headed Nigeria's
government from 1976 until 1979 following the assassination of the
former head of state, spent three years in prison for opposing the
military dictatorship of Sani Abacha.
</P>
<P>
   Obasanjo was released after Abacha's sudden death under
mysterious circumstances last year. A caretaker government pledged
democratic elections, which Obasanjo won earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that democracy is a process and not an event,''
said British-educated Obasanjo, speaking in English.
</P>
<P>
   He asked for Clinton's help, though, in seeking forgiveness of
Nigeria's foreign debt, which Obasanjo estimated at up to $30
billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot talk of being able to do what we need to do to
nurture, to sustain democracy, and to give our people democracy
dividend, bearing the burden of debt that is hanging over us at
this point in time,'' said Obasanjo.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton countered, though, that the best Nigeria should hope for
in the near term is a holiday on part of its interest payments. As
an exporter of more than $1 billion worth of oil each month _ 40
percent of it to the United States _ Nigeria doesn't qualify for
most third world debt reduction aid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we ought to get whatever relief we can,'' said
Clinton. ``Even the rescheduling relief is worth something. It
takes a burden off your back now, and gives you a chance to get
some breathing room, and doesn't raise the questions of
creditworthiness, so that we can get more investment into Nigeria
and more loans into Nigeria as well, if they're necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   OPTIONAL TRIM. STORY MAY END HERE.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, said Clinton, additional debt relief would likely
be pegged to the progress Obasanjo's government makes in
liberalizing the country's political and economic systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nigeria is a great country. You've got a large population,
vast resources, goodlocation, all that oil,'' said Clinton. ``You
have to be well-governed and competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Obasanjo pledged that Nigeria would play by the
new rules of the global marketplace, working to root out
corruption, set up a working system of laws and courts and and set
clear and transparent rules and regulations to govern commerce and
safeguard investment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are eliminatingcorruption as a way of life in Nigeria,''
Obasanjo said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
