<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-SPENDING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESS PASSES THIRD TEMPORARY SPENDING MEASURE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congress passed a third temporary spending measure
Thursday to keep the government operating through Nov. 5 amid signs
that Republican leaders and the White House may be close to an
agreement on final Year 2000 spending matters.
</P>
<P>
   The House also gave its approval Thursday to a 1 percent
across-the -board cut in spending, which it insisted will help
prevent lawmakers and President Clinton from dipping into Social
Security programs next year to fund government programs.
</P>
<P>
   But despite optimistic talk of an agreement on final 2000
spending matters, House Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas,
suggested that it could take up to two more weeks to work out
details giving both sides some of what they want.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a matter of coming to a final agreement on a very,
very short list of items,'' Armey told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Armey said Republicans are ``willing to talk with the president
on every subject'' on his budget wish list for next year, including
money to pay the nearly $1 billion U.S. debt owed to the United
Nations, and to hire more teachers and police officers.
</P>
<P>
   The financial obligation to the United Nations remains
controversial to many Republicans who object to how the money may
be spent in the international arena, particular on matters related
to birth control and abortion. But Armey said, ``We will work with
him on that, and we will work with him on teachers, and
on...(putting more) police on the street. It is not a long list of
items.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also sounded hopeful, telling reporters that Americans
should not be concerned about a possible repeat of the 1995-96
government shutdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be no government shutdowns,'' Clinton said, calling
on Republicans to work with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want a partisan fight on this. This is crazy for us to
be having a big partisan blowout because (we) both made a
commitment not to spend the Social Security surplus and then it
turned out to be harder than necessary, and all of it is being
mixed into a sort of a combustible political mix,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to sit down like grown-ups, go out and tell the
American people the truth and work through this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, however, the Republicans pushed a massive $327
billion bill through the House on Thursday, funding the Departments
of Labor, Education, and Health and Human Services that does not
include money for hiring the 100,000 new teachers Clinton wants.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, which passed on a party-line vote 218-211, was the
last of the 13 appropriations measures needed to fund government
departments and agencies in the 2000 fiscal year. Eight have been
signed into law by Clinton, but the rest have either been vetoed or
will be vetoed as soon they reach Clinton's desk.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton had promised to veto the education, labor and health
measure, not only because of his concern about the lack of funding
for new teachers, but also because it contains an across-the-board
cut in overall spending of nine-tenths of 1 percent, which amounts
to about $3.5 billion. Even though they knew a veto was certain,
Republicans passed the measure to claim that they completed all of
Congress' legislative business this year without tapping into the
Social Security Trust Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has characterized the spending cut proposal as
irresponsible, saying that it would have an adverse impact on
defense and child care programs. But he also objects to another
provision in the bill that would prohibit the National Institutes
of Health from using $7.5 billion of its nearly $18 billion budget
next year until the last two days of the fiscal year. The delay
would prevent the NIH from awarding billions in medical research
grants.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ken Bentsen, D-Texas, condemned the bill for that reason
and accused Republicans of protecting pork barrel spending
projects.
</P>
<P>
   The NIH spending delay, aimed essentially at rolling over money
into the 2001 fiscal year, and the across-the-board cut, are just
two of many unusual accounting techniques Republicans are using in
the their budget deliberations this year to avoid borrowing from
Social Security surpluses to help pay for government operations.
</P>
<P>
   Under an agreement reached with Clinton in 1997, Republicans
agreed to hold spending in the 2000 budget to $580 billion. But
despite utilizing $14 billion in Non-Social Security surpluses this
year and creative accounting efforts, the Congressional Budget
Office estimates that all 13 appropriations bills will total about
$611 billion. That means, according to CBO figures, that the bills
will actually spend about $17 billion in Social Security money.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats seized on the latest CBO assessment as evidence
that Republicans, as Rep. David Obey, D-Wis., put it, have
perpetrated ``a phoney, manipulative debate'' on the American
people about not spending Social Security money.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Armey and Republicans leaders continued to insist
that next year's budget will be balanced without dipping into the
retirement account or raising taxes. They also waved around their
own CBO letter suggesting that no Social Security money had been
used in putting together the budget. That letter, however, was the
result of a GOP leadership directive ordering the CBO to score the
2000 budget differently from the way it normally counts the
spending in annual bills.
</P>
<P>
   The disagreement over the Social Security issue sparked a bitter
exchange between some members during debate on the labor, education
and health bill. At one point, Democratic Rep. Charles Stenholm,
one of the most conservative members of Congress who often votes
with Republicans, accused his GOP Texas colleagues of trying to
deceive the American people.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time for a little honesty,'' he told Armey at one point
in the debate, imploring him to acknowledge that Social Security
money will be spent unless an agreement can be worked out with
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Stenholm also asked Armey why, if Republican leaders ``are
serious about protecting Social Security,'' they refused to work on
crafting a Social Security reform bill this year ``instead of
spending eight months promoting a tax cut'' that Stenholm suggested
would have ended up undermining the long-term stability of the
pension program.
</P>
<P>
   Before passing the last of the spending bills, the House and
Senate voted to extend temporary spending through Nov. 5 in order
to avoid a government shutdown and allow Clinton and Republican
leaders to work out their differences. Clinton was expected to sign
the measure Friday.
</P>
<P>
   It was the third time since the start of fiscal year 2000 on
Oct. 1 that Congress and the president had to take action to
prevent a partial government shutdown. The second temporary
spending measure was due to expire at midnight Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Passage of the stopgap spending measure, combined with the
narrow approval the last spending bill, was expected to put
pressure on both sides to wrap up their negotiations, which have
been hung up on policy differences more than funding levels.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, for example, wants $1.4 billion in education money set
aside specifically for hiring new teachers, but Republicans have so
far offered only $1.2 billion that would be given to states to be
used as they choose.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
