<SLUG> BC-WAFFLE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cook denies snubbing black customers
 &HT;    By Shelia M. Poole
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ An employee at the center of a lawsuit that accuses
Waffle House's largest franchisee of racial discrimination denied
that he refused to cook for five African-American customers.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Biddy, a former cook at the Waffle House contends in a
court filing that the plaintiffs harassed and threatened him and
used racial slurs.
</P>
<P>
   Biddy's detailed response, filed without a lawyer, is partly
handwritten, partly typed.
</P>
<P>
   Biddy, who is white, could not be reached for comment. Northlake
Foods, a Waffle House franchisee, is also named in the lawsuit,
filed in U.S. District Court in Atlanta. Atlanta-based Waffle House
is not named in the suit.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Arrington, of Atlanta, contends in the initial complaint
that he and four friends decided to stop at the restaurant after a
night of partying at a nightclub. According to the lawsuit, the
group placed their orders for grits, eggs and sausage with the
waitress, who was also black.
</P>
<P>
   The group claims Biddy filled the orders of white patrons, even
those who came in later, but refused to fill their orders.
</P>
<P>
   Biddy used obscenities and racial slurs, the suit alleges.
</P>
<P>
   Biddy denies those allegations, although he admits getting in
trouble with his employer before because of his temper.
</P>
<P>
   He begins by questioning whether the plaintiffs are even
African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have met one or two African-Americans before and they talk
funny, they have an accent, but these people...did not have an
accent like the people I have heard from Africa,'' he said in the
filing.
</P>
<P>
   Biddy claims that when the plaintiffs came in the restaurant and
placed their orders with the waitress, Lawanda Baker, that he was
backed up on orders at the grill. He said she initially called out
the orders improperly. When that was resolved, he said be began to
cook the food.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, at no time did I intentionally refuse to prepare
anyone's order,'' he said in his answer. He also denied using
racial slurs and profanity.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs ``kept raising hell and calling me names,'' Biddy
said in the filing. Biddy said he called the police when the
plaintiffs became rowdy and threatened him. They left before police
arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Biddy asked to have the case dismissed and asks for unspecified
damages and attorneys fees in his countersuit for emotional
distress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of their aggressive nature, their loud and vulgar
language, their threats, combined with what I observed as bulges in
the pockets of two of the plaintiffs and the fact that one of them
stood up and threatened to kill me, I believe they had guns and
weapons on them, and so I feared for my life,'' he said. ``Also,
there were five of them, including four grown men.''
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Robert Proctor, who has successfully argued against
several affirmative action cases in the metro area, is representing
Northlake Foods. Proctor was on vacation Thursday. An associate
confirmed that he didn't represent Biddy but declined additional
comment.
</P>
<P>
   David C. Cole, who res the plaintiffs, said Biddy's
admission in the filing that Northlake supervisors had previously
talked to him about his temper ``supports our case.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
