<SLUG> BC-SEARS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sears takHome Depot with decor stores
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sears, Roebuck &AMP; Co. is poised for an upscale counterattack on
Home Depot.
</P>
<P>
   Sears will soon start a national expansion of Great Indoors, a
new home decor and remodeling concept that debuted in Denver last
year. A second Great Indoors opens next week in Scottsdale, Ariz.,
followed by 15 more stores over the next year and a half.
</P>
<P>
   Longer-range plans call for 150 stores, including possible sites
in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Like Home Depot's Expo concept, Great Indoors goes after the
upper-income female shopper who wants to revamp an entire room.
Sears designed the new format to recoup sales lost to Home Depot
and Lowe's, and retailers like Bed, Bath &AMP; Beyond.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good sign that Sears is pushing forward on a successful
division,'' said Alan Mak, an analyst with Argus Research. ``This
is a high-margin business, and it's one of the areas that's working
for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Home-related merchandise is one of the fastest-growing areas of
retail. Great Indoors raked in first-year sales of $42 million in
Denver. Analysts have estimated the average Home Depot Expo
generates sales of $60 million, compared with roughly $43 million
at traditional Home Depot stores.
</P>
<P>
   Both Expo and Sears present wall coverings, cabinets, flooring
and appliances in lifelike bathroom and kitchen settings. Taking a
cue from Home Depot's popular workshops, Great Indoors also offers
free seminars on painting, decorating and other projects.
</P>
<P>
   There are some differences, though. Great Indoors sells more
furniture and bedding, while Expo aims to dominate in rugs and
lighting.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the new Great Indoors will compete directly with Expo
in the same market, including Dallas and Detroit. A Great Indoors
also will open near Denver. Sears did not identify the remaining 11
sites for its rollout, other than to say it was looking at the top
40 U.S. markets.
</P>
<P>
   While metro Atlanta certainly leads the list of possible sites,
the market already is highly competitive. Home Depot alone has 33
warehouse stores and two Expos. Another Expo is on the drawing.
</P>
<P>
   Add to that 14 Lowe's Home Improvement Warehouse stores in metro
Atlanta, plus scores of other home furnishing chains.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, Expo will operate 26 stores by the end of next year
and plans to have 200 by the end of 2005. Home Depot is targeting
large metropolitan areas and affluent cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of demand for these types of products,'' said
Mak, the analyst at at Argus Research. But he said few markets are
big enough to accommodate both Expo and Great Indoors.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some markets, one will be weeded out, and given the savvy
of Home Depot, I doubt it will be them,'' Mak said.
</P>
<P>
   Home Depot's stock closed Thursday at $74.56 1/4, up $4.87 1/2.
Sears closed at $27.68 3/4, up 18 3/4 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-99 1941EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
