A1674 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-ORE-SUICIDE-770(2TAKE     10-28 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ORE-SUICIDE-770(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OREGONIANS RESENT HOUSE VOTE TO CURB THEIR ASSISTED-SUICIDE LAW 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By SAM HOWE VERHOVEK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. _ Oregonians have long prided themselves on being
in the forefront on many social issues _ sometimes with ideas that
catch on in the rest of the nation, and sometimes not.
</P>
<P>
   They were among the first to decriminalize marijuana and to
approve its use for medicinal purposes, and they legalized abortion
years before the Supreme Court issued the Roe vs. Wade decision.
They were the first to conduct an election entirely by mail, and
they have long had some of the strictest growth-management
regulations in the nation. They even live in one of two states that
resolutely refuse to let customers pump their own gasoline at a
service station.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, the people of Oregon passionately debated and
narrowly approved a measure making theirs the first state, and one
of the few places in the world, to legalize physician-assisted
suicide. Two years ago, amid legal challenges to the so-called
``Death with Dignity Act,'' the state's residents voted 60 percent
to 40 percent to reaffirm it.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, a day after the U.S. House of Representatives passed a
measure that would effectively overturn the Oregon law and thus
amounts to an extraordinary rebuke of the popular will in a single
state, even many of those who opposed the law said they were angry
over impending federal interference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why are they doing this?'' said Ronald Nelson, owner of a
dance shop and studio owner here, who voted twice against
legalizing doctor-assisted suicide. ``The people in Oregon had a
vote. I may not agree with it, but is Congress really saying that
our vote doesn't count, it doesn't matter? That's just wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   From the governor to people in the street, Oregonians were
invoking the phrase states' rights Thursday, and the congressional
action only seems to have solidified the notion that the people of
Oregon, arguably the most aggressively libertarian in the country,
should have the right to decide this issue themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``There certainly is a strong libertarian impulse at work here,
of people wanting to be free to make decisions without the
government coming in,'' said James Moore, a professor of political
science at the University of Portland.
</P>
<P>
   ``But another thing is going on right now,'' Moore added,
``People may fight like cats and dogs here over issues such as
this, but if there is a whiff of outside interference over these
things, Oregonians will all gather together and defend their right
to fight and send a message to the outside, that you cannot dictate
to us.'' For precisely that reason, he said, a referendum today on
doctor-aided suicide would probably gather even more than the 60
percent yes vote it got last time.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, many here insisted that far too much was being
made of the issue by Congress anyway: despite predictions by
critics that Oregon would be flooded with those seeking death, they
noted, just 15 people took lethal medication last year, the first
full year the measure was in effect.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, resistance here to the House action is clearly
strong and intensely felt. The state's congressional delegation,
which includes several members who voted twice against legalizing
physician-assisted suicide, is staunchly united in trying to stop
the bill that passed the House on Wednesday on a 271-156 vote. Sen.
Ron Wyden, a Democrat who said he opposed the Death with Dignity
Act, has pledged to filibuster the bill in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. John Kitzhaber, who is a physician, and the staff of the
state attorney general's office are exploring possible legal
challenges if the measure passes the Senate and is signed by
President Clinton, which remains far from certain. (The Clinton
administration, which opposes provisions of the House bill that
could force doctors to spend up to 20 years in prison for
prescribing lethal medication, is looking for ways to revise the
House measure in the Senate, said U.S. Attorney General Janet Reno
in Washington on Thursday.)
</P>
<P>
   And some doctors here are already saying they may engage in
civil disobedience by continuing to offer mentally competent,
terminally ill people lethal prescriptions, or perhaps by employing
what they call a creative sidestepping around the measure.
</P>
<P>
   Technically, the House bill does not overturn the Oregon law,
though it effectively does so by banning the use of any federally
controlled substance for the purpose of aiding suicide. Some
doctors said they might explore whether there are substances
outside of federal regulation that could be offered to patients.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Peter Rasmussen, a cancer specialist in Salem, who says he has
helped two terminally ill people end their lives by prescribing
barbiturates that were added to a chocolate pudding mixture, said
in a telephone interview Thursday that he was disappointed by the
House vote and that a federal law prohibiting doctor-aided suicide
should and would face legal challenges.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do believe that this will wind up in the courts,'' he said.
``And to do that you need to have a case, and I would consider
being part of such a case.''
</P>
<P>
   Rasmussen also said he believed doctors remained within their
rights to discuss suicide with patients who were facing painful
death from diseases such as cancer, from which 13 of the 15 people
who took their lives here last year suffered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there are still things we could do,'' he said. ``If
what the patient is looking for is a painless, sure way of quickly
ending his life, as physicians I think we can offer advice as to
what would work and what wouldn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the law, an adult of sound mind, who, in the opinion of
two doctors, has less than six months to live, may request
authorization for lethal drugs. The person must sign a single-page
form. Doctors may prescribe but not administer the drug.
</P>
<P>
   The House bill, known as the Pain Relief Promotion Act,
stipulates that the use of controlled substances to alleviate pain
is a ``legitimate medical purpose,'' but doctors have disagreed
over whether its effect would be to strengthen or weaken
protections for doctors who prescribe drugs for pain control.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The American Medical Association and the National Hospice
Organization have supported the bill, while their state
organizations here in Oregon oppose it.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly why Oregon was the first and only state to authorize
doctor-aided suicide remains a matter of debate. The state
certainly has a strong populist tradition and was, just after the
turn of the century, one of the first to approve a statewide
initiative system providing for popular vote on measures such as
the Death with Dignity Act.
</P>
<P>
   But it is difficult to classify the state's political philosophy
and, between liberal-leaning Portland and conservative swaths in
much of the rest of the state, Oregon has sent an eclectic mix of
politicians to Washington and to the state capital in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are things that appeal to that populist streak in terms
of both left and right,'' said David Fidanque, executive director
of the Oregon branch of the American Civil Liberties Union. ``The
Death with Dignity Act is one that really brought together folks
from the left and from the right who believe government has no
business telling people how they should die.''
</P>
<P>
   There are other interpretations of the libertarian impulses
here. ``Personally, I think Oregonians are still in kind of a
flashback to the '60s,'' said Johnnie Adams, a 49-year-old
convenience store manager who said she was enraged by the House
vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``They haven't come forward to the 1990s,'' she said, ``but that
doesn't mean it's wrong or anything.''
</P>
<P>
   And some say that even the libertarian pigeonhole does not
really fit. There is the prohibition of self-serve gas, which
Oregon shares with New Jersey, and that seems to spring from both
ecological arguments (attendants are less likely to spill) and a
general sense that the ban preserves jobs. There is also the
willingness of Oregonians to impose zoning laws and sharp
restrictions on land use, though Moore suggested there was a
libertarian basis for the concept.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's seen as a way of protecting people's lands from the
arbitrary decisions of government and especially from the arbitrary
decisions of your richer neighbors,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There are certainly strong opponents of physician-assisted
suicide who endorse the House action.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought to begin with that people should be able to
vote on whether they want to take their own lives or not,'' said
Angela Johnston, who owns a plumbing and contracting business here.
Joseph Journagan, a Portland construction worker, said: ``There are
a lot of other ways for people to take their own life without
getting a doctor involved.''
</P>
<P>
   But the prevailing sentiment here seems to be opposition to the
House action, 3,000 miles away in the nation's capital.
</P>
<P>
   Toni Shemarya told reporters at a news conference here
Wednesday, organized by proponents of the Death with Dignity Act,
that her partner had taken great satisfaction from her prescription
for lethal drugs, even though she ultimately died without using
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was always a very independent woman, and this gave her a
sense of control,'' said Ms. Shemarya, adding: ``Congress has no
right to tell Oregonians that their vote doesn't count.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
