<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 19:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1677 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-JERICHO-MAYOR-ART-2TA     10-28 1011
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JERICHO-MAYOR-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEEL OF FORTUNE TURNS FOR JERICHO, THE WORLD'S OLDEST TOWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo, NYT9, was sent on 10/27; a map is being sent to
NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERICHO, West Bank _ Sometimes the young mayor of the oldest
city in the world gets ahead of himself.
</P>
<P>
   In the last year, Mayor Abdel Karim Sidr's sleepy Palestinian
town has been shaken awake by such a sudden spate of development
that he finds himself dizzy with concern: does he have a future Las
Vegas on his hands?
</P>
<P>
   ``Things are going too fast in Jericho,'' Sidr, 37, said. He
pointed to the casino, the resort village, the cable car, the fancy
parks, the shiny orthopedic hospital and the six small factories
already open as well as to the high-rise hotel, the international
airport and the quickie wedding parlor in the works.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a saying in Arabic that expresses my concern'' he
said. ``Money attracts even the person who prints it.''
</P>
<P>
   On the street outside his office, though, one is struck by the
very lack of bustle. Blazing hot under the desert sun, the heart of
Jericho seems, as always, on permanent siesta and in firm
possession of its rickety charm. While plans call for a futuristic
tower to rise from the town center, it now features a forlorn kiosk
topped by a giant, dented banana.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little early to talk about a boom,'' a merchant, Nahida
Halteh, said as she presided over the new souvenir display case in
her clothing store, whose carved camels have yet to gallop out the
door. ``But it is possible, for the first time in a long time, to
talk about a future.''
</P>
<P>
   It is also possible to talk about 700 new jobs that virtually
eliminated unemployment in the last 18 months, a doubling of the
annual municipal budget to a still paltry $3 million, and,
astonishingly, not only saunas and Jacuzzis but also what the new
Jericho Resort Village promises will be the very first oxygen room
in the Middle East. (``Don't ask me how it works,'' said Riyad
Hamad, the assistant general manager. ``But it has to do with
health things.'')
</P>
<P>
   Sidr said the Palestinian Authority had just signed a contract
with an Italian company to build a second Palestinian airport
several miles north of the city.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, Jericho, a town of 15,000, braced itself for
something big.
</P>
<P>
   Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian leader, was about to return from
exile, crossing the border from Jordan directly into Jericho, which
was to become the first independent Palestinian city in the West
Bank. Surely he would make it his capital, people thought.
</P>
<P>
   News organizations from around the world rented every rooftop in
town, and eager entrepreneurs happily cut down palm trees so the
cameramen's views would not be obstructed. Real-estate speculation
sent prices soaring.
</P>
<P>
   But after the arrival and the celebration, Arafat and the
Palestinian forces moved to Gaza. Only one official, Saeb Erekat, a
senior peace negotiator and the Minister of Local governments,
chose Jericho as a base _ and that was out of loyalty to his
family's hometown.
</P>
<P>
   The town, which is dotted with ancient ruins, fell into a
depression, and not the superficial kind that strikes when other
places challenge its claim, generally accepted by archeologists, to
be the oldest continuously inhabited city. (No one ever contests
its title as lowest city: 820 feet below sea level.) The low
spirits were not helped by drought conditions that every year
harmed its production of bananas, oranges and papaya.
</P>
<P>
   Slowly, though, the money, if not the rain, started trickling
in. First came international donations, totaling some $30 million
for public works. Then, last year, the $50 million Oasis Casino
Resort opened, giving impetus to a revival of the tourism industry,
which hopes to ride the millennial pilgrimage wave.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jericho's always been a forgotten town,'' said Hamad, a
Jerusalemite. ``All these projects will lift it and put it on the
map.''
</P>
<P>
   International donations built a sleek modern hospital, a
municipal water system that is about to open, a high-quality soccer
stadium and a luxurious park, complete with color-lit fountain.
Palestinians from all over the West Bank began traveling to Jericho
for its open-air night life, changing the nature and the self-image
of the town.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tickets for the Ehab Tawfik concert this weekend are going for
$25, but it's not too much,'' the mayor said, shrugging, as he
referred to an Egyptian pop star. ``In Vienna, they charge $200 for
the opera.''
</P>
<P>
   Although mellow Jericho was hardly the heart of the intifada,
the Palestinian uprising against Israel killed its winter business
over a decade ago, scaring away the Israelis who used to flock
here.
</P>
<P>
   The casino, which represented the first large, for-profit
international investment in Palestinian territory, started drawing
Israelis and foreign tourists back, if at first only to the
periphery of town. The casino, whose parking lot is always filled,
is pumping some $1 million a month into the local economy, not
including the tax revenues, which go to the Palestinian Authority.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ah, the casino,'' the mayor said nonetheless. ``This is a
subject I don't like to speak about.''
</P>
<P>
   Another touchy subject is that of the proposed wedding chapel.
Abdel Wahab Darawshe, a former Israeli Parliament member, said he
expects to open a civil marriage hall in Jericho soon. It would
cater to secular Israelis who do not want to be wed by an Orthodox
rabbi, as required in Israel; many now fly to Cyprus. Darawshe said
the Palestinian Authority authorized him to set up the business,
from which it will collect marriage registration fees.
</P>
<P>
   But many residents of Muslim Jericho, opposed to secular
marriage as to gambling on religious grounds, find the idea
repulsive, and Sidr said he would block the chapel. ``I'm not
responsible for solving the secular-religious problems of Israel,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE) nn
</P>
<P>
   Cashing in on the Mount of Temptation is another story. A few
months ago, a modern cable car system began making the climb up the
barren, rocky slope to the site where Jesus supposedly withstood
temptation by Satan after his baptism in the Jordan River. On the
terraced cliff, hard by the caves where tradition says Jesus fasted
for 40 days, a French restaurant is preparing to open.
</P>
<P>
   It is all part of a $10 million complex created by a wealthy
Palestinian family, the Sinokrots, who were given an exclusive
franchise on cable cars by the Palestinian Authority and a free
``forever'' contract by the Greek Orthodox Church, which controls
the mount.
</P>
<P>
   ``This particular business will change the itinerary of the
Christian pilgrim,'' said Amir Dajani, the operations manager, who
is looking at package deals with Israeli resort operators on the
Dead Sea. ``And its impact on Jericho will go far beyond the
casino, whose patrons are too busy to even use the toilet, much
less set foot in town. If you want my opinion, in 10 years there
will be 10,000 hotel rooms here.''
</P>
<P>
   At this point the only game in town is the resort village, which
has 58 rooms and 46 bungalows and caters to Israeli-Arab families
and European tour groups. The lush resort, in a barren landscape,
is almost always full, and often a study in contrasts.
</P>
<P>
   The other day, a tour bus picking up 100 Spaniards who had just
finished lunching on the poolside veranda was delayed at the gate
before leaving. A herd of goats crossed the drive before the
resort's elegant gates.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
