<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-HEALTH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bradley, Gore spar over costs of health plans
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The day after their first town hall meeting, Vice
President Al Gore and former New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley on
Thursday turned up the rhetoric on their health care proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Traveling in Iowa, Gore compared Bradley's $65 billion health
care plan to Gov. George W. Bush's proposed tax cut, saying both
would return the country to an era of deficit spending.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both the Bradley campaign and the Bush campaign have had
serious problems with fiscal responsibility,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   In New Hampshire, Bradley criticized Gore for failing to provide
specific cost estimates for his own health care proposal. Bradley's
campaign also issued a three-page memo disputing Gore's assertion
that Bradley misrepresented the cost of his plan.
</P>
<P>
   The sharpened criticism on both sides followed a more subdued
exchange the two candidates had over health care during Wednesday
night's town hall meeting in Hanover, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   During that meeting, Gore cited a study by Emory University
health policy expert Kenneth E. Thorpe that said Bradley's plan for
near universal health care coverage would cost $1.2 trillion over
10 years, or roughly double what Bradley says the plan would cost.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's campaign strongly disputed the charge Thursday, citing
its own experts, who found Thorpe's analysis to be flawed because
it did not take into account off-setting savings in Bradley's plan.
``Gore is attacking Bradley's plan simply because it is
comprehensive and bold,'' Bradley's campaign said.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's campaign also accused Gore of misrepresenting his own
plan to provide expanded health care coverage for poor children.
The campaign said Gore's claim that his plan would cover 90 percent
of all uninsured children was ``inaccurate'' because the plan was
voluntary.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's health care plan would allow the parents of poor children
to buy into a new Medicaid insurance plan for the poor and provide
tax credits to small businesses that provide coverage for their
employees.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's plan also would cover half of a Medicare patient's
prescription drug bill, up to a maximum of $2,000. It would carry a
$24 monthly premium.
</P>
<P>
   Thorpe's analysis of Gore's plan, which the vice president did
not mention in Wednesday's town hall meeting, found it would also
cost $48 billion more than Gore estimated and cover fewer people.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's plan would essentially eliminate Medicaid and allow
poor children and families to enroll in the private network of
insurance plans that cover federal employees. The federal
government would subsidize all or part of the premium, depending on
income.
</P>
<P>
   For Medicare patients, Bradley's plan would cover the cost of
prescription drugs, but require patients to pay a $25 monthly
premium and a 25 percent drug co-payment. The plan would also have
a $500 deductible, but no annual cap.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
