u k BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      10-28 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: BRADLEY'S GESTALT THERAPY  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By GAIL COLLINS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HANOVER, N.H. _ Thanks to this week's presidential debates _
forums, town halls, whatever you want to call them _ we now know
that Bill Bradley's idea of a great leader is Jimmy Carter
(``integrity''), Woodrow Wilson (``the ability to see around
corners'') or Mikhail Gorbachev (``courage''). Who could not find
this interesting? Once again, Bradley demonstrated that he is a new
kind of candidate, a man who skips the predictable tributes to
Lincoln and FDR, and instead names three former heads of state so
high-minded their constituents practically ran them out of town on
a rail.
</P>
<P>
   How many of you watched the debates on TV? (I don't want to see
any hands from people who taped. Sure, you're going to watch them
later, right after all six hours of ``Middlemarch.'') No matter.
We'll boil them down for you. We have nothing better to do with our
time _ in fact, we can travel right up to New Hampshire and watch
them on the spot, in a large hall where people are not permitted to
click over to the Weather Channel when Steve Forbes starts
explaining his economic agenda.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic debate seemed weightier because Bradley and Gore
are both perfectly credible presidential candidates. That's more
than you can say for the Republican crew, which featured John
McCain vs. a whole bunch of peculiar people with single-digit poll
numbers and a lot of time on their hands.
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush was forced to skip the event in order to watch
his wife receive an award in Texas. Family is very important to
Bush, who was undoubtedly looking forward to arguing foreign policy
with McCain, and hearing more about his experiences as a heroic
prisoner of war. But he apparently did not have enough clout to get
the ceremony scheduled on another day. This is yet another reminder
that Texas has a weak-governor system.
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore has a personality without a thermostat, and when he
tries to look animated he practically crashes into the wallboard.
On Wednesday he hijacked the auditorium early on, begging for a
chance to do a pre-debate Q&AMP;A. (``This person has a question! Do we
have time for his question?'') He tossed in a little Spanish and a
long joke, and made endless attempts to create Clintonesque
mind-melds with the audience. (``How old is your child, Corey? . .
. Are you unionized, Earl?'') At the end, he refused to be dragged
offstage. (``Can I say one more word? I would like to stay!'') He
bore an uncomfortable resemblance to the kid who asks the teacher
for more homework. Bradley, lounging on his stool, arms folded
across his chest, looked like the high school athlete watching the
class nerd volunteer to stay and clap erasers.
</P>
<P>
   ``His gestalt is the gestalt of the time,'' said the Bradley
adviser Rick Stengel. ``This elbowing back and forth, that's
history.''
</P>
<P>
   Either due to excess gestalt or lack of a good retort, Bradley
refused to fight back when Gore attacked his health insurance plan,
saying it would cost $1.4 trillion and eat up all the money for the
rest of the Democratic agenda. That made the vice president look
like the stronger candidate _ overstimulated, yes, but aggressive.
If Bradley keeps refusing to grab the initiative, he is going to
undermine the media-wide ban on use of basketball analogies and
force somebody to start recalling how, when he was a Knick, he
preferred passing the ball to making the critical shot.
</P>
<P>
   But what, by the way, ever happened to Gore's own budget-busting
Big Idea for high-quality preschool for every child in the nation,
which he bellowed at every opportunity back when he was working on
the theory that shouting a speech made it more interesting? The
campaign contends it's still there, although on Wednesday night it
had dwindled away to ``we've got to focus on preschools.''
</P>
<P>
   Once you weed out 80 percent or so of the Gore-Bradley debate _
the parts where they agree with each other and the parts where each
man starts talking about ``dreams'' _ you get down to some very
interesting questions. Do Americans want a Big Idea, if it costs a
lot of money? Which one? Is anybody willing to suggest trade-offs _
eliminating the new aircraft carrier we're building in Trent Lott's
district? The new fighter planes we're building in Richard
Gephardt's district?
</P>
<P>
   There's plenty of time, the World Series is over, and we're
actually finally about to enter the 2000 election year. Let the
games begin.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
