<SLUG> BC-CUSTOMS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Official faces marijuana possession charges
 &HT;    By Rebecca Carr and Bill Montgomery
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The president of the American Chamber of Commerce in Russia was
charged with possessing marijuana when he landed at Atlanta's
Hartsfield International Airport earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Blacklin, 46, was arrested by the Clayton County Drug
Enforcement Task Force on Wednesday after U.S. Customs Service
inspectors allegedly found 13 grams of marijuana in his underwear,
according to Police Maj. Jim Thompson, commander of the task force.
</P>
<P>
   Reached at a business conference he is attending at the
Ritz-Carlton Hotel in downtown Atlanta, Blacklin denied the
charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``The charges are not true,'' he said. ``I was stopped, but I
didn't have anything on me.''
</P>
<P>
   But Customs Service officials tell a different story.
</P>
<P>
   Blacklin was spotted by a dog specially trained to sniff out
narcotics and other controlled substances among international
passengers at the airport. The 13 grams of marijuana were
discovered during a ``pat-down'' search by customs inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We confirm that he was stopped and marijuana was found,'' said
Dennis Murphy, a Customs Service spokesman in Washington. Blacklin
was fined $500 and turned over to the drug task force, which
charged him with violating the Georgia's controlled substance law.
Blacklin was released from jail Wednesday evening after posting a
$2,250 bond.
</P>
<P>
   Blacklin had flown to Atlanta from Moscow to attend the
U.S.-Russia Business Council's annual meeting. As the president of
the American Chamber of Commerce in Moscow, Blacklin is responsible
for fostering ties between U.S. corporations and Russian
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Before becoming president of the chamber in 1997, Blacklin
worked for a number of major American corporations, including
Westinghouse and Motorola, according to his ex-wife, Ducana
Blacklin, who lives with their three children in the Washington
area.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
