<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1689 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS &LR;      10-28 1107
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLENN SAYS HE WANTS TO STAY PUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Other superstars around the league would
have been talking about restructuring their contract by now. Not
Terry Glenn. In the fourth year of a six-year deal, Glenn, who has
39 receptions (a league-leading 18.4 average), has decided he will
not bring up his contract until he's had a full, healthy year, and
when that time comes, he wants to remain a Patriot for the rest of
his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I would love to be a Patriot forever,'' Glenn said
Thursday. ``This is where I started. I see a lot of guys bouncing
around and it's not necessarily that they're not good anymore. For
example, the Curtis Martin situation. He was a great player around
here but the organization felt they didn't need Curtis Martin for
that kind of money. They felt they could get another player for
less for the same production.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't ever want to feel that. I go out and practice hard
every day and (want to) stay at the level where I don't feel you're
going to get another player at my level. There are a lot of good
players out there, but you have to find players who work well in
your system, and I think this is the perfect place for me and I
never want to leave here.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn's resurgence this season has transpired because he's been
healthy. He takes it, as the old cliche goes, one game at a time _
not one injury at a time, as was the case in the past. He's doing
all he can to earn his $2.1 million this year and $2.3 million next
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not right now,'' said Glenn about a renegotiation. ``I'm not
on that boat. I'm just trying to get through a healthy season
before I can even start thinking about stuff like that. I don't
even want to bring anything up about it because my past here hasn't
been all that great, even though I've given it my all and when I'm
out there, things happen for the good. I want things to happen for
a whole season.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn's comfort zone with the team is because he sees a strong
core of players who could be here for a while.
</P>
<P>
   ``You got me, Drew (Bledsoe), Willie (McGinest), Ty (Law) has
made his mark; Lawyer (Milloy) is a great player who should be
here. Ben Coates to me is a guy who hasn't caught a lot of balls
but he's a good player. You don't find many tight ends who do what
he does. He's perfect with Drew. Ben is a tight end who's in the
right place. You could go out and get a tight end who's faster, but
you have to have the chemistry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teddy Johnson is a great player we need to have back to
exploit what we can do defensively, and I'll add Andy Katzenmoyer
to that list also. He's shown flashes of what he can be and when
Ted comes back, we can put him back to a position that he may be
even better at than the one he's playing now.''
</P>
<P>
   Though he's been healthy through seven games, the last two weeks
have been tough _ he didn't have a catch vs. Miami and had just two
receptions for 80 yards (including a season-long 67-yard catch) in
a win over Denver. Every week, Glenn must fight and claw to get
open, and each week the coverage seems to get tougher.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I'm really pleased about is the way we've started,'' said
Glenn, always bringing the conversation back to the team. ``Two
games we should have won, but our future is looking great. I'm over
the past injuries, but we still have a lot of the season left and a
lot can happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he feels he's having an All-Pro season, Glenn
shied away from the question. ``I feel I'm doing fairly well with
my personal goals, but I don't like to think about those,'' he
said. ``I don't try to fulfill just personal goals because I have a
lot of team goals that I put first. We accomplish those team goals
and things should happen for me and for all of us on a personal
level.''
</P>
<P>
   He kicks himself for not being able to make plays early in the
Denver game when Bledsoe went to him quickly _ Glenn dropped a ball
because the sun was in his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're trying to take me away; trying to make it difficult
for me as opposed to the prior weeks, which we all expected,'' he
said. ``I expected it. They've done a good job of when they're
going to do it (double-teams). They don't do it on every down. But
when they do it, it just seems to come at the right time for them
and the wrong time for us.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy for people to say, `well, he had him one-on-one.'
Well, maybe we were running the ball on that play. There might be
another play where Drew's first read is not me. But they're doing
it when the first read is me. We're going to try to get other guys
involved, but sometimes when you do that it throws off the
quarterback. We just have to keep making adjustments. I'm just
gonna fight through them. Like last week, I just have to make plays
when I get the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   It's been interesting to Glenn how the receiving draft class of
'96 has fared. All of the first-rounders went to AFC East teams.
Since they were drafted, Keyshawn Johnson (drafted first by the
Jets) has the most catches with 256 for 3,515 yards and 25 TDs;
Marvin Harrison (drafted 19th by Indianapolis) has 241 receptions
for 3,187 yards and 29 TDs; Glenn (drafted seventh) has 206
receptions for 3,071 yards and 13 TDs, and Eric Moulds (drafted
24th by Buffalo) has caught 145 passes for 2,399 yards and 14 TDs.
Glenn also has the most 100-yard games of the group (10).
</P>
<P>
   ``(Keyshawn's) a great player who makes plays,'' said Glenn.
``But a lot of guys under him thought they were good also, such as
myself. I felt I was the best receiver in the draft no matter who
went first. Keyshawn was a taller receiver out of USC. But he
stayed his senior year, I left early. All those guys fell in line.
Each guy was put on a competition level by the media. A lot of
people thought Marvin should go before me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thinking Marvin's a great player. (He) has really stepped
his game up and is having a Pro Bowl year. He might be having the
best year in the league. I'm happy for him because he was the last
in the bunch to really show what he could do. And now I'm coming
back.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots needed three players to have healthy years:
Bledsoe, McGinest, and Glenn.
</P>
<P>
   And one game from the midpoint of the season, all three have
been healthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``These hamstrings can go at any time,'' Glenn said. ``I put
`Icy-Hot' on my hamstrings, I stretch really well before practice
and try to prevent those kind of injuries. I'm not going to say I'm
never going to get hurt again, but things can happen, so I'm taking
a lot of precautions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
