<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1690 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-FRISCO-MAYOR-ART-(TRI     10-28 1093
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRISCO-MAYOR-ART-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAN FRANCISCO'S HIGH-FLYING MAYOR MAY CRASH ON ELECTION DAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT23 has been sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By EVELYN NIEVES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ For an hour, it was 1995 again, when Willie
Lewis Brown Jr. was the newly minted mayor and San Francisco was
dazzled by his possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Brown played the crowd at City Hall like Mozart on the piano,
vowing to right what's wrong and to better what's right, and
tempering the high notes with quiet moments and meaningful pauses.
And when he was finished Monday with what he called this ``last
state of the city address to be given by any mayor in this
century,'' the chamber, so packed a person could faint, erupted in
the loud, long applause usually reserved for a Broadway hit.
</P>
<P>
   Then 1999, one week before the mayoral election, came rushing
back.
</P>
<P>
   In the hallway outside the chamber, someone held a newspaper
with the latest San Francisco Chronicle poll. It showed Brown with
33 percent of the vote, far short of the 50 percent plus one vote
needed to win the election Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby stood former Mayor Frank Jordan, who is one of Brown's
three main opponents, drawing a crowd as he wondered aloud where
the $1 billion increase in the city's budget over the last four
years had gone.
</P>
<P>
   Near him lingered Tom Ammiano, the president of the San
Francisco Board of Supervisors, who entered the race less than two
weeks ago as a write-in candidate. Ammiano was exulting over the
newspaper poll, which put him in a statistical tie for second place
without even being listed as one of the candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Given the polls, a run-off election in December seems likely.
And while the prevailing thought is that Brown, who entered office
as Mr. San Francisco, would win that race, no one is taking his
victory for granted. The fact is, San Francisco's mayor, a master
of the political universe who spent three decades in the California
Legislature (15 years as the speaker of the Assembly before a new
two-term-limit law forced him from office in 1995), is no longer
Prince of the City.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a booming economy, low unemployment and plunging crime
rates that mirror the trend across the nation, voters in
politically obsessed San Francisco are not happy. And while this is
not as surprising as it sounds _ San Franciscans are notoriously
hard to please, ousting the last two mayors after single terms _
Brown, as colorful and irrepressible as the city considers itself,
has disappointed voters on all sides.
</P>
<P>
   To his more liberal constituents, he is too cozy with developers
and other big business interests. To more conservative voters (a
conservative here is a moderate Democrat anywhere else in the
country), he does not pay enough attention to quality-of-life
issues like traffic and is too close to the fringe groups that give
San Francisco its reputation as a hotbed of radical chic.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Trying to cater to competing constituencies is a tricky
business. Earlier this month, the mayor ordered the confiscation of
supermarket shopping carts that homeless people use to haul their
possessions, on the grounds that they were stolen property. The
move was seen as a response to merchants' complaints.
</P>
<P>
   But even with public compassion toward homeless people at a
seemingly all-time low, publicity about the operation brought
outrage and sympathy. Brown stopped the operation before it began,
both denying he had ordered it and claiming it was misunderstood.
That, in turn, caused the more conservative pundits and business
people in the city to label the mayor a waffler.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The hard truth for Brown is that many San Franciscans believe
the city is not better off than it was four years ago. Half the
voters in the latest poll said that homelessness, considered the
city's No. 1 problem, has gotten worse during the mayor's term. A
third of the voters said the city's trouble-plagued public transit
system has deteriorated, while only 23 percent said it had
improved. And 43 percent of those polled say that a major problem,
the lack of affordable housing, has worsened, while only 14 percent
said the condition had improved. The mayor's administration has
also been plagued with accusations of cronyism and corruption in
several city agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Until last week, at least, Brown had the edge among liberals.
Both of his leading opponents up until then _ Jordan and Clint
Reilly, a political consultant and Jordan's former campaign
manager, who has spent more than $3 million of his own money on his
campaign _ are considered more conservative. So Brown concentrated
his heaviest campaigning in the more traditionally conservative
Asian neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   But the write-in candidacy of Ammiano, a former
special-education teacher who is gay, has thrown that liberal vote
into question.
</P>
<P>
   The Ammiano campaign, as it exists, has galvanized disenchanted
voters who had planned to sit out the election, his supporters
contend.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone I know was sitting around saying, `Gosh, who am I
going to vote for for mayor?''' said Tim Redmond, executive editor
of The Bay Guardian, a liberal weekly newspaper that repeatedly
urged Ammiano to run.
</P>
<P>
   Redmond estimated that several thousand voters who had planned
to stay home or vote for one of the fringe candidates, will write
in Ammiano as their choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of this pent-up frustration has been released because all
of a sudden people have a place to go with it,'' he said. ``I
haven't seen this kind of excitement in a while.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The Brown campaign seems resigned to losing some support.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no doubt that we're disappointed that Tom Ammiano has
entered the race and will probably help the more conservative
candidates by doing so,'' said P.J. Johnston, a spokesman for the
mayor's re-election team.
</P>
<P>
   In response to the threat, Brown's campaign brought no less a
liberal heavy-hitter than the Rev. Jesse Jackson to town Tuesday.
The mayor and Jackson made a series of stops in neighborhoods like
the Castro, a largely gay district, to remind voters of Brown's
long civil rights credentials. Jackson's presence certainly
attracted attention, though he tried to deflect it to the mayor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Willie Brown is the real thing,'' Jackson would say, as
passers-by vied to shake his hand.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
