</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GOOD AND BAD OF MODERN INDOOR ARENAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Now if you were sitting in a midcourt Staples
Center floor seat costing $350, would you like to know the score
and how much time was left at any given point in the game?
</P>
<P>
   If the answer is yes, then on Wednesday evening it would have
been tough patooties for you, pal.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so you couldn't see anything resembling a score on the
octagonal scoreboard, and there aren't any sideline scoreboards in
the building, and the scoreboards waaaaaaaaay back there on the
endline are significantly smaller than any good Indiana high school
scoreboards, and nowhere in the building were you offered
cumulative team stats, which are known in the arena trade as
``hustle stats'' (something even the FleetCenter, that K Mart of
indoor arenas, manages to do), but at least you could hear the
music very nicely on the spectacular Bose sound system.
</P>
<P>
   That $350 a pop is only for a Clippers game, by the way. When
the Varsity, er, the Lakers play, that same seat zooms to $1,150
(yup, even vs. Vancouver).
</P>
<P>
   Look, the $375,000,000 Staples Center is beautiful, and it's
about time LA moved itself into the 21st century with a thoroughly
modern arena. The Great Western (nee Fabulous) Forum was a '60s and
'70s anachronism. The Staples Center gives LA a proper venue for
its two NBA teams, its NHL team, a forthcoming Arena Football team,
and all the predictable concerts, shows, and mega-events, including
the 2000 Democratic National Convention and the 2000 Grammy Awards.
</P>
<P>
   And the scoreboard situation will improve, according to Bobby
Goldwater, the arena's senior vice president and general manager.
``We're waiting for some software,'' he says. ``We'll have
everything in place by the first (regular-season) game next Tuesday
night.''
</P>
<P>
   The Staples Center is everything _ good and bad _ we've all come
to expect from a modern indoor sports/entertainment venue. If one
thing is clear by now, it is that the modest druthers of a
committed sports fan who needs nothing more than a comfortable seat
and a few places to grab a hot dog and something to drink have been
overwhelmed by the seemingly insatiable demands of an entirely
different class of people whose priorities mystify the rest of us.
As one member of the Clippers' stat crew said during Wednesday
night's inaugural Staples Center basketball game (a Clipper loss,
naturally), ``To be honest, I had no problems with the Sports
Arena. The sight lines were great. I didn't need all this.''
</P>
<P>
   Luxury suites are now the engines that drive all indoor and
outdoor arena/stadium construction, so it should come as no
surprise that what distinguishes the Staples Center, as opposed to
all other such venues that have sprouted up in the past decade or
so, is the overwhelming visual spectre of the suites. It's not that
there are so many _ 160, or 50-some fewer than Chicago's United
Center _ as much as it is how big they are. In all other buildings,
the suites are clearly adjuncts. Not here. In this building the
clear impression is that the suites are totally and utterly primary
and the 16,000 other seats are clearly and utterly secondary. Now
we all know this to be the actual case, but in no other new arena
is it made so obvious. There is no ambiguity here. The seats here
are attached to the suites, not the other way around.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Springsteen, that noted Man of the People, had his own
commentary on the Them-vs.-Us nature of the modern arena. Surveying
the scene as he formally opened the building Oct. 18, he looked up
at the suites and said, ``Come on out, now. The show is starting.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a have-have situation,'' protests Goldwater, a longtime
Madison Square Garden executive who is now one of the many proud
Staples Center poppas. ``Yes, we have great luxury suites. But it's
also a good deal for the average fan. For example, in the Forum
there are four restrooms and four refreshment stands. Here we have
55 restrooms and 23 refreshment stands. And we have 1,200
television monitors.''
</P>
<P>
   From a GM's viewpoint, there's a lot to be proud of. Philip F.
Anschutz, a publicity shy multi-billionaire, is the big money man
behind the project and he did it right. There are, for example,
81,000 square feet of Terrazzo tile in the joint, not to mention 11
escalators and 10 elevators. It is LA, after all. It took a
monumental effort by both municipal and private forces to make this
downtown enterprise come to life, and they weren't about to do a
half-baked job.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to imagine this building not becoming a financial
success. With all those teams and all those shows and all those
Happenings, the building will be heavily used. ``Between now and
the end of June, we only have eight nights when the building is not
committed to something,'' Goldwater points out. ``And we've
reserved two days for changeover practice from basketball to hockey
and vice-versa.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to six basketball-hockey doubleheaders, the Staples
Center will be the scene of an interesting home-and-home series
between the Clippers and Lakers Jan. 4 and 5. On the 4th, the
Clippers will host the Lakers. On the 5th, the Lakers will host the
Clippers. And have we mentioned that each team has its own personal
floor?
</P>
<P>
   ``We were hoping the league office would want to allow us to
have a little fun with that,'' says Goldwater, ``and we did.''
</P>
<P>
   People here will like it. Intelligently located at the
convergence of several major freeways, and properly glitzy, the
Staples Center will quickly become the sports and entertainment
mecca for the entire West Coast. LA has gotten what it wants.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did a building that was right for us,'' points out
Goldwater, ``just as Indiana has done with a building that was
right for Indianapolis. They've got their `fieldhouse' look. We've
got outdoor terraces. You wouldn't want an outdoor terrace in
Indianapolis.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the Hoosier State you'd damn well better have a decent
scoreboard, even for an exhibition game.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
