<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECON-REPORT-ART-910(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLEASANTLY PUZZLING NEW REPORT ON ECONOMY SHOWS HEARTY GAINS
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By LOUIS UCHITELLE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The U.S. economy turned in its best quarterly performance of the
year this summer, virtually guaranteeing enough momentum to carry
the nation to its longest economic expansion in history early next
year.
</P>
<P>
   Strong growth often leads to shortages and rising prices. But as
the economy expanded at a brisk 4.8 percent annual rate in the
June-September quarter, inflation turned out to be mild and the
cost to employers of wages and benefits rose only modestly. The
combination of robust growth with little evidence of higher
inflation was so popular on Wall Street that the value of stocks
and bonds soared. The Dow Jones industrial average rose more than
227 points, or 2.19 percent, to 10,622.53. Other indexes chalked up
similarly impressive gains.
</P>
<P>
   The stock market's sharp rise reflected an expectation that the
Federal Reserve's policy-makers _ who have raised interest rates
twice this year in an attempt to prevent the economy from
overheating _ may be less likely to do so yet again at their next
meeting, on Nov. 16. And even if the Fed pushes rates slightly
higher again next month, analysts say, it now appears more likely
to refrain from further increases in the near future unless
inflation shows clear signs of worsening.
</P>
<P>
   The Commerce Department, at the same time as it provided its
fresh snapshot of the economy, also released a sweeping revision of
its past data, stretching back to 1959, that is intended to make
the government's measures of economic performance reflect the new
electronic technologies that are now so important. The revised
numbers showed the 1990s to be a decade of notably stronger
economic growth than originally reported, although not stronger
than any of the last four decades.
</P>
<P>
   What distinguishes the performance of the economy in the 1990s
is the length of the expansion, which began in March 1991 and will
surpass the 106-month record set in the 1960s if it lasts until
next February.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials cited the latest growth numbers
as evidence of the success of their economic policies. President
Clinton called the 1990s expansion ``the soundest in decades.'' And
Martin Baily, chairman of the White House Council of Economic
Advisers, linked the economy to what he described as the
administration's success in shifting the budget from deficit to
surplus.
</P>
<P>
   ``The private sector is generating the strong growth,'' Baily
said, ``but good economic policies have created an environment for
growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Caveats, however, punctuated the euphoria. ``What we have here
is consumption and investment growing faster than income,'' said
Albert Wojnilower, an economic consultant in New York. ``How are
people doing this? They are borrowing money, counting on the gains
in the stock market and in the value of their homes to help them
carry their debt.''
</P>
<P>
   Separately, the Labor Department released its Employment Cost
Index for the third quarter Thursday. This is the government's
broadest measure of labor costs, covering benefits as well as
wages, salaries and bonuses. It is closely watched on Wall Street
for evidence that rising labor costs will force companies to raise
prices, a prospect that often prompts traders to sell stocks and
drive up interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the strong economy and the labor shortages evident
in an unemployment rate of only 4.2 percent, the index rose by only
0.8 percent and 3.1 percent over the last 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   The broadest measure of the economy's performance is the gross
domestic product, which tracks the rising value of all goods and
services produced in the nation. Growth had slowed in the second
quarter, to a 1.9 percent annual rate, but bounced back sharply in
the third quarter, with the GDP, at an annual rate, rising by $106
billion to an inflation-adjusted $8.88 trillion.
</P>
<P>
   The largest component of that growth was attributed to a 4.3
percent rise in consumer spending, which was stronger in the third
quarter than in the second. But a big part of the increase in
output resulted from businesses deciding to build up their
inventories rather than draining them as they did in the second
quarter. They carried out this stockpiling in anticipation of
future sales, particularly sales of new car models, and also as a
precaution in the event of year 2000 computer-related disruptions,
analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Much of the inventory expansion came from motor vehicle
stockpiling at the dealer level,'' said Brent Moulton, associate
commissioner at the Bureau of Economic Analysis, ``but
manufacturers also stockpiled, mostly durable goods _ aircraft
parts perhaps, appliances, machinery and equipment.''
</P>
<P>
   Stepped up investment, in computers, software, trucks, buses and
aircraft, also played a big role in the third-quarter jump in
economic growth, and an increase in government spending at all
levels contributed to the rising economy. But strong growth in the
future seems uncertain to many economists. They expect the economy
to start slowing by early next year and point to what they see as
the first signs of that slowing.
</P>
<P>
   The housing market has weakened as mortgage rates have risen,
they note. Vehicle sales have edged down from their summer peak and
consumer spending, while still strong, has grown more slowly since
last fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have experienced four consecutive months of declines in
consumer confidence, and debt is inordinately high,'' said David
Wyss, chief economist at Standard &AMP; Poor's DRI. ``That has to take
its toll.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The puzzles in Thursday's reports were the mild labor cost
increases despite widely reported labor shortages and the slower
rise in a price index that the Commerce Department uses to
calculate economic growth. The index rose at a 1.3 percent annual
rate in the second quarter and 1 percent in the third.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever merchandise is in short supply because of the strong
economy is brought in from abroad, and that helps to hold down
prices,'' Wojnilower said, noting that imports had risen in the
third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Business executives insist that they have difficulty raising
prices because of growing competition in a global marketplace.
What's more, labor costs are not rising rapidly enough to force
price increases _ for a variety of reasons, economists say.
</P>
<P>
   One involves inflation. Because it is mild, workers are
demanding smaller increases. The widespread availability of
temporary workers means that employers are not under pressure to
raise wages to fill jobs. Bonuses and profit sharing have
increasingly replaced raises. And manufacturing employment has
declined by 500,000 jobs since March of 1998, with many of the
displaced workers taking service sector jobs at lower pay.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Lazar, an economist and partner at the ISI Group, a Wall
Street firm, cites mergers as still another explanation for mild
labor cost increases. ``The reason workers are not pressing for
higher wages,'' she said, ``is that mergers are running high and
layoffs as companies combine operations. Layoffs keep labor on the
defensive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
