<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1697 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-ANGEL-HISTORY-COX     10-28 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANGEL-HISTORY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Angels have history of high standards
 &HT;    By Jingle Davis and Ron Martz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Blue Angels, an envelope-pushing team of crackerjack Navy
pilots, was formed following World War II to boost Navy morale,
attract recruits and catch the admiring eye of Congress with
death-defying barrel rolls when budget time rolled around.
</P>
<P>
   But even the daredevil Angels have been deviled by crashes that
have killed 25 of their number through the years, including two
pilots killed Thursday near Moody Air Force Base in South Georgia.
No spectator has ever been harmed, however, and until Thursday, the
Angels had not had a fatal accident in over a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Blue Angels were formed in 1946, the team, based at
the Pensacola Naval Air Station in Florida, has performed for more
than 322 million people, flying 60 to 70 shows a year at some 35
sites across the nation. The six-pilot team now flies F/A-18
Hornets.
</P>
<P>
   Before Thursday, the last crash involving the squad was in 1990.
The last death was in 1985, in Niagara Falls, N.Y. Lt. Cmdr.
Michael Gershon was killed when two planes collided during an air
show.
</P>
<P>
   The team flew into heavy weather in 1995 when their commander,
Donnie Cochran, a Pelham, Ga., native, stepped down, saying he was
worried about his own flying performance and did not want to
threaten his pilots' safety. Cochran was the first black man ever
to lead the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   Cochran had taken the team back into intensive training after
lining up above the wrong runway during a high-speed, low-level
maneuver at Oceana Naval Air Station in Virginia Beach, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Every Blue Angel maneuver involves a series of procedures that
must be performed in precise sequence and with split-second timing
_ a tightly choreographed aerial ballet staged at 400 miles an
hour.
</P>
<P>
   At Oceana, one of the heart-stopping maneuvers above a crowd of
150,000 people called for four of the Angels' fighter jets to cross
simultaneously over a single point from different directions, using
two runways as their marks.
</P>
<P>
   Cochran, who was said to have trouble ``hitting his marks,''
approached the point over the wrong runway. He resigned as leader,
citing concern for the team.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier that same year, the Angels had canceled a show because
of performance problems with a pilot who was later replaced.
</P>
<P>
   So sensitive are the Angels to their high-profile mission that
team members can be dismissed for even the appearance of
impropriety.
</P>
<P>
   This June, the group commander removed a pilot and a team public
affairs officer for ``a loss of trust and confidence.'' An official
said the two had been directed to end a ``personal relationship,''
which involved jogging together and other activities of a
non-sexual nature, to avoid the perception of an inappropriate
relationship. The two ignored the directive and were reassigned,
the official said.
</P>
<P>
   Another scandal threatened the Angels' image in 1994, when the
Navy grounded Cmdr. Robert Stumpf, team leader at the time, because
he was under investigation for possible involvement in the 1991
Tailhook sexual harassment scandal. During the now-infamous
Tailhook Symposium, Stumpf was present in the unit's hospitality
suite as strippers performed. Although the convening authority
sought to charge him with conduct unbecoming an officer, he was
cleared by a special board of inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   But he remained on a list of officers named in the Defense
Department Inspector General's Tailhook report as being potentially
guilty of wrongdoing during the convention. He has since retired.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Angels' worst accident was in 1973, when two pilots and
a crew chief were killed when two planes flying belly-to-belly
collided.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force has its own precision flying team, the
Thunderbirds. The Thunderbirds were grounded for almost a month
this spring after a minor in-air collision in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   One of the pilots involved was subsequently removed from the
team.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first such action in six years and only the second
time the Thunderbirds had put shows on hold since a 1982 crash that
killed four pilots.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
