r a BC-ADL-HATE-COX     10-28 0507
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ADL-HATE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rise in hate crimes stirs concern at ADL forum
 &HT;    By Ron Martz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Millennium Madness. Generation Y. World Church of the
Creator.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next few years these could become buzzwords in the
language of violence in America, leaders of the Anti-Defamation
League were told Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Killorin, special agent in charge of the Atlanta office of
the federal Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms, said that
despite a recent downturn in crime, especially youth crime, the
future does not necessarily look all that bright.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to say the darkest clouds are behind us, but I fear
the darkest clouds are still ahead of us,'' Killorin said at the
opening session of the ADL's 85th annual national meeting in
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ADL leaders worry that three separate violent incidents this
summer aimed primarily at Jews could be the harbinger of more
attacks and a reversal of a decades-long decline in anti-Semitic
views in this country.
</P>
<P>
   The incidents included the burning of three synagogues in
Sacramento, Calif., allegedly by two brothers with ties to the
anti-Semitic World Church of the Creator; shootings in Indiana and
Illinois that killed two and wounded six and were carried out by a
former member of the World Church of the Creator; and the shootings
by an avowed white supremacist at a Jewish community center in Los
Angeles. David Lehrer, director of the ADL's Los Angeles office,
said the violence in his community that was directed primarily at
children caught many Jews by surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``For most of the Jewish community (in Los Angeles)
anti-Semitism is an esoteric subject that really doesn't apply to
them. It's something that their parents had to deal with,'' Lehrer
said.
</P>
<P>
   The confessed gunman, Buford Furrow, who shot and killed a
Filipino mail carrier before he gave himself up, has been linked to
the Aryan Nations and the Phineas Priesthood. Both are virulently
anti-Semitic.
</P>
<P>
   Many right-wing extremist groups such as Aryan Nations are using
the advent of the new millennium to foment hate, according to
experts, by predicting a breakdown in society that will lead to
race wars and an eventual end-time battle.
</P>
<P>
   The coming of age of the so-called Generation Y could also lead
to increased violence, Killorin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``About 2012, we will have the largest bubble of young men that
we've ever had in the country,'' Killorin said. ``The end of
Generation X and the beginning of Generation Y has brought us these
high school shootings.''
</P>
<P>
   But this summer's incidents have made more people aware of
anti-Semitic activity and other hate crimes, ADL members said.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Bernstein, director of the ADL's San Francisco office,
said the Sacramento community drew together after the synagogue
burnings to provide support and money to help rebuild them.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is noghtened consciousness and awareness of
hate,'' Hirschhaut said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
