<HEADER>
A1706 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-WORLDSERIES-SCOUT     10-28 1083
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-WORLDSERIES-SCOUT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCOUTING REPORT ON THE FRONT OFFICE: GREAT JOB 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The lineup on the field included names like Knoblauch, Jeter,
O'Neill, Williams, Martinez, Girardi and Brosius. Everyone knows
them. The names in the Yankees' other lineup are not so well known:
Michael, Didier, Taylor, Oppenheimer, Webber, Wurth, Hansen, Caro.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, among that other lineup, Gene Michael is known because
he has performed a vast variety of duties for the Yankees in the
last three decades _ playing, coaching, managing, general managing
and scouting. He has never performed better than he did the past
two months in directing the staff that scouted the three teams the
Yankees easily vanquished in the postseason, concluding with their
four-game World Series sweep of the Atlanta Braves.
</P>
<P>
   As scouts are quick to point out, the players have to take the
information and execute on the field, but it was obvious that the
Yankees took critical information onto the field with them. They
won 11 of their 12 postseason games, strongly indicating that they
knew something about their opponents before they pitched to them
and swung at their pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very much impressed with what the Yankees did against
the Braves' hitters,'' Carmen Fusco, the Mets' director of
professional scouting, said Thursday. ``I was at the games and
watched what they did, and their crew did a very good job.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' scouts had the benefit of watching the Mets'
pitchers hold the Braves to a .223 batting average after they had
hit .304 in their division series against the Houston Astros.
``They pitched their hitters very much the same way we pitched
their hitters,'' Fusco said.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves batted .200 against the Yankees, needing three
eighth-inning hits in Game 4 to get even that high. Before that
flurry of singles, the Braves were hitting .187 in the Series.
</P>
<P>
   George Steinbrenner gushed about a lot of things in the
emotional aftermath of the team's record-tying second successive
World Series sweep, but he particularly praised the role the scouts
played in the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's talk about the scouting staff of Gene Michael and the
job they did on scouting these teams,'' the owner said. ``I'll put
them up against anybody. They all deserve a bow.''
</P>
<P>
   And to think that one of the first steps Steinbrenner took when
he and his partners bought the Yankees in 1973 was to slash the
scouting staff on the premise that the team didn't need as many
scouts as it had. At least he didn't say, as Marge Schott did when
she ran the Cincinnati Reds, ``All they do is watch games.''
</P>
<P>
   But Steinbrenner subsequently learned that scouts are the
backbone of an organization and rebuilt his staff. Now the Yankees
probably lead the league in some scouting areas.
</P>
<P>
   They have, for example, two advance scouts to follow coming
opponents during the season where other teams have one. For the
post-season, they started with two scouts on each possible
opponent, then doubled that number as teams began dropping out of
contention.
</P>
<P>
   Michael stepped down as Steinbrenner's general manager after the
1995 season rather than take a cut in pay. He became a scout for
the team, watching games played in East Coast cities, then was
named director of major league scouting. He was responsible for
planning the postseason scouting strategy, deploying organization
scouts throughout both leagues.
</P>
<P>
   He also headed the eight-man contingent that watched the Mets
give the Braves a difficult time. Joining him were Bob Didier and
Wade Taylor, the advance scouts; Ron Hansen, a major league scout;
Joe Caro, who scouts professional players out of Tampa, Fla.; Damon
Oppenheimer, a national cross-checker from Phoenix, and two scouts
whose primary job is to find the best amateur players, Steve Webber
of Watkinsville, Ga., and Leon Wurth of Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have two scouts on every team in contention in September,''
Michael said, describing the plan of attack the scouting team
followed. ``We do the American League first. We started Sept. 3
this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``On Sept. 17 we started on the National League. We had two on
each contending team over there. We stayed on them until they were
eliminated or we knew they were not going to be in it. We stayed on
the Mets. We stayed on Atlanta. We stayed on Houston all the time
until they weren't there.''
</P>
<P>
   When a two-man team followed a team, Michael said: ``One does
the offense. One does the defense. Then they both do strategy,
outfield arms, bunting, who bunts, who steals, counts they steal
on, tendencies. By having one doing offense and one doing defense,
they can get better detail during the game because it's tough
watching the pitchers, watching the defense, watching the hitters
on the other team. We have the luxury of putting a little bit more
into it.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Braves-Mets series, Michael said, he, Oppenheimer,
Didier and Taylor watched both teams, Webber and Werth focused on
the Braves and Hansen and Caro did the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the Mets lost,'' the former shortstop said, ``Hansen and
Caro went home and the six of us met on Atlanta and put the report
together. The three scouts who did the hitters for Atlanta were
scouting for our pitchers. We all get together and give an opinion
on it. Then we did a consensus sort of thing about their pitchers
for our hitters.''
</P>
<P>
   Scouts derive a special pleasure from watching a postseason game
and seeing their ideas unfold on the field. Then there are the
instances where a pitcher or a hitter doesn't follow the scouts'
recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Naturally you're going to see a mistake, in your opinion, now
and then,'' Michael said. ``You see something you disagree with,
like what a pitcher should have thrown, and you wonder why. You try
to cut that down. You try to give them a better idea. I think our
guys did a pretty good job with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael thought of one exception, the approach some hitters took
against Pedro Martinez, the Boston pitcher, who was No. 1 in the
American League this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``He threw a lot of changeups to a couple of our hitters and it
seemed like they were never ready for them,'' Michael said. ``They
were looking for the fastball, but he threw so many changes. Any
time a pitcher is going to throw that many changes I think it's
kind of silly to look for that many fastballs.''
</P>
<P>
   The Martinez game was the only one the Yankees lost in this
postseason.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-99 2025EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
