</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-WORLDSERIES-COMPARE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN ANOTHER SPORT IN ANOTHER COUNTRY, A SIMILAR SUCCESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Their 25th World Series championship puts the Yankees well ahead
of all major league baseball teams and nearly all other franchises
in the professional sports leagues of North America. But the
Yankees lead one team by just a single title: the Montreal
Canadiens of the National Hockey League, who have won the Stanley
Cup 24 times. The Yankees passed the Canadiens on Wednesday night
when they beat the Atlanta Braves by 4-1 to take the 1999 baseball
championship in a four-game sweep.
</P>
<P>
   In sheer total of championships, no other franchise in any city
or any sport is even close to the Yankees and Canadiens, who are
situated roughly 300 miles apart on different sides of an
international border. Even their team names evoke something
patriotic beyond their sports. In colonial times, yankee referred
to a native of New England; later, of course, it became slang for
American. The name Canadiens is derived from the French word for
Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are the teams of the national imagination,'' said Ken
Dryden, the Montreal goalie for six of those Stanley Cup
championships. Dryden, now the president of the Toronto Maple
Leafs, is an enthusiastic baseball fan.
</P>
<P>
   As for the other two major leagues, basketball and football, the
Boston Celtics of the National Basketball Association have won 16
championships and the Green Bay Packers of the National Football
League have won 12.
</P>
<P>
   Dryden played in Montreal for Coach Scotty Bowman, who won five
championship rings with the Canadiens and three more with other
teams. Bowman's two most recent titles came with the Detroit Red
Wings, his current team, which will seek its third cup in four
seasons next spring. That feat would equal that of Yankee Manager
Joe Torre, who has three championships since 1996. Bowman knows
baseball and he knows Torre, too. They met in the 1960s in St.
Louis, when Bowman coached the Blues and Torre played for the
Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to compare what is common about dynastic teams in sports,
Bowman said: ``A lot of things are the same. Every season, they
seem to add players who help them get over the top. These teams
have role players who play big roles, and the stars come through.
The ownership in Montreal was real devoted and their focus was
always on winning, both the Bronfmans and the Molsons before them.
</P>
<P>
   ``They gave you the feeling they would do everything they could
to win the cup. You feel that's what they want more than anything
else. If they don't get it, they aren't happy. I think George
Steinbrenner gives you the same feeling with the Yankees. It makes
it a real easier job for the coach or the manager.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked to compare the Yankees and the Canadiens, Bowman said:
``They both have pretty good histories. Both have had a few dry
spells, but a lot of hot spots, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Yankees, the Canadiens are not the team of the
current decade. They are more like the forgettable Yankees of the
late 1960s and early 1970s. In recent seasons, Montreal's fortunes
have grown as cold as its ice. The team's last championship was in
1993 and the previous one was in 1986. Their last consistent run of
success came when Bowman's teams won four consecutive cups from
1976 through 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Dryden, when asked to compare the current Yankees to the
Canadiens of the Bowman era, said he sees some similarities between
the management styles of Bowman and Torre. ``Scotty was important,
Scotty was central,'' Dryden said. ``But he never insisted on being
the main guy. Torre is that way, too. Torre demands with a more
friendly face than Scotty, but the demands are still there.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowman grew up in Montreal as a fan of the minor league Royals,
a baseball farm club for the Brooklyn Dodgers. For Sunday
doubleheaders, he and his friends took one-hour bus rides from
their neighborhood to the ball park at Delormier Downs to see
Jackie Robinson, Roy Campanella, Don Newcombe and the other boys of
summer as they worked toward the majors while baseball's racial
barrier was being broken.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two-hundred, ninety-seven feet down the right-field line,''
Bowman recalled. ``Left field was 370. Kind of a funny park.
Robinson's team won the Little World Series in September. It was
just about snowing.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowman saw his first major league baseball game in New York at
the Polo Grounds in 1951, a World Series game between the Yankees
and the Giants. He and a friend took a bus from Montreal, and they
bought their tickets on the sidewalk before two of the games. ``We
scrounged it, somehow,'' said Bowman, who was 18 at the time.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1980s, when he was already well established in
hockey as the general manager of the Buffalo Sabres, Bowman saw
Mickey Mantle while waiting to change planes at Chicago's O'Hare
airport. He got Mantle's autograph for his son, who was then in
Little League. Bowman said Mantle did not recognize him but was
gracious about signing. Mantle personalized the greeting by using
the boy's name. (It is Stanley, as in Stanley Cup.)
</P>
<P>
   Comparing dynasties in different sports is inexact and tricky.
The Canadiens' first cup was won in 1916, before the formation of
the modern NHL. By then, the major leagues of baseball had been
playing a formal World Series for more than a decade. The
Canadiens' second cup came in 1924, when teams from outside the NHL
could still challenge for the trophy. Montreal's best continuous
streak came from 1956 through 1960, five consecutive championships.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics have won 16 titles in a league that was the last to
form, in 1946. On a proportional basis, no team has dominated its
league more than Boston, which won 11 of 13 championships between
1957 and 1969, including eight in succession. The Canadiens' best
span was 16 championships in 27 years, from 1953 through 1979 _
exactly the same as the Yankees' best sequence of 16 championships
in 27 years, between 1936 and 1962.
</P>
<P>
   In the National Football League, the compilation of titles is
muddled because the Super Bowl has been played only since 1967, and
it was not considered the league championship until 1970. In those
first years, the Super Bowl was a special game between the
champions of the NFL and the American Football League. And although
the NFL was formed in 1920, no formal championship game was held
until 1933, when the Chicago Bears beat the Giants, 23-21. The
Packers finished first in three consecutive seasons, 1929 through
1931. They are the only team to win three consecutive titles, and
they did it again by winning championship games in 1965, 1966 and
1967.
</P>
<P>
   In the modern era, with drafting, free agency and expansion, it
will be more difficult for any franchise in any sport to build a
dynasty similar to the Yankees and the Canadiens.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the Yankees and Canadiens, their greatest dynasties were
in dynastic times, when it was easier to have dynasties,'' Dryden
said. ``In some ways, the deck wasn't entirely stacked, but they
had more benefits. There were natural advantages. They basically
stemmed from the fact that there wasn't a draft. You could go out
and tie up players. That's what makes dynasties harder today to
create and sustain.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Dryden knew the Yankees and Canadiens had a similar
number of championships, he did not realize until Thursday that New
York had surpassed Montreal's total. When the bottom line _ 25 to
24 _ was mentioned to him, Dryden paused and sighed. ``Geez,
Murphy,'' he said, softly, the disappointment evident in his voice
over the line from Canada.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
