<SLUG> BC-SCI-MAMMOTH-DNA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOPES OF CLONING A MAMMOTH DIM AFTER FROZEN SPECIMENS ARE FOUND TO
BE DAMAGED  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ariz., Germany, France)   By NICHOLAS WADE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Hopes of cloning a frozen Siberian mammoth have been
dimmed by the finding that DNA retrieved from other mammoths
retains genetic information but is highly fragmented.
</P>
<P>
   Alex D. Greenwood, a molecular biologist at the American Museum
of Natural History, said on Wednesday that he had examined DNA from
the teeth of a mammoth found in the permafrost in Alaska, where it
died almost 14,000 years ago, and from the jaws and soft tissue of
mammoths found in Siberia.
</P>
<P>
   The animals have been frozen since their deaths and appear very
well preserved. ``I have samples of bone marrow that stink like
rotting meat,'' Greenwood said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their apparent freshness and promising odor, at the
genetic level the mammoths' remains were in rockier state. ``Even
though the samples are pristine, the DNA has suffered terribly over
time,'' Greenwood said. ``My studies show you can retrieve snippets
of DNA, but that's a long way from cloning an animal.''
</P>
<P>
   The notion of cloning a mammoth has come from Larry D. Agenbroad
of Northern Arizona University in Flagstaff. A geologist who has
long been interested in mammoths, Agenbroad was called in as a
consultant by Bernard Buigues, a French polar explorer who learned
of an intact mammoth, 11 feet tall, that was found in permafrost in
the Taimyr Peninsula of Siberia.
</P>
<P>
   Agenbroad told The Associated Press earlier this month that
besides studying the animal's stomach contents, a primary task
would be to clone a mammoth by extracting DNA and letting it
develop in the egg of an Asian elephant, the mammoth's closest
living relative.
</P>
<P>
   Frozen mammoths are usually excavated from the ice with
hot-water jets that destroy both their soft tissues and the
surrounding materials, which may hold essential clues to the cause
of death and the environment at the time.
</P>
<P>
   But the Taimyr mammoth was cut out of the ice intact, the first
mammoth to be retrieved in this way, Agenbroad said on Wednesday.
Last week it was airlifted to a military airstrip at Khatanga in
Siberia, where it is to be stored in an ice tunnel as soon as the
entrance to the tunnel can be enlarged.
</P>
<P>
   The specimen is a male mammoth, about 40 years old when it died.
Radiocarbon testing of its hair found that it died 20,380 years
ago, Agenbroad said. He has invited other scientists to conduct a
thorough examination of its tissues and did not seem particularly
discouraged by Greenwood's findings. Flesh or hair may yield better
quality DNA samples than a tooth, Agenbroad said, and in any case
``the cloning is an exciting possibility but it's not our main
focus.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenwood said the Taimyr mammoth was ``a beautiful find, but in
terms of DNA my guess is that it will be like most other samples,''
meaning the DNA would be heavily degraded and fragmented.
</P>
<P>
   Even if intact DNA were available, he said, trying to clone it
in an Asian elephant, a species from which mammoths diverged some 5
million years ago, would be ``the equivalent of crossing a human
with a chimpanzee.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Agenbroad and Greenwood are interested in the many ice age
animals, and possibly even people, whose bodies lie preserved in
the permafrost of Siberia and Alaska. DNA would be of great help
for many kinds of biological study, particularly in determining an
animal's evolutionary history and the size of its population.
</P>
<P>
   Many early claims of recovering DNA from tissues millions of
years old, such as dinosaur bones or insects embedded in amber,
have proved impossible to repeat. Any DNA in such tests probably
came from modern contaminants, such as bacteria, or the scientists'
own fingerprints. The early cloud of disrepute that settled on the
field was somewhat dispelled after scientists learned the rigorous
experimental procedures necessary to avoid contamination.
</P>
<P>
   Reports of ancient DNA as old as 30,000 years are now regarded
as plausible. In 1997 Dr. Svante Paabo, an authority on ancient DNA
at the University of Munich in Germany, isolated DNA from the
skeletal remains of a Neanderthal of the same age.
</P>
<P>
   Greenwood, who trained in Paabo's laboratory, hopes that further
studies of mammoth DNA will allow him to reconstruct their
evolutionary history and perhaps the manner of their extinction.
The snippets that have been analyzed so far, which he and his
colleagues describe in the November issue of the journal Molecular
Biology and Evolution, suggest that mammoths are more closely
related to Asian elephants than to African elephants.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier mammoth studies have focused on the DNA of the
mitochondria, components of the cell that provide its energy. As
each cell may have a thousand mitochondria, this kind of DNA is
much more plentiful and easier to retrieve from ancient samples
than is the DNA of the nucleus.
</P>
<P>
   Mammoths and elephants cannot be compared on the basis of their
mitochondrial DNA, which led Greenwood and his colleagues to
develop techniques for recovering the much rarer genes of the DNA
in the cell's nucleus. The nuclear DNA, they hope, will allow a
much broader range of genetic studies.
</P>
</TEXT>
