<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-WORLDSERIES-FUTURE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMID THE CHEERS, QUESTIONS ABOUT 2000 BEGIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Yankees' championship celebrations have evolved
beyond the uncontrolled spraying of champagne. Sure, there was some
dousing done after they wiped out the Atlanta Braves in the World
Series, completing their sweep with a 4-1 victory in Game 4 at
Yankee Stadium on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Clemens, having finally shed the tag of postseason
underachiever, was soaked, and Derek Jeter dumped some champagne
over the head of a giggling George Steinbrenner, the Yankees'
principal owner, who indicated that he would get even. But after
the immediate euphoria, many of the Yankees celebrated in their own
way _ Clemens retrieved two of his sons, David Cone posed for
pictures with New York's finest, Scott Brosius played with his
children as they ran around the infield.
</P>
<P>
   Paul O'Neill, whose father had died earlier in the day, spoke
with emotion about Charles O'Neill, his voice rising, sounding not
so much like an All-Star baseball player but like the youngest
child who already missed his father.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Torre, the Yankees' manager, had traded hugs with Brosius
and infielder Luis Sojo and his bench coach, Don Zimmer; it felt
like family, Brosius said afterward, and while this family had
reason to celebrate, there was a real sense in the Yankees'
clubhouse that this had been a very difficult year, personally and
professionally.
</P>
<P>
   Torre was treated for prostate cancer in March. Outfielder
Darryl Strawberry had struggled in his recovery from colon cancer,
and a relapse in his drinking problem led to his subsequent arrest
for solicitation and drug possession. All year, too, the Yankees
had grown weary of the constant comparisons to the record-setting
1998 team: the players complained that it was the news media doing
this, but O'Neill, Cone and others acknowledged that the players
themselves had fallen into this trap, and that only increased the
tremendous pressure that sometimes wore on them.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, however, the 1999 Yankees can say that they had the
best record in the American League, that they blew through the
playoffs by winning 11 of 12 games and that they won their third
World Series in four years. ``It was absolutely sensational to be
able to accomplish what we accomplished this year,'' Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner said: ``This has to rank at the top. Three out of
four is pretty damn good. It's not like it used to be. You have
three layers of playoffs. The third layer of playoffs doesn't make
it twice as difficult _ it might be five times as difficult. There
are more chances for a team to become unfocused and slip up.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Yankees have remained focused, and there is no doubt
that during their victory parade Friday they will feel the first
bit of the pressure that will face them next season when somebody
yells or asks aloud: can they become the first team since the
Oakland Athletics of 1972-74 to win three consecutive titles?
</P>
<P>
   Brian Cashman, the Yankees' general manager, figures the
planning for the 2000 season will begin ``just about the time the
parade ends,'' in discussions that will take place over the next
few days.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' first decision of the off season will very likely
be whether to exercise a $6.5 million option on O'Neill, which must
be determined within the next six days. The Yankees are seeking
ways to restrain and reconfigure their payroll, to rearrange their
budget so they can pay their two best players, shortstop Derek
Jeter and the closer Mariano Rivera, both of whom are eligible for
arbitration after making $5 million and $4.25 million,
respectively, this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees might feel greedy and pursue a deal for another
outfielder, like Toronto's Shawn Green or Cleveland's Manny
Ramirez, both of whom will be eligible for free agency after the
2000 season. But in the short term, that route would be far more
expensive and complicated _ the Yankees would have to trade top
prospects and arrange a contract extension for the new player that
would cost them tens of millions of dollars _ than keeping O'Neill
for another year. O'Neill will be 37 next season, but this year he
hit a respectable .285 and drove in 110 runs.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens is under contract at $8.1 million for next year, but he
has the right to demand a trade within 15 days of the World Series.
Executives with other teams suspect that when Clemens was swapped
to the Yankees in February, Steinbrenner reached an understanding
on a contract extension with his agents _ the same sort of
arrangement made when the Yankees traded for Chuck Knoblauch before
the 1998 season.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens seemed evasive when asked about his future with the
Yankees in the clubhouse after the sweep, saying he hoped it would
work out so he could stay with the team. For the immediate future,
he has full control of the issue. If Clemens, having achieved the
goal of winning a championship, wanted to finish his career in his
home state, Texas, and live closer to his ailing mother, Bess
Clemens, then he could effectively force the Yankees to trade him.
</P>
<P>
   Cone is eligible for free agency, after throwing well most of
the season, making the American League All-Star team and earning
$9.5 million this season, $8 million in base salary and $1.5
million from an incentive clause.
</P>
<P>
   Cone has not explicitly stated what he wants in his next
contract, but there is a very simple Yankees equation as they
consider their options. They have a five-man rotation and already
have six candidates for starting jobs under contract: Clemens, if
he chooses to stay; Orlando Hernandez, who made $1.85 million; Andy
Pettitte, who made $5.95 million and is eligible for arbitration;
Hideki Irabu, who made $2 million; Ramiro Mendoza, who is eligible
for arbitration, and Jeff Juden, who has agreed to a one-year,
$500,000 major league contract after spending almost the entire
season at Class AAA Columbus.
</P>
<P>
   If it is important to Steinbrenner and his executives to retain
Cone, then all parties involved will make it happen _ and if he
does come back, it will likely be because either Pettitte or
Clemens is traded. The big X factor in Cone's case, of course, is
how Steinbrenner will react if the Mets become seriously involved
in bidding for him.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees must decide whether to keep Pettitte for another
year or revisit trade talks with the Philadelphia Phillies.
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Joe Girardi is eligible for free agency, and while the
conventional wisdom is that Girardi will ultimately sign with the
Chicago Cubs, Steinbrenner could intercede again and find a way to
bring him back, at a salary greatly reduced from the $3.4 million
Girardi earned this year.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Stanton, who played an important role as the left-handed
setup man out of the bullpen, may get bigger offers from other
teams and may not be back. The designated hitter Chili Davis will
not be back with the Yankees, and it seems unlikely that Jim
Leyritz will be retained. The Yankees might explore the possibility
of trading Brosius to rid themselves of his $5.25 million salary,
and they are expected to talk to the San Diego Padres about a
possible deal for pitcher Andy Ashby, especially if Clemens is
gone.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees will be honored Friday for what they accomplished in
1999, but right away the executives who put this team together will
be thinking about next year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
