<HEADLINE>
REGIONAL IS HEADED FOR A SOFT LANDING, ECONOMISTS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eight boisterous years of economic expansion that has brought
prosperity even to remote corners of northern New England now
appears headed for a soft landing. But the question remains when.
</P>
<P>
   Economists who are members of the New England Economic Project
on Thursday hedged their forecasts of a downturn, saying the
surprising strength of the current expansion has caused them to be
wrong in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``The major question for the Maine economy is when the slowdown
will come,'' said Charles Colgan, a University of Southern Maine
professor who took part in a project meeting in Needham.
</P>
<P>
   Fueled by the success of financial companies such as MBNA Corp.,
Maine is experiencing stronger job growth this year than in 1998,
so strong, Colgan said, that a logging company has been unable to
fill positions in rural northern Aroostook County, where such a
problem is rarely seen.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Delay, economist for the Public Service Co. of New
Hampshire, characterized his state's economy as ``one of the
strongest in the country,'' with about 10,000 jobs added this year
alone.
</P>
<P>
   In Vermont, the boom has reached into the usually depressed
corner known as the Northeast Kingdom, and economic growth
statewide is more than 1.5 percent. ``It's tough to complain,''
said Jeffrey Carr of Economic and Policy Resources Inc.
</P>
<P>
   But the best may be over, the economists said. Job growth across
New England this year is expected to be 1.6 percent, down from 2.3
percent last year. Job creation next year is expected to slow to
less than 1 percent. Their projections for Massachusetts were
similar.
</P>
<P>
   As employers have made clear for several years, the downside of
the expansion is that much of New England is experiencing a labor
shortage that is driving up wages in the Massachusetts high-tech
sector.
</P>
<P>
   The economists said this labor shortfall is spreading to the
other states. Wages in New England rose more than 6 percent in the
first quarter, compared to the same period last year, while
national wages went up 3.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the economists said they are beginning to see
signs of a slowdown caused by increases in interest rates by the
Federal Reserve and the labor shortage. Consumer confidence has
also dropped this year in New England, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, there is no recession in sight, they agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think the Fed will be successful in engineering a soft
landing,'' said Alan Clayton-Matthews, a professor of political
economy at the University of Massachusetts at Boston.
</P>
<P>
   But they warned that if the stock market should crash and
consumer demand plunge, the blow would be worst in Massachusetts,
which has become reliant on its booming financial industry and a
high-tech sector funded by initial public offerings and venture
capital.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
