<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO. 1 PRIORITY   FOR SEMINOLES: CLEAN UP BAD ACT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OK, we've had enough. In case you missed it, the latest news out
of Florida State is that Tay Cody, a junior cornerback, was
arrested Tuesday and charged with possession of marijuana.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Bobby Bowden immediately suspended Cody for Saturday's
game against Virginia _ at least. ``I'm suspending him for the next
game and maybe more, until the facts are in,'' said Bowden.
</P>
<P>
   Now, we think Bowden is one of the class acts in college
football, one of the classiest in all of athletics. He wants to do
the right thing.
</P>
<P>
   He also wants to win national championships. Nothing wrong with
that.
</P>
<P>
   But in light of the recent arrests of Peter Warrick, Laveranues
Coles, and now Cody, and an assortment of other crimes and
misdemeanors dating back to the FootLocker case a few years ago,
the ``facts,'' as Bowden calls them, seem pretty compelling.
</P>
<P>
   Something is wrong at Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska had the same problem in the later days of Tom Osborne,
and because Osborne wasn't touchy-feely with the media, he was
hammered for running a program that coddled athletes who were not
exactly candidates for Citizen of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   But because Bowden will bring you into his office, sit you down,
and look you in the eye and tell you he treats his players like his
own children, he has been treated in a kinder, gentler fashion.
</P>
<P>
   However, it looks more and more like the problem at Florida
State is not so much with the athletes as with the people who are
recruiting them.
</P>
<P>
   Few programs have been better over the past decade than FSU. The
Seminoles have not finished lower than No. 5 in the national
rankings since George Bush was elected president. And there's
nothing to suggest they will finish any worse anytime before the
next presidential election, when the next generation of George Bush
could very well be vying for the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   Now, we recognize that each case is different and that some
people might have agendas that involve targeting members of the No.
1 team in college football.
</P>
<P>
   We also realize that coaches cannot control their athletes 24
hours a day, seven days a week.
</P>
<P>
   But it's happening too much at Florida State. The question is,
why.
</P>
<P>
   Should the recruiters do background checks as well as checking
their stopwatches when scouting high school players?
</P>
<P>
   Should they make citizenship as much a priority as touchdowns?
</P>
<P>
   Bowden does not run an exceptionally tight ship in terms of
discipline. Florida State players and students are what they are,
for everyone to see. ``The one thing I do tell them is, don't do
anything to embarrass yourselves or the university,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   In the past few weeks, players have embarrassed both themselves
and the university.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it rains, it snows,'' said Bowden, his point taken
despite his confused cliche.
</P>
<P>
   But Bowden remains philosophical. ``It's life,'' he said, ``and
you've got to deal with it.''
</P>
<P>
   He will do just that as he guides his team through the rest of
the season, perhaps winning his second national championship,
perhaps not.
</P>
<P>
   But the issue here is not the present but the future. Bobby
Bowden has worked too hard for too long to see his reputation
become tarnished by the misdeeds of a few players whose sense of
right and wrong and judgment appear clouded.
</P>
<P>
   However, like other coaches, he has to be held accountable.
Bowden has been at FSU since 1976, and if you look at the sum of
those years, there have been more than a handful _ more than
several handfuls _ of off-the-field incidents.
</P>
<P>
   This year's team is typical. Superbly talented, but lacking
discipline. It sometimes shows up in games in the form of penalties
and confusion, as was the case several times during last week's win
over Clemson.
</P>
<P>
   FSU is winning on talent and very little else, and the
responsibility for that falls on Bowden and his staff. You can win
while running a clean program. It takes a lot of work. In the case
of Florida State, it might take a change in recruiting philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Bowden, at the end of his career as he approaches age
70, can do that is questionable.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rose-y for Cardinal
</P>
<P>
   Stanford is the front-runner to win the Pacific 10 title and
earn a berth in the Rose Bowl. Neither the Cardinal nor the Pac-10
as a whole has received much credit this season, which is being
viewed as a down year for the conference. Stanford's two losses
have come against Texas and San Jose State. When was the last time
a Pac-10 champion lost to San Jose State? It was 1971, when
Stanford lost to SJS, 13-12, but won the conference title and beat
Michigan in the Rose Bowl by the same score . . . The Southeastern
Conference is still the hottest league in the country in terms of
attendance, with stadiums being filled at an average of 97.6
percent of capacity. A year ago, SEC teams did even better, filling
99.9 percent of capacity . . . Nebraska coach Frank Solich has
backed off his criticism of officials following last week's loss to
Texas. Solich used the words ``ridiculous'' and ``horrendous'' in
his postgame descriptions of some calls in the Huskers' first loss
of the season (and third straight to Texas). By Tuesday, he had
kicked back into neutral. ``I would rather not comment on the
officiating,'' he said. ``It appears I've done quite a bit in the
last two days.'' . . . Virginia Tech may not be No. 1 in either the
writers or coaches poll, but the Hokies rank No. 1 in scoring
offense and No. 1 in scoring defense as they prepare for Saturday's
game at Pittsburgh . . . A Florida win over Georgia Saturday would
be the Gators' 100th of the decade (99-19-1). Among major college
programs, only Alabama, Brigham Young, Florida State, Nebraska, and
Oklahoma have won 100 games during a decade in the 20th century . .
. While Boston College's 31-28 loss to Miami last Saturday was
devastating for the Eagles, it should also be taken in this
context: If before the game someone had said that with three
minutes left the score would be 28-28, even the most casual BC fan
would have accepted it in a heartbeat. The fact that it was 28-0
until there were two minutes left in the third quarter shows you
how good Miami is when it wants to play. BC should have won the
game, without question. But if there is a positive, it is that the
Eagles know they can play at a high level. It is coach Tom
O'Brien's task to get them to do that long enough to win another
game or two . . . The Bowl Championship Series rankings, which have
Florida State and Penn State at 1-2, won't change significantly if
both teams win the rest of their games, which is bad news for
Virginia Tech, hurt by having a lesser schedule than either the
Seminoles or Nittany Lions. Tech is upgrading its schedule for
future years. Another twist is that Tennessee still can get to the
BCS championship game, the Sugar Bowl, even while not qualifying
for the SEC title game. Unless Florida loses to Georgia on Saturday
or loses another SEC game, the Gators (who beat Tennessee in
September) will be the SEC East champion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
