A1723 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-BBN-BRAVES-COX     10-28 0630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves will be remembered for their resilience
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Now that the 1999 season is over, it's still hard to
figure how the Atlanta Braves surprised us more _ by winning 110
games without Andres Galarraga, Javy Lopez, Kerry Ligtenberg and
Odalis Perez, or losing four World Series games in a row to the
Yankees without much of a fight.
</P>
<P>
   By the time they got back to their clubhouse at Turner Field
late Thursday afternoon to clean out their lockers and say a few
goodbyes before heading off in 25 different directions, the Braves
didn't have a lot of answers. And maybe they didn't need them.
</P>
<P>
   For all the disappointment they felt after losing the fourth of
five World Series this decade and their claim on the ``Team of the
'90s'' label, the Braves felt few regrets.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not a lot of pride in going 0-4, getting your butt
kicked,'' said John Smoltz, whose career postseason record fell to
12-4 in Wednesday night's 4-1 loss. ``But we played with every
ounce of energy we could, physically and mentally.''
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz was the prime example. Faced with the unenviable task of
throwing himself in front of Roger Clemens and the Yankees after
they had gone up 3-0 in the series, Smoltz went back to pitching
from over the top, something he hadn't done since July when a
troublesome elbow nearly cost him his season.
</P>
<P>
   Bailing on the three-quarters delivery he had employed since
August, Smoltz was willing to take whatever pain the old mechanics
might have caused him. His fastball was back up around 95 mph and
his slider returned to its usual nastiness. He dominated Yankees
hitters like the usual October Smoltz, but lost on a three-run
lapse in the third inning when the Yankees took advantage of a
couple defensive misplays on the Braves infield.
</P>
<P>
   But as the Braves have long since learned out of necessity and
perfected to an art, Smoltz was looking ahead not even 24 hours
after the loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing I'll take into the offseason is I'm going to do
whatever I can to get back to that level,'' Smoltz said. ``I had
absolutely nothing to lose. I was going to give it everything I
had...(The arm) was great during the whole game. It was fun to do
that again. The outcome wasn't as fun.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves felt like the series played out much closer than it
seemed and have proof in leads heading into the eighth innings of
Games 1 and 3. But the Game 3 loss just proved too devastating,
after a 5-1 Braves advantage eroded on four Yankee home runs, the
two-run game-timing shot by Chuck Knoblauch and the game-winner in
the 10th inning by Chad Curtis.
</P>
<P>
   ``A loss is a loss,'' Greg Maddux said. ``I know during the
season it's easier to lose 10-0 than 2-1 because you know you're
going to lose. We didn't know we were losing (the series), right
until the end of last night. That doesn't make it any easier.''
</P>
<P>
   For all that's happened to the Braves in the last nine months -
from learning of Galarraga's cancer the first day of spring
training to watching another World Series celebration from their
dugout on Wednesday night, the 1999 version of the Atlanta Braves
will be remembered for their resilience. But then again, maybe
that's what makes them like the rest of the Braves teams of this
decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mood of this team doesn't change a whole lot,'' Walt Weiss
said. ``Pretty stable, pretty resilient. My attitude is you take
your best shot and move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Smoltz: ``We're all a little hurt with the fact that we
haven't won more than one World Series championship, but all in
all, when you think about it, it's been an awesome run, one we're
not ready to end.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
