u i BC-ARMENIA-ATTACK-ART-NY     10-28 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARMENIA-ATTACK-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
3 CHARGED IN KILLINGS IN ARMENIAN PARLIAMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Armenian prosecutors brought terrorism charges Thursday
against three of five gunmen who seized the Parliament on
Wednesday, killing eight people, most of them government officials,
and holding 40 hostages.
</P>
<P>
   The gunmen gave up the last of their hostages and turned in
their Kalashnikov rifles at about 10 a.m. Thursday after nightlong
negotiations that included a meeting with Armenia's president,
Robert Kocharian.
</P>
<P>
   All five were under criminal investigation, and the three
charged so far could receive the death penalty. Among the officials
killed in the attack were Prime Minister Vazgen Sarkisian and the
Parliament's speaker, Karen Demirchian.
</P>
<P>
   The government has declared Friday a day of mourning. A Russian
antiterrorist squad that had secretly flown overnight to the
capital, Yerevan, in preparation for an assault on the building,
will remain for the time being, Russian officials said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors charged three men with terrorism aimed at
undermining authority: the man identified as the leader of the
assault, Nairi Unanian; his brother Karen, and their uncle, Vram
Galstian. Nairi Unanian was variously identified earlier as a
journalist, a recent resident of the Crimean region of Ukraine and
a member some years ago of the Armenian Revolutionary Federation, a
radical nationalist party.
</P>
<P>
   The party has denied any connection with the attack.
</P>
<P>
   The identities of the two remaining gunmen were not immediately
known.
</P>
<P>
   A day after the attack, it still was not completely clear why
the men had chosen to assault the Parliament, which was conducting
a question-and-answer session with top members of Kocharian's
government.
</P>
<P>
   Kocharian bowed to the gunmen's demands Thursday and broadcast a
statement in which they demanded a guarantee of personal security
and a complete inquiry into the assault on Parliament. They also
demanded that officials who had ``plundered the nation'' be charged
and tried.
</P>
<P>
   But that did not explain the motive behind the attack, which
some have theorized was spurred by progress in negotiations to
settle a decade-old territorial dispute between Armenia and
Azerbaijan. Armenian nationalists are dead set against ceding any
of the territory at issue, which is a section of Azerbaijan called
Nagorno-Karabakh, now controlled mainly by ethnic Armenians.
</P>
<P>
   In their broadcast statement, the gunmen said they had entered
the Parliament, their weapons concealed under trench coats, with
the aim of killing the prime minister and no one else. Their plan,
according to the statement, was to frighten members of Parliament
by firing their weapons into the air.
</P>
<P>
   By their account, the attack widened after government guards
opened fire and forced them to fire back. ``All other casualties,''
the statement read, ``were accidental.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear how well that explanation accorded with
videotape of the incident, which showed gunmen racing into the
Parliament, emptying a magazine of bullets into the prime
minister's body and then turning their weapons on senior officials
in the front row of the chamber.
</P>
<P>
   It was equally unclear how the attackers got into the building
in the first place. By one account, the organizer, Unanian, carried
press credentials that granted him entry, but the account was not
confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   The attack appears to have divided Kocharian's government.
According to Russian television, the leadership of Armenia's
Defense Ministry demanded Thursday that the interior and security
ministers and the prosecutor general be fired, saying they had
failed to solve a single major crime in recent times.
</P>
<P>
   In their statement, however, they added that the military still
supported Kocharian and would uphold the constitution.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-99 2048EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991028.0424 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 20:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1725 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-ARMS-CONGRESS-NYT &LR;      10-28 1089
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARMS-CONGRESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATORS , WHO OPPOSED NUCLEAR TEST BAN TREATY , NOW AIM AT
MONITORING SYSTEM  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN:   Ind., Neb., Ky., Okla, Ga., N.C., Japan, France, Germany,
Britain, India Pakistan, Argentina, Italy)   By WILLIAM J. BROAD   and ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eager to insure that a treaty banning nuclear testing is never
revived, some of the accord's most ardent foes in the Senate are
discussing a plan to gut a $300 million global monitoring system
that is half built and seen as essential to making the pact work.
</P>
<P>
   Emboldened by the Senate's rejection of the treaty two weeks
ago, a small but powerful band of senior aides to Republican
senators is pushing to kill the U.S. share of the costs for an
agency created to put the treaty into force and set up the
worldwide surveillance system. Without Washington's aid, experts
say, the monitoring network is likely to collapse.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Only a handful of senior Republican senators are aware of the
strategy, which still needs final approval from such top lawmakers
as the Senate majority leader, Trent Lott, and Sen. Mitch
McConnell, a Kentucky Republican who oversees foreign aid bills.
Other Republicans, including Paul D. Coverdell of Georgia and James
M. Inhofe of Oklahoma, have expressed interest in the proposal,
aides said.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to take a look at that and see if there's a need
for that money,'' Lott said.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But a decision is likely soon, mainly because any effort to kill
the financing hinges on deleting it from a rewrite of the foreign
aid bill, which should be wrapped up in the next few days.
President Clinton vetoed the first version of the bill for reasons
unrelated to the monitoring. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For their plan to succeed, the senior aides are hoping to push
it through as part of a session-ending budget deal between the
White House and the Republican-controlled Congress. They are also
counting on the monitoring aid's price tag _ $16 million this year
_ to get lost in the reshuffling of billion-dollar programs. The
aides are all specialists in national security affairs and were
deeply involved in the Senate's rejection of the treaty.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear how much support the fund-cutters have, and
whether they are likely to prevail. Republican arms control
advocates like Sen. Richard G. Lugar of Indiana and Sen. Chuck
Hagel of Nebraska, oppose gutting the agency, the Comprehensive
Test Ban Treaty Organization, and its monitoring tasks.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``If, in fact, we want to continue to lead the nonproliferation
effort, we have to do all we can to assist it,'' Hagel said.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The United States pays one-quarter of the monitoring system's
development costs, with most of the other money coming from Japan,
France, Germany and Britain. To date, experts say, more than half
of the system's overall estimated cost of roughly $300 million has
been spent.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So far, Congress has met all administration requests for
building the system, which is meant to consist of 321 stations in
90 countries. Right now, fewer than 100 are built and producing
data. Advocates say the fledgling network proved valuable in
monitoring Indian and Pakistani nuclear blasts last year, but
conservatives want it killed. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This treaty has been soundly rejected,'' said an aide to a
senator who opposes the treaty, ``and that includes any form of
financial support.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Critics are also infuriated by Clinton's vow to abide by the
spirit of the rejected pact. ``I have no intention of doing
anything else than honoring the obligations of the treaty imposed
on the United States,'' Clinton said on Oct. 14, the day after the
treaty failed.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Senate's rejection makes it more likely that nations with
developing nuclear arsenals might not sign or ratify the treaty.
But it is also possible that treaty accord could survive without
U.S. participation. Or a new Congress and president might back the
accord or a renegotiated version of it. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``They recognize that the treaty is not dead and are looking for
ways to undermine the whole regime,'' Daryl G. Kimball, executive
director of the Coalition to Reduce Nuclear Dangers, a Washington
group that strongly supports the treaty, said of the conservative
Republicans. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Treaty opponents say the global surveillance system would be
useless for verifying treaty compliance and ideal for creating jobs
for third-world scientists and diplomats.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of the Senate rejection, Sen. Jesse Helms, the North
Carolina Republican who heads the Foreign Relations Committee, said
the system ``will provide zero benefit to our nuclear test
monitoring'' and would ``make life more difficult for the United
States.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Critics say they would redirect the funds into improving U.S.
surveillance of nuclear explosions, which is rooted in a variety of
intelligence tools that have been used for decades.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The program's defenders say the international monitoring system,
when finished and if buttressed by thousands of private sensors,
will detect all but the smallest blasts. Backers and opponents
disagree on whether small explosions are significant militarily. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ralph W. Alewine III, a top official in the Defense Department's
nuclear treaty program office, said American spending on the
international network was worthwhile.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think this is very valuable,'' he said. ``We're buying into
a big system at 25 cents on the dollar, and this provides us data
we couldn't get otherwise.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the $16 million proposed by the State Department,
the Pentagon pays for some international monitoring costs. Its aid
this year is $5 million.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Preliminary work began in late 1996 after the treaty was opened
for signature and has been accelerating ever since. Scheduled for
completion around 2002, the surveillance system is to have 170
stations that detect underground shock waves, 80 that sniff the air
for tell-tale radioactivity, 60 that listen for revealing sounds
and 11 that track undersea booms. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The roughly 90 states meant to host monitoring stations include
Argentina, China, Djibouti, Fiji, Italy, Madagascar, Nepal, Papua
New Guinea, Russia, Samoa and Zimbabwe. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Federal experts say 95 of the system's 321 planned stations are
complete and sending data to the Prototype International Data
Center, which is based in Arlington, Va., and supported by the
Defense Department. By the end of next year, the total number is to
rise to 164. In late 2001, the full complement of 321 stations is
to be up and running.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
