<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-PENICILLIN-SHORTAGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRUG MAKER'S SHUTDOWN CAUSES SHORTAGES OF PENICILLIN G 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ABIGAIL ZUGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A nationwide shortage of a powerful form of penicillin that
began quietly last spring, when a leading manufacturer shut down
operations, is now becoming critical, with hospital pharmacies
running out of the drug and new supplies harder and harder to
obtain.
</P>
<P>
   The drug is penicillin G, which is given intravenously to treat
serious infections like syphilis in newborn babies. A second drug
from the same manufacturer, cefazolin, one of the most commonly
used antibiotics to prevent and treat surgical infections, is also
in short supply in some areas. Both drugs have been in use for
decades.
</P>
<P>
   The shortage of the two drugs does not represent a public health
emergency; newer antibiotics can usually treat patients
successfully.
</P>
<P>
   But doctors fear the long-term consequences of using newer,
stronger antibiotics to treat infections that can be treated with
older drugs because the overuse of powerful new drugs has been
linked to the recent explosion of antibiotic resistance among
bacteria. Antibiotic-resistant bacteria may go on to cause
infections that can be treated only with difficulty, or not at all.
</P>
<P>
   And newer drugs are often far more expensive than the older
ones. For example, cefazolin (pronounced seh-fa-ZOH-lin), costs
about $5 a dose; alternatives may cost $40 or more.
</P>
<P>
   The manufacturer, Marsam Pharmaceuticals, based in Cherry Hill,
N.J., produced more than 60 percent of the penicillin G and about
40 percent of the cefazolin used in the United States. Marsam
stopped producing both drugs and issued a product recall in June in
response to a federal investigation into manufacturing
deficiencies. A spokeswoman for Marsam's owner, Schein
Pharmaceutical, said she could not predict when production would
resume.
</P>
<P>
   The other major supplier of penicillin G in the United States,
Pfizer, based in New York, has now exhausted its stock of the drug.
A letter from Pfizer to pharmacists earlier this month estimated
that new supplies would not be available until the end of next
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Depending on how much is in inventory around the country,
penicillin G is now either in very, very limited distribution or
not available at all,'' said Joseph Deffenbaugh, a spokesman at the
American Society of Health-Systems Pharmacists in Bethesda, Md.,
which represents pharmacists who practice in hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   The Food and Drug Administration has indicated that both Marsam
drugs were recalled at least in part because supplies were
contaminated with potentially dangerous microbes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a balance in regard to weighing the safety issues that
were observed and trying to get more supplies of the drug as
rapidly as possible,'' said Dr. Gary Chikami, director of the
division of anti-infective drug products at the FDA. The agency has
begun to look for other domestic or foreign sources of penicillin
G, which it considers essential for treating some conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Because several drug companies other than Marsam manufacture and
distribute cefazolin, the FDA says there is no serious shortage of
that drug.
</P>
<P>
   But doctors across the country say both drugs are so hard to get
that they have unwillingly turned to other antibiotics. ``We have
had to be incredibly creative to keep up,'' said Dr. Joseph
Guglielmo, a professor of clinical pharmacy who oversees the
antibiotic control program at the Medical Center at the University
of California in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors at Guglielmo's hospital must now use the drug ampicillin
instead of penicillin, he said. The drugs are similarly priced, but
ampicillin causes a rash more often than penicillin and is also
active against a far wider variety of bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ampicillin is unnecessarily broad in its activity,'' said Dr.
James Rahal, director of infectious diseases at New York Hospital,
where ampicillin has also replaced penicillin on the wards. When a
drug kills a wide variety of bacteria in the gastrointestinal
tract, as ampicillin does, it encourages resistant bacteria
belonging to many different species to multiply. These may go on to
cause antibiotic-resistant infections.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, alternatives to cefazolin are active against many
more strains of bacteria than it is and may also cause infections
resistant to antibiotics.
</P>
<P>
   Although many strains of bacteria have become resistant to
penicillin since it was first used in the late 1940s, for certain
infections it remains the first choice. These infections include
some forms of syphilis, pneumonia and meningitis, and rare diseases
like anthrax, botulism and gangrene. For the life-threatening
muscle infections caused by the streptococcal bacteria nicknamed
flesh-eating bacteria, penicillin G remains the most effective
antibiotic known, Rahal said.
</P>
<P>
   Both penicillin and cefazolin have been in use for so long that
the patents on their production expired years ago. As a result, the
profits generated by the drugs is far less than for newer drugs
unless large quantities are sold.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems that many of our tried and true antibiotics are
becoming orphan drugs,'' said Dr. Robert Muder, the hospital
epidemiologist at the Pittsburgh Veterans Affairs Hospital. ``They
sell for pennies, they're not advertised, yet they need the same
high-quality production as the newer drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   If these older drugs were to slowly disappear from the market,
``we would be forced to use broad-spectrum drugs for all the wrong
indications,'' Muder said. ``There's a real possibility that this
would exacerbate the problem of drug resistance in this country.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
