<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.H.)  
 BRADLEY POKES FUN AT GORE, BUYS NEW SHOES 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also GORE) 
(mk) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHUA, N.H. _ At a campaign rally Thursday morning, former Sen.
Bill Bradley did something he doesn't often do: He poked fun at
Vice President Al Gore, his rival for the Democratic presidential
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley had just been asked what he thought about the teaching
of creationism in public schools. He opposed it, he said, but added
that Gore would allow it in certain circumstances. (For example, in
religion classes, Gore's aides said.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that was sort of a misstep,'' Bradley told 150
supporters, an impish grin on his face as he imitated a clumsy
person tripping over his own feet. ``And sometimes when you do
that, this is what you have to do,'' he added, suddenly pivoting in
the opposite direction.
</P>
<P>
   That was just one way in which Bradley added some punch Thursday
to his generally laid-back campaign style. The former New Jersey
senator told his jokes with more verve, gave more detailed answers
and generally seemed more energized than usual. ``Every day I do
this, I feel stronger, more focused,'' Bradley told the group.
</P>
<P>
   The rally here came the morning after his first side-by-side
appearance with Gore in a town-hall-like forum at Dartmouth College
in Hanover. Throughout the forum, Gore was the aggressor,
repeatedly criticizing Bradley's proposals as too expensive. He
even walked to center stage minutes before the event was scheduled
to start and invited questions from the audience. And at the end of
the event, after Bradley left the stage, Gore stayed for nearly 90
minutes to answer more questions from the audience.
</P>
<P>
   Though they said they were not overly troubled by Gore's
aggressive tactics on Wednesday night, Bradley's aides acknowledged
that they had considered the possibility of responding more
assertively to Gore. But the aides said they decided to avoid
vigorously attacking the vice president for now, fearing that it
would undermine Bradley's efforts to portray himself as a different
kind of politician.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley reiterated that decision Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``You save your strength for your positive vision,'' he said.
``You save your outrage for the conditions in America that need to
be improved, whether it is child poverty or a lack of insurance for
people. You save your ingenuity for figuring out ways to convince
Americans that this is the direction we should go. You don't waste
all that on simply making a negative attack against your
opponent.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, his aides said, Bradley is intent on pushing back _
gently, perhaps _ against Gore.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Bradley was more direct than usual Thursday in
criticizing Gore for not providing what Bradley considers specific
details on the cost of the vice president's proposals. ``I think
it's very important when you propose a program to put out what it
costs, and that's what I have done,'' Bradley said. ``I would
observe the vice president has announced a number of programs and
has not put out the cost attached to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley also seemed determined to regain an edge in
impetuousness. After the rally here, he visited a local store,
Alec's Shoes, whose owner, John Koutsos, has allowed workers to
take Mondays off to spend time with their families. Bradley has
made helping working families a central part of his agenda.
</P>
<P>
   As he toured the store, Bradley _ with some prodding from a
salesman who inquired whether his worn-looking shoes had holes in
their soles _ agreed to buy a new pair. After looking at several
styles, Bradley chose a pair of $75 oxfords, size 13D, black, that
looked very much like the ones he had on.
</P>
<P>
   Though his staff has often accused Gore of campaign gimmickry,
Bradley, who is renowned for his frugality, said his purchase was
completely unplanned. ``It was the least I could do for a guy who
gives his employees Mondays off,'' Bradley said. ``I had no idea
what I was going to do when I went in there. You've got to be
spontaneous.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
