<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE STEPS UP THE ATTACK AGAINST BRADLEY ON HEALTH CARE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLINTON, Iowa _ Vice President Al Gore ripped apart Bill
Bradley's health-care proposal Thursday, saying it cost too much,
in part because it would provide insurance even for the wealthy,
and would swallow up the entire budget surplus.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be a big idea, but it's not a good idea,'' Gore
declared, offering a response to Bradley's assertion in their first
one-on-one appearance Wednesday night that health insurance was a
big problem that needed a big solution. ``Alchemy was a big idea,
but it wasn't a good idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore was campaigning by bus across the expansive farmland of
eastern Iowa Thursday with a spring in his step just hours after
the joint event in New Hampshire. His advisers were confident that
Gore had bested the former senator, his only Democratic rival for
the presidential nomination, in both style and substance and that
Bradley's answers on health care made him vulnerable on an
important issue that they could exploit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were stunned that he didn't defend his numbers,'' a Gore
aide said of Bradley's performance Wednesday night. ``He didn't
say, `I guarantee I'll save Medicare.' In a campaign, when someone
gives you an opening like that on a core Democratic issue, we'll
take it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bradley campaign disputed this central contention, saying
the Bradley plan, which guarantees health care for all children,
preserves and protects Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   But at stop after stop Thursday, Gore pounded on this theme. At
a rally here at the widest point in the Mississippi River, Gore
called Bradley's plan ``ill-considered'' and said it would drive
the nation back into deficits.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said his plan, which would cost $50 billion to $65
billion a year, would be paid for through the budget surplus and
through what he called the ``enormous savings'' achieved by
shifting to electronic record-keeping for health care from paper.
Gore said that such a shift was not possible, could not be relied
upon and would not provide much savings anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Gore based much of his criticism of the Bradley plan on a new
study by Kenneth E. Thorpe, a professor of health policy at Emory
University, a former Clinton administration official and, as the
Bradley camp pointed out, one contributor to the failed Clinton
health plan.
</P>
<P>
   Thorpe's study said that Bradley's plan, including coverage for
prescription drugs, would cost $1.2 trillion over 10 years. Gore's
plan, which would cover all children by January 2005 but is
otherwise based largely on Clinton administration proposals, would
cost $312 billion over 10 years and also includes coverage for
prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The study said that Gore's plan would cover about 12 million
people and that the Bradley plan would cover 18 million. There are
about 45 million Americans without insurance now.
</P>
<P>
   Citing the study, Gore told a group of elderly in Dubuque
Thursday morning that Bradley's plan cost so much ``because
two-thirds of all the money spent in this plan goes to people who
already have health insurance, many of them wealthy, many of them
well-to-do.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bradley camp also claimed its own supporting academic
experts. These include David Cutler, a professor of economics at
the Kennedy School at Harvard, who has said that Bradley's critics
say the plan would cost more than it would because they wrongly
assumed he provides a more generous insurance policy than he
actually does.
</P>
<P>
   ``In short,'' the Bradley statement said, ``Gore is attacking
Bradley's plan simply because it is comprehensive and bold.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore himself has been criticized for offering so many generous
proposals in this campaign that he, too, has already spent the
surplus. But Thursday he said that he was keeping a running tally
of the costs of his various programs and that they all fit within a
balanced budget.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton was asked Thursday at a news conference in
Washington about comments Gore made during the joint encounter
Wednesday night, when he was asked about the cynicism that many
people felt about politicians. The vice president responded that he
understood the disappointment and anger that the country felt
toward Clinton and said, ``I felt it myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said Gore had not expressed that anger personally and
added that he believed the American people were inherently fair.
``You know, I think a lot of people who may not like me may hold it
against him, but I don't think you hold him responsible. I don't
think mature people hold one person responsible for another
person's conduct, do you?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
