<SLUG> BC-BOEING-NASA-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOEING WANTS TO BE LANDLORD FOR THE SPACE STATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ NASA is looking for a commercial landlord for the
International Space Station, and Boeing wants the job.
</P>
<P>
   If the concept flies, Boeing could end up building and owning an
inflatable habitation module, which once in orbit would be blown up
like a balloon and would serve as the living and recreational
accommodations for the station's seven-member crew.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who wanted to spend time on the station doing research
would pay for their quarters, just as they might pay for a hotel
room on earth.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is part of a new strategy by NASA to triple the size of
the station's crew quarters while at the same time encouraging
commercial opportunities for the floating space platform.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost like you are going to build a hotel in space,''
said Daniel Tam, NASA's assistant to the administrator for
commercialization.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we are trying to figure out what the hotel looks
like, and then we need to figure out what's the best way to build
it. Do we have someone else pay for the whole thing ... or do we
want to co-own it for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Boeing is one of a number of companies working on preliminary
designs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would like very much, if NASA decides to go that way, to be
a part of it,'' said Steve Goo, Boeing's deputy space station
program director. ``We are working to help mature their concept.''
</P>
<P>
   NASA had hoped to pick its partner or partners for the project
by the end of October, but Tam said Thursday the selection process
will take more time.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing is already NASA's prime contractor for the space station,
and built the major U.S. elements under a multi-billion-dollar
government contract awarded earlier this decade.
</P>
<P>
   Those elements, one of which is already in orbit, included a
rigid habitation module made of aluminum. It will be used as
planned for the station's crew quarters if the inflatable module
doesn't pan out.
</P>
<P>
   The aluminum habitation module is now in Huntsville, Ala., where
it and the other key U.S. station elements were built by Boeing.
</P>
<P>
   The aluminum habitation module is just a shell. NASA issued a
stop-work order a couple years ago when the idea of an inflatable
module began to take root. The inflatable module was then called
TransHab, a reference to a plan to use it as a design prototype for
a manned Mars mission. The name has stuck, though it is now also
being called the inflatable habitation module.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of the hardware that would have gone inside the aluminum
habitation module, such as air revitalization equipment, would also
be used in the inflatable module.
</P>
<P>
   Even though work stopped on the aluminum module, Boeing has
continued to develop the hardware that would go inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``What NASA wanted us to do is protect their options and to make
sure we have all the common equipment ready to go no matter which
way this turns out,'' said Goo, whose previous job with Boeing was
overseeing production of the aluminum habitation module and other
station elements in Huntsville.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the same time, we are participating in these studies for
TransHab to see if we can come up with something that makes good
sense,'' Goo said. ``Like any other opportunity it has to make
sense from a business standpoint.''
</P>
<P>
   The current station assembly timetable calls for the aluminum
habitation module to launch in November 2004. If NASA decides to
use the inflatable module instead, it would have to be ready by
that same date.
</P>
<P>
   Assembly of the International Space Station began last December
with the launch of a connecting node built by Boeing, which space
shuttle astronauts attached to a Russian-built module.
</P>
<P>
   The assembly schedule could slip because of repeated delays in
launching the Russian-built service module, which will be the
temporary home of a rotating crew of three hard-hat astronauts
until the habitation module is ready for the permanent station crew
of seven.
</P>
<P>
   The launch of the service module, now set for late December or
early 2000, is already a year and a half late.
</P>
<P>
   The habitation module would be one of the final elements
connected to the station.
</P>
<P>
   NASA has spent $2.5 million to develop a prototype of TransHab.
It is 36 feet long and 27 feet in diameter.
</P>
<P>
   The aluminum habitation module built by Boeing is 28 feet long
and 14.5 feet in diameter.
</P>
<P>
   Because it has more than three times the volume of the aluminum
module, the inflatable module as envisioned by NASA would have four
different levels.
</P>
<P>
   Level one is the wardroom and galley. It is big enough so that
up to 12 people can dine together (More than 7 people will be on
the station when the shuttle is docked.) The wardroom includes a
20-inch window in the dining room for watching the earth 250 miles.
</P>
<P>
   Level two is the crew quarters. Each member of the crew would
have his or her own computer entertainment center for recreation
and personal work.
</P>
<P>
   Level 3 is an exercise area with a treadmill and stationary
bicycle. It also has a complete health care system, including a
space shower.
</P>
<P>
   Level four is a pressurized tunnel that serves as a passageway
between the habitation module and and the station element that it
is attached to.
</P>
<P>
   The 1.5-foot thick outer wall of the inflatable module has about
two dozen layers to protect the crew from space projectiles as big
as an inch and moving up to 15,000 miles per hour. Successive
layers of Nextel, a material commonly used as insulation under the
hoods of many cars, are spaced between layers of open cell foam,
similar to the foam used in chair cushions on earth.
</P>
<P>
   The layers are designed to break up small particles of space
debris or tiny meteorites that might hit the station with a speed
seven times as fast as a rifle bullet.
</P>
<P>
   Tam said NASA has fired projectiles into the TransHab mockup and
it held up well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are confident that it is better than the aluminum module,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   NASA Administrator Dan Goldin has said the space agency would
like to turn over operation of the space station to private
enterprise within 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the near term, we believe that the commercial habitation
module offers unbelievable opportunitie,'' Goldin said in a speech
last month.
</P>
<P>
   In August, NASA held a three-day conference near its Houston
headquarters to explore the commercial opportunities of TransHab.
More than 150 people from the aerospace industry were there. They
represented small companies as well as industry titans such as
Boeing and Lockheed Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Participants were urged to offer designs for an alternative to
the aluminum habitation module.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can come up with a design similar to TransHab or
something different,'' Tam said. ``But it has to satisfy what we
need, and what commercial users would want.''
</P>
<P>
   NASA would invest no more than $200 million, which is the cost
of completing the aluminum module. Tam doesn't know how much
something like TransHab would cost. It would be in the hundreds of
millions of dollars, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will not be a procurement like we usually do in
government,'' he said. ``We are not sending out requests for
proposals, getting a bunch in, choosing who we want and then paying
them to build it. We are looking for a business arrangement with a
commercial entity. They would pay for all or part of it and own all
or part of it ....
</P>
<P>
   ``NASA would only have to pay for what we use. Then we could
concentrate on cutting edge research and development as well as
far-frontier exploration, which is what I think we do best. And we
could leave the other stuff to the commercial people and let them
make money and benefit from it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
