<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-COSELL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV SPORTS: COSELL'S BACK, AND HE'S STILL COSELL 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is a once-upon-a-time quality to the life of Howard
Cosell. You almost have to educate younger viewers that a
television personality with his voice, erudition, bombast, ego,
arrogance, toupee, neuroses, sense of social justice and inner
anger towered over sportscasting for nearly two decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you describe Howard Cosell on the air to someone who
has never heard him before?'' the comedian Billy Crystal asks
during ``Howard Cosell: Telling It Like It Is,'' a new HBO
documentary Monday at 8 p.m. ``Think of a very smart man scolding
you, with a bad sinus condition who had a great vocabulary.''
</P>
<P>
   Cosell retired from ABC Sports in 1985 after a 20-year run. His
career switched between solid journalism and brilliant boxing calls
and hop-scotched from championing the rights of black athletes to
being the host for trash sports events. From his platform as the
catalytic converter of ``Monday Night Football,'' he became so big
that ABC gave him his own variety show, ``Saturday Night Live With
Howard Cosell,'' which faded quickly.
</P>
<P>
   From the late 1960s to the early 1980s, few TV stars were
bigger. He reveled in it and enjoyed informing others of his
magnitude. ``Let's put it on the table,'' he told Dinah Shore on
her talk show. ``I'm great.''
</P>
<P>
   His success came late in his career; by the time he was hired by
ABC Sports, he had withstood a six-year blackball of him by the
network's president, Tom Moore.
</P>
<P>
   At one time, he was voted by TV Guide viewers the most admired
AND hated sportscaster in America. Think of anyone in sports TV now
who generates such passion _ well, some players hope to hit the
billboarded face of Fox's Keith Olbermann on outfield fences
nationwide _ or a single one who would tell you, as Cosell did,
that he was more than capable of anchoring the evening news.
</P>
<P>
   His one-of-a-kind presence led Woody Allen to cast Cosell as
himself in the film ``Bananas'' to interview a South American
dictator as he lay dying from gunfire.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had the broadcasting presence all the time,'' Allen says in
the documentary. ``If Howard said, `Pass the salt,' or `I'm going
to get a newspaper,' it sounded like an exciting event. One can
only speculate what it was like making love to him, because
everything he said had that sense of event, of crisis and
urgency.''
</P>
<P>
   His fame at ABC led Cosell to guest-star twice on ``The Odd
Couple.'' The television show's co-star, Tony Randall, cracks up at
the memory of Cosell's penchant for exaggerated facial expressions.
</P>
<P>
   ``He believed he knew how to act,'' Randall tells HBO. ``No one
told him not to because it was kind of funny.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Cosell retired bitterly, filled with resentments that he
packed into his scabrous 1985 memoir, ``I Never Played the Game.''
He died of a heart embolism in 1995, but really, he had been
brokenhearted since the death of his wife, Emmy, in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   HBO succeeds in chronicling the scope of Cosell's career, and
the use of archival radio, video and film material is enriching.
There is a fascinating sequence about Cosell's 1976 call of the Joe
Frazier-George Foreman heavyweight championship bout, which is
renowned for Cosell's call of Foreman's first knockdown of Frazier:
``Down goes Frazier!'' which he repeated three times and which
would not have seemed memorable emanating from anyone else, lacking
his unusual vocal rhythms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can hear him patting himself on the back,'' Foreman recalls,
``saying: `I told you, I told you! Down goes Frazier!''' The
documentary cuts to Cosell in the ring after the fight, smugly
saying, ``Didn't I tell you?''
</P>
<P>
   The documentary successfully shows how Cosell's intelligence
drove him to great heights, but built a foundation of intolerance
toward the people who worked with him, the
athletes-turned-announcers whom he scorned as ``the jockocracy,''
and the newspaper reporters he excoriated as low-paid hacks.
</P>
<P>
   The story of Cosell's early life would have benefited from
college and law school contemporaries and colleagues from his years
as a practicing lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Colleagues like Frank Gifford, whom Cosell vilified in the
memoir after their 13-year union on ``Monday Night Football,''
clearly held back on their most withering comments. ``I never read
the book,'' Gifford says. ``I had enough agitation with him,
traveling with him for `Monday Night Football.'''
</P>
<P>
   The documentary turns emotional when it shows a Cosell you never
sensed existed. To hear the words of his daughters, Jill and
Hilary, you discover a man fiercely devoted to his family and
profoundly in love with Emmy, evidently the only person who could
tame him.
</P>
<P>
   Cosell's radio eulogy to Emmy will move you to tears. ``My heart
aches,'' he said, his familiar voice slowed and quavering. ``I
thank whatever gods may be, Emmy, for your unconquerable soul.'' So
will Gifford's recollection of his final visit to the dying Cosell,
who sang a lament to his dead wife: ``Where are you? Where have you
gone without me? How can I live without you?''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   There may also be a need to explain Wilt Chamberlain's impact on
basketball to those who never saw him. At 10:30 Friday night, ESPN
profiles Chamberlain, ranked 13th on its list of the century's
greatest North American athletes. The program looks skillfully at
the contradiction between his great strength and his unwillingness
to wield it in anger. It examines his battles with Bill Russell,
about which Bob Cousy says, ``If he had one-third of Russell's
intensity, God, he would have been more awesome than he was.''
</P>
</TEXT>
