been as concerned as I am right now,'' he says of rising oil
prices. ``Unless certain things happen, demand will outrace
supply.'' (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT37) NEW YORK -- Oct. 28, 1999 -- OBIT-VELEZ, 10-28 -- James
Velez, a medical riddle who inexplicably scratched himself to the
point of self-mutilation and who was the center of one of the most
ambitious attempts to attain an independent life for a profoundly
disabled individual, died on Wednesday at a hospital in Manhattan.
He was 25 and lived in Queens. Velez is seen in his apartment in a
1997 file photo. The cause of death was infections of the blood and
spine, his parents said. (Chester Higgins Jr./New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT36) WASHINGTON -- Oct. 28, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., OCT. 31 --
WINTER-COX, 10-28 -- Louis Uccellini is director of the National
Center for Environmental Prediction, points to a graphic produced
before Hurricane Floyd that predicted the heavy rains and severe
flooding for areas of North Carolina. Although several billion
dollars worth of new satellites, computers, ocean buoys and
software have dramatically enhanced the Weather Service's
forecasting skills in the past five years, the resolution of the
system is not fine enough to forecast snowstorms, Uccellini said.
(Rick McKay/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT35) TEHRAN, Iran -- Oct. 28, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., OCT. 31
