<P>
   (NYT18) QUANTICO, Va. -- Oct. 29, 1999 -- CRASH-KNIGHT-2-COX,
10-29 -- This CH-46 hydraulic pump increased the pressure in the
hydraulic system of Sea Knight helicopters by 15 percent and, at
the same time, increased the amount of fluid flowing through the
system. The increased pressure in the lines, Marine Corps officials
acknowledged, could increase the risk that leaking fluid could
become atomized, or flammable, but they called the 15 percent
additional pressure ``negligible.'' (Rick McKay/Cox News Service
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) NORFOLK, Va. -- Oct. 29, 1999 -- CRASH-KNIGHT-1-COX,
10-29 -- ``We have to make hard choices based on dollars and
cents,'' said Marine Corps Col. Roger Dougherty, a former Sea
Knight pilot and until June the director of aviation safety at the
Naval Safety Center. ``If it's a high risk that's going to happen
often, it gets fixed. the bottom line.'' The Daily News
examination found that problems such as those involving the Sea
Knight hydraulic system often continue. (Rick McKay/Cox News
Service Photo)
</P>
