<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 21:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1743 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-ARMENIA-KILLINGS-BOS &LR;      10-28 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARMENIA-KILLINGS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAMPAGE MAY IMPERIL PEACE PACT WITH AZERBAIJAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN WHITMORE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ The killers who stormed Armenia's parliament may have
succeeded in stalling a planned peace pact with neighbor Azerbaijan
_ whether or not it was their intent.
</P>
<P>
   The brazen attack by five gunmen Wednesday, which ended with
their surrender early Thursday, has shocked this small former
Soviet republic to its core and left the country's powerful prime
minister, Vazgen Sarkisian, and seven other top officials dead.
</P>
<P>
   President Robert Kocharian on Thursday declared three days of
mourning, and US Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright ordered
her deputy, Strobe Talbott, to return to Armenia's capital,
Yerevan, to reassure the country's leadership and ``see what we can
do to lessen the pain.''
</P>
<P>
   In a televised statement before his surrender, the group's
leader, Nairi Unanian, an ardent nationalist and former journalist,
accused the government of corruption and allowing the country to
disintegrate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to save the Armenian people from perishing and
restore their rights,'' Unanian &UR;  &LR; said. ``Those responsible for
robbing the country must face trial along with us.''
</P>
<P>
   The five gunmen included Unanian's brother, Karen Unanian, and
uncle, Vram Galstyan.
</P>
<P>
   Despite widespread speculation, there is no indication that the
action was designed to derail a US-brokered peace deal in the works
over the disputed territory of Nagorno-Karabakh, an ethnic Armenian
enclave in Azerbaijan.
</P>
<P>
   Fallout from the attack, however, may overwhelm and distract the
government for some time, putting off any possible deal, analysts
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The loss of a strong leader like Sarkisian, who was able to
consolidate society, could weaken Armenia domestically. To
compensate for this psychologically, Armenia will probably take a
harder position on Nagorno-Karabakh,'' said Emil Pain, a former
ethnic affairs adviser to Russia's President Boris N. Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   Talbott left Yerevan on Wednesday just hours before the attack.
</P>
<P>
   The gunmen, who stormed the parliament during a televised speech
by the prime minister Wednesday evening, surrendered Thursday
morning after a 17-hour standoff. Kocharian guaranteed their safety
and pledged they would receive a fair trial.
</P>
<P>
   Hours after the gunmen surrendered, military leaders demanded
the resignation of top law enforcement officials.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear how the gunmen gained access to the parliament
chamber. Unanian reportedly held a journalist's accreditation and
news agencies reported that the five hid their weapons under long
trenchcoats.
</P>
<P>
   ``A treacherous and premeditated crime was committed. It was a
plot aimed at Armenia's statehood and against the future of the
Armenian nation,'' said a Defense Ministry statement continually
broadcast on national television. ``In such circumstances the
national army cannot stand idly by.''
</P>
<P>
   The statement reiterated, however that the military remained
loyal to the president and the constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Armenia's prosecutor announced a criminal case against the
gunmen on charges of terrorism and undermining the state. If
convicted, the five could face prison sentences of 10 to 15 years
or the death penalty, although Armenia has observed a moratorium on
executions since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement released Thursday, parliament denounced the
attack, saying it ``interrupts notable, positive trends in
Armenia's transition to democracy and free markets.''
</P>
<P>
   Sarkisian, who formerly led a group supporting veterans of the
war in Nagorno-Karabakh, was considered a moderate nationalist. His
party, called Unity, helped bring down Armenia's previous
president, Levon Ter-Petrosian, accusing him of being weak and
``defeatist'' on Karabakh. Nevertheless, Sarkisian has been
actively seeking a solution to the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Ter-Petrosian Thursday called on the nation to rally around
Kocharian, the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not doubt that the Armenian authorities will do their
utmost to maintain discipline and public order,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
