u i BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      10-28 0704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   NORTHERN IRELAND: UNITY ON ATTACKS
</P>
<P>
   The Ulster Unionist leader David Trimble and Sinn Fein's
president, Gerry Adams, condemned two attacks on Catholic families
by Protestant hard-liners aimed at destroying the Northern Ireland
peace accord. They spoke separately outside the talks, now in their
eighth week and being run by former U.S. Sen. George Mitchell, that
seek to restore progress to the pact.
</P>
<P>
   IRELAND: NURSES END STRIKE
</P>
<P>
   Hospital services returned to normal after the suspension of a
nine-day-old strike by 27,500 nurses, the largest work stoppage in
Ireland's history. Nurses will be voting on a new pay offer
recommended by their union.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY: DELAY ON PIUS XII
</P>
<P>
   Leading Jews said they were told by Vatican officials that Pope
John XXIII would be beatified next year, but that Pius XII, who was
pope during World War II, would not be beatified in 2000. Many
Jewish groups oppose Pius XII's beatification, saying he remained
shamefully silent during the Holocaust. Vatican officials said Pius
XII would not be beatified only because the paperwork was not
completed.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY: RELAXATION ON KURDS
</P>
<P>
   The military-dominated National Security Council recommended
that the southeast province of Siirt, which is mostly Kurdish, no
longer be governed under emergency rule. The recommendation was a
step in what some Turks see as a loosening of government control
over Kurdish regions, a move urged by foreign powers.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA: PLEA TO YELTSIN
</P>
<P>
   Former Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov and other political
leaders called on President Boris Yeltsin to emerge from his
self-imposed ``political isolation'' and fire members of his staff
who they said were openly interfering with coming parliamentary
elections. The leaders said that members of Yeltsin's inner circle
were abusing their power and putting pressure on the news media and
state authorities for their own political purposes.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   IVORY COAST: RULED OUT
</P>
<P>
   A government-controlled court invalidated the citizenship papers
of Alassane Dramane Ouattara, former deputy managing director of
the International Monetary Fund and an opposition candidate in next
year's presidential elections. The government has said that
Ouattara, prime minister from 1990 to 1993, is from Burkina Faso
and ineligible to run. The decision followed clashes between police
and Ouattara's supporters.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   PERU: JAIL STRIKE ENDS
</P>
<P>
   Three imprisoned leaders of the Tupac Amaru Revolutionary
Movement ended a hunger strike that lasted more than a month in a
Callao prison without succeeding in their demands to improve
conditions for scores of rebels. A relative said the three quit
because of poor health.
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA: CAMERAMAN ABDUCTED
</P>
<P>
   A Reuters photographer has been kidnapped by a left-wing
guerrilla group after accepting its invitation to cover a news
conference near Cali. The National Liberation Army says it plans to
put Henry Romero, 42, on trial because he revealed the identify of
a commander in a photograph in June, after the group kidnapped more
than 160 churchgoers at a Catholic Mass.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   KASHMIR: MUSLIMS KILLS 3
</P>
<P>
   Anti-India Muslim guerrillas fired 10 rocket-propelled grenades
into the well-guarded compound of the state secretariat in
Srinagar, killing three and injuring 16, according to local
authorities and witnesses. The Harkat-ul-Mujahedeen group claimed
responsibility for the attack.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: PROTESTS DIE DOWN
</P>
<P>
   After three days of rioting set off by the killing of a
Palestinian by an Israeli soldier, protests have died down in
Bethlehem, where preparations for the millennium are in full swing.
The Palestinians reportedly moved to stop the unrest ahead of a
planned Israeli-Palestinian meeting on Tuesday in Oslo, Norway.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: CHRISTIANS DEPORTED
</P>
<P>
   Israel began deporting 20 members of two apocalyptic Christian
groups on suspicion they might carry out acts of violence to
coincide with the millennium. Two Britons were flown to London and
eight people were to be flown to the United States.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
