<SLUG> BC-HALLOWEEN-CHURCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CHURCH'S HAUNTED HOUSE DESIGNED TO TEACH MORALS DRAWS FIRE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Colo.)   (bl)  
 By JIM YARDLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CEDAR HILL, Texas _ The sign _ ``Hell House'' _ suggests any
Halloween haunted house, but this one is very different.
Blood-spattered teen-agers die in a drunken-driving wreck. A young
girl who has been raped by her father commits suicide. A gay man
dies of AIDS. And a young woman dies of a botched abortion and
descends to hell.
</P>
<P>
   Each scene is intended to shock, but it is the opening scene
that is most shockingly familiar: Two teen-agers dressed in black
trench coats burst into a high school library and begin shooting.
The gunmen murder a student after she proclaims her faith in God,
and then kill themselves. The scene is a re-enactment of the
shootings at Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo., where the
depiction has given rise to accusations of insensitivity.
</P>
<P>
   Hell House, staged by a conservative evangelical church in this
suburb south of Dallas, is a fire-and-brimstone sermon tailored to
an MTV generation grown accustomed to graphic media portrayals of
sex and violence. It presents itself as a message about right and
wrong, and about hell as an actual place that is a consequence of
the latter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was scary,'' said Jessica Rhodes, 14, who was chaperoned by
her mother the other night through a maze-like collection of
portable buildings that serve as the Hell House set.
</P>
<P>
   The production here in Cedar Hill is among more than 400 with
such themes presented by church groups around the country this
year. But this one, run by Trinity Church of Assemblies of God, is
one of a very few to stage a Columbine scene, a decision that has
brought condemnation on the grounds of poor taste and particularly
poor timing. Only last week, the mother of a girl wounded in the
Columbine attack committed suicide and a student was arrested on
charges of plotting a further assault on the school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've been through enough,'' said Connie Michalik,
whose son, Richard Castaldo, was another of the 23 people wounded,
in addition to the 13 killed, by the two young Columbine gunmen.
``We've had a terrible, terrible week.''
</P>
<P>
   Even before the addition of the Columbine scene, Hell Houses had
drawn a measure of controversy in recent years, for portraying
homosexuality as a sin and abortion as akin to murder. But the Rev.
Tim Ferguson, the Trinity youth pastor, said his church, which has
presented a Hell House since 1990, had never anticipated anything
like the current reaction.
</P>
<P>
   In his book-lined office Wednesday afternoon, Ferguson, 38, had
bags under his eyes after a relentless succession of interviews
with the talk radio programs, television shows and newspapers that
have been calling from around the country since local news
organizations began carrying accounts of his Hell House a week or
so ago. From the general public, he said, he has received about two
dozen telephone calls, most of them complimentary, although the 20
or 30 e-mail messages, all from strangers, have been ``pretty
nasty.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I see it as hypocritical that we're getting attacked when
every TV station in the country wants to talk to us, and show it,
too,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the Columbine scene, the girl who is shot after refusing to
renounce God is then led to heaven by Jesus, while demons drag the
two gunmen to hell. The scene's message, Ferguson said, is that
``if you don't accept Christ, there are consequences to that in a
real place called hell.''
</P>
<P>
   There has been a proliferation of Hell Houses around the country
since 1995, when the Rev. Keenan Roberts of the Abundant Life
Christian Center in Arvada, Colo., began marketing a Hell House
how-to kit: a 270-page instruction manual that costs $199 and
includes scripts involving abortion, homosexuality, gang violence,
drugs and school shootings.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts said 435 churches in 46 states and eight foreign
countries ordered the kit this year. But, he said, his own church
decided against a school shooting scene this fall because Columbine
is less than an hour away. ``We felt it would be the compassionate
decision for what this community has gone through to not include
it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent night here, more than 150 people paid $7 each and
waited in line as groups of 30 were led through a dark maze of
rooms with varying themes acted out by some 300 students affiliated
with Trinity Church or its Christian school. Afterward, each group
was invited to meet with spiritual counselors to renounce sin and
embrace Christ.
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson said the graphic scenes were necessary to grab the
attention of teen-agers conditioned to violence and sex on
television. He also said he believed that the controversy over the
Columbine scene had scared away some church groups that usually
attend Hell House. But it was hard to find a negative reaction the
other night from the people who had just walked through.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Jones, 15, said a scene of a girl dying of a drug
overdose had reminded her of an uncle who had overdosed twice. And
Williestyne Miller cried outside in telling of the fatal shooting
of her 29-year-old son three weeks earlier. ``I didn't know if I
could come,'' she said, ``but the Lord gave me the strength.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson said he regretted any pain that his production had
caused people connected to Columbine. But, he said, he thinks his
message may prevent other killings.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Michalik, the Columbine parent, who first heard of
Ferguson's Hell House through news reports in Denver, said in a
telephone interview that she supported a message about good and
evil. But, she said, mimicking the events at Columbine makes
matters too close, too painful, particularly at Halloween, which
``is a druid holiday to begin with.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They just hit too close to home,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
