<SLUG> BC-BELL-RECRUIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US TO HELP BELL ATLANTIC FILL 2,000 OPENINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Faced with the tightest labor market in decades, Bell Atlantic
Corp. and the US Labor Department announced an unprecedented
partnership Thursday. The arrangement is designed to help the
telecommunications giant hire 2,000 employees by tapping into the
large number of unskilled workers who flock to state unemployment
offices for jobless benefits and leads to potential jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been looking for innovative models and approaches to
dealing with the skills shortage,'' Labor Secretary Alexis Herman
said Thursday. And ``one of our biggest challenges is making sure
workers have the skills to connect with jobs and employers have a
way to connect with skilled workers.''
</P>
<P>
   New York-based Bell Atlantic, which said the partnership may be
the beginning of a long-term relationship, is seeking to bolster
its ranks by adding a variety of positions, from telemarketers and
operators to cable splicers and network technicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our industry, telecommunications, is one of the
fastest-growing segments of the economy,'' said Ivan Seidenberg,
Bell Atlantic chairman and chief executive. ``We need all the
skilled people we can find, but tens of thousands of
telecommunications jobs are going unfilled in New York, Washington,
and Boston. This will provide a pipeline and help assure a more
diverse work force.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the partnership, jobless workers will be tested and
screened in states, including Massachusetts, that the firm serves.
Openings will be available to anyone who walks into a state
unemployment office, from laid-off workers to former welfare
recipients and recent high school graduates. State intake workers
will determine an applicant's skill level, and then offer state or
federally-supported training.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic estimated that between 300 and 400 of the 2,000
jobs will be in Massachusetts. The company's employment needs are
expanding as it grows from a Northeastern local telephone company
to a national force in wireless and high-speed Internet
communication. It is pursuing a $55 billion takeover of GTE, which
it expects to close next year, and is forming a coast-to-coast
wireless joint venture with Vodafone AirTouch PLC.
</P>
<P>
   The company also is seeking to become the first of the Baby
Bells to offer long-distance service, a line of business the
regional phone companies have been forbidden to enter since they
were broken off from AT&AMP;T in 1984. In Massachusetts alone,
long-distance calling is a $3 billion market.
</P>
<P>
   The Labor Department had offered a $300,000 grant to the company
to help defray the cost of training state workers to use Bell
Atlantic's criteria for screening applicants, Herman said, but the
company turned the offer down.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Delgado, a Bell Atlantic senior specialist in charge of
implementing the partnership with the Labor Department, said
government workers have already completed a two-month training
program to help them identify the skills needed to complete the
company's various tests.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, people will be screened for basic skills, such as
math and spelling, at the unemployment offices,'' said Delgado.
``For technical jobs such as cable splicer, we will do a second
screening of basic electronics skills. If someone cannot spell or
needs help with math, the Labor Department will train them and
improve their skills.''
</P>
<P>
   The starting wages for the jobs, which are entry level, will
range from $319 to $414 weekly. The positions will be full time,
with such benefits as a savings plan and medical, dental, and
vision coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, jobs vacancies listed with Bell Atlantic will be
posted on America's Job Bank, a Web site developed by the Labor
Department and the state employment system. Applicants can visit
the site, http://www.ajb.dni.us, to find out more about job
openings.
</P>
<P>
   More than four years ago, Bell Atlantic slashed its payroll in
an effort to reduce costs, offering a buyout package that added
five years of service to workers' pension eligibility. In all, an
estimated 8,000 workers took the buyout, according to Jeff Miller,
communications director for the CWA.
</P>
<P>
   ``Skilled workers were flying out the door, and suddenly, (the
company) was in a bind,'' said Miller. ``More people took the
buyout than they expected and then the economy boomed. So they are
now trying to get staffing back up.
</P>
<P>
   ``But in this economy it is not that easy to get people who are
up to speed.''
</P>
<P>
   Morton Bahr, president of the Communications Workers of America,
which represents 72,000 Bell Atlantic employees, said the union
expects to refer job inquiries to the program and will help train
new hires. During a telephone news conference Thursday, Bahr urged
more companies to develop similar partnerships with the Labor
Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the next four years, we may have a shortage of 1.8
million skilled workers,'' he said. ``Rather than get into a debate
over how many foreign workers we will allow to come here, we should
consider what Bell Atlantic and the Labor Department are doing
now.''
</P>
<P>
   The partnership is the first such project to be developed under
a system of public-private collaboration envisioned under the
Workforce Investment Act of 1998. The law condenses 60 federal job
programs into three federal block grants to various states, giving
financial responsibility and decision-making authority to state and
local communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will let us leverage and gain access to places we would
not normally happen to be,'' Seidenberg said. ``It is actually more
efficient for us and can help us reach more people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
