<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-JUSTICE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACQUITTALS IN MASSACRE AROUSE BRAZIL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Map is being
sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(bl) 
 By LARRY ROHTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELDORADO DOS CARAJAS, Brazil _ Three years ago, 19 landless farm
workers were killed in a confrontation with police at this bend in
a highway in the southeastern Amazon. More than 1,500 people
witnessed the Para state military police open fire, and the
incident was filmed and shown on Brazilian television hundreds of
times.
</P>
<P>
   But bringing those responsible for the deaths to justice is no
simple matter.
</P>
<P>
   The first phase of the trial ended with the acquittal of the
three commanders of the 147 police officers charged with the
murders of the peasants. That set off a furor that still
reverberates across Brazil and to human rights groups abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``It cannot be that nobody was responsible,'' said Brazilian
President Fernando Henrique Cardoso, clearly puzzled and
frustrated, after the verdict was announced in August. ``Somebody
had to be.''
</P>
<P>
   From the start, the investigation has been hampered by the
evident defiance of local authorities. One police unit said it had
no idea which officers had which guns on the day of the killings,
another handed over a gun registry that had been tampered with, and
complete autopsies of the victims were conducted only as a result
of federal government intervention.
</P>
<P>
   ``The argument of the police has been that they didn't shoot at
anyone, did not see anyone die, don't know how the victims were
killed and only gathered up the bodies,'' said Marcelo Freitas,
director of the Para Society for Human Rights and a lawyer who was
part of the prosecution team. ``They even claimed the landless
killed each other in order to be able to blame the police.''
</P>
<P>
   In reality, autopsies indicate, the majority of the victims died
not in an exchange of gunfire, as police originally maintained, but
after they were taken into custody.
</P>
<P>
   Several were shot in the head or neck at close range, leaving
powder burns, while others were hacked to death with their own
machetes and sickles. One had no gunshot or knife wounds at all;
his head was smashed by a rock.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real massacre did not occur in the initial skirmish,''
said James Cavallaro, the Brazil representative of the
Washington-based group Human Rights Watch. ``It occurred later,
after the police had knocked people to the ground or handcuffed
them and dragged them away and summarily executed them.''
</P>
<P>
   In a recent interview with foreign reporters, Brazil's minister
of agrarian reform, Raul Jungmann, acknowledged that state police
officers are often at the service of large landowners, ``who may
even kill in certain places where they are strong.'' Lawyers
representing the victims said that appears to be what happened
here.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have witnesses who heard the police asking `Where is so and
so,' so that they could take him away,'' said Carlos Guedes do
Amaral, a lawyer for the landless families here. ``To us, the fact
that the police had been ordered to remove the name tags from their
uniforms indicates that they went there with a clear intention to
kill.''
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to prevent powerful local landowners from
interfering, the case was transferred to the state capital, Belem,
350 miles upriver, and a special prosecutor was appointed after a
local judge said she ``prayed every night that the policemen will
be absolved.'' But the seven-member jury included an accountant who
is now under investigation on charges that he offered $1,500 bribes
to other jurors if they would vote to acquit.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors have filed an appeal and announced a postponement of
the trials of the remaining 147 officers until early next year,
after the commanders' situation is resolved. They have also
requested the suspension of the judge, citing irregularities in his
behavior during the trial and public remarks favorable to the
defendants made afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``The judge's behavior was tendentious,'' Amaral said. ``He did
not ask pertinent questions that should have been asked, that under
our legal system only the judge, and not the prosecution, can ask,
and he phrased his charge to the jury improperly, in such a way to
induce an acquittal.''
</P>
<P>
   The verdict has provoked fears of more intense outbursts of
violence in this Amazon frontier region. Farm workers have for
months been occupying other ranches in the area, including one
called Cabeceiras that is owned by the region's most powerful
family. The 600 families squatting there say they have been
threatened several times by gunmen.
</P>
<P>
   ``This decision is a license to kill the landless,'' said Jose
Batista Goncalves Afonso, local representative of the Pastoral Land
Commission, a Roman Catholic group that monitors rural property
conflicts. ``It says you cannot put a brake on the ability of
police and hired guns to take the law into their own hands, and it
gives judicial support to the violence.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the massacre at Eldorado, on April 17, 1996, at least 38
other people have been killed in land conflicts in this area, the
church body calculates. Afonso said there had been nearly 700
tenancy-related killings committed in Para since the Amazon land
rush began in the 1960's, and of those, he said, only two cases
ever went to trial and only one resulted in a conviction.
</P>
<P>
   For the survivors of the Eldorado massacre, there has been some
restitution. To acknowledge its moral responsibility, the federal
government has compensated the survivors by giving them title to
the ranch that was the focal point of the dispute.
</P>
<P>
   After the massacre, an investigation found that the owner of the
ranch had not paid his taxes for more than a decade, an omission
that allowed the government to seize the 42,000-acre property. Now,
690 formerly landless peasant families live and farm there on a
settlement called 17th of April.
</P>
<P>
   At the curve in the highway where the killings took place, a
museum and monument, in the form of 19 charred trunks of Brazil nut
trees, have been erected to honor the dead. But Francinete dos
Santos, the widow of Robson Vito Sobrinho, one victim, finds the
very sight distressing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I pass by, I realize we could all be here, working
together,'' she said in an interview at her simple wooden house at
the settlement. ``But what can you do? You can only hope that
justice will still be done.''
</P>
<P>
   At that, Celso Feitosa, a neighbor, shook his head and chided
her. ``You know that in Brazil, there is justice only for those who
have money,'' he said. ``We want bread, but they give us nothing
but lead.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
