<SLUG> BC-BIZ-ATM-CARDS-ART-$ADV31-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SIREN SWIPE OF THE DEBIT CARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic of debt
vs. credit card holders is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 31)  
 (af)  
 By JAN M. ROSEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Look at the people in front of you at the grocery check-out or
at the gas pump. Odds are they are swiping plastic through a
card-reading machine, cards that often are debit cards, not credit
cards.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, banks are replacing simple ATM cards with debit
cards bearing the Visa or Mastercard logos, good not only for
getting cash, but for shopping wherever those cards are accepted,
with the money debited from the card holder's account.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, soon more people may carry debit cards than credit
cards, according to The Nilson Report, an industry newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers show that consumers are embracing debit cards. Visa
reports an eightfold increase in cards issued, to 73.8 million last
year from 9.2 million in 1991, and a seventeenfold increase in
sales volume, to $134.7 billion from $7.9 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Olivier Cassegrain, who recently moved to New York from Paris
and opened a branch of his family's leather goods store, Longchamp,
on Madison Avenue, used his debit card from Chase Manhattan for
everything he bought to set up the new store.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's perfect,'' he said. The card provides the records a
business person needs. Unlike checks, it is readily accepted. And _
befitting a man who sells fine wallets _ ``it does not bulge in the
wallet.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Gerri Detweiler, education adviser to Debt
Counselors of America and co-author of ``Slash Your Debt, Save
Money and Secure Your Future'' (The Financial Literacy Center,
1999), said she carries her debit card only when she goes to the
bank for cash.
</P>
<P>
   ``Losing a debit card and having someone use it can be a real
hassle,'' she said. A thief could wipe out everything in your
checking account, leaving you without funds until the matter is
resolved. ``If you toss receipts at the register and don't read
your bank statements, don't use it,'' Ms. Detweiler advised.
</P>
<P>
   Under federal law, credit card holders are guaranteed much
stronger protection in case of loss, fraud or billing errors, she
noted, with damages limited to $50 if a loss is reported promptly.
</P>
<P>
   Debit card liability could also be $50 if the bank is notified
within two days of the loss or fraud being discovered. If
notification is later, however, the liability could be $500, and,
after 60 days, unlimited.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Visa and Mastercard pledge consumers stronger
protection on debit cards than the law requires _ Visa even pledges
zero liability _ so check a card issuer's policy.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, people who pay credit card bills on time enjoy an
interest-free loan until payment is due. Debit card charges are
taken from an account promptly.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, card holders who pay their entire bills on time will
be better off charging to their credit cards, while those who run
balances or miss payments, or simply like the ease of not having to
pay the bill, might be better off using debit cards.
</P>
<P>
   Say a card holder pays an annual fee of $85 for a credit card
that provides American Airlines frequent-flier miles and charges
$1,000 a month, always paying on time _ transferring money from a
savings account. In two years, the card holder earns enough miles
for a round-trip ticket worth perhaps $500 and has earned $25 to
$50 a year in interest _ a net gain of perhaps $400.
</P>
<P>
   But suppose the card holder pays the same $85 fee, charges only
$300 a month and misses three payment dates, incurring interest
charges at a 17.15 percent annual rate and a $29 late fee each
time. In two years that card holder has spent over $300 and has
fewer than one-third the miles needed for an plane ticket.
</P>
<P>
   This card holder would be better off with a no-fee,
lower-interest credit card and _ most of all _ the discipline to
pay on time, or a debit card.
</P>
<P>
   Either card is more secure than cash or checks, Ms. Detweiler
added. And a debit card may be the only one available to a person
with damaged credit or too new to the job market to have a credit
rating.
</P>
<P>
   Parents may also want to provide a debit card for a student away
in college, with the stipulation that it be used only in an
emergency. Similarly, some compulsive shoppers limit themselves to
debit cards.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Anthony N. McEwen, an executive vice
president at Visa USA, said people should carry both. ``We don't
see them as one versus the other,'' he said, ``but as complementary
products.''
</P>
<P>
   The one instance in which a customer may need a credit card, he
noted, is reserving a rental car. Only one debit card offers
frequent-flier miles: Chase has a Mastercard linked to Continental
Airlines. Beth Hirschhorn, a Chase senior vice president, reported
that people were opening Chase accounts just to get the card and
miles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
