<HEADER>
A1782 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-ABOUT-CARS-FOCUS-ART-     10-28 1167
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABOUT-CARS-FOCUS-ART-$ADV31-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2000 FORD FOCUS: THE ECONOBOX TURNS A CORNER AND PICKS UP AN EDGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 31)  
 (af)  
 By MICHELLE KREBS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Judging by the models arriving in dealer showrooms
this fall, one might think that small car sales are booming and
profits from them are soaring. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the opposite is true. The small car market has been in a
slump for nearly three years as cheap gasoline and stable car
prices have drawn buyers to larger vehicles, including sport
utilities. Profits from small cars are negligible to nonexistent. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Still, auto manufacturers must churn out small, fuel-efficient
automobiles to help bring down their federally mandated corporate
fuel economy averages, which are being pulled higher by brisk sales
of big, gas-guzzling vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, small cars are aimed largely at young, often
first-time buyers, a group expected to grow to as much as a third
of the market by 2005, according to J.D. Power &AMP; Associates, the
market research company.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the doldrums in the small-car market, the auto maker's
latest efforts to lure buyers to their much improved products have
been valiant. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last spring, DaimlerChrysler revamped its Neon for the 2000
model year, giving it a more grown-up look but maintaining its
fun-to-drive character. This fall Toyota introduced the Echo, an
unusual-looking small car with a price that starts around $10,000.
Saturn has spruced up its dated S-Series, and Nissan in the spring
will bring out a new Sentra, which is expected to be certified in
California as the world's first gasoline-powered ``super ultra low
emission'' vehicle. And Honda will revise the segment's
best-seller, the Civic, next year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Among the most impressive small cars of recent years, however,
is a new entry from the Ford Motor Co., the Ford Focus. The Focus
melds edgy styling with a spacious interior and superb driving
dynamics, and the entire package is reasonably priced.
</P>
<P>
   After a month with four versions of the Focus _ the base and
mid-level sedans, the station wagon and the sporty, top-line sedan
_ I concluded that the car is well suited to buyers who want more
than basic transportation, but still want an entry-level price. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Focus, which began arriving in dealer showrooms on Oct. 1,
is intended to replace the Escort eventually, but for now that car
will stay around; the Focus is priced and sized between the Escort
and the compact Contour. It comes as a ZX3 hatchback, a wagon and a
sedan in three versions _ the base LX, the big-volume SE and the
sporty ZTS.
</P>
<P>
   The car sold in the United States is virtually identical to the
one introduced in Europe a year ago, which auto writers have
already voted European Car of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Mercury Cougar, the Focus is cloaked in a rather
extreme example of Ford's New Edge styling, which features crisp
lines and taut surfaces. The Focus won't be mistaken for anything
else on the roads. I found more people liked its look than hated
it, but few fell in between.
</P>
<P>
   The interior is unusually spacious for a small car, with a high
roofline that comfortably accommodates 6-footers. Rear legroom is
among the best in class. The very supportive seats are raised
higher than in most small cars, and entry and exit is easy through
tall, wide doors. If nearly 13 cubic feet of trunk space isn't
enough, one simply folds the split rear seats to add capacity.
</P>
<P>
   To anyone accustomed to the clean, generic interiors of small
Japanese cars, the Focus seems awfully busy, a puzzle of assorted
geometrical shapes. Still, the pieces fit snugly, and the interior
materials seemed to be of good quality. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The controls are large and easy to operate; the gauges use large
numbers, making them easy to read. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ford says it used human and electronic testers to insure a
pleasant new-car smell in the Focus, but I still detected the acrid
odor that comes from plastic parts that haven't cured long enough. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Focus has many conveniences, including a
tilting-and-telescoping steering wheel, a height-adjustable
driver's seat, useful cup holders and a console with storage and a
pen holder.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Its standard safety features include seatbelts with
pre-tensioners and load-limiting retractors to keep occupants in
position in a crash, child safety seat anchoring system and an
emergency release inside the trunk. Side air bags are optional at
$350; and anti-lock brakes, standard on the ZTS, cost $400 on other
models. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After their purchase, Focus buyers receive a welcome package in
the mail from Ford, part of a youth-oriented marketing campaign
that includes live television ads and Webcasts. The welcome items
include a watch, a picture frame that attaches to the dashboard, an
expandable mega-sized cup holder and a sunglass case.
</P>
<P>
   To further personalize the car, as young buyers often do, Ford
plans to sell several accessory packages: one for pet owners has a
color-coordinated water bowl, among other things; a Friends Package
has seat covers, a candy dispenser and an ice cooler. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I could do without the candy or the dog bowl, but the car's
driving dynamics would seal the deal.
</P>
<P>
   This tiny car is darn fun to drive. It reminded me of Ford's
sporty Puma, a wonderful little coupe sold overseas. In fact, it is
built from the same basic architecture.
</P>
<P>
   The Focus is available with two 2-liter four-cylinder engines,
either a 110-horsepower single-cam version or a 130-horsepower
dual-cam Zetec, which is standard on the GTS and ZX3. Transmission
choices are a five-speed manual or a new electronically controlled
four-speed automatic.
</P>
<P>
   The dual-cam engine puts the Focus in the league with the peppy
Dodge Neon and versions of the Civic that have a zippy Honda engine
with variable valve timing. It handily accelerated onto the freeway
even when carrying five adults.
</P>
<P>
   The base engine did not measure up so well, however, and it felt
especially sluggish in the heavier station wagon, where it is the
only engine available. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the engine or trim level, the Focus handles
crisply and responsively. The steering is precise and the brakes
feel sturdy. The ride is comfortable for a car of this size, though
road noise is excessive, especially in the back seat.
</P>
<P>
   The Focus hatchback starts at $12,280, sedans at $12,540 and the
wagon at $15,795. The prices seemed attractive when they was
announced last spring, but Toyota upstaged Ford by putting a
sticker of $9,995 on the Echo hatchback.
</P>
<P>
   With its edgy styling, ample people and cargo space, great
handling and numerous features, the Focus makes a big impression.
It is a lot of small car for the money.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE TRACK: A funky-looking small car for drivers who like to
drive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
