<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 22:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1783 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-ECON-IMPACT-750(2TAKE     10-28 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECON-IMPACT-750(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CLEARER VIEW OF THE ECONOMY AS THE COMMERCE DEPARTMENT ANSWERS
ITS CRITICS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By LOUIS UCHITELLE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   With millions of Americans enjoying today's prosperity, some
experts have complained that the government's methods for measuring
the economy have failed to capture its true strength and dynamism.
Now the Commerce Department has responded with confirmation that
the critics were at least partly right.
</P>
<P>
   But the revised numbers on the economy's performance in recent
decades, published Thursday, still fall short of the prosperity
achieved in earlier booms since World War II. The ``New Economy''
that many proclaim is still a vision rather than a reality.
</P>
<P>
   True, the economy has grown faster in the 1990s than federal
statistics had acknowledged. Spending is stronger, investment is
greater, productivity is higher, inflation is a little lower. It
all adds up to an economy that produced an estimated $8.76 trillion
worth of goods and services last year, according to the revised
statistics, or $248 billion more than under the old method of
calculating economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   But it stopped short of recording the breakthrough to the
promised land of a new economy _ one in which high technology is
bringing about a transformation that makes the economy capable of
productivity advances reminiscent of the golden era of the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Growth is a couple of tenths of a percentage point higher,
particularly in recent years, but there is no change in long-term
trends,'' said Steven Landefeld, director of the Commerce
Department's Bureau of Economic Analysis, the bookkeeping agency
that published the revision of the statistics all the way back to
1959.
</P>
<P>
   It is not simply that pockets of overlooked production have been
belatedly discovered and incorporated into the gross domestic
product. There was some of that but, more importantly, the
government has provided a clearer view of the economy's performance
by giving much more credit than in the past to computer software
and banking improvements. Moreover, downward revisions in the
consumer price index _ already present in the unrevised data since
1995 _ have been applie back to 1959, a process that raised the
economy's inflation-adjusted ``real'' growth rate.
</P>
<P>
   And illogical bookkeeping has been fixed. The personal savings
rate, for example, has been raised to 3.7 percent of income in 1998
from nearly zero by listing federal contributions to the pensions
of government workers as savings rather than payments to social
insurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``That does not change the trend in savings, which has been
steadily downward,'' Landefeld said.
</P>
<P>
   The main goal of the revision has been to capture in the numbers
what the federal statisticians believe to be the true strengths and
characteristics of a modern economy. ``The economy is still the
same as it was before, but computer software and also banking are
playing much larger roles, and with this revision we are measuring
their contributions more accurately,'' said Brent Moulton, an
associate commissioner of the bureau.
</P>
<P>
   Economists on Wall Street found the revisions pleasing. ``They
show us that the economy has been growing somewhat faster than we
had thought and inflation is slightly lower, and that revised mix
is exactly what you like to see,'' said Richard D. Rippe, chief
economist for Prudential Securities.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing jumps out of the bureau's sharper focus on the economy
with greater force than computer software, which accounted for
nearly two-thirds of all the revisions. Every expert sensed that
software and the computers in which software is installed had
enhanced the nation's productivity, making the sort of contribution
that the spread of the automobile did in the 1920s. But until
Thursday, the Bureau had not quantified that improvement or raised
the growth rate of the economy as a whole to account for software's
rising contribution.
</P>
<P>
   Here is the crux of the ``New Economy'' argument. The rapidly
advancing electronic and information technologies, so dependent on
software, are viewed by this camp of economists and forecasters as
transforming the way Americans do business. As a result, they are
generating a breakthrough in economic growth that should be
sustainable for years.
</P>
<P>
   By this reasoning the stock market is not particularly
overvalued; the rising productivity of American workers helps to
justify high stock prices. And the inflation rate is lower than the
bureau has incorporated in its statistics. That would raise the
``real,'' inflation-adjusted value of all the goods and services
included in gross domestic product beyond the bureau's revisions.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   The bureau's fresh look failed to endorse this rosy perspective.
Even in the strongest period of the current expansion _ the last
four years through the third quarter of 1999 _ the GDP rose at an
average annual rate of 4.1 percent, up 0.4 of a percentage point
from the earlier figures. But there were similar spurts of even
stronger growth in the 1970s, 1980s and 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   And the comparison is flawed. Most economists gauge an economy
by comparing not just expansions but entire business cycles, with
each cycle including a recession as well as an expansion. By that
measure, the American economy in the 1990s has grown at an annual
rate of nearly 3 percent, up 0.5 of a percentage point after the
revision. But nearly 3 percent turns out to be no stronger than the
1970s and 1980s and significantly weaker than the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   ``The '60s were unprecedented and they still are,'' said David
Wyss, chief economist at Standard &AMP; Poor's DRI, a data gathering
operation.
</P>
<P>
   But the revisions do suggest that the long expansion of the
1990s, with its combination of healthy growth and low inflation,
could continue for a while. And while the overall growth rates for
the last three decades are similar, the latest data show that more
of the economy's growth in the 1990s was generated by improvements
in output per person rather than simply by putting more people to
work, while the reverse was the case in the 1970s and 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, the Federal Reserve and most economists believed
that the economy could grow over the long term at no more than 2.5
percent without suffering from shortages and inflation. Now the
upper limit appears to be 3 percent or a bit higher, says Robert M.
Solow, the Nobel laureate in economics at the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology.
</P>
<P>
   That is roughly the rate of growth since 1990. Implicit in this
new higher growth rate is an upward adjustment in the productivity
growth rate. Productivity measures the value of what a worker
produces in goods or services during an hour on the job.
</P>
<P>
   When that output rises, partly because of advances in
technology, so does the productivity growth rate. That rate had
advanced at a robust annual average of 2.8 percent from 1947 until
1973. And then for reasons never fully understood, the average
plunged to 1 percent or so for nearly 25 years. There has been a
partial rebound since 1995, and the revisions suggest that the
average has lately been roughly 2 percent, or even a bit more.
Complete productivity data, however, will not be available until
the Labor Department incorporates the higher output in its own
calculations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The productivity slowdown remains in place, it is just less
than it was, as these revisions suggest, for which we should be
grateful,'' said Jeffrey Madrick, an author who has written
extensively on productivity.
</P>
<P>
   Solow agrees. ``When productivity grows at 1 percent a year it
takes 72 years for the standard of living to double,'' he said.
``At 2 percent, it takes just 36 years. It is possible that we are
at that level now, although I will not take that to the bank until
the 2 percent survives the next recession.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Commerce Department's new approach, software purchased by
business, previously listed as an expense, becomes an investment,
retroactive to 1959. The difference is considerable. A $100
software purchase counted the old way as an expense was included in
the value of the final product sold by the company, like the steel
that goes into a car. But that same $100 worth of software,
properly counted, should be added directly to GDP, the bureau
concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Software is now classified like computers _ as a long-lasting
investment capable of generating revenue for a company. And indeed
software helps to generate such things as greater revenue from
telephone tolls and improved results from an automated, more
efficient assembly line. The $100 value, once added to GDP, is
subtracted or depreciated only gradually, over the three to five
years considered to be the life of a piece of software.
</P>
<P>
   Banking is the other big change. Its contribution to GDP had
been measured indirectly, by computing the number of hours worked
by the nation's bank employees and inferring a dollar amount. But
as new technology has spread through banking and hours have
declined, banking activity and revenue have risen. The new
yardstick is transactions: the number of checks cleared, the number
of ATM transactions, the number of loans made.
</P>
<P>
   The conceptual changes also coincided with various revisions
that pop up every few years when more complete data on such things
as wages, retail sales, consumption, profits and investment becomes
available as a supplement to the surveys used to determine the
quarterly growth numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are seeing here, apart from conceptual changes,'' said
Martin Baily, chairman of the President's Council of Economic
Advisers, ``is a stronger economy than we had thought because of
improved data collection.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-99 2209EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991028.0456 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 22:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1785 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SCI-KOOP-LATEX-2TAKES     10-28 0994
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-KOOP-LATEX-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER SURGEON GENERAL CRITICIZED FOR FINANCIAL TIES TO LATEX
MANUFACTURER  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Minn., Md., Ga.)   By HOLCOMB B. NOBLE    c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the spring of 1997, Dr. C. Everett Koop, the former surgeon
general, made a telephone call to Dr. Linda Rosenstock, director of
the National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health. The
agency was about to warn health workers that latex gloves widely
used in hospitals could cause serious, even life-threatening
allergic reactions. Koop told her that the language of the warning
was ``way overstated'' and could cause health workers to abandon
gloves that could protect them against infection, Rosenstock said.
</P>
<P>
   The issue arose again this year when Koop testified in the House
on March 25 before the oversight and investigations subcommittee of
the Committee on Education and the Work Force. Koop told the panel
that the hazards being linked to the gloves by scientists and other
health authorities were exaggerated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Borderline hysteria,'' he called them.
</P>
<P>
   But now, a spokeswoman for Koop, Mary Beth Zupa, acknowledges
that Koop had received substantial sums of money under a four-year,
$1 million contract he signed in 1994 with a leading manufacturer
of the latex gloves, a relationship he did not disclose to
Rosenstock or the subcommittee.
</P>
<P>
   Koop was not required to have registered as a paid lobbyist for
the company since he was not under contract with the glove
manufacturer when he made the call to Rosenstock at NIOSH or
testified before the subcommittee, which is headed by Rep. Charlie
Norwood, R-Ga.
</P>
<P>
   When told of Koop's contract with the glove manufacturer, John
Stone, the press secretary for Norwood, said, ``This is the kind of
thing he is adamant about at hearings on all issues. He always
wants to know if there have been financial arrangements with
parties interested in matters under discussion.''
</P>
<P>
   Koop repeatedly declined to discuss the matter, but Ms. Zupa
said he had done nothing improper. His contract with the glove
maker, WRP Corp., did not last the full four years and had nothing
to do with its latex division, she said, adding that it never
occurred to Koop to make such disclosures.
</P>
<P>
   NIOSH issued its warning anyway. But ethicists and public
interest groups say that although he was not required to do so by
law, Koop had an obligation to disclose his financial ties to
NIOSH, to the Congress and to the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``What this long admired and respected man has done in taking
money from a glove manufacturer and then speaking out on its behalf
is wrong,'' said Susan Wilburn, senior specialist in occupational
safety and health for the American Nurses Association. ``But worse,
he has given very powerful help to an industry whose product is
harming health workers and patients.''
</P>
<P>
   She added, ``People harmed through use of the gloves, and their
loved ones, wouldn't call the concern `hysterical.'''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Wilburn said an estimated 200,000 nurses had developed
allergies, and NIOSH studies show that 10 percent of health-care
workers regularly exposed to the gloves and 17 percent with heavy
exposure have developed allergies. Nearly 10 million Americans are
employed as health workers but little data exists on their rates of
exposure to the gloves. More than 300 lawsuits have been filed by
health workers and patients who say they have been harmed. Also,
some of the nation's leading hospitals, including the Mayo Clinic
and Johns Hopkins, have begun replacing powdered latex gloves with
alternatives. Hospital officials say these gloves work as well as
the powdered latex gloves and are well accepted by hospital
workers.
</P>
<P>
   Koop has long been one of the nation's most trusted health
experts, a reputation he gained as surgeon general in the 1980s in
battling the tobacco industry and focusing a reluctant nation on
the seriousness of AIDS, among other efforts.
</P>
<P>
   But critics have found fault with steps that Koop and his
business associates took to profit from his name and reputation,
including establishing financial ties to companies whose products
and services were described on a Web site he established,
dr.koop.com, which is designed to present objective health
information. (Modifications were subsequently made on the site in
response to the criticism.)
</P>
<P>
   The critics say the glove contract is more troubling because it
involves public policy and public health.
</P>
<P>
   According to filings with the Securities and Exchange
Commission, the glove company contract called for Koop to deliver
four speeches a year on health and nutrition. He gave the company
the right to use his ``name, picture, speeches and biographical
information'' and agreed to serve as a company adviser. He also
agreed not to endorse products of competitors, and to submit his
speeches for editing as long as the company did ``not change the
substance'' of the text. The contract also entitled Koop to a
five-year option to buy 500,000 shares of company stock at a 1994
price, and a percentage of the net sales of nutrition products, a
new line the company was entering.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Zupa, said that Koop did not receive the full $1 million
called for in the contract, but she would not say how much he did
receive. However, a footnote to a WRP corporate filing with the SEC
refers to an unnamed ``individual'' who served as a ``spokesman for
the company'' and received $656,250 in consulting fees, through
February 1997. A representative of the company confirmed that the
individual was Koop.
</P>
<P>
   Sanford Lewis, a lawyer for a group called Healthcare Without
Harm, formed, Lewis said, to monitor health and safety in the
medical field, said that Koop's activity on the glove issue, and
particularly his testimony in Congress, had been influential.
``Would even Dr. Koop have sounded so convincing,'' Lewis asked,
``if he had disclosed his financial deal with the glove company?''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Lewis said Koop's testimony in March was still being cited in
state legislatures as reasons to delay action on the gloves, even
though ``it was based on a study that was never done.'' Koop had
told Congress that he based his conclusions _ that concern about
the gloves was unwarranted _ on a study by the Centers for Disease
Control. But the agency said later that it had not made such a
study.
</P>
<P>
   The report Koop referred to was paid for, it turned out, by
another glove maker, Allegiance Healthcare Corp., the author of the
study said in a court deposition. Koop said in an interview last
month that he had been misled about the report's origin.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Zupa said Koop became involved with WRP because of an
interest ``in increasing the efficacy of vitamins for health care
for some time.'' She said he never received any royalties on net
nutrition sales because there were none, something confirmed in the
company's 1997 10K filings with the SEC. As a result, the company
declared it was concentrating on latex gloves.
</P>
<P>
   According to SEC documents, the company's board had already
decided that the company should get out of the nutrition business.
``That means,'' Lewis said, ``that for a year and a half after the
company lost any interest in promoting its nutrition products, Koop
was still its consultant _ and it would be hard for him not to know
what business they were in.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosenstock of NIOSH said that Koop telephoned her as her agency
was preparing its bulletin on the potential dangers of exposure to
rubber latex gloves containing protein and powdered corn starch.
The powder is meant to make it easier to get the gloves on and off,
but allergists say that when it mixes with the protein in the
gloves it can cause severe allergic reactions leading on rare
occasions to anaphylactic shock and, in five known cases, death,
Rosenstock said. If the powder from the gloves is dispersed in the
air, it can even affect people who have not worn the gloves.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenstock, whose agency is a research division of the CDC, said
Koop told her he had seen a draft of the NIOSH bulletin. She said
his view was that it would ``cause more harm than good'' because it
might frighten hospital workers out of using gloves that protect
them in handling infectious materials, Rosenstock said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I assured him that we had sent the bulletin out for peer
review and I was confident that it was well based scientifically,''
she said, and in the end, the agency issued the bulletin, including
language in the final version that Koop objected to.
</P>
<P>
   The bulletin suggested that health workers use nonlatex gloves
for activities not involving infectious materials and that if they
chose latex gloves for handling infectious materials, they use
``the powder-free kind with reduced protein content.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the Food and Drug Administration, the Occupational
Safety and Health Administration and a number of scientists,
including members of the American Academy of Allergies, Asthma and
Immunology, all have taken the same basic position.
</P>
<P>
   Sheldon Krimsky, a professor in urban and environmental policy
at Tufts University who has written extensively in science journals
on disclosure issues, said of Koop's role in the glove issue,
``anyone who attempts in a public forum to influence public policy
has an absolute obligation to disclose any financial interests he
has or has had within a time frame that could be perceived to
represent a bias _ and it certainly did in the Koop cases.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Sidney M. Wolfe, a physician and director of Public
Citizen's Health Research Group, which sought unsuccessfully in
1988 to have the powdered-gloves banned from all hospitals, said,
``The whole issue with these gloves is a no brainer: Powdered
gloves are causing serious problems. They're causing hospitals to
lose workers who become disabled and there are perfectly good
alternatives to that type of glove _ and Koop has absolutely no
scientific basis for the position he has taken.''
</P>
<P>
   In response to criticism, an OSHA spokeswoman said that the
current warnings seemed to be sufficient but that the agency was
considering whether to take active enforcement action.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-99 2215EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
