<DOCNO> NYT19991028.0458 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 22:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1787 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-GREENSPAN-COX     10-28 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GREENSPAN-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Greenspan upneat about U.S. economy
</P>
<P>
   By Jeff Ostrowski
</P>
<P>
   BOCA RATON, Fla. _ Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan said
market-driven rising interest rates are likely to keep the economy
on a sustainable, non-inflationary path, and that U.S. productivity
gains are genuine and lasting.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan's comments Thursday night to an audience of business
executives at the Boca Raton Resort &AMP; Club _ hours after the
government reported the economy expanded in the third quarter at
the fastest pace this year without triggering higher inflation _
suggest the central bank chief isn't itching to raise the overnight
bank lending rate a third time this year when the Fed meets Nov.
16.
</P>
<P>
   ``The process of containment may already be significantly
advanced,'' Greenspan said in a speech to the Business Council,
made up of the chief executives of the nation's top companies.
</P>
<P>
   A rise in real, or inflation-adjusted borrowing costs for
businesses, home buyers and consumers should slow growth and keep
the economy from overheating, Greenspan suggested.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. economy has benefited in recent years from a
significant upturn in the growth of productivity, which has helped
keep inflation under control, Greenspan said.
</P>
<P>
   But Greenspan warned the Fed must be particularly alert to any
signs that productivity gains are faltering and be ready to contain
inflationary forces that could derail America's long period of
prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan did not directly address whether the central bank is
preparing to raise interest rates. But he left no doubt that Fed
officials are on heightened alert.
</P>
<P>
   He said the extra vigilance is needed in part because the U.S.
economy is in uncharted waters with productivity _ the amount of
output for each hour of work _ accelerating in recent years after
two decades of lagging gains.
</P>
<P>
   HEADLINE HERE
</P>
<P>
   Private economists said Greenspan gave no clear signal in his
remarks about what the central bank might do next.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. prosperity has been produced by ``a major acceleration in
productivity'' spurred by technological developments such as the
Internet, Greenspan said.
</P>
<P>
   Businesses can get more information faster and make decisions
more quickly, enabling companies ``to remove large swaths of
inventory safety stocks and worker redundancies,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a ``virtuous cycle,'' Greenspan said, in which ``a
whole new set of profitable investments raises productivity, which
for a time raises profits _ spurring further investment and
consumption. At the same time, faster productivity growth keeps a
lid on costs and prices.
</P>
<P>
   Other than his seeming reluctance to tinker with interest rates
_ no guarantees, of course _ Greenspan was even more low-key than
usual during his speech.
</P>
<P>
   No mention of ``irrational exuberance,'' nor even of the stock
market.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan stuck to his theme _ technology's effects on the
economy. He credited technology for creating what he called ``this
period of extraordinary innovation and progress in the American
economy.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he warned, the boom likely will slow.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rate of growth of productivity cannot continue to increase
indefinitely,'' Greenspan said. ``At some point it must at least
plateau.''
</P>
<P>
   If productivity slows, and if low unemployment boosts wages,
inflation could be the result, he said. Greenspan's favorite
anti-inflation weapon: higher interest rates. But he didn't say the
hated word ``inflation,'' instead couching the concept in less
direct terms.
</P>
<P>
   HEADLINE HERE
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan read from an 11-page speech for a half-hour. He never
gesticulated and only occasionally glanced up from the lectern to
look at his audience.
</P>
<P>
   He earned one subdued chuckle with this comment to a crowd of
200 heavy with national media: ``I do not perceive the end of the
shopping mall, if for no other reason than I have been strongly
advised that shopping is not solely an economic phenomenon.''
</P>
<P>
   The Business Council's clout is illustrated by Greenspan's
decision to show up in person. In the past year, Greenspan has
talked to two other groups in Boca Raton _ the Securities Industry
Association last November and the Futures Industry Association in
March _ but both times he appeared by satellite.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan isn't paid for his speeches. The Fed pays for the
economy's most powerful man to fly coach to speaking engagements.
</P>
<P>
   Two more household names _ Microsoft Chairman Bill Gates and
Democratic presidential candidate Bill Bradley _ are scheduled to
address the CEOs today in Boca Raton.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
