<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 22:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1791 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-CONGRESS-SPEND-1STLD-     10-28 1297
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-SPEND-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE PASSES GOP SPENDING BILL AMID CHARGES OF `CREATIVE
ACCOUNTING' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (subs for clarifications and refinements throughout)  
 (ATTN: Fla., Ky., Mo., Va., Wash., Ill., Calif., S.C., Wis.)   (ART ADV: Photo NYT4 has been sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By TIM WEINER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House on Thursday narrowly passed the last
spending bill of the year, an $85 billion measure for labor, health
and education programs, containing an 0.97 percent across-the-board
cut in federal spending. The cut would create on paper a budget
that did not tap into Social Security money.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has said he will veto the bill, setting the
stage for the final act in this year's budget battle: negotiations
between the White House and Congress that will go into high gear
next week.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the budget plan preserved Social Security money
only as the result of ``smoke and mirrors'' _ creative accounting
by Republican lawmakers _ that had ``totally bumfuzzled'' American
voters.
</P>
<P>
   He was supported in that argument by the nonpartisan
Congressional Budget Office, which said Thursday that the
Republicans were $17 billion over their spending limits and into
Social Security money.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton offered to compromise with the Republicans. ``I'm
prepared to work with them,'' he said at a news conference with
Nigerian President Olusegun Obasanjo. ``I don't want a partisan
fight on this. This is crazy for us to be having a big partisan
blowout'' over the Social Security issue.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans remain wary, having been bested by Clinton in budget
battles before.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our numbers are not that far apart,'' said Rep. C.W. Bill
Young, R-Fla., the chairman of the House Appropriations Committee.
``We are far apart on the political rhetoric.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   This was a rare understatement on a day marked by furious
speeches and duels fought with numbers on the House floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's Halloween and the Democrats are up to their old tricks,''
said House Majority Whip Tom DeLay, who argued that the Republicans
had ``just won the first battle of this war'' with Clinton by
writing a budget that ``protects every penny of the Social Security
surplus.''
</P>
<P>
   A jazz quartet played ``Pennies From Heaven'' as the Republicans
gathered on the Capitol's lawn to celebrate passage of the bill, by
a vote of 218-211, in which four fiscally conservative Democrats
voted for the bill. The four were Reps. Frank Lucas of Kentucky,
Pat Danner of Missouri, Virgil Goode of Virginia and Adam Smith of
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Seven Republicans defected.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is we've stopped the raid on Social
Security,'' said Speaker Dennis Hastert.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate will take up the bill financing the departments of
Labor, Health and Human Services and Education, along with the
across-the-board cut, as early as Friday. The spending bill
contains $314 billion, of which $85 billion is discretionary
spending and $229 billion is mandatory funds that are required by
law. It also includes 316 earmarks, pet projects backed by
individual Republican lawmakers, totaling at least $360 million.
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans contend that their across-the-board cut in all
13 spending bills that finance the operations of all federal
agencies but not mandatory programs like Medicaid and welfare will
save about $5.7 billion. That, they say, will create a budget that
will not tap surplus Social Security revenues to operate government
agencies _ which would be the first time that has happened in four
decades.
</P>
<P>
   But the CBO said in a new analysis Thursday that this was not
true.
</P>
<P>
   It said the Republican-written spending bills exceed lawmakers'
self-imposed spending limits by about $17 billion and will drain
that much money from surplus Social Security revenues. It cited
$17.7 billion in spending outlays that the Republican leadership
has instructed the CBO to ignore.
</P>
<P>
   This technique, called directed scorekeeping, allows the
Republicans to argue that their across-the-board cut will result in
a small surplus in general government revenues and leave the Social
Security funds untouched.
</P>
<P>
   As an alternative to the across-the-board cuts, Clinton has
proposed either raising revenue with a tobacco tax, finding
spending cuts in government programs or realizing savings from
unspent government funds.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Republicans' spending bills also include $18.6 billion in
outlays that the leadership has designated as unanticipated
``emergency spending,'' which technically does not count against
the spending limits that Congress imposed on itself. These include
programs like the 2000 census, which by law must be conducted ever
10 years, and a 25-year-old program to help poor people pay their
heating bills in winter.
</P>
<P>
   They also rely on about $2.3 billion in outlays taken from the
budget for fiscal 2001, and two payments that will be delayed until
that year _ $3.3 billion in research grants at the National
Institutes of Health and $1.3 billion due Pentagon contractors.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the appearance of a balanced budget relies on at least
$43 billion in creative accounting by the Republicans, according to
an analysis of the 13 spending bills and the CBO report. It would
require an across-the-board cut of 4.8 percent to bring the budget
into balance without using Social Security funds, the congressional
auditors say.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans adamantly deny that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've now proved that you can fund the government without
raiding Social Security,'' said House Majority Leader Dick Armey.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats are running ``a disinformation campaign'' by
emphasizing the CBO numbers, said Rep. John Edward Porter, a
moderate Republican from Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jerry Lewis, R-Calif., said the CBO analysis proved that
``there are lies, darn lies, and statisticians.''
</P>
<P>
   But House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt said the CBO analysis
``repudiates the Republicans' false claims.''
</P>
<P>
   The ranking Democrat on the House Budget Committee, John Spratt
of South Carolina, called the Republicans' accounting ``too clever
by half'' and compared their arguments to ``a medieval trial.''
</P>
<P>
   And the ranking Democrat on the Appropriations Committee, David
Obey of Wisconsin, called the Republican spending claims ``a magic
show designed to put on a phony debate about Social Security.''
</P>
<P>
   The Social Security issue has been used by both parties as a
lightning rod, with both sides claiming that their spending
strategies will protect retirees in years to come. But independent
budget analysts say the spending of surplus Social Security
revenues has no effect on the solvency of the retirement fund. But
the surplus funds can be used to pay down the federal debt, which
now stands at $3.6 trillion, a strategy increasingly favored across
the political spectrum.
</P>
<P>
   In this increasingly cranky Congress, with each party all but
calling the other liars, the bitterness spilled over to the Senate,
where Democrats are frustrated by Republican control of the agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been the biggest legislative graveyard since I've
come to Congress,'' said Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle. He
also said Senate Democrats would start running television ads
countering commercials made by House Republicans that ``will deal
with Social Security _ what the real facts are.''
</P>
<P>
   The House and Senate also passed the month's third continuing
resolution, which keeps government agencies running in the absence
of a real budget until Nov. 5.
</P>
<P>
   Although fiscal 2000 began Oct. 1, the budget battle will
continue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-99 2217EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991028.0463 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 22:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1792 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS &LR;      10-28 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANDREYCHUK POWERS BRUINS PAST LIGHTNING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ When the Bruins went winless in their first nine games
(0-5-4) to tie for the longest winless start in franchise history,
the tension around the club was so thick you could cut it with a
knife. But coach Pat Burns remained upbeat through all the
hand-wringing and predicted his club's fortunes would turn around.
</P>
<P>
   In its last four contests, starting with a tie in Los Angeles in
the last game of that winless stretch, Boston is 3-0-1, including a
wild 7-3 victory over the Tampa Bay Lightning at the FleetCenter
Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Andreychuk had four goals as Boston generated more than
twice the offense of any other game this season and continued to
creep back toward .500 (3-5-4).
</P>
<P>
   In the first 11:31 of the first period, the Bruins jumped out to
a 4-0 lead. Boston took full advantage of Tampa Bay's penalty
trouble, scoring three goals on the power play, with Andreychuk
picking up his sixth and seventh of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Andreychuk's first came at 4:16 after defenseman Ben Clymer,
originally a Bruins draft pick, was whistled for tripping.
Defenseman Ray Bourque, at the right point, backhanded a pass to
defenseman Darren Van Impe at the left. Van Impe teed up a shot
that was blocked by Tampa defenseman Ian Herbers, but the puck
squirted right to Andreychuk in the slot, and the left wing rifled
a shot past goalie Daren Puppa.
</P>
<P>
   Soon afterward, Clymer was nailed again on another tripping
call, leading to the Bruins' second goal. Jason Allison, positioned
along the left-wing boards, dished a pass to Van Impe at the left
point. Van Impe set up Bourque for the one-timer, and the puck
appeared to glance off a Tampa defender and high into the net for
the 2-0 lead at 9:54. It was Bourque's third goal of the year, and
Allison extended his assist streak to six games.
</P>
<P>
   Boston's next two goals came only 22 seconds apart. During the
power play, Allison skated around behind the net and came out near
the left post, trying to bury the puck through Puppa's pads. It
bounced off one of them and right to Andreychuk, who beat Puppa top
shelf with a backhander at 11:09.
</P>
<P>
   Lightning coach Steve Ludzig had seen enough and pulled Puppa
(eight shots, three goals) in favor of Kevin Hodson. But he didn't
fare well in the early going, surendering a goal on the first shot
he faced.
</P>
<P>
   At 11:31, with the teams back at even strength, Joe Thornton
drove down the right side, beating defenseman Andrei Zyuzin, and
flung the puck at the net. The puck went through the crease,
bounced off a Tampa player, and went into the net for the 4-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Lightning rallied for the next three goals. During a
three-on-two rush, left wing Andreas Johansson took a pass from
Robert Petrovicky and beat goalie Rob Tallas to the glove side at
17:44.
</P>
<P>
   At 5:43 of the second, center Vincent Lecavalier beat Tallas
with a backhand shovel shot, pulling the Lightning to within 4-2.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa made it even tighter at 13:52 when right wing Stan Drulia
scored. Center Chris Gratton had centered pass that travelled
through the crease and pinballed around. Tallas appeared to have
corralled it, but Drulia jabbed it free and into the cage.
</P>
<P>
   Only 21 seconds later, though, Andreychuk completed his 11th
career hat trick to give Boston some breathing room. Allison beat
defenseman Bill Houlder down low in the left corner and relayed the
puck right to Andreychuk in front. He buried his shot, and the
Bruins were up, 5-3, at 14:13.
</P>
<P>
   For some reason, Ludzik opted to put Puppa back into the game
for the third period. The Bruins took advantage of that and scored
a pair of goals 1:18 apart to surge ahead, 7-3.
</P>
<P>
   Andreychuk potted his fourth of the game and ninth of the season
at 6:19, giving him his third career four-goal contest. He also has
a five-goal game, coincidentally against the Bruins, in an 8-6 win
by the Buffalo Sabres Feb. 6, 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Heinze completed the scoring with his third goal of the
year, scoring at 7:37 when his slapper from the right point hit a
Lightning stick and changed direction, fooling Puppa.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
