<SLUG> BC-TB-GLOBAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORT RAISES ALARM ON TUBERCULOSIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A major Harvard University report that raises the
specter of a global tuberculosis epidemic has become the
battleground on how best to fight the deadly disease.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes are huge: the outcome determining whether some will
be treated and others not, and whether enough new money will be
found to combat drug-resistant strains of the disease.
</P>
<P>
   In a report released Thursday, Harvard Medical School authors
challenged the conventional means of tuberculosis control, saying
drug-resistant TB cases flourish even in areas with well-run
TB-control programs. They documented the spread of drug-resistant
TB to 104 countries and territories.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the authors predict, no country will be immune to
the disease, and major outbreaks could occur anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   To date, drug-resistant tuberculosis has made only sporadic
inroads into the United States, most prominently the 400 cases in
New York earlier this decade that cost $1 billion to control. But
with more outbreaks around the world, the authors believe it could
happen again and again in America, especially with 47 million
visitors a year arriving here.
</P>
<P>
   Americans traveling abroad also could be soon affected, the
authors said. ``People could soon think twice where they travel
to,'' said Dr. Jim Yong Kim, who wrote parts of the report. ``In a
few years, it may be judged by some too big a risk to go to the
Dominican Republic, or even visit Machu Picchu in Peru.'' Both
countries have reported drug-resistant TB outbreaks in the past.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the World Health Organization warned that if
drug-resistant tuberculosis ``is unleashed, we may never be able to
stop it.''
</P>
<P>
   Harvard's study said multidrug-resistant TB ``has already, in
fact, been unleashed. The questions before us are no longer when?
but rather how? and to what extent?''
</P>
<P>
   Policymakers are at odds on how to answer those questions. The
World Health Organization has established a low-cost program called
DOTS, which stands for directly observed treatment, but coverage is
spotty. It still has not reached 84 percent of people worldwide
with active TB.
</P>
<P>
   Resistance develops when people forget to take their medication
or the pills run out, and someone with drug-resistant TB can then
pass it on to others, transmitting the infected bacteria by
coughing or sneezing.
</P>
<P>
   Mycobaterium tuberculosis already is the world's most deadly
infectious disease, killing about 2 million people a year. Fully
one-third of the world's population is infected with TB, but only
10 percent of those will ever develop active cases in their
lifetime. Once someone develops an active case, they infect 10
people every year.
</P>
<P>
   WHO officials argue that the most effective way of fighting TB
is through their basic programs, which can cost as little as $10 a
patient in the Third World. By comparison, drug-resistant cases can
cost between $300 to $4,000 a patient.
</P>
<P>
   The Harvard authors argued for both fights: WHO programs with
singular efforts to cure each drug-resistant TB patient. Otherwise,
they argue, the deadly strains of drug-resistant TB will spread
unchecked.
</P>
<P>
   ``To give a Russian prisoner, for example, the regular
WHO-recommended treatment when he has multidrug-resistant TB is the
equivalent of rubbing spinach on their head,'' said Paul Farmer,
the principal author of the Harvard study, in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   After the release of the report, funded by George Soros' Open
Society Institute, the Harvard authors, WHO leaders and other
TB-control experts met Thursday night to discuss strategies on
where to put funds and how to raise more money. The meeting was
closed, at the request of the WHO officials.
</P>
<P>
   One key participant, Arata Kochi, director of WHO's global
tuberculosis program, has great doubts about a rapid expansion of
the fight against drug-resistant TB.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview from Geneva this week, Kochi said the
success in Peru does not mean the Harvard team could stop the huge
outbreak in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no comparison,'' Kochi said. ``We have to do
something about drug-resistant TB, but it costs a tremendous amount
of money. How do you do it? We don't have a solution yet. It costs
$3,000 to treat one Russian prisoner, but only $10 to treat a
person in India with easily treatable TB. The choice has to be
made: the $3,000 prisoner or the $10 cost to others.''
</P>
<P>
   Farmer disputed arguments that fighting drug-resistant TB should
take a back seat to expansion of the DOTS program.
</P>
<P>
   The battle now, he believed, should be over finding funds, not a
fight among TB-control experts. In Russia, where drug-resistant
cases account for as much as 9 percent of all TB cases in some
areas, the only way to treat each infected person is to learn which
drugs will work, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The World Bank is considering a $100 million loan to fight TB in
Russian prisons. While that may help, Farmer estimated that $1
billion may be needed for Russia alone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-99 2223EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
