<SLUG> BC-LEVI-LEVI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   Levi Strauss Will Halt Sales On Its Web Sites 
 &HT;     By Carol Emert 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Taking a 180-degree turn from the rest of retailing, Levi Strauss &AMP;
Co. will halt sales from its Levi's and Dockers Web sites after
Christmas. Instead, J.C. Penney and Macy's, two big Levi's
merchants, will begin selling the merchandise on their sites.
<P>
   Like most of its attempts to sell clothes through its own
brick-and-mortar stores, Levi's e-commerce effort was not
implemented effectively. Sales at www.levi.com and www.dockers.com
have been dismal and costs have been extremely high, industry
sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Troubled Levi's, whose sales have been sliding for three years,
launched its e-commerce effort last November, saying it wanted to
learn more about its consumers through direct interactions with
them.
</P>
<P>
   The move angered its retail partners, who had been barred from
selling Levi's and Dockers over the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Under Phillip Marineau, the chief executive who started last
month, Levi's is attempting ``to focus back on their core
business,'' said one source. ``Online is not something they're
specialized in.''
</P>
<P>
   The heat is on: Levi's faces its third year of declining sales
this year and is expected to suffer its first net loss in more than
a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Beckman, a Levi's spokesman, said the company was happy
with sales from the sites. But ``during the past year, it became
clear to us that the cost of running a truly world-class e-commerce
business is unaffordable right now as we look at other competing
priorities.''
</P>
<P>
   One problem is that consumers have to send returns through the
mail instead of being able to take them to stores, Beckman said.
The sites will continue to offer information such as store
locators, he said. E-commerce partners may be expanded beyond
Macy's and Penney's in the future, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Penney's will begin selling Levi's and Dockers merchandise at
www.jcpenney.com in time for Christmas, said spokeswoman Stephanie
Brown. ``We are expecting great things, but of course, it's too
early to tell,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Macys.com will begin selling Levi's and Dockers products after
Christmas, Beckman said. ``The online customer has told us
repeatedly that powerful national brands, which I consider Levi's
and Dockers to be, are very desirable merchandise on the Web.''
said Kent Anderson, CEO of Macys.com.
</P>
<P>
   USWeb/CKS, a San Francisco consulting firm, has been managing
Levi Strauss' e-commerce business. An executive there declined to
comment. Levi's spokesman Danny Kraus said there will be no change
in the relationship with USWeb/ CKS.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
