<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HMO-HMO </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Class-Action Suit Filed Against Aetna  &HT;     By Tom Abate 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
A San Francisco law firm filed a class-action suit yesterday in
state court in Martinez charging Aetna U.S. Healthcare with
misleading customers by not disclosing that doctors may have a
financial incentive to withhold care.
<P>
   The suit was filed by San Francisco attorney Fred Furth, who is
part of a national legal syndicate that won millions of dollars in
tobacco-suit settlements and who now has targeted health insurers.
</P>
<P>
   These attorneys already have filed similar suits against Aetna
and other HMOs in the federal courts.
</P>
<P>
   In essence, these suits claim that health insurers are
misleading customers by not disclosing the common practice of
capitation. HMOs commonly pay doctors a fixed monthly fee of about
$40 per patient. That fee must cover most of a patient's care,
including visits to primary-care doctors, specialists and tests. It
usually does not cover hospitalization. The doctor gets the same
fee from the HMO if the patients uses a lot of services or none.
</P>
<P>
   The suit argues that patients aren't aware that these capitation
agreements could give doctors an incentive to withhold care because
the doctors get to keep any money left over after all of their
patients have been treated and must pay for services that exceed
capitation fees.
</P>
<P>
   ``These capitation agreements have been guarded secrets,'' Furth
said at a press conference. ``They may have been known to some, but
they were not known to all.''
</P>
<P>
   Atena spokesman Bobby Pena denied that Aetna had misled members
or violated the law or standard industry practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an instance of trial lawyers targeting health insurers
in the name of profit,'' Pena said.
</P>
<P>
   HMO critic Harvey Rosenfield, founder of Consumer's for Quality
Care in Santa Monica, also questioned Furth's motives. ``There's
plenty of injustice that needs to be remedied,'' Rosenfield said.
``But these guys are just in it for the money.''
</P>
<P>
   Furth disputed that assessment, saying that if he wins his suit,
filed on behalf of a San Diego woman who was denied care to treat
cancer, he would seek to force Aetna to explain the poorly
understood capitation system and to refund millions of dollars in
premiums to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   He said his firm is working on similar cases against other HMOs.
He predicted that eventually, ``all of the other HMOs will be
involved in this litigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Aetna had other legal headaches yesterday. It said the
Securities and Exchange Commission is reviewing its accounting
practices in relation to some recent acquisitions, including the
company's $1 billion purchase of Prudential Insurance Co. of
America's health care unit.
</P>
<P>
   But that didn't dampen Aetna's finances. The company reported a
27 percent rise in earnings despite problems it has been having
integrating the money-losing Prudential business into its own.
Aetna's stock dipped 7.7 percent late last month when officials
told analysts that losses at the Pru unit were running at $200
million a year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
