<BODY>
 AM-GAP-GAP_ SF CHRON  
 Gap Division Boss Robert Fisher Resigns
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By Carol Emert &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Robert Fisher, son of Gap Inc. founder Donald Fisher, resigned
yesterday as president of the sagging Gap division, ceding control
of the unit to chief executive Mickey Drexler.
</P>
<P>
   With Fisher's resignation, effective November 15, no members of
the Fisher family will be involved in day-to-day operations at Gap
Inc., which also runs the Old Navy and Banana Republic chains.
Donald Fisher remains chairman of the board.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Fisher also will resign from his position as executive
vice president of the parent company, Gap Inc., but will remain on
the board.
</P>
<P>
   Performance at domestic Gap, babyGap and Gapkids stores began
sliding this year after impressive growth last year. ``They've
squeezed themselves on the top end with Banana Republic and on the
bottom end with Old Navy, so what do you do?'' said one retail
watcher, explaining Gap's dilemma.
</P>
<P>
   Gap Inc. stock rose $3.13, or 10 percent, yesterday to $34.75,
but it is down from a 52-week high of $52.69, largely because of
softness in the Gap division.
</P>
<P>
   Gap Inc. sales are projected to total $11.6 billion this year,
with adult U.S. Gap stores, the largest single  &LR; division,
accounting for $3.9 billion, according to Credit Suisse First
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Drexler, who reportedly has focused more attention on the Gap
division in recent months, will run it for the foreseeable future,
said company spokesman Alan Marks.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Marks said Robert Fisher's resignation was ``an entirely
personal decision'' that has ``no connection with the business.''
Robert Fisher, who has three children, ``has no specific plans
other than to spend time with his family,'' Marks said.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Fisher, 44, who became president of the Gap division in
1997, is one of Gap Inc.'s biggest stockholders, with a 5.7 percent
stake, according to a public filing. He joined the company as a
store manager in 1980 after earning an MBA at Stanford University,
and he rose through the ranks to serve as chief operating officer
and chief financial officer, among other positions.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he was not seen as an heir apparent to Drexler as CEO.
Fisher earned a salary of $950,000 last year, according to a
Securities and Exchange Commission filing.
</P>
<P>
   His brother, William Fisher, a former head of Gap Inc.'s
international operations, resigned from the company last year and
is no longer connected with the company, Marks said.
</P>
<P>
   Doris Fisher, Donald Fisher's wife, is a board member.
</P>
<P>
   Another family member with close ties to Gap Inc., Donald's
brother William, owns and operates Fisher Development Inc., a
privately held company that is the general contractor for most Gap
stores. Fisher Development is not formally related to Gap Inc.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
