<HEADER>
A1807 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-CHROMOSOME-GENDER-BOS     10-28 0528
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHROMOSOME-GENDER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY TRACES ORIGIN OF GENDER GENES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KAREN HSU  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   About 300 million years ago, an ordinary chromosome mutated,
creating what would become the male and female chromosomes as
nature began a grand experiment in using genes to determine gender.
</P>
<P>
   Until that point, gender was probably determined not by
differing chromosomes, but by some environmental factor, like the
temperature of the water in which the egg incubated, which still
happens in such reptiles crocodiles and sea turtles: these
creatures preceded mammals in evolution history.
</P>
<P>
   Now, researchers say they have reconstructed the history of the
gender genes by tracing back the mutations that make the X
chromosome different from the Y chromosome. Their work suggests
that the chromosomes were last identical between 240 million and
320 million years ago, shortly after the divergence of the
evolutionary lines leading to mammals and birds.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, it was believed that the first changes were around
170 million years ago, said Dr. David Page, of the Whitehead
Institute in Cambridge, Mass., who worked with Bruce Lahn of the
University of Chicago on the study.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 46 human chromosomes, 44 are identical pairs. Over the
years, a pair of regular chromosomes differentiated into two
distinct ones, the X and the Y, which determine whether a baby is
boy or girl.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think today's X chromosome retains the gene content'' of
the non-sex chromosome, Page said.
</P>
<P>
   Using genetic sequence information obtained from a variety of
sources, Page said that he and colleagues found 19 genes that are
the same on both chromosomes, and all of these genes are
concentrated on the tip of the short arm of the X, whereas they are
scattered across the length of the Y.
</P>
<P>
   A mutation somehow created a gene called SRY, for
sex-determining region Y, and it became the master switch for
creating a male, Page said. Over millions of years, the
male-determining Y chromosome lost more and more genes, and Page
said that it hasn't finished evolving and losing genes. The X
chromosome has three times more DNA than the puny Y, and has 100
times as many genes.
</P>
<P>
   Page and Lahn were able to rough out four major genetic
shuffling events that were responsible for the evolution of the
distinct chromosomes. After the first, others occured 130 to 170
million years ago, 80 to 130 million years ago, and, the most
recent, 30 to 50 million years ago. This was after monkeys diverged
from the lower prosimian primates. The first Homo sapiens did not
appear until less than 1 million years ago.
</P>
<P>
   James Bull, a professor of integrative biology at the University
of Texas in Austin and a specialist in evolutionary biology, said
that Page's work provides the first evidence to prove what
evolutionary biologists have long theorized: that the Y was
originally like the X chromosome and then lost many of its gene
functions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is fair to say that this is the best evidence to show''
that the theories are correct, Bull said. ``I think genetics
textbooks will have this study in them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-99 2226EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991028.0474 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 22:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1810 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-WELLS-WELLS_SFCHRON &LR;      10-28 1288
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WELLS-WELLS </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 New Wells Fargo CEO Now Winning With Sales Pitches  &HT;     By Sam Zuckerman  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Richard Kovacevich was one of the top hurlers on the Stanford
baseball team in the 1960s, a big league prospect until a rotator
cuff injury ended his career.
<P>
   Three decades later, Kovacevich is still pitching, except now
he's serving up mortgages and checking accounts instead of
baseballs. The chief executive of San Francisco's Wells Fargo may
well be the industry's top salesman _ a leader who has defied the
conventional wisdom that banking is a slow-growth industry and
turned his institution into a marketing machine.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a retailer at heart and most bank CEOs are not,'' said
Terri Dial, the group executive vice president who runs Wells
Fargo's California network.
</P>
<P>
   Kovacevich, a former toy company executive who will turn 56 in a
few days, brought his brand of banking to California a year ago
next Tuesday when his Minnesota bank, Norwest, bought the old Wells
Fargo, took its name and moved its headquarters to San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The new Wells Fargo, the nation's seventh-largest bank, has
branches in 21 Western and Midwestern states. It also owns a
mortgage company and a consumer finance company with nationwide
operations.
</P>
<P>
   As CEO of the combined bank, Kovacevich moved quickly to instill
Norwest's sales spirit in the old Wells Fargo territory. In
California, employees at the branches, known as ``stores'' under
the Norwest system, started getting big doses of the Minnesota
bank's old-time religion _ sell more products to existing
customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cross-selling is our mantra,'' said Kovacevich.
</P>
<P>
   Inside branches, new sales incentives were adopted and links
were set up with the bank's mortgage and consumer finance units.
Additional salespeople were added in some branches, which something
that  &LR; would have been anathema under the penny-pinching philosophy
of the old Wells.
</P>
<P>
   Sales surged as a result. During the first half of 1999,
California mortgage originations more than tripled and total
product sales per employee jumped 24 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the bank's revenue rose to $12.3 billion during the
first nine months of 1999, up 6.5 percent from the year before, a
strong figure in the banking industry, where revenue growth is
typically in the low single digits.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Making Merger Work
</P>
<P>
   Snappy top-line growth has made the new Wells Fargo one of the
few financial success stories among the crop of bank mergers
unveiled in the past few years.
</P>
<P>
   Of 11 major banks and thrifts that took over rivals in 1997 and
1998, only Wells Fargo and Wisconsin's Firstar met Wall Street's
profit projections, according to the New York brokerage Keefe,
Bruyette &AMP; Woods.
</P>
<P>
   Wells Fargo's stock has risen by a third in the past last &LR; 
 &LR; year, closing yesterday at $49.06, up $2.56. That beat the KBW
Bank Stock Index, which rose 24 percent in the same period.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, to meet its profit targets, Wells Fargo isn't axing
as many jobs as some rivals. The bank said it expects to eliminate
about 5 percent of total jobs through next year, about 4,600
positions.
</P>
<P>
   That's fewer less  &LR; than the 18,000 jobs, or 10 percent of total
positions, disappearing at Bank of America, created last year when
North Carolina's NationsBank bought San Francisco's BofA and took
its name.
</P>
<P>
   At Wells Fargo, ``management seems to be more involved with
their employees,'' said Scott Edgar, director of research at Sife
Trust, a Walnut Creek mutual fund that invests in banks. ``They
don't go in and fire a lot of people all at once.''
</P>
<P>
   The good reviews Kovacevich has gotten doesn't mean that
combining the old Wells Fargo and Norwest has been a walk in the
park. slam dunk. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  The two banks were studies in contrast. Wells Fargo was a
hard-boiled institution that focused on efficiency and used
technology _ ATMs, telephone banking and computers _ to keep costs
down.
</P>
<P>
   Norwest was warmer and fuzzier, a people-oriented place that
regularly held rallies for '`team members'' and specialized in
one-on-one service at the branches.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think the bank has got huge potential,'' said Thomas
McCandless, an analyst with the investment bank CIBC World Markets
in New York. ``But coming up with one playbook has not been easy.''
</P>
<P>
   In trying to build a single institution, Kovacevich said he has
been careful to select the best the two banks had to offer.
</P>
<P>
   When banks combine, ``some people want to demonstrate that they
were right and you were wrong, and that they're in control,''
Kovacevich said. `'That's the kiss of death.''
</P>
<P>
   Kovacevich has been scrupulous about picking executives from
both banks. Paul Hazen, the CEO of the old Wells Fargo, Fargo's &LR; 
CEO,  &LR; remains as chairman and supervises corporate banking
operations. Rod Jacobs, the chief financial officer of the old
Wells Fargo, has the same job at the new bank, as do many other
senior managers of the former San Francisco bank.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Kovacevich has gone with the old Wells Fargo's
popular Internet banking program, which recently signed up its
millionth customer. But he has stayed with Norwest's mortgage
operation, a unit that ranks as the nation's No.2 mortgagemaker.
mortgage maker. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  In some cases though, analysts worry that Kovacevich may be
postponing tough decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Take commercial real estate lending and corporate banking. The
old Wells Fargo took calculated risks, lending corporations and
developers big sums after carefully evaluating their
creditworthiness. Norwest considered big commercial loans too
risky, focusing instead on selling companies an array of financial
services, such as managing their cash receipts.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Kovacevich hasn't settled on a single model. Instead, he
is letting the two sides of the bank continue business as usual in
the corporate arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's taking them a lot of time for them to figure out how to
put together the corporate side of the bank,'' said analyst
McCandless.
</P>
<P>
   Wells Fargo officials counter that they have moved slowly to
combine the two banks to avoid the kind of breakdowns and snafus
that plagued bank integrations that were rushed. Such mishaps
prompted tens of thousands of customers to flee after the old Wells
Fargo took over First Interstate in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   While Kovacevich insists on calling his transaction a ``merger
of equals,'' there's no doubt who is in charge. ``As a practical
matter, I know who the CEO is,`` said Hazen, chief of the old Wells
Fargo.
</P>
<P>
   Kovacevich, the son of a lumber mill worker, grew up in
Enumclaw, Wash., in the shadow of Mount Rainier. He honed his
salesmanship three decades ago hawking Play-Doh and Snoopy
toothbrushes while serving as manager of Kenner Products, then the
toy division of cerealmaker General Mills.
</P>
<P>
   After a stint as an entrepreneur, Kovacevich jumped to Citibank,
where he managed the bank's New York retail branch network. He
moved to Norwest in 1986, after a Citibank rival was tapped to run
consumer banking operations, and became the Minnesota bank's CEO in
1993.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Kovacevich has been a banker since 1975, he
certainly doesn't fit the buttoned-down stereotype.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, at an Orlando, Fla., Florida,  &LR; meeting of
hundreds of Wells Fargo staff members, Kovacevich brought the house
down by climbing onto a stage and launching into a rendition of the
Rolling Stones' ``Satisfaction.'' (I still get some satisfaction,
when I see that finance action. ...'')
</P>
<P>
   ``He came out with a red tank top and jacket and started pulling
his jacket back,'' recalled Dial. ``It scared the hell out of me _
he really looked like Mick Jagger.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
