<SLUG> BC-GAP-EXECUTIVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAP PRESIDENT IS LEAVING AMID LAGGING REVENUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By LESLIE KAUFMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Robert Fisher, the son of Gap Inc.'s founders, announced
Thursday that he would step down as president of the flagship
division, The Gap, whose sales have been lackluster in recent
months.
</P>
<P>
   His duties will be assumed by Millard Drexler, the chief
executive of Gap Inc. and the dynamic executive credited with the
vision that helped propel the company's extraordinary rise. Even as
The Gap store sales have stalled, the company's newer Banana
Republic and Old Navy chains have posted strong growth.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher said disappointing sales at his unit were irrelevant to
his decision. ``When you spend 19 years in this business, you have
a lot of up and down cycles,'' he said in an interview. ``If I let
every fluctuation on business bother me, I would have been on leave
a long time ago.'' Fisher, 44, described his departure as a leave
of absence effective Nov. 15 and said he would remain on the board
of directors.
</P>
<P>
   Stock analysts heralded the management change. ``It is a sign
that the corporation has put a major agenda on fixing Gap stores,''
said Janet Kloppenburg, a retail analyst with Robertson Stephens.
``Mickey to date has never taken over anything and not been
successful.'' The stock rose $3.125 on the news, to $34.75, as the
broad market averages lept higher.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher took over as president of The Gap division in May 1997.
Soon after, he began a television ad campaign showing lithe young
people boogieing in khaki pants, an effort that ushered in several
months of double-digit growth for the chain. But The Gap, which
still accounts for roughly 35 percent of Gap Inc.'s revenue, has
been in a slump since the spring. For September, sales declined
nearly 4 percent at stores open at least a year, the sixth
consecutive month of flat or declining sales.
</P>
<P>
   Gap Inc., powered by the Banana Republic and Old Navy divisions,
continued to post solid sales and earnings growth during this
period. But the share price, which is down 34 percent from its July
peak, still looks rich to some analysts unless the company can
return to double-digit sales growth, for which it needs better
numbers at the 1,021 Gap stores.
</P>
<P>
   The Gap has been criticized for reacting slowly to increasing
demand for items that are of-the-moment trendy instead of
tried-and-true basics. While The Gap has had fashionable items like
leather jackets and embroidered jeans in its inventory, it readily
admits that it did not stock enough of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gap has been missing with key trend items, like cable rib
sweaters, paratrooper pants and distressed embroidered denim,''
John Morris, a stock analyst at Gerard Kleiner and Mattison, said
of the fall lineup. ``Or when they have some of these items, they
have not been featuring them in their advertising.''
</P>
<P>
   The miscue has been particularly painful because more and more
competitors have gotten the formula right. The Limited Inc., which
runs stores like Express and Lane Bryant, has been dead-on with the
urban sophisticate look this season. Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch and
American Eagle Outfitters have similarly been enjoying double-digit
growth as they connect with hip, college students at The Gap's
expense. Old Navy, Gap Inc.'s spinoff with lower-cost merchandise,
has been taking a chunk of The Gap's cool as well.
</P>
<P>
   Although Fisher came to the company by way of his founder
parents, his role as an executive has hardly been cosmetic. He
started as a store manager in 1980 and in 1985 was named executive
vice president for merchandising at Banana Republic, then an
11-store division of Gap Inc., and eventually become that
division's president. Over the years, he also served stints as Gap
Inc.'s chief operating officer and chief financial officer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
