<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 22:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1812 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-FAMILY-FAMILY_SFCHRON     10-28 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-FAMILY </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Lobbyists Want States to Pay Workers on Family, Medical Leave  &HT;     By Sam McManis 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Lobbyists who gave birth in 1993 to the Family and Medical Leave
Act now want states to pay workers when they take time off to care
for a new child or ill family member.
<P>
   Donna Lenhoff, general counsel for the National Partnership for
Women and Families and the author of the FMLA, said her
organization is campaigning for all states to pay workers _ either
through disability or unemployment benefits _ when they take family
or medical leave. The FMLA requires companies with 50 or more
employees to offer workers up to 12 weeks off each year to care for
a new child, a sick family member or if they become ill.
</P>
<P>
   Many parents, Lenhoff said, do not take advantage of the FMLA
because they fear lost income. A recent survey conducted by the
bipartisan Family Leave Commission reported that nearly 1 worker in
10 who takes family or medical leave is forced into public
assistance during that span. The commission also reported that 64
percent of employees who did not take family leave said they could
not afford to be without a paycheck.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paid leave will make the promise of family leave so much more
workable for almost all workers,'' said Lenhoff, who is in San
Francisco today to speak at the Family Caregivers' Alliance
Convention at the Holiday Inn in the Financial District.
</P>
<P>
   She sees California's program as a model for other states.
California allows for a maximum of one year of temporary disability
insurance for pregnancy and recovery from childbirth _ depending on
complications and pending a doctor's approval. For normal pregnancy
and childbirth, women are entitled to six weeks of paid leave.
</P>
<P>
   Four other states _ Hawaii, New Jersey, New York and Rhode
Island _ provide some kind of pay for family and medical leave.
</P>
<P>
   As controversial as the original family leave act was _
President George Bush vetoed legislation twice before President
Clinton signed it in 1993 _ the idea of dipping into unemployment
and disability funds for family leave has drawn loud protest from
employers' groups.
</P>
<P>
   The National Federation of Independent Businesses opposes
government regulation of employee benefits. The U.S. Chamber of
Commerce wrote to the Department of Labor that using unemployment
funds would open a ``Pandora's box.'' And Deanna Gelak, director of
governmental affairs for the Society for Human Resources
Management, seeks to curtail or even abolish the FMLA.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that raiding the unemployment fund or disability
will jeopardize the future of unemployment benefits,'' Gelak said.
``We've always felt the best arrangement is to have employers set
up leave policies. The FMLA hurts co-workers and customers when
it's misapplied.''
</P>
<P>
   Lenhoff said she expected opposition for state-financed family
leave income from the same groups that originally objected to the
FMLA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hearing the same thing (now) that they said about the FMLA
and, in historical perspective, about the minimum wage and overtime
regulations in the '30s,'' Lenhoff said. ``I understand that
there's a lot of emotion and knee-jerk fear, but that same
`the-sky-is-falling' predictions didn't happen with family leave,
and it won't happen now.''
</P>
<P>
   The bipartisan Commission on Leave, founded by Congress as part
of the 1993 legislation, reported in 1998 that 86 percent of
companies said the FMLA had no noticeable effect on productivity,
and 92.5 percent reported no impact on profits.
</P>
<P>
   Lenhoff said her group is not lobbying for a federal law, as it
did in the original family leave act, because paid leave is too new
a concept.
</P>
<P>
   ``Income leave was in the front of our minds when we were
lobbying for the FMLA, but it was too much to ask for then,''
Lenhoff said. ``Before you can get something to the federal level,
it needs to have a track record in the states, like the FMLA did.
It needs exposure. We have only five states that finance leave
(through disability).''
</P>
<P>
   Starting January 1, the weekly disability benefit in California
will rise to $490 from $336 per week.
</P>
<P>
   ``California's plan is great, but it's limited to the
(pregnancy/childbirth) portion of the FMLA,'' Lenhoff said. ``We
need broader family leave (income) for workers who need time off
for elder care or if they have a child in the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   In July, Gov. Gray Davis signed a bill that enables employees to
use their own paid sick leave to care for ill family members, which
is not covered by disability insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Netsy Firestein, director of the Labor Project for Working
Families in Berkeley, said many lower-income workers cannot afford
to take leave beyond the disability allowance afforded for
pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear that a lot from the unions I deal with but also from
professional people,'' Firestein said. ``I just talked to an
attorney who took six paid weeks off after a normal birth. She
could have taken an additional 12 weeks without pay, but even she
couldn't afford that. Six weeks of paid leave is almost nothing.
Parents still are faced with hard choices.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
