<HEADER>
A1813 &Cx1f; tad-z
r p BC-GOP-DEBATE-COX     10-28 0687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-DEBATE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush's no-show dominates GOP debate
 &HT;    By Brian E. Crowley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HANOVER, N.H. _ He wasn't on stage, but the presence of George
W. Bush was felt during an hour-long candidate forum Thursday where
the Texas governor was pelted for his absence and the $60 million
he has raised for his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   It began seconds into the nationally televised event when
Arizona Sen. John McCain told the audience that ``what the people
of New Hampshire expect and demand, (is) to see us, to talk to us
and hear what we have to say.''
</P>
<P>
   In the final minutes, publisher Steve Forbes criticized Bush for
not showing up, saying that Bush skipped one other joint appearance
to raise money for his campaign and that ``perhaps in the future,
if we call it a fund-raiser he'll show up.''
</P>
<P>
   With Bush absent, attention was focused on his two most serious
rivals: McCain, who has been steadily gaining in statewide polls
here, and Forbes, who has vowed to ``spend whatever it takes'' of
his personal fortune to win the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Staying in Texas was a calculated risk for Bush, who risks
alienating New Hampshire voters who delight in spoiling frontrunner
campaigns. At the urging of his New Hampshire campaign staff, Bush
made a five-minute appearance on a statewide television station
and, somewhat defensively, apologized for attending an award
presentation for his wife, Laura, at Southern Methodist University
in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an important night in New Hampshire,'' he said. ``But
it's a more important night in Dallas as far as my family is
concerned. I really don't regret this opportunity to honor my
wife.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the forum was spent answering serious questions about
issues including gay rights, legalization of marijuana, abortion,
campaign finance reform and education. Sharing the stage with
Forbes and McCain were Sen. Orin Hatch of Utah, former United
Nations Ambassador Alan Keyes and Gary Baur, who worked in the
Reagan administration.
</P>
<P>
   Saying he is proud of being a ``pro life person,'' McCain said,
the Republican Party should not discourage people who support
abortion rights from joining the GOP. `` We want you in our
party,'' he said. ``We can have respectful disagreements about
issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Forbes, who has been criticized for not disclosing exactly where
the money he is spending for his campaign is coming from, said that
unlike ``the lobbyists who have rallied around Bush'' who ``want a
coronation,'' his candidacy is being opposed by them ``because I'm
independent.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatch, who got into the campaign late and has had a difficult
time making any progress said that he wants to prove that big money
isn't necessary to win the nomination. ``If I get a million people
to give me $36, I'll have as much money as George Bush,'' and it
would change politics forever, he said.
</P>
<P>
   At one point the forum was interrupted by a woman shouting in
the audience who ignored efforts to get her to be quiet. She was
removed from the hall.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, got some laughs when he was asked about legalizing
marijuana at least for medical use. ``That's is an excellent
question,'' he said then waiting a beat, ``to duck.'' He then said
he does not support legalization and added, ''My friends we're
losing the war on drugs. ...There was a time when we weren't losing
and that's when Nancy Reagan had a very simple program 'just say
no.' ``
</P>
<P>
   ``Homosexuality is an abomination,'' said Keyes in response to a
question concerning discrimination against homosexuals. Any
comparison of discrimination against blacks and homosexuals ``is
absurd,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes congratulated his opponents for their support of a flat
tax. He said that when he ran four years ago, he was the only
candidate favoring a flat tax. He said it shows that ``education
can work.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who has only spent nine days here insisted that he is not
taking the Granite State for granted. He promised to attend a
televised debate on Dec. 2, his first with the the other
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
