s f BC-BIZ-BRIBE-RATINGS-$AD     10-28 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-BRIBE-RATINGS-$ADV31-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. GIVEN LOW MARKS FOR HONESTY  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 31) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By SKIP KALTENHEUSER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is it the Ugly American all over again?
</P>
<P>
   Transparency International, the organization based in Berlin
that annually ranks countries based on how corrupt their officials
are perceived to be, added a new wrinkle this year by rating the
bribe payers, not just the bribe takers.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest surprise in the results was how badly the United
States fared, despite its long history of inveighing against
international commercial bribery.
</P>
<P>
   For decades it stood alone in making payments by its companies
to overseas officials a crime, and Washington pressed hard for the
adoption of an antibribery convention in late 1997 by the
Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development, or OECD; the
agreement took effect in February.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for all that, the United States was rated down in the middle
of the pack in the Transparency survey, tied with Germany, a
country seen by anticorruption campaigners as recalcitrant on the
issue and reluctant even to stop companies from taking tax
deductions for ``commissions'' and ``finder's fees'' paid to
overseas officials, let alone outlaw the payments, known
colloquially in German as Schmiergeld, or grease money.
</P>
<P>
   Transparency officials said the explanation for the United
States's relatively poor showing might lie at least in part in the
nature of the survey. On the group's behalf, Gallup International
asked executives, bankers, accountants, lawyers and chambers of
commerce in 14 large developing countries to assess how likely
companies from the leading export nations were to pay bribes to
obtain contracts. So the resulting index measures reputation _ not
necessarily behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Being the only superpower probably did not help the United
States, according to Jeremy Pope, executive director of
Transparency International. ``It is a fair bet that U.S.
heavy-handedness builds resentment and may well have driven down
the U.S. rating,'' he said, even though the Foreign Corrupt
Practices Act, the 1977 law outlawing bribery of overseas
officials, ``undoubtedly has major impacts on the conduct of many
large U.S. corporations.''
</P>
<P>
   Fritz Heimann, chairman of the group's American chapter, saw
some irony in the law's effects. ``Because U.S. companies have
comparative success in countries known for endemic corruption,
locals assume they must be paying bribes,'' he said, when in fact,
American companies use the 1977 law ``effectively as a bribe
solicitation conversation-stopper.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mike Hershman, a co-founder of Transparency International
and the chairman of DSFX, an international investigative firm, said
deep-seated suspicions of American practices among some foreign
executives may not be groundless. ``They believe U.S. companies
have honed sophisticated methods to circumvent the FCPA, such as
setting up ventures unconnected to the contract they seek in which
public officials or family members are silent equity partners,''
Hershman said.
</P>
<P>
   In his eyes, though, that is not unique. ``When foreign
businessmen tell me they are looking for ways to comply'' with the
new OECD convention, Hershman said, ``I know many really mean they
are looking for loopholes, like the ability to give campaign
contributions to public officials, a defect the treaty should
correct.''
</P>
<P>
   Hershman said it was unclear how energetically the new
antibribery convention would be enforced by the 34 nations that
have signed it. Only 18 of the 34 have ratified the agreement so
far, including the United States; several major countries that drew
poor ratings in the survey, including France and Italy, have not
yet ratified the agreement, according to Transparency.
</P>
<P>
   Though pressure will still be needed from advocacy groups like
his, Hershman said, ``a coordinated, multilateral approach, such as
the OECD convention, is the only way forward.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States fared better in Transparency International's
annual corruption index, ranking 18th-best among 99 nations based
on the perceived level of corruption among public officials;
Denmark did best and Cameroon worst.
</P>
<P>
   Information about both surveys is available on
www.transparency.de, Transparency International's Web site.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-99 2232EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
