<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 22:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1815 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-INVEST-MERRILL-LYNCH-     10-28 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-MERRILL-LYNCH-ART-$ADV31-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEEPING MERRILL STOCK FUNDS ON TARGET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ill., Mass.)   (ART ADV: Graphic of mutual fund flows at Merrill Lynch is being
sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 31)  
 (af)  
 By PATRICK McGEEHAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Trying to turn around a big, struggling mutual fund business
sounds like a full-time job. But for Robert C. Doll Jr., chief
investment officer for Merrill Lynch's stock funds, it will be just
part of a day's work.
</P>
<P>
   Doll, who joined Merrill from Oppenheimer Funds in June, is
taking on the additional duty of running three large-cap stock
funds the brokerage firm plans to open by year-end. In the
meantime, he is overseeing the rollout of a litter of funds, run by
newly hired managers, that are aimed at filling some gaping holes
in Merrill's fund lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the market has changed, we haven't introduced enough
products to keep up with those changes,'' Doll said. To appeal to
investors who carefully choose funds by the size and type of stocks
they buy, the funds managed by Doll will be strictly defined and
will not stray from their declared styles, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, Merrill funds have not shown such discipline. For
example, its main technology fund, Merrill Lynch Technology Fund,
made contrarian bets that caused it to perform very differently
than most technology stock funds before it was merged last month
into the Merrill Lynch Global Technology Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, the Merrill Lynch Growth Fund looked and acted more
like a value fund before a new manager overhauled it early this
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you've had your assets exclusively at Merrill, essentially
what you've ended up with are funds that have been heavy on the
value side, that have chased beaten-down stocks and out-of-favor
sectors,'' said Kunal Kapoor, an analyst at Morningstar Inc., the
Chicago financial publisher.
</P>
<P>
   Investors have been pulling cash out of Merrill's funds for a
couple of years and moving it in many cases to the funds of other
firms with better-performing funds, mostly those that invest in the
biggest and fastest-growing stocks. That outflow went from a
trickle to a torrent last year and has not stopped yet.
</P>
<P>
   Since the end of 1997, sales of Merrill funds have exceeded
purchases by about $15 billion, according to the Financial Research
Corp. in Boston. This year, through Sept. 30, assets in Merrill's
long-term mutual funds _ excluding money market offerings _ had
dropped by about $7 billion, or 9 percent, to $69.8 billion,
according to Financial Research. That decline followed an outflow
of $5 billion in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The loss of faith among Merrill fund shareholders, most of whom
are clients of Merrill's brokerage business, has been widespread.
Even Merrill funds that have performed well lately, like its Global
Allocation Fund, which is up about 25 percent over the last 12
months, have had more money flow out than in, Kapoor says.
</P>
<P>
   Doll says that almost half of Merrill's funds have posted
returns this year that rank them in the top 25 percent in their
respective categories. Investors may slowly be taking notice: the
third quarter was the first in a year in which the firm had net
outflows of less than $3 billion, according to Financial Research.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been pretty bleak for them for the past three to five
years,'' Kapoor said. ``You have to translate good performance into
a string of good years. I think they still have a long way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   To get there, Merrill plans to roll out at least six funds by
early next year, including the three that Doll will manage with a
team of stock pickers and quantitative analysts. One of Doll's
funds will be a pure growth fund, another will be a value fund and
the third will be a blend of the two styles.
</P>
<P>
   Another, which Merrill brokers will start selling this week,
will be a global financial services fund managed by James Ellman,
who joined Merrill from the AIM Management Group this year. The
most eagerly anticipated of the bunch will be two funds managed by
James McCall, who arrived at Merrill this fall after settling a
legal battle with his former employer, Pilgrim Baxter &AMP; Associates.
Pilgrim had sued to stop McCall, who ran four funds for that
company, from going to work for a competitor.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill hopes to begin selling McCall's funds early next year.
</P>
<P>
   As new funds are created, others probably will disappear. Doll
said he and other Merrill managers were considering which funds no
longer fit into the firm's plans, a process Doll described as
``making sense of the product line.''
</P>
<P>
   He declined to identify funds that may be scrapped, giving only
this hint, ``In some cases, we have sliced the bologna a little too
thinly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
