<HEADLINE>
A TOURIST'S HEAVEN AND TOURIST'S HELL 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Locator Map is being sent to NYT photo clients. Photo is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 31)  
 (af)  
 By STEPHEN KINZER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KARAKOL, Kyrgyzstan _ The place is remote, romantic and
implausibly gorgeous. Deep in Central Asia and thinly populated,
Kyrgyzstan boasts some of the world's most spectacular Alpine
scenery, ideal for trekking, climbing, camping, horseback riding,
white-water rafting, canoeing, sailing, scuba diving and almost
everything else one might want to do in the great outdoors. In
short, it is a tourist's heaven.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, it is also a tourist's hell. There are few good
roads and, outside Bishkek, the capital, not a single modern hotel.
Travel agencies are disorganized and unreliable.
</P>
<P>
   Unrest and lawlessness in neighboring Tajikistan occasionally
spills over the border. The government gives lip service to the
importance of attracting visitors, but officials seem more
interested in lining their pockets than in promoting an industry
with immense potential here.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of entrepreneurs have been trying, with decidedly
mixed results, to close the gap. One of the most intriguing is
Valentin Derevyanko, a man who knows Kyrgyzstan's wild places as
well as anyone, but whose understanding of the tourism business is
developing very slowly.
</P>
<P>
   Derevyanko reflects both the huge opportunities and the huge
obstacles facing tour operators in the former Soviet Union. They
sense that tourism can not only make them rich, but also contribute
to developing their newly independent nations. But they are hobbled
by indifferent governments and, just as seriously, their own lack
of experience.
</P>
<P>
   By background and inclination Derevyanko is an adventurer, not a
businessman. He is a former motorcycle racing champion, and for
years he coached a motorcycle team, which fell apart when the
Soviet Union did in 1991. In need of a new livelihood at 48,
Derevyanko set out to capitalize on his beloved wilderness by
establishing Yak Tours.
</P>
<P>
   The company is a family enterprise. Derevyanko plans trips and
accompanies travelers if they want him. His wife, Galina, handles
administrative chores. His mother is the cook, and his adult
children serve as guides when necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Headquarters is a ramshackle lodge here in Karakol, a town of
75,000 that is the jumping-off point for travel through the vast
meadows around Lake Issyk-Kul and the regal Tien Shan mountain
range.
</P>
<P>
   Downstairs, one room serves as a dining hall and office. Maps
and thick mountain-climbing ropes cover the walls. Upstairs are a
few modest, unheated bedrooms.
</P>
<P>
   The lodge, though, is not what Yak Tours is all about. Its real
product is nature, and Derevyanko never seems at ease until he is
outdoors, hiking or climbing or setting up camp, or steering his
Russian-made jeep over icy mountain passes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very flexible,'' he said. ``Most of the people who call
us only want information and suggestions. Some want us to make
arrangements for their trips. And then there are people who want us
to do all the work, to set up everything. Whatever they want, we
can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the summer tourist season, Derevyanko had a total of about
250 customers. A sample week's patrons reflected the variety of
what he has to offer.
</P>
<P>
   One young Western couple wanted to take an easy trek through
unspoiled country. They had brought their own sleeping bags, and
asked Derevyanko to suggest a scenic route, lend them a tent, drive
them to their starting point and then pick them up three days
later.
</P>
<P>
   Another group, however, was frighteningly hungry for adventure:
eight highly trained Russians who travel the world in search of the
wildest and most dangerous rivers. They were eagerly embarking on a
monthlong raft trip on the roughest rivers in Kyrgyzstan, including
a 10-day portage over rugged mountains. It would be the third time
they had made this trip. On both previous occasions, one of their
number had been killed.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-99 2234EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
