<DOCNO> NYT19991028.0481 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 22:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1817 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-TOUR-SPOT-ART-2ND     10-28 0635
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-TOUR-SPOT-ART-2NDTAKE-$ADV31-NYT </SLUG>
  
 KARAKOL, Kyrgyzstan: been killed.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   At the opposite end of the spectrum are the groups of children
with cerebral palsy and other chronic diseases that Derevyanko
brings to Karakol, largely at his own expense. He takes them to a
small zoo he has built so they can touch and learn about animals.
The stronger children also go on gentle camping trips _ for many,
their first glimpse of Kyrgyzstan's natural wonders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hear from all kinds of people who want all kinds of
different things,'' Derevyanko said. ``Some weird groups come only
to watch birds. They go absolutely wild when they see what we have
here. Then there are the flower people, especially the orchid
lovers. They also go crazy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not too long ago I had a group of these orchid people from
England. I took them up to some fields that were full of orchids,
and when we got there they started screaming out loud. Apparently
some of these flowers are very rare and valuable in England. A cow
was eating them, and one guy in the group ran over and started
shouting at the cow to go away.''
</P>
<P>
   Derevyanko knows there is big money to be made from tourism in
Kyrgyzstan, but he is unsure how to make it. His Soviet upbringing
left him almost wholly ignorant of promotion, marketing or the
demands of Western tourists.
</P>
<P>
   Few people know what Kyrgyzstan has to offer, and Derevyanko
isn't doing much to get the word out. His modest brochure isn't
widely distributed. He has no Web site, because he thinks having
one ``takes a lot of time and is very expensive.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been mentioned in a couple of travel guides,'' he
shrugged. ``People come, and then they tell other people what's out
here. A company in Belgium that specializes in extreme trekking
sends us a few groups every year, and we're starting a partnership
with a company in Holland. Naturally I'd like more business, but
I'm not really sure how to get it.
</P>
<P>
   ``And there's another problem,'' he added. ``I don't have room
for too many people. What if they show up and don't like what we
have? They'll tell other people not to come.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not an idle worry. The accommodations in Derevyanko's
lodge are primitive, and there is nothing more comfortable anywhere
nearby. He spends the winter months trying to modernize his place,
but has made limited progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some ways I think he represents the past rather than the
future,'' said Max Haberstroh, a German aid worker who has been
given the daunting task of shaping a modern tourist industry in
Kyrgyzstan. ``He knows everything about nature and the region where
he lives, and he's very keen on eco-tourism, which is exactly what
Kyrgyzstan needs to promote. But he hasn't grasped anything about
how to make his business succeed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This country has a huge tourist potential, but it has a long
way to go,'' Haberstroh continued. ``Obviously they need roads and
nice inns and decent restaurants. But they also need a change in
mentality. Somehow they have to make the jump into the competitive
world of international tourism.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortcomings and all, though, Derevyanko is trying. ``Naturally
I wasn't prepared for life as a businessman,'' he said. ``I started
out knowing nothing about business, and I haven't learned much
since then. But in another sense I was prepared, because I'm an
adventurer. I can survive in all conditions. I know how to depend
on myself, either in the wilderness or in business. I know that
whether you get what you want depends mostly on how much you want
it.''
</P>
<P>
   For a man who has climbed so many mountains, literal and
figurative, can there be any fantasies left?
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course,'' Derevyanko replied with a smile. ``Every day I
dream about how much fun it would be to go forget all this and go
back to motorcycle racing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
