<SLUG> BC-GREENSPAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREENSPAN SAYS ECONOMY'S RECENT GROWTH RATE CAN'T GO ON  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By RIC STEVENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Alan Greenspan, the Federal Reserve chairman,
called the economy's recent growth rate unsustainable Thursday, but
said the rise in long-term interest rates appeared to be containing
the risks of inflation.
</P>
<P>
   With less than three weeks to go before the central bank next
meets to consider monetary policy, Greenspan gave no clear signal
that he planned to raise interest rates for a third time this year,
but expressed enough concern about the pitfalls facing the economy
to leave open the possibility.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech to business executives in Boca Raton, Fla.,
Greenspan said there was a compelling case that huge investments in
technology were driving a lasting increase in productivity growth,
dampening inflationary pressures even as demand for goods and
services grows at a robust pace.
</P>
<P>
   But Greenspan warned that the growth rate of productivity would
inevitably level off, leaving the economy vulnerable to a
resurgence in inflation. He repeated his long-standing warning that
the economy was running out of workers so fast that continued
strong growth could lead to a surge in wages and then in prices. He
suggested that the growing trade deficit might crimp the flow of
cheap capital into the United States from abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not have enough experience with technology-driven gains
in productivity growth to have a useful sense of the time frame in
which market pressures contain demand,'' Greenspan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Moreover it is not clear as yet how much cumulative impact the
rise in real long-term interest rates over the past two years will
have on demand,'' he said. ``Going forward, the Federal Reserve
must monitor not only this response, but also the evolving capacity
of our economy to meet higher levels of demand.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of Greenspan's speech to the corporate executives was given
over to the topic that has preoccupied him for the last several
years: the degree to which technology is reshaping the way business
operates, making the economy more efficient and allowing higher
growth rates with less inflation risk.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan said there remained a debate among economists about
whether growth in productivity _ or output per worker for every
hour worked _ was truly improving over the rather sluggish trend
that began around 1970. But he said he was increasingly convinced
that the improvement was for real.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although it is still possible to argue that the evident
increase in productivity growth is ephemeral, I find such arguments
hard to believe, and I suspect most in this audience would agree,''
Greenspan said.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, Greenspan said, is that no one knows whether
technological advances will continue at their current breathtaking
pace, or whether businesses will be able to capitalize on them to
offset increased costs. So far so good, Greenspan said _ there was
no sign of trouble in the economic data released by the government
today.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the same, the rate of growth of productivity cannot
continue to increase indefinitely,'' Greenspan said. ``At some
point it must, at least, plateau. Should, at that point, labor
market tightness result in faster growth of nominal wage rates,
there would be no offset from accelerating productivity. As a
consequence, unit costs would likely rise, pressuring profit
margins and prices.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan left no doubt that he was particularly concerned about
the shrinking pool of available workers. The number of people
seeking jobs has declined over the last two years and is heading
lower as the economy hums along, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, reining in the economy, Greenspan said, ``may already be
significantly advanced'' because of ``upward pressure on real
long-term market interest rates, especially as economies abroad
strengthen.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem for the Fed, Greenspan said, is that it can no
longer assume that it knows when the economy is at risk of
overheating. The Fed must not only make judgments about when demand
is entering a danger zone, he suggested; it must now also gauge
whether productivity improvements are increasing the economy's
capacity to handle greater demand, and the degree to which
improving productivity stimulates demand.
</P>
</TEXT>
