<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLUEANGELS-1STLEDE </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   EDS: Adds pilots' IDs.
</P>
<P>
   Two die when jet plunges near Valdosta
</P>
<P>
   By Alan Judd
</P>
<P>
   and Mark Bixler
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Two members of the Navy's elite Blue Angels flying
team were killed Thursday when their F/A-18 Hornet crashed on a
farm near Moody Air Force Base in South Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   The jet crashed into pine trees at 12:20 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Cmdr. Patrick Driscoll, flight leader of the Blue Angels,
identified the dead pilots as Lt. Cmdr. Kieron O'Connor, 35, of
Burtonsville, Md., and Lt. Kevin Colling, 32, of Castle Rock, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had the privilege of flying with both these pilots,''
Driscoll said. ``They are two of the best naval aviators I know.
This is a tragic loss to the families, to the Blue Angels and the
U.S. Navy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Angels have canceled their participation in an air show
at Moody this weekend, Driscoll said.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first fatal crash involving the Blue Angels since
1985.
</P>
<P>
   Beverly Peters of Douglas said she saw the Blue Angels fly over
the grocery store where she was shopping just before the crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``They came over in a beautiful formation. I think there were
six of them,'' she said. ``It was probably a half an hour later
that we saw the smoke. I didn't hear a crash or anything. Someone
said they must be burning garbage. Then a little while later the
fire trucks came by. It was just a big, black billowing.''
</P>
<P>
   Pilots in the Blue Angels dazzled 15 million people with their
aerial acrobatics last year. They typically fly in 60-70 air shows
a year and had 68 shows in 36 sites in the United States and Canada
on this year's schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Cmdr. Jack Papp, a spokesman at the Pensacola Naval Air Station,
said the Blue Angels had just arrived in Valdosta when the crash
occurred. The team was flying over the site of the air show _ a
routine task before any performance. The idea, he said, is to
``become familiar with the terrain'' and to note the location of
power lines or other obstructions.
</P>
<P>
   Four jets were flying at the time of the crash. Papp said the
planes were circling the air field and preparing to land. He said
there were no civilian casualties or damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``With crashes, we can't confirm anything,'' he said, ``because
it's under investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   The jet that crashed is the only two-seater in the team; it's
often used to take reporters on flights
</P>
<P>
   Members of Blue Angels are chosen through a ``rigorous selective
process,'' Papp said. They are considered among the best fliers in
the Navy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The maintenance is top notch. You also have top-notch naval
aviators.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor had been with the Blue Angels since last November,
Driscoll said. Colling had joined recently and was being trained.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington D.C., Ken Bacon, a Pentagon spokesman, said the
Navy is eager to learn from the crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, if any sort of procedural or maintenance problems
are revealed by the investigation they will be addressed
aggressively by the Navy,'' he said. ``This is its premier flying
team ... and you can be sure the Navy will do whatever it can to
make sure that this team is at the very top of its ability to
fly.''
</P>
<P>
   The group was formed in 1946. The deaths Thursday brought to 25
the number of Blue Angels killed in air shows or training.
</P>
<P>
   The crash was devastating news at Pensacola Naval Air Station,
home of the 14-member Blue Angel crew.
</P>
<P>
   ``It breaks your heart,'' Papp said.
</P>
<P>
   He said other members of the Blue Angels stayed in Valdosta
after the crash. He did not know when they would return to
Pensacola.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're feeling it right now,'' Papp said. ``Any time you lose
shipmates like this, it's a tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   At American Legion Post 240, about two miles from the naval
station's main entrance, a group of military retirees and their
wives had just finished their weekly bingo game when they learned
of the crash on television.
</P>
<P>
   Several gathered at the post's bar, sipping drinks and watching
a wide-screen television set for updates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely terrible,'' said Libby Lee, a military spouse, as
she sipped a Busch beer mixed with Sprite. ``Oh, my God, it's
terrible. Those Blue Angels, they do a beautiful job. Scares the
holy hell out of me, but it's a beautiful job.''
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the bar, a retired Navy aviator sat alone, dressed
in his old uniform. In a barely discernible whisper, he said he
couldn't talk about the crash. He stared straight ahead and drank
his beer.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
