<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-DEBATE-ANALYSIS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIVAL REPUBLICANS AGREE: GEORGE W. BUSH SHOULD JOIN THE FRAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 News Analysis   
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush's rivals for the Republican
presidential nomination gave the absent GOP front-runner a harder
time Thursday night than they gave either President Clinton or the
Democrats who hope to succeed him.
</P>
<P>
   Four of Bush's five remaining GOP challengers faulted the
governor for failing to join the second candidates' forum in six
days in the state with the nation's first presidential primary.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was mentioned only once and the Democratic hopefuls,
Vice President Al Gore and former New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley,
were not mentioned at all.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona Sen. John McCain, magazine publisher Steve Forbes, Utah
Sen. Orrin Hatch, and former Reagan administration official Gary
Bauer criticized Bush's decision to skip the question-and-answer
session in Hanover, N.H. Only former State Department official Alan
Keyes did not mention Bush or his absence.
</P>
<P>
   As if to underscore the point: The only Republican president
repeatedly mentioned by one or more of the candidates was Ronald
Reagan. George Bush, father of the Texas governor, was not
mentioned at all.
</P>
<P>
   The cautionary message to the younger Bush: The privileged son
of the last Republican president had better join the struggle for
the GOP nomination or he will become the lightning rod for
criticism by all of his rivals.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, the former Navy aviator and Vietnam prisoner of war,
targeted Bush without naming him. McCain thanked the moderators
``for being here.''
</P>
<P>
   And he thanked New Hampshire's WMUR-TV and Cable News Network
for ``sponsoring what the people of New Hampshire expect and demand
_ and that's to see us, to talk to us and hear what we have to
say.''
</P>
<P>
   Forbes, the multimillionaire publishing heir who is financing
much of his second presidential campaign, said he shared the
disappointment voiced by at least one member of the audience that
Bush was not taking part.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps in the future at a forum like this, if we call it a
fund-raiser, he might show up,'' Forbes said in a not-so-subtle
reference to Bush's fund-raising muscle.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes later urged New Hampshire Republicans to say: ``No, this
is not going to be a coronation. ... If you don't participate in
forums like this, if you don't put specific proposals out, you are
not going to get your support.''
</P>
<P>
   Bauer seized upon a question read by CNN moderator Judy Woodruff
to quip: ``Judy, I think you need to be honest with us. That
questioner that couldn't be here tonight, that wasn't Governor Bush
that asked this question? Because that would not be fair.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatch said he had entered the race on July 1 ``two years late
and $36 million short'' _ a thinly veiled reference to Bush's
staggering campaign treasury.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I get a million people to give me $36 dollars, I'll have as
much money as George W. Bush, and I'll win this doggone presidency
for you and you'll have somebody that's beholden only to the
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, anticipating that his absence could become the unifying
theme for his rivals, staged damage control from afar with a
hurriedly scheduled pre-debate television interview on WMUR in
Manchester, beamed into the Granite State via satellite.
</P>
<P>
   Bush explained that he was forgoing the second New Hampshire
forum to attend a ``once-in-a-lifetime'' award ceremony where his
wife, Laura, was receiving the Distinguished Alumni Award from her
alma mater, Southern Methodist University in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``My family is important to me,'' Bush said, adding: ``I think
the people of New Hampshire will recognize that.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bush, who has been on the road for 80 days so far this year
waging a nationwide campaign, said that he was ``looking forward''
to taking part in the next scheduled GOP debate in Manchester on
Dec. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Bush emphasized that he would be available to the voters of New
Hampshire during a campaign swing next week where he could answer
voters' questions. Bush said he's ``got a lot of work to do'' to
cement support in a state that has a reputation for punching
front-runners in the nose.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he would ``take nothing for granted,'' yet he still
believed that ``the people of New Hampshire accept my vision and
want me to be the nominee.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Bush left New Hampshire for neighboring Vermont just
a few hours before Republican aspirants faced each other at their
first side-by-side forum in Durham. Bush explained that the GOP
session conflicted with his scheduled appearance at a fund-raiser
in Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who has visited New Hampshire five times this year, vowed
to return to the state next week to deliver an address on
discipline in public schools.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The debate at Dartmouth College in Hanover was the first
side-by-side appearance of five of the six remaining Republican
presidential candidates since commentator Pat Buchanan bolted to
the Reform Party on Monday and former Red Cross President Elizabeth
Dole withdrew from the race. on Oct. 20.
</P>
<P>
   The candidates also touched on tax reform, health care and other
issues.
</P>
<P>
   But the candidates' comments on Bush underscored the stakes in a
volatile state where the latest public opinion poll shows McCain
gaining on Bush, who has visited the state only five times in the
last ten months.
</P>
<P>
   A Research 2000 survey released last weekend showed McCain's
progress in a state where he hopes to dent Bush's front-running
stature in the first in the nation primary on Feb. 1. The latest
survey showed McCain cutting Bush's lead over him in New Hampshire
from 35 percentage points in August to just 12 percentage points
last week. Bush now leads McCain 39 percent to 27 percent compared
to leading McCain 45 percent to 10 percent two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, Bush continues to enjoy wider margin over McCain and
other rivals. A CNN/USA Today survey completed on Oct. 10 showed
Bush enjoying the support of 60 percent of the 413 likely GOP
primary voters, compared to 8 percent who supported McCain and 4
percent who favored Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 and via
E-mail: stewart(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
