<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 22:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1829 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-GOP-FORUM-BOS &LR;      10-28 1211
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-FORUM-BOS </SLUG>
  
 MINUS BUSH, McCAIN STEPS OUT FROM GOP PACK  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILL ZUCKMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HANOVER, N.H. _ Seeking to separate himself from the rest of the
Republican presidential field, Arizona Senator John McCain
repeatedly told an audience of Upper Valley voters Thursday night
that before any of society's problems can be addressed, the special
interests that control the political process must be broken.
</P>
<P>
   ``The special interests rule in Washington,'' said McCain, a
staunch proponent of overhauling the way campaigns are funded.
``The big money, the huge six- and seven-figure contributions come
in and we add another loophole.''
</P>
<P>
   From problems with the military, to rewriting the tax code, to
solving America's health-care problems, McCain turned almost every
question back to money in politics during an hourlong town-hall
forum broadcast on WMUR-TV in New Hampshire and on CNN nationally.
</P>
<P>
   Five of the six Republican candidates for president attended the
session at Dartmouth College: Gary Bauer, Steve Forbes, Utah
Senator Orrin Hatch, Alan Keyes, and McCain. In an evening of
polite discourse, each candidate tried to stress his key point _
Forbes on economic freedom and opportunity, Bauer and Keyes on
improving morality, Hatch on his government experience, and McCain
on reforming government.
</P>
<P>
   The missing candidate was the front-runner, Texas Governor
George W. Bush, who was attending an event in Texas honoring his
wife. It was the second New Hampshire Republican forum he has
skipped in a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an opportunity for the candidates to distinguish
themselves,'' said Steve Duprey, the New Hampshire Republican
chairman. ``A lot of voters haven't met some of the candidates.
This is fabulous for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night's forum was also a chance for McCain _ who in
recent weeks has emerged as the chief threat to Bush in New
Hampshire _ to stand out without the presence of the front-runner.
McCain's poll numbers have been rising steadily, and he is drawing
large crowds during his frequent trips to the first-in-the-nation
primary state.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a great opportunity we're giving them,'' said
Thomas D. Rath, a longtime GOP activist and a top Bush supporter.
``They should thank us.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Bush suffered a few more slings Thursday night than he
did last week during a Republican roundtable at the University of
New Hampshire. When a woman told Forbes that she wished she could
ask Bush her question about buying nominations, he agreed with her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like you, I share the frustration that Governor Bush is not
here tonight,'' Forbes said, noting that Bush had skipped last
week's get-together in favor of a fund-raiser. He pointed out also
that Bush skipped a visit to a Rhode Island elementary school not
long ago in order to go to a fund-raiser when his plane was
delayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps in the future if we call this a fund-raiser, he might
show up,'' Forbes said, in one of the toughest barbs of the
evening.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes, who is largely funding his campaign through his vast
private fortune, accused the Republican establishment in Washington
of seeking ``a coronation, rather than a contest.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night was also notable for the fact that President
Clinton received gentler criticism than he did from his own vice
president during the Democratic town hall meeting the night before.
Hatch commended Clinton for the strong economy, pointing to the
balanced budget and the appointments of Treasury Secretary Robert
Rubin and Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday Vice President Al Gore, responding to a question
about restoring trust in government, said he understood ``the
disappointment and anger that you feel toward President Clinton. I
feel it myself.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans also differed from Gore and his challenger Bill
Bradley, who used their time to talk about programs and policies,
by focusing mainly on morals, values, and trying to stand out from
the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch, for example, pointedly said he has the most experience to
run the country of any candidate running for president _ including
the two Democrats. He said he is worried about the appointment of
judges to the federal bench in the coming years.
</P>
<P>
   Bauer repeatedly talked about his working class, Kentucky roots,
and his service in the administration of Ronald Reagan. ``America
is a great nation militarily,'' Bauer said. ``It also has a virtue
deficit. If we are going to be a shining city on a hill again, we
need to balance virtue and liberty.''
</P>
<P>
   Keyes appeared to agree with Bauer, but presented his concerns
in a sharper, more pessimistic tone. ``This nation is in the worst
moral crisis it has ever faced,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the evening, Keyes drew laughs from the audience. He
called for the end of the ``socialist income tax,'' and became so
worked up during a denunciation of the United Nations that he
concluded by saying, ``Sorry about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Keyes, an African-American, accused reporters of being racist.
He said he wins most of his debates, but the news media's response
``is nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I frankly think you all should be ashamed of yourselves,''
Keyes said, before stalking off.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes took credit Thursday night for the popularity of the flat
tax, an idea he championed during the 1996 presidential campaign.
Noting that the idea has gained currency among his fellow
Republicans over the years, he said wryly, ``So, education does
work.''
</P>
<P>
   While the forum provided no real opportunity for the candidates
to engage one another, Bauer took a shot at Forbes over the flat
tax, saying the plan would allow corporations to escape without
paying their fair share. Bauer has been battling Forbes for the
conservative mantle. But Forbes largely ignored Bauer, setting his
sights, instead, on Bush's absence.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes was also asked if he would hire qualified men and women
to work in his administration if they are openly gay, or if he
would fire them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will hire people who are qualified for the job, who can do
the work at hand, who are there to get something done, not to make
a statement about a lifestyle,'' Forbes said. ``If they are there
to make a statement, they're not going to get the job.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was McCain who seemed to dominate the hour, sticking to
his message of cleaning up government and reducing the power of
special interests. The only time he got thrown slightly off-stride
occurred when a Hanover man asked him how he reconciles society's
tolerance for alcohol with the problems of legalizing medical
marijuana.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is an excellent question, which I'd prefer to duck,''
McCain joked.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said that while there are clearly problems with alcohol,
the nation is losing the war on drugs. ``There was a time when we
were not losing the war, when Nancy Reagan had a very simple
program called `just say no,' '' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But then McCain said he wanted to answer the previous question
about people who travel to Canada and Mexico to buy perscription
drugs. ``I want to say why we can't come up with a decent patient
bill of rights,'' he said. ``Until we reform this campaign-finance
system, we're not going to reach a conclusion.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-99 2240EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991028.0488 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 22:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1831 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-INVEST-EXTREME-TRIPS-     10-28 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-EXTREME-TRIPS-2TAKES-$ADV31-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REST AND RELAXATION, BUT NOT FOR THE WEAK  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 31) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 James M. Clash covers mutual funds and adventure travel at
Forbes.  
 By JAMES M. CLASH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The top of the world, the bottom of the ocean, the edges of
space _ all were virgin territory at the beginning of this century.
Now all of them are visited regularly by people who have a sense of
adventure _ not to mention a lot of money.
</P>
<P>
   Blame it on a collective midlife crisis of baby boomers, the
near-tripling of the stock market in five years or other reasons,
but well-heeled adventurers are lining up to see who can take the
most extreme journeys. Many of these travelers want nothing less
than an excursion to the North or South Pole, or the world's
highest mountains. A walk on the Great Wall of China or a glimpse
of the sunrise over Machu Picchu won't do.
</P>
<P>
   Laurence S. Huntington, chairman of Fiduciary Trust
International, a global fund manager, has been on Mount Everest
three times. Max C. Chapman, former chief executive of Nomura
International, has climbed the Matterhorn, and Neil A. Armstrong,
the first man to walk on the moon, flew to the North Pole with Sir
Edmund Hillary, the conqueror of Everest.
</P>
<P>
   For the intrepid, at least in spirit, here are 10 of the most
extreme trips and their costs, excluding round-trip airfare to the
departure points.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Off to Space &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When the space shuttle Challenger exploded in 1986, killing a
teacher and the six other crew members, so did most people's dreams
of going into space. After the accident, NASA banned civilian
passengers. But because of a handful of entrepreneurs, the dream
may not be lost forever.
</P>
<P>
   Two companies, Space Adventures of Arlington, Va. (703 524-7172)
and Zegrahm Expeditions of Seattle (206 285-4000), are taking
deposits toward suborbital rides into space (defined as 62 miles
up) for $90,000 and $98,000, respectively. The rides, probably
lasting from 30 minutes to two and a half hours, are scheduled to
begin as early as 2002.
</P>
<P>
   To carry the tourists into space, more than a dozen private
rocket builders, including Rotary Rocket of Mojave, Calif., Kelly
Space and Technology of San Bernardino, Calif., and Vela Technology
Development of Vienna, Va., are scrambling to raise capital.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the farthest up you can go is 16 miles _ in a
Russian MIG-25 fighter jet _ as long as you have $11,900 and a
plane ticket to Moscow. At that altitude, above 99 percent of
Earth's atmosphere, you can see the blackness of space and Earth's
curvature. You also break the sound barrier, twice over. When I
went on this 35-minute ride in April, we hit Mach 2.6 _ a mile
every two seconds _ on our way to 83,700 feet (Space Adventures and
Incredible Adventures of Sarasota, Fla., 800 644-7382). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To the Top of the Globe &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Robert Peary, the American explorer, risked his life to become
the first to reach the North Pole in 1909. Now anyone can go in
relative style. In 1992, Quark Expeditions in Darien, Conn. (800
356-5699), began running nuclear-powered icebreakers to the pole;
the price for the two-week cruise from Helsinki, Finland, in a
standard cabin, is $15,950.
</P>
<P>
   For the more adventurous, Northwest Passage (800 732-7328) of
Wilmette, Ill., offers two-week dog sled trips for $25,500,
departing from Resolute Bay, Canada, initially by air, then by
sled. If you're pressed for time, Northwest Passage offers a
``champagne flight'' from Resolute Bay for $10,000, over six days.
</P>
<P>
   I flew to the pole in 1995, but because the ice pack floating
above the pole moves constantly, I had to walk a few yards each
minute just to stay there. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Because It's There &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Sir Edmund Hillary climbed Everest with Tenzing Norgay in
1953, he figured that the world's highest peak (29,028 feet) would
finally rest in peace. ``We thought that since we'd climbed it,
people would lose interest,'' said Sir Edmund, now 80.
</P>
<P>
   Wrong. More than 700 people have climbed Everest and more than
150 have died trying. The 1996 disasters, in which eight climbers
from different groups perished, became the subject of Jon
Krakauer's best-selling book ``Into Thin Air'' (Villard Books,
1997). And a film, called ``Everest,'' is on its way to becoming
the highest-grossing Imax movie.
</P>
<P>
   Alpine Ascents International in Seattle (206 378-1927) is among
the best for Everest expeditions, and charges $65,000. Needless to
say, the trip is only for experienced mountaineers. And even they
might want to read the sobering Krakauer book first. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Conquering the Continents &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The first to climb the ``seven summits,'' the highest on each
continent, was Dick Bass, owner of the Snowbird Ski and Summer
Resort near Salt Lake City. When Bass and the late Frank Wells,
president of the Walt Disney Co., went in 1985 (Wells climbed six;
he didn't get up Everest), the experience was novel. ``There wasn't
much of an industry,'' said Bass, now 69. ``We paid the guides'
way, and they were thrilled to go to those remote mountains. It
evolved from there into an industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Now a package deal is offered: all seven peaks for $97,000
(Mountain Madness, Seattle, 800 328-5925). The same rules about
Everest apply, though, as it is one of the seven. The others:
Aconcagua, 22,834 feet, in South America; McKinley, 20,320 feet,
North America; Kilimanjaro, 19,340 feet, Africa; Elbrus, 18,510
feet, Europe; Vinson, 16,864 feet, Antarctica; Kosciuszko, 7,316
feet, Australia. &QL; 
 &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the Penguins &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For most of this century, Antarctica was a domain of scientists
and explorers. Now no fewer than a half-dozen outfitters offer
cruises from South America to the world's coldest continent, where
penguins and blue, yellow and white icebergs fascinate tourists.
</P>
<P>
   The truly adventurous go all the way to the South Pole, first
reached in 1911 by Roald Amundsen, a Norwegian. The South Pole is
stable ice over land, and scientists work year-round at its frigid
Amundsen-Scott station.
</P>
<P>
   Adventure Networks International of Beaconsfield, England
(44-149-467-1808) operates flights only from November to January,
warmer months in the Southern Hemisphere ($25,000 to $30,000).
Two-month cross-country ski trips ($45,000) are also available.
</P>
<P>
   During the South Pole's winter, when temperatures plummet to 100
degrees below zero, aircraft cannot fly in or out because metal
landing gears become so brittle that they can snap. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Titanic, the 3-D Version &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If the movie wasn't enough, and if you have $35,500 and aren't
too claustrophobic, you can visit the real Titanic, 12,460 feet
below the surface of the North Atlantic. Trips depart from St.
John's, Newfoundland. Buzz Aldrin, the second man to walk on the
moon, went down for a few hours in a submersible in 1997. ``It was
crusty, like gingerbread cake,'' Aldrin, 69, said of the wreckage
(Zegrahm Deep Sea Voyages, 206 285-3743). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Meet Me at the Matterhorn &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Like a giant shard of glass, beautiful but dangerous, the
Matterhorn juts out of the Italian-Swiss border. The 14,687-foot
peak was not reached until 1865 when Edward Whymper, an Englishman,
led his party to the summit. But of the seven who got there, four
fell to their deaths on the descent.
</P>
<P>
   The Matterhorn is still dangerous; more than 500 climbers have
died there. But the popular Hornli ridge route is surmountable by
fit climbers with intermediate skills. In the summer season, be
prepared to be jostled and delayed by swarms of climbers.
</P>
<P>
   When I climbed it last year, my guide, hearing my complaints,
said: ``You're lucky. On my last Matterhorn trip, I saw one climber
punch another in an argument over a fixed rope.'' The International
School of Mountaineering in North Wales (44-176-689-0441) offers a
weeklong course, lodging and the climb for $2,000.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Seclusion, and Then Some &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last year, only 6,000 tourists visited the tiny kingdom of
Bhutan, bordered by Nepal, China and India. To visit is rare
enough, but only a few Westerners have made the 25-day trek to the
base camps of Masa Gang and Chomolhari, two sacred mountains, and
through the remote town of Laya ($5,395; Geographic Expeditions,
800 777-8183). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Powder Summitry &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you are tired of waiting in the lift lines at Vail or Jackson
Hole, helicopters can drop you at the top of some remote mountains.
Once there, you blaze your own trail down. For a private group of
10, Canadian Mountain Holidays (Calgary, Alberta, 800 661-0252)
charges a total of $105,000 for a week of heli-skiing in British
Columbia's remote Cariboo range.
</P>
<P>
   The big danger on ungroomed trails is avalanche. Kristen Ulmer,
one of the world's best extreme skiers, advised: ``If you're buried
under one, spit. Then dig in the opposite direction that the spit
falls.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Meandering on the Slambezi &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Zambezi River, which winds its way through Zimbabwe,
Botswana and Zambia, is nicknamed the Slambezi for its Class 4 and
5 rapids. A screaming bargain as adventure trips go ($2,690,
excluding air fare to Victoria Falls in Zimbabwe), a two-week
excursion also includes a three-day canoe safari for viewing
elephants, lions and kadu (Mountain Travel-Sobek, El Cerrito,
Calif., 800 227-2384).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-99 2241EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
