<DOCNO> NYT19991028.0490 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 22:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1833 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-FOR-ME-$ADV31-NYT     10-28 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-FOR-ME-$ADV31-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWENTYSOMETHINGS' LAMENT  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 31) 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: The (star) word should be replaced with the symbol)  
 (af)  
 Amy Wu, 23, is a freelance writer based in New York.  
 By AMY WU   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The almost overnight success of the Jerry Yangs of America has
made them the symbol of my age group, replacing the goofy Adam
Sandler image that once defined Generation X.
</P>
<P>
   But Silicon Valley success stories like that of Yang, 30, the
co-founder of Yahoo, have given my parents' generation the wrong
impression that all young people are _ or even want to be _ wealthy
owners of the Internet companies commonly called dot-coms,
investors in dot-coms or Wall Streeters who arrange stock offerings
for dot-coms.
</P>
<P>
   The reality for most of us, of course, is not all that different
from what the older generation faced: most of my friends and I _
just a few years younger than Yang _ remain mired in college loan
debts and struggle to make ends meet as we try to figure out what
we will do with our lives.
</P>
<P>
   A few of my friends who are analysts or traders or Internet
entrepreneurs live in Manhattan penthouses and dine daily at
restaurants where they are seated back-to-back with celebrities.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, after three years spent traveling and working
for news organizations and as a freelance writer in Hong Kong, I
recently returned to my parents' home in suburban New York and
commuted to my job in the city. Usually, I dined out of a brown bag
at lunch time.
</P>
<P>
   And while other twentysomethings may be chauffeured to the
office or arrive in their Porsches, I drove my two-door Toyota to
the train station each dawn, where I was likely to run into a
classmate from high school who had also returned to the nest. They,
too, arrived at the parking lot in second-hand cars and with brown
bags.
</P>
<P>
   Primarily, we commiserated about life at the entry level: the
hours spent monitoring fax machines and fixing cappuccino makers.
Most of us studied liberal arts in college or were aspiring actors
or writers; Java, margin calls and E(star)Trade were foreign
territory _ not because they were out of our reach but because we
had chosen not to take that path.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it's hard to stay grounded when high-tech nerds are
becoming poster boys for our generation and making it onto the
most-wealthy lists. It's even worse when people who are old enough
to know better look at us as if something has gone awry because
we're not making six figures.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks ago, a middle-aged man I met at a party was stunned
when I told him I was a writer. ``That's weird. Isn't everyone your
age starting their own dot-com,'' he asked, implying that I was
either incredibly ignorant or hopelessly idealistic.
</P>
<P>
   And at a family gathering, soon after I began working as a
producer at a dot-com, the hefty dinner bill was sent my way.
Everyone assumed I was well-fixed because of my job, and too proud
to disappoint them, I clenched my teeth and handed over my credit
card.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, most young people live ordinary lives. Many of my
friends have chosen lower-paying jobs like research assistants,
teachers, social workers and even extras in films because they love
what they do and understand that for most of us the ladder of
success must still be climbed rung by rung.
</P>
<P>
   Even those of us making our livings from the Internet mostly
live ordinary lives. At the dot-com where I worked until recently,
there were plenty of younger workers who ate stale pizza and hunted
for roommates.
</P>
<P>
   My stint in HTML-land came to an end as soon as I realized that
money, titles, successful initial public offerings, corner offices
and Porsches were important things, but not important enough to
sustain me beyond my 40s if that wasn't where I wanted to be.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, I'm already planning a trip to Asia in a few weeks, and
I'm planning to continue to make my living as a writer _ even if it
only pays me peanuts. At least my relatives won't expect me to pick
up the tab again.
</P>
</TEXT>
