<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON PERSONAL BUSINESS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 31) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y.)   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Rare Opportunity To Reverse Losses &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Internal Revenue Service, granting another extension, is
giving taxpayers who last year converted regular individual
retirement arrangements to Roth IRAs a chance to reconsider. Until
Dec. 31, they may switch their accounts back to regular IRAs _
should they wish to do so _ opening up an opportunity for those
whose portfolios have lost value in the recent rocky market.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost like getting to bet on a horse after the race,''
said Edward A. Slott, a CPA in Rockville Centre, N.Y., and
publisher of Ed Slott's I.R.A. Advisor. There is a drawback,
though, he cautions: the time and expense of filing an amended
return to reclaim the taxes that were paid for tax year 1998 make
the tactic worthwhile only if the loss is substantial.
</P>
<P>
   With a regular IRA, whether the $2,000-a-year kind or a rollover
of a company pension plan that could be hundreds of thousands of
dollars or more, the money is contributed before taxes and
retirement distributions are taxable.
</P>
<P>
   A Roth is the reverse; after-tax money goes in and normally
withdrawals will be tax-free, meaning that the interest, dividends
and capital gains earned in the account escape taxes. But if the
account has a loss, its tax benefit is lost.
</P>
<P>
   In extending the deadline for what it calls recharacterizations,
the IRS said it was acting ``in light of the newness of the Roth
IRA and problems that taxpayers have had applying its rules.'' It
said it was sending notices to 20,000 taxpayers who reported Roth
conversions on 1998 tax returns but who did not meet the
eligibility requirement, most often because adjusted gross income
exceeded $100,000 but in some cases because married couples filed
separate returns.
</P>
<P>
   Slott noted, however, that the extension to recharacterize
applies to anyone who converted to a Roth, not just to those who
did so in error.
</P>
<P>
   Jan M. Rosen &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bitten by the Tax Bug &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The top 1 percent of Americans are making more and paying a
bigger share of income taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The 1.2 million singles and couples who made more than $250,736
in 1997 earned 17.4 percent of all income and paid one-third of
federal income taxes, the Tax Foundation, a nonprofit research
group in Washington, calculated from tax return data.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, the top 1 percent made 12.3 percent of all income and
paid 24.8 percent of income taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The top tax rate now is 39.6 percent, up from 28 percent in
1987. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   David Cay Johnston &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
