<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 22:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1835 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-LA-TIMES-DISPUTES-NYT     10-28 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-TIMES-DISPUTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. TIMES PUBLISHER ADDRESSES EDITORIAL CONCERNS ON COMMERCIAL
INFLUENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Faced with a rebellion by distraught and angry
staff members, the publisher of The Los Angeles Times described at
a meeting with them Thursday the steps that she intended to take to
keep the news content of the paper free from any appearance of
commercial influence.
</P>
<P>
   In an article in Thursday's paper, its publisher, Kathryn M.
Downing, said that her own ``fundamental misunderstanding'' of
editorial principles led her to sign an agreement sharing the
profits of the Oct. 10 issue of The Times' Sunday magazine with the
Staples Center, the focus of all the articles in that issue.
</P>
<P>
   That acknowledgment and an apology were carried in a news
article in Thursday's business section of The Times on a day when
news and editorial staff members were preparing to question Ms.
Downing and Michael Parks, the newspaper's editor, about any other
financial arrangements that might cast doubt on the newspaper's
credibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've worked here 21 years, and I've never seen anything so
horrendous, anything that galvanized such a reaction from the
staff,'' said Times reporter Henry Weinstein in an interview.
Referring to a petition that circulated Wednesday protesting the
profit-sharing arrangement, he said, ``The people who signed
believed that executives had crossed a journalistic Rubicon and had
to be brought back from the other side of the river.''
</P>
<P>
   The staff outrage built quickly after the profit-sharing
arrangement was reported in The New York Times on Tuesday and The
Wall Street Journal on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   When Mark H. Willes, the chief executive of Times Mirror Co.,
the newspaper's parent, worked 18 months as the newspaper's
publisher, he led an onslaught on the old newspaper practice of
maintaining a figurative wall to insulate news and editorial
employees from its business operations. Ms. Downing, who was
Willes' handpicked successor when he stepped down as publisher last
spring, was quoted in the article as saying that she was trying to
abide by the old practices when she decided not to tell Parks about
the arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   The 164-page issue of the magazine, built around the opening of
the Staples Center, a $400 million sports and entertainment arena
that civic leaders have heralded as the cornerstone of a downtown
revival, brought in more than $2 million in revenue.
</P>
<P>
   While newspapers have for years run special sections devoted to
a theme, from fashion and culture to technology or philanthropy, it
is highly unusual for a newspaper to share the profit from such
sections with the subjects of continuing news coverage.
</P>
<P>
   About 300 newsroom employees signed a petition earlier this week
saying, among other things, ``As journalists at the L.A. Times, we
are appalled by the paper entering into hidden financial
partnerships on editorial products with the subjects we're writing
about.''
</P>
<P>
   In the article in Thursday's issue of The Times, Parks is quoted
as saying that he found out about the profit-sharing arrangement
after the magazine was printed but before it was distributed.
During the sometimes-tense two-hour meeting with the staff
Thursday, a meeting that virtually emptied out the newsroom, Ms.
Downing and Parks repeatedly apologized, according to three people
who attended the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   But it was Ms. Downing's apologies _ characterized by one person
as ``abject'' _ that set the tenor of the gathering. She said it
was ``unacceptable'' to have the newspaper's editorial integrity
questioned and added, ``I am responsible.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Both of them said that a betrayal had occurred and they had
allowed it to occur and they were sorry,'' said one editor who was
there and spoke on the condition of anonymity. ``They said they
understood now that we were operating under a cloud, out from under
which we would have to move ourselves. And they were determined to
do that.''
</P>
<P>
   The person added, ``What happened here was the business side
deceived the editorial side into betraying its integrity.'' At the
meeting, one staffer wondered out loud why The Times had publishers
without newspaper backgrounds. Ms. Downing replied that she
understood the intent of the question and responded, ``I am not
resigning.''
</P>
<P>
   At the meeting, Ms. Downing discussed steps to repair the
paper's reputation. Among them, according to another person who
attended the meeting but spoke on the condition of not being
identified, was a commitment not to honor the provisions of the
newspaper's contract with the Staples Center that called for future
revenue-sharing ventures.
</P>
<P>
   She also said business-side employees would be trained in
journalistic principles, and she wanted to spend more time in the
newsroom to acquaint herself with journalistic culture and values,
according to two people who were present.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Downing came to Times Mirror as president and chief
executive of a legal publishing division, Mosby Matthew Bender,
which has since been sold. She became the newspaper's president in
the summer of 1998 and publisher a year later.
</P>
<P>
   At Thursday's meeting, Ms. Downing also confirmed that she had
discussed a possible special issue of the Sunday magazine, focused
on next summer's Democratic Convention, with members of the civic
group LA Convention 2000. It is unclear if those discussions raised
the possibility of a similar profit-sharing arrangement. Parks told
the group that the project was shelved when he objected to it.
</P>
<P>
   Shawn Hubler, a columnist for the Metro section, provoked one of
the meeting's few moments of laughter when she said, ``Why don't we
just say the wall is back?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-99 2243EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991028.0493 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-28 22:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1847 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-HMOS-ART-2TAKES-NY     10-28 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HMOS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESCRIPTION DRUGS CAUSING BIG SHIFT IN HEALTH CARE COSTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also AETNA-OUTLOOK) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By JENNIFER STEINHAUER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Health insurance companies are starting to pay as much for
prescription drugs as they pay for care of hospitalized patients, a
stunning change in direction for the New York region's health care
dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The effects of these rising drug costs are felt at every point,
from the manufacturers battling with Congress and the White House
to the doctor pressured to prescribe a drug preferred by a health
maintenance organization to the shopper at the pharmacy counter who
learns that her asthma medication will cost twice as much as it did
last month.
</P>
<P>
   For the insurance industry, the shift in health care costs is
prompting health maintenance organizations to change the ways
patients pay for drugs, in some cases passing on the increases
directly to consumers, or trying to persuade hospitals to absorb
some of the new burden.
</P>
<P>
   Some employers, faced with rising premiums, are requiring
workers to pay 20 percent of each prescription, rather than
continuing the practice of a fixed co-payment, like $10, every time
they go to the pharmacy. Other businesses have resorted to plans in
which generic drugs cost a certain amount, name-brand drugs
identified by the health plan cost more and some drugs not on a
plan's preferred list are more expensive still. Health maintenance
groups have designed this three-tiered pricing system along the
same model as the HMO alternative in which patients pay more to go
to doctors who do not belong to their network.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next generation of drug programs is here in our region,''
said Edward Kaplan, a vice president at Segal Co., a
benefits-consulting firm in New York. ``Employers are being forced
to make changes, because no matter how you slice it, drug prices
are going up and someone has to pay.''
</P>
<P>
   At Empire Blue Cross and Blue Shield, drugs will represent 15.5
percent of premiums this year, and the cost of hospital care will
be just below 15 percent, said Michael Fedyna, the chief actuary
for Empire. He estimated that three years ago, drugs took 12
percent of premiums and 22 percent went for in-patient care. He
would not translate the increases into a dollar amount. ``Drug
trends have been outstripping any other component of the medical
cost dollars,'' Fedyna said.
</P>
<P>
   The story in New York has been similar to those in other parts
of the country, just later to arrive. Prescription drug prices,
fueled by research and development efforts and Madison Avenue's
attempt to sell the latest and hottest products, have been rising
rapidly in the last few years. At the same time, the increase in
the cost of caring for hospital patients has slowed, as the length
of stays has decreased or outpatient care has become more common.
</P>
<P>
   Drug manufacturers and many health care experts point to the use
of drugs as a cost-saving measure, saying prescribed drugs have
replaced some expensive medical procedures or reduced bills for
others. For example, high-blood-pressure medications now keep some
patients from having heart bypass surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Even with those advances in medicine, who pays for what
prescriptions is a hot topic for debate.
</P>
<P>
   The fight over drug costs, which in Washington centers on
President Clinton's proposal to offer drug benefits for Medicare
recipients, has several aspects. One discussion is over the drugs
like Viagra and Botox that enhance lives but do not save them:
Should they be included in plans, who ought to pay for what, and
who should regulate the industry to keep price increases in check.
</P>
<P>
   ``The drug issue, if you step back, is the classic
health-care-cost conundrum in miniature,'' said Keith Korenchuk, a
partner and a co-chairman of the health law section at Davis Wright
Tremaine, a Washington law firm. ``There are increasing costs,
technological advances, biotech creations that are life-style
enhancing, and the demand from the consumer,'' he said. ``And then,
you have the providers and payers in the middle.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Insurance companies and legislators, who have been focused on
the costs of doctors' fees and hospitals' charges, are now
directing more of their attention to drug costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prescription prices are a very large concern,'' said Leslie
Moran, senior vice president for the New York Health Plan
Association, a trade group for managed care plans. ``Plans are
looking at ways to offset some of these cost increases, which may
get pushed back on consumers, whether it is a health plan not
covering Claritin anymore in favor of another drug, or plans that
go to a multitiered payment structure.''
</P>
<P>
   Oxford Health Plans, which provides insurance for subscribers in
New York and New Jersey, has been offering three three-tiered
systems to its small employers since the beginning of the year.
Under the plan, employees pay three different prices for each drug
they buy: from $5 to $7 for generics, $15 to $20 for a drug that
the insurance company has negotiated a good rate with, and $35 to
$50 for drugs in neither basket.
</P>
<P>
   Larger employers have said that they, too, would like this plan,
but Oxford is awaiting approval from New York state to offer it, a
spokeswoman for the company said. Plans that require consumers to
pay a percentage of prescription costs rather than a flat rate are
also gaining ground.
</P>
<P>
   Hospitals are also starting to feel the increase in drug costs.
The Greater New York Hospital Association said drug costs had risen
14 percent this year, compared with five years ago, when the
increases were closer to 7 percent. Drug price increases account
for part of the rise, but increased drug use accounts for far more,
said Bill Larkin, vice president of pharmacy service for the
association.
</P>
<P>
   There are many more drug therapies now for illnesses that just a
few years ago gave doctors limited options. ``Drugs used to be 5
percent of a total hospital budget five years ago,'' Larkin said.
``Now, it is approaching 10 percent, and I don't see this trend
reversing itself.''
</P>
<P>
   To try to contain the rising costs, insurance companies and
hospitals are exploring whether to limit the amount of money spent
per patient on drugs administered during their stays. To do that,
some insurers want hospitals to absorb the losses when the cost of
a patient's drugs exceeds the limit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been timid about doing it,'' said Ruth Levin, vice
president in charge of managed care for Continuum Health Partners,
which runs Beth Israel and St. Luke's-Roosevelt Hospital Center.
``We have not yet come up with a price that gives us that comfort
level. Typically, the margin they give us is too small to take the
risk, knowing that the cost in pharmaceuticals is rising.''
</P>
<P>
   In California, where doctors and hospitals accepted caps on drug
costs and assumed the risks in the early 1990s, losses were so
great that some doctor groups went bankrupt.
</P>
<P>
   The sticky issue of access has arisen in the debate over the
costs of new drugs. With the huge growth in advertising for
prescription drugs, consumers have come to clamor for specialty
drugs as if they were designer jeans. They are luxuries they cannot
live without, like wrinkle-removing injections; or else they are
seen as a way to fix seemingly intractable medical problems, even
when not needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I warn medical departments that it is not the price side that
will get them,'' but overuse of drugs, said Larkin. He described a
new anti-inflammatory drug that does not severely irritate the
stomach, a common but not universal side effect of such drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be derelict to say they will replace all old
therapies with this one,'' he said. ``They do have their place, but
in what indications and what populations? Those with ulcers. Those
over 65. You have to start setting criteria.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
