<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMA-INTERNET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMA AND 6 OTHERS SET UP MEDICAL INTERNET COMPANY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DAVID CAY JOHNSTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The American Medical Association and six other medical societies
said Thursday that they had created an Internet company that,
starting next year, will publish consumer information on health
care and help doctors set up their own medical Web sites to
communicate with patients by e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Medem.com, a for-profit company, enters a crowded field of
Internet medical information companies that includes DrKoop.com,
Healtheon and Medscape, as well as 17,000 other World Wide Web
sites devoted to health care information.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Edward Fotsch, a former emergency-room physician from
Sausalito, Calif., who is Medem's chief executive, said doctors
need a reliable source of information for patients, and by bringing
together seven medical societies, the company would provide it.
</P>
<P>
   Some medical Web sites provide information that ``is great, some
is so-so and some of it will probably kill you if you follow it,''
Fotsch remarked. Doctors, he said, ``certainly don't have the time
to read every page of information from an Internet start-up
company.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are going to refer patients,'' he continued, ``you have
to have confidence in that information, sight unseen.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials of Healtheon and Medscape said their medical
information was developed under the same standard that Medem
proposes to use.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of who trusts what, our track record shows we are
trusted,'' said Dr. George Lundberg, editor in chief of Medscape,
which he said had 300,000 doctors and 1.2 million other users.
Lundberg, a former editor of the Journal of the American Medical
Association, noted that he was instrumental in formulating those
standards.
</P>
<P>
   Healtheon said it was ``the pre-eminent source of trusted
content for physicians and consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Upah, chief operating officer of DrKoop.com, said his
site had become the leading medical information Web site by posting
medical content reviewed by other doctors.
</P>
<P>
   Medem will get its editorial content through a separate,
nonprofit organization called called Medem E, a separation intended
to insure its integrity, said Dr. William Mahood of Abington, Pa.,
an AMA trustee.
</P>
<P>
   Five percent of Medem is owned by a charity, called the Medem
Trust, that will use its profits to provide health care to the
poor, Fotsch said.
</P>
<P>
   While Medem is owned by the seven medical societies, Fotsch said
he expected other professional societies to join, with groups
representing osteopaths and chiropractors to apply to be owners.
``The board wants to be inclusive,'' he said, adding that the
company's charter banned only tobacco companies from involvement.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, he said, ownership stakes may be sold to investors
or even to the public.
</P>
<P>
   The imprimatur of major medical societies, representing more
than 400,000 of the nation's 650,000 doctors, is likely to help
Medem attract both advertisers and providers of health care
services.
</P>
<P>
   It may also have links to other sites like Healtheon, which
wants to digitize the paperwork now required of doctors and
patients to collect insurance payments, issue and renew
prescriptions, and store treatment records. Until last week, Fotsch
was a vice president of Healtheon, which was hired by the medical
societies to draw up the Medem business plan.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the AMA, the other Medem owners are the American
College of Allergy, Asthma and Immunology; the American Academy of
Ophthalmology; the American College of Obstetricians and
Gynecologists; the American Academy of Pediatrics; the American
Society of Plastic Surgeons, and the American Psychiatric
Association.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
