<SLUG> BC-BBO-UMPIRES-VOTE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UMPIRES TO VOTE ON PHILLIPS' FUTURE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The fight over Richie Phillips, who has represented
major league umpires for 20 years, will end Nov. 30. The
pro-Phillips faction among the umpires and the insurgent group that
bolted from his mass resignation strategy reached agreement
Thursday for the National Labor Relations Board to conduct a mail
ballot on the umpires' labor representative.
</P>
<P>
   The board's New York office will mail ballots to 93 umpires Nov.
5 and count the returned ballots on Nov. 30. The umpires will have
three choices on the ballot: the existing union, a new union or no
union. The choice that receives a majority of the votes cast will
win.
</P>
<P>
   The insurgent group, a person close to some of its members said,
is confident it has enough votes to prevail. Going into the
election, the group would need at least 47 votes to ensure victory.
If some umpires were to vote for no union, it would be conceivable
that neither the existing union, the Major League Umpires
Association, nor the new group would receive a majority. A second
ballot then would have to be sent to the umpires.
</P>
<P>
   The Major League Umpires Independent Organizing Committee
petitioned the labor relations board to hold the election as a way
of ousting Phillips as the umpires' lawyer and labor negotiator. He
has three years remaining on a contract the umpires awarded him
last spring.
</P>
<P>
   The election will be critical because the umpires' labor
agreement with baseball expires Dec. 31. As sharply divided as they
are, the umpires would face a near impossible task to negotiate a
new contract with Major League Baseball. The independent group has
acknowledged the gains Phillips has made for umpires but feels his
methods are no longer appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-two umpires lost their jobs after they signed letters of
resignation last July 14 and Phillips submitted them to the league
office the next day. More than 50 umpires signed the letters, but
many quickly rescinded their resignations. The leagues hired 25 new
umpires, prompting the American League to accept the resignations
of nine umpires and the National League 13.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the two sides in the intraunion fight agreed that
all of the umpires would be permitted to vote without challenge,
including the 22 who lost their jobs and the 25 who were hired.
</P>
<P>
   The so-called independent umpires have invited all umpires to a
meeting in Baltimore next Tuesday. They chose Baltimore as the site
because it is the home of Ron Shapiro, the lawyer who has been
advising them, and Joel Smith, another lawyer, who has represented
them for the labor relations board election.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
