</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DRUGS-SEIZURE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAGS SITTING AT AIRPORT POINT WAY TO FINDING 200,000 TABLETS OF
ECSTASY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER S. WREN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Three hard-sided suitcases sitting unclaimed at
Newark International Airport after a flight from Amsterdam last
Friday attracted the curiosity of customs inspectors. Searching the
suitcases, they found 200,000 tablets of MDMA, a mind-altering
stimulant popularly known as Ecstasy.
</P>
<P>
   The record seizure of the tablets _ 106 pounds _ illustrated how
the party drug, made in the Netherlands, is flooding the New York
area, where it fetches high prices on the Manhattan club circuit.
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, the U.S. Customs Service has reported seizing
more than 1.7 million doses of Ecstasy in the New York area,
including the shipment caught at Newark. By comparison, customs
inspectors and agents intercepted 233,000 Ecstasy doses locally in
1997 and only 94,400 last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's predominately coming to New York,'' said John C. Varrone,
director of investigative operations for customs on the East Coast.
``New York and Miami are clearly arrival points, but we're seeing
distribution networks going to California.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis Rice Jr., the special agent in charge of the Drug
Enforcement Administration's operation in New York, described the
local growth in the smuggling and abuse of Ecstasy as significant.
The traffickers, Rice said, ``are multinational, multilingual and
extremely mobile.''
</P>
<P>
   Customs agents who tracked the unclaimed suitcases at Newark
Airport arrested three Dutch visitors from Amsterdam. They were
identified as Hendrikus Van-Zyp, 54; his wife, Maria Van-Zyp Landa,
46, and Willem Van Derkraan, 51.
</P>
<P>
   The flight carrying their luggage was overbooked, so they were
bumped to later flights. Thomas Manifase, the assistant special
agent in charge of customs investigations in Newark, said that when
the Van-Zyps arrived at their hotel in Queens, they asked the
airline to deliver their suitcases. Customs agents obliged, and
arrested them on Friday night. Van Derkraan was arrested on Sunday
when he claimed his suitcase.
</P>
<P>
   For smuggling the drugs, Manifase said, the three suspects were
promised $10,000 each and a free trip to Aruba. The suspects face
up to 20 years in prison if convicted. Mrs. Van-Zyp Landa told
investigators that she had terminal cancer and expected to live
only a few more months.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Ecstasy tablets reaching New York have been traced
to the Netherlands, where Dutch police officers have closed more
than 35 clandestine laboratories.
</P>
<P>
   In July, American and Dutch law enforcement officials arrested
two other Dutch nationals and broke up a ring that hired young
Hasidic men to smuggle Ecstasy tablets into New York from
Amsterdam.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli organized crime dominates the trafficking in Ecstasy,
investigators say. Earlier this month, the Israeli authorities
working with the Dutch police arrested nearly 50 trafficking
suspects and seized a million doses of Ecstasy. An Israeli agent
went undercover in the Netherlands to infiltrate the network.
</P>
<P>
   Ecstasy appeals to traffickers because it is so lucrative.
Varrone said each tablet cost only a penny or two to make but
brought $25 or $30 at retail. ``The markup in dollars makes it more
profitable than heroin,'' Varrone said. Rice said the wholesale
price for Ecstasy in the New York area was $2 a tablet.
</P>
<P>
   MDMA stands for the chemical compound
methylenedioxymethamphetamine and was first synthesized in Germany
as a potential appetite suppressant. Ecstasy promotes euphoria,
breaks down inhibitions and delivers mellow hallucinations,
prompting users to consider it harmless. But The Lancet, a British
medical journal, reported last week that babies born to women who
took Ecstasy early in pregnancy had a higher rate of birth defects.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
