<HEADER>
A1971 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-GOP-DEBATE-HNS &LR;      10-28 1165
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-DEBATE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAIN ISSUE AT GOP DEBATE: NO BUSH 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HANOVER, N.H. _ Capitalizing on his surge in the polls,
Republican presidential candidate John McCain used a televised town
hall meeting Thursday to stress his political independence and
underscore his belief that political change must be preceded by
campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``The special interests rule in Washington, D.C.,'' the U.S.
senator from Arizona said at the end of an hourlong debate
sponsored by CNN and WMUR-TV of Manchester, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, Steve Forbes, Gary Bauer, Orrin Hatch and Alan Keyes
fielded questions from a Dartmouth College audience that ranged
from legalization of marijuana to funding of the space program.
</P>
<P>
   But the absence of Texas Gov. George W. Bush itself was a
participant in the forum. WMUR gave Bush a statewide platform to
explain his decision to skip the event: His wife, Laura, received a
Distinguished Alumnus Award from her alma mater, Southern Methodist
University in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Most of his rivals took pointed shots at Bush, but the most
direct criticism came from an audience member who said she wished
she could direct a question about prodigious fund-raising to the
one candidate who was not there. Bush has raised far more money
than any of his competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes, a magazine publisher, pounced on the question, telling
the woman that ``I share your frustration that Governor Bush is not
here tonight.'' He noted that Bush missed a debate last week
because he had to attend a fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we called this a fund-raiser he might show up tonight,''
said Forbes, who his financing his own campaign primarily from his
own substantial wealth. Bush, whose campaign has raised $60
million, has been blamed for forcing several other candidates,
including Elizabeth Dole, out of the race.
</P>
<P>
   Bush requested the televised interview to explain his absence.
</P>
<P>
   ``As much as I regret missing the debate and getting a chance to
talk about what I believe in New Hampshire, I really don't regret
missing the opportunity to honor my wife,'' he said. Bush was
seated next to his wife Laura, who acknowledged that the couple
would have been able to ``work it out'' if the governor wanted to
go to New Hampshire to participate in the forum.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he had been well received in the state whenever he
visited and had agreed to participate in a Dec. 2 debate in
Manchester.
</P>
<P>
   But Dartmouth political science Professor Constantine Spilliotes
said he didn't believe Bush had been severely hurt by not attending
the town meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is still a wait-and-see attitude,'' Spilliotes said,
noting that McCain ``might get a little bit of a bump but I don't
think he stood out as much as some thought he might.``
</P>
<P>
   McCain clearly had the most to gain or lose. Polls in the state
show up him inching up on Bush with his maverick stands on issues
such campaign finance reform appealing to many independent voters.
</P>
<P>
   McCain played to those voters, stressing that contributions from
special interests had made it impossible for the major parties to
reach consensus on such important issues as health care, tax and
defense spending.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican forum did not produce any high moments of drama
or elements of surprise as the candidates remained largely civil.
There was even a surprising lack of criticism toward the Democrats
and the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative activists Gary Bauer actually chided his own party
for not cooperating with the Democrats in approving a strong bill
aimed at regulating managing care companies. Bauer said he agreed
with Democrats' contention that consumers should have a right to
sue their HMOs, a proposal opposed by many Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   And Hatch, a U.S. senator from Utah, credited former Clinton
Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin for improving the domestic economy.
</P>
<P>
   Even conservative firebrand Alan Keyes said that he didn't
believe the federal government should halt funding of the space
program saying that such exploration was akin to the westward
expansion of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   On the divisive social issues such as abortion, McCain said that
although he opposed the procedure he believed ``there must be a
dialogue and discussion on the issue.'' But McCain also told one
questioner that he opposed legalization of marijuana for medicinal
purposes.
</P>
<P>
   On the issue of hiring openly gay workers, Forbes said he would
``hire people who are qualified for the job, people who are there
to get something done not to make a political statement.``
</P>
<P>
   McCain also tried to diffuse recent reports that he has an
uncontrollable temper saying ``people say McCain gets angry.'' But
McCain said he gets upset at congressional approval of expensive
military projects that the armed services don't want, while
military personnel don't earn enough to feed their families.
</P>
<P>
   McCain advisors have blamed the reports about his temper on the
Bush campaign. They say Bush is trying to dampen his rise in the
polls, particularly in New Hampshire where the Arizona senator
poses a threat to the Texas governor.
</P>
<P>
   A Research 2000 poll published last week by the Concord Monitor
had Bush leading with 39 percent, followed by McCain with 27
percent in New Hampshire. In August the same poll had Bush with 42
percent and McCain at 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   To build on that momentum, the McCain campaign announced they
would begin airing their first television commercials in the state,
spots that recount the former Navy pilot's ordeal being shot down
over Vietnam and held as a prisoner of war for more than five
years.
</P>
<P>
   McCain advisors refused to say whether the spots were intended
to draw a contrast with Bush's military experience during the
Vietnam War. Bush served in the Texas Air National Guard at
Ellington Air Base. Lt. Gov. Ben Barnes may have been asked by a
family friend to help Bush get into the unit that included other
sons of high-profile Texans.
</P>
<P>
   Before the town hall meeting began, Forbes attacked Bush and
said the governor's excuses for ducking appearances with the other
candidates ``won't wash, '' with the state's voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just underscores that one candidate thinks he can play by
his own rules,'' said Forbes. Campaigning in Claremont in the
morning Forbes mocked the governor's response for not showing up.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to say his wife had a commitment and he made a
commitment to her. Blah. Blah, Blah,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush apparently made no effort to have the SMU event changed
when he found out about the New Hampshire debates.
</P>
<P>
   SMU spokeswoman Janet Ragland said the event honoring four
prominent Texans had been scheduled ``months and months ago'' and
that none of the honorees had indicated that the date was
inconvenient.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he will be in New Hampshire next week, where among
other things he will stress his support for charter schools.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
