<HEADER>
A1972 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-GLF-TOUR-CHAMP-NYT &LR;      10-28 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-TOUR-CHAMP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON A SAD AND MISTY MORNING, FOND RECOLLECTIONS OF STEWART
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ It was a day of golf and another day of grieving.
</P>
<P>
   The first round of the Tour Championship began with a moving
memorial service for Payne Stewart that was brief, yet powerful. As
most of the 29 players in the field sat silently behind the first
tee at 7:45, a bagpiper appeared through the morning mist, walked
up the first fairway and played a Scottish hymn entitled ``Going
Home.''
</P>
<P>
   A few moments later, Tom Lehman, one of Stewart's teammates at
the Ryder Cup a month ago, gave an eloquent speech that summed up
how much his 42-year-old golfing buddy would be missed following
his death Monday in a plane crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``Payne was an emotional guy,'' Lehman said in part, pausing
several times to compose himself. ``He wasn't ashamed to cry, so
I'm not going to be ashamed of my tears this morning. When he died
Monday, a big part of us died too.''
</P>
<P>
   During Lehman's remarks, many others cried. Then the bagpiper
played ``Amazing Grace'' before walking down the fairway, ending a
service that set the tone for a day of wide-ranging emotions.
</P>
<P>
   When the day ended, 27 holes had been completed, and Davis Love
3rd was the leader at 7-under par, one stroke ahead of Tiger Woods
and two strokes ahead of Carlos Franco, Fred Funk and Steve Pate.
</P>
<P>
   The only troublesome news from the golf course involved Woods,
who injured his left arm on No. 15 when he struck a rock with his
club as he tried to hit a ball that was wedged against the base of
a tree. He finished his round and insisted he would be fine, but
played the final three holes grimacing whenever he took a full
swing.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday will be remembered not for the competition, but for the
tragic circumstances surrounding it. Even Love, who played well
enough to lead, had trouble remembering his round, thinking more
about Stewart and the funeral that will be held Friday morning in
Orlando, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   The tournament will be suspended Friday as Stewart's family,
friends and fellow players say goodbye in Florida. It will resume
with 27 more holes on Saturday and the final 18 on Sunday. Under
the circumstances, being in first place hardly mattered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a tough time gathering up enough emotion to play,'' said
Love, who lost his father in a 1988 plane crash. ``You shouldn't be
out there playing golf with tears in your eyes. Some guys might not
want to do it again after today. But I think being together might
be more important than packing it in and going home.''
</P>
<P>
   It was impossible, however, to escape the memories. Players wore
black ribbons on their hats, and in the most unusual gesture of
tribute, Bob Estes used a putter on his first tee shot, hitting the
ball 16 feet off the tee, which led to a double bogey.
</P>
<P>
   ``The putt was somewhat symbolic of the putt that Payne made to
win the U.S. Open,'' said Estes, who dressed in black from head to
toe. ``Payne and I had become much better friends in the last six
or seven months. Maybe he got a little chuckle out of it.'
</P>
<P>
   Nick Price could not resist poking just a little fun at Estes'
gesture.
</P>
<P>
   ``He obviously felt like he was doing something that made him
feel good for doing it,'' Price said. ``I often think, if Payne was
around, what would he have wanted? If something happened to me, I'd
want all of the guys to go out and birdie the first hole, say,
`This one's for you, Bud,' then have 20 beers in the locker room
afterward.''
</P>
<P>
   Love managed to smile a few times on the course, but the good
feelings didn't last.
</P>
<P>
   ``You kind of chastise yourself every time you'd have fun
today,'' Love said. ``Part of me says we shouldn't be playing, but
then the other part says we need to be out here.''
</P>
<P>
   Love also sustained an injury Thursday, to his left shoulder,
but he did not think it was serious.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started losing some shots and hitting it shorter,'' said
Love, who had nine birdies and two bogeys in his 27 holes.
``Sometimes I play better when I've got something on my mind, or
I'm hurt. I was just trying to get through. Don't get me wrong,
this is a big golf tournament. But it just doesn't have the same
excitement to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Funk was visibly moved by the morning service.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gave a strange start to the tournament, with emotions
flying so high, or really so low,'' he said. ``I concentrated, but
I could never get Payne out of my mind when I was playing. I know
that he would have wanted us to play. There is no question. It was
the best thing. As a group, we needed to play and go through this
together.''
</P>
<P>
   But on Friday, the players attending Stewart's funeral will face
another difficult day.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people are thinking about tomorrow,'' Price said. ``I
know I am. It wasn't an easy day. We are all still missing him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
