<HEADLINE>
OFFER FOR AIR CANADA TO EXCLUDE AMERICAN STAKE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By TIMOTHY PRITCHARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ Faced with virtually certain defeat of its plan to buy
Canada's two major airlines and merge them, Onex Corp. raised its
offer Thursday for Air Canada by more than half and took steps to
ensure that a new, merged carrier is Canadian-controlled by
removing American Airlines as an important partner.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Schwartz, chairman and chief executive of Onex, said his
efforts to promote a plan announced in August to consolidate Air
Cath Canadian Airlines had encountered two formidable
obstacles _ insufficient support from Air Canada shareholders and
opposition to part-ownership by a U.S. carrier. Schwartz said
public and political opinion would only support a merged airline
that ``was unquestionably owned, managed and controlled in
Canada.''
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, American's parent, AMR Corp., which was to have
owned 15 percent of the merged airline, will have no interest under
the revised offer. It has agreed to withdraw financial backing to
Onex and, if the merger plan succeeds, sell its current 33 percent
equity interest in Canadian Airlines. American would continue to
have a relationship with the new carrier through the One World
global alliance, which coordinates schedules, sales and ticketing.
</P>
<P>
   By offering its revised proposal Thursday, Onex has provided
just enough time under securities regulations for the offer to be
voted on by Air Canada shareholders at a meeting to be held on Nov.
8. Shareholders were to vote on the original plan, one that
industry analysts think would have been defeated mainly because Air
Canada countered with a more attractive initiative nine days ago.
Under that deal, it would have taken over Canadian Airlines and run
it as a separate carrier.
</P>
<P>
   Onex's proposal requires approval by two-thirds of the holders
of Air Canada's voting and nonvoting shares.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
