<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-BREAKTHROUGH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IBM TO ANNOUNCE NEW, FLEXIBLE TRANSISTORS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JOHN MARKOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Heralding an era in which computers, and especially computer
displays, can blend into the fabric of everyday life, IBM
researchers will report Friday that they have developed flexible
transistors that can be embedded in curved surfaces or even in
thin, foldable materials.
</P>
<P>
   The breakthrough promises products ranging from electronic
newspapers and magazines that could be folded and tucked into a
briefcase or shirt pocket to big computer screens that could unfold
from cellular phones or other hand-held devices.
</P>
<P>
   The advance, made by a group of scientists at the company's T.J.
Watson Research Center in Yorktown Heights, N.Y., will be reported
in Friday's issue of the journal Science. It is considered
significant because by combining organic and inorganic materials
for the first time, IBM scientists think that they will be able to
achieve both low manufacturing costs and high performance.
</P>
<P>
   Transistors, the fundamental ingredient in computer circuits,
are generally etched in silicon, a rigid, inorganic material. And
although researchers have found ways to fabricate transistors from
organic materials in the past, the complexity and high cost of the
processes involved made mass production impractical.
</P>
<P>
   IBM officials said Thursday that their researchers had, for the
first time, managed to combine inorganic and organic materials.
This approach could quickly lead to a new generation of inexpensive
computer displays that are either flexible or embedded within
curved plastic, glass or other materials.
</P>
<P>
   Like today's semiconductor chips, wholly inorganic
semiconductors require processing at high temperatures, making it
impossible to embed circuits in plastic or other heat-sensitive
materials. But IBM's new hybrid materials ``self-assemble,''
crystallizing from a liquid solution at low temperatures to form
alternating organic and inorganic layers of material with the
correct semiconducting properties.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to computers and flat-panel displays, the
researchers suggested that the technology might have applications
in solar cells, making such devices easier to transport.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
