</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-WORLDSERIES-KNOBLAUCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNOBLAUCH, WEAK LINK, HAS STRONG ROLE
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Chuck Knoblauch had to sit down to keep talking. He
was too drained to stand any longer. It was evident Wednesday night
in the way he methodically unlaced his cleats, the way he slowly
pulled off his uniform and the way he barely budged when Clay
Bellinger swooped in and kissed him on the forehead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thanks,'' said Knoblauch, a response that was more rote than
reasoned.
</P>
<P>
   There was relief mixed into Knoblauch's world, too, after the
New York Yankees had completed their World Series sweep of the
Atlanta Braves. More than any other Yankee, Knoblauch had been
pinpointed as the player who could make a defensive mistake in the
postseason to damage the team's potentially splendid sprint. More
than any other Yankee, Knoblauch was a target.
</P>
<P>
   The bull's eye belonged on Knoblauch because he had turned the
routine act of throwing a baseball from second base to first base
into a daily rendition of show and tell. Except that it was throw
and yell: Knoblauch threw and fans yelled for him to please throw
it accurately. He did not always oblige.
</P>
<P>
   But there sat Knoblauch, with matted hair, with red blotches
across his face from too many champagne dousings, with a hoarse
voice, with a fatigued body and with another finger waiting for a
World Series ring. Knoblauch is still a terrific and patient
leadoff hitter, and he was a tremendous catalyst in the four-game
conquest of the Braves, contributing two game-altering at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Someone asked Knoblauch if he felt courageous for overcoming the
throwing problem that could have sabotaged the Yankees' season. The
barrel-chested second baseman, who conquered his woes when it
counted most, shrugged.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever is going on in my life, whether it's struggling
offensively or struggling with the throws, I just got to do the
best I can do,'' Knoblauch said. ``If that's courage, if getting
knocked down and then being able to get back up and hold your head
high, if that's courage, then I guess that's what it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch was uncomfortable praising himself or gloating as he
sat in a victorious clubhouse, but the evidence was undeniable.
While Knoblauch committed 28 errors in the regular and postseason _
while he gave manager Joe Torre headaches and made first baseman
Tino Martinez feel like Dominik Hasek _ the Yankees did not suffer
from them. They won 11 of 12 postseason games, and Knoblauch hit
.283 with four runs batted in, nine runs scored and two errors. As
Torre often said, he gave more than he gave back.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Knoblauch was rescued by two controversial umpiring
decisions in the American League Championship Series against the
Red Sox, neither had to do with his spotty throwing. One came on a
dropped ball at second and the other on a missed tag. Both calls
were somehow ruled in the Yankees' favor. Knoblauch did make
several erratic throws, causing Torre to finally bench him in the
later innings starting with Game 5 of the ALCS. Knoblauch accepted
the decision, even suggesting that he might see a hypnotist in the
off-season to address his throwing problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great feeling this year because it was a little
tougher road,'' Knoblauch said, speaking personally and
collectively. ``Sometimes when the road is a little bit rocky, it
makes it sweeter in the end. This is almost like a dream. To be
able to do the things we did, especially against a team like the
Braves, is really unheard of. It's amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch was instrumental in that, with two of the most
important at-bats of the Series, one a bunt and one a homer. With
the Yankees trailing, 1-0, and runners on first and second in the
eighth inning of Game 1, Knoblauch pushed a bunt between Greg
Maddux and first baseman Brian Hunter to fill the bases. The
Yankees scored four runs in the inning and took quick control of
the Series.
</P>
<P>
   Three nights later, Tom Glavine was clinging to a 5-3 lead in
the eighth inning of Game 3 at Yankee Stadium. The Braves
desperately needed a victory to have any chance of coming back in
the Series, but Knoblauch ripped a fly ball to right field that
tipped off the glove of a leaping Brian Jordan for a two-run homer.
</P>
<P>
   ``That ball went 315 feet,'' Atlanta manager Bobby Cox lamented.
``That was a Yankee Stadium home run.''
</P>
<P>
   What was Knoblauch's reaction to Cox's slight?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad I hit it at Yankee Stadium,'' he said cheerily.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees returned to the Stadium for Game 4 on Wednesday, and
Knoblauch described how the players talked about ``closing it out''
and ``holding that trophy tonight,'' which they did. Knoblauch's
infield single initiated a three-run rally against John Smoltz,
Roger Clemens started and soared, Mariano Rivera closed and
Knoblauch finally and gallantly eliminated a nagging bull's eye.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to judge yourself and to have an opinion on
yourself,'' Knoblauch said. ``People can say things about you or
have an opinion about you, but the only thing that I can do is work
as hard as I can. If someone called this courageous, that's fine.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
