<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLANE-SAFETY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAA PROPOSES NEW RULES FOR SAFER FUEL TANKS ON PLANES 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Responding to the explosion of a TWA jetliner that
killed 230 people off Long Island in 1996, the federal government
proposed rules on Thursday that would tighten design and
maintenance standards for fuel tanks on aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   The rules proposed by the Federal Aviation Administration are
intended to prevent a disaster like the one that destroyed Trans
World Airlines Flight 800 on July 17, 1996, the agency said. The
fiery end of the Boeing 747 was initially thought to be the result
of a bomb, but many investigators later attributed the explosion to
an accidental ignition in the center fuel tank.
</P>
<P>
   Under the rules, the FAA would basically call on aircraft
manufacturers to review how they design and make fuel tanks, and on
the airlines to develop regular maintenance programs for tanks,
assuming they do not already have them.
</P>
<P>
   ``This action represents a fundamental change in how fuel tanks
are designed, maintained and operated,'' the FAA administrator,
Jane F. Garvey, said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But the agency's own estimate of the cost of the program, $170
million throughout the industry over a decade, suggested something
less than revolutionary, and a spokesman for the Boeing Co. said
there would be no need to ground planes flying now.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed rules do not contain any of the radical changes
that some airline safety experts have discussed since Flight 800
blew up. These include using less flammable fuel and pumping inert
gases into fuel tanks to minimize vapors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're continuing to study that,'' an FAA spokeswoman, Kathryn
B. Creedy, said on Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   The rules, which are subject to a 90-day comment period and a
year of review before taking effect, would cover some 6,000
aircraft with 30 or more seats _ in other words, many of the
aircraft most familiar to frequent commercial travelers.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Creedy said the proposed rules were the fruit of ``thousands
of man-hours of research and development since Flight 800.''
</P>
<P>
   The standards would require manufacturers to review the designs
of their fuel-tank systems to insure that failures could not create
ignition sources within the tanks. Tougher standards for new
aircraft would be required, intended to minimize the chance of
fuel-tank vapors, and aircraft companies would be called on to help
airlines develop maintenance programs for fuel systems.
</P>
<P>
   And the standards would require aircraft makers to ``provide a
means to prevent catastrophic damage if ignition does occur.''
</P>
<P>
   That language seemed to be a reference to the last moments of
Flight 800, which many investigators said was doomed the instant a
spark set off the vapors in its center tank.
</P>
<P>
   The investigations after July 17, 1996, highlighted not only the
hazards of fuel-tank vapors but also uncovered ways that sparks
could be created by chafed wires and various tiny parts housed
within the center fuel tanks of a jumbo jetliner. The center tank
on the Boeing 747 that was designated Flight 800 contained
relatively little fuel, and thus had more room for vapors to
develop.
</P>
<P>
   John Dern, a Boeing spokesman, said his company welcomed the
proposals in principle and would be filing comments. ``In some
cases,'' Dern said, ``these are systems that have been in service
for 30 or 40 years, so we're confident they're safe. But we've also
learned some things in the last few years.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he was confident that the rules, whatever their final
form, would not result in wholesale grounding. He based his
confidence, he said, on changes that Boeing and other manufacturers
have put in place since the Flight 800 tragedy, including changes
in fuel-tank components.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of work has been done across the industry,'' Dern said.
Still, he said, ``we'll go back and look at the design of each
airplane.''
</P>
<P>
   Dern said he could not speculate on whether any of the Boeing
aircraft in production would have to be revamped. The FAA proposal
contains language intended to improve the safety margin around fuel
tanks, and the 747's air-conditioning equipment, which produces
heat, is not far from the center fuel tank.
</P>
<P>
   Although Dern said Boeing had been diligent in making
improvements since the Long Island accident, and the FAA conceded
that some manufacturers had ``aggressively completed'' safety
reviews, it said others had not been, and that their slowness had
``delayed the adoption of corrective action.''  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
