<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HOMELESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK OFFICIAL FEARS THAT NEW RULES MAY WRONGLY DEPRIVE HOMELESS
OF SHELTER
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By NINA BERNSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Acknowledging that strict new welfare rules have
mistakenly cut some people from the rolls, the city official in
charge of homeless services expressed concern Thursday that work
requirements and other new rules for homeless people could risk
wrongly depriving some families of shelter.
</P>
<P>
   The official, Martin Oesterreich, commissioner of the Department
of Homeless Services, made the remarks in a tense meeting with
executives of many of the private, nonprofit agencies that are
contracted to operate the city's homeless family shelters.
</P>
<P>
   ``There probably are decisions that were wrong on their face and
should never have been made,'' he said when members of the group
spoke of shelter residents who had been mistakenly denied welfare
benefits or judged fit to work when they were actually disabled.
``I don't know how to cure that system.''
</P>
<P>
   The work requirement is only one of a list of rules that those
seeking shelter will have to obey to keep their beds under the
city's plan, which makes the city's homeless shelters subject to
the same system of eligibility screenings, job searches, work
assignments and sanctions that city welfare offices have used since
1995 to move more than 400,000 people off public assistance.
</P>
<P>
   In the meeting Thursday, shelter operators said they feared that
under the new rules, bureaucratic problems that have improperly cut
some families from the welfare rolls would result in families'
being wrongly evicted from homeless shelters and left with nowhere
to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``I share your concerns,'' Oesterreich said.
</P>
<P>
   Many problems with the plan are still unresolved and might have
to be worked out after it takes effect, Oesterreich said, since
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani wants ``a full-blown program in place'' by
Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any way you look at it, for some families there will be some
pain,'' he said. ``The problem is how to make sure that pain is
justifiable and not the result of a bad decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Debra Sproles, a spokeswoman for the city's Human Resources
Administration, said in an interview that homeless people were not
fundamentally different from the general welfare population, and
that existing mechanisms gave recipients a chance to contest
mistakes. ``We think it's the right policy direction to take,'' she
said, ``and that it's important for all people, especially people
in a homeless shelter, to get a job and become self-sufficient.''
</P>
<P>
   City officials have said that children in homeless families who
are expelled from the shelter system could be taken into foster
care. But a 1989 court decision bars the city from removing
children from their families solely for lack of housing, and state
social services law requires the Administration for Children's
Services to try to keep families together.
</P>
<P>
   Oesterreich indicated that while the city had been legally free
to impose the rules on families since last year, one reason for
delay was concern by Nicholas Scoppetta, the commissioner of the
Administration for Children's Services, about the impact on the
city's system of child protection and foster care.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their mission is not to run a juvenile shelter system,''
Oesterreich said.
</P>
<P>
   Oesterreich added that public disclosure of the mayor's plan for
putting the new rules in effect surprised him, Scoppetta and Jason
A. Turner, the commissioner of Human Resources, while they were
still meeting to try to resolve these conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   The city has promised to give five days notice to Steven Banks,
a Legal Aid lawyer who is counsel to the Coalition to the Homeless,
before putting the rules into effect for families.
</P>
<P>
   The city agreed in court Thursday that it would not put the
rules into effect for homeless single adults until the legal issues
had been aired at a hearing set for Jan. 7 before Justice Stanley
L. Sklar of State Supreme Court in Manhattan. Thomas Crane, a
lawyer for the city, said the city would submit its legal papers on
Nov. 12.
</P>
</TEXT>
