<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-ALBERTI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAFAEL ALBERTI, WIDELY READ SPANISH POET, DEAD AT 96
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Spain)  (rk) 
 By AL GOODMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MADRID _ Rafael Alberti, one of Spain's most popular poets and
the last member of the ``Generation of 1927,'' a group of artists
whose ranks included poet Federico Garcia Lorca and film director
Luis Bunuel, died Thursday at his home in El Puerto de Santa Maria,
in southern Spain. He was 96.
</P>
<P>
   Alberti wrote more than a dozen books of poetry and in 1983 was
the recipient of the Spanish government's Miguel de Cervantes
Literature Prize.
</P>
<P>
   King Juan Carlos and Queen Sofia and Prime Minister Jose Maria
Aznar wired their condolences to the Alberti family Thursday,
state-run television reported.
</P>
<P>
   Alberti spent 38 years in exile after Gen. Francisco Franco's
troops won the Spanish Civil War in 1939. He returned to Spain in
1977 and was elected that year as a Communist Party member of
Parliament, representing Cadiz. He later resigned his seat to give
poetry readings, which attracted large crowds.
</P>
<P>
   Alberti was born Dec. 16, 1902, in El Puerto de Santa Maria,
near Cadiz, to a family of prosperous wine merchants. Cadiz and its
shimmering bay were constant reference points in his work. His
first book of poems, ``Marinero en Tierra'' (``Sailor on Dry
Land''), written when he was 23, won him Spain's national
literature prize in 1925 and lasting fame. In it, he called on
readers to be:
</P>
<P>
   On alert, for in these eyes of the South, and in this song, I
bring you all of the sea.
</P>
<P>
   Look at me, the sea is passing by.
</P>
<P>
   Four years later he published what many critics consider his
masterpiece, ``Sobre los angeles'' (``Concerning the Angels'').
Lorca had that same year produced ``Romancero Gitano'' (``Gypsy
Ballads''), and for many critics the two books marked the high
point of modern Spanish lyricism.
</P>
<P>
   With his friend Lorca, Alberti shared a passion for the
Andalusia region in southern Spain, and their poetry drew upon its
colors, sights and sounds.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1920s, Alberti met Lorca, Salvador Dali and other
artists connected to Madrid's famed student residence. Together,
their artistic movement became known as the Generation of 1927. The
group produced poetry unparalleled since the golden age of Spanish
literature. Among its members, in addition to Lorca and Alberti,
were Damaso Alonso, Pedro Salinas, Jorge Guillen, Luis Cernuda and
Nobeate Vicente Aleixandre.
</P>
<P>
   Alberti became a strong supporter of the Spanish Republic when
it was formed in 1931 and a staunch anti-fascist when the civil war
broke out in 1936. He fought in the air force against Franco. He
also toured the Republican lines giving poetry readings and became
a major propagandist for the Loyalists.
</P>
<P>
   Alberti's interest in theater was strong even in the 1930s, when
he created the ``Guerrillas del Teatro'' to entertain troops
fighting Franco. As a playwright, his work included ``Noche de
guerra en el Museo del Prado'' (``Night of War in the Prado
Museum''), which had its premiere in Italy in 1973. He won Spain's
national theater prize in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Lorca was executed by fascist troops in 1936 in Granada. After
the Loyalists were defeated, Alberti and his first wife, writer
Maria Teresa Leon, began a life in exile in 1939 that took them to
Paris, Buenos Aires and elsewhere in Latin America, and to Rome.
Their home in Rome became a rendezvous for Spaniards opposed to or
stifled by the Franco dictatorship.
</P>
<P>
   Alberti's work includes ``Vida bilingue de un exiliado espanol
en Francia'' (``Bilingual Life of a Spanish Refugee in France''),
``La Amante'' (``The Lover'') and ``Trece barras y 48 estrellas''
(``Thirteen Bands and 48 Stars''), the latter written in the 1930s
to criticize American imperialism. But he also wrote poems of
passion, as in the book ``Entre el Clavel y la espada'' (``Between
Sword and Carnation''):
</P>
<P>
   A carnation goes on a trip
</P>
<P>
   A carnation goes traveling
</P>
<P>
   From the legs, the sea is above
</P>
<P>
   From the breasts, the sea is below
</P>
<P>
   Alberti and his first wife had one daughter, Aitana, born in
1941 in Argentina. Ms. Teresa Leon died in 1988, and in 1990
Alberti married Maria Asuncion Mateo, a writer about 40 years
younger who had studied his work extensively.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his wife and daughter, he is survived by a
stepdaughter, a stepson and two grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
