<HEADLINE>
MEMORIES OF STEWART LOOM LIKE A MISTY TUNE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By EDDIE SEFKO 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ It was 30 minutes before the first tee time Thursday
and there wasn't a soul on the practice range at Champions Golf
Club except for Payne Stewart's.
</P>
<P>
   Anybody who doesn't think Stewart was everywhere during the
first round of the Tour Championship wasn't paying attention. He
was there. In every musical sob coming from the bagpiper, he was
there. In the poetic words delivered by so many friends and fellow
golfers, he was there.
</P>
<P>
   In the still, foggy air that hung like a curtain that might have
dropped on a life but was rising on an afterlife, he was there.
</P>
<P>
   And in every heart, Stewart was there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Payne Stewart was a very emotional guy,'' said Tom Lehman in
his eulogy of Stewart during the pre-tournament memorial ceremony.
``He loved to laugh. And he wasn't afraid to cry. So I'm not going
to be ashamed of my tears.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, the current U.S. Open champion, was one of six people
killed Monday aboard a Learjet that crashed into a pasture near
Mina, S.D., four hours after leaving Orlando, Fla., en route to
Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``On Monday, six people got on that airplane,'' Lehman said.
``Today, there are wives without husbands and kids without fathers.
All of us were a part of Payne. And Payne was a part of all of us.
When he died Monday, a big part of us died, too.''
</P>
<P>
   But life goes on. Memories go on. And on a bizarre day that will
go down as one of the most un-golf-like days in the sport's
history, the game wasn't so much played as it was tolerated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I considered not playing this tournament because I didn't feel
like playing it,'' Lehman said. ``But I thought it was important
that we be here for Payne. And then I was asked to be part of the
ceremony and I was up all night worrying about it. I didn't want to
completely collapse and not be able to blubber a word.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's appropriate that we had that service. As a Christian,
you know this is not the end. I know one day I'll see Payne Stewart
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart's friends and colleagues paid personal homage to him in
many ways.
</P>
<P>
   Davis Love III, the leader through Thursday's 27 holes, Justin
Leonard and other players inscribed a ``P.S.'' on the back of their
golf caps. Duffy Waldorf wrote tributes to Stewart as identifying
marks on his golf balls. Swatches of a plaid, kilt-like material
were pinned to players' hats or golf bags.
</P>
<P>
   The most bewildering tribute came from Bob Estes, a former Texas
Longhorn who approached the 10th tee for his first shot of the
tournament and pulled out his putter, tapping the ball about 15
feet from the back of the tee box to the front of it. He then
swatted a 3-wood down the fairway for his second shot, but went on
to make double bogey to start his tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was symbolic of the last putt he made to win the (U.S.)
Open,'' Estes said. ``But maybe more importantly, it had to do with
the way Payne had changed. The way faith, family and friends were
his top priority. It symbolized that also. It meant I wasn't
worried about the first hole or the score I would shoot or
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, golf was way down the list of priorities Thursday. And
it no doubt will be again Saturday, when the tournament resumes.
Today's play has been canceled to allow players the option of
attending Stewart's memorial service in Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   The revised schedule called for 27 holes Thursday and 27
Saturday before Sunday's 18-hole finale. But the tournament is
running a distant second in everybody's thoughts. Fans are
respectful, but the momentous roars of good shots were missing. The
players played well at times Thursday. But it was with hollow
feelings they made those strokes of genius.
</P>
<P>
   The day began with a poignant gathering on the first tee.
</P>
<P>
   A lone bagpiper, Steve Agan of the Houston Pipe Group, strolled
out of the foggy morning air onto the No. 1 tee, playing ``Going
Home,'' a slow Scottish hymn.
</P>
<P>
   Lehman addressed a crowd of approximately 50 PGA Tour players
and officials and several hundred fans, talking through his tears
about Stewart's legacy and reading a passage from a funeral service
handbook.
</P>
<P>
   ``In such a time, there is but One who can bring light out of
darkness, who can heal the heart that is broken by grief, who can
bring peace of soul and strength of spirit,'' he said. ``That One
is the One whom Paul called `The God of all comfort.' He did not
fail Job. He did not fail Paul. He did not fail Christ. He will not
fail you.''
</P>
<P>
   After Lehman said a brief prayer and called for a moment of
silence, the bagpiper played a verse of ``Amazing Grace,`` then
returned into the fog slowly, playing ``Going Home`` again.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day, a plane hauled a banner above the course that
had a red heart and a message that read: ``We will remember you
Payne.''
</P>
<P>
   ``At some point today, it really hit home,'' Love said. ``When
that little airplane flew over with that banner, I couldn't putt. I
had a four-footer straight in for birdie, and it took me 10 minutes
to get ready to putt it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You shouldn't be out there playing golf with tears in your
eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   But that was the way it was Thursday. And Stewart was right
there, watching every step of the way.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
