<SLUG> BC-GLF-SENIORS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INMAN CAN BE TALK OF TOWN AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE SHELBURNE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Given Joe Inman's gift of gab and his upbeat
disposition, it's hard to imagine how unrecognizable he was with
the golfing public before winning last year's Pacific Bell Senior
Classic.
</P>
<P>
   But that's professional golf, where _ apart from fellow touring
players _ the impression of who you are is often stitched to what
you have won.
</P>
<P>
   And Inman, the 1998 Senior PGA Tour Rookie of the Year who opens
defense of his Pacific Bell title today at Wilshire Country Club,
hadn't won much before last November.
</P>
<P>
   When he did _ with birdies on three of the final five holes at
Wilshire to hold off Lee Trevino by one stroke _ Inman also won
over the attending media with his unabashed enthusiasm and
appreciation.
</P>
<P>
   He nearly wept after the breakthrough victory, his first as a
senior and first anywhere as a pro since the 1976 Kemper Open _ his
only PGA Tour win.
</P>
<P>
   But if Inman was misty-eyed, he was hardly choked up. He turned
his post-match interview into an entertaining filibuster on courage
and character, the value of family and work ethic, the difficulty
of tour access, the satisfaction of delayed success and his belief
that winning is its own reward.
</P>
<P>
   The former Wake Forest teammate of Lanny Wadkins and Leonard
Thompson talked and talked and talked, and his vitality was
infectious.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm overwhelmed,'' he said, finally. And from somewhere wafted
a response: ``But not speechless.''
</P>
<P>
   A year later, Inman still talks about the impact of that '98
Pacific Bell victory, which earned him a last-chance berth in the
'98 Senior Tour Championship and full exemption this year.
</P>
<P>
   His three rounds at Wilshire have led to $1,070,447 in winnings
with the potential for more in this week's $1.2 million Pacific
Bell event and next week's $2 million Senior Tour Championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never dreamed I would have this chance to play again,'' said
Inman, 51, who left the PGA Tour in 1986 and worked as a golf club
sales representative and PGA radio broadcaster before joining the
Senior Tour last year.
</P>
<P>
   He earned his Senior Tour card with a fifth-place finish in the
'97 tour qualifying tournament but was in danger of losing
exemption for '99 entering last year's Pacific Bell. Then, thanks
to an 11-under showing capped by a four-foot par putt on the final
hole, life got dramatically better.
</P>
<P>
   Inman earned a career-best $165,000, then followed with a
sixth-place finish worth $87,500 at the Tour Championship. He has
seven top-10s and $817,947 this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never dreamed that my game would come back like it had by
that time, like it has continued this year,'' he said. ``I didn't
know a golfer was still in me.''
</P>
<P>
   That golfer will likely have to be at its best to defend against
perhaps the strongest field in the Pacific Bell's 10-year history,
which was formerly played at Rancho Park.
</P>
<P>
   Nine of the tour's top-10 money winners are on hand, including
1-2 players Bruce Fleisher and Hale Irwin, both contending for
Player of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   Irwin, with six wins, including his fifth senior major, is
bidding for an unprecedented third consecutive POY title. Fleisher,
a lock to follow Inman as Rookie of the Year, has seven victories.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-99 2357EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
